<SLUG> BC-BROWN-VS-BOE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOPEKA SCHOOLS TO CONTINUE WITH DIVERSITY EFFORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN L. PETTERSON  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOPEKA, Kan. -- Topeka School District officials say they will
continue pressing forward with the district's program to eliminate
the remains of segregation, even without federal court
supervision. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, federal Judge Richard Rogers closed the
Brown vs. Topeka Board of Education case that began in 1951 and
resulted in the 1954 U.S. Supreme Court decision abolishing the
``separate but equal'' doctrine of segregation across the country. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We see it as a milepost, not as a destination,'' Bruce
Mallory, president of the Topeka Board of Education, said
Thursday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Robert McFrazier, the district's superintendent, joined Mallory
in assurances that the district has ``no ambitions whatsoever to
dismantle the remedies that are in place. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in a sense relieved, but at the same time we will
maintain the status quo as it relates to the remedies we are
currently under.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In his four-page order that was signed Tuesday, Rogers said that
the district had complied with the court's mandates and that ``the
vestiges of past discrimination in the school district have been
eliminated to the extent practicable.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His order came as no surprise. Plaintiffs in the case had told
the court they wouldn't object to the district's attempt to end
federal-court oversight of the program to eliminate any remains of
segregation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rich Jones, attorney for the plaintiffs, who has been working on
the case since 1979, said although it was now closed he wouldn't
walk away. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``As an interested citizen, I'm not going to sit back and watch
any discrimination without saying something,'' Jones said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the time the original action was initiated, Topeka had
segregated elementary schools. Its single high school was
integrated. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1955, the federal court ruled that Topeka had made a
good-faith effort toward complete desegregation, but it entered no
further orders. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The case remained dormant until 1979, when attorneys convinced
one of the original plaintiffs, Linda Brown, to be a plaintiff in
an effort to bring the case back before the court. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The case was revived by Rogers, and he ruled in 1987 that the
school district had eliminated all vestiges of the old segregated
school system. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But in 1989, the 10th Circuit Court of Appeals reversed Rogers,
and that decision stood through several appeals. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Five years later, Rogers approved a desegregation plan to remedy
remaining problems involving the ratios of white and minority
children as well as the racial mix of faculty members. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the 1993-94 school year, 13 Topeka schools were classed as
``racially identifiable.'' Three years later the district had no
schools in that category. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the district has a minority enrollment of 41 percent,
including 25 percent African-Americans and 11 percent Hispanic.
Fifty-nine percent of the students are white. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mallory said that even though the federal court no longer was
looking over the district's shoulder, that didn't mean any dramatic
changes were planned. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have a ways to go with the commitment we've made to
the spirit of the Brown case,'' Mallory said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
