<SLUG> BC-GA-SHOOT-COMPANY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO ATLANTA FIRMS ARE LEADERS IN `DAY TRADING' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to insert sentence in 8th graf re absence of known business
relationship between Barton and Momentum. No other changes.)   (With GA-SHOOT and related stories.) 
(mk) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The two brokerage houses where a gunman opened fire Thursday in
Atlanta, killing nine people, are among the most well known firms
specializing in day trading, the fast and furious, minute-by-minute
trading of stocks by computer.
</P>
<P>
   With offices in 23 cities across the country, All-Tech
Investment Group Inc., based in Montvale, N.J., is one of the
nation's largest day trading specialists. Momentum Securities, a
day trading firm in Houston, has branches in Chicago, Milwaukee and
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   A bull-market phenomenon, day trading has caught the fancy of
throngs of investors who believe they can profit from the smallest
of stock price changes in the course of a trading day. An estimated
5 million investors day trade currently, accounting for 15 percent
of the volume in Nasdaq stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Some trade in offices like All-Tech's in Atlanta, others trade
from their homes. Clients of the roughly 100 day trading firms in
the United States are typically required to put up at least $50,000
to open a trading account. Some firms, including All-Tech, offer
courses in day trading which train interested customers for a fee.
</P>
<P>
   All-Tech Investment Group's chief executive officer, Harvey
Houtkin, has been something of a day trading evangelist. A former
professional stock trader, he started the firm that later became
All-Tech in 1983. He calls himself the father of electronic stock
trading and has written two investing books on day trading
techniques, one with a drawing of a burglar's mask on the cover.
</P>
<P>
   Houtkin did not return a phone call seeking comment on the
shootings. But he told The Associated Press that his employees told
him that the suspected gunman, identified by authorities as Mark
Barton, hadn't traded since April.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (the gunman) was a former client,'' Houtkin said.
</P>
<P>
   Momentum Securities, founded in 1995, is run by James Lee, who
is also president of the Electronic Traders Association, a lobbying
group for electronic trading firms. Momentum Securities planned to
become a public company through a stock offering, according to a
news report late last month. It was not known whether Barton traded
with Momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, All-Tech filed plans with the Securities &AMP; Exchange
Commission to issue stock in a public offering but the deal was
never done. At that time, the company said it had approximately
1,500 customers in 22 offices nationwide. These customers made
between 2,000 and 3,000 trades per day, according to documents
filed with the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   Day trading firms have come under fire in recent months from
securities regulators who believe the firms do not warn investors
adequately about the risks of losing money day trading. In May,
All-Tech settled a complaint brought by the Securities Division of
the Commonwealth of Massachusetts that a branch office of the firm
in Watertown, Mass., had misled customers with deceptive
advertising and misused customer funds. Matthew Nestor, director of
the Securities Division, said Thursday that the branch had
approximately 130 customers and that the firm's advertising
essentially said that day trading ``was easy, profitable and
anybody could do it.'' In settling with regulators, All-Tech agreed
to pay a $50,000 fine and reimburse customers $228,000, and said it
would not solicit customers from Massachusetts for two years.
</P>
<P>
   At its board meeting Thursday and before news of the shooting
emerged, the National Association of Securities Dealers approved a
measure requiring day trading firms to disclose to their customers
the risks associated with the trading practice. Mary Schapiro,
president of NASD Regulation Inc., said the rule will help protect
investors in an increasingly sophisticated environment.
</P>
<P>
   All-Tech's Web site downplays the risks in day trading. ``The
amount of money you can lose is directly related to your degree of
discipline in following the trading techniques our affiliate
All-Tech Training Groups, Inc., teaches.'' Elsewhere, the web site
stated: ``Electronic Day Trading attracts people dead-ended or
unhappy in their current field of endeavor and people with a desire
to make trading their life's work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
