<HEADER>
A9474 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFL-ANALYSIS-LADN     07-30 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-ANALYSIS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAD CALL SETS L.A. BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ That's a neat trick, taking a muddled melange that
finally has a chance at being cleared up, and then leaving it all
the messier.
</P>
<P>
   This is the NFL, where all inconceivable and foolhardy acts are
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Just when everybody is eager to put a happy face on the Los
Angeles bid to acquire the next NFL team, the league decides to
play hardball and Commissioner Paul Tagliabue announces more public
money will be required to close the Coliseum deal.
</P>
<P>
   With one brilliant stroke, everybody is quickly pushed into an
uncomfortable corner that is a threat to kill the whole deal.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gray Davis has long been on record as to opposing any
existing public money to help pay for aquiring an expansion team.
And it would hardly be a politically correct move for him to change
his stance now.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want more state money?'' Davis said. ``I stand by my
previous position.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not smart to box a governor in. Davis signaled he was
willing to back bond issues to pay for parking at the state-owned
Exposition Park when he asked Bill Chadwick, an investment banker
who specializes in bonds, to bring the competing ownership groups
together under one directed effort.
</P>
<P>
   You have to feel a little sympathy for Chadwick, who thought he
laid out the framework for an agreement and was led to believe the
league was ready to agree to it. He mistakenly announced to the
press Wednesday after meeting with owners he expected them to sign
off on the deal by the week's end.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the league praised his efforts, the state's
participation . . . and then essentially rejected his deal and sent
him home bloodied and wounded to search for more public money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little surprised when I was told they wouldn't execute
the negotiating agreement,'' Chadwick said. ``But it's no surprise
they want more money. They've been consistently trying to sweeten
the economics for them, and I've been trying to protect the state's
interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Chadwick said he will spend the next few days going over
numbers, searching for any other ways to generate revenue, and then
meet with Davis over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then he'll either say, `OK' or `I think not,' '' Chadwick
said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if it is ``I think not,'' that could end your Los
Angeles expansion effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably would,'' Chadwick said.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, there is not much more Chadwick can do. The
league claims its Sept. 15 deadline for Los Angeles to finalize its
franchise bid is firm, which leaves six weeks for the unexpected to
happen and just who to get it done?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Eli Broad?
</P>
<P>
   Michael Ovitz and partner Ron Burkle have been the favorites of
most owners and league officials. Tagliabue reportedly pushed for
owners on the expansion committee to approve Ovitz as the team
owner Tuesday night, but owners said they did not come to Chicago
prepared to make an ownership decision.
</P>
<P>
   But Tagliabue might have unwittingly given Broad an opportunity
to take the lead in the ownership race when he __ the commissioner
_ strangely made public his hard line for more public financing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Chadwick has gone as far as he can,'' Broad said. ``He
got the ball moving, but we're at the 10-yard line. Somebody has to
be given the ball to run with and make it happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to pick an ownership group, whether it's ours or the
other group, to get this done. Someone with the wherewithal and
relationships to get all the parties _ the governor, the mayor, the
NFL _ into one room and have everyone bend a little bit. If they do
that, I think we can get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Broad, with partner Ed Roski Jr., might be the only one with
both the state and local connections who can hammer out a fast
deal. Broad acts like a man who sees an opportunity. And, of
course, he has the money, which he is willing to put up.
</P>
<P>
   Broad said Thursday he'd give the league $2 million in earnest
money if he is named the franchise owner and given the opportunity
to close the deal over the next 47 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't get it done, I'd forfeit it,'' Broad said. ``I'm
not guaranteeing that it will happen, but I have confidence that if
Ed and I were doing it, we'd get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Money is the constantly intriguing element in this whole
unsavory mess. Only in the wacky world of the NFL could a deal
expected to cost $1 billion be on the verge of blowing up because
of $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   That's the amount that Chadwick proposed as the team's annual
lease payment to help pay off the $150 million needed in bonds for
new parking. The rest comes from a 10 percent ticket surcharge and
parking fees. But owners believe that additional $5 million per
year leaves the team with too little net revenue to effectively run
a Los Angeles franchise, and Broad agrees.
</P>
<P>
   Broad estimates that between the cost of renovating the Coliseum
and paying the expansion fee, that even with the NFL kicking in
$150 million, the team owner will need to put up $750 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to do it,'' he said. ``You get emotionally involved. I
believe it's good for the city and the park. But to invest that
kind of money and then take on an operating deficit, that's nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   The whole thing can seem plenty wacky. Councilman Mark
Ridley-Thomas, though, is not about to concede anything. It was
Thomas and Roski who brought the Coliseum back from the dead as a
prospective NFL site.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prospect of returning football to the Coliseum was far
more daunting then than the unfinished business before us,'' he
said. ``It's easy to talk about what's left to do and lose sight of
what has been accomplished. I refuse to believe creative minds
can't settle this.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, but time is getting precious. And there is yet another
mess to clean up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
