u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-SUSPECT-PROFILE-2N     07-30 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-SUSPECT-PROFILE-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECT IN ATLANTA KILLINGS WAS LINKED TO PREVIOUS VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS: in 9th graf, bgng Barton ran, changes name and age of
daughter to Elizabeth Mychelle, 7.)  (With GA-SHOOT and related stories.) 
(mk) 
 By WILLIAM GLABERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before he burst into the national news as a frustrated day stock
trader turned suspected killer Thursday, Mark O. Barton had already
been at the center of an extraordinarily violent story.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, his wife and mother-in-law were found beaten to death
inside a camper at a campground in northern Alabama. On Thursday,
the authorities said that although Barton, 44, was never charged,
he was a suspect in the killings.
</P>
<P>
   Barton, a Scout master and chemist, seemed to have led an
ordinary life for the past few years in the Atlanta suburb of
Morrow. But neighbors did notice that he seemed intent on keeping
to himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was preoccupied,'' said Cindy Northcutt, a neighbor on
Sinclair Place in Morrow, a solidly middle-class suburb about a
20-minute drive from downtown Atlanta. ``He was always short and
brief.''
</P>
<P>
   He seemed stand-offish, said neighbors along the street where
Barton and his two children by his first marriage lived with a
woman who the authorities said was his second wife, Leigh. But
until the shooting Thursday, several neighbors said they thought he
was simply busy with some sort of computer work.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always on the computer. Always on the phone,'' said
Mrs. Northcutt, a neighbor two houses down.
</P>
<P>
   But Martha Jean DeFreese, whose grandson was a friend of one of
Barton's children, said she had recently noticed something when
Barton came to drive the boys to a Scout meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked a little odd to me,'' she said. ``I said to myself,
`There is something wrong with this man.'''
</P>
<P>
   Barton ran a chemical consulting business out of his home. Last
winter, his wife and his 7-year-old daughter, Elizabeth Mychelle,
moved to an apartment in nearby Stockbridge. On the recent Fourth
of July weekend, Barton and his 12-year-old son, Matthew, moved
into the Stockbridge apartment, apparently in at effort at
reconciliation. Bodies believed to be those of his wife and
children were found Thursday in the apartment.
</P>
<P>
   The new residents of the house at 6475 Sinclair Place said that,
aside from a lot of computers and three or four phone lines, the
scene the Barton family left behind was as ordinary as could be.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was your average middle-income business person,'' said Gail
Walker, the woman whose family took over the $850-a-month rental
after the Bartons left.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors said that Barton usually wore slacks and dress shirts
and that there was little that distinguished him except for his
being well over 6 feet tall and thin.
</P>
<P>
   A few neighbors said they were not even sure if he and the woman
he lived with were married.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been told she left because he couldn't decide what they
were going to do, whether he was going to settle down and get
married,'' said Lucius Johnson, who lived two doors away.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Earls, who runs a day care center in her home three
doors down from Barton, said the Barton children seemed typical.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the 1993 killings, Barton's first wife, Deborah
Spivey Barton, 36, and her mother, Eloise Powell Spivey, 59, had
been spending Labor Day weekend without Barton. They were found
inside the camper, which showed no signs of forced entry. While
some jewelry was missing, other jewelry and cash had been left
untouched.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview that appeared several months later in The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Bill Spivey, Barton's former
father-in-law, said that Barton had been the perfect son-in-law
until the murders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since then,'' Spivey added, ``we have cooled tremendously
toward each other.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
