A9478 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEAT-DEATHS-KAN &LR;      07-30 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEAT-DEATHS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT LEAST 10 KC AREA RESIDENTS NOW DEAD IN JULY HEAT WAVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE HILL KAVANAUGH  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- Kansas City suffered through the hottest day
of the year as officials on Thursday confirmed that eight more
persons in the area had died of illnesses related to the heat wave,
now in its second week. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Worried that the death rate will grow, officials upgraded Kansas
City's weather status from heat advisory to heat alert. That kicks
into action several contingency plans for the opening of additional
cooling shelters. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The official high for the area was 103 at Kansas City
International Airport, and Thursday was the sixth straight day of
triple-digit readings downtown, where the high Thursday was 106. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ron Steve, of the National Weather Service in Pleasant Hill,
said today would be more of the same, with a high around 100 and a
heat index of 105 to 115 degrees. Relief may be in sight, though,
beginning Sunday, when a cool front is expected to produce highs of
85 to 90, and in the mid-80s on Monday. But WeatherData Inc. of
Wichita was less optimistic; the private forecasting firm predicts
highs of 94 degrees on Sunday and Monday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before a cool front can move in, though, the heat could claim
more victims. Statewide, the death toll is now at least 27; the
Kansas City area has accounted for at least 10 heat-related deaths
since July 8. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seven of the deaths announced Thursday involved residents of
Kansas City's urban core, most of them near midtown, who were
between 40 and 81 years old. The eighth victim was a 37-year-old
man from Cass County. Two of the victims died Thursday morning. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We had seven victims who did not leave their home,'' said Dan
Lindholm, chairman of the Kansas City Heat Task Force. ``But
opening more shelters may not help. For some of these victims,
there were heat shelters on their own block but they didn't go to
it. If people don't go, we can't always reach them.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Task Force, a group of 16 city agencies headed by the Kansas
City Health Department, monitors temperatures, deaths and area
hospital emergency departments to gauge how the heat is affecting
Kansas Citians. Kansas City has had a Heat Emergency Plan since
1980, when as many as 176 deaths were blamed on one of the worst
heat waves in decades. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Task Force's criteria for a heat alert includes having a
heat index -- a combination of temperature and humidity level -- of
105 degrees by 11 a.m. for two days. But at 4:30 p.m. Thursday,
they threw out the criteria. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``As hot as it is, we still haven't been at critical levels,''
said Lindholm. ``But we're responsive to people's needs. Heat
accumulates in the human body. We have a good heat plan, but if we
feel we can impact people's health, we do it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``People need to get out of the heat and into air conditioning,
if only for a couple of hours. If they can't do that, they should
take several cool baths or showers.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City, there are three levels of urgency: heat
advisory, heat alert and heat emergency. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But only when a heat emergency is declared are cooling shelters
kept open around the clock. Another criteria for a heat emergency
is that the nighttime temperatures not drop below 85 degrees. The
overnight low Wednesday night and Thursday morning was 75 degrees
at Kansas City International Airport but 84 downtown. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the heat continues, officials are asking the public to take
an even stronger interest in their neighbors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Had these people been taken to a heat shelter, maybe they
could have been saved,'' Lindholm said of the heat wave's victims.
``But many people will not go to a shelter. You need to get out,
knock on these doors and check on your neighbors. Invite them over
for a few hours. Someone's life could depend on it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Complicating efforts to ensure the safety of homebound
residents, the relief agencies say, is a scarcity of window fans.
On Thursday, the Salvation Army, which is leading the distribution
of fans for 33 agencies, had only a few left. More than 1,100 fans
have been given away this summer, but there is still a long list of
people in need. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm beginning to panic,'' said Joyce Schau of the Salvation
Army. ``Right now, we have gone through all the supplies we've had
and we don't expect a new supply until next week.'' She said
donations are needed now. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``People need to realize that heat kills easily, especially the
elderly, the very young and those suffering with a medical
condition,'' said Schau, who is also a member of the Heat Task
Force. ``Often, people get entrenched. Either they're too
frightened to leave their homes empty or they don't have a way to a
shelter.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SHARE-A-FARE, of the Kansas City Area Transportation Authority,
is offering free rides to cooling shelters during the heat alert
for Kansas City residents who are elderly or disabled. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Officially sanctioned cooling shelters in the Kansas City area
are at the Salvation Army sites, the Kansas City Public libraries
and the Mid-Continent libraries, said Lindholm. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``But any public building that has air-conditioning and a
drinking fountain can also work,'' he said, including places like
shopping malls, movie theaters and even the casinos. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For residents without air conditioning, staying cool means
staying alive. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
