A9480 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUN-DEENA-LADN-(SLANG     07-30 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-DEENA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DROSSIN READY FOR THE WORLD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KIRBY LEE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Deena Drossin does not doubt she belongs in the
World Track and Field Championships this time around.
</P>
<P>
   Drossin, 26, passed on the opportunity in 1997, unsure she was
physically or mentally prepared for that level of competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was difficult decision, but I didn't look back,'' said
Drossin, who placed third at the U.S. national championships this
summer and now lives in Alamosa, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew my best years were ahead of me. I have a lot more
experience and I feel I am ready to compete on an international
level.''
</P>
<P>
   At the national meet, Drossin ran a lifetime-best 32:00.72 in
the grueling 10,000 meters, moving into 12th on the all-time
U.S.-performer list in that event.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her world travels, Drossin said her high school coach,
Bill Duley, remains strong in her thoughts. Duley was at the 1997
national cross country championships, watching Drossin win what she
called the breakthrough race of her career. Drossin took the
8,000-meter race by 35 seconds over nine-time national champion and
former world champion Lynn Jennings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see all my races collectively as a progressio, but it
definitely gave me confidence running up in the pack,'' she said.
``Being up there with highly ranked people was thrilling for me and
to be surrounded by people I care about was really great.''
</P>
<P>
   She visits Duley and her parents Paul and Heleana frequently.
Last year, Drossin presented Duley with a glass-framed singlet; she
had worn the singlet when she won her first national cross country
title.
</P>
<P>
   Drossin wrote: ``Bill Duley, Thank you for molding me into this
sport that has given me so much in return.'' The jersey is
prominently displayed in Duley's running store in Agoura Hills.
Drossin said her years competing under Duley led to her success.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always encouraging and I still hold his philosophies to
this day,'' she said. ``I remember him for his excellent coaching,
not necessarily running extra laps for being late for practice, but
mostly showing the fun side of the sport and rewards of running.''
</P>
<P>
   The world championships will be Drossin's toughest test. Along
with adapting to the heat and humidity of Seville, she must run two
quality races in two days if she advances to the finals. Drossin,
who has spent the past month competing in Europe, will train in
Portugal for two weeks prior to the world championships to
acclimate herself to the conditions.
</P>
<P>
   However, it has been in the thin air of Alamosa, Colo., that she
has rediscovered her zeal for running after an injury-plagued
career at Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Training under coach Joe Vigil for the past three years has
rejuvenated Drossin, who enjoys tending to her herb garden or
taking runs along the Rio Grande with her 3-year-old chocolate
Labrador retriever, Aspen, and her boyfriend, marathoner Jeff
Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a positive environment, simple and fulfilling,'' she
said. ``It's the best place for me. I'm training more consistently.
It has allowed me to have a narrower focus instead of worrying
about school and other distractions.''
</P>
<P>
   Running with an all-male group that includes Campbell, former
Agoura teammate Bryan Dameworth (a four-time state champion in
cross country and track), and former area standouts Derek Kite
(Camarillo) and Peter De La Cerda (Granada Hills) has steadily
built her mileage up from 40-50 a week in college to as many as
100.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is one of the finer young distance runners in America,''
said Vigil, who led Adams State to 25 NAIA or NCAA Division II
cross country titles in 28 seasons before retiring in 1993. ``There
are a lot of other girls as talented as Deena, but there aren't
many as disciplined and dedicated. She places things in perspective
and doesn't worry about the competition. She's confident in her
abilities and runs her own race.''
</P>
<P>
   That confidence surfaced when Drossin first began running at age
13. While at Agoura, she decorated her hotel room with signs
congratulating herself the evening before the state cross country
championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was always a competitor,'' Duley said. ``She had the
ability to dial in on her self-confidence when the pressure was
on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
