u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-SHOOT-GUNS-NYT &LR;      07-30 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-SHOOT-GUNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUN CONTROL AWAITS ACTION BY CONFEREES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Utah, S.C., Ala., Vt., Mass., N.Y.)  (With GA-SHOOT and related stories.) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The issue of gun-control legislation has come back
to life in Congress this week, and to anyone unfamiliar with the
ways of Washington, it might appear that some kind of law is about
to be enacted.
</P>
<P>
   But in fact, there may be no law enacted for months.
</P>
<P>
   And whether there is a law probably will have little to do with
the fallout over the shooting in Atlanta and more to do with the
political sensitivities of Washington, some members of Congress
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta bloodshed brought expressions of sorrow and
determination from lawmakers, even though it was not clear by
Thursday night whether the killer had obtained his weapons
illegally, or even whether any gun control short of outright
confiscation could have prevented the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nita Lowey, D-N.Y., said, ``This terrible tragedy
highlights once again how important it is that we enact meaningful
gun-safety legislation. The American people are demanding action.''
</P>
<P>
   The subject of gun control is fraught with emotion and political
sensitivities, which is why the House and Senate could not agree
when various firearms regulations were debated earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   What happened, basically, was that the Senate passed certain
restrictions, including mandatory background checks on all
customers at gun shows, that were attached to a bill on juvenile
crime.
</P>
<P>
   But the House could not agree on gun control, because some
members thought the various proposals were too strict, other
proposals too lenient. So the House version included nothing about
gun control.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has lain mostly dormant as leaders in the two chambers
took up other battles.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the legislative prospects will become a bit clearer when
the House names its conference committee members on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The members, appointed Wednesday, are Sens. Orrin Hatch of Utah,
Strom Thurmond of South Carolina and Jeff Sessions of Alabama,
Republicans; and Patrick Leahy of Vermont and Edward Kennedy of
Massachusetts, Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Carolyn McCarthy, a Long Island, N.Y., Democrat, said,
``The conferees are going back in and trying to pass what the
Senate passed; hopefully this will be done by next October.'' Mrs.
McCarthy's husband was killed when a gunman opened fire on a Long
Island Rail Road train in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The first obstacle comes after next week when Congress will
recess for four weeks. That means the conference committee will
probably not complete its reconciliation of the juvenile crime bill
until September, or perhaps October.
</P>
<P>
   But it would surprise no one who had watched Congress agonize
over the issue to see the politics of late spring and early summer
re-enacted.
</P>
<P>
   That is, the conferees could get caught up in the paralysis that
stalled the House, and in the end agree on nothing.
</P>
<P>
   And even if the conferees compromise enough to agree on some
kind of gun control, President Clinton had threatened to veto any
measures that he deems too weak.
</P>
<P>
   The president was in Sarajevo, Bosnia, Thursday and had no
immediate comment on the Atlanta bloodshed, but he described
himself as deeply upset in April after the shooting at the high
school in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
