<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GA-SHOOT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE SHOOTINGS IN ATLANTA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (CHANGES daughters to children in 4th graf, changes ``in'' to
``is`` in last graf) (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, July 30: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, the fatal shooting of nine people in Atlanta
Thursday can be seen in isolation, as the mad handiwork of a lone
individual venting uniquely twisted grievances through the barrel
of a gun. Yet the incident is also part of a larger and dismally
familiar story of shootings that seem increasingly to pop up out of
nowhere and in the most unlikely places _ in orderly small towns,
in offices, in suburban schools, in genteel neighborhoods and, in
this case, in the commercial district of the well-to-do Buckhead
section of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   There is one other thread that connects these shootings to the
others. It is of course hard if not impossible to protect society
from a determined killer camouflaged, as this one was, by his own
ordinariness. But it is also true that there are too many weapons
floating around this country _ 200 million at last count _ and,
because of the continuing failure of our national legislators, too
many ways for people to get their hands on those weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta killer has been identified by police as Mark Barton,
a 44-year-old suburbanite and day trader in stocks who walked into
a brokerage office in the Piedmont Center, made an apparently
casual comment about the drop in stock prices and suddenly opened
fire.
</P>
<P>
   He then walked across the street and started shooting in another
office in the same complex. Nine people died altogether, and a
dozen others were wounded. Later in the day, when the police
spotted his van and pulled him over, he shot himself. He apparently
was suspected but never charged in two murders in 1993. Police
suspect he may also have killed his wife and two children , who
were found dead Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the toll rises, in the workplace and in the schools. Just
last month a psychiatrist in Michigan was shot by a former patient,
who then gunned down a 45-year-old woman and wounded others. In
April, a 71-year-old man raked the first floor of a Mormon library
in Salt Lake City with gunfire from a .22 caliber handgun, killing
two people and wounding four others. In March, a Johnson City,
Tenn., man shot his lawyer and another client in an apparent
dispute over his former wife's will.
</P>
<P>
   Before that were the killings that gave grotesque definition to
the 1997-98 school year _ students dead and wounded in Pearl,
Miss.; West Paducah, Ky.; Edinboro, Pa.; Jonesboro, Ark., and
Springfield, Ore. All of that seemed but a preamble to this year's
carnage at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo. This is an
appalling list, and while there are no easy answers, the failure of
Congress to limit access to weapons among dangerous or unbalanced
individuals is appalling, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
