<HEADLINE>
PAPPAS DEFENDS HIS ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-PAPPAS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Red Sox doctor Arthur Pappas Thursday defended his
handling of pitcher Tom Gordon's medical care, saying that the Sox
closer was supportive of delaying surgery until other avenues,
including rest and treatment, proved futile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently he has decided that people have not been honest
with him,'' said Pappas in an interview on Boston radio station
WEEI. Pappas said Gordon was a full participant in discussions
about his treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This discussion has been had right along. He's very much
wanted to stay involved with the team, contribute to the team if he
could, and then if something had to be done after the season, it
would be done at that time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe, in what you're saying to me, all that is out of
focus and today he has a different opinion than what the discussion
has been about in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Pappas also expressed surprise and disappointment that Red Sox
star Nomar Garciaparra voiced indirect criticism of the medical
treatment Sox players receive.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by WEEI's John Dennis if Garciaparra was qualified to be
critical, Pappas said: ``Well, apparently he feels he is. It's not
uncommon that when someone excels in the athletic arena, everyone
believes their opinion is the accurate opinion all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday afternoon in Toronto, after Gordon informed teammates
he probably would require Tommy John tendon transfer surgery on his
right elbow, Garciaparra had loudly criticized the team's medical
staff to his teammates, while reporters were in the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our doctors are killing us,'' Garciaparra said to teammates,
then made a reference to the delay last season in diagnosing Lou
Merloni's stress fracture, which was first diagnosed as a bone
bruise.
</P>
<P>
   Pappas, asked if players have second-guessed him to his face,
said: ``Nomar _ I am surprised to hear that from Nomar, but that's
in a moment of stress and his friend (Merloni) not doing as well. I
think that all those are concerns that he has to weigh in whatever
way he wants to.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who pitching coach Joe Kerrigan said told him that he
originally hurt his elbow last November while pitching in an
exhibition series in Japan, had problems with the elbow in spring
training and has since been on the disabled list twice this season,
the last time for six weeks. Gordon was placed on the DL,
retroactive to June 11, when an MRI revealed a small ligament tear
and inflammation of the ulnar nerve.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, Pappas prescribed rest and anti-inflammatory
medication. That opinion was supported by Dr. James Andrews, the
Birmingham, Ala.-based orthopedist Gordon sought out for a second
opinion. But six weeks later, Gordon continued to feel discomfort,
and after expressing dismay that Andrews had not received the
results of a second MRI two weeks ago, Gordon was told by Andrews,
who finally reviewed the pictures Wednesday, that the ligament tear
was still present.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon will not pitch for the rest of the season and almost
certainly will have to undergo the tendon transfer surgery to
repair the ligament, a procedure that often requires a year of
recovery time.
</P>
<P>
   Pappas said Gordon was apprised of that possibility throughout
the discussions of his condition, yet preferred to see if more
conservative treatment _ the rest and medication _ would prove
beneficial.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Tom Gordon had come to me in October last year or early
this year and said, `This is my problem, here are the findings,
then I am sure the discussion would be `I think you should have
this done' and it would have been done,'' Pappas said. ``You'd like
to give all opportunities to the resolution of the problem before
you say `OK, your season is over, it can't work.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And I think that's the frustration that . . . it gets to the
point where if something didn't resolve, then you go back and say,
`Well, why didn't you do something sooner?' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
