<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-SPELLMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS SIGN SPELLMAN TO ONE-YEAR DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Defensive end Alonzo Spellman sped across
the practice field on the passenger seat of a golf cart yesterday
afternoon. The Dallas Cowboys now hope to re-create a similar image
in terms of Spellman running down opposing quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   After much deliberation, the Cowboys signed the 27-year-old,
out-of-work free agent to a one-year, $400,000 contract with an
incentive package that can reach $800,000. The incentives are
categorized as ``hard to make.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He would have to be a monster year to reach them,'' said
Stephen Jones, vice president/director of player personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Spellman, who was Mike Ditka's last first-round draft choice in
Chicago (22nd overall, 1992) last played in the NFL for the '97
Bears. In 1998, he encountered a series of highly publicized
emotional problems, including one incident in which he barricaded
himself inside his publicist's home during an eight-hour standoff
with police, and was waived by the Bears three months later.
</P>
<P>
   No other team in the NFL even tried to sign him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done our homework on him, and we're satisfied that he
fits in,'' Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said. ``He has given us a
commitment. He does not join our team subject to suspension by the
league. We've checked and confirmed that with the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get a player who has had success, and a player who has had
some challenges, and a player who can be very productive for us
without any risk. When we got everything answered that we wanted
answered, it didn't take me 30 seconds to make my mind up.''
</P>
<P>
   Spellman brings to the Cowboys both an upside and a downside of
notable proportions.
</P>
<P>
   He has 27 NFL career sacks. He has what has been described as
the perfect NFL body. He was, and is once he gets back into playing
shape, in the prime of his career.
</P>
<P>
   He also has had a series of off-field behavior incidents caused
by a manic-depressive condition known as bipolar disorder.
</P>
<P>
   As Cowboys coach Chan Gailey put it yesterday: ``You could paint
a picture (of Spellman) about any way you'd want to paint it.''
</P>
<P>
   Spellman's condition can be regulated with medication. The
Cowboys needed a commitment from Spellman that he would stick to
his medication and apparently received one.
</P>
<P>
   Jones also credited Calvin Hill, who oversees the Cowboys'
behavior department, which was established only a few years ago,
with ``providing the resources to allow us to make a decision like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Spellman was in team meetings last night when Jones held a news
conference to announce the signing. Spellman arrived in camp
yesterday after making the two-hour drive from Dallas, where he had
been staying since Monday when he met with both Jones and Gailey.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg said of his client: ``You have to keep in mind that
Alonzo Spellman's problems have not been willful behavior,''
adding, ``This guy was everything I was looking for in a role
model, then he got sick.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones was reminded yesterday that they passed up wide receiver
Randy Moss in the 1998 NFL draft because they wanted to improve the
team's image, not risk a setback.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the fact that Spellman's problems can be traced to a
bipolar condition treatable through medication, Moss ``required a
No. 1 pick,'' Jones pointed out, while Spellman ``was signed for
the league minimum for a veteran.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Jones: ``So is this a departure from what we're doing? Not
at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the March 9, 1998, standoff with police which ended
only when ex-Bears Hall of Famer Mike Singletary talked him into
surrendering, Spellman kicked down the door of a hospital the next
day and was found by police wandering in frigid conditions with no
shirt or shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Two months later, he was involved in a scuffle with a security
guard at a Detroit hotel, where police reportedly needed pepper
spray to quiet Spellman, who was trying to break up a fight between
two women accompanying him. No charges were filed. He was divorced
that same month.
</P>
<P>
   ``If and when I get to be perfect, then I'll be able to throw
harsh judgment at other people,'' Gailey said when asked about
dealing with Spellman's transgressions. ``But if somebody is
willing to try and do things the right way _ and it doesn't matter
who it is, whether it's this guy or anybody else _ I think
forgiveness and second chances are a part of life.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Spellman hasn't played for so long concerns Gailey
and the Cowboys' coaching staff as much as anything else. Nineteen
months is a long time between putting on pads, which Spellman will
do today for the first time since the end of the '97 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very physical player with great athletic ability. I
just don't know what kind of shape he's in,'' said Cowboys
defensive coordinator Dave Campo. ``He's been out for a year ...
(but) I expect him to play. How quickly he does, we'll have to wait
and see.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys believe they've made the right move, the smart move,
for both themselves and Spellman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you take into consideration somebody's past? Sure,'' Gailey
said. ``But I'm much more interested in the present and the future
of a person than forever comdemning somebody for what they've done
in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   The future for Alonzo Spellman begins today. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
