<SLUG> BC-AID-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE VOTES TO TRIM FUNDS FOR SCHOOL FOR LATIN AMERICAN SOLDIERS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House voted early Friday to withhold
recruitment money for the Army's School of the Americas, a facility
long criticized for training Latin American officers who turned out
to be tyrants and murderers.
</P>
<P>
   The school's graduates include Gen. Manuel Noriega, the dictator
of Panama, now imprisoned in Miami on a drug conviction; the late
Roberto D'Aubuisson, a reputed death squad commander and political
leader in El Salvador, and dozens of soldiers accused of political
killings in El Salvador and Peru.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was 230-197, with 56 Republicans joining 174 Democrats
to support the measure, sponsored by Rep. Joe Moakley, D-Mass.. On
the floor supporters denounced the school as a Cold War relic and
an academy for assassins. The measure would withhold about $1.5
million for recruiting and transporting officers to the school at
Fort Benning, Ga. The school has an operating budget of about $15
million.
</P>
<P>
   The vote came as an amendment to the $12.7 billion foreign aid
bill, which the House began debating Thursday night. The House
adjourned after midnight, postponing until Monday a final vote on
the bill, which would slash nearly $2 billion from the White
House's request, including half a billion dollars aimed at
furthering peace in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the $500 million that the administration had
requested to carry out the Israeli-Palestinian accords reached last
year, the bill would also cut $200 million for a World Bank
subsidiary that provides interest-free loans to the world's poorest
and least-developed nations.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Senate, which passed a similar bill in June, the House
made an unusual acknowledgment of a covert American relationship
with a foreign intelligence service.
</P>
<P>
   In a report accompanying the bill, the House criticized American
``support for Peruvian National Intelligence Service.'' It said the
agency had been ``directly implicated in death squad activity'' and
that it ``withholds intelligence from U.S. officials.'' It said
that the agency was not ``accountable to civilian authorities'' and
``is not a reliable partner in he drug war.''
</P>
<P>
   The foreign aid bill is primarily a vehicle for direct economic
assistance for American allies overseas like Israel and Egypt. But
it also annually becomes a forum for debate over abortion, birth
control and family planning abroad.
</P>
<P>
   By a 228-200 vote, the House passed an amendment barring
American funds for family-planning assistance from being spent by
foreign governments or organizations that perform abortions,
promote abortion rights or seek to liberalize abortion laws.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment's sponsor, Rep. Christopher H. Smith, R-N.J.,
called the spending of U.S. funds for family planning overseas a
form of ``cultural imperialism.'' He has been trying for five years
to reinstate the restrictions, imposed by the Reagan and Bush
administrations and lifted by President Clinton in 1993. The House
has passed his bill yearly since 1995, but the measure has never
made it past the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of a bipartisan alternative said they hoped to
prevail in a House-Senate conference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-99 0108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990730.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 01:09 </DATE_TIME>
