A9491 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIG-BREAK-LADN     07-30 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIG-BREAK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFI GRANT GIVES WOMAN DIRECT SHOT AT FILM DREAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDS, this is first in five-part series.) 
BY STEVE CARNEY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Not long after dawn, a vintage Thunderbird
lumbered beneath a Ronald Reagan Freeway overpass, the eyes of a
film crew locked on its progress.
</P>
<P>
   The scene was unremarkable except for the credit that will one
day share the screen with it: ``A film by Joanne Small.''
</P>
<P>
   That credit has been an elusive dream for the Studio City
resident ever since she was a teen-age movie buff growing up in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fell in love with movies at a young age. I was watching D.W.
Griffith and Charlie Chaplin and John Ford,'' Small said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, Hmmm _ that's what I want to do. I want to be a
director. But I had no idea how difficult that was going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   For nine years she's toiled in Hollywood, working as a sound and
film editor, screenwriter and a script supervisor, most recently on
``The X-Files.'' Before that she attended New York University's
graduate film school. Every deliberate step extended her filmmaking
skills as she crafted her path to the director's chair.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday she took a seat.
</P>
<P>
   She began videotaping her project for the Directing Workshop for
Women, an exclusive program of the American Film Institute, the
organization dedicated to preserving and promoting excellence in
movies and television.
</P>
<P>
   As one of eight winners out of about 150 applicants, Small got
approval to begin shooting her movie, ``Joey Was Here,'' a
``Twilight Zone''-esque tale of a young man driving from New Jersey
to Hollywood who gets trapped en route in a surreal service
station.
</P>
<P>
   ``The AFI has this program, thank goodness,'' she said.
``Finally someone has said, You deserve a break. And I'm very, very
thankful for that.''
</P>
<P>
   AFI gives each winner in the program a $5,000 grant and access
to equipment. Participants can raise up to an additional $15,000
with which they produce a 20-minute short film in five days,
somewhere in the Los Angeles area.
</P>
<P>
   The women's workshop began 25 years ago with a class of
beginning directors that included actresses Lee Grant and Ellen
Burstyn, and poet Maya Angelou. Grant went on to win an Academy
Award for directing the best documentary of 1987.
</P>
<P>
   The program continues to target women who have excelled in other
areas of entertainment who are looking for a chance to direct.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about the nurturing of talent,'' said AFI chief
executive Jean Picker Firstenberg. ``Very gifted people need an
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no other program of its kind specifically for women
who have talent in the profession,'' she said. ``It gives them a
window to directing that is not otherwise available. It's about
that individual vision, and seeing that flower is exactly why we
plant the seeds.''
</P>
<P>
   But as much as she cherishes the program, she hopes one day it's
no longer needed. She said they're making strides, but women are
far from being on an equal footing with men in filmmaking _ only
13percent of the directors in the Directors Guild of America are
women, or 721 out of 5,714 as of Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this community, there are very, very few opportunities for
professional women to make the jump. Now it's my turn,'' Small
said. ``To me, the highest joy I can get is when I'm immersed in
directing. Everybody should want to go to work as badly as I do.''
</P>
<P>
   On the set, a sunbaked dust bowl of parking lot off Rocky Peak
Road, Small darted from the cast-and-crew trailer to the caterer's
tent to the truck towing the cars being used in the movie _
checking on every detail, cheerfully making sure everyone else had
what they needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``How's everybody doing? Has everybody eaten?'' she asked.
Grabbing her own lunch between takes, she said, ``I've been too
busy to eat. I made a bologna sandwich one night, and every time I
went to take a bite, the phone rang. That bologna sandwich lasted
me an hour and a half.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Carlson, one of the two producers of ``Joey Was Here,''
said he has tried to act as a calming influence on the set. Like
everyone else there, he's working for free _ most are friends of
Small's, helping her out and looking for increased experience
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're excited for her _ it's a great opportunity,'' he said,
adding that she's the one person he hasn't had to calm.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's probably got it figured out six ways to Sunday,''
Carlson said. ``She's a freak _ she lives, breathes and eats this
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlson called Small ``the next Penny Marshall,'' referring to
the former ``Laverne and Shirley'' star who went on to direct
feature films including ``Big,'' ``Awakenings'' and ``A League of
Their Own.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Small, he said, ``I've seen her vision. She's got the goods.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be her calling card,'' Carlson said. ``This
is the first project that's going to have `Directed by Joanne
Small' on it.''
</P>
<P>
   But first Small has to make it to Monday. And her lead actor
quit to take a paying job, her wardrobe mistress had a car break
down on the way to the shoot, and the Agoura Hills City Hall might
close before she gets permits to film there Monday.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-99 0109EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990730.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 01:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9493 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-dale-HNS &LR;      07-30 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-dale </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Like 61, 755's days may be numbered
<TEXT>
<P>
   By DALE ROBERTSON
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   Here they go again. Mac and Sammy. Sammy and Mac. Dinger derby,
the sequel.
</P>
<P>
   Quietly, minus the trumpets of a year ago, Mark McGwire and
Sammy Sosa have muscled their way through the hoi polloi to reclaim
their rightful place atop the home-run standings. It's a dead heat.
Mac has 37 and so does Sammy.
</P>
<P>
   That's four more than anyone else in the chase. That's also a
61-homer pace, formerly a magical number. Had 1998 never happened,
the hysteria would be building.
</P>
<P>
   But we're jaded, aren't we? After The Great Race, which saw
McGwire (70) and Sosa (66) turn Roger Maris into a historical
footnote, the laddies are going to have to jack a whole bunch more
before anyone gets too overheated. Until one or the other reaches
60, preferably before the end of August, it's almost a non-story.
</P>
<P>
   Amazing.
</P>
<P>
   But such are the wretched excesses of our day. And, in the age
of andro, no records are safe, even Henry Aaron's.
</P>
<P>
   Hammerin' Hank went yard 755 times, obliterating Babe Ruth's
``unbreakable'' 714, one of sport's most famous numbers. Yet there
are six active players who must be considered reasonable threats to
surpass Aaron _ and McGwire and Sosa, ironically, are closer to the
bottom than the top of the list.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's problem is he's 35. Were he to hit 60 this year, he
still would need to average 48 for the next five seasons to bump
Aaron into second place. Even for Big Mac, the only player besides
Ruth to average that many over half a decade, such a feat so late
in one's career would be a lot to ask.
</P>
<P>
   As for Sosa, 30, supposing he also whacks 60, he would need a
little more than 42 per for the next 10 seasons to climb Hank's
majestic mountain. Both, nonetheless, seem solid candidates to join
the Babe and Aaron in the 700 club.
</P>
<P>
   We have to look to the Junior Circuit, and specifically to the
young man we call Junior, to find the gravest threat to Aaron. Ken
Griffey Jr., based on the prodigious pace he has set during his
first decade of ripping through the American League, should wind up
as the greatest home-run hitter ever.
</P>
<P>
   His target number is, yikes, 800.
</P>
<P>
   If Griffey stays the course he's on, he'll finish the season
with 52 homers for a career total of 402 before his 30th birthday.
Assuming he can play until he's 40, and there's no reason to
believe he can't considering his fat-free body, he would have to
average a shade over 36 for the next 11 years to get there.
</P>
<P>
   At 30, Aaron had ``only'' 366 home runs, Willie Mays 319 and
Ruth 309. Mays wound up third on the all-time list with 660.
Notably, Jimmie Foxx had 379 and Mickey Mantle 374 when they were
30. But Foxx's career would be torn asunder by World War II and he
finished with 534. Mantle, a physical wreck late in his career,
ended his chase at 536.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Griffey, three other mighty twentysomething American
Leaguers _ Juan Gonzalez, Manny Ramirez and Alex Rodriguez _ can't
be summarily dismissed as contenders for Aaron's throne.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' Gonzalez, 29 like Griffey, has bashed 40 or more
homers the past three seasons and he's on track to up his streak to
four. Still, he would need 10 more years at 42 per to surpass
Aaron.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians' Ramirez, 27, belted 45 a year ago and has 27 to
date. Thirteen more seasons at 43 per and he's in Henry's face.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey's precocious Mariners teammate Rodriguez, 23, might have
the best shot of all. Assuming he hits 40 this season _ he has 23 _
17 more seasons at 36 per would put him there. At present, he's
averaging just under 34.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, Rodriguez seems a lock to destroy the record
for dingers by a shortstop. Cal Ripken's 345 and counting is tops,
but A-Rod figures to blow by 350 before he turns 30. Nomar
Garciaparra, 26, is well off Rodriguez's pace, but he probably has
350 home runs in him.
</P>
<P>
   Lively balls, puny pitching, shrinking ballparks and high-tech
muscle-building are conspiring to jeopardize most of the position
homer standards save for perhaps pitcher (Wes Ferrell, who was
rarely pinch-hit for, smacked 36) and third base. Mike Schmidt's
hot-corner total of 539 (548 overall) appears unreachable.
</P>
<P>
   With 142, Roberto Alomar, 31, will push Ryne Sandberg (270) at
second base. With 220, Mets catcher Mike Piazza, 30, is within
striking distance of Carlton Fisk's 376.
</P>
<P>
   Home runs sell tickets and, at today's salaries, the clubs need
to sell as many as they can. Nobody will be dumb enough to try to
de-juice the game.
</P>
<P>
   Mac and Sammy aren't freaks of nature. Rather, they're on the
front end of what figures to be a long-term long-ball trend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
