<HEADLINE>
LAKERS WILL RE-SIGN FOX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With the signing period just two days away, the
Los Angeles Lakers are moving swiftly toward retaining free agents
Rick Fox and Derek Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to the team indicated the Lakers are ready to
offer Fox a multiyear deal starting at just over $3 million.
Contract length is the only remaining issue, with Fox seeking a
maximum six-year deal that would total close to $24 million.
</P>
<P>
   Fox seems likely to get his wish. The 30-year-old forward has
twice turned down more lucrative offers elsewhere to to sign with
the Lakers, and the team is apparently planning to reward his
loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher's prospects for staying are less certain, but his agent
is optimistic a deal will be reached after meeting with general
manager Mitch Kupchak on Thursday. The Lakers presented Fisher,
their starter for most of last season, an initial contract offer
Thursday, in a face-to-face meeting with Fisher and agent Elbert
Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   According to Crawford, contract length will not be a stumbling
block, but the Lakers' first offer is short of what other teams
have offered. Toronto, Indiana, Miami, Orlando and San Antonio are
among the teams pursuing the three-year veteran.
</P>
<P>
   The gap between the Lakers' offer and Fisher's target salary is
``not very significant,'' Crawford said. ``I wouldn't say it's an
ungodly amount of difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the offer indicated to Crawford that the Lakers, in
transition under new coach Phil Jackson, might not be totally
committed to bringing Fisher back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's still some questions there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The parties will probably speak again today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm optimistic something can get done,'' Crawford said. ``The
willingness has to be on the Lakers' part. They made an offer today
that wasn't a bad offer, it wasn't a good offer.''
</P>
<P>
   NBA teams have been negotiating with free agents since July 1
but have been prevented from signing deals or making trades until
Aug 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
