<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' HUTSON SPRAINS KNEE, WILL BE OUT TWO TO FOUR WEEKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ The Dallas Cowboys' offensive line
suffered a setback Thursday when reserve offensive lineman Tony
Hutson suffered a sprained medial collateral ligament in his right
knee that is expected to sideline him for two to four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Hutson had been tabbed to replace right guard Everett McIver,
who is still recovering from a torn anterior cruciate ligament that
cut short his 1998 season. McIver is not expected back until late
August.
</P>
<P>
   Backup center Mike Kiselak, who played some guard last season,
could be the leading candidate to fill in for Hutson. The other
options are rookie second-round pick Solomon Page and first-year
players Freddie Childress and Chris Brymer. ANOTHER SPORT FOR
DEION?
</P>
<P>
   Injured cornerback Deion Sanders reported to camp Thursday with
the rest of the veterans, looking to add to his list of sporting
endeavors.
</P>
<P>
   Already a documented football and baseball player and avid
fisherman, Sanders initially looked to be taking a cue from Lance
Armstrong, as he rode onto the practice field during the morning
practice on a bicycle.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of a long conversation with Cowboys owner Jerry
Jones regarding his rehabilitation progress from April toe surgery,
Sanders revealed that he was playing basketball as a part of his
therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all very curious,'' Jones said. ``He's been running and
playing a little basketball. It causes him to get on his toes
pretty good. But he's cautious. He's getting some strength that
way.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as Sanders' return is concerned, Jones said, ``the facts
are we don't know anymore about when he will play. It's looking
good, but that's all we can say.'' HELLESTRAE BACK FOR ANOTHER YEAR
</P>
<P>
   In the mood to save money, the Cowboys seriously considered life
without deep snapper Dale Hellestrae.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take the Cowboys long to change their mind, thus
Hellestrae reported for his 10th training camp with the team
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said Hellestrae, considered one of the
league's best deep snappers, is hard to replace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dale is very good at what he does,'' Gailey said. ``He has
created a good niche that is tough to replace. He has set a
standard that's hard to top.'' IRVIN AND THE OFFENSE
</P>
<P>
   Just when Cowboys receiver Michael Irvin thought he had the
team's intricate offense down, coach Chan Gailey threw him for a
loss.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said he implemented only about 85 percent of his massive
playbook last year. He plans to give the rest of it to the team
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That scares me,'' said Irvin, who said he's just getting the
85 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he plans on putting in more, that tells you what kind of
work I have to do.'' FROM RIVALS TO PALS
</P>
<P>
   Aggies and Longhorns across the state would be astonished to
learn that former Texas receiver Wane McGarity and former Texas A&AMP;M
linebacker Dat Nguyen have become fast friends since joining the
Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   The two have almost been inseparable at training camp _ riding
to lunch together and going to and from practice together.
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen said it's a natural relationship, as he's known McGarity
since the two took a recruiting trip together as seniors in high
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was going to come to Texas A&AMP;M,'' Nguyen said.
</P>
<P>
   McGarity would have none of that. He said he likes Nguyen. His
only problem with his new friend is that ``he's an Aggie.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
