<HEADER>
A9502 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RODEO-LANEFROST-TEX     07-30 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RODEO-LANE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROST'S LEGACY LIVES ON 10 YEARS AFTER HIS DEATH
</HEADLINE>
 FROST-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT HOFFMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a Sunday afternoon of oyster gray skies and drizzle at the
1989 Cheyenne Frontier Days Rodeo, Lane Frost eased atop a snorting
bull named Taking Care Of Business.
</P>
<P>
   At the final performance of the sport's equivalent to a
Wimbledon stage, the 1987 world champion bailed off the bull after
eight seconds and rolled onto the soggy soil. Taking Care Of
Business uncharacteristically then charged and plunged his mammoth
ivory horns in Frost's back. The hit didn't break the skin, medical
officials said, but caused massive internal bleeding, ending
Frost's life within minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Frost's legacy lives, however.
</P>
<P>
   Friday is the 10th anniversary of his death at age 25. A
ceremony honoring Frost is scheduled during the afternoon
performance of the Wyoming rodeo's 103rd edition.
</P>
<P>
   Frost envisioned spurring the sport to another level. Today, the
top performers sew on as many sponsorship patches as their
bulletproof vests can hold while competing on a nationally
televised tour. In Frost's era, when there were only a handful of
high-profile bull-riding shows, a souped-up series was only a gleam
in a bull rider's eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lane was ahead of his time,'' said Kellie Macy of Post,
Frost's wife at the time of his death. ``For his age, he was way
further along in years than most competitors in that he realized
the importance of promoting himself and rodeo.''
</P>
<P>
   In the decade since Frost's death, rodeo has adopted many of its
practices and formats from more popular sports using Frost's
lifestyle as a model. Three examples:
</P>
<P>
   A national tour: In 1985 and 1986, Frost competed on the Winston
Tour, a series of shows that featured the sport's marquee
competitors in bucking stock and timed events, such as calf roping
and barrel racing. But the Professional Rodeo Cowboys Association
voted to end the tour in 1987, which irked marketable athletes such
as Frost, Tuff Hedeman and Dave Appleton.
</P>
<P>
   Three years after Frost's death, Hedeman, who was Frost's best
friend and traveling partner, became the founding patriarch of
Professional Bull Riders. The PBR offers a 29-city, $5.5 million
tour in North America. Today, the PRCA has plans to re-employ a
tour format for its high-profile athletes, commissioner Steve
Hatchell said.
</P>
<P>
   A Bull vs. Cowboy promotion: In 1988, Frost engaged in a
best-of-seven series against a bull named Red Rock. The bull, which
had never had a qualified ride on his back after 309 tries, was
brought out of retirement for the series against Frost on the West
Coast. Frost stayed aboard Red Rock four times.
</P>
<P>
   Today, highly touted showdowns commonly are staged in addition
to the regulation rodeo. Hedeman's PBR show in March in Fort Worth
featured a $10,000 match between a marquee bull and rider. If the
bull wins, its owner collects; if the cowboy wins, he's secured the
highest spin atop the Wheel of Fortune.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the PRCA landed a bounty bull program with a national
automobile dealership. Riders collect for staying on a bull for the
required eight seconds. Each time a designated bull bucks off a
rider, the bounty increases $500. After bucking off 43 consecutive
riders, the bounty for staying on the Mesquite Championship Rodeo
bull, Dodge Durango, is a record $30,500.
</P>
<P>
   The necessity for protective equipment: Frost was not wearing a
protective vest when he died. Ten years ago, virtually no
competitor wore protective gear. Today, almost every bull rider
does.
</P>
<P>
   Frost's death might be the most dramatic event in rodeo history.
With his rugged good looks, his charismatic personality and his
championship form on rodeo's roughest event, Frost was the ultimate
package for sponsors and fans.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Fleming, the PRCA communications director of the past two
decades, said Frost, who notched only one world title, is more
prominent than cowboys with multiple championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``His smile was infectious,'' Fleming said. ``He was like a
grown-up little kid with his good manners. His achievements, along
with his personality, the way he died and where he died make him
legendary.''
</P>
<P>
   Hedeman, who became one of rodeo's most marketable athletes from
modeling his career after Frost, said if his friend were competing
today he would be in the thick of lucrative title-race hunts on the
PBR tour and would rope in huge sponsorship packages.
</P>
<P>
   Frost's legacy accelerated down a network of other trails. His
biography is portrayed in the Hollywood movie Eight Seconds, with
Luke Perry playing the lead role. Songs, poems and books testify of
his legend. Rodeo achievement awards beam a neon Frost label.
</P>
<P>
   More than 40,000 Bibles that feature a picture of Frost riding
have been mailed from Frost's family church in Southeastern
Oklahoma; his parents say that Lane's faith in Christianity has
gained numerous converts after Lane's life testimony is read from
the Bibles.
</P>
<P>
   Frost's family are spokespersons for his legacy. His parents,
Clyde and Elsie Frost, live in Lane, Okla., and make numerous
public appearances at rodeos and church services.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Kellie Macy, married two-time National Finals team
roper Mike Macey and they are rearing their two small children in
the West Texas town of Post. Hedeman, who broke the news of Frost's
death to his wife and parents from Cheyenne by phone, lives on a
ranch in Morgan Mill and presides over the PBR.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on the fatality, Kellie Macy said: ``What Tuff and I
have done is show that you can triumph over what happened and not
be bitter.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
