r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-HOLTZ-SEC-TEX     07-30 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HOLTZ-SEC-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLTZ FINDS WEIGHT OF NEW JOB AT SOUTH CAROLINA REQUIRES HUMOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ All that was missing was a couch and Johnny
Carson or Jay Leno.
</P>
<P>
   As the new coach at downtrodden South Carolina, Lou Holtz is
back on stage and in the spotlight. He dominated both as the final
speaker at Thursday's Southeastern Conference football media days.
As always, humor was a major component of Holtz's 41-minute
interview session.
</P>
<P>
   Laughter is one way to camouflage the Gamecocks' considerable
shortcomings. Holtz, who has a national championship, 216 victories
in 27 seasons at five previous college coaching stops, is now in
charge of a program that has as many Heisman Trophy winners as bowl
victories (one of each).
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an answer to every problem. Can we find the answers?''
Holtz said. ``All I'll promise is, we won't forfeit. We will win at
South Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
   When Holtz speaks before a pack of rapt reporters, he seemingly
has a one liner for each of his coaching victories. The trick is
reading between the lines.
</P>
<P>
   Holtz loves to run the ball. His son, Skip, left a good job at
Connecticut to become his father's offensive coordinator. ``My son
loves to throw the football. He'll call the plays until we throw 11
passes and then I'll call 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   First joke, first translation: ``Lou Holtz will do what it takes
to win. In his mind, that means a dominant running game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Coaches told me not to take this job because you can't win at
South Carolina. So why did I take the job? The psychiatrist who
examined me asked the same question.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: ``Holtz left Notre Dame in 1996 with a bad taste.
His ego demands he turn around one more program before he
retires.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what would be a good season, Holtz answered: ``In all
honesty, winning a national championship.'' That of course, brought
laughter. Holtz knows a comedian's biggest asset is his delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: ``Holtz knows he doesn't have the talent to win
now. And playing in the SEC's East Division, the best that South
Carolina can usually hope for is finishing fourth behind Tennessee,
Florida and Georgia. But that doesn't mean he won't try.''
</P>
<P>
   Largely because of Holtz, South Carolina's first two games
(North Carolina State and Georgia) will be televised by ESPN and
ESPN2. ``I've been asked why. I said they're trying to reduce the
amount of violence on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: ``Holtz wants the emphasis placed on the players.
But since he was hired Dec. 4, interest in Gamecocks football has
been at an all-time high. And that's because of the new coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite a 1-10 record, South Carolina's average attendance was
more than 74,000. ``We raised more money per victory than any
school in America.'' Translation: ``Holtz knows that Gamecocks fans
are loyal and spoiled for a winner. He believes he can supply it.''
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina's opener at N.C. State and the Oct. 16 game
against Arkansas in Little Rock, give Holtz a pair of coaching
homecomings. The near-fatal throat cancer of his wife, Beth, is
under control. His hair is just as sandy blonde, though his glasses
appear a bit thicker. Holtz looks primed for one more coaching
charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the competition in the SEC, this is probably the
most difficult job I've ever taken,'' the 62-year-old Holtz said.
``I'm not a young man. This is not an eight-year rebuilding
program.''
</P>
<P>
   During his 11 seasons at Notre Dame, Holtz was famous for a lot
of things. One was poor mouthing his team's chances against Navy or
Army and the other was building up each week's opponents so that it
appeared that the Irish were playing a schedule full of national
championship contenders.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain. In his first season at South Carolina,
when Holtz denigrates his team and praises the opponent, he'll be
closer to the truth. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
