<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-WAC-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAC COMMISSIONER SAYS LEAGUE HAS CHANCE TO SURVIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING AND JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a brand-new conference heading out after a shattering split,
the WAC has adopted a new slogan: ``Mapping A New Course.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some may wonder if we are just a collection of schools in a
holding tank,'' said commissioner Karl Benson, ``but conferences
mean loyalty, and with these eight schools and a ninth (Nevada)
joining next year, I think we finally have it. We can also identify
the necessary steps to success.''
</P>
<P>
   Foremost among these, Benson said, is a television contract with
Fox that guarantees no upfront revenue but gives the WAC what it
needs most: visability.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is revenue potential if the format succeeds,'' Benson
said, ``but the important thing now is exposure, not revenue.''
</P>
<P>
   The network will provide three national telecasts: TCU-Arizona
on Sept. 5, Fresno-SMU on Oct. 14, and SMU-TCU on Nov. 26, plus
four regional games. The only WAC team left out of the package is
UT-El Paso because of a scheduling problem.
</P>
<P>
   The second step, Benson said, is the bowl package. The WAC
champion will play in the Las Vegas Bowl on Dec. 18 _ ironically,
against the No. 2 team from the Mountain West Conference, composed
of former WAC members. Another WAC team will play in the Mobile
Bowl on Dec. 22, against a Conference USA opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Of the first engagement, Benson said, ``This provides us with a
great opportunity to send a message that the WAC is not a
stepchild. I hope we fill Sam Boyd Stadium and make it hard for
them to turn their back on us (it's a one-year deal).''
</P>
<P>
   The Mobile Bowl, he said, ``is primarily interested in one of
the WAC teams in the Central Time zone (TCU, SMU, Rice, Tulsa)
rather than those on the West Coast.'' In 2000, the WAC champion
will play in the new bowl (Silicon) in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   After noting a variety of new facilities being built around the
league, Benson was asked if the WAC could erase its ``stigma'' of
being regarded as second-rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is a stigma?'' he said. ``It's a perception. You erase
the stigma by changing the perception, and that's what we're going
to do.'' RAINBOW OF A NEW HUE
</P>
<P>
   Describing his job, new Hawaii coach June Jones said, ``We have
a long road ahead of us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rainbow Warriors were 0-12 last year and are working on an
18-game losing streak. They have lost 24 consecutive WAC road
games.
</P>
<P>
   As a starting remedy, Jones has installed the run-and-shoot and
turned over about half of the personnel, and brought in 25 to 30
walk-ons. WAC WHAT?
</P>
<P>
   SMU coach Mike Cavan, for one, remains dry-eyed at the breakup
of the 16-team WAC.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest with you,'' he said, laughing, ``I'm not real
sure I could name all 16 schools.'' UTEP'S `FREAK'
</P>
<P>
   UTEP coach Charlie Bailey, on 6-foot-5, 300-pound Norwegian
defensive end Leif Larsen, reputed to have broken a national record
by bench-pressing 225 pounds 50 times: ``He's kind of a freak of
nature.'' PUNTER COMING BACK
</P>
<P>
   TCU coach Dennis Franchione doesn't consider himself a ``phone
person.'' But he had maybe his best phone conversation in a while
last Saturday when the Horned Frogs' wayward punter, Royce Huffman,
called to say he'd likely be back to play his final season.
</P>
<P>
   Huffman was drafted by the Houston Astros in June and has been
playing in a summer league on the East Coast. Franchione wasn't
sure if Huffman would return for his final year of eligibility.
Huffman wasn't sure either.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he called and said he'd be back by Aug. 20th or 21st,''
Franchione said.
</P>
<P>
   Good news, too. The Frogs have him slated as the starting punter
and wide receiver. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
