<SLUG> BC-GEN-SURF-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`OCCY' UPSET BY BRAZILIAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE STEVENS  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTINGTON BEACH, Calif. _ A few minutes elapsed, then boom!
</P>
<P>
   The biggest upset in professional surfing this season just came
down at the Huntington Beach Pier.
</P>
<P>
   Australian Mark Occhilupo, a surf legend who was leading the
World Championship Tour, lost in the second round Thursday to
unranked Brazilian Neco Padaratz, who made Occhilupo the first
surfer eliminated in the Gotcha Pro by beating him 20.65 to 20.l5.
In this second round, the top seed lost to the 32nd seed.
</P>
<P>
   Occhilupo's heat was the first of the day, starting at 8:40 a.m.
He failed to wait for better waves, which left him continually
playing catch-up to Padaratz.
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest mistake was taking the first wave because it didn't
have much potential,'' Occhilupo said. ``That could have changed
the outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Occhilupo usually is referred to by his nickname, ``Occy.''
After missing several years on the tour in the mid-'90s after an
emotional breakdown, he came back for the 1997 season and he
finished second in what the WCT called ``the greatest comeback in
surf history.''
</P>
<P>
   On paper, Occhilupo's loss is a major upset, but those who know
surfing don't consider it a surprise. Occhilupo is known as a power
surfer, so he often does not thrive on the 2- to 3-foot waves at
Huntington.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Padaratz is unranked also is deceiving because he
was ranked as high as 10th last season. However, he had ``personal
issues'' and left the tour. So, Padaratz, 22, is trying his own
comeback and he appears much as he did last season, with the
exception of newly bleached blond hair.
</P>
<P>
   To qualify for the Gotcha Pro, Padaratz finished the highest of
the unranked surfers in last week's U.S. Surfing Open at Huntington
and received a wild-card berth.
</P>
<P>
   Padaratz's fellow Brazilian, Fabio Gouveia, who advanced over
San Clemente's Shane Beschen in his heat, wasn't surprised by the
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can beat everyone,'' Gouveia said. ``He's really angry.''
</P>
<P>
   But Padaratz's victory might be overshadowed by Occhilupo's
early exit. Occhilupo nearly advanced in the first round on
Wednesday but lost to Australia's Luke Egan, 19.65 to 19.10.
</P>
<P>
   __ Random waves: The wave conditions at Huntington have been
erratic. Some surfers have gotten steady, solid waves, while others
have spent nearly their entire 25 heat minutes waiting for a
respectable wave. Australia's Todd Prestage had average waves in
his 21.35 to 15.15 victory over fellow countryman Matt Hoy.
</P>
<P>
   __ The cut: On Thursday, 16 competitors of the 48-surfer field
were eliminated. The field will be cut in half today, starting at 7
a.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
