<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX SPORTSWEST2 BLACKOUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   We have reached Game 14 in the Los Angeles Dodgers hostage
crisis, and co-conspirators Fox and Charter Cable show no signs of
releasing their prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   That would be you, any Dodgers fan who are cable customers of
Charter. You have now missed 14 Dodgers games on Fox Sports West2
(FSW2) since July 6, when the regional cable outlet began airing
alternate programming because of an impasse with Charter. Game No.
15 comes Sunday, and five more games are slated to be yanked on the
Dodgers' next road trip.
</P>
<P>
   For the uninitiated, here's the background. The Dodgers in
January announced they would televise 80 Dodgers games on FSW2 this
season, doubling the number from 1998. Around the same time, FSW2
officials told cable operators there would be a 25-cent surcharge
for the added games.
</P>
<P>
   Charter was one of several operators that balked at the
quarter-per-customer-per-month surcharge, but all of the others
have since come to terms, leaving Charter to fend for itself.
Charter and Fox officials have met often since the issue flared in
June, when FSW2 announced it would replace Dodgers games with other
programming beginning July 6.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line for viewers: You haven't seen the Dodgers on
FSW2 since July 1, there's no evidence a deal is coming, and the
same blackout/alternative program situation is about to begin with
Angels telecasts on Fox Sports West (FSW) on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides report a steady stream of complaints from viewers,
and both sides have tried to explain their side of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   A Charter spokesmen said this week that the quarter surcharge
Fox wants works out to a $250,000 hit over the course of a year.
Charter has approximately 78,000 subscribers, and doesn't want to
pass the fee along to customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's my analogy,'' erstwhile Charter sports director John
Craig said. ``Let's say I order a hamburger, and the waitress says
the price has gone up a quarter because of the price of pickles. I
say `I don't want pickles.' But the waitress says that doesn't
matter, the price is the same whether or not I want pickles. Now is
that fair?''
</P>
<P>
   It's at least food for thought. Craig also noted that several
years ago, when Dodgers games were televised on Cablevision, a pay
cable outlet, the buy rate was less than 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   There is no reliable way to determine how great the demand is
for Dodgers games by Charter subscribers. FSW2 and FSW both are
part of Charter's ``expanded'' cable tier, which also includes
ESPN, Nickleodeon, CNBC, MSNBC, A&AMP;E, Fx, Lifetime, MTV, USA
Network, BET, Bravo, Sci-Fi, The Food Network and The Learning
Channel.
</P>
<P>
   The price for that package is roughly $30 a month, and about 90
percent of Charter's 78,000 take it. Doing the math, Charter
grosses $2.1 million a month from that package, or around $25
million a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point we've tried to make to Fox is that we already have
an existing contract, and we shouldn't have to charge those people
who don't want Dodgers games,'' Charter vice-president Pete Eliason
said. ``We've tried to talk Fox into a season or game-by-game (pay)
package, and said we'd bear the cost of making the system work, but
they declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten a lot of calls, although I wouldn't say we've
been swamped. I know one thing: If we raised our rate (25 cents),
we'd get 10 times the number of calls we're now getting.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox officials are as frustrated as anyone that the issue has
dragged, especially since they struck deals with other opertors
very quickly. Part of the Charter problem is that negotiations have
also included Charter outlets and Fox regional nets in other
cities.
</P>
<P>
   Fox dismisses Charter's suggestion of a pay tier as irrelevant;
they're in the basic cable business, not the pay TV business. And
as far as Charter balking at a surcharge, they note that the price
of ESPN (NHL) and ESPN2 (NHL) has increased because of expanded
programming packages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customers need to know that even with the surcharge, Charter's
cost to carry FSW and FSW2 is less than its cost for ESPN and
ESPN2,'' Fox spokesman Steve Webster said. ``And we offer the home
teams I think most people in Southern California want to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Webster also noted that while Fox and the Dodgers are part of
the same family, they don't necessarily share the same pocket.
Major League Baseball (as well as tax laws) require that broadcast
fees be accounted for even if there is a relationship between the
club and carrier. Broadcast sources say the per game rights fee for
every Dodgers telecast on FSW2 is between $200,000 and $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it is is frustrating,'' Webster said. ``I sort of feel
like a fool every time I say `They're still negotiating.''' Chances
are he still feels better than Long Beach's Dodgers fans.
</P>
<P>
   AND NOW THE NEWS: Boxing fans will have to dig much deeper into
their pockets to see the Oscar De La Hoya-Felix Trinidad fight. The
PPV price has been set at an all-time high of $49.95. ... The
Lakers remain one of NBC's favorite teams despite their swoon last
season. They're one of four teams that will play the maximum 11
games on NBC. Defending champ San Antonio, New York and
Philadelphia are the others. NBC will have 34 telecasts next
season, an all-time high, and half of them will be in prime time
(at least in the East). ... ABC airs the ``Shootout at Sherwood''
Monday live in the East, meaning David Duval and Tiger Woods will
tee off at 5 p.m. Actually, the plan is for them to actually start
play at 4 p.m., meaning the TV show will pick them up in progress.
This was done because of concerns they couldn't play 18 holes in
three hours, or before sundown. The event has a provision allowing
it to be stopped early (like after 16 holes) in case they run out
of sunlight or time. Gotta love those made-for-TV spectaculars.
Also: The winner makes $1.1 million, the loser $400,000. Where do I
sign up to be the loser?
</P>
<P>
   __ Rumor control: Fox and ABC-ESPN plan an aggressive bid for TV
rights to Wimbledon. NBC wants to retain its over-the-air rights,
but it is disappointed with ratings the last few years, and isn't
interested in a package bid including cable. HBO chose not to renew
its cable package. Also, CBS and the NCAA are talking about
extending their NCAA basketball tournament package, even though the
current contract has three years remaining ... VCR recommendation:
ESPN Classic on Saturday reruns the five-part documentary
``Brooklyn Dodgers: The Original America's Team.'' All five
episodes will run beginning at noon. ... Tour de France winner
Lance Armstrong will be featured in a documentary next year
produced by Olympic filmographer Bud Greenspan. ... The 1999-2000
NHL TV schedule will include 102 regular-season games on ESPN2, 27
on ESPN and just four on ABC, not including the All-Star game on
Feb.6. That game will be ABC's first telecast. The four others will
be late-season Sunday telecasts. ESPN will air a series of Sunday
night games, a la its Sunday evening NFL and baseball series, and
ESPN2 adds more West Coast late games to its slate. ABC will air at
least one playoff game each weekend, as well as Games 3-7 of the
Stanley Cup finals. Games 1 and 2 will be on ESPN.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
