<SLUG> BC-GEN-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANDERS RETIREMENT DOUBTFUL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  Barry Sanders, at a mere 31, at a personal cost of $10
million, at only 1,458 yards away from breaking Walter Payton's
all-time NFL rushing record of 16,726, retiring permanently?
</P>
<P>
   Oh please, Barry, you silly, spoiled, preposterous, irrational,
nonsensical phony, you're just like everyone else these days in our
society.
</P>
<P>
   You just can't tell the truth.
</P>
<P>
   You've become a master prevaricator.
</P>
<P>
   You're about as likely to retire as the misguided umpires union
boss, Richie Phillips, is of publicly admitting he made a
disastrous tactical error by having his members hand in their
resignations and thereby costing at least 22 of them their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   You're about as likely to retire as Kevin Malone is of making a
trade for the Los Angeles Dodgers that makes sense, or of Bob
Graziano making a decision that doesn't invite ridicule.
</P>
<P>
   You're about as likely to retire as Terry Collins is of finding
peace and tranquility this season with an Anaheim Angel team whose
lousy pitching is exceeded only by its lousy attitude.
</P>
<P>
   You're about as likely to retire as Mike Tyson is of ever
regaining the form that once made him the most intimidating fist
fighter on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   But, for the time being, Barry Sanders will persist with his
retirement lie, instead of just coming out and telling the truth
that he wants more money from the Detroit Lions and that he
despises Bobby Ross.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, one does take a hair-raising risk in actually telling
the truth i.e., betraying one's honest feelings on a sensitive
subject in this obscenely politically-correct era in which the most
innocuous utterance is liable to get you in trouble with some
segment of society.
</P>
<P>
   Just once before I depart this celestial sphere, I'd like to
unload all my opinions unvarnished, but that's highly unlikely
because I like to eat and need the financial resources to buy food.
...
</P>
<P>
   The wide-spread condemnation of the UCLA players who illegally
used handicap parking passes has been well-deserved.
</P>
<P>
   So was the punishment meted out to them by the court system
$1,500 in fines and 200 hours of community service and by the UCLA
coach, Bob Toledo suspensions in the Bruins' first two games,
against Boise State and Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   There is no one condoning what these athletes did, but the
savagely shrill reaction and the outrageously moral posturing by
some critics is far disproportionate to the crime.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, these UCLA players didn't mug, rape, rob, or murder
anyone, nor did they bilk anyone out of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   They are a bunch of young, silly college students who committed
a foolhardy act I'm sure they now deeply regret. But they also
should be forgiven and not continue to be treated as though they've
been convicted at the International War Crimes Tribunal at The
Hague. ...
</P>
<P>
   For the good of the baseball owners, Richie Phillips should
remain in charge of the umpires union. For the good of the umpires,
Richie Phillips should resign immediately. ...
</P>
<P>
   The old Forum and Irvine Marriott fight promoter, Mr. Don
Fraser, is the mastermind behind today's first annual Women In
Boxing awards luncheon at the Old Spaghetti Factory in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   The ladies who will be honored will be Gwen Adair, the first
woman referee in California history; Debbie Garcia, the state's
first female timekeeper; Lilly Rodriguez, who holds the distinction
of once boxing on the same Forum card as her husband, Blinkie
Rodriguez; Trudy Latka, husband of one-time boxer and referee
George Latka and publicist for the Boxing Hall of Fame; Carol
Steindler, one-time owner of the storied Main Street Gym; and Ruth
Fraser, who also deserves a Medal of Honor for being married more
than 50 years to Don Fraser.
</P>
<P>
   Admission will be $15, and old-time fighters like Art Aragon,
Joey Barnum, Willie Vaughn and many others are expected to be
present. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``This is absolutely delicious,'' UCLA basketball coach Steve
Lavin said as he ate a steak prepared for him by his incoming
freshman, Jason Kapono, the former Artesia High star, at Trani's.
</P>
<P>
   Kapono is spending his nights this summer as an unpaid
apprentice cook being taught by that master chef, Phil Trani.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, Trani's joint was overflowing with celebrities
Wednesday evening, with Lavin seated in one corner, former Ram
coach Chuck Knox holding court in another and one of the hottest
actresses in the world, the Long Beach-native, Poly High grad
Cameron Diaz, chowing down with her parents in still another.
</P>
<P>
   Conspicuous by his absence was my one-time friend gosh, I have a
lot of ex friends Joe McDonnell, off I suspect somewhere doing his
brief quarterly hour sound bites in the eternal obscurity of
all-news radio. ...
</P>
<P>
   Long Beach celebrity bodyguard Mike (The Hammer) DiMarzo,
one-time Mayfair High soccer hero, has settled down to the point he
now performs duties full-time for the billionaire businessman Jerry
Perenchio. Perenchio and the late Jack Kent Cooke were the ones who
put up the money for the first fight between Joe Frazier and
Muhammad Ali in 1971. ...
</P>
<P>
   On the weekend of Aug. 14-15, they're going to actually stage
robotic combat at the Pyramid in a competition known as BattleBots.
</P>
<P>
   The remote control machines in three weight classes from 84
pounds to 300 will square off in a 48-foot square ring with walls
19 feet high.
</P>
<P>
   Wonder if my pal the prez, Dr. Robert (Fightin' Bob) Maxson,
will be present for this unusual event that could become standard
fare during the 21st century. . .
</P>
<P>
   __ If I'm involved contractually with the 21-year-old fistic
star, Fernando Vargas, I would get him out of Oxnard immediately
and away from his childhood friends. . .
</P>
<P>
   __ I've never been more tense at a movie than I was the other
evening when I saw the ``The Blair Witch Project.'' I was worn out
when it finally concluded, and don't recommend it to those faint of
heart. . .
</P>
<P>
   __ The NFL might as well wait until the 22nd century before it
gets Los Angeles to put up public money for a football franchise. .
.
</P>
<P>
   __ Go ahead, laugh, but the feeling grows stronger in me each
passing NFL owners meeting that Al Davis and the Raiders have a
better chance of one day playing at a new stadium at Hollywood Park
than L.A. does of getting an NFL expansion team. . .
</P>
<P>
   __ It Would Have Made Ski Demski Proud: I recently ran into the
Seal Beach policeman, Rick Paap, and, darned, if the ol' codger
wasn't wearing an American flag tie. The 1967---or was it
1957?---Wilson High grad and one-time Olympic Auditorium amateur
fighter still actually does his Officer Safety puppet bits at
various service clubs and still performs MC duties at strip mall
openings. . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Sources tell me Charlie Hough warned Kevin Malone in spring
training that Carlos Perez would be a problem for the Dodgers this
summer, but that Malone said he would take care the matter.
Malone's bizarre way of taking care of the matter was firing the
messenger before grudgingly demoting the ineffective Perez. . .
</P>
<P>
   __ The Dodgers could use Tom Lasorda's spirit and enthusiasm in
the dugout these disturbing days.
</P>
