<HEADLINE>
WAC ANOINTS TCU AS ITS `FLAG-BEARER'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Maybe the funniest part was that Fresno State
defensive back Payton Williams wasn't joking.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we look at TCU,'' Williams said, ``we see a team that is
what we want to be like.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, when the Western Athletic Conference had 16 teams
and the media gathering spanned two days, programs were scrambling
to schedule, not emulate, a TCU football team coming off a 1-10
season.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the Horned Frogs found themselves not just favored to
win the scaled-down eight-team WAC, but being hailed as the ``flag
bearer'' for the beleaguered conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a good sign,'' TCU coach Dennis Franchione said. ``I
think.''
</P>
<P>
   It's at least a sign that WAC folks didn't miss the Frogs' 7-5
finish in 1998, including their nationally televised upset of
Southern Cal in the Sun Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're aiming at us now,'' said Horned Frogs safety Reggie
Hunt, who was voted the preseason defensive player of the year by
the media. ``But they're going to have to aim pretty hard, be a
pretty straight shooter because as hard as we've been working we're
aiming to have an even better record this year. So they've got to
fight pretty hard to get one because it's not going to be easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Player after player said the Frogs were the team to beat. They
were picked to finish first in the media poll, followed by Fresno
State, SMU, and Rice.
</P>
<P>
   Coach after coach beginning with Fresno State's Pat Hill said
the Frogs also had distinguished themselves as the ``flag bearer''
for the conference with their victory against USC.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going into the bowl game, I had given a little bit of thought
that we were kind of carrying the WAC flag a bit,'' Franchione
said. ``I thought if we could play well or win, which we did, we'd
give our new version of the WAC a little bit of credibility, which
it needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we needed that whether it was TCU or Rice or Fresno.
Our eight schools needed that to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The WAC was still reeling from the announcement by eight of the
16 schools that they planned to leave the conference to form what
has become the Mountain West Conference when the Frogs were
selected to go to the Sun Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   TCU's victory was a victory for the WAC, according to
commissioner Karl Benson. It also turned the Frogs into the marquee
name in the conference. Want proof? Look at the WAC's television
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The deal calls for Fox Sports Net to broadcast three WAC games
nationally and five games regionally. TCU has two of the three
national games, the season opener against Arizona on Sept. 5, and
the season ender against SMU on Nov. 26.
</P>
<P>
   Benson said the WAC needs a good showing in these games to be
able to go back to Fox next year and try to get a more financially
beneficial deal. This is a big year for the WAC, he says.
</P>
<P>
   So the pressure is on, and the flag has been placed in the hands
of a team that is a season removed from a 1-10 finish.
</P>
<P>
   Are the Frogs ready for the pressure of being the favorite
instead of the underdog?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's one of the questions that is still out there to
answer,'' Franchione said. ``Learning to win is one thing and
learning to live with winning is another. Obviously, how I handle
this team and how much pressure I put on them is important. They
are going to hear the fans, but they are going to listen to me.''
</P>
<P>
   His message is simple.
</P>
<P>
   While it looks a lot has changed in the past year, a lot has
stayed the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not too far removed from 1-10,'' Franchione said, ``and
we're not too far away from having a really good year.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
