<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-ORIOLES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PITCHING, HOME RUNS LIFT RANGERS, 3-1
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Rangers general manager Doug Melvin drove from
Charlotte, N.C., to Pulaski, Va., after his flight was canceled
Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that allowed Melvin the time to ponder whether making a
trade for a starting pitcher would enhance the Rangers' rotation.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, right-hander Mike Morgan, the Rangers' No. 3
or 4 starter, presented an argument against making a move while
pitching six masterful innings in hitter-friendly Oriole Park at
Camden Yards during a 3-1 victory against the Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   Now, would Baltimore's Juan Guzman, St. Louis' Darren Oliver,
Colorado's Darryl Kile or Kansas City's Kevin Appier help the
Rangers significantly in the postseason?
</P>
<P>
   And what would it cost to acquire one of those pitchers?
</P>
<P>
   Melvin, who went to evaluate the Rangers' rookie-league
affiliate in the Appalachian League, earns his living making such
decisions. This one likely will be made before Saturday's 11 p.m.
trade deadline, although it remains to be seen what Melvin will
decide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any need to change six for a half
dozen,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said. ``I know something
about our five guys. They're giving us a chance to win a lot of
ballgames.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers strengthened their lead in the AL West to nine games
and moved 19 games above .500 on the strength of Morgan's
performance and solo home runs from right fielder Roberto Kelly,
shortstop Royce Clayton and catcher Ivan Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if Doug is going to make a trade,'' Oates said.
``I don't think it's imperative that we make one. I'm for it if it
makes us a better ballclub, but I don't think Doug is going to make
a trade just to make one.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan, who allowed one run on three hits and two walks, beat
the Orioles' Guzman Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guy pitched better than he did,'' said Oates, who also
acknowledged that Morgan might have pitched six scoreless innings
if not for a fly ball Kelly lost in the sun. That resulted in a
fourth-inning triple for the Orioles' Mike Bordick and led to their
lone run.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Orioles manager Ray Miller appeared much less impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to sound disrespectful, but this is the kind of
game you can count on scoring runs off Morgan,'' Miller said.
``We've got really good numbers against him. I'm not being
disrespectful, but this is a game where you think you're going to
score some runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan, though, nipped the Orioles' only other legitimate
scoring opportunity in the sixth inning. Morgan induced an
inning-ending, double-play ground ball from Bordick with two
runners aboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to keep a close eye on him,'' Oates said of
Morgan, 39, pitching in the 94-degree heat. ``Mike is a
well-conditioned athlete, but he's not 22 years old anymore. He
went out and gave us six strong innings, but he was sucking for air
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Mike Venafro and right-hander Jeff Zimmerman served
as the bridge to closer John Wetteland with two innings of perfect
relief, and Wetteland pitched a scoreless ninth for his 31st save.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers don't appear to need help with pitching like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this entire clubhouse has a different feel,''
right-hander Aaron Sele said. ``It almost seemed like we were
waiting for a trade to be made last year, and we made it and got
three pretty good players (Todd Stottlemyre, Royce Clayton and Todd
Zeile) who helped us win. It doesn't feel like we're waiting for a
trade to be made this year. We're just going out and playing good
baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Lee Stevens echoed Sele's comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Doug is going to force a trade just to make
one,'' Stevens said. ``I'll take my chances right now with what
we've got. Why wouldn't we? We feel we can win. We feel we can beat
anyone.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
