<HEADLINE>
BURKETT WANTS A SHOT TO PITCH IN POSTSEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Right-hander John Burkett, the only pitcher to win a
postseason game for the Texas Rangers, wants that opportunity again
in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to pitch well enough the rest of the way so I can
start a playoff game,'' said Burkett, who is 3-2 with a 4.57
earned-run average since rejoining the rotation June 24. ``I want
to be a part of it. It's hard to be a part of it if you're not
starting, setting up or closing. I sat and watched last year, and
I'd prefer not to do that again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy with the way I'm throwing the ball, but the first
order of business is winning this division.''
</P>
<P>
   Burkett (3-5, 6.16 ERA) took the loss in the Orioles' 8-6
victory Wednesday, but the 34-year-old pitched significantly better
than the box score indicated. Burkett allowed six runs on eight
hits despite being in command most of the evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he did a good job of changing speeds and keeping
them off balance,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said. ``In his
five-plus innings, only two balls were hit decently. Other than
that, every base hit was a flare that fell in or a ball just inside
the line down the third-base line.'' NEW APPROACH FOR CRABTREE
</P>
<P>
   Right-handed batters continue to baffle right-hander Tim
Crabtree.
</P>
<P>
   So, expect Crabtree to begin pitching right-handed batters
differently instead of relying solely on his sinking, two-seam
fastball that travels in the mid-90s and bears in on the hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``All right-handed hitters are taking the same approach against
me,'' Crabtree said. ``I have to make right-handed hitters aware
that I can pitch away.''
</P>
<P>
   That means Crabtree will show right-handed batters his slider
and four-seam fastball more often in an attempt to counteract their
success. Right-handed batters are hitting .370 (34-for-92) against
Crabtree.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating,'' Crabtree said. ``Johnny is bringing me in
to get right-handed hitters out, and I'm just not getting it
done.'' ZEILE PREFERS NOT TO SIT
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Oates originally planned to give third baseman Todd Zeile
the day off yesterday and replace him in the lineup with reserve
infielder Luis Alicea.
</P>
<P>
   Oates, though, asked Zeile after Wednesday's game whether the
hot-hitting infielder would prefer to play. Zeile, who is hitting
.434 (23-for-53) since the All-Star break, accepted Oates' offer to
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a guy is going like he is ... Well, if he were
struggling, he wouldn't have had a choice,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile went 1-for-4, but that snapped his streak of three
consecutive multiple-hit games. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
