<HEADLINE>
ANGELS DEAL PAIR TO A'S
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Anaheim Angels made a trade Thursday
night, but it wasn't the deal that has been anticipated for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Chuck Finley is still an Angel _ for now. Instead, the
Angels sent second baseman Randy Velarde and starting pitcher Omar
Olivares to the Oakland A's for three minor-leaguers. The Angels
got pitcher Elvin Nina and outfielders Jeff DaVanon and Nathan
Haynes in exchange for their most consistent player and pitcher
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Velarde is hitting .306 with nine homers and 48 RBI, and
Olivares is 8-9 with a 4.05 ERA in 20 starts.
</P>
<P>
   Sending Velarde seems to be a sign the Angels are about to trade
Finley to the Indians because one of the players the Angels would
like in return is speedy second baseman Enrique Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Both Velarde and Olivares are free agents at the end of this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Nina, a right-hander from the Dominican Republic, was a
17th-round pick of the A's in 1997. DaVanon was a 26th-round pick
of the A's in 1995, and Haynes was chosen the first round of the
supplemental draft in '97. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
