<SLUG> BC-TEN-MERCEDES-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO HOME-COURT ADVANTAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Eric Taino found only the surroundings familiar,
not the level of competition.
</P>
<P>
   Taino, a former All-American at UCLA playing in only his second
ATP Tour event, lost to Andre Agassi, 6-2, 6-3, in the second round
of the Mercedes-Benz Cup on Thursday night at UCLA's Los Angeles
Tennis Center.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi converted 26 of his 27 service attempts in the second
set, and also stung Taino with a strong two-handed backhand from
the baseline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't complain about any part of my game right now,'' said
Agassi, who advanced to the quarterfinals today to face 18-year-old
Australian star Lleyton Hewitt, a 6-3, 6-1 winner over Germany's
Axel Pretsch.
</P>
<P>
   Taino, a former doubles player in college who made the Mercedes
main draw as a qualifier, answered Agassi's shots well at times but
fell behind a break early in the first set.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously the score says I didn't come close to winning, but I
accomplished a lot of the things I wanted to accomplish,'' Taino
said. ``Hopefully this is just the beginning for me, and this won't
be the last time you see me in a tournament like this playing
against great players.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi controlled the second set, but the players held serve
until Agassi broke to go up 5-3 and served out the match.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took my a while to get used to the rhythm of his swing,''
Agassi said. ``He has a good backhand, but he needs to work on
tightening up his forehand.''
</P>
<P>
   In today's feature match, Agassi faces Hewitt, who continued an
impressive run by reaching the quarterfinals of a tournament for
the sixth time this year. Hewitt, ranked No. 33 in the world, beat
Pretzsch in 57 minutes and has dropped only nine games in four sets
at the Mercedes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big opportunity for me,'' said Hewitt, trying for
his third ATP Tour title. ``I'm looking forward to facing Andre,
I'm definitely going to have my work cut out.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be the first challenge this week for Hewitt, who broke
Pretzsch to open the match and won the last three games to close
out the first set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a bit of a tough start because I felt I could have been
up a double break early,'' Hewitt said. ``I was up 3-2 serving, and
he made a couple good shots to break me, but I was able to get my
concentration back.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt cracked three aces in the first game of the second set
and dropped only nine points in the seven games.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt's countryman Andrew Ilie, ranked No. 61 in the world,
beat big-serving Goran Ivanisevic, 6-4, 6-4. Ivanisevic's serve
consistently topped 120 miles-per-hour, but Ilie countered with a
sharp backhand and never faced a break point on his own serve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to concentrate on holding my serve and staying in the
first set,'' Ilie said. ``I just wanted to hang in there and get a
better look at his serve and try to make him play the ball and
think about his second serve a little more.''
</P>
<P>
   The first scheduled match of the day was not contested after
Magnus Larsson withdrew due to tendinitis in both forearms. Anthony
Dupruis was awarded the walkover victory and will face Ilie today.
</P>
</TEXT>
