<P>
   GA-SHOOT-GUNS (Washington) _ The issue of gun-control
legislation has come back to life in Congress this week, and to
anyone unfamiliar with the ways of Washington, it might appear that
some kind of law is about to be enacted. But in fact, there may be
no law enacted for months. By David Stout.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SECT (Beijing) _ The Falun Gong crackdown is a classic
clash of ancient Chinese beliefs with the grim modern reality of
Communist Party politics. In interviews, followers promise to fight
the ban. Other developments, including an arrest warrant for the
Falun leader, Li Hongzhi, who is in exile in New York. By Seth
Faison.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-LI-RAILROAD (New York) _ A status report on one of New York
City's major commuter systems. For years, riders on the Long Island
Railroad, the nation's busiest commuter line, were more accepting
of its shortcomings. Now complacency seems to be giving over to a
kind of nascent rail rage. Confrontations between passengers and
crew members have become common, and crew members are threatening
to eject disgruntled passengers. By David M. Halbfinger.
</P>
<P>
   NONSTOP-EATING (Chicago) _ On a Sunday morning at a Roman
Catholic church here, Mary Hallan Fiorito glanced at a nearby pew
to see a woman drinking a can of Coke during the Mass. At a musical
in a Broadway theater in New York, Alex Wang turned to the row
behind him to discover people eating corn on the cob. In schools
that once forbade chewing gum, students now bring doughnuts and
candy to class. Americans seem to be eating all the time, and
wherever they please. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT-CASINO (Detroit) _ A casino opens in Detroit, the
largest U.S. city to have one. Officials see it as a source of jobs
and a spur to revitalization of a still-moribund downtown. By Robyn
Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-STEM-CELLS (Undated) _ Researchers report a big step toward
using embryonic stem cells to repair the body: working with rats,
they have found a way to turn stem cells into specific neural cells
that were effectively used as donor cells in young rats that lacked
them. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-DAEWOO (Seoul, South Korea) _ The government's decision to
take charge of the overhaul of Daewoo, South Korea's second-largest
and most-troubled business agglomeration, has pushed skepticism
about the country's commitment to economic restructuring to the
forefront. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphics have been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   ENTERPRISE-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ July was a tough month for
shareholders of Internet-stock funds, but not for the lucky few in
the Enterprise Internet fund. The tiny new fund has soared almost
70 percent since its introduction on July 1, while other Internet
funds have declined about 10 percent. By Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ICECREAM-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ July has been declared National
Ice Cream Month by one of the industry's chief trade groups, and it
is hard not to notice the relentless marketing that ice-cream
makers have put in place _ from movie tie-ins to associations with
NASCAR drivers to spinoff products like candy and children's
clothing. By Constance L. Hays.
