</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEEKEND (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NY-SUMMER-DANCE (New York) _ Dance heads for the parks, plazas
and streets of the city and beyond each summer. In a working
vacation of sorts, dancers have a chance to perform for larger,
newer audiences, often on shared programs with artists in other
fields. For audiences, summer festivals can be full of distractions
not found in a formal theater setting. Still, the experience is
also serendipitous and the price is right most of the time, with
admission often free or by small suggested donation. By Jennifer
Dunning.
</P>
<P>
   PICKETT-EARLY-MUSIC (New York) _ One might have thought that all
the European period instrument ensembles that have become stars on
recordings over the last couple of decades had already visited New
York, where appetites for early-music recordings are healthy, and
indigenous competition, while formidable, is not overabundant. But
there are pleasures still to be sampled. Philip Pickett, a recorder
player and one of the most imaginative early-music directors
working in Britain, is just now getting around to performing in New
York with the New London Consort, the ensemble he founded in 1976.
The group is to make its United States debut in a Mostly Mozart
concert on Sunday afternoon at Alice Tully Hall. By Allan Kozinn.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   APPLES-PITTSBURGH (Pittsburgh) _ One fine day this summer,
wreckers toppled six towering smokestacks along the Monongahela
River. Once part of a huge coke works but long idle, they were the
last vestiges of Big Steel left within the Pittsburgh city limits.
The mills that once employed tens of thousands of workers and made
a third of the world's steel have vanished like ghosts at dawn.
Iron City, aka Steeltown U.S.A., is no more. But having survived
the truly grueling loss of most of its heavy industry, Pittsburgh
is alive and well and getting better. It has had not one
renaissance but two, and a third is under way, fueled by an intense
local pride and a gritty determination to bounce back. By R.W.
Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   BRIDE-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Runaway Bride'': Garry Marshall,
director; with Richard Gere. By Janet Maslin.
</P>
<P>
   FALLS-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Twin Falls Idaho'': Mark and
Michael Polish, directors. Reviewed by Janet Maslin.
</P>
<P>
   CONDUCT-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Conduct Unbecoming A Woman,''
by Regina Marantz-Sanchez (Oxford). Reviewed by Richard Bernstein.
</P>
