<SLUG> BC-JUDGE-OUSTED-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIERCE COUNTY JUDGE REMOVED BY STATE COURT FOR MISCONDUCT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT GAVIN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLYMPIA, Wash. _ The Washington state Supreme Court on Thursday
ordered the removal of a Pierce County judge charged with selling
part of a client's estate at a cut-rate price and accepting more
than $30,000 in payments on the judge's Cadillac.
</P>
<P>
   The decision against Grant L. Anderson marks the first time a
Superior Court judge has been removed from the bench since the
state adopted its judicial discipline system in 1980. It is also
the first time in memory the Supreme Court has ordered a tougher
sanction than recommended by the state Commission on Judicial
Conduct.
</P>
<P>
   The 11-member panel this year recommended that Anderson be
censured, suspended and required to complete ethics training. The
Supreme Court, however, makes the ultimate decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judge Anderson's misconduct has eroded the integrity and
respect for the judiciary to such a degree that he must be relieved
of the duties of office,'' the court said in a unanimous opinion.
``The commission's recommendation of suspension for four months
without pay is too lenient, and removal from office is the
appropriate sanction.''
</P>
<P>
   The misconduct cited by the court occurred shortly before
Anderson began his first Superior Court term in 1993. Then a lawyer
and part-time municipal judge in Fircrest, near Tacoma, Anderson
sold part of a dead client's estate at a reduced price to a friend.
</P>
<P>
   The friend later made $31,185 in loan payments on Anderson's new
Cadillac El Dorado, secretly paying $800 a month from Jan. 1993 to
May 1995, according to court documents. The friend deducted the
payments from his company's taxes as a business expense.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to reach Anderson and his lawyer, Kurt Bulmer of
Seattle, were unsuccessful Thursday. Anderson, who denied
wrongdoing during disciplinary proceedings, has 14 days to ask the
court to reconsider. He can continue to serve during that time,
according to the Supreme Court clerk's office.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's removal of Anderson ends a three-year process that
began when Douglas Schafer, a Tacoma lawyer, contacted the
Commission on Judicial Conduct with information about Anderson's
actions. Schafer Thursday expressed relief at the decision, but
said he was concerned it took so long.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was clearly a serious misconduct case, and obvious right
from the start,'' he said. ``The disciplinary system is not
functioning correctly.''
</P>
<P>
   The court's ruling also spares the state Legislature from moving
forward with its own removal proceedings. Lawmakers last session
approved a resolution to begin the proceedings if the Supreme Court
did not oust Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Had the court accepted the Judicial Conduct Commission's
recommendation, it would have been only the second time in state
history _ the first in 108 years _ that the Legislature had tried
to remove a judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Supreme Court stepped up and made the right decision,''
said Senate Majority Leader Sid Snyder, D-Long Beach, who sponsored
the resolution. ``He didn't deserve to remain on the bench.''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder pressed for the judge's removal after a hospital in his
district claimed that Anderson's handling of his client's estate
had cost it $1.5 million. Ocean Beach Hospital in Ilwaco, the
estate's prime beneficiary, later settled with Anderson and others
for $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson maintained throughout the proceedings that he acted
properly. He said the loan payments were a gift from a friend. He
also argued that the alleged violations were insignificant, not
worthy of sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court, however, cited Anderson's lack of remorse as
additional proof that he was unfit to serve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judge Anderson's failure to acknowledge or recognize that he
committed any misconduct at all weighs heavily against him,'' the
court said. ``It demonstrates his disregard for the importance of
the integrity of the judicial system.''
</P>
<P>
   David Akana, executive director of the Commission on Judicial
Conduct, said this is the first time in memory, possibly the first
time ever, that the court has imposed a tougher sanction than the
commission. The court, the ultimate authority, has overridden the
commission's recommendations before, but always to lighten
punishment, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Akana said Anderson is the first Superior Court judge removed
from the bench since voters passed the constitutional amendment in
1980 creating the current disciplinary system. A lower court judge,
King County District Court Judge John Ritchie, was removed from the
bench in 1994 for billing taxpayers for vacations to Florida and
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, the Supreme Court also supported the removal of Pierce
County District Court Judge Mark Deming for sexual harassment.
Deming, however, resigned before the decision, and later lost a bid
to be elected again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
