<SLUG> BC-FBC-SEC-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYERS FLEE TO RIVALS, UPSET ALABAMA FANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ Alabama fans are whipping themselves into a
frenzy because two Crimson Tide players are transferring to the
enemy.
</P>
<P>
   In June, wide receiver Eric Locke, a Tennessee native, left
Alabama to play for Tennessee. Linebacker Travis Carroll, a Florida
native, announced this week he is leaving Alabama. He hasn't
announced his new school, but it is expected to be Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama coach Mike DuBose is trying to calm the Tide fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alabama's not for everybody and everybody's not for Alabama,''
DuBose said Thursday at the Southeastern Conference football media
day. ``We'll miss both of them. And both of them left for totally
different reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Locke was seeking more playing time. Carroll, projected as the
team's middle linebacker, has had trouble with a shoulder injury
and was uncertain that he would be happy if he stayed and was
unable to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there are any underlying problems,'' DuBose
said. ``The focus has been on them instead of the rest of the
players who are busting their fannies to get ready for the
season.''
</P>
<P>
   DuBose said it was university policy not to release players from
their scholarships when they decide to transfer to another SEC
school. BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ After playing in the 1998 SEC championship game, Mississippi
State is being picked fourth in the SEC West this year. However,
Bulldogs coach Jackie Sherrill hints that his team could be a
surprise. ``Our goal was to replace the offensive linemen we lost
and we did that,'' he said. ``We're better off than we ever have
been. But the SEC West, it's another coin flip as far as who could
win it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Kentucky coach Hal Mumme doesn't appear concerned that Dusty
Bonner will be taking over for record-setting Tim Couch at
quarterback. ``We're not going to cut back on the number of
plays,'' he said. ``If anything, we'll expand the playbook. Dusty
is a bright guy who has studied the playbook for two years.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Tennessee quarterback Tee Martin says he looks forward to
playing at Florida's ``Swamp'' on Sept. 18. The game will be played
at night and televised by CBS. ``I don't think he knows what he's
in for,'' Florida wide receiver Travis Taylor said. ``There's going
to be 85,000 people who just came from Happy Hour. It's gonna be
loud. Plus, there's going to be 11 Florida players out there trying
to take his head off.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Alabama senior running back Shaun Alexander, a Heisman Trophy
candidate, prepared for his senior season with a rigorous summer
workout program. Part of his workouts included acceleration
training on a treadmill. ``I got up to 23 mph,'' he said. ``I tell
people that would get me a ticket in a school zone.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
