u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PASTOR-GAY-SPI &LR;      07-30 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PASTOR-GAY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPENLY GAY MINISTER PICKED TO LEAD SEATTLE EPISCOPAL CHURCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN IWASAKI  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A priest known for his energetic work on social
justice issues will be named Friday as dean of St. Mark's Episcopal
Cathedral in Seattle's Capitol Hill neighborhood, becoming the
first openly gay man in the country chosen to head an Episcopal
cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Robert Taylor, 40, was forced to flee his native South
Africa in 1989 with the help of Archbishop Desmond Tutu because of
his work against apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   In his current post in New York, Taylor is credited with
transforming St. Peter's Episcopal Church in Peekskill from a
troubled congregation into a vibrant one, partly by launching a
variety of social service ministries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am absolutely thrilled at the call to come to St. Mark's and
working with the congregation in further developing their vision
for ministry, and in building the strength of the parish,'' Taylor
said Thursday by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   He said he looked forward to ``engaging in the issues of the
city and working more closely with Christians around the world. I
really delight in those prospects.''
</P>
<P>
   The Very Rev. Gerald Porter, provost for the Episcopal Diocese
of Olympia and interim priest at St. Mark's, said Taylor's sexual
orientation was ``not a factor'' in his selection and that he was
chosen for his leadership qualities.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue stands out, not the least because Taylor will be
head of the 1,800-member cathedral, the largest Episcopal
congregation in Western Washington and the church where the bishop
makes his headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor declined to comment further about his appointment. He
will attend Sunday services at St. Mark's, an activist congregation
on Seattle's Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Since Taylor arrived at his Peeksville post in 1989, membership
has risen from about 70 to 400.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were floundering, dwindling,'' said Betty Ashton, an office
volunteer at St. Peter's. ``Father Taylor has the energy we needed.
He gave us the spark.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Taylor's leadership, St. Peter's opened an outreach center
that provides day-care service and ministers to the elderly and
those with HIV/AIDS. The church also has a children's outreach
choir made up of both St. Peter's members and citizens of
Peekskill, a middle-class city of 21,000 residents 45 miles north
of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were looking for someone who can be an articulate
spokesperson for the church and the greater community,'' Porter
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone who's a good preacher. Someone who's a bridge-builder
to work with (Bishop Vincent Warner) and other diocesan leaders.
Someone who has a passion for social justice, who understands the
Gospel in that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner was on vacation Thursday and was unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor has visited St. Mark's three times, the last time two
weeks ago when he and his partner were introduced and warmly
received.
</P>
<P>
   ``We anticipated hearing (some complaints about Taylor's sexual
orientation) from the congregation,'' St. Mark's spokesman Jeff
Wilson said. ``It was the exact opposite.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor will replace the Very Rev. Frederick Northup, who
resigned in May 1998 to move to Atlanta, where his wife, an
attorney, had accepted a job.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1994, Northup offered to bless the commitment of two
gay men despite Warner's request that the ceremony not proceed. The
couple called off the ceremony but later were united in a ``vow of
commitment'' ceremony. Though not liturgical and thereby official,
the local church considered the ceremony to be part of the pastoral
duties of a priest and therefore allowable.
</P>
<P>
   The Episcopal Canon states that sexual orientation can't be a
barrier to ordination. At the denomination's last general
convention in 1997, a resolution that would have authorized the
development of a liturgy that would bless same-sex relationships
was narrowly rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Still, under the structure of the ``very inclusive, very broad''
denomination, ``a lot of latitude is given to a diocese on what
they want to do,'' Porter said.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of a priest who is gay is ``no surprise,'' given the
broad community that St. Mark's serves and the prevalence of gay
clergy within the denomination, said a priest of another Episcopal
church in the diocese.
</P>
<P>
   The priest, who opposes the ordination of gay priests, did not
want his name published. His church, like others in the diocese,
has gone through intense discussion on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``For those who have stayed in the Episcopal Church after all
this stuff, this one thing is not going to push them over the edge.
Because they've already been pushed _ way pushed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, a statement adopted by the general convention of the
diocese ``honored'' committed relationships between homosexual
partners.
</P>
<P>
   But not all priests agree. Last year, a letter signed by 33
diocesan priests strongly objected to that statement. While
resolving to ``oppose bigotry in all its forms,'' the clergy said,
the statement ``implies a theology we cannot support.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor was chosen by a search committee that included
non-Episcopalians, including the Rev. Tom Quigley, executive
director of the Church Council of Greater Seattle, an ecumenical
organization.
</P>
<P>
   The committee was broad because St. Mark's sees its mission as
serving ``not just the parish but the diocese and the community at
large,'' Porter said. ``We're a prophetic voice on the hill. ...
We're really concerned about issues affecting the wider
community.''
</P>
<P>
   Quigley said Taylor was viewed by political and business leaders
in Peekskill as ``a key spokesperson for the religious community.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor will be a good fit for St. Mark's because the cathedral
``really values the role it plays in Seattle,'' Quigley said.
``They like to be on the cutting edge. They really want to mean
something. They want to stand for the right things, the right
quality of life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
