<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEATTLE-SIDRAN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARK SIDRAN IS SEATTLE'S POINT MAN IN CREATING CIVIL CLIMATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELAINE PORTERFIELD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In the struggle for the hearts, minds and good manners
of Seattle, Mark Sidran is more than willing to wage war.
</P>
<P>
   Sidran, the three-term Seattle city attorney, is the city's
point man in creating a civil climate, from stopping people from
lying on downtown sidewalks to trying to cork noisy nightclubs to
stopping panhandlers from intimidating those with change in their
pockets.
</P>
<P>
   He's also championed a controversial city ordinance that allows
police to impound cars driven by people with suspended licenses,
and has enforced a law banning posters on utility poles.
</P>
<P>
   ``These laws are important in keeping the streets safe,'' says
the 48-year-old attorney. ``You have less crime and less
victimization when they are enforced.''
</P>
<P>
   For those views, he has been reviled as a Nazi, a prig and
someone out to make Seattle safe for the equally reviled yuppies of
the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see these (laws) as more hostility for people who
traditionally lived in Seattle _ working-class people,'' said
activist Matt Fox, who opposes Sidran's enforcement of a city
ordinance banning posters from utility poles. ``These laws
needlessly expand the power of government and are disrespectful of
individual rights and liberty.''
</P>
<P>
   Sidran, with his receding hairline, plastic-rimmed glasses and
regulation working stiff's blue-shirt-and-tie, hardly looks the
type to disrespect anyone. A classic Everyman at first glance, he's
the block-watch captain down the street, the policy wonk who revels
in sociological studies, the lawyer who loves arguing a case.
</P>
<P>
   And, he says, he's a scapegoat for those who accuse him of
insensitivity to the poor or of being a totalitarian in a sensibly
priced suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to be compassionate,'' Sidran said. ``But these
issues are complicated. Most people will not choose to be in an
environment that makes them feel unsafe or threatened.''
</P>
<P>
   Broadly speaking, Sidran is fighting for his vision of Seattle's
soul, pushing for a civilized, law-abiding city, with safe, clean
streets and thriving businesses and neighborhoods where drunks
don't frighten kids in the park.
</P>
<P>
   His opponents _ and they are many _ yearn for the grittier
working town of yesterday, the Seattle that spawned Skid Road and
values a beer in a city park or a garage band's flier on a utility
pole.
</P>
<P>
   A sometime opponent, City Councilman Nick Licata, says he
realizes many middle class residents of Seattle find Sidran's ideas
seductive. But he warns they could drain the vitality from the city
if they aren't carefully monitored.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can very quickly become a stagnant city,'' Licata said.
``This could also become a very oppressive city ... there is a
balance that has to be obtained.''
</P>
<P>
   Annoyances can fester
</P>
<P>
   Mark Sidran's view of life in the city can be found in ``Fixing
Broken Windows,'' a 1996 book by George Kelling and Catherine
Coles. The authors write that small annoyances in an urban setting
can fester and become big problems: Graffiti and litter create the
impression that lawlessness is tolerated, which leads to increased
street crime.
</P>
<P>
   Then businesses fail as customers become increasingly fearful of
patronizing neighborhoods they perceive as unsafe. Whole
neighborhoods can fall into blight and decay, a world in which
petty thieves, public drunks and drug dealers have the upper hand
on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to fight that downward spiral, say proponents of
the Broken Windows school, is to prevent it from starting. Employed
in New York City, proponents credit it with rescuing streets and
subways from increasing chaos and fear, leading to a per-capita
murder rate that's now lower than that of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Results like this made him embrace the philosophy, Sidran said,
and to use it to help Seattle master its problems. He's spoken and
written widely on the ideas in ``Fixing Broken Windows.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I get a percentage of the book sales,'' Sidran likes to joke.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, they are ideas that need to be seriously considered
at all levels, he says, because they benefit all residents, from
the well-off to the those who live on the streets who are most
likely to be the victims of crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone needs standards in their life in terms of their own
self-dignity,'' he says, ``even late-stage alcoholics.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a view that profoundly disturbs some civic leaders and
advocates for the homeless, and Sidran's promotion of civility has
touched off a surprisingly vehement debate in a city where nearly
all elected officials pride themselves on being part of a long
tradition of cooperation and progressiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``His emphasis is maybe more on social order,'' said Councilman
Peter Steinbrueck, another Seattle native. ``I'm concerned about
efforts to clean everything up ... Seattle is becoming increasingly
more intolerant. The civility laws I think are to appease and
increase the comfort of the well-to-do and the well-heeled.''
</P>
<P>
   Former City Councilman and council candidate Charlie Chong says
he opposes everything about Sidran's philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's puritanical,'' Chong said. ``It's what somebody else
decides is civil, and it's not necessarily my view.''
</P>
<P>
   But that said, Sidran is only suggesting and enforcing laws
approved by a majority of council members, Chong said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The council is just as guilty as Mr. Sidran _ more guilty,
because they voted for them,'' Chong said.
</P>
<P>
   Views like that anger Chris Martin, a Sidran supporter whose
company, CityScapes, specializes in graffiti removal and litter
control in Pioneer Square.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is not whether you're homeless, it's if your
behavior is unacceptable,'' Martin said. ``Our problem is with
people who are drinking, smashing bottles and defecating in the
parks ... I think the majority of Seattle citizens are fed up with
this kind of behavior on the streets.''
</P>
<P>
   Sidran says he senses support from many Seattle citizens _ ``I
hesitate to call them the silent majority'' _ including the poor
who cannot flee to expensive suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe there is a broad middle ground,'' he said,
attributing the high high-profile criticism he's drawn in part to
the polarizing politics of his opponents. He recalls that one group
representing the homeless publicly crushed his effigy under an
outhouse after he pointed out problems associated with opening
public toilets on downtown streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``This makes great political theater,'' he said, but does little
to advance a solution to deal with the problem. ``It's an
idealogue's view of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   John Fox, coordinator of the Housing Displacement Coalition,
which advocates for the homeless, relishes attacking Sidran and
enforcement of the civility laws, laws he believes are specifically
targeted at the homeless, the poor and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``He represents a community view that in my mind is dangerous,''
said Fox, who is not related to Matt Fox. ``His policies drive a
wedge through the community, alienating and creating divisions.
That's clearly the effect of his policies and he knows that, but I
honestly believe he doesn't care.''
</P>
<P>
   Sidran says his critics couldn't be more mistaken about his
capacity to care.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a pharmacist from Seward Park, Sidran went east to
Harvard for college, but returned to his beloved hometown to study
the law. He notes that his path in life was outlined in his college
admission essays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wrote my college applications on my interest in urban policy
and politics and how in my own view, Seattle would confront many of
the issues other cities were then wrestling with,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Decades later, Sidran is still wrestling, and his stake in the
city is bigger than ever. Last year, he and his wife, Anais Winant,
took out a mortgage to purchase the Smith Block Building at 1923
First Avenue, just north of the Pike Place Market, for $1.5
million. Once dominated by a theater that showed XXX-rated movies,
the three-story building has been remodeled and now houses a
bed-and-breakfast, residential units and a salon.
</P>
<P>
   The scars of battle
</P>
<P>
   Re-elected to the $105,000-a-year job without opposition in
1997, Sidran is in his third four-year term as City Attorney.
Though willing to continue the war for the soul of the city, he
does show scars of battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say, `You're so prosecutor-focused,' and I say, `Yeah,
right,'' he said, irritated. ``I have written (editorial) pieces
for years saying I don't think the answers to these complicated
issues is simply more law enforcement. You also have to deal with a
lack of treatment beds. We also have a lot of late-stage alcoholics
killing themselves, and we have the state licensing stores to sell
(alcohol) to them. We have to look at the complexity of these
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Sidran says he really doesn't mind most of the things his
opponents say about him _ with one exception: being branded a Nazi.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, it bothers me because I'm a Jew,'' he said. ``Second,
it's a cheap shot. There are people alive who lived through (the
Holocaust), who survived it. I find it unbelievably insensitive.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not yet clear if Sidran has the ability to carry that brand
of problem-solving to higher office _ or even if he wants to. He's
mum about his plans, although he didn't say `no' when asked if he
would run for King County prosecutor should longtime Prosecutor
Norm Maleng retire.
</P>
<P>
   His stands on posters and nightclubs may have alienated young
voters _ the kind who volunteer for campaigns. But he may also
attract supporters for his consistent stands.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, Sidran is unlikely to change his ways any time
soon. In his view, the stakes are too high.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is better off in a city that works,'' he said. ``It
is possible for cities to die.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
