<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9532 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-HASEK-TEX     07-30 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-HASEK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEKING MORE PRIVACY, HASEK ANNOUNCES RETIREMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The best running back in professional football retired this week
citing disinterest in the game. Not wanting to play for his current
employer might also have played a part in the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the best goaltender in professional hockey announced
he will call it quits after the 1999-2000 season for a far more
personal reason: his family and their privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Weary of constant media scrutiny and trapped by the celebrity of
a sports superstar in America, Dominik Hasek said he will abandon
the Buffalo Sabres and his contract after next season and return to
his native Czech Republic, family in tow, where they might again
lead something approaching a normal life.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek's departure comes in a dramatically different manner than
that of NFL great Barry Sanders, who stunned the sports world when
word got out Tuesday night that he was suddenly quitting the
Detroit Lions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to retire because of two reasons, my kids (and) too
much public and media attention,'' said Hasek, a two-time NHL most
valuable player who last spring led the Sabres into the Stanley Cup
Finals, where they lost a six-game series to the Stars on a
controversial overtime goal in Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek said during the playoffs that he was tired of the media
attention and the fan following he has received since emerging as
the league's top goaltender following his acquisition from the
Chicago Blackhawks in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   His celebrity status soared after he led the Czech Republic to
the gold medal with a brilliant performance during the 1998 Winter
Olympic Games in Nagano, Japan.
</P>
<P>
   During an interview prior to the Stanley Cup Finals, Hasek said
he longed to live a quieter, more private life where neither he nor
his family, including his two young children, would receive so much
attention from media or fans. He said the attention had become too
much, both in Buffalo and in his homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Hasek reiterated those sentiments while saying he was
99 percent sure he would never play hockey again after the
1999-2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his unquestioned prowess between the pipes, Hasek has
been roundly flayed in the media in recent seasons for deciding not
to play through injuries. During the 1999 Eastern Conference finals
against Toronto, he flew to the Czech Republic to have a strained
groin checked out and missed two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy to play the game and I enjoy to be with my teammates.
It's part of my job to talk to the media,'' Hasek said. ``It is
something I don't really enjoy. It's not fun for me.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the fan frenzy that has followed him on both sides of the
Atlantic, Hasek said, ``The attention I've received is
overwhelming. It's something I don't enjoy at all. It's time to
step back.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasek also said he wasn't comfortable with having his 9-year-old
son, Michael, and 4-year-old daughter, Dominika, spending most of
the year living in the United States. Hasek said he and his wife,
Alena, want their children to spend more time in the family's
homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want our kids to go back to Czech Republic and share in our
families' backgrounds and culture,'' Hasek said. ``Every year, it's
more and more difficult, especially for my son, to adapt to the
Czech life. Every year, he has more problems to speak Czech.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasek dismissed suggestions that he might, as other star
athletes have, be simply trying to increase his $7 million-a-year
salary, second among NHL goalies only to Patrick Roy, who makes
$7.5 million annually with the Colorado Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek, 34, has two years remaining on his contract and would
forgo $7.5 million in 2000-01 as well as a club option for $9
million in 2001-02 by retiring.
</P>
<P>
   However, money, he said, ``was not an issue at all. I have
enough money to live a nice life, not only for me but my kids and
wife.''
</P>
<P>
   More of an issue, he said, was, ``I miss the game and I miss my
friends, my teammates in the locker room.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasek said he most enjoys having his teammates skate up to him
in his net after a win, followed by the skate back to the locker
room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy the game the way I did three, four, five years ago,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, ``I made a decision: it's over. I hate to say
never. (But) I am 99 percent I will never come back to hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasek defended the timing of his announcement, which, it was
suggested, could be a distraction to the Sabres as they seek to
follow up their surprisingly successful 1998-99 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel it was the best time to do it,'' he said. ``I really
don't know what is the better time. Closer to training camp is not
good. ''
</P>
<P>
   Hasek has had several nagging injuries in recent years, but said
his decision was not affected by them.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he has not discussed the possibility of a trade
with Sabres management, nor has he considered it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to finish my career in Buffalo, and I think I will,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo assistant general manager Larry Carriere said the timing
of Hasek's announcement actually helped the Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave us the opportunity to plan ... our future a year in
advance,'' Carriere said.
</P>
<P>
   In retirement, Hasek plans to spend more time with his family
and concentrate on his clothing line, which is available in the
Czech Republic and, Hasek said, could soon be available in the
United States and Canada as well.
</P>
<P>
   The name of the line: ``The Dominator.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Hasek, ``I need to compete in something. It's something I
feel I can compete in.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
