<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 02:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9538 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPEARS-LOOKALIKE-LADN     07-30 0527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEARS-LOOKALIKE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN SURPRISE WINNER OF LOOK-ALIKE CONTEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DONNA HUFFAKER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Sporting pigtails and above-the-knee nylons, the
winner of the Britney Spears look-alike contest was twice as old as
most of the other contestants and seven years older than the
17-year-old sensation herself.
</P>
<P>
   But more remarkable than that _ Robert Stephens is a man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to die,'' he exclaimed Thursday at the thought of
standing side by side with his favorite diva.
</P>
<P>
   As Stephens was handed his prize _ tickets to the singer's
sold-out Saturday concert at Universal Amphitheater where he will
also get to meet Spears backstage _ the 24-year-old drag queen
shrieked through thunderous applause from the lunchtime spectators,
many of whom thought he was a she.
</P>
<P>
   Although the contest, part of the Sprint PCS Summer Splash
Spears Style, was not limited by age or gender, the majority of
would-be Britneys ranged from 11 to 14 years old and were decidedly
lacking in Y chromosomes.
</P>
<P>
   But despite their losses, the girls took it all in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's show biz,'' shrugged 11-year-old Rachel Snow of La
Crescenta.
</P>
<P>
   Rachel, a radiant redhead, said she wasn't intimidated at all by
the growing crowd as she mouthed the words to her favorite singer's
song and danced back and forth across the stage. She graciously
accepted her consolation prize, a Sprint PCS hat.
</P>
<P>
   Set in front of a Sprint PCS store at the corner of California
Avenue and Brand Boulevard, the competition featured more than 30
contestants, some performing in groups that counted as one entrant.
Each Britney hopeful danced and lip-synced to songs from the pop
star's CD, spun by a disc jockey from KIIS-FM (102.7).
</P>
<P>
   Solo on the stage during her rendition of ``Baby One More
Time,'' 11-year-old Katrina Dariell braided her hair, made up her
face and borrowed her friend's Catholic school uniform skirt. The
second-place winner mouthed ``good job'' to Stephens as he received
tickets and roses, and Katrina won a backpack.
</P>
<P>
   Katrina had hoped to demonstrate her vocal as well as dancing
skills during the contest but was allowed only to mouth the words
like the other performers. Disappointed because she wanted tickets
``really, really, really, really bad,'' Katrina will keep listening
to the radio for free tickets to Saturday's concert at Universal
Amphitheatre.
</P>
<P>
   Rocking their own hips in rhythmic synchronicity, Stephens and
his two backup dancers will split the tickets and limousine ride to
the show, he said. Dancer Nakia Sisowath said he is more excited
about watching the choreography than its teen-age star.
</P>
<P>
   Not Stephens.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's my favorite. She's the total reigning teen diva,''
Stephens said, adding he will don anew the miniskirt, nylons, fuzzy
hair scrunchies, pigtails and platform shoes when he shakes his
idol's hand this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The all-male trio, who work as dancers at Disneyland,
acknowledged a pang of guilt for disappointing girls half their
age.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they'll get over it,'' said Le Derek Rocque, 21.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
