A9547 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-TRADE2-LADN-(SLAN     07-30 0475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-TRADE2-LADN-(SLANG)WRITETHRU </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS DEAL PAIR TO A'S
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Anaheim Angels made a trade Thursday
night, but it wasn't the deal that has been anticipated for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Chuck Finley is still an Angel _ for now. Instead, the
Angels sent second baseman Randy Velarde and starting pitcher Omar
Olivares to the Oakland A's for three minor-leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels got pitcher Elvin Nina, 23, and outfielders Jeff
DaVanon, 25, and Nathan Haynes, 20, in exchange for their most
consistent player and pitcher this season. Velarde is hitting .306
with nine homers and 48 RBI, and Olivares is 8-9 with a 4.05 ERA in
20 starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is what it is,'' Angels general manager Bill Bavasi said of
the trade. ``These are two good veterans going to a club that has a
chance at the wild card and we're trying to retool for the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Sending Velarde might be a sign the Angels are about to trade
Finley to the Indians because one of the players the Angels would
like in return is speedy second baseman Enrique Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi said this trade ``may be our last deal or there may be
others.'' He would not speculate on Finley's situation.
</P>
<P>
   Both Velarde and Olivares are free agents at the end of this
season, and it shows the Angels didn't expect to bring back either
one next season despite what they've done this year.
</P>
<P>
   Velarde is 36 but might be the club's MVP this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we thought about that, but sometimes you have to
weigh the odds,'' Bavasi said. ``What are the odds of bringing him
back at the dollar figure you feel is right?''
</P>
<P>
   Olivares leads all the starters on the staff in wins and has
thrown the club's only two complete games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a breakthrough year for him,'' Bavasi said.
``He's always been a guy that might've been cursed by his ability
to go from the bullpen to the rotation and back to the bullpen. For
him, I'm sure he hated that. He wanted to start.''
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi said he doesn't expect the trade to go over well in the
Angels clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both are very popular guys,'' he said. ``I would guess there
will be some discussion to the negative, but that's only natural. I
think players probably view that as an insult to the players who
left.''
</P>
<P>
   Nina, a right-hander from the Dominican Republic, was a
17th-round pick of the A's in 1997. DaVanon was a 26th-round pick
of the A's in 1995, and Haynes was chosen in the first round of the
supplemental draft in '97.
</P>
<P>
   Haynes, whose speed was important to the Angels, will report to
Single-A Lake Elsinore and Nina and DaVanon will report to Double-A
Erie.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Sheets will be called up to play second base for now, but
Bavasi said he did not know who would replace Olivares in the
starting rotation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-99 0245EDT &QL; 
