<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMOKERS' IDEA A FLASH IN THE CAN
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  The solution to the cigarette butt blight is so simple that if
I was more limber, I'd kick myself in the butt for not thinking of
it first.
<P>
   So would the Board of Supervisors, which is kicking butts by
requiring owners to place ashtrays in front of their bars, stores
and offices, for sidewalk smokers.
</P>
<P>
   The butt drifts on sidewalks are unsightly, but do we need a
million ashtrays which will need to be dumped, maintained,
monitored and policed?
</P>
<P>
   How many enforcement officers will this require? How many tons
of sand?
</P>
<P>
   If you have your dog in a store and the dog indicates it needs
to heed nature's call in the worst way, and you take Rover outside
to the curb, do you leave the residue for the shopkeeper to clean
up? Do you tell Mabel Teng we need sidewalk poop-deposit boxes?
</P>
<P>
   Let's say the answers are no. So if you're in a store, shop or
bar and you need a smoke and you step outside, why is the bar owner
responsible for providing a means of disposal for your mess?
</P>
<P>
   ``The solution to the butt problem is simple,'' says Peter
William Brown. ``What do you think God intended us to do with all
those empty Altoids containers?''
</P>
<P>
   Make this the law, Supes: Smokers must stick their butts where
the sun don't shine _ in a little tin box, kept in pocket or purse.
</P>
<P>
   You smokers, the public is going to pick up the tab for your
cancer treatments, we shouldn't have to buy you ashtrays, too.
</P>
<P>
   It's called individual responsibility: You puff it, you stuff
it.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU`RE going to go Code Blue on us and want to live to tell
about it, have your heart attack at the Bay Club on Battery, which
is connected to the Synapse Medical Group.
</P>
<P>
   At lunchtime Wednesday, a man went into full cardiac arrest at
the club while playing basketball, and within 20 seconds Dr. Ryan
Honda had scooted over from his office and was giving
mouth-to-mouth, a first for both parties.
</P>
<P>
   The man wasn't breathing and had no heartbeat, but Honda's CPR
kept blood flowing to the brain for the three or four minutes until
paramedics arrived with the de-fib paddles, shock you very much.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's awake, doing well and he's very happy to be alive,'' Doc
Honda reported Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   But how did the guy's team do?
</P>
<P>
   UNFORGETTABLE, that was the experience of songbird Natalie Cole
when her bus hit a snag at the new, improved SFO.
</P>
<P>
   Natalie was in the Bay Area for some performances and to visit
with her old buddy Judi Basolo. When it was time to fly out, Cole
jumped on her tour bus for a drop-off at SFO.
</P>
<P>
   Oops! The bus was too tall for the new entrance to the departure
drop-off area at the United terminal. This bus has been all over
the country and never before been too tall.
</P>
<P>
   Cole's manager flagged down a passing van, which gave the star a
lift to the departures curb.
</P>
<P>
   Only in San Francisco: Natalie Cole, hitchhiking.
</P>
<P>
   ``JUST SAW a hooker,'' reports Edwin Heaven, ``she was standing
in front of one of those new Shell billboards that read, `I'd like
to pay, pump and bolt.' Of course, I drove right by, not being in
the mood to shell it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Or not wanting to part with 50 clams.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
