<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 08:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9645 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN30-CO     07-30 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN30-COX-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: How Warsaw's young warriors view
NATO
 &HT;    (Eds: Corrects fourth-to-last quote: It is sad that it ever took
place ...)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Eds: Second in a series. Cox News Service columnist Joe Murray
reported from Eastern Europe during a visit 10 years ago, just
before the fall of the Berlin Wall. This summer he returned to
write about the changes that have led three former Eastern Bloc
countries _ Hungary, the Czech Republic and Poland _ to become the
newest members of NATO. At the end of the series, CoxNet will
compile these columns into our weekly Focus page, good for running
as a Perspective-type page or op-ed feature. These pages are
available for sale to New York Times News Service clients at
www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARSAW _ Other than its history, there's nothing old about Old
Town.
</P>
<P>
   Like most of Warsaw, this segment of the city -- dating back to
the 13th century -- was bombed to basement level, and then some,
before World War II was over and done with.
</P>
<P>
   Old Town has since been reconstructed according to 18th century
architecture. Never mind that New Town is only slightly younger.
The tourists like what they see.
</P>
<P>
   Old Town, too, is where you find the young people, a fine place
for music and beer on warm summer evenings. So it was that I was
here in search of our newest NATO allies, Warsaw's young warriors,
Poland's finest, prepared as they were to lay down their lives for
the NATO way of life.
</P>
<P>
   I had some trouble getting them to set down their beer long
enough to talk. But here are comments I recorded through the help
of an interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   This was not a scientific poll. If nothing else, it may reflect
a sense of history:
</P>
<P>
   Tomasz Stawinski, high school student, age 17:
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a good step for Poland to become a NATO member. Many
politicians, deciding to make that step, perhaps thought first
about their own career, not about the whole nation. But from the
point of view of the ordinary people, it is good to receive support
from the rest of Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Micha Wilczek, student, age 24:
</P>
<P>
   ``It is good that Poland is in NATO. We never knew before whose
side we were on. It was as if we were between a hammer and an
anvil. In our feelings, we were always on the side of Western
democracy, but we were bound to the East. We couldn't help that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mirek Mordak, student, age 21:
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sure it will be better for Poland than it used to be. But
Poland has no business in Kosovo. It is an American problem, not
ours. I would like to join the army, but I would not go to Kosovo.
If I had a choice to kill or not to kill someone, I would choose
not to.''
</P>
<P>
   Mariola and Katarzyna Dbrowska, sisters who work and attend
school part time, ages 19 and 22:
</P>
<P>
   ``It is better now. Poland will be safer now. We'll have a
chance to develop. We will be safer from aggression of our Eastern
neighbors. Intervention in Kosovo was necessary. We had to put an
end to people killing other people.''
</P>
<P>
   Katarzyna Majka, student, age 22:
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a NATO member is a protection of our safety. It gives us
a feeling that we belong to this world and that we mean something
for it. The bombing of Kosovo was not necessary and it is sad that
it ever took place.''
</P>
<P>
   Lidka (no last name given), nurse, age 29:
</P>
<P>
   ``It is going to take much more for us to become a real NATO
member. We should solve our inner problems first before becoming a
NATO member. We cannot solve our ordinary problems of education,
health care and agriculture. We are too weak to handle all the
responsibilities of NATO membership. The invasion of Kosovo was a
very big mistake made by an irresponsible person.''
</P>
<P>
   Edyta Wacierak, student, age 21:
</P>
<P>
   ``The invasion of Kosovo was a game played at the top by
politicians, between the U.S. and Russia. Those countries gained
profits from it. It's not about people's problems, but about
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Pawe Lang, student, age 21:
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO is a good thing to stabilize our country, but on the
other hand it can spoil our relations with our Eastern neighbors.
As for the bombing of Kosovo, I think it was a good thing, but it
lasted too long.''
</P>
<P>
   There you have it, the news from Old Town _ in some ways, not so
different from what you'd hear in a cafe back home, except for that
polka music.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin Daily News,
is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. Address is P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915; e-mail, jmurray(AT)lcc.net.)
</P>
