<HEADER>
A9654 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-BEDOUIN-$ADV01     07-30 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-BEDOUIN-$ADV01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ISRAELI BEDOUIN HOPE NEW GOVERNMENT LIFTS THEM FROM LIMBO AND
POVERTY
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    EDs: For purposes of a locator map, Um Bateen is about 5 miles
northeast of Beersheva in the northern Negev desert.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Aug. 1 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UM BATEEN, Israel _ The Bedouin in the Abu Kaf family raise
camels and goats, grow their own food and value the
self-sufficiency they have on their desert hillside.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are satisfied with our lives. We just want to stay on our
land,'' said 52-year-old Talal Abu Kaf, seated on carpets on the
land where his family has lived for hundreds of years.
</P>
<P>
   About 3,500 Bedouin live in here in Um Bateen, where the water
arrives in black tubes that snake from house to house and
barefooted children fly kites fashioned from scraps of trash.
</P>
<P>
   But, as far as the Israeli government is concerned, Um Bateen
barely exists. The village is one of about 45 Bedouin settlements
in the Negev Desert that remains unrecognized by the government and
therefore denied its own local government or services such as
electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Bedouin leaders hope Israel's month-old government will
give the 70,000 villagers in unrecognized settlements equal status
with their neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   They back a $123-million plan to recognize 16 additional
villages in Negev and upgrade the medical, educational and utility
services for them and others.
</P>
<P>
   Parliamentary candidates in the spring elections gave tentative
backing to the plan, but it is too early to tell if they will
implement it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every election they come here. After the election, everything
vanishes,'' said Alasam Atiah, chairman of the Regional Council for
the Unrecognized Negev Arab Villages. ``Now, we have some
connections, so maybe we can do something.''
</P>
<P>
   A key backer of the improvement plan was Labor Party
parliamentarian Yossi Beilin. More than 90 percent of the Bedouin
voted for Labor's Ehud Barak in his election as prime minister, but
Beilin's personal endorsement expressly did not bind his party to
the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``How fast we can deal with it, I cannot tell you,'' said Amir
Avramovitch, Beilin's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's Bedouin -- a Muslim Arab sub-group -- have long had
trouble fitting in with the modern Jewish state. For generations,
they roamed the Negev and Sinai deserts, traveling the feeding
routes of their camels and goats while authorities of the old
Ottoman Empire or British Colonial rule cared little about their
arid land.
</P>
<P>
   But, since they took over in 1948, Israeli authorities have
actively settled and industrialized the Negev. The desert's
development has been important as it comprises more than half of
Israel, a country about the size of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Bedouin need government permits to travel the routes of
their livestock and most have abandoned their nomadic ways. Many
rely on farming or, if they are not among the 50 percent of Bedouin
unemployed, they work in Israel's cities. Hundreds serve in the
Israeli army.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has taken most Bedouin land and knocked down their tents
and block homes. Technically, 16,000 Bedouin homes in the
unrecognized settlements are under threat of demolition. The
authorities usually just target occasional new structures, but that
has lead to near riots.
</P>
<P>
   The Bedouin say the government has taken 98 percent of their
land, sometimes offering paltry compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Their hold on the land is often more traditional than legal.
Clinton Bailey, who has studied them for more than 30 years, said
the Bedouin often fail to register their land because they crave
privacy and fear government taxation. Often, the land was not in
demand, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Conditions for the Bedouin lag far behind the rest of Israel.
According to a study by an Israeli think tank, the Negev Bedouin
infant mortality rate is 19 per 1,000 compared to just four per
1,000 for Jewish infants. Half the families live below the poverty
line.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Israel recognizes seven out of 52 Negev Bedouin
cities and only two of those are allowed Bedouin leadership. The
government gives them services in hopes other Bedouin will move
there rather than stay spread out where, the government maintains,
it is too hard to provide services.
</P>
<P>
   For moving to the recognized villages, the Bedouin can receive
modest subsidies, such as an acre of land and a few thousand
dollars. But, the recognized towns have high unemployment and
frequent disputes between families over their small plots of land.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Bedouin fear that the city life means forfeiting their
land, privacy and tent compounds, and exposing their traditions --
such as polygamy -- to possible extinction.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, unrecognized villages such as Um Bateen struggle with
a lack electricity, steady water supplies, high schools and
adequate health care centers. The Association for Civil Rights in
Israel, the country's largest independent civil rights group,
called last month(July) for better health care for the Negev
Bedouin.
</P>
<P>
   Moti Zaken, adviser to the Israeli government on Arab affairs,
noted that the government recently started a five-year, $154
million plan to improve services for 50,000 Bedouin in northern
Israel. He said it is time to take care of the Negev, but the
Bedouin there are more dispersed and more attached to traditional
land claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much more complicated,'' he said. ``It's confronting the
Old World with the New World.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
