r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-SKYE-COX     07-30 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SKYE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Isle of Skye full of beautiful landscape and heavenly visions
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLE OF SKYE, Scotland _ Within minutes of crossing the bridge
from the Scottish mainland, my wife, Cathy, and I left more than
our earthly cares behind. We left Earth. Crossing a ridge in our
rental car in early evening, plunging through wisps of cloud into a
vast V-shaped ravine toward a pewter-colored loch, we arrived on
Planet Skye.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the occasional cottage of whitewashed stone, not a
human habitation could be seen. Thus the ubiquitous sheep _ peering
down from rocky crags, scratching their sides against fenceposts _
seemed like friendly aliens, welcoming us to their ruggedly
beautiful world. The treeless landscape was carpeted with
grayish-green briar and pale purple heather. Waterfalls, flush with
frequent rains, glinted with silvery brightness against the dark
slopes. Mountains _ some surreally topped by patches of June snow _
loomed ahead, and more mountains hunkered dimly in the mist behind
them, like the ghosts of their ancestors.
</P>
<P>
   Mist is a leitmotif of Skye _ called Eilean o Cheo (Island of
Mist) in Gaelic _ whose turbulent and bloody history is now stilled
in ancient standing stones, the ruins of medieval castles and Iron
Age forts. The island's name comes from skuy, the word for cloud
among the Norsemen who raided these western Scottish shores in the
Middle Ages. But we decided, after a two-day exploration of the
northern half of the 50-mile-long island (which ranges from seven
to 25 miles wide), that Skye simply means sky. Some of the island's
greatest glories are overhead. Light puts on a constant, awesome
show, refracted through tumbling mists or breaking through clouds
to form searchlight beams that sweep across the hillsides. In the
words of Kate Porteus, proprietor of the Quiraing Lodge: ``With the
weather changing completely every 20 minutes, we never lack for
entertainment up here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Up here'' means the same latitude as Alaska, so summer
twilights linger past 11 p.m. It was between 8 and 9 p.m. when we
crested a ridge and saw the town of Portree, our destination, in
the distance. Since it had been mostly overcast on our four-hour
drive from Glasgow and we'd assumed the sun was long gone, it was
startling when clouds ahead began glowing reddish and backlighted
the cliffs above the town. There, weirdly silhouetted and poking
out from the cliffs like a colossal gargoyle, is the Old Man of
Storr, a 165-foot column of basalt. It marks the beginning of
amazing rock formations stretching along the northeastern coast
beyond.
</P>
<P>
   We descended into the harbor town as if into a dream.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
