<HEADER>
A9656 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-SKYEROCKS-COX     07-30 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SKYEROCKS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Slipping into a hiker's paradise
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLE OF SKYE, Scotland _ I spent the better part of a cool,
windy morning trying to get into prison. And The Prison set me
free.
</P>
<P>
   From a precarious perch in this well-named rock formation _ a
maze of spooky natural monoliths suggesting jail bars _ I had an
exhilarating view. Two thousand feet below I could see Staffin Bay,
distant rock islets and green hills where hundred-yard rows of peat
moss strips _ sliced from the turf and flipped over to dry _ looked
like colossal zippers holding the land together.
</P>
<P>
   The Prison is one of the most striking formations in the Quirang
(COO-rang, from the Gaelic), a cluster of eccentric low mountains
on the east coast of Skye's northermost Trotternish Peninsula. As
you drive past The Prison, or wind toward it on the popular hiking
trail that starts on the Uig Road, the rocks offer shifting shapes
and evocations. At twilight, when fog seeps out between the
monoliths, it seems a huge witches' caldron _ a good place, say,
for Macbeth to meet the Weird Sisters. When the light allows a
brief glimpse into The Prison's deep recesses, it becomes the
Minotaur's maze, beckoning to suckers like me.
</P>
<P>
   Impatient to enter the maze, I left the gently rising path to
strike up an almost-vertical funnel-shaped ravine filled with loose
rock, which occasionally dislodged and banged down the mountain for
an unnervingly long time. Looking down, I suddenly realized that
giant boulders in the valley below had obviously tumbled down this
ravine. And I understood why the Trotternish coast is called one of
Europe's largest landslips. It's a place where masses of soft rock
are slumping toward the sea from a 4,000-foot spine of volcanic
basalt _ of which The Prison bars are a skeletal remnant.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling I was about to personally experience landslip, I
nervously gripped the ravine wall and with the other hand gingerly
focused my camera on a looming monolith. Boom: a black cloud
clamped over the sun like an iron lid. As Lee Swedenbourg, a
visitor from San Francisco, told me earlier, ``You can line up the
greatest shots in the world on Skye, but by the time you get the
lens cap off, they're gone.'' Ah, well. I quickly retreated down
the trembly ravine.
</P>
<P>
   The Quiraing is remote even by Skye standards, with few hotels
handy, but there is an exceptional one in the Quiraing Lodge, a
rambling, homey 1850 hunting lodge on the south shore of Staffin
Bay. Innkeeper Kate Porteus' vegetarian dinner and breakfast
(included in the $93.50 charge for a double) are satisfying even to
a dedicated carnivore. In the back yard is a rare and lovely sight:
a freshwater river tumbling steeply into the salt bay.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond is another prime hiking area (Wellingtons are a must, and
Porteus has a pair for every foot!), a secluded headland strewn
with yellow irises and purple thistle. Streams chuckle in hidden
gullies. Cormorants boldly dive for fish in the sea swells.
Standing atop the headland, my wife, Cathy and I got a view that
silenced us for minutes, as we swiveled 360 degrees to take in the
Quiraing, backlit by the evening sun (it was about 9:30 p.m.), and
a rolling plateau of sheep pastures cut off by seaside cliffs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-99 0924EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990730.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 09:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9657 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-SKYETOUR-COX     07-30 1829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SKYETOUR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A violent past, Serene present
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLE OF SKYE, Scotland _ Skye, part of the Inner Hebrides that
arc across the northwest coast of the Scottish Highlands, has bred
a tough, independent, outsider spirit, not unlike American outposts
such as Appalachia and the Old West.
</P>
<P>
   It was here in 1746 that Flora MacDonald fearlessly harbored
Bonnie Prince Charlie, fugitive pretender to the English throne, by
smuggling him over from another island in a rowboat and disguising
him as her Irish maid, ``Betty Burke.'' Skye clans were a law unto
themselves _ specifically, the MacDonalds and the MacLeods, who
feuded bloodily for centuries. Visits from English kings failed to
shake them into submission.
</P>
<P>
   Portree, the island's only substantial town, is derived, some
believe, from the Gaelic Portrigh (Port of the King), commemorating
one of these ineffectual saber-rattling visits by James V in 1540.
</P>
<P>
   We stayed at the Bosville, a delightfully snug
turn-of-the-century hotel with pine-paneled rooms. For dinner we
had local salmon: heaven on a plate. The local ale is classified by
weight, not unlike American motor oil (``70 shilling'' is golden
and medium, ``80 shilling'' is dark and heavy), but tastes much
better. The Scots' typically hearty morning meal (eggs with choice
of kippers, smoked haddock or ham and sausages) is built into the
price of a Bosville room ($150, double). ``After this breakfast,''
a waitress cracked, ``you're set for the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Below the hotel, pastel storefronts picturesquely line the quay,
where fishermen load their craft to the cries of wheeling gulls.
Beyond the quay is The Lump, a little fistlike peninsula in the
harbor, topped by a grassy amphitheater where traditional Scottish
games are played on warm evenings. A flagpole marks where public
hangings took place well into the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   Strolling among these sights on a quiet, cloudy morning, it's
hard to believe the island was once a violent place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pace is so easy here they actually call it Skye Time,''
says Allison Rouse, who was so taken with the isle that she ditched
her career as an Edinburgh lawyer a few years ago to run the
Rosedale Hotel on the quay. ``The newspapers from the mainland
don't arrive until half ten (10:30 a.m.) and nobody cares. It's
wonderful _ like the Spaniards' notion of manana. But when a
repairman says he'll do it Wednesday, it's a good idea to ask,
`Which Wednesday?'''
</P>
<P>
   From hilltop fort to sunken dungeon
</P>
<P>
   After lunch a steady rain (get used to it _ the price you pay
for the lush greenery and all those thrashing streams) sent us into
our car. We were bound on a circuit of the top half of Skye that
would take us south to Sligachan, northwest to Dunvegan Castle and
north around the Trotternish Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest of Sligachan, we spotted the ruins of Dun (or Hill)
Beag, best preserved of the brochs, or stone forts, on the island
that have been dated to a century before or after Christ. They're
believed to have protected livestock from thieves. Dun Beag is
worth the 100-yard climb from the road because there's more to its
roofless ruins than can be seen from below. Kids would have a ball
(within reason, since this is a fragile historic site) exploring
the trenchlike passage between the inner and outer walls and the
little round chambers that bulge out of the outer walls. It's a set
for a tykes' ``Braveheart.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost across the road begins a loop to the secluded Ullinish
Lodge, a handsome 18th-century inn that hosted Samuel Johnson and
James Boswell on the 1773 trip that Boswell recorded as ``Journal
of a Tour of the Hebrides.'' Judging by a quick tour, the rates,
starting at $103 for two, are astoundingly reasonable, especially
with a 2,700-acre back yard for shooting and fishing. There's a
magnificent view of Loch Harport and The Cuillins, famed hiking
mountains of southern Skye. There was no arguing with proprietor
Claudia Mulford: ``If it's ruggedness you want in your sceneries,
we're second to none.''
</P>
<P>
   Using the detailed map in the indispensable booklet ``Touring
the Isle of Skye'' (sold at the Bosville), we spotted two standing
stones, dramatically framed against Loch Snizort Beag, though
they're on private, fenced-off property. Legend says the stones
supported the stew pot for the island's ancient giants, the
Fiennes. (Much larger, judging by the monoliths, than their
namesake actors Ralph and Joseph.)
</P>
<P>
   Attention must be paid to the oldest continually inhabited
residence in Scotland: Dunvegan Castle, perched on Skye's
nothwestern shore, still seat of the MacLeod clan after 720 years.
</P>
<P>
   The stone exterior, evidently added in the early 20th century,
is drab but completely deceptive: The beautifully preserved
interior has weapons, documents, portraits and furnishings
representative of every century since the 16th. A source of
fascination is the Fairy Flag, of which a tattered scrap is
displayed on the wall. Legend says that it was a gift to an early
MacLeod chief from his fairy lover, tenderly placed over his
sleeping child when the nanny slipped out for a nip of celidh
(party) cheer. Whether you buy the notion that the flag gives
magical protection for any fighting MacLeod (soldier sons who
carried photos of it survived World War I) or can charm herring
into the bay, you have to be intrigued that fiber analysis suggests
it was made in medieval Syria. One theory is that it was a banner
for knights in the Crusades.
</P>
<P>
   With all the tasteful exhibits in Dunvegan, it's almost a relief
to peer down into the shadowy dungeon _ the oldest, 13th-century,
part of the castle, a pit scooped from solid rock _ and hear a tape
loop of moans and groans. Amusingly cheesy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prodigious wild prospects''
</P>
<P>
   Heading north and east, we circled the most remote, northwestern
part of the Trotternish Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   The ``main'' coastal road, weaving on a high headland, narrowed
to a single track with frequent turnouts to let a car pass; local
etiquette demands that you salute the turnout-ee. With the timeless
air of the landscape, who's in a hurry anyway?
</P>
<P>
   We rounded a bend to find the road clogged with sheep _
galloping toward us, the lambs bobbing in their stiff-legged way,
like rocking horses. We laughed with delight as their fleeces
brushed past the car.
</P>
<P>
   Further on is the Skye Museum of Island Life, featuring exhibits
of tools, diaries, paintings, photographs and other personal
effects of island crofters (farmers), fishermen and seaweed
harvesters. All of it is cozily tucked into the characteristic
thatched ``black houses'' that were inhabited right up to the
1950s. On the hill behind the museum is a Celtic cross marking the
grave of the aforementioned Flora MacDonald.
</P>
<P>
   As the road swings around to the south, toward Staffin and
Portree, the coastline becomes more cliffy and dramatic. One thinks
of Robert Louis Stevenson, who traveled among these islands as a
boy with his lighthouse-builder father and wrote in ``Kidnapped,''
set on the similar Isle of Mull: ``The sea runs deep into the
mountains and winds about their roots, making the country full of
prodigious wild prospects.''
</P>
<P>
   The picturesque ruins of Duntlum Castle, old power base of the
MacDonalds, commands a headland. It was abandoned in 1732, believed
cursed when a nurse dropped a baby out of a window onto the rocks
below. After passing by the imposingly eerie Quiraing rocks and
through the immaculate village of Staffin, we pulled over to take
pictures of Kilt Rock, the most amazing seaside precipice I've seen
outside Ireland's Cliffs of Moher. The tubelike columns of smooth
black basalt make the cliff look a bit like a pleated kilt.
</P>
<P>
   We backtracked to Staffin to stay at the Quiraing Lodge and rest
up for an assault on the Quiraing rocks the next morning, before
heading back to the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   An image to remember
</P>
<P>
   In our 40-hour whirlwind tour, we were sorry to miss seals,
puffins and eagles _ all most common, the locals say, out on the
island's northwestern Duirinish Peninsula. Nor did we manage to
catch one of the frequent local rainbows. But a chance encounter of
a different kind had a magical effect.
</P>
<P>
   Late on the evening we arrived, I couldn't resist a little
reconnaissance around Portree, even though it was drizzling.
Following the lane that winds steeply above the Bosville, I looked
out over the harbor and saw a weirdly beautiful sight: a sheer,
towering wall of fog stretching from one cliff to another, neatly
sealing off the harbor, perhaps marking the line where the colder
ocean waters start. I thought of the vanished fishermen who'd had
to plunge into that wall _ and worse _ or starve.
</P>
<P>
   Strolling back into town, I thought I heard Celtic music _
fiddle and accordion _ but it was so faint below the patter of rain
on my umbrella that I couldn't be sure. Most of the town's lights
were out. Finding myself at the dead end of a side street _ a wall
looking straight down on the quay _ I realized the music was coming
from the Celidh (pronounced kaylee) Room pub right beside me.
</P>
<P>
   Peering through the fogged windows, I saw four older couples
clapping and singing in front of the musicians, evidently the
rugged survivors of a long night of revelry. A gray-haired man and
(would it be too much to presume?) his gray-haired wife playfully
circled each other on the little plank dance floor. The music _ the
sound, somehow, of melancholy squeezed and distilled into joy _
built to a head. The man stiffly but gallantly extended his arm,
and the woman, with as much girlish grace as she could muster,
arched her back against it, and for an instant there were flashes
of white teeth in laughing mouths.
</P>
<P>
   I went in for a nightcap.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   -- Getting there: British Airways flies to Inverness, Scotland,
with a plane change at London's Gatwick Airport. For departures
through Sept. 4, the fare is $1,072, with a seven-day advance
purchase and Saturday night stay required. Or fly to London and
take BritRail up to Scotland or rent a car. The current best fare
to London is a ``Midtown Special'' consolidator special: $559 round
trip on departures through Sept. 6 _ or $406 for departures Sept. 7
through Oct. 31. Only a travel agent can book this special; you'll
be told the airline when you reserve. Some restrictions apply.
</P>
<P>
   -- Accommodations: (use 011-44 phone prefix) Bosville Hotel,
Portree, 147-861-2846; Quiraing Lodge, Staffin, 147-056-2330;
Ullinish Lodge, Struan, 147-057-2214.
</P>
<P>
   -- Hiking: For information on hiking the Quiraing, the Cuillins,
Neist Point and other scenic areas of Skye, see ``Walking in
Scotland'' at www
</P>
<P>
   .b-mercer.demon.co.uk/skywalk.htm.
</P>
<P>
   -- Information: British Tourist Authority, 1-800-462-2748;
online at www.usagateway.visitbritain.com or www.skye.co.uk.
</P>
