<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ WARSAW _ The Old Town district is where you
find the young people, a fine place for music and beer on warm
summer evenings. So it was that I was here in search of our newest
NATO allies, Warsaw's young warriors, Poland's finest, prepared as
they were to lay down their lives for the NATO way of life.
(Murray, Cox News Service) MOVED THURSDAY FOR SATURDAY.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ A new suggestion of evidence
that the FBI lied about its actions during the final tragic assault
on the Branch Davidian compound _ as tenuous as it may be _ is
difficult to dismiss. (Nethaway, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED FOR
SATURDAY.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ The selling of donor lists by
some PBS affiliates is reprehensible, shameful, insensitive to the
nature and mission of public broadcasting. The same could be said
for those Republicans who are seizing upon the scandal as an excuse
to ``re-examine'' federal funding for public television.(McCarty,
Dayton Daily News) MOVED FOR SATURDAY.
</P>
<P>
   MINTER-COLUMN _ FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ For a long time I've
thought that if there is such a thing as reincarnation I'd like to
come back rich and live in South Georgia. Not necessarily
Rockefeller rich, but rich in the way of friends whose hospitality
I've often enjoyed. (Jim Minter is a former editor of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED FOR SATURDAY.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Trying to forecast Middle East politics would
unnerve even the most brazen soothsayer, but for what they are
worth, the early portents from the change in Israeli governments
are promising. (Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox
Newspapers.) MOVED THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ For those of us fortunate to have insurance
reimbursement for our drugs, the Golden Years are a lot more
palatable than for those who don't; those who cut their pills in
half, take them maybe once every three days, or can't afford them
at all. (Howard Kleinberg is a columnist for Cox News Service.)
MOVED THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ The real story of the Big Boil of 1999 is not how
many people have been subjected to the heat but rather how many
millions have all but escaped its full impact in
temperature-controlled houses, offices, cars and malls. (Andy Glass
is a columnist for Cox News Service in the Washington bureau.)
MOVED THURSDAY FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ After a tension-packed race that
went down to the wire, New York's next U.S. senator, Hillary Rodham
Clinton, celebrated her victory by ripping off her blouse, falling
to her knees and screaming for joy. By pulling off her top in a
sign of triumph, New York's next senator was following the recent
example of Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright, who pulled off
her blouse after the televised signing of a new Mideast peace
accord between Palestinian and Israeli leaders in the White House
Rose Garden. (Nethaway, Waco Tribune-Herald). MOVED THURSDAY FOR
SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN _ WASHINGTON _ For millions of Americans,
nothing fosters a sense of security quite like a fat roll of crisp
$20 bills. Polls show that as more people begin preparing for New
Year's Day and the computer problems that may come with it, the
desire to hoard cash is growing. The Federal Reserve Bank is
bracing for large cash withdrawals late in the year, even while
assuring customers that such stockpiling is unnecessary. (Geewax,
Cox News Service). 22. FOR SUNDAY
</P>
