   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-JAKES _ ATLANTA _ He's big and he's back. Bishop T. D.
Jakes, dubbed the black Billy Graham, spends much of the week in
Atlanta, talking to tens of thousands of women taking part in his
``Woman, Thou Art Loosed'' revival at the Georgia Dome. Jakes has
turned himself into a mini-industry, pastoring a mega-church in
Dallas, writing books and lecturing across the country. We explore
the reasons for his success and what the future holds as he wraps
up his latest visit to the metro area. (Blake, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25. EMBARGOED UNTIL 0731
</P>
<P>
   WITH CHURCH-WOMEN _ ATLANTA _ The church has pushed women aside
for years, even told them to keep quiet in church. But they've
always been around, always been pushing for change, always been the
congregants who got work done. Now, more than ever, they are being
noticed and, in some cases, being accepted as leaders. Bishop T.D.
Jakes, a Dallas-based minister who has a national following,
understands the power of women and their importance in the church.
Other pastors are also taking notice. We talk with Jakes about his
ministry, his interest in empowering women, and what the future
holds. (Blake, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   COPTIC-VISIT _ For many Egyptian immigrants in the Miami Valley,
this is the most important summer of their lives. Pope Shenouda
III, the patriarch of the Coptic religion, is visiting St. Mina &AMP;
St. Abunoub Coptic Orthodox Church in Centerville Aug. 20. It is
the first time the patriarch has come to southwestern Ohio. ``It is
really a big event for us,'' said Father John Ragheb, 41. ``We are
really excited _ for some it will be their first time to meet him,
and they will be very honored.'' (Dayton Daily News). 15. WITH
PHOTO. RELIGION-CONVERTS _ Not so many years ago, Eugene Genovese
was a committed communist and his wife, Elizabeth Fox-Genovese, a
feminist scholar with a Marxist point of view. Not only that but
they had been nonbelievers almost all their lives. But today the
Genoveses are devout Catholics, taking Holy Communion each week at
the Cathedral of Christ the King in Buckhead. (Skube, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 80. WITH PHOTOS and LAYOUT
</P>
