<HEADER>
A9719 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN31-COX     07-30 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Leave public broadcasting alone
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The selling of donor lists by some PBS affiliates
is reprehensible, shameful, insensitive to the nature and mission
of public broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said for those Republicans who are seizing
upon the scandal as an excuse to ``re-examine'' federal funding for
public television.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I'm mad at the 26 PBS stations that have swapped donor
lists with political parties. But I'm even madder at the
Republicans exploiting the scandal as a pretext to dredge up their
deep-seated antipathy for any federal funding for public
broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about throwing out the baby with the bath water. If our
public libraries became embroiled in scandal, would politicians be
calling for an end to federal support?
</P>
<P>
   Of course not. You punish the individuals involved, not the
whole organization.
</P>
<P>
   PBS president Ervin S. Duggan is recommending an independent
investigation into whether the list-swapping violates federal tax
law. That question, certainly, deserves scrutiny _ but so do the
motives of those who would yank federal funding from public
broadcasting, which enriches all our lives in innumerable ways.
</P>
<P>
   It's ironic that the funding review is being called for so soon
after the Columbine tragedy. Remember all the soul-searching about
violence in the media? Yet here we have some members of Congress
who refuse to rein in the NRA, but can't wait to clip the wings of
public broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   I know I'm not the only parent, Republican or Democrat, who
feels PBS is the one place you can park the kids without their
being bombarded with garbage _ be it sex, violence or commercial
brainwashing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Increasingly, we do hear from parents who are looking for a
safe haven for their children,'' said David Fogarty, president and
general manager of WPTD-TV (Channel 16) and WPTO-TV (Channel 14).
</P>
<P>
   It's not only wild-eyed liberals who share my enthusiasm for
public TV. Our local PBS stations are heavily supported by
corporations, community leaders, citizens of every political
stripe. ``We have the area's largest membership organization of
23,000 members,'' Fogarty said, ``and those folks are as diverse as
this community, politically and in every other way.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the federal government gives $250 million a year to
the Corporation for Public Broadcasting _ less than a dollar for
every American. Do we really want to fall even farther behind
countries like Canada and Great Britain in our support of this
vital public resource?
</P>
<P>
   WPTD and WPTO received $650,000 in federal funding last year,
roughly 10 percent of the stations' annual budgets _ already a
``significant drop'' since 1995, Fogarty said. Further reductions
would prompt ``a critical look at what programs we could purchase,
and whether we stay on the air 24 hours a day,'' Fogarty said.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes the scandal won't undermine the trust of the public,
who contribute more than half the stations' budgets. ``We want
people to know that if they're a donor, their names are safe with
us,'' Fogarty said.
</P>
<P>
   Others argue that the scandal proves PBS can survive in the open
market. ``Big Bird is strong enough to fly on his own,'' wrote
Boston Globe columnist Jeff Jacoby. ``It's time he was told to
leave the nest.''
</P>
<P>
   Leave it to the marketplace, the thinking goes.
</P>
<P>
   Well, the marketplace has brought us ``Melrose Place'' and
``Jerry Springer.'' Public television has brought us ``Sesame
Street,'' ``Masterpiece Theater,'' Ken Burns' ``The Civil War.''
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, I hope Big Bird sticks around
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCarty writes for the Dayton Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
