<HEADER>
A9721 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINTER-COLUMN31-COX     07-30 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: South Georgia's good life
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ For a long time I've thought that if there
is such a thing as reincarnation I'd like to come back rich and
live in South Georgia. Not necessarily Rockefeller rich, but rich
in the way of friends whose hospitality I've often enjoyed.
</P>
<P>
   They all have a pickup that runs good, two or three shotguns, a
carport full of fishing poles, a couple of bird dogs, and
good-looking wives who don't give them much trouble as long as they
stay out of fistfights at Georgia football games and don't get too
friendly with the waitresses at the Moose Lodge.
</P>
<P>
   I've wondered if life below the gnat line is really that good,
or if it just looks that way from a distance. After Dwain Walden's
book arrived in the mail, I no longer have doubts. Life in South
Georgia is just as wonderful as I suspected.
</P>
<P>
   Dwain is editor of the Moultrie Observer, and has been since
1981. Born in Cairo, raised on a farm near Whigham, he earned his
journalism degree at Georgia State University while carefully
avoiding citification. His book is a collection of columns from the
Observer. No persons raised in South Georgia, or who wish they had
been, should be without ``From My Back Porch.'' You can get a copy
by writing the Moultrie Observer in Moultrie.
</P>
<P>
   Life in South Georgia is different from Atlanta, or from Middle
Georgia, or from North Georgia. South Georgians are more laid back.
They have perfected an ambience perhaps unique in all the world. An
example is Dwain's complaint about stress caused by having to
decide whether to go fishing or barbecue ribs.
</P>
<P>
   His book is about, among other things, butterbeans, crowder
peas, roastneers (roasting ears), lightered (lightwood) knots,
washholes, religion, bird dogs, fishing the Ochlockonee,
skinny-dipping, religion, marriage, vegetable gardens, UFOs,
neighbors, heart pine pews, and how everybody bunches up in front
of the macaroni and fried chicken when the Providence Baptist
Church has dinners on the grounds. It paints, along with the
laughs, the most authentic picture of farm and small-town life I
know about.
</P>
<P>
   Although the author grew up a few years behind me, similarities
in our rural past are amazing. I certainly understood when he wrote
about the rocking chair: ``It was on my grandma's front porch.
Before we had a television I'd climb into this big, high-back
rocker with a cowhide bottom and journey to far-off places. I drove
a stagecoach, piloted the African Queen, dodged poisonous arrows,
and even turned a triple play ...
</P>
<P>
   ``A corn field across the road was the Amazon jungle.
Silhouettes of great water oaks were giants I held at bay. Distant
headlights were the torches of an advancing army. A cow's bellow
was the roar of a rogue lion on the Serengeti Plain. A dog barking
was one of Jack London's wolves.'' (How does that compare to an
afternoon of strolling a shopping mall?)
</P>
<P>
   I spent many summer afternoons in my own grandmother's
front-porch swing, seated under an armrest, bare feet dangling,
pumping the swing sideways, piloting a B-17 over Frankfurt and
Berlin, dodging Messerschmitts and German flak, bombing Hitler to
smithereens.
</P>
<P>
   Something else the South Georgian and I have in common are
vegetable gardens, and wives who wonder why we have them. Dwain
says it happens every spring. ``She asks me why I plant a vegetable
garden, when considering all the time and expense I put into it I
could buy the produce at much less the cost.'' He always gives her
the same answer: ``Because.''
</P>
<P>
   Because his father always planted one, and before that his
grandfather, and before that his grandfather's father, all the way
back to Ireland and the potato famine.
</P>
<P>
   It's funny how kids growing up 200 miles and almost two decades
apart remember the same insignificant tidbits. Dwain retains
cherished memory of his father thumping watermelons to see if they
were ripe, and how the two halves fell apart under his Barlow
knife.
</P>
<P>
   My boys were in a conversation just last week about how their
grandfather, gone 30 years now, cut their watermelons. He used a
string instead of a knife. I can't explain why, but when he did,
kids stood around to watch, as if he was performing magic.
</P>
<P>
   In Attapulgus and Whigham and thereabouts, a fire in a fireplace
is much more than a place to keep warm. ``I think some of the
greatest thoughts have come from in front of a fireplace,'' Dwain
speculates. ``The purveyor of those thoughts focused on yellow
tongues licking oak logs, warmed by the flames and subsequent
insights into the mysteries of the universe, like: `Why did God
make mosquitoes?'''
</P>
<P>
   Dwain Walden is a man who takes his mother bream fishing for her
Mother's Day present, remembers what he learned at Providence
Baptist Church, shares bologna sandwiches with his bird dog, and
complains about having to negotiate a four-way stop every day when
he drives home to lunch.
</P>
<P>
   I love his reply when a friend asked him what he did last Friday
night: ``Sat on the back porch and listened to the rain.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Minter is a former editor of The Atlanta Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
