<HEADER>
A9722 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN31-COX     07-30 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Feds have only themselves to blame for Davidian raid
skeptics
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ A new suggestion of evidence that the FBI lied
about its actions during the final tragic assault on the Branch
Davidian compound _ as tenuous as it may be _ is difficult to
dismiss.
</P>
<P>
   After all, officials with the FBI, the Justice Department and
the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms so severely damaged
their credibility during and following the incident that it is
difficult to accept these recent denials of wrongdoing at face
value.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest development, the appointed board chairman of the
Texas Department of Public Safety said he believes that evidence
recovered from the charred remains of the Branch Davidian compound
appears to contradict FBI and Justice Department claims that agents
did not use incendiary devices on the day of the fiery assault.
</P>
<P>
   Before a worldwide television audience on the windy morning of
April 19, 1993, FBI tanks attacked the compound and pumped massive
quantities of disabling gas into the building.
</P>
<P>
   Branch Davidian survivors have claimed that FBI agents fired
into the building and that government incendiary devices were
responsible for the fire and the resulting deaths of 76 men, women
and children inside the building. Autopsies revealed that 17
Davidians died from gunshots.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to end the 51-day siege with a tank assault was
made by Attorney General Janet Reno and FBI tactical agents over
the objections of FBI behavioral experts who warned that the action
could cause a mass suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Balancing the conflicting claims of the followers of David
Koresh, the Branch Davidians' apocalyptic leader, and federal law
enforcement agents would be no problem for most Americans had
government officials not been caught in a swirl of lies, cover-ups,
evasions and denials.
</P>
<P>
   Paranoid, anti-government conspiracy zealots maintain that ATF
and FBI agents purposefully massacred the innocent Davidians, which
is preposterous.
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans believe that the Davidians _ at least their
leaders _ were not innocent and that the government made a series
of flawed decisions that led to the tragic ending, which is not
preposterous.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials conducted a self-examination of
their own actions and produced a massive three-volume, 1,000-page
report filled with self-praise and no blame. The New York Times
properly called the report a whitewash.
</P>
<P>
   The reason no one in the Justice Department or the FBI was
blamed for wrong decisions or actions was because no one did
anything wrong, Americans were told. ``People should get blamed if
they did something wrong,'' Reno said. No wrong, no blame.
</P>
<P>
   Congress and the administration should have insisted on an
independent investigation of Justice Department and FBI actions.
They didn't.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury Department ordered an independent investigation
into the actions of ATF agents in the botched initial raid. That
report listed a series of lies, cover-ups and mistakes by ATF
officials, who received little or no punishment.
</P>
<P>
   DPS Chairman James B. Francis Jr., according to the Dallas
Morning News, said evidence held by the state indicates that the
sort of incendiary devices that the FBI claims it did not use were
found in areas of the compound where fires broke out.
</P>
<P>
   Francis also said FBI agents made statements to Texas Rangers
after the fire ``that are contradictory'' to the government's
subsequent account of events.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some evidence there that the world needs to see, in
my opinion,'' Francis said. ``The government does not want this
evidence out, and yet, that's not right.''
</P>
<P>
   A Justice Department spokesman called the allegations nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps so. But Justice Department officials have no one to
blame but themselves for their unbelievable claims of
blamelessness.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
