<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 11:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9725 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN1-CO     07-30 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN1-COX-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DOLLARS AND SENSE FOR Y2K
 &HT;    Eds: Note corrections in grafs 5 and 8. In graf 5, second
sentence: from ``That increase'' to ``By some estimates, that
increase.'' In graf 8, from ``this week'' to ``last week.''
 &HT;    Marilyn Geewax, formerly with the Atlanta Journal and
Constitution, is now a national correspondent with Cox Newspapers'
Washington Bureau.
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Aug. 1
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For millions of Americans, nothing fosters a sense
of security quite like a fat roll of crisp $20 bills.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show that as more people begin preparing for New Year's
Day and the computer problems that may come with it, the desire to
hoard cash is growing. The Federal Reserve Bank is bracing for
large cash withdrawals late in the year, even while assuring
customers that such stockpiling is unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   The cash craving is being fed by fears about the ``Y2K bug,'' a
software flaw that will cause some older computers to interpret
dates ending in ``00'' as 1900 instead of 2000. That
misunderstanding has the potential to shut down the computerized
systems that control everything from power generators to financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Though programmers are racing to correct the problem, some
people doubt they will finish the job in time to avert disruptions
in many basic services. A poll conducted by the Associated Press in
mid-July found that one-quarter of Americans plan to take extra
money out of the bank in case problems arise, such as automated
teller machines that stop working or power outages that keep banks
closed.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare for a possible grab for greenbacks in December, the
nation's central bank is increasing the value of its cash inventory
by the end of September to more than $200 billion, up from its
usual $150 billion. By some estimates, that increase would provide
enough cash for each U.S. household to withdraw an extra $500 for
New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Fed governors last(cq) month voted to make
special loans to banks, thrifts and credit unions that might need
emergency funds because of consumer fears about Y2K. The loans will
be offered from Oct. 1 to April 7 to help financial institutions
``more confidently commit'' to making loans to other banks during
the Y2K transition.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan said last(cq)
month that the efforts to fix Y2K-related problems in the banking
and financial system have been so ``exhaustive'' that ``we expect
the full array of payment options to work'' as usual after Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most risky activity people can take is to take all their
currency out of their banks because there will be a new industry
that will emerge as a consequence ... millenium thievery,'' he told
the Senate Banking Committee last week.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, bankers point out that dollars can be destroyed by
fire, and
</P>
<P>
   money in the mattress is not insured for free up to $100,000, as
it is in a federally insured institution.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan said ``the most sensible thing'' to do on Dec. 31 is
to keep your money insured and earning interest in the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers in many major industrialized nations share the Fed's
belief that cash hoarding is unnecessary and even foolhardy. Still,
the central banks in Japan, Britain, Canada, Sweden, Italy,
Switzerland and Singapore are printing more money to prepare for
the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   And while hoarding cash can be unsafe for individuals, it isn't
risk-free for bankers either. According to a report by the Bank of
England on Y2K preparations, the huge stacks of bills will create
so many security problems that many banks around the world are
planning to stash money in secret locations.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, Y2K may create opportunities for those who
prey on armored vehicles. With an extra $50 billion moving in
trucks from the Treasury Department's Bureau of Printing and
Engraving to the Fed's vaults around the nation, guards will have
more money to watch over.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not everyone will be interested in obtaining paper
bills. For those who believe Y2K will trigger social and economic
catastrophes, gold is the answer. For months, companies that sell
gold coins have been urging people to buy the glittering metal to
use in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   One Web site, which opens with the phrase ``Year 2000 News
Flash: Economic Crisis Grips World,'' is offering consumers a
``Gold Jubilee Pack'' of 50 gold medallions bearing likenesses of
religious leaders. For $1,770, consumers get a pack of coins
weighing 4.58 ounces.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site does not mention that this year, gold prices have
tumbled, recently falling to a 20-year low. At current prices, 4.58
ounces of gold is worth less than $1,200.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
