<DOCNO> NYT19990730.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 11:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9727 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD-COX     07-30 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Doormaker's book makes doormaking a do-it-yourself job
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Building a door _ a front entry door, not a cabinet door _ is
something I've thought about, but never even got close to doing.
</P>
<P>
   But the arrival of a new book from Sterling, ``Doormaking: A
Do-It-Yourself Guide,'' by John Birchard, may get me going again.
This $20 softbound book is written by a California doormaker, so
most of the designs are inventive and informal, but the main value
of the book is the general information on building a door that will
last.
</P>
<P>
   There is a detailed discussion of how to work the design around
conditions, such as the amount of exposure the door has to the
elements and the direction in which it faces, and the best ways of
installing doors.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most useful parts of the book is the discussion of
finishing and maintenance. The finishing of wood exposed to sun and
weather has always been a problem for me, and Birchard makes it
abundantly clear that it's a problem for anyone.
</P>
<P>
   However, he does define the options and their consequences, and
provides the best solutions for various situations.
</P>
<P>
   Every time I think about replacing our front door, which
although battered looks OK from the outside, I notice the interior
side of it. One would think we had been housing a restless bobcat.
Long, ugly scratch markings run from the floor all the way to the
doorknob.
</P>
<P>
   Sound advice
</P>
<P>
   In response to recent discussions of quality woodworking tools,
I received an e-mail that I think is worth passing on. The
gentleman writes:
</P>
<P>
   ``I represent a distributor of woodworking power tools and find
myself faced with the same questions, day-in and day-out, relating
to the purchase of inexpensive equipment that will perform to the
high expectations of the purchaser.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a daily basis we have customers come into our store wanting
to purchase a new fence for their 'cost efficient' table saw they
bought elsewhere. They are immediately faced with one or two
problems. Chances are the better grade fence will not fit on their
saw and if it does the cost is far greater than they anticipated.
They also find that other accessories (i.e. good tenoning jigs,
etc.) do not fit their saws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our company does not pay commissions to our sales personnel.
We stress selling the right tool for the needs of the customer. We
will not attempt to sell an arbor saw to someone needing a
contractor's saw. I mention this because when we determine needs of
a customer we also attempt to get them to foresee what they will be
doing in the future. We do not tell a customer to purchase a
contractor saw in anticipation of later upgrading it with a 52-inch
fence, table board, etc. but explain to them that if they purchase
a high quality saw and maintain it properly they will be able to
sell it later, and put that money toward a saw that will meet their
new needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recently I had a customer who owned a contractor saw that was
manufactured by one of the companies you recommended. He wanted to
add a table board and a larger fence. I figured the cost of
upgrading and then figured what he could sell his contractor saw
for and subtracted it from the cost of a Jet 52-inch arbor saw.''
</P>
<P>
   The result, the gentleman reports, was that it would cost a lot
more to upgrade than to sell and buy, and in the case of upgrading
the customer would still have had a 1 1/2 HP saw instead of a 3 HP.
He continues:
</P>
<P>
   ``One other matter that should be mentioned. While I am partial
to Delta and Jet (we sell these brands), your readers should be
cautioned about the fact that these companies have or are selling
``low-end'' equipment such as the Delta Contractor II saw and the
Jet Shopline.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside of the fact that he agrees with me, I'm passing this
man's advice on to you for another reason _ he had the amazing good
taste and class not to mention the name of his store.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: jwarner(at)ajc.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
