<HEADER>
A9732 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAJUNS-COX     07-30 1313
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAJUNS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cajun reunion expected to draw record numbers
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABBEVILLE, La. - Joe and Barbara Hebert have the same last name,
but not simply because they've been married for more than 45 years.
They're both Heberts by birth, and they share a great-great-great
grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not really that amazing in Louisiana,'' Barbara Hebert
Hebert said.
</P>
<P>
   Some 13,000 Louisiana families are named Hebert -- pronounced
A-Bear -- making it the most common surname here. They'll be joined
August 6-8 by Heberts from around the world who are coming to
Abbeville to celebrate their Acadian heritage. This reunion and 80
others across the state are at the heart of a two-week celebration
of Acadian heritage that begins August 1.
</P>
<P>
   Called the Congres Mondial Acadien, or the World Acadian
Congress, the statewide event is expected to attract half a million
visitors with names like Boudreaux, Gautreaux and Prejean.
Acadians, usually called Cajuns in Louisiana, will two-step,
fiddle, speak French, cook gumbos and crack crabs while they share
their common roots, which stretch back to Canada, and before that,
to France.
</P>
<P>
   The first world Acadian reunion, in 1994 in New Brunswick,
Canada, drew 225,000 Acadians. The Louisiana gathering is expected
to be the largest reunion of the Acadians since their expulsion
from Canada in 1755.
</P>
<P>
   ''Historically, we've been scattered to the winds,'' said Brian
Gabriel Comeaux, president and executive director of the congress.
''This is an attempt to get everybody together.''
</P>
<P>
   A quick history lesson:
</P>
<P>
   Acadians are descended from rural French folks who settled in
Acadia, Canada in the 1600s. In 1755, British Canadians, on the
verge of war with France, deported thousands of Acadians after they
refused to pledge their allegiance to the British crown. Many died
along the way, and many families were separated in an attempt to
weaken their resolve to return.
</P>
<P>
   About 3,000 refugees wound up in Louisiana, which had a heavy
French influence even though it was then a Spanish territory. They
settled in the swamps and prairies of Southeast Louisiana, becoming
trappers, loggers, farmers, and fishermen. Their new home was
called Acadiana.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there are large concentrations of Acadians in Louisiana,
eastern Canada, and rural France. There are smaller Acadian
communities in Texas, Massachusetts and Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Almost half a million Louisianans claim Acadian ancestry and
call themselves Cajuns. Many more Louisianans of Scottish, German,
Spanish, Caribbean and African-American descent who have
intermarried with the original Acadians call themselves Cajuns as
well. About 250,000 residents claim French as the primary language
they speak at home, according to the 1990 census.
</P>
<P>
   ''Cajuns are Louisianans who embrace the culture and maybe speak
French,'' Mrs. Hebert said. ''But Acadians are real descendants of
those from Canada. So you can be Cajun without being Acadian, but
if you are Acadian, you are also a Cajun.''
</P>
<P>
   The world congress is the crowning event of FrancoFete, a
year-long celebration of the 300th anniversary of French influence
in Louisiana. The other major tourist draw of FrancoFete is an
exhibit of works by French Impressionist Edgar Degas, on display
through August at the New Orleans Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're the only state that claims such a strong French
heritage,'' said Delia Taylor, spokeswoman with Lt. Gov. Kathleen
Babineaux Blanco's office, which oversees tourism. ''We have so
many people here that speak French, we have parishes instead of
counties, and we are the only state that follows the Napoleonic
Code. Even if you don't have French blood in your veins, you still
have French culture all around you if you live here.''
</P>
<P>
   The economic impact of FrancoFete likely will set a record for
tourism in the state, pushing close to $8 billion. And an
unprecedented 28 million visitors are expected to come to Louisiana
this year.
</P>
<P>
   While the family reunions are the highlight of the world
congress, there are hundreds of events planned, including
festivals, opening and closing ceremonies, French Catholic masses,
and academic conferences. The conferences focus on genealogy, on
diseases that have a higher incidence among Acadians, and on the
preservation of the culture and the French language in Acadian
children.
</P>
<P>
   This last issue is particularly important to Louisianans. Older
Cajuns such as the Heberts -- Joe is 71 and Barbara is 68 --
remember when being Cajun was something to be ashamed of. Both grew
up speaking only French, and were quickly admonished and encouraged
to speak English once they started school. Many children were
punished if they spoke French.
</P>
<P>
   ''My grandmother spoke only French,'' Joe Hebert said. When he
left Louisiana with his new bride in 1952 to become an Air Force
weather officer, he remembers being looked down upon for being
Cajun.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara clung to her Cajun French and eventually learned
standard French so she could teach it. She taught French and German
in high schools for more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   When the Heberts retired five years ago, they decided to return
home to Louisiana. They were delighted to find Cajun culture had
become not only accepted, but trendy. Cajun music and food are now
known throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now there is a real renaissance of people wanting to learn
French,'' Mrs. Hebert said. Some school systems in the state have
French immersion programs, where students not only take French
classes but also take other subjects in French, such as math and
science.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've started speaking French in restaurants together,'' said
Russell Gaspard, 66, an organizer of the Hebert reunion in
Abbeville. Gaspard's mother was an Hebert. His wife is teaching
their grandchildren to speak French, in part to erase guilty
feelings over not teaching it to their children.
</P>
<P>
   The Abbeville reunion will be one of the larger gatherings, and
will include a dance, a French mass, the unveiling of a monument
marking the event, and genealogy seminars.
</P>
<P>
   But the highlight of the weekend will be the cooking of the
giant omelette. Normally a November event, the Giant Omelette
Celebration will take place a second time this year, on August 7,
for the reunion.
</P>
<P>
   ''We wanted to show off,'' Gaspard said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Giant'' is no exaggeration: The omelette is made with 5,000
eggs and is cooked on a 12-foot wide skillet in front of the
courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   The event, in its 14th year here, is not as silly as it sounds.
Its origins go back to 18th-century France; legend has it that
Napoleon Bonaparte once ordered the village of Bessieres in the
south of France to make his army a giant omelette.
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, Bessieres began staging an annual giant omelette
festival. Now six cities worldwide with French ties have an
omelette event; Abbeville is the only U.S. city. The omelette chefs
are called ''chevaliers'' or ''knights'' and are part of a
fraternal order that promotes cultural exchange and friendship
among French-loving people. Joe and Barbara Hebert are chevaliers
and have traveled to every omelette city.
</P>
<P>
   To give their omelette a Cajun flavor, the chevaliers of
Abbeville add Tabasco sauce and crawfish tails to the usual 5,000
eggs, 50 pounds of onions, two gallons of parsley and 52 pounds of
butter.
</P>
<P>
   Gaspard, who has been looking forward to a Louisiana reunion for
more than a decade, says he has no idea if 600 or 6,000 Heberts
will come to Abbeville, a sleepy, picturesque town famous for its
oysters. He's worried the Heberts from Canada won't like the steamy
weather August in Louisiana promises, but he sums up his
predictions of how things will go like this:
</P>
<P>
   ''If they don't have a good time, well, tsk tsk tsk.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
