<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIT-FOR-TAT CAMPAIGNING 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani provided his
fellow New Yorkers with some fetching entertainment this week. He
journeyed down to Arkansas to rub elbows with razorbacks.
</P>
<P>
   As Hillary Rodham Clinton made another ``listening tour'' across
upstate New York, the mayor decided to do some listening of his own
in the rural state where Mrs. Clinton first served as a first lady.
At the invitation of Arkansas' new Republican governor, Mike
Huckabee, Giuliani loped off to Little Rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's never been here before,'' the governor told reporters,
``he's never worked here, he's never lived here. Today he will be
announcing his candidacy for some significant major office in
Arkansas, we're told.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon Giuliani's arrival in Little Rock, his hotel promptly ran
up the New York state flag. City Hall responded by flying the
Arkansas flag over lower Manhattan. New York City Councilman Bill
Perkins, a black Democrat, was incensed. He said that he was
``outraged that the Arkansas flag that is designed to commemorate
the Confederacy, i.e., slavery, and the Old South is flying from
City Hall, our city's bastion of democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Really, this is more fun than the circus, bigger belly laughs
than Wrestlemania.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Perkins has a point. One of the blue stars in the
Arkansas flag really does represent the state's membership in the
confederacy. New York Gov. George Pataki not long ago removed the
flag of another southern state from the Albany Capitol because it
contained a confederate symbol. Minority lawmakers were bent out of
shape over its presence in the Capitol's Hall of Flags.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, though, seems to have adopted more of a
forgive-and-forget attitude than he usually demonstrates. Maybe
that's because he raised about $200,000 in Little Rock to use in
what everybody now presumes will be his battle next year against
Hillary Clinton for the U.S. Senate from New York _ assuming that
either of them ultimately runs and that Giuliani really can get the
Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, it appears that he'll have a primary fight from
Rep. Rick Lazio, a Republican from Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Against Clinton, Giuliani's big issue would be the charge that
Hillary was trying to pull a Bobby Kennedy. In 1964, Kennedy came
roaring into New York and won a Senate seat against Ken Keating, a
snowy-haired incumbent who hadn't been bothering anybody. Kennedy
was denounced, as Clinton is being denounced now, as a shameless
carpetbagger.
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody thought that was a problem back then, however. For
example, a columnist for the Manhattan College newspaper, the
Quadrangle, wrote an impassioned attack on the people criticizing
Bobby Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They maintain that Kennedy is a cynical, power-hungry
politician moving into New York and using it as a springboard to
higher office ...'' the columnist wrote. ``The `carpetbagger'
issue, which has so far been the only issue Sen. Keating has gotten
any response on, is a truly ridiculous reason for not voting for a
man in the year 1964 ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Without doubt, the Kennedy candidacy is perfectly in accord
with the Constitutional stipulation that a Senator must be a
resident of the state he represents on the day he is elected ... A
Kennedy victory will bring about the assertion of a most valuable
precedent; that a representative of a particular state must be able
to think and vote in the light of national needs and not to be tied
only to local and sectional pressures.''
</P>
<P>
   The columnist made a ferocious assault on ``sectional
divisions'' and ``outdated parochialism.'' Vote for the candidate
and not the address, a young Rudolph Giuliani urged his readers in
1964.
</P>
<P>
   I found out about this when an Albany-area Democratic Party
activist named C.B. Smith stumbled across a copy of the column on a
Web site called thesmokinggun.com. Smith thought he had died and
gone to Heaven, and he couldn't wait to let me know about it. I
called up the Web site, and there it was. And Giuliani's people say
it's legitimate. He wrote that column, all right.
</P>
<P>
   Well, that was then, and this is now. Giuliani's people say that
he has grown up considerably in 35 years. He probably didn't
mention any of this in Little Rock. The rubes might not have found
it amusing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
