A9824 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUINNESS-HNS &LR;      07-30 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUINNESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRISH BREWERY TAKES ITS BEER SERIOUSLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Alicia Shiel eyes the clear plastic tubes
running from the keg room to the polished wooden bar at Foley's
Irish House and pronounces them clean and clear of nasty
micro-organisms.
</P>
<P>
   She climbs the stairs, goes behind the bar and lifts a 20-ounce
imperial pint glass. Tilting it under the tap at a 45-degree angle,
Shiel pours night-black stout into the glass, pauses to allow the
liquid to settle, sniffs the brew for freshness, then tops it off
with a creamy head.
</P>
<P>
   Voila _ a toothsome pint, which Shiel passes to a surprised and
pleased Foley's tippler as a free sample to go with the whiskey
he's been quietly sipping at the bar.
</P>
<P>
   It's all in a day's work for Shiel, one of 43 draft specialists
employed in the United States by Guinness Bass Import Co., the
Greenwich, Conn.-based distributors of Guinness stout, Bass ale,
Harp lager and other drinks from Guinness's base in Ireland and the
United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guinness is different,'' says Shiel, an Irishwoman from Dublin
who lives in San Francisco. Impatient American bartenders have to
be persuaded to pour Guinness' signature stout just-so and wait the
one to two minutes it takes to settle. And American drinkers, who
fancy light beers and lagers, may need some time to appreciate
Guinness's robust flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Draft specialists like Shiel check refrigeration and delivery
systems in bars and restaurants to ensure quality control, and
serve as good-will ambassadors for beer companies.
</P>
<P>
   Their personal touch and attention to detail are especially
useful for marketing imports and craft beers, which are niche
players in the big U.S. beer market. Imports had 8 percent of the
market in 1998, and craft beers _ made in small batches by
traditional brewing methods _ owned 3 percent that same year,
according to the Association of Brewers, in Boulder, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   An international company like Guinness _ a brewing giant that
pours 10 million pints daily worldwide, according to communications
director Howard Pulchin, but has a relatively small market here _
must be enterprising to differentiate itself.
</P>
<P>
   Guinness' specialist program is one way to do that.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco area is the company's prime U.S. market after
New York, says Tim Kelly, Guinness Imports president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The section of the market we're in is very big here,'' Kelly
says. ``There are a lot of young people here; there is a lot of
money here; Silicon Valley is here.''
</P>
<P>
   Guinness is not the only company to go after market share by
tapping draft-beer wizards, to be sure. Draft-beer pioneer Anchor
Brewing Co., of San Francisco, and major brewer Coors Brewing Co.,
of Golden, Colo., among others, also send technicians into the
field to look after things.
</P>
<P>
   Coors, the third-largest domestic brewer, with 10.5 percent of
the U.S. market, requires independent distributors who handle Coors
beer to employ draft specialists, according to Dave Taylor, the
company's communications manager.
</P>
<P>
   These specialists ``attend a course provided by Coors on our
beer, and they are certified through our training system,'' Taylor
says.
</P>
<P>
   Given that Coors draft isn't pasteurized and doesn't include
preservatives or stabilizers, it must be served within 45 days,
kept well-refrigerated in storage and poured at a chilly 36
degrees, according to Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Anchor Brewing, which makes the highly regarded Anchor Steam
beer, plus Liberty ale, a porter and other drinks, doesn't specify
temperature, according to Anchor's Philip Rogers. ``We have the
philosophy that if the temperature is good to you, it's good
beer,'' he jokes.
</P>
<P>
   However, Anchor is quite serious about ensuring quality, working
with distributors who employ draft managers of their own to oversee
its systems.
</P>
<P>
   One such company, the independently owned Anchor Distributing
Co. of San Rafael, ensures that the lines linking kegs of Anchor
Steam to barroom taps are narrower than usual. Anchor _ brewed with
a high amount of naturally occurring carbonation and known for its
thick, creamy head _ would be all foam if too much CO2 bubbled into
the glass.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite a bit more involved in setting up Anchor,'' says
Don Saccani, president and general manager of Anchor Distributing.
``There is an applied physics that takes place.''
</P>
<P>
   While many beer companies use specialists, Guinness impresses
bar owners as exceptionally attentive to detail.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an easy product to pour, but quality is No. 1 with
Guinness. They'd rather not sell it if it's poured badly,'' says
Martin Connolly, co-owner of Foley's Irish House.
</P>
<P>
   Foley's, says Shiel, is careful to serve Guinness in the
traditional way _ poured slowly, with a head ranging from 1/2 inch
to 1 inch high, and chilled to 39-45 degrees. ``It should be served
cold,'' Shiel says _ not warm, as many Americans believe of Irish
and British beers.
</P>
<P>
   Other myths, according to Shiel:
</P>
<P>
   _ Guinness stout is exceptionally potent (it's 4.3 percent
alcohol on draft, about the same as mainstream American beers)
</P>
<P>
   _ It's heavy (``10 calories per ounce; it's a light beer despite
the color,'' she says)
</P>
<P>
   _ Guinness tastes different _ that is to say, better _ in
Ireland and the United Kingdom than it does in the United States.
``It's the exact, same beer, shipped in kegs from the brewery at
St. James's Gate in Dublin,'' she says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
