A9835 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLU     07-30 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GET IT IN WRITING OR TAKE A BRUISING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: It was with great excitement that I let the
cable modem people in. I had taken a day off work and convinced my
wife that the $100 installation fee was a bargain. Anyway, they
couldn't install it because my apartment had the wrong kind of
cable. They would need to set up an appointment with
``construction'' and then another one with themselves. Oh, yes, and
the fee would go up $75. Faced with almost double the installation
and two more days of missed work, I told them to put everything
back the way it was, and I'd just live with 56K. Was I being
scammed, or did I cut my nose off?
</P>
<P>
   _Noseless
</P>
<P>
   DEAR NOSELESS: Sorry; even though that was pretty cheesy
treatment by the cable modem guys, it doesn't exactly count as a
scam. If ever there was something to read all the fine print about,
it's these high-speed alternatives to regular modems.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the cheapest way to go is with either a digital
subscriber line (DSL) from the phone company or a special modem
that's hooked into your digital cable, in which case the Internet
is delivered on the same wire as Nick at Nite. In either case,
you'll be paying as much as 40 bucks a month for the service on top
of an installation fee, plus a couple of hundred dollars for
equipment. For all that dough, you get to surf at least 10 or 15
times _ maybe a lot more _ faster than you do now.
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't just matter that the service is offered in your
area. The wires in your house have to be capable of carrying the
signal. You'd think the cable guys would have known that when you
placed the order, but there's every chance your service rep was
flipping burgers last week and thinks ``digital service'' means you
have to change channels without a remote.
</P>
<P>
   You need to protect yourself. Have the cable or phone company
guarantee that your line is up to snuff in writing. If they won't
do that, at least tape a supervisor telling you that on the phone.
Sure, that's not exactly legal, but think how good it will sound on
``The People's Court.''
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: My otherwise sensible husband insists it is
better to leave computers running 24 hours a day. I disagree; I
think they should be shut off entirely when not in use.
</P>
<P>
   _Miffed Wife
</P>
<P>
   DEAR MIFFED: No matter what I say, one of you is going to think
I'm an idiot. How about this? Both of you just do whatever you want
to with your computers and talk about something noncontroversial
like the Mideast instead.
</P>
<P>
   It's true that every time you switch on a computer, the sudden
surge of power can degrade components slightly, but your box will
probably be obsolete and ready to be replaced by the time any real
damage becomes apparent. It's just as true that leaving the power
on all the time puts wear on moving parts like fan and disk-drive
motors, but most of those things can run for four or five years
without a problem, and they're cheap to replace when they do fail.
There's no answer, is there?
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that might tip the scale is if you care about
gobbling up the extra electricity it takes to run your PC
constantly, which isn't too much more than my Spiderman night light
uses.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what I do: I turn my computer off when I'm done with it.
If it's on, it's too easy to sit down and lose another three hours
to Half-Life or Quake, and my carpal tunnels are inflamed enough as
it is, thank you.
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay had a pretty good
worker's comp suit going until that last paragraph. Send
suggestions for a new scam to drbombay(at)star-telegram.com, via
snail-mail to Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX
76101, or fax: (817) 390-7257. In real life, Dr. Bombay is Michael
Gerst, editorial systems manager for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
