<HEADER>
A9840 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-GLASS-COLUMN0810-     07-30 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-GLASS-COLUMN0810-1st </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 LEDE &HT;    COMMENTARY: THE COOL STORY BEHIND THE HEAT WAVE
 &HT;    Editors: Updating lede reflects Atlanta murders
 &HT;    For release Sunday, August 1.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON When, save for the occasional mass murder, the top
story
</P>
<P>
   nowadays often turns out to be the mid-summer heat wave that has
scorched much
</P>
<P>
   of the nation, you know that we're also enduring a slow news
cycle. Reports of
</P>
<P>
   persistent temperature records are coupled with the opinions of
presumed experts
</P>
<P>
   on the meaning of changing weather patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Dehydration that stems from extreme heat can prove fatal. But
</P>
<P>
   doctors have long recognized that sweltering temperatures should
be
</P>
<P>
   properly seen as one of several contributing causes to death
whenever
</P>
<P>
   other serious medical problems are also present.
</P>
<P>
   The real story of the Big Boil of 1999 is not how many people
have
</P>
<P>
   been subjected to the heat but rather how many millions have all
but
</P>
<P>
   escaped its full impact in temperature-controlled houses,
offices,
</P>
<P>
   cars and malls.
</P>
<P>
   Today, three in four American homes are air conditioned.
Houston,
</P>
<P>
   the nation's fourth largest city, plans to spend over $750
million
</P>
<P>
   this year just to keep cool. It's a good investment: In 1900,
only
</P>
<P>
   some 45,000 people lived there, sweltering each summer by the
Texas
</P>
<P>
   Gulf coast.
</P>
<P>
   Like television, air conditioning has been around for much of
the
</P>
<P>
   20th century. A year after earning a master's degree in
electrical
</P>
<P>
   engineering from Cornell in 1901, Willis Carrier patented a unit
that
</P>
<P>
   soon came to comfort the very comfortable, much as private jets
do
</P>
<P>
   today.
</P>
<P>
   But the broad middle class had to wait several more decades for
its
</P>
<P>
   turn. And, by and large, poor people, among whom a good deal of
</P>
<P>
   heat-related suffering occurs, are still unable to obtain
relief.
</P>
<P>
   In 1955, Hollywood made a movie,
</P>
<P>
   `The Seven Year Itch,'' based on
</P>
<P>
   the premise of a
</P>
<P>
   `bachelor'' who sends his wife and kids to the beach
</P>
<P>
   for the entire summer to escape their sultry apartment, thereby
</P>
<P>
   setting up his sultry escapade with Marilyn Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   As a teenager living in a hot and humid New York City in the
1940s,
</P>
<P>
   I'd escort my future wife to a
</P>
<P>
   `healthfully chilled'' movie house on
</P>
<P>
   summer weekend afternoons. There we'd cool off, sitting through
two
</P>
<P>
   feature films, cartoons, newsreels and coming attractions.
</P>
<P>
   As grown-ups in 1970, we bought a house from a partner in a
</P>
<P>
   regional movie chain. When building the house in 1949, he
mounted a
</P>
<P>
   nine-ton water-circulation tower by the driveway, utilizing the
same
</P>
<P>
   crew and much the same gear that served his movie emporiums.
</P>
<P>
   At first all went well once we had found a technician who could
</P>
<P>
   decipher the various dials, valves and switches needed to run
the
</P>
<P>
   massive commercial-grade apparatus. But then came the oil shock
of the
</P>
<P>
   mid-1970s and the sticker shock of soaring electricity bills.
</P>
<P>
   The last straw came when the power company's chieftain wrote to
</P>
<P>
   inform us that we'd been chosen for a
</P>
<P>
   `special study'' by dint of
</P>
<P>
   being among the utility's top 100 residential customers.
</P>
<P>
   Our over-engineered
</P>
<P>
   `movie'' air conditioning system more
</P>
<P>
   powerful than even the pioneering one Carrier installed in 1922
at
</P>
<P>
   Graumann's Metropolitan Theater in Los Angeles had to go.
</P>
<P>
   In its place came a heat pump, a bunch of fans and utility bills
</P>
<P>
   appropriate to a journalist's salary. They aren't newsworthy,
but
</P>
<P>
   they'll help us get by until the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
