<HEADER>
A9844 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-TITLES-HNS &LR;      07-30 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TITLES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETWORKS ARE TITULARLY CHALLENGED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ It's bad enough that we're often left with
the gnawing feeling that most television shows are merely tinkered
versions of what we've seen before. With notable exceptions, we
wonder if Hollywood has run out of ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Now we have to wonder if television has even run out of titles.
</P>
<P>
   The most glaring example is two new dramas, one for CBS, the
other for ABC. Both are arguably the best new offerings for the
networks.
</P>
<P>
   For CBS, it is ``Now and Again.''
</P>
<P>
   For ABC, ``Once and Again.''
</P>
<P>
   You might as well add MSNBC, which will continue to air ``Time &AMP;
Again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We simply ran out of words,'' ABC entertainment president
Jamie Tarses joked of her industry.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is budging. Both CBS and NBC said the titles would stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obviously unfortunate the two shows have similar
titles,'' Tarses said. ``We are not changing our title. It bears no
resemblance to the other show at all.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not even that big a deal, Tarses said: ``It is shocking ...
about how little title recognition people have.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it will be difficult to have title recognition when
all the titles sound the same. Consider:
</P>
<P>
   There is ``Family Guy'' (Fox) and ``Family Law'' (CBS), not to
be confused with ``Martial Law'' (CBS), which is categorically
different from ``Law &AMP; Order'' or the new ``Law &AMP; Order: Special
Victims Unit'' (NBC).
</P>
<P>
   Moving on, Fox will have the one-hour ``Ally McBeal,'' and the
new half-hour ``Ally.'' Fox, which also airs two versions of
``Cops,'' has ``Malcolm in the Middle'' (mid-season) as opposed to
UPN's ``Malcolm &AMP; Eddie.''
</P>
<P>
   There is ``Grown Ups'' (UPN) and ``Oh, Grow Up'' (ABC), ``The
Badland'' (ABC) and ``Wasteland'' (ABC), ``Third Watch'' and
``Third Rock'' (both NBC), and ``Angel'' (WB), ``Touched by an
Angel'' (CBS) and ``City of Angels,'' (CBS, mid-season), which is
different, of course, from ``Sex and the City'' (HBO) or ``Spin
City'' (ABC).
</P>
<P>
   ``Odd Man Out'' (ABC) is about a lone guy in a house full of
women, not to be confused with ``Ladies Man'' (CBS), which is about
... a lone guy in a house full of women. ``Ladies Man'' (which is
the annual entry in the grammatically incorrect show of the year _
there should be an apostrophe at the end) is also entirely
different from ``Ladies' Man,'' the Tim Meadows feature film in
production, or ``Ladies' Man,'' a 1980 CBS sitcom about ... a lone
guy surrounded by women.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is ``The Downtowners,'' a new animated comedy from
the WB. The problem was it sounded too much like the new MTV show
``Downtown,'' so WB changed it to ``Mission Hill'' ... except now
it could get tangled with the animated ``King of the Hill'' (Fox),
but not ``Jack and Jill'' (WB).
</P>
<P>
   ``Seven Days'' (UPN), meet ``Seventh Heaven'' (WB). ``Sports
Night,'' (ABC), ``Tonight Show'' (NBC), ``Saturday Night Live,''
(NBC), ``Mad TV'' (Fox), ``Stark Raving Mad'' (NBC), four
``Datelines'' (NBC), four ``20/20s'' (ABC), a ``60 Minutes'' and
``60 Minutes II'' (CBS), ``West Wing'' (NBC), wrestling (every
other network) ... oh, God, make it stop.
</P>
<P>
   The aforementioned ``Once and Again,'' from the makers of
``thirtysomething'' and ``My So-Called Life,'' has a good shot to
succeed _ if an audience first finds it, then is patient enough to
wait around for a while.
</P>
<P>
   The ABC drama about two divorced parents will premiere on
Tuesdays at 10 p.m. If that time slot sounds familiar, it should:
That is when ``NYPD Blue'' airs.
</P>
<P>
   ``NYPD Blue'' has an October start-up, so ABC plans to put the
new drama in its slot for a month, then re-introduce it on Monday
nights after ``Monday Night Football'' concludes its season.
</P>
<P>
   So will any audience gathered in the fall be willing to wait
through up to a three-month hiatus?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have plans,'' Tarses said. ``It is our responsibility to
keep it alive through any and every means we have available to
us.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a risky proposition at best. Last season the network's
best new drama, ``Cupid,'' died because scheduling exiled it to
Saturday night. ABC would be wrong to repeat slotting infanticide
again with what could be a strong show.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
