<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COATES-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGHT END BEN COATES LETS HIS PLAY SPEAK FOR ITSELF 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- More than 30 years after wrapping up one of the NBA's
greatest careers, Bill Russell allowed fans to really see, know,
and touch him for the first time at a recent FleetCenter tribute.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Rice, one of the most dominating hitters over a 12-year span
(1975-86), didn't soften his once-intimidating demeanor until
taking over as Red Sox hitting coach a few years ago, long after
his playing days were over.
</P>
<P>
   And now another great Boston athlete may be known _ or, more
correctly, not known _ for his reluctance in letting people into
his world. Patriots tight end Ben Coates, probably the NFL's best
of his era at his position, may never see his career fully
acknowledged because he has never been there to speak about it.
</P>
<P>
   But his words probably couldn't add much more to the
6-foot-5-inch, 245-pounder's resume of five Pro Bowl selections,
five straight years of catching 60 or more passes, and the power to
fight off what is usually double coverage to haul in Drew Bledsoe's
passes.
</P>
<P>
   His entire life has been quiet, even after Bobby Grier found
Coates at tiny Livingstone College in Salisbury, N.C., and watched
him turn into one of the NFL's best ``finds'' of this era. But few
athletes would have survived his 1998 season.
</P>
<P>
   On the field, it was typical: 67 catches, once again Bledsoe's
go-to guy every time the quarterback couldn't find a receiver open.
</P>
<P>
   Off the field, his life unraveled: forced to cope with the
deaths of his mother, aunt, and sister all within a five-month
span, while also standing up to a public trial over the alleged
assault of the mother of his child. Coates was eventually
acquitted, but in the meantime was a moral punching bag when it was
revealed how many children he was supporting out of wedlock.
</P>
<P>
   But Coates, as usual, was left standing.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family gave me a lot of support and we were all there for
each other,'' said Coates this week in a telephone interview from
his home in North Carolina. ``I wasn't the only one who went
through it. My whole family had to go through it. My wife and my
kids were there for me, and now we've moved on.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not take part in the team's offseason conditioning
program, even though team officials asked him to be there.
Certainly, in the end, they understood that Coates needed time away
from everything.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When he returns to Smithfield, R.I., this weekend for the start
of training camp, none of what happened a year ago will be in his
mind-set.
</P>
<P>
   He will never speak or think of it again, except for warm
memories of his mother, who died at age 56, his sister, Ann, who
was only 38, and an aunt whom he loved like a mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got away from it all and stayed home and hung around with
the wife and kids,'' said Coates. ``I tried to block everything out
and looked on this as a new year. I can't do anything to change
what happened. All I can do is look ahead to '99 and go on the
field and be the best player I can and improve on the things I've
done in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   How does a potential Hall of Famer improve? How could Ben Coates
possibly be tougher, smarter, better?
</P>
<P>
   ``My yards per catch was down (9.9 from 11.2 the previous
season). Maybe it didn't look like it,'' said Coates, ``but there
were times I didn't have 100 percent concentration because my mind
would start thinking about things that were going on. When I come
back, none of that will be there.''
</P>
<P>
   No, you would not have noticed any difference in Coates's play,
except for the game in St. Louis he missed to attend his mother's
funeral.
</P>
<P>
   He was still Bledsoe's savior when Terry Glenn, Vincent Brisby,
and Troy Brown were all out with injuries.
</P>
<P>
   While Coates took no bows in the media, he took them in the
locker room from an admiring group of teammates who appreciate
everything he does.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been around a man who is as classy as Ben Coates,''
said Shawn Jefferson. ``For what he does on the field and for how
he conducted himself when everything was falling apart in his
personal life, it was amazing to see the inner strength he has as a
person. If that didn't rub off on some people on this team, nothing
will.''
</P>
<P>
   Silent in good times and in bad, Coates said he has made a
conscious choice to keep to himself. This is the way he was raised
by his late mother _ never to boast about his accolades, to always
be humble, and to be strong in crisis.
</P>
<P>
   And, to be consistent.
</P>
<P>
   That's what his public image is. He is not surly or
disrespectful to anyone. Quite the contrary, when he sees a
familiar face he's always polite and says hello. But, usually, the
conversation ends quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I choose to be to myself,'' he said. ``When I'm playing, I'm
performing. And during the season I like to keep to myself because
I have my own way of preparing for the game. I have in mind a
routine that I follow and I have a way to prepare for the game. I
replay the game over and over in my mind. I think about different
situations and what I might do if something like that were to come
up. I build up to that. And when the game comes along I try and
execute what I've been thinking about all week.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If Bledsoe, Ty Law, Glenn, and others get the attention while
he's just being Ben Coates, that is not a problem with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't think about it,'' said Coates. ``This is the
player I am. If the accolades come, they come. Some athletes in my
position can get real selfish and say, `Oh well, I played great,'
and they get a little too cocky about themselves and never perform
at that level again.''
</P>
<P>
   But that will not happen to Coates. He plays hurt. He plays in
pain. And while he admits he's taken punishment over the years
because of all the double-teaming and dirty tactics used to defend
him, Coates says he doesn't feel old yet.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
