<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990730.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9850 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COATES-2     07-30 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COATES-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... old yet.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I admit I've taken a lot of punishment over the years. That's
why I wanted to come into camp lighter than usual. I think I was
about 245 or 250 last year, and I'd like to be around 240. I've
gotten into good shape for that reason,'' Coates said. ``The older
you get, the better-conditioned you have to be. If we can keep our
receivers healthy, it would help me out tremendously.''
</P>
<P>
   Some may think Coates is on the downside of his career, but he
doesn't agree, though acknowledging he needs more help from backup
tight end Rod Rutledge, with whom he's worked closely.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's better than in his rookie year,'' acknowledged Coates.
``Now he's going to have to come in and show that he can catch and
block. He can block, but his catching is suspect. He didn't catch
any balls last year and now that they've gotten rid of Lovett
Purnell, he's got to come in and be the second tight end. If I'm
double-teamed and he's open, he's got to show the ability to catch
the ball. But I really need the guys on the outside to be healthy.
That's what would help me a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   And toward that end, Coates doesn't miss many opportunities to
bend Glenn's ear. They are locker neighbors, and Coates has been
urging Glenn to take care of his body so he can play a full season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talk to him,'' said Coates. ``Terry could go out and put it
all together this year. He's shown what he can do. If he can do
what he did as a rookie, that would make all of us have a better
year.''
</P>
<P>
   He appreciates the chance he's had to play with Bledsoe, whose
rifle arm enables Coates to see a lot more balls despite often
being caught in a sea of enemy shirts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It works hand in hand,'' said Coates. ``Drew has helped my
career and I think I helped his career the first three or four
years. He's a little too overprotective sometimes. I tell him all
the time, `If you get into situations where you need to get me the
ball, I'll always be there for you.' Sometimes he looks for the
other receivers, but I'm always there. I think we know that we have
each other. He's there for me, and I'm there for him. What we'd
like is to get somebody else in there that Drew can rely on so it's
not always 87 and 11.''
</P>
<P>
   Coates thinks the Patriots can still get back to the level of
their Super Bowl team. He hasn't cringed as much as other veterans
at the loss of so many players from that team, feeling the younger
players the Patriots have gone with could do the job.
</P>
<P>
   But, he warns, ``We have to have a lot of the guys we drafted
two years ago step up and perform at a high level. I think the big
thing for them is that they can't be content to be backups anymore.
They have to start looking at the guys in front of them and start
taking their jobs. But I think we're definitely the caliber of team
that can get to the Super Bowl. I think these guys have had the
luxury of being able to sit, watch, and develop, but now it's time
for them to step out of that into starting roles.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What's left for Coates to accomplish? In order: a Super Bowl
triumph, breaking Stanley Morgan's all-time Patriots' reception
record, and the Hall of Fame. To reach those goals, he will have to
play a few more years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to play three or four more years after this year,''
said Coates, who turns 30 Aug. 16. ``I feel I'd still be a top
player and that I could take the punishment of the position for
that long.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he spoke to Morgan last year about his receiving record
of 534 catches (Coates enters the season with 458).
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I could do it. It'll be tough, but if I have good
years I can make it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And to do that, he would have to remain a Patriot for the
forseeable future. He's currently in the second year of a
three-year deal that will pay him $2.1 million and $2.6 million the
next two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the type of person where I'm going to let the contract run
out, said Coates. If they decide they want to re-sign me before
that, then they do. If not, the contract is not an issue. After
next year, who knows what the option might be?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to stay here the rest of my career. The quarterback
is there and there are a handful of guys I hang around with. I've
been through a lot with them and we like being together. But two
years from now? A lot can happen in two years.''
</P>
<P>
   The only place Coates might like to go other than Foxborough is
Canton, Ohio. That would finish off the story of the kid who came
out of a small, little-known school in the South to become one of
the best at his position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to get (to the Hall of Fame) because that's one place
that if I do get there, there won't be many others there,'' said
Coates. ``I think there are two others guys in the '90s _ Shannon
(Sharpe) and Keith Jackson _ who will be there. But who knows how
the voting will go?''
</P>
<P>
   He remains close to Sharpe, with whom he has had a running
competition to see who catches the most balls each year. Sharpe,
though, is not as pure a tight end as Coates, who is a better
blocker and better at catching the ball in crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I taunted him before he left for training camp,'' Coates said
with a laugh. ``I talk to him a lot in the offseason. It's fun.
We're friends off the field and we've always pushed each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody, though, has pushed Coates more than himself. He hasn't
cared who the coach was, or what was going on around him, only that
he had to be the best. That part has remained as consistent as his
resolve to keep himself out of the spotlight and out of the media.
He wants none of that, until the day he gives his acceptance speech
in Canton.
</P>
</TEXT>
