<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSTANT-MESSAGING FLAP HURTS NET USERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When America Online used to charge by the hour, chat was the
online service's big moneymaker. For all of its then-glitzy
graphics and specialty content, it was something very simple that
kept subscribers paying AOL's hourly rates.
</P>
<P>
   People like to talk to each other.
</P>
<P>
   The power of online chat _ in which people type text messages to
each other via computers _ is now at the center of a fascinating
game of cat and rat between AOL and Microsoft. It's a wonderful
battle of wills, a situation in which roles are reversed, and a
classic example of how the Internet really does change everything.
</P>
<P>
   First, some history is in order.
</P>
<P>
   For years, America Online has offered its users the ability to
send instant messages to one another. This is a simple, one-on-one
chat with another person, and it became one of AOL's most popular
features. You know a technological achievement is a hit when its
acronym becomes a verb, and AOL users began to urge their friends,
``Why don't you IM me?''
</P>
<P>
   The feature got a boost when AOL created Buddy Lists, which let
you see when your friends sign onto the service, and allowed users
to invite people on their lists into group chat rooms.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
AN AOL DEAL FOR NON-CLIENTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This turned AOL into the virtual version of a town square _ or
maybe the correct analogy in the 1990s is the shopping mall. It was
like waving and saying, ``Hi, how are you?'' when you saw someone
you knew.
</P>
<P>
   The kicker came when AOL began offering a free version of its
instant-message feature to Internet users who didn't subscribe to
the online service. AOL Instant Messenger, which combined messaging
and the Buddy List feature into one simple application, was an
instant hit.
</P>
<P>
   Now, people who are not on AOL can communicate with their
friends who are, as well as anyone else on the Net who uses the
Instant Messenger software. Although it's free, there is an
advertising banner that appears atop the Buddy List, so AOL makes
money by selling that space.
</P>
<P>
   The company also builds what's known as mindshare _ it puts its
brand front-and-center on the desktop of people who don't normally
use AOL. They have a good feeling about the brand, because it gives
them something of value for free. It also gives AOL a certain
cachet _ after all, it's doing something cool for the online
community.
</P>
<P>
   AOL believes instant messaging is the next ``killer app''
online, according to Marc Andreessen, the co-founder of Netscape
Communications, which AOL bought this year. Andreessen recently
called it a ``tornado app'' at the PC Expo trade show, because the
more people use it, the more valuable it becomes, and the more
valuable it becomes, the more people use it. AOL recently put its
money where its vision is and bought Mirabilis, an Israeli company
that developed the popular, if overly complex, ICQ instant message
program.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MICROSOFT FIGHTS SHUTOUT &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Enter Microsoft, the 900-pound gorilla of personal computing.
When a market develops to the point that Microsoft thinks it can
make money there, it moves in with a vengeance. And that's what it
did last week with its own instant messaging program.
</P>
<P>
   Tied to both its Microsoft Network and Hotmail Web e-mail
services, MSN Messenger could also talk to AOL's users. Both Yahoo
and Prodigy also recently released their own instant-message
clients, and they, too, could talk to AOL's users.
</P>
<P>
   This is not something AOL officials wanted. They tweaked the AOL
system so the newcomers couldn't get in. Both Prodigy and Yahoo
said fine, be that way. Not Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Saying it was acting on behalf of Internet users who want to see
open standards applied to instant messaging, Microsoft issued a new
version of its software that got around AOL's block. Then, AOL shut
out the new version. Then, Microsoft's programmers hammered out a
fix. Then, AOL closed the door again. And so on.
</P>
<P>
   In public statements, both companies are trying to appear as the
good guy. Microsoft says it's fighting for an open Internet, where
everyone can chat with everyone else. America Online says Microsoft
is violating its users' privacy by enticing them to enter AOL
passwords into the MSN Messenger software.
</P>
<P>
   Both statements, of course, are full of beans.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft doesn't want an open Internet; it wants to seduce
market share from AOL's Instant Messenger. Although MSN Messenger
doesn't have advertising on it, it would be easy to add. And MSN
Messenger is closely tied to Hotmail _ it will alert you when
there's something new in your Hotmail inbox _ which does have
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   AOL, of course, wants to keep its users all to itself. If its
users switch to MSN Messenger, then they won't view AOL's
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The argument that AOL users are giving up privacy by using MSN
Messenger is nonsense. Microsoft says the passwords are only used
to connect to AOL's own servers, and Microsoft does not retain
them.
</P>
<P>
   AOL would have some merit in its argument that Microsoft's
actions amount to hacking into its server, except for the fact that
AOL at one point published on the Web the information necessary to
build an AOL Instant Messenger client. Several pieces of software,
mostly for Unix and Linux systems, were developed from this effort.
Doesn't this amount to an invitation to join the party?
</P>
<P>
   Looking in on Usenet discussion groups and various Web message
boards, it appears the Net is cheering on Microsoft in this case.
What an irony. Everyone's favorite bully is suddenly everyone's
favorite victim!
</P>
<P>
   So far, there's no end to the dispute in sight, though AOL has
sent Microsoft a letter asking for some kind of resolution. Here's
hoping AOL opens up its servers and lets Microsoft _ and everyone
else _ in to play. Instant messaging currently is balkanized, and
not until there's a single standard that lets everyone talk to each
other will its full capabilities be realized.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Columnist Dwight Silverman can receive mail on the Internet at
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
