<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO DIFFERENT METHODS LET USER COPY OUTLOOK'S PERSONAL INFORMATION
FILES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Many folks, including myself, lose a hard drive from time to
time. We usually have backed all program data files onto a floppy
disk. There is one file that is not and that is the Microsoft
Outlook 98 ``Address/contact'' book. It is heck to rebuild. I am
using Windows 98. Any suggestions?
</P>
<P>
   A: Outlook 98 and Outlook 2000 _ Microsoft's personal
information management programs _ store their info in folders with
a .PST extension. In theory, you could search your drive for these
files and make copies of them onto a floppy disk.
</P>
<P>
   But some of them may be way too big for a floppy, or may contain
information you don't want. It's actually better to use one of two
other methods for backing up your e-mail, contacts, to-do lists and
other items.
</P>
<P>
   If you have Outlook installed, there should be a Mail or Mail
and Fax icon in the Windows Control Panel. Launch it, and you'll
see a list of items that can be copied, including e-mail boxes and
personal folders (the latter likely will contain your contact
information).
</P>
<P>
   Click on the one you want to copy, and click the Properties
button. In the window that appears, you'll see the name of a folder
where that file is stored. Make a note of this folder. Click
Cancel, go back to the list of items, and click Copy to duplicate
the one you want.
</P>
<P>
   Use Explorer to get to the folder where it's stored and move the
copy to a floppy drive.
</P>
<P>
   If it's too big for a floppy, go back to the Control Panel
module for Mail and open it. Click on the copy, choose Properties
again and choose Compact Now.
</P>
<P>
   This will compress the folder dramatically _ you should be able
to put it on a floppy.
</P>
<P>
   The other way is actually simpler, though you don't get the
option to compress.
</P>
<P>
   From within Outlook, go to the area you want to back up. Choose
File, then Import and Export. From here you have several choices,
including Export to a File. Choose that, and then you can decide
how you want to save the data.
</P>
<P>
   For example, you can export to other Office products, such as
Access or Excel, or to any spreadsheet that can read
comma-delineated text (where each field is separated by a comma).
In this case, choose to export to a Personal File Folder.
</P>
<P>
   You'll be asked which Outlook component to export. Choose the
one you want (click the Filter button to only export certain
fields), and click Next. You can then tell Outlook where to put the
PST file, such as on a floppy disk, if it will fit.
</P>
<P>
   More details can be found at this Microsoft Knowledge Base
article on the Web:
support.microsoft.com/support/kb/articles/Q181/0/14.ASP
</P>
<P>
   Q: I want to be able to take my old vinyl LPs and convert them
to compact discs using a writeable CD-ROM drive I am about to buy.
But I have a question. How do I connect the turntable to my
computer?
</P>
<P>
   A: The best way to do this is to buy a device called a
preamplifier. You can get these at any electronics parts store.
Connect the turntable to the preamp, then the preamp to the line-in
jack on your computer's sound card.
</P>
<P>
   You may need to buy an adapter cable for the connection between
the preamp and the sound card.
</P>
<P>
   You will also need software that can handle the conversion.
Check out Easy CD Creator Deluxe 3.5 from Adaptec, which comes with
a component called SpinDoctor. It's specifically designed for
converting LPs to CDs. It also has some tips on how to handle the
hardware.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You once printed the address of a Web site that offers free
e-mail technical support. I've lost that article. Can you reprint
the address, please?
</P>
<P>
   A: Sure. It's NoWonder at www.nowonder.com. Ask a question about
your PC, and you're likely to get an answer back in hours.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question? Maybe Computing columnist Dwight Silverman can
help. Send e-mail to dwight.silverman(at)chron.com &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
