u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV01     07-30 1184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV01-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS ARE ON THE WAY TO AN $8.8 MILLION RETIREMENT NESTEGG 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August 1, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My husband and I are 34 and 32 years old respectively. Ever
since I quit my job to stay home with our two newborns, we have
been trying to determine if we are on our way to a comfortable
retirement. Currently my husband's new job gives us $78,000
annually. Before I quit my job, we made an average of $120,000 a
year. We have accumulated $186,000 in stocks, $21,000 in Janus
fund, $2,000 in Janus Olympus fund, and $4,500 in Vanguard Index
500. We have no credit card debt, owe $20,000 on a home equity line
(used to buy a car) and owe $170,000 on our home, which is
appraised at $250,000. Each year we are adding $2,000 to each of
our Roth IRAs (Vanguard and Janus Olympus) and my husband has just
started his 401(k), where we plan to invest the $10,000 maximum. On
average, we plan to save $25,000 a year through the Roth IRAs, the
401(k) and other savings. Will this be enough to retire
comfortably, and if not, how far off the mark are we?
</P>
<P>
   T.A., Yorba Linda, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. C'mon. You must know you will be in very good shape given
your aggressive savings habits. With a savings rate of $25,000 a
year, you would build your portfolio to a whopping $8,854,068 over
the course of 31 years, presuming 10 percent average annual
portfolio growth. That's more than double what you would need to
match your current life style, even after calculating in the
awesome effects of inflation. The math works this way: If inflation
averages 3.5 percent over the course of 31 years, you would require
$226,592 a year to buy the same goods and services that $78,000
buys today. But if you established a fixed-income portfolio that
brought you an average yield of 6.5 percent, you would need less
than half of your total portfolio to do the trick, leaving the
remainder in growth-oriented holdings to offset the effects of
later inflation on your retirement income stream.
</P>
<P>
   That is what I call sitting pretty.
</P>
<P>
   It seems to me that the major thing for you to be thinking about
is taxes. Of your current savings, nearly 97 percent is in taxable
accounts. If you continue the savings program you outline, with
$14,000 a year going into tax-deferred or tax-free accounts (the
401(k) and the Roth IRAs) and with $11,000 going into taxable
savings, you would end up with $6,065,890 in the taxable accounts.
I know this probably doesn't seem to make sense at first blush, but
you should remember that it's the considerable nestegg you have
already accumulated that is the big factor in the projection. If
you simple stopped saving entirely, the projection would carry that
$213,500 to $4,097,991 over 31 years.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, I suggest that you look for tax-deferred instruments
for a good deal of that $11,000 annual savings that goes beyond the
401(k) and Roth IRA investments. You might also look to some
changes in your current holdings. For example, the people at Janus
tell me that the Janus Aspen Series Growth Portfolio variable
annuity substantially duplicates the portfolio of Janus fund. So
you might want to transfer some or all of your Janus fund holdings
to that instrument -- remembering, of course, that there will be
current-year tax implications of selling the Janus fund position to
buy the annuity.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps you could work out a schedule of transfers over several
years which would minimize the current tax load.
</P>
<P>
   These are all fairly minor wrinkles -- you should be in great
shape, and the substantial amount of money you have already saved
at a relatively young age makes me feel it's likely you'll stick to
the program. (Sometimes, I confess, I am a little bit cynical about
the prospects of people in their mid-forties who propose to begin a
grand retirement savings program and ask for a projected
accumulation amount; if they've saved little or nothing by then,
the chances that they'll stay on track sometimes seem mighty
sketchy to me.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 40 years old and I received a $26,500 accident
settlement last year. I paid off my credit cards ands invested
$20,000 with Vanguard, putting $5,000 each in The Total Stock
Market Index, Extended Market Index, Index Value, and Index 500. I
add a further $100 each month through Vanguard's automatic
investment plan, with the money evenly divided among the four
funds. I am single and make $24,000 a year. I am a first-time
investor and have twenty years plus to go until retirement, so I
can be aggressive. What do you think of my portfolio?
</P>
<P>
   R.R., Encinitas, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. While these four funds seem like a fairly broad
diversification, when you look at their portfolios carefully,
you'll find a good deal of duplication of holdings and market
concentrations. Both Index 500 and Index Value focus on the
Standard and Poor's 500 Index of the nation's dominant companies,
with Index 500 tracking the entire 500 index and Index Value
focusing on a subset of the index, containing the stocks of the
companies with the lowest price to book value ratios.
</P>
<P>
   The Total Stock Market Index sounds as if it would be a
meaningful diversification, but while it tracks the nation's 5,000
leading public companies, it does with a market-cap weighting. For
example, the market value of all the shares of Microsoft Corp.
represents 3.39 percent of the market value of all of the 5,000
companies in the Wilshire 5000 index, and accordingly the Microsoft
position represents 3.39 percent of the portfolio of the fund. When
you combine this with the positions in the 300 or 400 other
companies that dominate the Standard and Poor's 500, there is very
little weight given to the small- and mid-cap stocks. The upshot of
all this is that this fund ends up in exactly the same category as
Vanguard Index 500 -- a large-cap blend of growth and value
oriented stocks.
</P>
<P>
   It's only with the Vanguard Extended Market fund, which tracks
the Wilshire 4500 Index, that you get a direct participation in the
small- and medium-cap markets, with the same kind of market-cap
weighting giving the fund an overall rating as a mid-cap blend
fund.
</P>
<P>
   If I were making such a portfolio, I'd be a little more direct,
perhaps putting $10,000 in the either Index 500 or Index Value (or
divided between the two as you have done), and then putting $5,000
each into Vanguard's Mid-Cap Index and its Small-Cap Index.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, you don't mention the purpose for which you are saving,
but if it is retirement, I suggest you stash up $1,000 of those
ongoing contributions in a bank account -- enough for the minimum
initial investment in an IRA account -- and then open an IRA
account in Vanguard International Value fund. It's not an index
fund, but my suspicion is that in the volatile international stock
arena, a managed portfolio should have an advantage over an index
fund.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
