<HEADER>
A9856 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-RUNAWAY-BOS &LR;      07-30 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-RUNAWAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERTS MAKES A WINNING `RUNAWAY BRIDE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
RUNAWAY BRIDE 
Directed by: Garry Marshall 
Screenplay by: Josann McGibbon, Sara Parriott 
Starring: Julia Roberts, Richard Gere, Joan Cusack, Hector
Elizondo, Rita Wilson, Paul Dooley, Christopher Meloni, Donal
Logue, Reg Rogers, Yul Vasquez 
Running time: 116 minutes 
Rated: PG (language and some suggestive dialogue) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The big difference between ``Pretty Woman'' and ``Runaway
Bride'' is that this time Julia Roberts is a lot more confident and
Richard Gere is a lot more laid back. This alone makes ``Runaway
Bride'' far more likable than ``Pretty Woman,'' their huge 1990
hit, which only I seem to have regarded as sexist drivel dedicated
to what it would have us believe is the sunny side of prostitution.
``Runaway Bride'' is an altogether more entertaining factory
product, which is to say it's synthetic from the word go, but charm
and stardust carry it past its blatantly manufactured quality. If
not as witty as ``Notting Hill,'' teaming Roberts and Hugh Grant,
it nevertheless puts inventive spin on its formulas. Inventive
enough, at any rate, to turn them into a successful part two of
what may have begun as the Summer of Sam, but indisputably has
become the Summer of Julia.
</P>
<P>
   In a slightly different and more contrived way than ``Notting
Hill,'' ``Runaway Bride'' plays off Roberts's much-documented
skittishness, tailoring for her the role of a small-town Maryland
woman who keeps getting cold feet at the altar and bolting, a
process aided by her habit of wearing running shoes under her
wedding gown. Gere plays a throwback to the crumpled wiseguy
protagonists of the golden age of newspaper movies like ``Libeled
Lady.'' He begins as a USA Today columnist who loses his job when
he gets the facts wrong in writing about Roberts's marriage-shy
Maggie Carpenter after being spoon-fed the story in a bar. To get
his job back, he goes as a freelancer to her Eastern Shore town to
get the facts right via a self-vindicating feature story.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the film's allure emanates from the actual Maryland
Eastern Shore town of Berlin, where some of the scenes were shot.
It pleasantly reinforces the period flavor of the screwball comedy.
Maggie, who not only runs her family's hardware store but can fix
most of what's brought into it, isn't pleased to see him,
especially when he starts moving in on her relatives, her
neighbors, her friends, and even the high school football coach (a
very funny Christopher Meloni) who's about to give Maggie her
fourth shot at marriage. Roberts and Gere can only play the comedy
of antagonism for so long before the film is forced to bring them
together on the flimsy grounds that she can use the $1,000 he's
offering to pay her for an interview so she can buy her latest
wedding dress.
</P>
<P>
   One needn't be an oracle to predict what will happen once they
get together, although writers Josann McGibbon and Sara Parriott
deserve credit for resourcefully avoiding what could have been
obnoxious levels of obviousness. At one point, when he takes her
for a drive and the car stalls, she knows exactly what's wrong with
it. And we always believe that the strength of her impulse to flee
is stronger than the attraction the story demands she feel toward
Gere's character. He's named Ike, by the way, a possible subliminal
trigger to the ``I like Ike'' Eisenhower generation. But it's not
really his film, it's hers. The smartest move this romantic comedy
makes is to downplay the romance, with its built-in credibility
problems, and emphasize the comedy.
</P>
<P>
   It works because Roberts's outsize features and outsize gestures
make her a natural comedian, a pretty obvious fact of which too few
of her films have taken advantage. She whoops and carries on here
with sunny exuberance, yet remains believably nervous about things,
big brown eyes darting to the edges of the frame as if looking for
an exit. In ``Pretty Woman'' she played a personality so squashed
that she needed Gere's preening high roller to tell her what
clothes to wear. Here, although she plays a stronger woman, she's
still tagged as neurotic, in need yet again of Gere's guru figure
leading her to wholeness. I'd have liked it more if the film had
held open the possibility that running from the men was a valid
choice, which it certainly seems to be, given their oafishness.
</P>
<P>
   The film also takes longer than necessary to get where we know
it's going. But it gives Roberts the launching pad she needs to
rocket into lovable goofiness and high-powered shyness. On the
agreeably relaxed Gere, a little humility looks good. There are
times when he looks relieved to have her carrying the film, as well
he might. Spencer Tracy and Katharine Hepburn they're not, but they
deliver a smooth pas de deux here. Garry Marshall, who led them
through ``Pretty Woman,'' obviously established a positive work
vibe on the set. The film's big, open, simpatico energies are upped
by Joan Cusack's perfect sidekick to Maggie; Rita Wilson's tough
but humane editor who fires, then rehires Ike; and Hector Elizondo,
whose role as Wilson's husband and Ike's favorite photographer may
have been a reward for his performance in ``Pretty Woman.'' Roberts
has really hit her stride this summer, segueing from ``Notting
Hill'' to ``Runaway Bride'' without missing a step.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
