<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SLIM-PICKENS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLIM PICKIN'S: IF YOU TRY, YOU CAN DINE OUT AND EAT HEALTHY, TOO 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Also see:  
 
By DAI HUYNH  
 c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Dining out and scaling down are like caviar and hot
dogs _ they really don't mix.
</P>
<P>
   But gone are the days when moms can spend hours in the kitchen.
They're more likely to pick up a bucket of fried chicken at the
drive-through window.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, restaurant foods are often packed with more fat
than those prepared in homes, the U.S. Department of Agriculture
says.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Americans are eating out twice as often as they did
three decades ago, according to a new U.S.D.A. survey. The study
also found that restaurant food accounted for 39 percent of U.S.
meals bought in 1996 _ up from 26 percent in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Pity the dieters.
</P>
<P>
   Climbing out of the fat trap isn't easy when eating at
restaurants is a habit. But don't throw up your hands yet, the
experts say. You can still frequent the little diner down the
street without acquiring an extra chinny-chin-chin. When eating in
restaurants is a way of life, you simply need a strategy to choose
what's healthy on the menu. No, this doesn't mean ordering a salad
and no dressing.
</P>
<P>
   Depriving yourself of the foods you like is never a good idea in
the long run, Houston nutritionist Linda McDonald says. Instead,
she recommends paying more attention to what you're ordering.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you can still have a good meal and a good time,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, once people walk into a restaurant, they think it's time
to indulge, the experts say. Who can blame them? They've had a long
day at work. And instead of eating a salad and entree, they go for
the works _ shrimp tart in a phyllo crust, artichoke heart salad,
Peking duck with spiced plum compote, licorice parfait with
espresso, and a glass of wine or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``They lose control,'' McDonald says.
</P>
<P>
   Once in a while, this is OK, but make it a habit and plan to add
a notch or two to your belt.
</P>
<P>
   To get control _ and to prevent the menu or chef from
controlling you _ here are some suggestions from diet and fitness
experts and individuals trying to stay in shape.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants have gotten into the mentality that bigger is
better. That may be all right for your wallet, but not your
waistline, McDonald says.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where people get into trouble. They lick their plates
clean.''
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants often give double the portions. McDonald suggests
counteracting this by sharing an entree or taking half home.
</P>
<P>
   There isn't anything dancer Sally Rojas of the Houston Ballet
says she won't eat. The Venezuelan wife of restaurateur Chuck
Russell of Solero in downtown Houston has sampled culinary delights
ranging from fried beef tongue to boiled pig tripe.
</P>
<P>
   ``You name it, I've eaten it,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   In her line of business, maintaining a lithe figure is a must.
But that doesn't stop Rojas from indulging in her favorite dishes.
She simply cuts back on the portion size when she's eating
something high in fat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very much about portion,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Actress and diet guru Suzanne Somers takes another approach.
</P>
<P>
   Somers dines until she feels comfortably full, refusing to eat
past the point where some people keep stuffing themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no counting fat grams, there's no counting calories,''
Somers, the author of ``Eat Great, Lose Weight'' (Crown Publishing,
$23) and ``Get Skinny On Fabulous Food'' (Crown Publishing, $24),
says.
</P>
<P>
   Choosing wisely is often half the battle. Stay away from
anything fried, advises Frank Messina, owner of the Ragin' Cajun
restaurant in southwest Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Messina has lost 60 pounds in the last six months, weight that
he had gained after frequenting too many restaurants, he says. The
restaurateur still eats out, but instead of ordering onion rings
and fried shrimp, he prefers nibbling on boiled shrimp, raw
oysters, green salads and chicken gumbo.
</P>
<P>
   When ordering, choose dishes that are steamed, poached, broiled,
roasted, grilled, baked or cooked in their own juices, says Patti
Ramsey, owner of Living Lean, a Houston company that offers
healthy, low-fat food.
</P>
<P>
   Eating on the run is Carol Isaak Barden's motto. The
contributing editor of Travel and Leisure magazine travels
frequently from one continent to the next. This means spending most
of her time in hotels and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, I'm very good, and others, I slide,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping her weight down hasn't been easy, but Barden has managed
through sheer determination.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest thing is the bread basket. I love it, but it goes
right to my rear,'' she says. ``I really would love to eat the
whole thing, but I kind of have to sit on myself and tell myself
that I'll pay for it later on the treadmill.''
</P>
<P>
   She also makes special requests, like asking for her fish to be
grilled without oil or the salad dressing on the side.
</P>
<P>
   ``All those little things help,'' Barden says.
</P>
<P>
   Some people starve themselves before they eat out. Not a good
idea, McDonald says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes you hungrier, and you'll end up eating more.''
</P>
<P>
   McDonald recommends eating a light breakfast and lunch, instead.
She also suggests having a light snack an hour or two before going
to a restaurant, such as a glass of milk, cheese, crackers or
fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in the battle of the bulges, personal trainer Jason
Washington offers this simple advice: exercise.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
