<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SLIM-TIPS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF YOU SNOOZE, YOU WON'T LOSE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAI HUYNH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Controlling what you eat when you cook is one thing _ dining out
is another. Here are strategies and tips for nearly every
restaurant situation.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mexican fare: Pass up the cheese enchiladas, chimichangas,
tacos and flautas, and opt, instead, for the fajitas and tacos al
carbon or soft burritos in nonfried flour tortillas.
</P>
<P>
   Think willpower when it comes to those nacho chips. Either ask
the server to take them away, or grab a handful and send the rest
away.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chinese food: Always ask the server that the food be prepared
with very little oil.
</P>
<P>
   Stay away from fried dishes, like sweet and sour pork or General
Tso's chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Request steamed rice instead of fried rice.
</P>
<P>
   Skip the egg rolls; go for the spring rolls.
</P>
<P>
   _ Italian delight: Pasta is good for you, but not when it's
loaded with Alfredo sauce. Go for tomato-based sauces, instead,
such as marinara.
</P>
<P>
   Ask for plain bread instead of garlic bread.
</P>
<P>
   _ Steakhouse know-hows: Pick leaner cuts, like sirloin, filet
mignon or tenderloin. Avoid prime cuts of beef, which taste yummy
but have the most fat.
</P>
<P>
   Request any visible fat to be removed before grilling the steak.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be tempted by the 22-ounce steak; all you need is a
3-ounce serving, about the size of the palm of your hand.
</P>
<P>
   If it comes with fries or onion rings, substitute a salad or
baked potato.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fast-food strategies: Order the grilled chicken instead of
hamburger or chicken nuggets. If you're craving the Cheddar
cheeseburger, have it _ but skip the fries.
</P>
<P>
   It may be a great deal, but resist the temptation to supersize.
No one needs the extra serving of fatty fries or high-sugar soft
drinks.
</P>
<P>
   _ A few more tidbits: Split dessert with a friend, or order a
sorbet, which is mostly ice and fruit flavors.
</P>
<P>
   Avoid rich sauces, such as hollandaise, bearnaise and beurre
blanc.
</P>
<P>
   Ask if the restaurant offers half-portions.
</P>
<P>
   Just because it's soup doesn't mean it's low-fat. Fish chowders
and bisques are often made with whipping cream. Ask the server when
in doubt. In fact, make it a habit to ask the server how a dish is
prepared. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-99 1335EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
