<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULT REGROUPS, RETURNS TO BASICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The Cult was last heard from in 1995 in Rio de Janeiro, where
singer Ian Astbury walked off the job from ``exhaustion.'' After 12
years of sometimes inspired music, sometimes hollow
experimentation, and a habit of making tabloid headlines, the Cult
appeared dead.
</P>
<P>
   The burial was premature, however.
</P>
<P>
   The Cult, which first rose from the tough streets of Brixton,
England, has risen again after regrouping at the Viper Room in Los
Angeles a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Minus a new album, the Cult is playing such favorites as the
incendiary ``She Sells Sanctuary,'' ``Revolution,'' and ``Sweet
Soul Sister.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy campers. We're really glad to be back,'' says
guitarist/attitude-setter Billy Duffy, whose stinging,
psychedelic-sonic-boom guitar sound has been cited as a bridge
between the Jimmy Pages and Mike McCreadys of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about rock 'n' roll now,'' says Duffy. ``It's lean,
and it's for real, and we mean it.
</P>
<P>
   He admits the Cult had veered from course before breaking up.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of good-spirited musical invention, but we
were missing what we were about, which is rock 'n' roll in the
classic mold,'' says Duffy, speaking on a cell phone from the road.
``We were described as post-punk or early alternative or whatever,
but we were just following the people we loved _ Jimi Hendrix, Led
Zeppelin, Bad Company, Iggy Pop, the New York Dolls, and the
Stooges. That's the essence of the Cult.''
</P>
<P>
   That essence was rediscovered at the Viper Room. Duffy was on
stage with the Neurotic Outsiders _ an all-star band with a
revolving lineup that includes Billy Idol, John Taylor of Duran
Duran, and Duff McKagan and Matt Sorum of Guns N' Roses. Astbury
showed up and was invited on stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the catalyst. It felt great right away,'' says Duffy.
``There was a lot of love in the room.''
</P>
<P>
   The new tour is an intimate, get-reacquainted session with
``hardcore Cult'' fans, says Duffy. And the group drummer Sorum
(who had been in the Cult in the late '80s and early '90s, before
joining Guns N' Roses) and Martyn LeNoble, who has played with
Porno for Pyros.
</P>
<P>
   While on hiatus, Duffy made an album with the band Colorsound
(also featuring Mike Peters of the Alarm) that is expected to come
out this fall, while Astbury traveled on a spiritual search to
Tibet and Nepal. But with the return of the Cult, look for a new
album next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be very visible next summer,'' says Duffy. ``Look for us
at rock barbecues and festivals near you.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More Woodstock: More horror stories are emerging about the mobs
of disgruntled youths that rioted as Woodstock '99 ended last
Sunday night at the former Griffiss Air Force base in Rome, N.Y.
The youths set fire to 12 tractor trailers (destroying all of
them), overturned a sound tower, burned a telephone truck in the
campground, and looted vendor tents and ATM machines. And if it
wasn't for the work of two bikers, Peter Wagner (a Vietnam War
veteran from Virginia) and Walter Jolley, a $250,000 Budweiser beer
truck also would have been looted. The bikers, who were friends of
the truck's owner, said they drove off the rampaging youths by
swinging 2-by-4s at them.
</P>
<P>
   Other eyewitness accounts:
</P>
<P>
   --From Erika Scott, 21, of Allston, Mass., who spent a harrowing
last night in the campground as the fires raged: ``My friend and I
were afraid we would be burned alive in our tent by half-naked men
who had gone insane, so we ran to the road and sat sleepless and
scared on the asphalt until the morning came . . . The hooting and
hollering of men, moved by anger, raging with testosterone. Men,
from ages 13 to 30 howling under the not-quite-full moon, tossed
trash and anything else into the flames. . . . (The fire was) maybe
20 feet in diameter and twice as high, I had never been that close
to a fire so large. . . . Vending carts had been tossed into the
flame, as were tables, chairs, and trash cans. As we stood there,
three men pushed down a toilet, crouched behind it and ran it
straight into the fire. It had a tribal feeling to it _ very
reminiscent of `Lord of the Flies.' ''
</P>
<P>
   --From Haddim Scott Kime, 27, a Berklee College of Music
student: ``I was back near the sound tower that got tipped over.
The kids tore off the walls around it and made a bonfire of that. .
. . In the campground, you'd see people burning tents. There was a
spirit of anarchy and one guy ran through the crowd saying,
`Anarchy reigns tonight!' It was younger kids doing it _ and all
males. I didn't see any women doing it. It was males screaming to
be heard. . . . It looked like drunken college kids in shorts and
ball caps. I didn't see any of the stoners or hippies doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spinning the '90s: Nirvana's ``Nevermind'' is Spin's No. 1 album
of the '90s, anticipating what is sure to be many similar lists in
these millennially obsessed times. Spin editors voted the ``90
greatest albums'' of the '90s for the September issue. It makes for
great reading, even if you don't always concur with the choices
(what, did you expect Bruce Springsteen or the Stones to be on an
alt-rock-tilted Spin list?). Rounding out Spin's top 10: Public
Enemy, ``Fear of a Black Planet''; PJ Harvey, ``To Bring You My
Love''; Beck, ``Odelay''; Pavement, ``Slanted and Enchanted'';
Hole, ``Live Through This''; Bjork, ``Post''; Dr. Dre, ``The
Chronic''; Radiohead, ``OK Computer''; and Chemical Brothers, ``Dig
Your Own Hole.'' The two most questionable calls were dropping U2's
``Achtung Baby'' to No. 19 and Pearl Jam's ``Ten'' to No. 35. That
Pearl Jam disc should be in the Top 3. A personal opinion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
