<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-SADLER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR NOW, SADLER'S SAFE AT SECOND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- There is no guarantee Donnie Sadler will be the second
baseman when the Red Sox meet the Yankees Friday night in the
opener of a six-game homestand that features three games against
the iron of the American League East and three more against the
Cleveland Indians, the iron of the American League Central.
</P>
<P>
   Even after benching his All-Star second baseman, Jose Offerman,
for the last three games and summoning him into his office to tell
him his defense wasn't cutting it, manager Jimy Williams reserved
the right to change his mind at a moment's notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a player has to sit a day or two, whatever, that's what I'm
going to do,'' Williams said after meeting with Offerman. ``One
thing I've said, I can't please players all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things don't always go (straight). Sometimes there's a detour,
a bump on the highway, and then you hope you go forward.''
</P>
<P>
   But given that Offerman is hitting .219 in his last 55 games and
his defense didn't suddenly take a dramatic upturn just from taking
some extra ground balls from coach Wendell Kim, chances are that
the rookie, Sadler, will be logging the majority of playing time on
the homestand, and perhaps much longer.
</P>
<P>
   This, after spending the entire season playing shortstop for
Triple A Pawtucket. ``I can't even remember the last time I played
second base,'' Sadler said.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, this wasn't the plan back in March, when the Sox hoped
Jeff Frye was fully recovered from knee surgery and general manager
Dan Duquette, who signed Offerman to a four-year, $26 million deal
last December, thought that Offerman's potent bat would more than
compensate for any deficiencies he had with the glove.
</P>
<P>
   But Frye lost his job three weeks into the season, then hurt his
knee again, and Offerman not only stopped hitting, but wore down
Williams's patience with his ineffectiveness in turning a double
play and reaching balls hit to his left.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Sadler, who probably would have arrived here sooner if he
hadn't developed tendinitis in his throwing shoulder. Lou Merloni,
who now looks as if he's living on borrowed time, was given the
summons instead, but after spending some time on rehab assignment
in Fort Myers, Fla., Sadler says he is fully recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``For awhile, I couldn't get anything on the ball,'' he said,
``so I shut it down for three weeks. I went down to Florida and it
started to feel good. I had a lot of treatment _ ultrasound,
massage, stretching _ and it helped me get back pretty quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadler, who hit .291 in 43 games for the PawSox, said he hoped
he'd get some playing time when he was summoned by the Red Sox to
Toronto Tuesday, but acknowledged he was caught by surprise by
Williams upon his arrival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimy asked me if I was ready,'' Sadler said. ``I said yes, and
he said I was in there that night. I said, `Let's go.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It really helped my confidence out, that he had that kind of
faith in me, especially with things this tight in the wild- card
race, that he told me to get out there and play.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadler was charged with two errors in his first game back, but
the first may have been the result of overeagerness, and the second
probably shouldn't have been ruled an error at all. Sadler ranged
far to his left to glove a ground ball to the right side, but when
he spun and threw to second base for an attempted force, the ball
bounced past shortstop Nomar Garciaparra. The second came when
Willie Greene hit a one-hop rocket that hit off Sadler's glove.
</P>
<P>
   ``It broke my glove,'' Sadler said. ``Snapped a string in two in
the webbing.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sadler also doubled and scored on his first at-bat, beat out
an infield hit on his last, and also began two key double plays.
``He made the plays at the right time,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Then Wednesday night, Sadler made a terrific belly-flopping,
rug-hugging catch of Carlos Delgado's line drive, then flashed his
speed, the best in the organization, scoring from first on Trot
Nixon's double to the left-field wall.
</P>
<P>
   It's why Williams refers to him as a ``scatback.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadler, who started 38 games at second base last year when
Williams had to mix and match second basemen because of injuries to
Frye and Mark Lemke, is making no predictions about how long he'll
stick this time. But at 24, it is becoming increasingly clear that
his time has come, even if a $26 million player like Offerman
doesn't figure to remain on the bench for long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping I can stay with the team,'' Sadler said, ``but
right now I'm taking it one day at a time. I'm just coming in
prepared to play every day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
