<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEPLETED REVOLUTION COULD USE A SPARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was never a grand plan with a professional soccer career
as the goal. If anything, Chaka Daley presumed the current A-League
season would be a farewell tour. The 25-year-old defender had
prepared for early retirement from competitive soccer and hoped to
make a graceful transition to college coach and businessman.
</P>
<P>
   But two exhibition games with the New England Revolution led to
a mid-June free agent signing. Daley's skills and 6-foot-2-inch,
185-pound frame caught the attention of goalkeeper/coach Walter
Zenga. And it appears the former Providence College star may be in
the right place at the right time. As Zenga struggles to find the
right combination on defense with central back Dan Calichman
injured, Daley has the opportunity to see more playing time
Saturday against Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't really played much yet, but I'm just being patient
and waiting for my time. If I'm called on, I'm going to make sure
I'm ready,'' said Daley. ``I think he liked my height and my being
athletic at my height. I think I have pretty good feet and that
helps me out a little bit. I'm competitive. I try to be aggressive
and compete all over the field. As a defender, all you have to do
is defend and give it to the good guys _ the Joe-Max (Moores) and
John Harkeses _ and let them sort it out.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Revolution take on the Mutiny, New England will be
without forward Moore and midfielder Harkes, who are with the US
national team for the Confederations Cup. Despite just one
appearance for New England, as a substitute in a 3-2 win over the
New York/New Jersey MetroStars July 4, Daley knows he must be
prepared to raise the level of his game if called upon by the
depleted squad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the guys that come off the bench like Chaka or anyone
else need to step up,'' said Ted Chronopoulos. ``If they step up
into their roles, then they prove to the coach that they can play
on this team.''
</P>
<P>
   The transition from the Boston Bulldogs to the Revolution has
forced Daley to be faster and sharper on the field. He is also
adjusting to the more technical play of Major League Soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely know I can stay up here and play,'' said Daley.
``I just have to be patient and pay my dues and see what happens
after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Daley is close to earning a master's degree in business, but
will wait before he enters the boardroom. For now, the original
plans have been scrapped in favor of a soccer career.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Suffering from a strained right hip flexor, Dan Calichman has
shown improvement over the past few days. He practiced Thursday for
a half-hour and did short sprints along the sideline at Babson
College. Then he left for a pool workout. The Revolution's other
key injured player, Giovanni Savarese, has also shown improvement.
He tested the Grade 1 sprain of his right medial collateral
ligament with running and stretching. Both players will travel to
Tampa and take a fitness test prior to the game to determine if
they are ready . . . Forward Ariel Graziani spent the day in Mexico
finalizing paperwork for his visa. He was scheduled to meet the
team Friday in Tampa . . . Salvadoran national player Elias Montes
trained with the Revolution Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-99 1341EDT &QL; 
