<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990730.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9875 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-MCLACHLAN-BOS &LR;      07-30 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MCLACHLAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SARAH MCLACHLAN'S NEXT MOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The official subtitle is ``A Celebration of Women in Music.''
But Lilith Fair, now in its third and final lap around the country,
has been called a few other things, among them a patchouli-scented
clubhouse for girls, a pseudo-feminist blight on the women's
movement, and a narrow, unadventurous slice of musical pie.
Lilith's founder, singer-songwriter Sarah McLachlan, cheerfully
defuses all critical bombs tossed her way with the same sort of
gently articulate turns of phrase that characterize her songs. ``It
was a simple, selfish one,'' McLachlan says, when asked about her
original agenda for Lilith Fair, which rolls into the Tweeter
Center Tuesday. ``I wanted to meet all the women I like to listen
to and hear them play live.''
</P>
<P>
   A Lilith-style sentiment, indeed. But McLachlan was also mad as
hell (a not-so-Lilith-style sentiment; more on that later), and she
wasn't going to take it anymore. Speaking on a cell phone from the
Austin, Texas, concert site, McLachlan is drying off after a sudden
downpour and reflecting on the music festival that _ whatever else
you want to say about it _ has rewritten the rules of the road for
women. One of the top-grossing tours of the decade, Lilith Fair has
shattered the myth that female artists aren't moneymakers when it
comes to live concerts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lilith has effected change,'' McLachlan says with pride. ``I
think its helped to change the attitude of the industry. Its almost
gone the other direction. There's such an incredible amount of
female musicians out there. Guess who's having a really hard time?
Guess who's really ghettoized right now? The pendulum swings.''
McLachlan's pointed remarks aren't directed at male artists, but
rather the male-controlled music industry, which has historically
marginalized women for their ostensible lack of drawing power.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, as McLachlan was preparing to tour behind her
double-platinum album ``Fumbling Toward Ecstasy,'' she encountered
strong resistance from concert promoters to her request that Paula
Cole sign on as opening act. A female double bill, McLachlan was
told, was bad business. ``Yes, there was this big reactionary
element,'' McLachlan recalls. ``Being told I can't do something
makes me want to do it. For years the industry has underestimated
fans, and the music they want to listen to.'' Outraged, McLachlan
dreamed up Lilith Fair, an all-women lineup that shocked the
industry by pulling in more than $16 million its first year,
outselling testosterone-fueled goliaths like H.O.R.D.E. and
Lollapalooza.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all the positive changes she and Lilith have wrought,
McLachlan has come under fire. By organizing a festival that clumps
women together, some have wondered, doesn't that furthur ghettoize
them? McLachlan, no stranger to this hypothesis, treads cautiously.
``It depends on where it's coming from. I've spoken so openly and
honestly about my idea of celebrating the diversity of women. I
think it really depends on the ideals behind it. If I was a man
doing it, it would be something that could be a topic of
discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   Early on McLachlan considered opening the Lilith Fair to men,
but she was talked out of it by one of her musical idols. ``There
was this continual onslaught from the media,'' McLachlan says. ``
`Why do you hate men?' I got beaten down. I thought maybe I should
make it egalitarian. But Emmylou Harris took me aside and said,
`You've started a beautiful thing. Let it grow.' I was so thankful
to her. From that point on I said `no. No men.' ''
</P>
<P>
   This summer, a rotating lineup of 150 women grace the Lilith
stages. Boston's Main Stage performers are McLachlan, Sheryl Crow,
the Pretenders, Mya, and Me'Shell Ndegeocello. The B Stage features
Aimee Mann, Kendall Payne, and Lamb; local talent search winner
Lori McKenna, along with Bertine and Nina Gordon play the Village
Stage. Although the stylistic cross section has grown broader each
year, the emphasis continues to be on comfortable, mainstream pop
and rock. Where's the fire, and the edge? Where's the urban
element? Where is the healthy share of diversity that McLachlan
says she set out to celebrate? ``All I can say is we asked
everybody, from lots of different kinds of music, and the people
who said yes are on the tour,'' says McLachlan, clearly weary of
defending herself. ``I ask Courtney Love and Garbage every year.
Hole finally said yes, then they said no a week later. Something
about a scheduling conflict,'' she says, sounding doubtful. ``I
think they would have known about that earlier. It would have been
good for her and good for us.''
</P>
<P>
   She goes on to point out that people don't seem to register what
they're hearing on the smaller stages, where she says ``there's
some really hard stuff.'' You wouldn't know it from the Boston
lineup, though, which prompts McLachlan to note that each city gets
a different (and not necessarily representative) lineup _ based on
individual artists' availability. ``Ohio might not get the urban
artists,'' she notes.
</P>
<P>
   If there's one thing everyone seems to agree on, it's that
McLachlan has thrown her heart and soul into Lilith Fair. She
oversees every aspect of the project, and works tirelessly to
ensure that everything _ from the music to the on-site village to
the crew to the involvement of many charitable organizations Lilith
supports _ runs smoothly. It's been hard labor, she says _ trying
to make the festival bigger and better every year _ but one of
love, and McLachlan has mixed feelings about saying farewell to
Lilith Fair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure I'm ambivalent,'' she says, ``especially when I'm out
here having a fantastic day. But there are moments when (things go
wrong) and I'm like, `thank God.' But we had always had a
three-year plan, from the beginning. Of course no one else ever
talked about it or listened to me,'' she says laughing. ``In
January, we reassessed, and at that point we felt it was right. We
want to end on a high note. And a lot of us are kind of at a
crossroads. For me, it's Lilith or children. I can't do both.''
</P>
<P>
   After this summer's tour, McLachlan plans to take at least a
year off to travel for leisure, she says, and start a family.
She'll keep writing, and if an offer to do a song for film comes
along, she'll consider it. What will she least miss about Lilith
Fair? ``The press conferences!'' she practically shouts. ``That's
the worst part. It just (angers) me when you have the creme de la
creme of women in music and the media gawk like a bevy of monkeys.
`Come on,' I want to say, `ask us a question. We're so nice!' ''
</P>
<P>
   But McLachlan walks away with more than a mixed bag of memories.
She gushes about a musical education that, she says, she couldn't
have gotten anywhere but the Lilith Fair. ``Getting to sing with
Emmylou, Bonnie Raitt, the Indigo Girls, Sheryl Crow, Chrissie
Hynde, Sinead O'Connor, Queen Latifah,'' McLachlan says, ``that's
the best. And to get to hear the Village Stage artists, who are so
fresh and excited . . . it's a constant affirmation. That's the
essence of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
