<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE REGULATORS ACCUSED ALL-TECH OF WRONGDOING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- All-Tech Investment Group Inc., based in the northern
New Jersey town of Montvale, has clashed with Massachusetts
securities regulators, who shut down the company's Watertown office
this year, charging abuses including forgery and deceptive
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   In an administrative complaint filed in December, the state
securities division accused All-Tech, whose Atlanta branch was a
site of shootings that eventually are believed to have killed nine
people, of conveying ``the impression that investors are likely to
achieve profits,'' while minimizing the risks of day trading.
</P>
<P>
   All-Tech officials also allegedly forged clients' signatures and
co-mingled client funds, according to the complaint. Some clients
allegedly lost tens of thousands of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Lashing out at the regulators at the time, All-Tech's chairman
and chief executive, Harvey Houtkin, who has called himself the
``father of electronic day trading,'' said the charges were
politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are looking to put themselves on the map, and they are
doing it with day trading,'' he said in an interview. ``What they
have charged is nothing short of lunacy.''
</P>
<P>
   But in May the firm settled with the state, agreeing to close
the Watertown office for two years and pay $278,000 in fines.
</P>
<P>
   ``With one possible exception, that was our biggest day- trading
case,'' said Matthew Nestor, the state's director of securities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deceptive marketing is the lynchpin of all this stuff. We
won't tolerate false claims about income. Day trading is a very
risky business, and any claim to the contrary is simply wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Day trading, which gets its name from the practice of holding
stocks for less than a day, has become big business across the
country. About a half-dozen firms like All-Tech have sprung up to
cater to a growing number of amateur investors who trade huge
blocks of stock, in transactions that often last only seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Dedicated traders work in boutiques such as All-Tech eight hours
a day, five days a week, often performing hundreds of trades a day
in pursuit of profits on minuscule movements in stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   Many are young men who have little investment experience,
regulators and industry insiders have said. Rather, they rely on
quick reaction times to dart in and out of the market. Some traders
say they get into a ``zone,'' in which information about stock
movements flashing on their computer screens is almost
instantaneously translated to keystrokes, ordering up blocks of
shares.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators, particularly in Massachusetts, have taken a dim view
of the practice, saying it is little better than gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Many inexperienced traders hoping to tap a vein of stock market
riches have instead found themselves buried in debt after months of
nonstop trading, regulators say.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, day trading firms collect large commissions on stock
transactions whether traders make money or lose it, regulators say.
According to estimates by a consortium of state agencies, only two
in 10 professional day traders make money, and only a small number
of those make large returns.
</P>
<P>
   Spurred in part by Massachusetts regulators, the federal
Securities and Exchange Commission, the National Association of
Securities Dealers, and key members of Congress have sounded
warnings about the risks of day trading.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the NASD approved a rule requiring firms that promote
day-trading strategies to disclose to customers _ before they open
accounts _ the risks associated with that type of trading. The
risks include the loss of their entire investment. Those using
borrowed money to trade could lose that as well, the ruling said.
</P>
<P>
   With 22 offices in 15 states and about 1,500 active trading
accounts, All-Tech is among the largest US day-trading chains. In
addition to the Massachusetts action, Oregon regulators conducted
an investigation of the company's practices in that state but never
brought charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
