<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANDATORY-OVERTIME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVERTIME MEANS EXTRA PROBLEMS FOR HARRIED WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; After a day care center slapped her with a $50 late fee for
not picking up her child on time, telephone service representative
Cheryl Charette sought a transfer to another office, an hour
farther from home, to escape the mandatory overtime that made her
late.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to work where there is less stress, and I won't be
treated differently if . . . I have to leave work early to pick up
a sick child,'' said the 38-year-old mother of twins.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to hire enough employees in a tight New England labor
market, service centers operated by Bell Atlantic Corp. in Andover,
Mass. and by AT&AMP;T Corp. in Fairhaven, Mass. are invoking clauses in
their collective bargaining agreements that require overtime from
their employees.
</P>
<P>
   And the employees _ mostly women who, according to labor
statistics, are already working longer hours in general _ are at
wit's end as they try to balance their work and home lives with no
safety valve in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Given a choice, they say, they value time over the money that
overtime offers them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure what I'm going to do,'' said Monique Samagaio,
34, who fears she will have to quit her job taking customer orders
at the AT&AMP;T call center in Fairhaven if she can't find someone to
stay with her children until she gets home at 6:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Samagaio, who has been working part time since spring, wants to
go full time but can't because she cannot find a baby sitter who
can both take care of a toddler, 2 1/2, and an 11-month-old baby
and assist her elderly parents, whose health is failing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come the end of August, if I cannot get an extension (of her
part-time status), I am going to have to quit,'' she said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Both AT&AMP;T and Bell Atlantic say they appreciate the plight of
their employees and want to hire more people to reduce overtime
hours.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T spokeswoman Terri Cohen said the firm's current need for
overtime hours was triggered last spring by an increased volume of
calls. She said the measure is temporary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is not to have people work overtime all the time,''
said Cohen. ``Our goal is to hire enough workers so that we can
handle the high volume of calls we are receiving. In the meantime,
we need (employees to work overtime) so that we can maintain a high
quality of service.''
</P>
<P>
   State and federal laws allow companies to require employees to
put in overtime as long as they are paid 1 1/2 times their regular
rate of pay after 40 hours of work. Unions, however, can negotiate
a limit to the number of overtime hours.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic's contract with Communications Workers of America
Local 1400 specified employees at the Andover site be limited to a
maximum of 12 hours overtime per week five months of the year, and
10 hours a week for another six months. Local vice president Debbie
McCarthy said workers must be notified by 1 p.m. the previous day
if they are to work extended hours.
</P>
<P>
   But, she said, many workers believe a day's notice offers too
little time to find day care substitutes or make other personal
arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   At AT&AMP;T's Fairhaven facility, the company said the number of
required overtime hours has dropped to 7 per week from 10 hours in
recent weeks, and the number of employees affected has decreased to
700 from 800. Another 200 employees are exempt from working
overtime for medical reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic acknowledged its mostly female service staff in
Andover is required to work extra hours, but spokesman Jack Hoey
maintained that the company's workers logged, on average, 3 1/2
hours of overtime per week in July.
</P>
<P>
   Both AT&AMP;T and Bell Atlantic, like other companies around the
country with similar policies, cite historically low unemployment,
increased demand for products and services, and an ongoing shortage
of skilled employees.
</P>
<P>
   Hoey said Bell Atlantic has hired 400 new employees, but half
are still in a 15-week training program. ``There is no question
that this is a tight labor market,'' Hoey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, we have customers who are installing second
and third lines and there is greater demand across the board, which
is all linked to the economy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For both women and men in all lines of work, the average work
week has been getting longer in recent years. A report this year by
the Center for Labor Market Studies at Northeastern University
found that working mothers' hours in New England rose 15 percent
between 1983 and 1997, from 1,397 per year to 1,608.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a pretty big increase, and it means that for many
working women the pressure is on,'' Paul Harrington, associate
director of the center, said. For married mothers, the jump was
bigger, to 1,590 hours from 1,336. Their husbands worked long hours
too, as much as 2,333 hours per year, an increase of 162 hours
annually, Harrington said.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Morin, president of CWA Local 1400, said overtime
demands at Bell Atlantic shot up shortly after the company mailed
140,000 pieces of mail to the wrong customers, prompting an
onslaught of calls.
</P>
<P>
   At AT&AMP;T in Fairhaven, the union contends, the company failed to
hire enough people to deal with a surge in business.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic spokesman Hoey said guidelines developed by the
company and the union ``have provisions for managers to excuse
employees under certain circumstances. On a daily basis, management
has excused numerous employees from overtime requirements. We are
cognizant our employees have families.''
</P>
<P>
   Charette, the mother of 6-year-old twins who will transfer next
week from Andover to a Bell Atlantic site in Boston, says that even
a normal work day can be stressful, and a request to work an extra
half-hour upsets her entire family's life.
</P>
<P>
   Her new hours in Boston will be 8 a.m. to 4 p.m. and the work
rarely involves overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Gaudreau, 39, of Fairhaven, who works at the AT&AMP;T call
center there, wishes she could choose her own hours, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like being told on Wednesday what my hours will be the
next day, next week. You do overtime when the company needs you.
It's hard to run a family life or any kind of life. . . . I'm
always missing opportunities to take my kids to sports activities
or summer activities. They take care of themselves when I'm not
around. Do I worry? Of course I do. What mother wouldn't?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
