<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW PERSPECTIVE ON SOX-YANKEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Weisman is considered one of the best television
producers of baseball games in the business.
</P>
<P>
   He proved it during the recent All-Star Game at Fenway Park,
when he blended a little Hollywood, a little technological
wizardry, and a lot of emotion, generated mainly by Ted Williams,
to produce one of the finest telecasts in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   Weisman is back in Boston this weekend to work the Yankees-Red
Sox series. With all of the history between the teams _ the 1976
brawl and Bucky Dent's homer to name just two famous episodes _
Weisman plans to recap the memorable moments and the Curse of the
Bambino as a buildup to, drumroll please, five-time Cy Young Award
winner Roger Clemens pitching against the Red Sox in pinstripes.
</P>
<P>
   It was one thing for Clemens to play for the Blue Jays, but the
Yankees? At Fenway?
</P>
<P>
   Now another producer might jam all sorts of graphics and video
clips to milk Clemens's return to Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   Not Weisman.
</P>
<P>
   He said he probably will turn up the microphones in the stands
to let the Fenway faithful do all the talking. Weisman also said he
might split the screen to show viewers the reaction from the crowd
and the reaction on Clemens's face.
</P>
<P>
   Deserved or not, boos are expected and will be on Channel 25
starting at 1:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Celtics close to rights deal
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics are about three weeks away from signing a television
deal with Fox Sports New England and Channel 38.
</P>
<P>
   The parties are in the final stages of negotiations to give the
team an over-the-air partner after the departure of Channel 68,
which Pax recently bought from Boston University.
</P>
<P>
   Pax, a family-oriented station, had no interest in keeping the
Celtics' road games, which Channel 68 carried last season in an
unusual arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics and Channel 68 agreed to split advertising revenue,
share production costs, and deal with the rights fee over time. The
station would make money after a certain point.
</P>
<P>
   Channel 38 carried the games before the Celtics accepted the
three-year deal with Channel 68. Two years ago, Channel 38 paid an
estimated $100,000 for every road game covered (about $4 million
per year). The station also carries Bruins games and didn't press
hard to keep the Celtics package. Unconvinced that sports teams
would generate profits, station officials opted to pick up
syndicated shows.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Fox Sports New England offered the Celtics a
lucrative 10-year deal, but the team balked at having the majority
of their games on cable.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A first for Mortensen
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ESPN's Chris Mortensen gets the scoop award for breaking the
story on Barry Sanders's retirement. ESPN interrupted its
``Baseball Tonight'' program at 10:06 Tuesday night to inform
viewers that Sanders was leaving the Detroit Lions . . . ESPN's
``Monday Night Countdown'' expands to a two-hour format and debuts
Sept. 13 at 7. Mike Tirico is host with Tom Jackson, Ron Jaworski,
Sterling Sharpe, Mortensen, and Lesley Visser. On Aug. 2, a
30-minute version of the show kicks off the preseason. On Aug. 9,
``Monday Night Countdown'' airs from Canton, Ohio, preceeding the
Hall of Fame Game between the Browns and Cowboys on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Levy in the morning
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Former Buffalo Bills coach Marv Levy joins Fox Sports Net as an
analyst on its new ``NFL This Morning.'' The hourlong show debuts
Sept. 12 at 11. Jim McKay recently re-signed with ABC for a
multiyear deal. Under the agreement, McKay will continue to cover
horse racing and the British Open . . . ESPN Classic airs a new
30-minute program Wednesday featuring classic moments in horse
racing. McKay and Jack Whitaker host ``Thoroughbred Classics
Presented by the National Thoroughbred Racing Association'' . . .
Reggie Miller and Mary Murphy offer their WNBA playoff predictions
during tonight's 9 o'olock game between the Utah Starzz and Los
Angeles Sparks on Lifetime . . . The Revolution-Kansas City Wizards
game will be on ESPN2 Sept. 7 at 8 p.m. The Sept. 24 game between
New England and the Dallas Burn will be carried by Fox Sports New
England at 7:30 p.m. Fox signed a five-year, $650 million deal to
broadcast Dominican Republic pro baseball, starting Oct. 22.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
