<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9883 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-NASHVILLE-BOS &LR;      07-30 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-NASHVILLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASHVILLE BREAKS OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``We are,'' says guitarist Ruyter Suys (pronounced ``Rider
Sighs''), of the band Nashville Pussy, ``aiming for the more basic
enthusiasms of life, just having a good time. I mean, the message
is: Forget everything. Drink if you have to. What we do is
low-attention-span music, but there is more behind it, also,
something that will immediately grab you. We started the band out
of boredom, and we wanted to start a band that we wanted to go and
see. I have always wanted to see a chick go nuts on stage. I'm
really apalled that it's me doing it. I thought for sure somebody
else would be doing it by now.''
</P>
<P>
   And, these Nashville cats offer not one chick going nuts, but
two, the other being Amazon-like fire-breathing bassist Corey
Parks, sister of Minnesota Timberwolves center Cherokee Parks.
Also, front and center is Suys's husband, singer-guitarist Blaine
Cartwright. At one or more points during an NP show you can bet all
three will be involved in some serious lip-locking. (``We have our
little moment,'' says Suys.) And they will indulge in lots of
sleazy, speedy rocking.
</P>
<P>
   Put it this way: If Beavis and Butt-head were still with us,
this band would be their very favorite. The group plays heavy, fast
rock 'n' roll, a steamrolling sound that might best be referenced
as Motorhead meets Lynyrd Skynyrd, with bits of AC/DC and Ted
Nugent tossed in. Suys and Parks are not ones to wear much clothing
so, as with the Cramps, sexuality is never far from the center of
the show.
</P>
<P>
   Got a problem with that? Suys purrs a curse and says, ``Some
people can't take a joke. This is (expletive) fun. It is the
greatest job in the world. . . . Why are guys the only ones allowed
to be sexy on stage? I have been turned on by every rock musician
from Angus Young to Jimmy Page. I was getting turned on before I
knew what turned on was. . . . There is no reason for anybody to
get offended about what we do. We are trying to have a simple, good
old-fashioned rock 'n' roll show and there is nothing heavy,
mind-altering, or mind-boggling about what we are doing.''
</P>
<P>
   You might consider the group a rougher and more ribald version
of Southern Culture on the Skids. They drape the Confederate flag
behind them on stage; they pose for photos with guns. They write
songs like ``Snake Eyes,'' ``Kicked in the Teeth,'' ``Eat My
Dust,'' and ``Somebody Shoot Me.'' (There are a few unprintable
titles, as well.) Their fans and friends include actor Stephen
Baldwin, KISS bassist Gene Simmons, singer/ex-porn star Traci
Lords, actress Alicia Silverstone, and rockers Rob Zombie and
Juliana Hatfield.
</P>
<P>
   The band, which also includes drummer Jeremy Thompson, is a
perfect example of the old punk-rock DIY (do-it-yourself) ethic.
Based in Atlanta, the band was formed in 1996; the name was taken
from a comment Nugent made on stage recorded on a live album. Suys,
a Vancouver native, says she and Cartwright became a romantic
couple before they became a rock 'n' roll couple _ five days of
loving until they picked up guitars. Cartwright hails from
Kentucky, Parks from California, Thompson from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   They started at point zero. They recorded an independent album
for the Minneapolis-based Amphetamine Reptile label, toured
relentlessly, built up a rabid following by word-of-mouth, signed
to a major label (which rereleased the album) and, of all things,
got nominated for a Grammy in the heavy metal category. This was
clearly the weirdest Grammy nomination since GWAR received one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a message on our answering machine from a reporter in
Nashville,'' says Suys, ``and he said he was calling to get our
reaction to the Grammy nomination. We played the message nine times
before we called back. We were like `What?! This is insane.' Sure
enough, it was real.''
</P>
<P>
   Affiliation with Mercury hasn't really changed their approach.
The four tour constantly, without record company tour support, and
don't expect the company's full attention at all times. They know
it's their lives, their career, and they want to steer. They just
recorded a new album, with plans for a Christmas release. ``The
record is longer, more varied, a few more mid-tempo songs,'' says
Suys. ``We have learned how to groove. When we did that first
album, we thought we were Aerosmith and we are so totally not
Aerosmith. Now, we think we're a boogie band.''
</P>
<P>
   For Suys, who jerks about on stage like her idol Angus Young of
AC/DC, playing raw, sweaty rock 'n' roll serves a dual purpose.
One, she gets to kick out the jams. Two, she gets to be a role
model for girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going through a guitar magazine the other day,'' she
says, ``and there were two women in the entire magazine and both of
them were being used to sell merchandise. Not a single one of them
was presented as a musician _ they were just chicks hanging on a
guitar. I am, like, `This is terrible.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Suys's own role models _ and this may be the first time these
two ladies were ever linked _ were the late Plasmatics singer Wendy
O. Williams and Heart guitarist Nancy Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the two women who have done something for me,'' Suys
says. ``Everybody else is, like, `Joni Mitchell,' and I grew up on
that for a while and it was good, but that's not where I want to
go.'' Wilson gave Suys the confidence to play lead; Williams gave
her the confidence to embrace a take-no-prisoners philosophy and to
use her sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Is there an element of shtick involved? Sure. A member of the
band Gaunt, which toured with NP last year, said the band was like
KISS, its apparently spontaneous moves well choreographed. So be
it. ``You get your moves down and it turns the whole show into one
big unit rather than a bunch of little pieces put together,'' says
Suys. ``We always try to make it a roller coaster, rather than
going on a bunch of different rides. . . . I am more me when I am
on stage than anywhere else. At the same time, I am like a monkey,
a goofy kind of monkey girl, running around causing trouble. That's
basically what I am, a little kid. When I am off stage I somehow
become really responsible, which makes being on stage so much
fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-99 1348EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
