u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV0     07-30 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV01-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY NOT NEW CELLAR WINDOWS? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August 1, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I need old windows for my cellar to replace some rotted ones.
Where can I find old ones?
</P>
<P>
   TONY RICCI, Dedham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Try a salvage yard, but you might not find the right sizes,
and who knows that windows as old as yours might not be decaying,
too. So why replace the old windows with old windows? I think you
are better off with new ones; you can get the right size, the wood
is treated (not pressure-treated) to resist decay, and it is an
easy matter to slip them in the rough opening in the concrete
foundation. You may have to glue them in with construction
adhesive.
</P>
<P>
   You can order wood cellar windows from Brockway-Smith at a local
lumber store, not a chain, although a chain might have some in
stock. Styles are limited, but not sizes; besides, who needs style
in cellar windows?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My old steel cellar windows are rusting badly and I'd like to
replace them with wood. How can I remove them? They must have been
installed when the foundation was poured.
</P>
<P>
   ANXIOUS IN DORCHESTER
</P>
<P>
   A. You got that right; those frames were, indeed, in place when
the concrete was poured around them. First, remove the sash (the
frame holding the glass); the hinges are riveted, so you may have
to pry them off. Trying to hammer the frame out is likely to break
a lot of concrete, so you will have to cut the frame out with a
power hacksaw; a sword saw with heavy hacksaw blade would do it.
Actually, you may have to cut only three sides; then you can wiggle
or worry out the fourth frame, working it back and forth. Be
careful that you don't wiggle too far; this can break the concrete.
</P>
<P>
   You can leave the cut flanges embedded in the concrete, then
install a wood window.
</P>
<P>
   Thinking about it, you may not have to cut out the frame. Remove
only the sash (the frame holding the glass). Then rabbet the new
wood window's frame so that it can be installed in the opening
against the steel frame. This way you can drill through the steel
frame to hold the wood window in place.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. When we bought our house, the inspector said the attic space
is badly mildewed because the attic is sealed with no vents at all.
He suggested we put in vents, which we will do. One contractor
would charge $500 to put in vents. Doesn't that seem kind of high?
</P>
<P>
   SALLY CARROLL, North Reading, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. There's nothing like an unvented attic to cause mildew to
grow. It's the same with a closed-in basement, to cause that dank,
musty smell and all kinds of mildew growth. Ugh. At least it is
curable by ventilation, allowing excess water vapor to escape.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of putting in vents depends on what the vents are and
where they are.
</P>
<P>
   The ideal venting system is a ridge vent going the full length
of the roof ridge, and soffit vents (a continuous two-inch-wide
strip along the full length of the the soffit, the under part of
the roof overhang). A ridge vent costs about $10 per foot,
installed, soffit vents mabe $5 per foot, installed. If your house
is 30 feet long, the ridge vent would cost $300, and the vent on
each soffit (one in front and one in back) would be $150, for a
total of $600. So that $500 may not be exorbitant.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I'd like to move my water bed in the basement elsewhere in
the house. Obviously I have to drain the water; can I drain the
water through the washing machine drain?
</P>
<P>
   BILL ANTOS, Hyannis, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You can if the house is on sewers and not a septic tank. I
think that much water would overload a septic system. Or, why not
syphon it outdoors and save the water for irrigation?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The wood bottom of my painted garage door is crumbling, and
the rubber gasket on the bottom edge is loose. Can that be fixed,
or do I need a new door?
</P>
<P>
   BENJAMIN CHERNOFF, Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You might not need a door, despite what the makers of the
door might say. You may have to make repairs yourself, because it
would be difficult to find a handyperson willing to do such a fussy
job.
</P>
<P>
   These paneled, folding doors have a wide rail at the bottom;
this is the rail that is decayed. First, remove the gasket, then
determine how deep the decay is gone into the wood. Cut off the
decayed part; that is, cut several inches off that rail, and cut a
filler piece of pressure-treated wood to attach to the bottom. If
the filler peice is less than a few inches thick, screw it on; if
it is more than a few inches, you will have to secure it with
mending plates. Reapply the gasket and repaint the door. It should
be good for many more years.
</P>
<P>
   And if that all seems too fussy, too much work or simply not to
your liking, a new door is the only way to go.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes you will have to replace the entire rail, which makes
it more complicated because the new rail would also have to secure
the panels. With that in mind, this too is a reason to buy a new
door.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
