<HEADLINE>
RADIO STATION ASKS EMPLOYEES TO RETURN TO WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE CHAO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ Employees of Berkeley's landmark public radio
station have turned down an invitation to return to work and
demanded to see the offer in writing from the Pacifica Foundation,
which owns KPFA-FM.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the KPFA steering committee, who represent the
station's employees, volunteers and listeners involved in federal
mediation with the management, accused Pacifica chairwoman Mary
Frances Berry on Thursday of circumventing the mediation process by
going directly to the news media with her offer to reopen the
station.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of noisy protesters stormed the radio station in
mid-July after the management dismissed its third radio host in
three months at the 50-year-old station. And more than a dozen KPFA
supporters were arrested during a protest at the station in June.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime staffers maintain that Pacifica's board wants to give
KPFA a more mainstream image so that it can attract corporate
donations. Others worry that KPFA, traditionally a loud liberal
voice, might be sold to a commercial buyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We, as representatives of this effort, won't trust any offer
that isn't in writing,'' said Robbie Osman, a steering committee
member who had a weekly music program on KPFA until he was fired
last month. ``We have experience with (Berry) saying things to the
press, and doing the exact opposite the next day.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Berry said that re-opening the station was not an
offer but a decision. She asked the employees to return to work.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict between the listener-sponsored KPFA and the
Pacifica governing board has been in a stalemate for two weeks,
with the station airing only tapes of old programs and federal
mediation showing few signs of progress.
</P>
<P>
   Berry said she called both the local and international heads of
the Communications Workers of America, which represents roughly two
dozen KPFA workers, to explain the decision to re-open.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned, the union has been notified up and
down the line of the fact that we intend to open the station,'' she
said. ``The union is perfectly able to inform everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Berry, who is also chairwoman of the U.S. Civil Rights
Commission, said she was surprised at the workers' confusion. She
said she was ``puzzled because all the things we did are things
they want.''
</P>
<P>
   Osman said the Pacifica negotiating team, which includes
executive director Lynn Chadwick, had nothing in writing to present
Thursday at the mediation session. Chadwick did not return a
telephone call seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   KPFA's 11-member steering committee represents not only the 25
or so unionized staff members, but also the hundreds of non-union
workers, volunteers and listeners, said Osman, who is not a union
member.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary Frances Berry has simply never communicated with this
group of 11,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Berry's offer was drafted at a meeting Wednesday of the
six-member executive committee of the Pacifica Foundation board. It
was arrived at after much debate, said executive committee member
Jewelle Taylor-Gibbs, a psychologist and professor at the
University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been trying to come to a consensus on the board. We've
had intense discussion,'' Taylor-Gibbs said. ``This proposal is an
honest-to-goodness effort to make peace with the committee and the
protesters.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the board has made tremendous concessions and hoped
workers will return to work.
</P>
<P>
   Pacifica also owns and operates stations in Houston, Los
Angeles, New York and Washington, D.C.
</P>
</TEXT>
