<HEADER>
A9889 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENSUS-RACE-ART-BOS &LR;      07-30 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-RACE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINORITIES FEAR CENSUS FALLS SHORT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Norma Rosario, whose skin is the color of coffee with
a dash of cream, was known as Latino back in Puerto Rico, but when
she and her family moved to Boston in 1980 they were commonly
referred to as African-American.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother was stopped by the police constantly because they
thought he was black,'' said Rosario. ``The color lines are clearer
here, but in Puerto Rico it's more political.''
</P>
<P>
   While the decision to allow US residents to choose more than one
race on next year's census survey will give Rosario and others a
chance to select their own identity, the move has also forced an
unprecedented bond among black, Hispanic, and Asian civil rights
groups that fear the change will undermine their political gains
and divide their ranks.
</P>
<P>
   This week, national Hispanic and Asian leaders met with their
respective communities in Boston to urge residents to accurately
fill out their ethnicity as well as their race on the 2000 census
forms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe if you are of African descent and you are also, say,
Panamanian, then you are African-American as well as Latino,'' said
Beatriz Lopez-Flores, vice president of education and public policy
for the Mexican American Legal Defense and Educational Fund. ``We
understand the racial dynamics of this country and we are trying to
educate people on this.''
</P>
<P>
   MALDES shares the concern voiced by black leaders and race
specialists across the country that the new survey could undermine
the social gains and solidarity of the nation's 34 million people
of African descent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a diversionary tactic to deplete our numbers and
influence in the political arena,'' said Minister Don Muhammad of
The Nation of Islam in Boston. ``This is done to keep the so-called
minority groups from uniting and becoming a political force in this
country.''
</P>
<P>
   The concern is that some Hispanics and biracial residents,
fearing they will be stigmatized if they check ``black'' in the
race category, will instead identify themselves as white, diluting
the numbers of the country's African-American population.
</P>
<P>
   The federal census was never meant as a forum for racial
expression, said James S. Jackson, an African-American adviser for
the 2000 census.
</P>
<P>
   But that is exactly what it has become, some critics say.
Minorities fear that the rule change will prompt some residents _
who had in the past chosen one race or another on the form _ to
check more than one box or write in another race, in effect
creating a separate race category.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said advisers from every minority group have opposed the
change; so now those groups are working with the federal government
to ensure their communities are accurately counted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very much together on this. We are with our black and
Latino brothers,'' said Glenn Magpantay, a member of the Asian
American Legal Defense and Educational Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1977, the federal government has stuck to four racial
categories on the census: black, white, American Indian or Alaska
native, and Asian or Pacific Islander, which consists of several
subcategories. But those choices came under criticism by people
such as golf superstar Tiger Woods, who said that America's
categorization of its minorities was not reflecting his mixed
heritage.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, 1 million children in the United States were of
mixed-race parentage; that number had doubled by the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   While the federal government has not established a tabulation
method for the new census forms, Claudette Bennett, chief of race
and statistics for the US Census Bureau in Washington, said a
respondent who chooses more than one race will be placed in a
category called ``two or more'' races. The other approach will be
to count every single response in the race category. Civil rights
officials are estimating a possible 63 race combinations.
</P>
<P>
   The census has far-reaching implications, said Magpantay, since
the data is often used for social programs and political
representation.
</P>
<P>
   State Representative Byron Rushing, a Boton Democrat, believes
the change will only further prove that race is a made-up social
construct in this country. ``The most important thing is that
people fill out the forms and they are counted, rather than what
race they choose,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The ability to check off more than one box instead of wholly
claiming black could give a false impression that America is moving
to a mixed and colorblind society, said Emmett Schaefer, an adjunct
professor of sociology at the University of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``That social construct is still with us _ black and white _ and
so are the consequences,'' he said. ``A person with dark skin who
drives in a new car, the police will still stop them not factoring
in that he may be be mixed with Irish or Cherokee,'' said Schaefer.
</P>
<P>
   Rosario said she is proud and open about her black, Indian, and
Spanish heritage _ but she will only mark Latino on the census, and
not choose a race _ exactly what minority groups don't want to
happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider myself Latino,'' said Rosario. ``But my daughter
will choose African-American because her father and friends are
black, and my son will choose Latino because his friends are
Latino.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilda Hurdle was born in Panama, where her ancestors from
Jamaica and Barbados migrated in the early part of the century to
work on the Panama Canal. While she is clearly of African descent
with her dark complexion, her race was never an issue until she
moved to the United States as a teenager.
</P>
<P>
   While she will mark herself as some race other than black on the
census, Hurdle will identify her American-born daughter as black.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the way Americans view her daughter's skin color,
Hurdle said the girl ``doesn't have a choice (in America) and
therefore she will only be seen as one or the other (black or
white). I have a choice because I come from Panama.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurdle's brother, however, a lawyer, will mark both Latino and
black.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez-Flores said that regardless of a person's choice on the
census survey, the reality is that Hispanics in this country are
considered second-class citizens, as are blacks: ``So the person
who is Mexican and chooses white is still a Mexican,'' she said.
``For Hispanics what is crucial is that we want them to be as
accurate as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Census officials say they don't know the social ramifications of
the change. Census trial tests have shown that only a small
percentage of those taking the survey considered themselves
multiracial. In Columbia, S.C., less than 1 percent of the
population chose two or more races on the test forms.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, the census adviser, is concerned that the change may
cause a schism among blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``African-Americans don't have a problem saying they are
black,'' he said, ``but those who do have been (calling themselves)
something else for a very long time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
