<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT DO THE RICH GET FROM THE TAX BILL? MORE, OF COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A million bucks ain't what it used to be. That's why so many
millionaires want what Samuel Gompers wanted for the labor
movement: more.
</P>
<P>
   And more is what the rich would get from the obscenely bloated
tax bill belched out by the Republican Congress and laying like a
beached whale on a Cape Cod beach. Like a dead whale, this lumpy
titan of a tax boondoggle can never again do what it was designed
to do. But the sheer bulk of it leaves one dumb-struck.
</P>
<P>
   What hath the House of Reps wrought? Another giveaway to the
rich. ``Everyone's Getting Rich!'' hollered Money Magazine's May
cover. Really? Congress knows better. They're not fools, even if
they play the part.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a crash course in political economy. In presidential
elections, the two major parties each start out with roughly 40
percent of the vote. The 20 percent in the middle decide the
outcome. The winner has to get to 51. How? By convincing, seducing,
or frightening at least 11 of the 20 to vote for you, natch. But
not everyone who can votes. The poorer, younger, more nonwhite you
are, the less likely you'll vote. Sad but true.
</P>
<P>
   So to get to 51, the winner can afford to ignore those poor,
young, or nonwhite voters you can figure will be too busy,
discouraged, or ignorant to understand that not voting their own
best interest pushes them further behind on the earning curve. So
both parties make their pitch to a richer slice of the spectrum of
earning power.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats spend less time and money courting the underclass,
because they won't vote; that's why you got all the ``welfare
reform.'' Democratic priorities run from the working poor to the
middle class. Democrats run out of gas for taxpayers with incomes
between $75,000 and maybe $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans start getting worked up on behalf of the
$75,000-per-year crowd, and get feverish on behalf of the rich.
Example: the House GOP tax bill would give back to a two-parent
family with two kids the following: $841 if the family lives on
$75,000, $4,084 if the family has $200,000, and $31,138 smackeroos
for the $1 million per year family. Is that fair? Or is that
entertainment for the plutocracy?
</P>
<P>
   Coming off a bad season of impeachment (Clinton won) and the
Kosovo war (Clinton won) and fearful of losing the skinny five-seat
margin which gives them precarious control of the House, the GOP
needed a juicy issue. Who can say no to a tax cut, right? Clinton's
veto will derail the GOP freight train, something perhaps half its
size will be approved, probably reducing the extra burden hefted by
married couples over singles, and propping up Social Security and
Medicaid. Then comes the election. Way out in front is Texas
Governor George W. Bush, who has raised $200,000 a day all year
long because well-off people think they'll be even richer if he
wins next year.
</P>
<P>
   Bush reaps cash forked over by business lobbyists benefiting
from the $100 billion in tax breaks the GOP voted for
multi-nationals, utilities, oil and gas, timber, steel, and
insurance interests. ``. . . the fine print will reveal another
cornucopia for the special interests, and a chamber of horrors for
the taxpayers,'' gripes Arizona Senator John McCain, who may be
Bush's principal opposition in New Hampshire's perhaps-decisive
presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the people who track the numbers on how wealth is
divvied up in America are amazed at how docile are the middle class
and working class folk whose share has dropped. ``Most households
have lower net worth than they did in 1983, when the Dow (Jones
Industrial Average) was still at 1,000,'' instead of 11 times
higher. ``Average workers are earning less, adjusting for
inflation, than they did when Richard Nixon was president.''
</P>
<P>
   These claims come from a left-leaning worker's rights outfit,
United For a Fair Economy in Boston (Web site: www.stw.org) in a
scary little book of plain hard numbers, titled ``Shifting
Fortunes: The perils of the growing American wealth gap.'' The
richest one percent got 42 percent of the stock market gravy; the
next richest 9 percent got 44 percent; that leaves 14 percent of
the gravy for 90 percent of the people. Hmmm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom 40 percent of households lost an astonishing 80
percent of net worth'' from '83 to '85. Working women pad out
family incomes; one out of five families is in red ink. It's the
``middle Americans'' who got creamed, argues MIT's Lester Thurow in
the book's foreword. The middle 80 percent ``are the big losers
over the last 25 years . . . At some point, those who are losing
economically have to use their political power to vote in a
government that reverses the outcome of the market. No one knows
where this point is.''
</P>
<P>
   Lester, in politics, the points are at the working end of the
pitchfork.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-99 1352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990730.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9894 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-30 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S BAND SINGS SAME OLD SONGS TO WORKING POOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the beginning of July, President Clinton took the Grateful
Poor Tour. Grateful Poor tours are conducted every few years when
the Democrats are in the White House or every few decades when the
Republicans are in the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   They are scheduled only after presidents have taken care of
corporations, defense contractors, party donors, and selected
international hotspots. These are called ``vital interests.'' The
Grateful Poor are called such because everyone knows they are not
vital interests, having been ignored during this great outbreak of
foreign sweatshops, suburban sprawl, and celebratory cigars.
</P>
<P>
   In the concert world, Grateful tours played the same old songs
to everyone's satisfaction until Jerry Garcia's final breath. In
politics, the Grateful Poor Tour has begun to grate on people whom
the president assumes will bow down and lay carpets across their
streets of broken bottles and dreams when he shows up.
</P>
<P>
   In Watts, Clinton visited a high school where few members of the
actual community were allowed to attend his speech. A 75-year-old
man from the neighborhood who came in a suit and tie, but was
denied entrance, said, ``If the community's not here, it's not
serving any purpose. They could have held it downtown.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton went to an Oglala Lakota Sioux reservation at Pine
Ridge, S.D. He hoped no one remembered that he signed a budget for
the Bureau of Indian Affairs that was cut by Congress in 1995 and
that Indians are suing the government for mismanaged trust funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thousands of members of that tribe are being actively
defrauded by the Clinton administration,'' said Jim McCarthy, a
consultant in the trust fund suit. ``For him to go out there and
throw some crumbs off the federal plate is really appalling.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there were still plenty of Grateful Poor to lay out
the carpets in these places as well as Appalachia, Mississippi,
East St. Louis, and Phoenix. There were enough individual success
stories to make it seem on TV that poverty is being attacked. But
child poverty has remained at around 20 percent during the Clinton
era. Poverty rates for Indians, Latinos, and African-Americans
remain more than twice that of white Americans.
</P>
<P>
   While official poverty declined in Clinton's time from 15.1
percent to 13.3 percent, the wealth gap between rich and poor has
never been wider and real wages for all but high-income workers
have stagnated or fallen. What the overall poverty rate does not
say is that the poverty rate among workers has actually increased
from 5.7 percent in 1979 to 6.7 percent today.
</P>
<P>
   What Grateful Poor tours rarely explore is how the working poor
actually feel. Last week, Rutgers University's Heldrich Center for
Workforce Development and the University of Connecticut's Center
for Survey Research and Analysis released a nationwide survey of
500 adults, most of whom made $25,000 or less.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, ``Working Hard But Staying Poor,'' found an upbeat
work force, with 84 percent of participants generally satisfied
with their jobs. Only 24 percent of the working poor wanted to work
less, compared to 58 percent of other workers from earlier Rutgers
studies. Conversely, 24 percent of the working poor said they want
to work more, compared to 12 percent of other workers. ``The
working poor and the unemployed are in large numbers seeking a
better life and are willing to work for it,'' the survey said.
</P>
<P>
   But the opportunities for a better job are slim. Eighty-one
percent of the working poor say they would enroll in an education
or training program. But only 18 percent work for employers who
give financial help to enroll in off-site job training or education
(compared to 36 percent of higher-income workers). Only 27 percent
have received government aid for that purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Without that education or training, the working poor will not be
able to bridge the digital gap. The survey found that 48 percent of
the working poor and unemployed use computers on the job or at
home, compared to 77 percent of other workers. In addition, it
would sure help if jobs were located near them. Nine out of 10
respondents said they need jobs in their community. But many were
also willing to move or commute with better public transit.
</P>
<P>
   The report concluded that the best immediate ways to raise the
living standards of the working poor is to increase the minimum
wage to $6.15 an hour, improve on-site childcare and public
transit, and increase job training and education opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The working poor and unemployed have less access to the
critical paths of opportunity in the new economy,'' it said. To
provide that access, particularly at a time of widening wealth
gaps, presidents will have to do more than announce a tour of the
Grateful Poor. The president will have to bring along the
instruments so the poor can get up on the stage and jam.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
