A9903 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-GAS-HNS &LR;      07-30 0424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-GAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUPS SEEK TO REVERSE RULING ON CALIFORNIA GAS SALES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE KAY  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Two environmental organizations have gone to
court seeking to reverse a state regulatory agency's ruling giving
the Chevron Corp. the right to sell gasoline that does not meet the
California's stringent clean-air requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Communities for a Better Environment and Earth Island Institute
filed a request Thursday for an injunction against the state Air
Resources Board in San Francisco Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   They are trying to overturn the board's decision two weeks ago
giving Chevron permission to sell gasoline that does not meet
clean-air standards.
</P>
<P>
   An explosion at Chevron's Richmond refinery damaged a unit used
to produce the gasoline, called reformulated clean fuel. Chevron
requested the emergency variance to sell gasoline from other states
for 45 days.
</P>
<P>
   The two environmental groups say the refining and use of up to
3.5 million barrels of the gasoline would add 23 tons of volatile
organic compounds and 7 tons of nitrogen oxides to the skies every
day.
</P>
<P>
   The compounds react in sunlight to produce ground-level ozone,
the primary ingredient of summer smog.
</P>
<P>
   ``Selling dirty gasoline will endanger public health and the
environment,'' said Denny Larson, the Northern California director
of Communities for a Better Environment. ``Yet, the Air Resources
Board failed to implement any effective measures to offset the tons
of extra pollution. Offsets are required by state law.''
</P>
<P>
   Chevron, which received the variance on July 15, hasn't yet sold
any of the gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``To date, we've been fortunate to continue to supply California
cleaner-burning gasoline, and haven't needed to sell one drop of
the variance fuel,;; said Nancy Malinowski, a spokeswoman for
Chevron, which is based in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will only use it as a last resort. We don't have an
incentive to use the fuel,'' she said. The state will levy a
15-cent fee on each gallon that doesn't meet its standards.
</P>
<P>
   So far Chevron has been able to get cleaner fuel from Finland,
Korea and the Los Angeles area, while it works to fix the damaged
unit, Malinowski said.
</P>
<P>
   But she doesn't know how long Chevron can find enough to sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Industry inventories are tight, and it's the peak of the
summer driving season. The price of crude oil has gone from roughly
$12 a barrel to $20 in two months. The market is responding to
it,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
