 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SATURDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Saturday, July 31:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ATLANTA SHOOTING &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 1{ pages of coverage on the aftermath
of the shooting rampage in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   GA-SHOOT-RDP (Atlanta) _ Ledeall: Developments in the shooting
and suicide, including more on the motive behind the shooting, why
the suspect was never charged in the earlier killing of his wife
and mother in law, what's in the notes. By Kevin Sack. (1400 words)
</P>
<P>
   GA-SHOOT-SUSPECT (Atlanta) _ Notes left behind indicate Mark O.
Barton was a deeply troubled man who feared living more than death,
sought to end his children's lives rather than let them suffer as
he says he had and sought revenge for some reason still unclear on
people he blamed for his troubles. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   GA-SHOOT-TRADERS (Undated) _ Besides trading stock all day,
day-traders spend time in Internet chatrooms. We visit them there,
gauge their reaction and hear about the stresses of the occupation.
By Amy Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, we are considering stories on the victims, on media
coverage and on what impact this incident may have on the gun
control debate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TAX-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Developments on the third day of
debate in the Senate on the tax bill, with a vote on the overall
bill scheduled. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SPEND-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Congress, determined to increase
military spending and unable to cut the rest of the budget deeper
than it has already done, is certain to wipe out the projected
$14.5 billion surplus in coming weeks. Now the Republican
leadership is scouring the entire federal budget, seeking unspent
money from programs like Medicaid, welfare benefits and interstate
highway funds to fill a spending gap that is running upwards of $15
billion. Strict spending caps, which have helped create the
surplus, may be broken in the process. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TAX-GORE (Minneapolis) _ The vice president gives a speech
detailing his tax policy. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   TRIPP-INDICT (Ellicott City, Md.) _ Linda Tripp has been
indicted by a state grand jury here for secretly taping phone
conversations with Monica Lewinsky. By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   RELGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly religion column. By Peter
Steinfels.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BALKANS-U.S. (Sarajevo) _ President Clinton offers aid to
Balkans, except Serbia. Other developments at European Union Balkan
meeting. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SECT (Beijing) _ A senior military officer, identified as
Falun Gong's highest-ranking leader in Beijing, has confessed his
role in the spiritual movement, a milestone in the government's
crackdown on the group. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TAIWAN (Beijing) _ A long-awaited policy statement by
Taiwan's top china envoy ruins chances for a fresh start in
negotiations. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-EMBASSY (Beijing) _ The U.S. State Department announces it
will pay $4.5 million to victims of NATO's bombing of the Chinese
Embassy in Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital, during the Kosovo
campaign. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   AID-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The House has passed an amendment to
the foreign aid bill cutting off $1.5 million for recruiting Latin
American officers to the School of the Americas, the Army school
that has trained, among other luminaries, Noriega, D'Aubuisson,
etc. That's about a tenth of the school's budget, but it's still
unusual. Other developments including international family planning
aid, money for putting the Wye Mideast accord into effect, cuts in
aid for interest-free loans to the poorest nations. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   PEPSI-POWER-AISLE (Pittsfield, Mass.) _ Here in the Price
Chopper supermarket, between Aisle 6, devoted to detergents and dog
food, and Aisle 9, featuring peanut butter and jelly, is Pepsico
chairman Roger A. Enrico's vision of the future: ``the Power
Aisle,'' a large space stocked with mostly Pepsi soft drinks and
Frito-Lay snack food. Pepsi's hope is that a shopper looking for a
two-liter bottle of Mountain Dew will grab a bag of Cool Ranch
Doritos as well. The goal, of course, is to pump up Pepsi's sales
and profits by taking advantage of some synergies unavailable to
its arch-rival, Coke, and thereby boost its lagging share price. By
Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   LONDON-MARKET-IPO (London) _ Taking its cue from markets in the
United States, the London Stock Exchange, Europe's largest market,
plans to offer shares to its members, ending mutual ownership by
brokers as it faces competition from electronic trading networks
and seeks European alliances. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   EVERBRIGHT-RESIGN (Beijing) _ The China Everbright Group, one of
the country's largest corporate groups, announces that its chairman
resigned. But company officials deny reports that he was under
investigation for alleged ``economic irregularities.'' By Seth
Faison.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-PAPERS (London) _ Trinity PLC, Britain's largest
regional newspaper company (The Liverpool Echo and The Belfast
Telegraph are among its papers), agrees to buy Mirror Group PLC,
publisher of The Mirror tabloid for $2.5 billion, creating the
country's largest newspaper publisher. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-ARGENTINA (Sao Paulo) _ Argentina agrees to revoke trade
barriers that were imposed on several Brazilian goods last week
after a meeting Thursday night between Presidents Fernando Henrique
Cardoso of Brazil and Carlos Menem of Argentina. By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Frank Rich's ``Journal.''
</P>
