 Friday, July 30, 1999    
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following for
Saturday and Sunday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee
or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all
sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Saturday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-VIEQUES (Washington) _ A federal cancer-monitoring
agency looks into charges by civilians on the Puerto Rican island
of Vieques that U.S. bombing exercises there have caused high
levels of cancer. The probe comes as the White House prepares to
decide the future of the military's bombing range. That decision
could influence Puerto Rican political support for the campaigns of
Vice President Al Gore and First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton next
year. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-PRESCRIPTIONS (Washington) _ Food and Drug
Administration officials tell Congress they are starting to crack
down on Internet sites that sell prescription drugs illegally. By
JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   SAFE-SEX (Washington) _ Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla., who is also a
physician, lectures some 300 congressional interns. His message: If
you want to avoid painful sexually transmitted diseases, abstain
from sex. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY-CLINTON-BANKS (Washington) _ Senate Banking Committee
Chairman Phil Gramm, R-Texas, says First Lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton's bid for a U.S. Senate seat may boost prospects for
enactment of legislation that would allow banks, securities and
insurance firms to merge. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN. Filed
Thursday in the WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'') and the FINANCIAL-BUSINESS
NEWS (``f'') categories.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-WINE (Washington) _ The wine industry is fighting
legislation aimed at stopping teen-agers from ordering its products
over the Internet, contending the measure will hurt small vintners
trying to make sales to adults on the Web and through mail-order
catalogues. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN. Filed Thursday in the
WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'') and the FINANCIAL-BUSINESS NEWS (``f'')
categories.
</P>
<P>
   RIVLIN-FED (Washington) _ Alice Rivlin, once told by Harvard's
public service school that women need not apply, has had
high-profile government jobs that many Harvard grads can only dream
of holding. Rivlin, who just stepped down as vice chairman of the
Federal Reserve, looks back on three decades of public service. By
JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN. Filed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ In a presidential election, the
party that defines the agenda for debate is the one that usually
wins. That's why the Democrats and Republicans are fighting so hard
over how the first federal budget surplus in three decades will be
divvied up. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON. (Filed Wednesday.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
