<DOCNO> NYT19990730.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 14:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9937 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-BALKANS-0731-     07-30 1258
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BALKANS-0731-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON, WORLD LEADERS SET BLUEPRINT FOR PEACE IN TROUBLED
BALKANS
 &HT;    EDs: With optional trim.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina _ Victors in war, the United States
and its European allies rallied here Friday around a blueprint for
peace in the troubled region scarred by Europe's bloodiest
conflicts since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and his counterparts from 40 other nations --
including Russia, Britain, Germany, France -- launched a
broad-ranging Balkans Stability Pact, meant to ensure that the
major powers won't simply walk away from the region now that the
flames of its latest conflict have been smothered by NATO air
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came to talk about a greater Europe, based on including
people, and healing,'' Clinton said in a speech at a local high
school following the summit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The war is over,'' Clinton said, ``but we have to build a
better peace for Bosnians and all the people of southeastern
Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's national security adviser, Samuel Berger, told
reporters that Clinton stressed during the summit the need for a
comprehensive, regional approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal here is to begin the process of integrating this
region into the mainstream of Europe,'' Clinton told leaders
attending the one-day summit, meant to be the diplomatic capstone
to NATO's qualified success in Kosovo. ``We can't do it one country
at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Serbia, though, is being excluded from the benefits of Friday's
Stability Pact, so long as Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic,
Yugoslavia's president, remains in power.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic, under indictment as a war criminal, was not invited.
His political opponents were.
</P>
<P>
   ``A decade-long campaign by Mr. Milosevic to carve out a greater
Serbia has left more than a quarter million people dead, uprooted
millions more and undermined the stability of this entire region,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serbia will only have a future when Mr. Milosevic and his
policies are consigned to the past,'' he added. In a closing
statement, he and the other leaders appealed to Serb-led Yugoslavia
``to embrace democratic change and work actively for regional
reconciliation.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   In a smaller but decidedly more tangible gesture, Clinton
delivered 10 new Apple I-Mac computers -- still in their jelly-bean
colored boxes -- to a local high school the president hailed as a
model of multi-ethnic recovery for a region shattered by nearly a
decade of ethnically-based bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This school is a monument to Sarajevo's proud tradition of
teaching young people from all backgrounds,'' said Clinton,
speaking before several hundred students, dignitaries and local
residents at the school, named the Third Gymnasium. ``I want this
school, this school rebuilt, to be the symbol of all of our
tomorrows.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday's Balkans summit, held in this former Olympic host city
that endured a bloody siege at the hands of Serb snipers and
gunners from 1992 until 1995, was in itself a richly symbolic vote
of confidence in Balkans renewal.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders met in the Zetra arena, where East German figure
skater Katerina Witt won her gold medal in the 1984 Winter Games.
The arena was an early casualty of the war and Friday's summit
marked its first use since its reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton flew in aboard a giant C-17 military cargo jet, landing
at Sarajevo International Airport, one of the most hazardous spots
in town during the three-and-a-half year war.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   The stability pact -- a package of programs, incentives and aid
meant to promote security, democratization, free market reforms and
economic growth -- is essentially a promise that the United States
and its allies will remain deeply engaged for years to come in a
region where four wars have been fought since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Three of those conflicts -- in Bosnia, Croatia and the Serb
province of Kosovo -- have involved U.S. and other NATO forces. A
fourth, in Slovenia, lasted only a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire purpose of this is to make sure that the fourth war
in the former Yugoslavia is the last ethnic war, or conflict,
regarding the territory of the former Yugoslavia,'' said NATO
spokesman Jamie Shea. ``We don't want any more of those.''
</P>
<P>
   There are 6,200 U.S. peacekeepers in Bosnia, as part of a larger
NATO force of 29,000. Another 7,500 American troops are going into
nearby Kosovo as part of a NATO contingent rapidly working its way
to the 50,000 mark.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign troops alone, however, won't secure an enduring peace,
said Clinton, who focused Friday on augmenting security efforts
with economic aid.
</P>
<P>
   With annual income averaging less than $2,000 per person, the
Balkan countries are the poorest in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton offered a five-point plan for helping promote growth.
</P>
<P>
   By themselves, the measures are low-octane steps. Clinton's hope
is that the initiatives he proposed would be echoed by European
countries to amplify the impact. European leaders responded
favorably, Berger said, and indicated that they would soon take up
the matter before the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Among Clinton's proposals were:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  a reduction in tariffs charged on certain products shipped
from the region to the United States, in a change that, if approved
by Congress, could mean reductions of up to $80 million, over five
years, in the price U.S. consumers would pay for Balkan footwear
and other goods;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  an investment compact -- complete with a planned autumn trade
mission -- aimed at increasing private U.S. investment in Balkan
countries that take steps to help safeguard foreign capital, combat
corruption and let the market take over where central governments
have long held sway;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  $350 million in funding to help back loans to businesses
willing to invest and trade with Balkans countries considered as
high risk propositions by commercial banks;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  and $34 million for loans to small and medium-sized
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's summit comes on the heels of an agreement by the United
States and its key allies to pony up $2 billion for immediate
humanitarian and reconstruction efforts in Kosovo, a province of
Serbia, Yugoslavia's dominant republic.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo was ravaged this spring by attacks targeting ethnic
Albanians by Serb-led Yugoslav forces, and by 78 days of NATO air
strikes targeting those forces.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of Kosovo, the air strikes destroyed more than 700 major
targets throughout Serbia. Bridges were dropped into the Danube
River, refineries and factories were bombed to ruins and dozens of
key highway interchanges were reduced to rubble in damage Belgrade
claims would cost scores of billions of dollars to repair.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders tough position to exclude Serbia from any
reconstruction efforts or economic aid to the Balkans was a sharp
contrast with Russian Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin, who said the
West is wrong to make aid to Serbia conditional on Milosevic's
departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not associate (ourselves) with this strict linkage that
it's either Milosevic or assistance,'' Stepashin told a news
conference after the summit.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding Yugoslavia from a stability pact endorsed by the
Sarajevo summit could prove an obstacle to lasting peace in the
region and would hurt innocent Serbs, Stepashin said.
</P>
<P>
   The West's approach ``could lead to very serious
repercussions,'' Stepashin said through an interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-99 1429EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
