<DOCNO> NYT19990730.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9962 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STONEWALK0801-COX     07-30 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STONEWALK0801-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    VOLUNTEERS PUSH AND PULL TOMBSTONE ON A JOURNEY TO HONOR
CIVILIANS KILLED IN WAR
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With PHOTOS 
 &HT;    Advance for use on or after Sunday, August 1 
 &HT;    By RAVEN HILL 
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   VALLEY TOWNSHIP, Pa. _ It's a strange caravan that moves along
the country road on a scorching hot summer day.
</P>
<P>
   A tan van leads the way with the words, ``Stonewalk, Veterans
for Peace,'' printed on its side. Seven men of varying ages are
behind it, hand-pulling a 2,000-pound tombstone on a caisson
decorated with an American flag.
</P>
<P>
   It is the 24th day of their 33-day mission to deliver the stone
honoring civilian war victims to an unknown site at Arlington
National Cemetery, across the Potomac River from Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most fitting way to bring the memorial to
Arlington,'' said Karl Schlotterbeck, a project coordinator. ``It's
a struggle, but it shows our devotion to the cause and our concern
and anguish over the deaths of civilians.''
</P>
<P>
   Stonewalk was organized by a peace group called the Peace Abbey
in Sherborn, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The gray stone _ it's inscription reads ``Unknown Civilians
Killed in War'' _ was loaded onto the caisson in Sherborn on July
4. The 1-ton piece of granite had been unveiled there by Muhammad
Ali in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The group is scheduled to end its 485 mile journey at Arlington
National Cemetery on Aug. 6, the anniversary of the bombing of
Hiroshima. However, cemetery officials said they will not be able
to leave the stone in the cemetery. That would require
congressional approval.
</P>
<P>
   As a compromise, cemetery superintendent John Metzler spoke by
phone with Stonewalk organizers on Thursday and they agreed to
leave the headstone with a yet-to-be-designated embassy in
Washington. It is not clear what will then happen to the stone, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   White roses have been placed on top of the tombstone, which is
surrounded by the flags of all nations. Black and purple bunting
are on both sides of the caisson. Bottles of water, which provide
liquid relief in the blazing heat, are stored in the back under
more bunting of red, white and blue.
</P>
<P>
   During their journey, organizer Lewis Randa said they've
attracted as many as 25 volunteers in a single day. They have been
of varying ages and walks of life, including members of Scout
troops, veterans, children and police officers. A man in
Connecticut celebrated his 84th birthday by taking 84 steps pulling
the stone.
</P>
<P>
   As it passed near Valley Township this past week, the group was
down to seven volunteers. They began their day around 9 a.m. and
had been pushing and pulling ever since. The day usually starts
with breakfast. Trail mix and granola bars sustain them until their
next big meal in the late afternoon or early evening.
</P>
<P>
   Fair weather or foul, they walk every day. Rain has provided
relief only once, said Schlotterbeck, who has been associated with
the Peace Abbey for almost 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Dennes (CQ) Wilson, 20, joined the group in Paoli, Pa. He'd read
about their mission and happened to see them chugging along through
his small community. They asked his family for a place to stay that
night and he went out with them that next morning.
</P>
<P>
   Though Wilson did not plan to make the entire trek to Arlington,
he said that's partly why the mission is so amazing.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a sense, it's a trip of faith. You pull it through your own
community and someone from another community will replace you,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the strain and the heat, Wilson said he has no regrets
about making the trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``You find out the real strength you need is in your heart and
spirit. It's the cause that's driving you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dot Walsh alternately steers the caisson and walks. She has been
involved with the Peace Abbey since 1988. Noting the world is
nearing the end of a century of wars, she said this is a fitting
time in history for such a memorial. As a mother and grandmother,
she said, she is bothered by the numbers of children killed in
wars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an incredible journey of faith,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Goodnow, 60, is pulling the stone all the way to Arlington.
As he helped pull the caisson through Pennsylvania one hot day this
past week, not one bead of sweat rolled down his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a cakewalk compared to what has happened to the
civilians in war-torn towns,'' he said. ``I feel no pain, heat or
discomfort from the journey at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodnow, who did not serve in the armed forces, said the stone
has great meaning to the veterans he knows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Statistics indicate that 90 percent of all (war) casualties
are civilians,'' he said. ``The voices of the voiceless are
forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodnow said that civilian deaths are often reduced to the term
``collateral damage,'' which appalls him
</P>
<P>
   ``If it were my brother or daughter or wife, I wouldn't want
them called that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The group takes breaks as needed, and typically there is a
moment of silence before they start up again. People often stare at
them from their front porches. They sometimes snap pictures and ask
what they're doing. Some briefly join them.
</P>
<P>
   Randa noticed three teenagers join in. ``This is how it
happens,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The group struggled to get the stone up the hills in this rural
Pennsylvania town. They pulled, pushed, leaned on the caisson _
whatever way works. With red faces, sweat pouring down their neck
and backs, they made it up and took a break.
</P>
<P>
   Gulping bottles of water, some looked like they were trying to
ignore the heat. Drivers stopped behind them peered out of their
windows as they tried to figure out what was going on. One
passenger swore they'd die of heat exhaustion before reaching
Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Randa said he decided that walking the stone would be the most
fitting way to deliver it as he recalled images of Kosovar refugees
leaving their country with all of their possessions on their backs.
In a way, this journey reminds Randa of them, although he admits
``the safety of American soil'' certainly makes this trip less
harrowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``How it gets there is what's important, not just getting it
there,'' he said. ``The journey is not meant to be easy.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
