<SLUG> BC-DAY-TRADING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOOTING HIGHLIGHTS STRESS OF ON-LINE INVESTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The shooting spree carried out by a distraught Georgia investor
has focused attention on the high-stress world of people who play a
white-knuckle, high-stakes game of buying and selling stocks on
personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``With day trading, there's no quicker way to stare into the
abyss of your soul,'' said Joey Anuff, a San Francisco day trader
and author. ``A day trader's life is always about the deal they
missed, or a stock they got stuck with.''
</P>
<P>
   The police in Atlanta say Mark O. Barton, 44, opened fire in two
brokerage offices Thursday, killing nine people and wounding at
least 13 others. The police say Barton was concerned about
financial losses incurred through his investments.
</P>
<P>
   The man, who killed himself before the police could capture him,
also is believed to have beaten to death his wife and two children.
</P>
<P>
   Barton is a former chemist who had been trading shares full
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can put an incredible amount of your money at risk day
trading,'' said Andrew Ross, an investor from Redwood Shores,
Calif. ``And when things go south, you can suffer incredible
losses, and just lose it, emotionally.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, professional stock brokers have buffered
individuals from daily stock market swings. But tales of windfall
profits and the ability to trade stocks on a personal computer have
sparked a rush of consumers into the stock market. Industry
estimates say individual traders can sometimes account for up to a
quarter of a day's stock market trades.
</P>
<P>
   Day traders try to build profits by buying and selling shares
based on the tiniest minute-to-minute fluctuations in stock prices.
These investors sometimes hold a stock for only a matter of
seconds, banking thousands on a stock moving up or down by pennies.
</P>
<P>
   Ross, a photographer who has been trading stocks on line for
more than a year, said the dizzying pace of day trading makes the
practice resemble gambling, with all its thrills and potential
pitfalls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incredibly intoxicating to watch your money grow on your
computer screen,'' he said. ``And it's even more terrifying to
watch it shrink.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Anuff, author of the soon-to-be published ``Dumb
Money: Confessions of a Day Trader,'' the stresses of day trading
are immense: A typical trader will buy fluctuating shares, hold
onto it until the very last second, and then attempt to sell it
over the Internet, a fragile network that can crash during the
sale, sticking a trader with large losses. Compounding these
frustrations are the constantly updating Internet chat boards,
where rival traders crow about triumphs other traders missed.
</P>
<P>
   The budding industry was starting to wake up to the stresses of
day trading prior to the Georgia slayings.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the National Association of Securities Dealers
board approved a rule that would require on-line brokerage services
to screen customers to determine whether they are suited to the
lightning-fast daily trading style.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the Atlanta shooting, the on-line brokerage
ETrade in Menlo Park, Calif., issued a public statement saying it
was heightening security at its offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always taken significant steps to ensure (employee)
safety, including the deployment of state-of-the art security
systems at all of our campuses,'' the company said. ``Clearly, with
the incident today in Atlanta, there is heightened awareness of
security at all of our facilities.''
</P>
<P>
   But if day traders are a stressed group, they're also a tough
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   An hour after the Atlanta shooting made the news, traders posted
messages on the Yahoo Web site, advising other day traders to buy
stock in gun lock manufacturers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
