<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9974 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SF-MAYOR-HNS &LR;      07-30 0459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-MAYOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN SAYS HE HAS RAISED $1 MILLION FOR RE-ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New because of Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHUCK FINNIE and GREGORY LEWIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Mayor Willie Brown has amassed $1 million in
campaign cash, delivering a forceful challenge to anyone trying to
stand in the way of his re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Brown disclosed Thursday that his campaign fund-raising machine
had piled up $1,049,633, an average of $250,000 per month from
March through June 30.
</P>
<P>
   Contributions to Brown, the former speaker of the California
Assembly, cascaded in from city contractors, the real estate
industry, Hollywood and longtime political supporters in public and
private employee unions. Checks arrived from cities across
California and at least 21 other states.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the money that is already in the bank, the
mayor's bid for a second term in November will be augmented by
well-funded, volunteer-rich, get-out-the-vote efforts launched by
the Democratic Party and city labor leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Brown released the campaign finance report ahead of the Monday
filing deadline, while a handful of prominent Democrats ponder
mayoral bids of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Some interpreted the move as part of a strategy to persuade
potential competitors on both the political left and right to forgo
the race.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates have until Aug. 6 to qualify for the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the mayor was trying to convey any specific
message to opponents,'' said P.J. Johnston, Brown's campaign
spokesman. ``However, serious contenders probably will have to take
a look at this and answer some hard questions about their ability
to catch up in this race.''
</P>
<P>
   Two Democrats known to be seriously weighing whether to run in
the Nov. 2 election, Board of Supervisors President Tom Ammiano and
Supervisor Leland Yee, said they wouldn't be intimidated by the
mayor's money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why am I thinking David and Goliath here?'' Ammiano quipped.
</P>
<P>
   Yee said he thinks the mayor is going to have a hard time
erasing negative attitudes about his term, despite all the money at
Brown's disposal to reach the voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Willie Brown can raise all the money in the world. There is
enough information in the last four years to know what he is about.
No amount of money is going to change that perception. The question
is going to be whether San Franciscans want this type of mayor for
the next four years,'' Yee said.
</P>
<P>
   Only one candidate has formally challenged Brown, Clint Reilly,
a millionaire who is a former campaign consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion polls give Brown low ratings among voters, in
part because of dissatisfaction with his handling of the city's
troubled public transportation system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-99 1510EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990730.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 15:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9981 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-BALKANS-$ADV0     07-30 1286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BALKANS-$ADV01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. EFFORTS TO INTERVENE IN BALKANS CONSUMING CLINTON FOREIGN
POLICY
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Aug. 1 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO _ The Balkans have a way of breaking the hearts of
optimists.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a man can dream.
</P>
<P>
   And so came President Clinton, striding down the ramp of a giant
U.S. Air Force cargo jet on Friday, clutching the hand of Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright, stepping into the morning sunlight at
the Sarajevo International Airport and bearing a grand vision of
hope and renewal for this most tragic and tortured of regions.
</P>
<P>
   As acts of faith go, it was a dramatic gesture, richly rewarded
with powerful symbols of the possibilities of peace in a city that
long stood for the hopelessness of war.
</P>
<P>
   Where soldiers once crouched behind sandbags and stood sentry
against Serb snipers and gunners in the surrounding hills, a
sparkling new air terminal stood ready to welcome the world.
</P>
<P>
   On a hilltop that was once part of a lethal no-man's land, two
young boys perched to watch the presidential motorcade wander out
of the airport and wind its way past apartment buildings with fresh
grey spackle plugging bullet-pocked walls.
</P>
<P>
   And all along the broad boulevard into town, a route so perilous
during Bosnia's 3 1/2-year-long war that it was dubbed ``sniper's
alley,'' small gaggles of well-wishers gathered and waved as the
president's limo whisked past in a dizzying blur of black gloss and
chrome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peace, Democracy and Prosperity are Our Hope and Our Goal,''
read a billboard erected by city officials. ``Europe for
Sarajevo,'' read the freshly painted mural on a bullet-riddled
wall, in a reference to Friday's Balkans summit here, attended by
Clinton and his counterparts from 40 other countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very important day, and I would hope it is a very
proud day for the people of Bosnia-Herzegovina,'' Clinton said.
``They've done a remarkable, astonishing job of rebuilding
Sarajevo.''
</P>
<P>
   To watch Clinton straining to put the best face on the rebirth
of a city still deeply scarred and badly reeling from the ravages
of war is to be reminded of the enormous stake he's placed,
politically and personally, in this often haunted region.
</P>
<P>
   No other major world leader has spent more time, taken more
risks nor vested more faith in the prospect of Balkans peace than
Clinton. He has sent thousands of American soldiers into harm's way
first to fight for and later to secure peace in Bosnia, Croatia and
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, no other single issue -- not Russia, not China,
neither the global economy nor the reduction of nuclear weapons --
has captured the international agenda of the Clinton administration
like the business of trying to arrest a decade of Balkan turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   And, as things look now, no other single foreign policy issue
will be as central to Clinton's legacy as his struggle to end
bloodshed in the impoverished southern underbelly of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has even framed what many foreign policy analysts have
begun calling the ``Clinton Doctrine.'' More an expression of good
intentions, really, than a substantive policy guide, the so-called
``doctrine'' rests on the premise that the United States should
intervene militarily to avert humanitarian crises when it has an
interest in doing so and when it has the capacity to make a
difference.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's national security adviser, Samuel Berger, has cast the
Kosovo crisis as a test of the nation's moral character that the
country simple couldn't afford not to pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had America and our allies done nothing,'' Berger said in a
speech last week before the Council on Foreign Relations, ``we
would have faced history's judgment that the world's most powerful
alliance was unwilling to act when confronted with crimes against
humanity at its own doorstep.''
</P>
<P>
   What's yet to be defined is a way to avoid interventions driven
by the cameras of CNN more than by any cold and sober calculus of
American interests abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The Balkans, in fact, have presented Clinton with a rolling set
of policy dilemmas and a constantly evolving drama of wrenching
failure and heady successes.
</P>
<P>
   No one could have predicted seven years ago, when Americans
elected Clinton to be the first president to lead their nation into
the promise and uncertainty of the post Cold War age, that this is
where his foreign policy legacy would so largely be forged.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Balkans have loomed much larger in this presidency than
anyone would have intended,'' said Daniel Serwer, director of the
Balkans Initiative at the U.S. Institute of Peace, a
government-funded research and policy group in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in fact, has been criticized by some for devoting so
much time and effort to the Balkans, at the expense, these critics
charge, of issues that have greater potential to reshape the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The amount of time and energy and effort that the Clinton
administration has put on the Balkans has just been
extraordinary,'' said Lee Hamilton, former chairman of the House
International Relations Committee. ``You obviously are not spending
huge amounts of time and effort on other areas that really are more
important when you think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, now director of the Woodrow Wilson Institute, a
Washington foreign policy think tank, took a generally dim view of
U.S. military intervention in the Balkans when he served in
Congress as a Democrat from Indiana. More broadly Hamilton, one of
Washington's most respected foreign policy voices, chafes at the
expenditure of vast amounts of political and diplomatic capital on
what he regards as issues of second-tier importance to U.S.
interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the toughest problems that any American policymaker
faces,'' said Hamilton, ``is to keep his eye on the big
relationships and not be diverted from those relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has attached enormous weight to addressing humanitarian
crises that Hamilton regards as ``second tier,'' issues -- Bosnia,
Kosovo, Haiti and Somalia among them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spend so much time on these second-tier issues,'' said
Hamilton, ``and they come, in some ways, to dominate our policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's supporters insist that his attention to humanitarian
issues in general and the Balkans in particular has not sapped
undue resources from the post-Cold War imperatives he inherited.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, said former Clinton foreign policy aide Jeremy Rosner,
his focus on core American ideals has served to strengthen the
country's position in the world and helped to strike a new balance
in U.S. relations with its European allies.
</P>
<P>
   Standing firm against ethnic atrocities in the Balkans, said
Rosner, has reinforced, not undermined, Clinton's wider goal of
broadening the base of democracies and free-market economies across
central and eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he has really made a mark on central and southeast
Europe and trans-Atlantic relations more generally and even
Russia,'' said Rosner, vice president of Greenberg Quilan Research,
a Washington, D.C. polling and political consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Serwer, of the U.S. Institute for Peace, said Clinton has led
the call for a comprehensive international Balkans recovery program
because the bloodshed that has wracked the region since the breakup
of the former Yugoslavia began in 1991 has convinced him that
there's simply no choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good investment, unless you think we can wash our hands
of the Balkans and walk away,'' said Serwer, former U.S. envoy to
Bosnia ``But that's the one thing we've never been able to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
