u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV01-B     07-30 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV01-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS THE NATION READY FOR A KING? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August 01, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Maine _ That bald ex-wrestler in the feather boa and
the eye makeup gets headlines as Minnesota's third-party governor,
but the most effective independent operator in the political game
today may be a lanky, laid-back, mustachioed technocrat up the road
in Augusta, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Angus King, a low-key independent in his second term,
operates under the national media's radar screen, plugging away at
the unglamorous chores that are every governor's daily lot. But
he's just added several notches to his belt as a pro-business
environmentalist, a light-handed but deft administrator, and a
consistent devotee of the middle way.
</P>
<P>
   Maine just won first-place bragging rights in the Children's
Rights Counil ratings as the best state for raising kids, based on
ao statistics. (Obviously, winter temperature was not a factor.)
And the decision King made last fall to reject the federal
government's adoption of the fuel additive MTBE was ratified when
the federal advisory panel acknowledged it harms underground water
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to win one every now and then,'' said the governor.
He won another when the feds approved dismantling of the Edwards
Dam that had interrupted the flow of the Kennebec River for 162
years.
</P>
<P>
   So in addition to the clam strips and the lobstah salad, Maine
is on a roll this year. King's businesslike approach, short on
ideology and long on compromise, goes down well in Maine, which 20
years ago had another independent governor, Jim Longley. With two
Democrats in the US House and two Republicans in the Senate, power
depends on persuading people toward the middle. Senators Olympia
Snowe and Susan Collins are moderates who opposed impeachment and
favor compromise with the Clinton White House in the current tax
debate.
</P>
<P>
   Like most of the other 49 governors, King's popularity is high
because of the strong economy. Unlike the attention-grabbing Jesse
Ventura, the only other independent governor, King is a stranger to
the talk show circuit in D.C. He's ruled out running for the
Senate, and concentrates on his day-to-day tasks. Other than
drought, he faces a serene summer.
</P>
<P>
   About the only things going the wrong way were the van that ran
over prized mystery author Stephen King, now recuperating, and the
Portland Sea Dogs, the minor league ball club that cavorts on a
lovely little ballpark downtown. Through Thursday the Dogs were
winless in eight. As elsewhere, the economy hums, and anyone who
wants work can find it.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's Maine Sunday Telegram carried 25 pages of
help-wanted ads. There are $8-an-hour jobs going begging. Employers
will fit jobs to your schedule. Sunday River is the latest resport
operator to recruit help abroad; The ski operator is hiring in
Australia to augment last year's 1,300 hires.
</P>
<P>
   Summer traffic on the Maine Turnpike is up 7 percent over last
year, triggering six- and seven-mile-long Saturday traffic jams at
the Hampton, N.H., tolls and the pike entry. Traffic is an issue;
the turnpike will be widened to six lanes from four in the 30 miles
between York and Scarborough. Meanwhile, some old-line industrial
jobs in shoes, chicken-plucking, papermaking, and timber melt away.
The new jobs are in call centers, tourism, and high-tech. Fishing
has been badly hit because of declining stocks, but tourism filled
that gap.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to fishing for votes, there seems to be a
slight uptick in the fortunes of third-party candidates in New
England. Ventura may be the poster boy for the corporate media
crew. But in addition to King, there is popular US Representative
Bernie Sanders of Vermont, the peppery lefty who is the only
independent in the House, and Senator Bob Smith of New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, a way-to-the-right conservative, just walked out of the
GOP over beefs about philosophy, guns, abortion, etc. ``I'm the
most reliable Republican in the Senate, you could look it up,''
said Smith as he bailed from what he sees as a rootless passel of
accommodators.
</P>
<P>
   Smith will now take his quixotic _ maybe it's more Sancho
Panza-tic _ presidential campaign into the third-party route. Ross
Perot got 18 percent in '92, half that in '96, and just lost
control over his self-financed Reform Party to Ventura, who's
shopping for a presidential candidate to spend the $12.5 million
available in federal matching funds.
</P>
<P>
   Like everyone else except the majorities in Congress, the Reform
Party is for campaign finance reform and a balanced budget. But,
like the Green Independent Party, which functions as a spoiler in
Maine, the Reformers find it hard to get their cantankerous
membership to follow anywhere in particular.
</P>
<P>
   Maine's Greens last fall promoted nearly 30,000 votes for their
gubernatorial candidate, Pat LaMarche, and they bang away at King
for being insufficiently reformist. But after a decade or more of
big money corrupting the political process in Washington, Maine
voters seem happy to take what they've got for officeholders.
</P>
<P>
   In a year when Congress disemboweled its procedures in a
fruitless impeachment bid, then refused to back the Kosovo air
campaign spearheaded by American air crews, and refuses to do
anything sensible about gun control, no matter how frequent the
firearms massacres, the third-party route looks promising. Cowed by
the NRA and whipped to a froth by the Religious Right, the Sunbelt
conservatives running Congress gave us after the Littleton
shootings a law suggesting we post the Ten Commandements in every
public school. If that's your idea of suitable action, then you
should feel just fine about the current impasse in D.C.
</P>
<P>
   But if Ventura, the Perot crowd, and the disillusioned
everywhere want a third-party candidate for president with a proven
track record as governor, they can do better than Donald Trump
(number two in the Reform Party convention delegate poll, if you
can believe it). They could look to Angus King, who packs no
ideology in his kit bag. Can America be finally ready for a King?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
