<HEADLINE>
.MDNM/ 
 &HT;    MADDOGS-PART1-TEX
</HEADLINE>
  &HT;    AUSTIN, Texas _ They worked hard, played harder. They drank too
much, slept too little, womanized incessantly, and frittered away
days and nights with mind-bending chemicals. They called themselves
``Mad Dogs,'' and they embraced the image with the passion of
mildly deranged journalists and musicians, which they were. Yet
this handful of writers and ``picker poets'' created a significant
body of work, influenced a generation of Texas artists, and changed
for all time the state's music and literary landscape. By MIKE
COCHRAN. (Second of three parts moves today.) Story will move in
``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle categories. 
 
 
(DUPLICATION ALERT: Story also moving in ``l'' lifestyle category) 
TEXAS WRITERS AND MUSICIANS HELPED DEFINE THE SIXTIES AND
SEVENTIES 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE COCHRAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ As recounted by Jay Milner in his lively memoir,
``Confessions of a Maddog,'' the turbulent Sixties was a pivotal
decade for his so-called rabble of Texas writers and musicians.
</P>
<P>
   Milner himself returned to Texas in 1961, the same year Bud
Shrake left the ``Dallas Times Herald'' to write a sports column
for the rival ``Dallas Morning News.'' In 1964, Shrake hit the
journalistic big time, joining Dan Jenkins at ``Sports
Illustrated'' in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The two old Fort Worth cronies soon were socializing with some
of the country's best-known writers, among them George Plimpton,
James Dickey, William Styron and Norman Mailer.
</P>
<P>
   They also crossed paths on occasion with Texans Larry King and
Billie Lee Brammer and ``Harper's'' Editor Willie Morris, the
University of Texas alum who once edited the iconoclastic ``Texas
Observer.'' Morris abandoned Texas and his Mississippi homeland for
New York and wrote about all three in a splendid book, ``North
Toward Home.''
</P>
<P>
   During Morris' celebrated reign at ``Harper's,'' both King and
Shrake were regular contributors, King out of necessity, Shrake
simply showcasing his versatility.
</P>
<P>
   Although Shrake called his New York adventure ``exciting,'' he
soon soured on Manhattan and fled to Austin in 1968. He continued
his association with ``SI'' while writing books and screenplays.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Confessions,'' Milner marveled that Shrake ``somehow
churned out books, screenplays, as-told-to biographies and magazine
pieces _ regardless of the situation at home, the hour or how much
fermented liquid he had managed to swallow the night before.''
</P>
<P>
   Shrake wrote his first three novels in the Sixties: ``Blood
Reckoning'' (1962), ``But Not for Love'' (1964) and ``Blessed
McGill'' (1968).
</P>
<P>
   Back in Dallas, Gary Cartwright had jumped from the ``Times
Herald'' to the ``News'' and was working on his first book, ``The
Hundred Yard War.'' In 1968, after a brief fling as a columnist at
``The Philadelphia Inquirer,'' he said farewell to the newspaper
world and headed to Austin.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Brammer was struggling off and on, mostly off, with
a sequel to his masterpiece, ``The Gay Place,'' and living in a
once-elegant, now crumbling old house known as the Caswell Mansion.
Cartwright insists that Caswell Mansion was to Austin what Gertrude
Stein's salon at 27 Rue de Fleurus was to Paris in the Twenties.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a way station for intellectuals, artists, musicians,
writers, politicians and other power-trippers,'' he wrote in his
latest book, ``HeartWiseGuy.''
</P>
<P>
   If anything, he said, the conversation at Brammer's was even
wittier than at Gertrude's, inspired as it was by pot, speed,
mescaline, acid and peyote.
</P>
<P>
   As the Sixties drew to a close, Willie Nelson and Jerry Jeff
Walker were not yet living in Austin, but they had been in and out
on several occasions and now were headed that way. They would be
followed in short order by other musicians. Cartwright, Brammer and
Shrake were in place, providing Austin a unique writers' colony.
</P>
<P>
   It was a volatile mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything just came together in Austin,'' says David McHam, a
University of Texas at Arlington professor and longtime observer of
the Texas music and literary scene. ``I think that's what happened
with this group. Texas was just waking up.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus was the stage set for the Mad Dog Seventies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the best times to be having a good time in
Austin,'' is the way Jerry Jeff put it.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   In ``Confessions,'' Milner hammers home evidence that it was the
Seventies when ``McMurtry and the other Mad Dogs blossomed into
stars that shone beyond the borders of the Lone Star State.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt McMurtry's national exposure got a tremendous boost
from the movie version of ``The Last Picture Show,'' which was
nominated for an Academy Award as Best Picture in 1971. It lost out
to ``The French Connection.''
</P>
<P>
   McMurtry opened the decade with ``Moving On'' and followed with
``All My Friends Are Going to Be Strangers'' (1972), ``Terms of
Endearment'' (1975) and ``Somebody's Darling'' (1978).
</P>
<P>
   Eight years after the book come out, ``Endearment'' made it to
the big screen. With Shirley MacLaine, Jack Nicholson and Debra
Winger in the starring roles, it won the Oscar for Best Picture.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Dan Jenkins scored a winning touchdown of his own.
After two earlier works of nonfiction, he came out with the widely
and lavishly acclaimed 1972 novel ``Semi-Tough,'' which thrust
halfback Billy Clyde Puckett, teammate Shake Tiller, coach T.J.
Lambert and the ever-lovely Barbara Jane Bookman on an unsuspecting
public.
</P>
<P>
   That was but one of a long-running string of terrific reads that
included 1974's ``Dead Solid Perfect'' and 1976's ``Limo,'' which
he wrote with Shrake. On their heels would come ``Baja Oklahoma,''
``Life Its Ownself,'' ``You Gotta Play Hurt'' and ``Fast Copy.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   He was a New Yorker named Ronald Clyde Crosby, but by the time
he arrived in Texas for keeps in 1971, he was vagabond singer Jerry
Jeff Walker and widely known for a wastrel's tale of a wino and his
dead dog.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Bojangles'' was inspired by one of Jerry Jeff's recurring
visits to the nation's jails, this time in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   His long-suffering friends called him Jacky Jack Doubletrouble,
and for years he wandered around in a crazy daze, rarely sleeping
and growing surly when others did, recounts Larry King in ``None
but a Blockhead.''
</P>
<P>
   ``His main hobby was causing riots,'' King asserts, recalling
the time Jacky Jack walked into a motel room full of drunken
cowboys during an Oklahoma rodeo and inspired them to beat him half
to death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry Jeff looked up from the floor, while dripping blood and
surrounded by broken furniture, and sneered: `Y'all ain't so
bleepin' tough. I been beat up worse than this by motorcycle
gangs.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his hard-core carousing, or maybe because of it, Jerry
Jeff Jacky Jack was a leader in the musical revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, an Austin writer and music publicist, describes a 1972
album, recorded in a primitive downtown Austin studio, as a
declaration of Walker's musical independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Austin, he found a creative community that let him mix
folk, rock, country, and anything else that caught his ear,'' Davis
wrote in a 1998 profile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Along with fellow Austinites like Willie Nelson, Asleep at the
Wheel and Michael Martin Murphey, he became one of the arbiters of
the `progressive country' movement of the mid-1970s.''
</P>
<P>
   In those days, Walker and a handful of ``outlaws'' were
resisting Nashville's stranglehold on C&AMP;W music, and succeeding.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able to get the first independent record deals and use
our own bands,'' he says today. ``We were trying to break the mold,
and we didn't mind if our records were a little rough.''
</P>
<P>
   The term they used at the time was ``ragged but right,'' Walker
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means we were winging it, catching the spark and the
camaraderie and bringing it off in an offhanded manner as opposed
to the slick layered sound of Nashville.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis recalls that in 1973, when Jerry Jeff arrived at the
famous Hill Country saloon in Luckenbach to record ``Viva
Terlingua,'' his collection of free-lance Austin pickers had
coalesced into the Lost Gonzo Band.
</P>
<P>
   ``A celebrated ensemble in their own right, the Gonzos would
flesh out Jerry Jeff's songs and enthrall audiences for the next
four years and four more albums,'' Davis wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But Jerry Jeff's Mad Dog tendencies were becoming the stuff of
legends. If he did show up for a concert date, he wasn't always
sure what town he was in.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Blockhead,'' Larry King remembers the night at Austin's
Castle Creek Saloon when Jerry Jeff stumbled on stage three hours
late and was greeted by catcalls and obscenities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry Jeff gave as good as he got and then some,'' King says.
``When he wearied of cussing, he grabbed a live armadillo from a
bystander and flung it toward ringside tables.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he snatched the microphone and invited everyone to come
onstage and fight.
</P>
<P>
   Some did.
</P>
<P>
   After order was restored, Walker began singing, through a split
lip, a dirty little ditty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Halfway through it, he began to stagger backward and didn't
stop until he'd crushed his poor drummer's equipment to
smithereens,'' King says. ``He lay there, snoring, while management
churlishly chunked refunds and caught abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their many successes, that scene could be the trademark
of the Mad Dog Seventies.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   PART 1: In the beginning: lyrics, literature and lunacy.
</P>
<P>
   PART 2: Wasted days, wasted nights, surprising success.
</P>
<P>
   PART 3: Looking back: Remorse and regret ... but not much.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Some additional good did come from the Mexican madness. Gent
started his thinly disguised satire of the Dallas Cowboys, ``North
Dallas Forty,'' in Durango. He would finish it while staying with
Cartwright during his six-month Texas Institute of Letters
fellowship on the Dobie Ranch near Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Before the decade ended, this, too, would become a major
Hollywood movie, starring Nick Nolte. Nolte wasn't a Mad Dog, but
he acted like one, in the movie and in real life.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   As the Seventies opened, Willie Nelson was living in Nashville,
the so-called Music City, and had just penned a new song: ``What
Can They Do to Me Now?''
</P>
<P>
   Two days before Christmas 1970, he found out: His Tennessee home
burned down.
</P>
<P>
   Although the exact time period is a mite hazy, at some point
before leaving Nashville, Willie tried to kill himself, according
to a story Cartwright tells about his longtime boozing buddy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went out one night and laid down in the middle of a
snow-covered road and waited for a car to come by and run him
over,'' Cartwright says. ``The car didn't come by, so he didn't get
run over.''
</P>
<P>
   Willie had had it with Nashville. He loaded up his guitar, his
family and his band, and headed to Austin, a couple of hours south
of his birthplace in Abbott. He soon found a second home at a hot
new rock/country music palace, Armadillo World Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, Nelson and the Armadillo had united country
and rock, ropers and dopers, longhairs and rednecks.
</P>
<P>
   Texas audiences obviously were ready for Willie's rock-oriented
country music and thoughtful lyrics. He signed with Atlantic
Records, and in 1973 recorded his breakthrough album, ``Shotgun
Willie.''
</P>
<P>
   He followed that with ``Phrases and Stages,'' an even bigger
seller and a story in itself given the turbulent times in the
recording industry.
</P>
<P>
   With borderline indignation, Milner points out that Nashville at
the time was using its own bands and arrangements and ``making
everything sound the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Willie simply didn't fit that mold. Any mold, for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told him they didn't want him to sing,'' Milner says.
``They said he was out of meter, that no bands could play with him.
He was out of meter, all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Sinatra and Crosby were out of meter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he'd have done like they told him in Nashville, he'd still
be up there in the hills writing songs,'' snorts Milner. ``There
would be no Willie.''
</P>
<P>
   Fellow Mad Dog Billy Joe Shaver, a Corsicana native, also was a
major player in the outlaw country movement, but less as an
entertainer than as a songwriter. Dave Ferman, the Star-Telegram's
pop music critic, points out that nine of the 10 songs on Waylon
Jennings' seminal 1973 LP ``Honky Tonk Heroes'' _ ``a defining
moment of the outlaw movement'' _ were Shaver's.
</P>
<P>
   During this period, the Texas music scene was at a pivotal
point, with a new breed of country musicians coming of age, Milner
writes in ``Confessions.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a generation ``young enough and sensitive enough in the
rocking Sixties to know that country music could be better if it
had more than three chords and delved deeper with its lyrics than a
minnow's plunge.''
</P>
<P>
   That special ingredient, Milner says, was provided by the music
and the presence of Willie Nelson and his ``family'' of band
members.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, Nelson recorded ``Red Headed Stranger'' for Columbia.
It was a country concept album that stunned just about everyone by
yielding a pop hit, ``Blue Eyes Crying in the Rain.''
</P>
<P>
   A year later, RCA packaged some older Nelson material with songs
by Waylon Jennings, Jessi Colter and Tompall Glaser on one disc,
``Wanted: The Outlaws.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It became the first million-selling country album and sparked
a musical revolution,'' recalls Nelson biographer John T. Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Milner put it this way:
</P>
<P>
   ``His physical appearance, his tolerance for sincere ideas
coming from all directions, even his progressive ideas regarding
certain mind-altering potions _ caused Willie to be seen as a
rebel, and this appealed to the young rock and roll crowd. And,
amazingly, it didn't turn away his older fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Milner was at the center of the revolution with Willie and
others and chronicled those ``exhilarating times'' for various
publications. He also published the programs for Nelson's
rollicking Fourth of July picnics.
</P>
<P>
   ``... It was _ looking back on it _ inevitable that Shrake,
Cartwright and the other writers I knew were becoming friends with
the Austin-based picker poets _ Willie and Jerry Jeff in
particular,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was inevitable because they were all cut from the same
cloth.''
</P>
<P>
   A reporter recently asked Shrake what it was that brought the
writers and singers together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whiskey,'' grinned Shrake. ``We were playing in the same
joints they were playing in.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   Back home, Willie, Waylon, Jerry Jeff and a handful of Texas
songwriters such as Billy Joe Shaver, Townes Van Zandt and Ray
Wylie Hubbard were making serious sounds in and out of Texas. It
was Hubbard who gave the rebel movement its unofficial anthem, ``Up
Against the Wall, Redneck Mother,'' but it was Jerry Jeff's
recording that made it so wildly popular.
</P>
<P>
   Like King and Brammer, Milner had scratched out a meager living
with his writing through much of the previous decade. But he did
establish a good reputation as a journalism teacher at Texas
Christian University in the Sixties.
</P>
<P>
   By 1970, Milner was acting chairman of the Southern Methodist
University journalism department, rescuing a program that had
fallen on harsh times and was in danger of being discontinued. In a
risky move, he lured Pete Gent and Brammer to Dallas for part-time
teaching duties, and, of course, the students loved them.
</P>
<P>
   Within a short time, SMU was sweeping many of the major student
journalism awards in the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   Less successful but probably more entertaining were Milner's
later ventures: starting up a well-received but ill-fated country
and western magazine and promoting the rise of C&AMP;W's newest
superstar, Willie Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   Careerwise, things were looking up for Larry King in the
Seventies even before the staggering financial success of ``The
Best Little Whorehouse in Texas,'' which was based on an article he
wrote for ``Playboy.''
</P>
<P>
   Although a college dropout, he suddenly found himself in high
demand as a teaching fellow at such lofty institutions as Harvard,
Princeton and Duke.
</P>
<P>
   King earned a National Book Award nomination in 1972 for
``Confessions of a White Racist'' and won the Stanley Walker
Journalism Award in 1973 for one of his magazine articles.
</P>
<P>
   His ``Whorehouse'' success would one day make him a millionaire.
It also freed him from the demands of the ``magazine treadmill,''
and he since has penned several plays, including Texas-based ``The
Night Hank Williams Died'' and ``The Golden Shadows Old West
Museum,'' scripted from an award-winning short story by Mike
Blackman, the former editor of the ``Fort Worth Star-Telegram,''
now free-lancing in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Austin, Cartwright and Shrake were as busy as ever.
</P>
<P>
   Cartwright followed ``The Hundred Yard War'' with the
fictionalized ``Thin Ice'' in 1972 and hit his stride in 1979 with
``Blood Will Tell,'' the second of four books on the Cullen Davis
murder case in Fort Worth. The 1997 ABC miniseries based on his
book starred Peter Strauss as Cullen and Heather Locklear as his
estranged wife, Priscilla, and appeared in reruns last month.
</P>
<P>
   Later, after 1982's ``Confessions of a Washed-Up Sportswriter,''
Cartwright took another shot at true crime in 1984 with ``Dirty
Dealing,'' the story of El Paso's star-crossed Chagra family and
the murder of a federal judge in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   In the Seventies, Shrake was researching a book on Willie
Nelson, but that biography would emerge some years later. His
published books at the time included ``Strange Peaches'' (1972) and
``Peter Arbiter'' (1973).
</P>
<P>
   Shrake also was churning out screenplays, two of which were
produced in the early '70s. The first, co-written with Cartwright,
was ``J.W. Coop'' and starred Cliff Robertson as an aging rodeo
cowboy.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was ``Dime Box,'' which staggered to the screen as
``Kid Blue'' in 1973 despite an invasion by a gaggle of Mad Dogs
who arrived on the film set in Mexico in a van driven by Shrake and
a Winnebago driven by Pete Gent. This would become yet another
benchmark adventure in the checkered history of Mad Dog Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, both vehicles, decorated with signs
proclaiming ``Mad Dog Production Company,'' reached Durango
overflowing with felonious pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then, you didn't have a drug problem until you ran out,''
Shrake recalls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kid Blue'' starred Dennis Hopper, still riding high from the
stunning success of ``Easy Rider'' and himself seemingly on a
collision course with chemical suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Hopper, Mexico and the Mad Dogs were a mercurial mix and, in
time, remarkably productive despite themselves. Before the filming
of ``Kid Blue'' ran its woozy course, substantially over budget
because of Mad Dog shenanigans, Shrake, Cartwright and Gent had
recruited Hopper and film director Marvin Schwarz as full-fledged
Dogs. The membership swelled with the inclusion of cast members
Peter Boyle, Warren Oates, Howard Hesseman and Janice Rule.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on one's tolerance for decadence and depravity,
Cartwright's account of the filming of ``Kid Blue'' may be as
comical as anything he's written.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dennis Hopper's career was almost wrecked during the craziness
that swallowed Durango,'' Cartwright reported.
</P>
<P>
   Just why so many Mad Dogs were in Durango for the filming is a
bit of a mystery, although Cartwright would claim that he and
Shrake were writing a screenplay for Schwarz.
</P>
<P>
   And, in fact, 20 years later, CBS produced a version of the
Durango script as a made-for-TV movie, ``Pair of Aces.'' Kris
Kristofferson and Willie Nelson landed the leading roles.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, a year later there was a sequel, ``Another Pair of
Aces.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
