</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990730.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 15:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0005 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MADDOGS-PART2-2500(4T     07-30 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MADDOGS-PART2-2500(4TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
.MDNM/ 
 &HT;    MADDOGS-PART1-TEX
</HEADLINE>
  &HT;    AUSTIN, Texas _ They worked hard, played harder. They drank too
much, slept too little, womanized incessantly, and frittered away
days and nights with mind-bending chemicals. They called themselves
``Mad Dogs,'' and they embraced the image with the passion of
mildly deranged journalists and musicians, which they were. Yet
this handful of writers and ``picker poets'' created a significant
body of work, influenced a generation of Texas artists, and changed
for all time the state's music and literary landscape. By MIKE
COCHRAN. (Second of three parts moves today.) Story will move in
``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle categories. 
 
 
(DUPLICATION ALERT: Story also moving in ``l'' lifestyle category) 
TEXAS WRITERS AND MUSICIANS HELPED DEFINE THE SIXTIES AND
SEVENTIES 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE COCHRAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ As recounted by Jay Milner in his lively memoir,
``Confessions of a Maddog,'' the turbulent Sixties was a pivotal
decade for his so-called rabble of Texas writers and musicians.
</P>
<P>
   Milner himself returned to Texas in 1961, the same year Bud
Shrake left the ``Dallas Times Herald'' to write a sports column
for the rival ``Dallas Morning News.'' In 1964, Shrake hit the
journalistic big time, joining Dan Jenkins at ``Sports
Illustrated'' in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The two old Fort Worth cronies soon were socializing with some
of the country's best-known writers, among them George Plimpton,
James Dickey, William Styron and Norman Mailer.
</P>
<P>
   They also crossed paths on occasion with Texans Larry King and
Billie Lee Brammer and ``Harper's'' Editor Willie Morris, the
University of Texas alum who once edited the iconoclastic ``Texas
Observer.'' Morris abandoned Texas and his Mississippi homeland for
New York and wrote about all three in a splendid book, ``North
Toward Home.''
</P>
<P>
   During Morris' celebrated reign at ``Harper's,'' both King and
Shrake were regular contributors, King out of necessity, Shrake
simply showcasing his versatility.
</P>
<P>
   Although Shrake called his New York adventure ``exciting,'' he
soon soured on Manhattan and fled to Austin in 1968. He continued
his association with ``SI'' while writing books and screenplays.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Confessions,'' Milner marveled that Shrake ``somehow
churned out books, screenplays, as-told-to biographies and magazine
pieces _ regardless of the situation at home, the hour or how much
fermented liquid he had managed to swallow the night before.''
</P>
<P>
   Shrake wrote his first three novels in the Sixties: ``Blood
Reckoning'' (1962), ``But Not for Love'' (1964) and ``Blessed
McGill'' (1968).
</P>
<P>
   Back in Dallas, Gary Cartwright had jumped from the ``Times
Herald'' to the ``News'' and was working on his first book, ``The
Hundred Yard War.'' In 1968, after a brief fling as a columnist at
``The Philadelphia Inquirer,'' he said farewell to the newspaper
world and headed to Austin.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Brammer was struggling off and on, mostly off, with
a sequel to his masterpiece, ``The Gay Place,'' and living in a
once-elegant, now crumbling old house known as the Caswell Mansion.
Cartwright insists that Caswell Mansion was to Austin what Gertrude
Stein's salon at 27 Rue de Fleurus was to Paris in the Twenties.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a way station for intellectuals, artists, musicians,
writers, politicians and other power-trippers,'' he wrote in his
latest book, ``HeartWiseGuy.''
</P>
<P>
   If anything, he said, the conversation at Brammer's was even
wittier than at Gertrude's, inspired as it was by pot, speed,
mescaline, acid and peyote.
</P>
<P>
   As the Sixties drew to a close, Willie Nelson and Jerry Jeff
Walker were not yet living in Austin, but they had been in and out
on several occasions and now were headed that way. They would be
followed in short order by other musicians. Cartwright, Brammer and
Shrake were in place, providing Austin a unique writers' colony.
</P>
<P>
   It was a volatile mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything just came together in Austin,'' says David McHam, a
University of Texas at Arlington professor and longtime observer of
the Texas music and literary scene. ``I think that's what happened
with this group. Texas was just waking up.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus was the stage set for the Mad Dog Seventies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the best times to be having a good time in
Austin,'' is the way Jerry Jeff put it.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   In ``Confessions,'' Milner hammers home evidence that it was the
Seventies when ``McMurtry and the other Mad Dogs blossomed into
stars that shone beyond the borders of the Lone Star State.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt McMurtry's national exposure got a tremendous boost
from the movie version of ``The Last Picture Show,'' which was
nominated for an Academy Award as Best Picture in 1971. It lost out
to ``The French Connection.''
</P>
<P>
   McMurtry opened the decade with ``Moving On'' and followed with
``All My Friends Are Going to Be Strangers'' (1972), ``Terms of
Endearment'' (1975) and ``Somebody's Darling'' (1978).
</P>
<P>
   Eight years after the book come out, ``Endearment'' made it to
the big screen. With Shirley MacLaine, Jack Nicholson and Debra
Winger in the starring roles, it won the Oscar for Best Picture.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Dan Jenkins scored a winning touchdown of his own.
After two earlier works of nonfiction, he came out with the widely
and lavishly acclaimed 1972 novel ``Semi-Tough,'' which thrust
halfback Billy Clyde Puckett, teammate Shake Tiller, coach T.J.
Lambert and the ever-lovely Barbara Jane Bookman on an unsuspecting
public.
</P>
<P>
   That was but one of a long-running string of terrific reads that
included 1974's ``Dead Solid Perfect'' and 1976's ``Limo,'' which
he wrote with Shrake. On their heels would come ``Baja Oklahoma,''
``Life Its Ownself,'' ``You Gotta Play Hurt'' and ``Fast Copy.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to crazy stuff, the lakeside group reached at
least one unanimous conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the best time to do it is when you're young,'' said
Walker. ``It's like going to New York. Was it exciting coming into
Manhattan? It was when I was young. ... One time we burned up three
limos.''
</P>
<P>
   Cartwright dreamily remembered one of his ``great New York
moments'' of yesteryear.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a snowy night and I'm taking a cab to Elaine's, and I
look over and there's this couple trudging through the deep snow. A
little short Greek guy and a tall black-headed woman. I realize
it's Aristotle Onassis and Jackie O., and I'm there in a cab and
waving at 'em as I go by.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm thinking, `Is this a great country or what?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Back then, Cartwright said, he and the other writers were
actually performing when out drinking and carousing, and at the
same time expending creative energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're 30 or 40 years old, you've got a lot of creative
energy. I can write a lot better now than I could then, but I don't
have the creative energy I left on the dance floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Health problems disrupted Shrake's lifestyle at a much younger
age, but, like Walker, he got in his licks: ``When I quit the heavy
stuff and the whiskey, red meat and booze, I said, `Well, it wasn't
like you didn't get your share.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Even Jerry Jeff conceded that while he wouldn't change much,
he's glad he got the craziness out of his system in his younger
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't want to spend my whole youth being real busy, and
then decide I want to go with some wild chick to Las Vegas and get
some coke and lock myself up in a room at 57 years of age.''
</P>
<P>
   His old picker pal is slowing down also.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Willie at 65,'' the 1998 ``Texas Monthly'' article,
Cartwright told of sharing a joint with Nelson in his bus, the
``Honeysuckle Rose,'' before a Thanksgiving holiday concert in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to be a hermit, but I'm better off staying out
here by myself,'' Willie told him. ``Too many temptations. In the
old days we'd stay in town after a gig and start drinking and
chasing women, and some of the band would end up in jail or
divorced.''
</P>
<P>
   That's when he started leaving right after each concert, often
driving his bus all night.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it wasn't for the bus and this weed, I'd be at the bar
right now, doing serious harm to myself,'' he told Cartwright.
</P>
<P>
   So despite the good times and the many Mad Dog successes, there
is, if not full-time remorse, serious second thoughts and some
regret about the time and toll of those ancient wasted days and
nights.
</P>
<P>
   At the lake that sparkling spring day, Shrake touched on those
shadows of his life. ``I think about it a lot. There is no doubt in
my mind I could have done at least five more movies.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone brought up a segment in Cartwright's ``HeartWiseGuy'' in
which he relates a conversation with Shrake and Dennis Hopper
several years ago at Austin's Raw Deal, once one of the Dogs'
favorite watering holes.
</P>
<P>
   Shrake, who hadn't had a drink in years, confessed to his
friends: ``I wake up at three in the morning revisiting those
places and remembering our drunken adventures. Only now they don't
seem funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Cartwright told of the ``decadelong dead spot'' that blighted
his memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure I must have been around in the Seventies and
Eighties,'' Cartwright said, ``because I see my name on books,
screenplays and magazine articles. But it's as though someone
mailed them to me in a box with no return address.''
</P>
<P>
   As the lakeside session ended that day, the sun dropped into the
hills that snuggle up to Austin, and the old Dogs began drifting
away, one by one, timetables to abide by. It was nothing like the
old days, and one could not help but recall a passage from
Cartwright's book. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what I don't see that fills me with regret: all the work
that was never attempted because my body and brain were pickled in
the pursuit of ... that's the rub; I can't remember what I was
pursuing.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   PART 1: In the beginning: lyrics, literature and lunacy.
</P>
<P>
   PART 2: Wasted days, wasted nights, surprising success.
</P>
<P>
   PART 3: Looking back: Remorse and regret ... but not much.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   He said he always wanted to live beyond the boundaries. Like
Willie Nelson maintains, you pick a road and go for it. ``I don't
think Willie figures there was much he could change one way or
another,'' Walker said. ``He just took what's been given him and
made the most of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Willie's goal was to play music as long as he could, and he's
been able to do that, Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least I was going to have some fun,'' he continued. ``I
kept hearing stories about how they rip you off and take everything
away, and I said, `Well, I'm going to get my licks in before it's
done.' ''
</P>
<P>
   One of those licks, they recalled, occurred many years ago when
he and Willie were to share a stage in Chattanooga, Tenn. Susan
Walker and the Cartwrights arrived separately to help Jerry Jeff
celebrate his birthday.
</P>
<P>
   The only issue not in dispute about that night is that the cops
arrested Walker on stage and hauled him off to jail.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Jeff's story: Tired of flying, he bought a 1954 Lincoln,
which was so slow the trip took longer than expected. Or, possibly,
he took a ``short cut'' and got lost. Either way, he failed to make
the show on time but insisted on taking the stage anyway.
</P>
<P>
   That's when, where and why the cops got him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the few times I got thrown in jail when I wasn't
drinking,'' he claimed. ``I got arrested for being late.''
</P>
<P>
   Nodding, winking and scoffing, the lake crowd remembered it
differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think,'' said Susan Walker, smiling, ``you left out the part
about why you got lost.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you weren't drunk, you were stoned,'' added Cartwright.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went back to the hotel that night with Willie,'' Susan
said, ``and Willie called down to get him out of jail. He said,
`This is Willie Nelson,' and they hung up on him.''
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, they retrieved their wayward troubadour from
the drunk tank.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was on his birthday,'' Susan said, sighing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next day was my birthday,'' Jerry Jeff shot back, trying to
keep things in proper perspective.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the new Jerry Jeff looks and acts differently, he's
lost none of what biographer John Davis calls the ``unalloyed,
straightforward simplicity'' that has been the trademark of his
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``The essence of his music is still distilled one night at a
time, one stage at a time, from Maine to Malibu,'' insists Davis,
an Austin writer and publicist. ``... His music _ elastic,
unqualifiable, uniquely empathic _ has retained the power to touch
two generations of listeners.
</P>
<P>
   ``He remains one of America's musical landmarks.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   And then, they pointed out, there's Willie, who Cartwright
maintained is quite possibly the greatest who ever lived. At age
26, in a single week, Nelson penned three classics: ``Crazy,''
``Night Life'' and ``Funny How Time Slips Away.''
</P>
<P>
   Cartwright pointed out that Patsy Cline's cut of ``Crazy''
eventually won an award as the most-played song on jukeboxes ever
and that Ray Price adopted ``Night Life'' as his theme song. What's
more, Faron Young's version of Nelson's ``Hello Walls'' sold more
than 2 million copies.
</P>
<P>
   After triggering a musical revolution, Nelson changed course
again with his ``Stardust'' album of pop standards that roosted on
the country charts deep into the Eighties.
</P>
<P>
   He invaded Hollywood, appearing in 30 movies, among them
``Red-Headed Stranger,'' ``Honeysuckle Rose,'' ``The Electric
Horseman,'' ``Songwriter,'' ``Thief,'' and ``Barbarosa.''
</P>
<P>
   During this period, he also cut records with such eclectic
talents as Julio Iglesias, Bob Dylan, Dolly Parton and Ray Charles,
and with country-and-western peers such as Kris Kristofferson, Ray
Price, Webb Pierce, Merle Haggard, George Jones, Waylon Jennings,
Faron Young and Hank Snow.
</P>
<P>
   Willie, his fellow Dogs concluded, has proved even to this day
that he is as adaptable as he is durable.
</P>
<P>
   And it seems only appropriate that a fellow Mad Dog, Shrake,
would collaborate with Nelson for ``Willie: An Autobiography,'' one
of three such projects that carried Shrake into the Nineties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bootlegger's Boy'' profiled Barry Switzer before his
tumultuous tenure with the Dallas Cowboys, and Shrake followed that
with a surprisingly hot seller, ``Harvey Penick's Little Red
Book,'' a golfer's guide to an improved game. He did all this while
pounding out screenplays and embracing his true love, novels.
Shrake's latest is set in Austin in the 1870s and will be out soon.
</P>
<P>
   And, finally, there's Cartwright, who simply has become one of
the best magazine writers in America. Besides co-authoring an
occasional screenplay with Shrake, he has written seven books.
</P>
<P>
   In a ``Texas Monthly'' article last year, Cartwright told of
reminiscing with Willie Nelson about life's vagaries and how the
two old Dogs agreed that attitude is surely the key.
</P>
<P>
   ``However you want things to be, create them in your own mind,
and they'll be that way,'' Willie assured him.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson was just back from the Bahamas, where, Cartwright
reminded him, 20 years earlier he had been thrown in jail for
smoking pot and banished from the island for life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was so happy to be free of that damned jail, he jumped off
the curb and broke his foot,'' Cartwright said.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   The lakeside retrospective shifted off and on to Larry McMurtry,
and Walker compared McMurtry's books with Anthony Quinn's movies.
``He either made your favorite movie or your unfavorite,'' he said
of the actor. ``McMurtry had either hits or misses.''
</P>
<P>
   McMurtry's latest novel, ``Duane's Depressed,'' received some
excellent reviews, but in a recent interview, the enigmatic author
seemed less interested in literary notices about his 22nd novel
than with his ever-expanding bookstore in Archer City, which he
named Booked Up.
</P>
<P>
   In that interview with ``The Washington Post,'' he was described
as ``Texas' best writer.'' The article pointed out that in a recent
``New York Review of Books,'' Thomas Powers endorsed McMurtry as
``author of a longer stream of good novels than perhaps any man
since Anthony Trollope.''
</P>
<P>
   What seems certain is that McMurtry's long-running success
served both to underscore Texas as a worthy literary subject and to
inspire a generation of the state's up-and-coming writers, which
the Mad Dogs most assuredly were in the Sixties.
</P>
<P>
   As always, the conversation soon turned to Blackie Sherrod, the
``Morning News'' sports columnist for whom Shrake and Cartwright
once worked, and to their longtime colleague Dan Jenkins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We grew up under Blackie,'' said Shrake, at the same time
confessing that they tried hard to keep their mentor in the dark
about most of their nocturnal activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't tell Blackie anything. It would be like going home
and telling your mother, `Mama, guess what I did last night?' We
were scared to death of Blackie.''
</P>
<P>
   Cartwright joked also that ``Jenkins wouldn't have anything to
do with us,'' but indicated that was only after he got rich and
famous and ``became a Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   They laughed again at the reunion in 1987, the Austin affair
when Jenkins, Shrake, Cartwright and Larry King were immortalized
on Austin's Sixth Street ``Walk of Stars.'' Blackie pointed out
that Shrake, Cartwright and Jenkins all started out as
sportswriters but had gone on to loftier subjects such as dope
smuggling, chicken-fried steak and mass murder.
</P>
<P>
   Their lakeside banter that day turned to their aging
compatriots, most of whom were scattered around Texas and still in
hot pursuit of the killer phrase and perfect lyric.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins is back in Fort Worth, settling into a new home there
and putting the final flourishes on a Southwest Conference
remembrance. He also is working on another golf novel. His columns
still appear monthly in ``Golf Digest,'' and he continues to report
on the major tournaments for the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Just out to mixed reviews is his newest novel, ``Rude
Behavior,'' another bawdy romp with Billy Clyde Puckett and
friends. Jenkins calls it his favorite and some critics agree.
</P>
<P>
   Pronouncing it Jenkins' best and funniest work yet, David
Burgin, writing in Milwaukee's ``Journal Sentinel,'' described Dan
as a ``national treasure, one of America's great humorists.'' He
called his book a ``monument to courage.''
</P>
<P>
   Courage?
</P>
<P>
   ``It dares to tackle political correctness,'' explains Burgin.
``Jenkins doesn't just tackle it. He blitzes it, slams it to the
turf and then jumps on it about a hundred times as if to make
certain this disguised American evil, this national insecurity,
this tyranny of thought and language is dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Shucks, said Jerry Jeff, Dan was doing the same thing 26 years
ago with ``Semi-Tough,'' his breakthrough novel: ``He didn't know
any better, so he broke all the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   The same could probably be said about all the Mad Dogs. As the
century moves toward a close, they just keep on keeping on.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1986, Walker has produced 10 albums on his own independent
record label, Tried &AMP; True Music. The most recent, ``Cowboy Boots &AMP;
Bathin' Suits,'' was recorded at his second home in Ambergris Cay,
an island off the coast of the Central American country of Belize.
</P>
<P>
   Another album on his independent label will be released this
fall in conjunction with his autobiography, ``Gypsy Songman.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't read it yet,'' said Susan, Jerry Jeff's manager and
president of Tried &AMP; True. ``But Bud wrote the introduction, and
Jimmy Buffet is writing the foreward to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``... He tells it all, from the time he started hitchhiking out
of New York up until the time he started sending our children out
into the world.''
</P>
<P>
   In shorts, shades and straw hat, the new Jerry Jeff on this day
looks not at all like the old liquored-up, brawling outlaw who
spent many a night sobering up in rural America's finest drunk
tanks.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike many of his fellow Dogs, Walker, at 57, says there
may have been a trace of method in the old madness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think sometimes the carousing, the drinking, gave me the
courage to do a few things I might have rationalized away in a more
sober moment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I knew then what I know now, well, I don't know. I had my
chance, and this is the route I chose to take.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
