<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF YOU'RE HAPPY AND YOU KNOW IT ...
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OK. Let's all be happy.
</P>
<P>
   That's a hard thing to do these days, but let's make an effort
anyway. Say it: ``I'm happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Now let's try that together on Aug. 8, the day the Secret
Society of Happy People would like to designate as ``National Admit
You're Happy Day.''
</P>
<P>
   Just the thought of a happy day gets me all worked up. It's the
same feeling I get when I pull my car into the driveway and see my
daughters spilling from the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mommy!'' they scream at the top of their voices. ``Mommy!''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes our reunion _ after just eight hours _ is so intense
that it takes me a half-hour to untangle myself and walk into the
house. I have a lot of moments like that, so full of happiness I
have to pinch myself.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not bragging. I believe, with Pam Johnson, that we don't
share enough of those moments with others.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is the founder of the Secret Society. She believes that
somewhere between the Ed Sullivan and Jerry Springer shows, our
conversations have lost the language of happiness; that we're more
receptive to listening to one another whine than to hearing about
the things that give us reason to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were times this year that Jerry Springer had higher
ratings than Oprah,'' Johnson says.
</P>
<P>
   To counter life's doom and gloom, Johnson started the happy
society a year ago, and more than 100,000 people have embraced its
message.
</P>
<P>
   To celebrate the first anniversary of the Secret Society and
encourage people to spread their cheer, the society is hoping the
governors of our 50 states will declare next Sunday ``National
Admit You're Happy Day.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the nation's governors haven't been too
receptive, which is why Johnson isn't entirely happy. When we
talked Monday, only 15 governors had agreed to declare Aug. 8 a
happy holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen earned Johnson's ``stick in the mud'' or ``parade
raining'' titles by denying the proclamation request. Fellow Texan
and presidential hopeful George W. Bush made Johnson's list of
``undecided'' governors.
</P>
<P>
   My first thought is, what harm would it do to ask your
constituents to be happy? It might seem like a small thing, but
sometimes in our rush to make ends meet, to get the kids to piano
lessons or to the next soccer game, we don't have time to explore
our feelings.
</P>
<P>
   There's no time, for instance, to enjoy a beautiful sunrise or
the smell of coffee perking or the kids laughing in the next room.
We take the little things our mate does for us for granted, and we
forget that there are small pleasures we can bring to their lives.
They don't cost anything. They just make the other person feel good
_ feel loved, feel happy.
</P>
<P>
   I can't recall a time when I didn't experience such moments,
however brief. even in the midst of pain, joy has been the center
of my being.
</P>
<P>
   I've always tried to be like the apostle Paul, content in any
situation. And like Job, knowing that we should not expect to
receive only good at the hand of God.
</P>
<P>
   I understand when Johnson says that she is not asking people to
go into denial. She knows there are times when happiness doesn't
seem possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't tell people to pretend to be happy,'' she said.
``But if you are happy, talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Gracie Bonds Staples is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7791, or e-mail:
gbs(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
