r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN     07-30 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSECUTED EARLY ENGLISH BAPTISTS MADE THE ULTIMATE SACRIFICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OXFORD, England _ One thing about England: It is full of
surprises.
</P>
<P>
   I'm here at Regents Park College, a part of Oxford University,
for three weeks of study about church history with a group of Texas
seminarians.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise came when I attended the New Road Baptist Church in
Oxford on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   During coffee after the service, professor Larry Kreitzer from
Regents Park College introduced me to a distinguished-looking
gentleman, Barrington R. White.
</P>
<P>
   I knew the man I was talking to was a retired Oxford professor.
He was full of wit and gladly answered several of my questions
about English Baptist beginnings.
</P>
<P>
   What I did not know, and learned later, is that White is
considered by many to be the greatest living authority on English
Baptist history.
</P>
<P>
   White is considered ``Mr. Baptist'' in England and is the
retired principal, meaning president, of Regents Park College,
where I am taking courses in a program led by faculty from
Southwestern Baptist Theological Seminary in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   A large painting of White looks down on me each day from the
front wall of Helwys Hall, the name of the refectory at the
college, where our meals are served each day.
</P>
<P>
   In my conversation with White, I asked him what contributions
English Baptists have made to the cause of religious liberty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've provided a lot of martyrs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And he was not joking.
</P>
<P>
   The Baptist movement as we know it, including the giant Southern
Baptist Convention in the United States, was created by dissenters
from established faiths in the early 1600s. And those early
nonconformists often paid with their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Helwys, whom historians credit with establishing the
first Baptist church on English soil in the Spitalfield section of
London in 1612, died for his dissent in Newgate Prison. (He was not
executed but died in jail, where he was sent for defying state
church practices.)
</P>
<P>
   We know that people other than Baptists have died for their
faith.
</P>
<P>
   Just in front of Regents Park College is a monument honoring
three Anglican church leaders, including Thomas Cranmer, who were
burned at the stake.
</P>
<P>
   They refused to recant their allegiance to the Church of England
during the short and murderous reign of Mary Tudor, the Roman
Catholic daughter of Henry VIII.
</P>
<P>
   More than 300 people were executed during the time of ``Bloody
Mary,'' including about 200 Anabaptists who, like later Baptists,
rejected infant baptism, said Karen Bullock, the Southwestern
Seminary professor who is teaching my Baptist history course at
Oxford.
</P>
<P>
   Catholics have had an even longer history of people martyred
because of their convictions.
</P>
<P>
   The Baptist martyrs mainly died as a result of laws designed to
force compliance with Church of England practices.
</P>
<P>
   Baptists were not even allowed to attend Oxford University until
the 1680s. Regents Park College, founded in 1810, is the only
Baptist-related college connected to Oxford University.
</P>
<P>
   Cambridge University, the chief rival of Oxford, allowed
Baptists to enroll much earlier, White told me.
</P>
<P>
   But White, ever loyal to Oxford, said there were strings
attached when Baptists were allowed to attend Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would not let them graduate until they became
Anglicans,'' he said. ``It was a dissenter trap.''
</P>
<P>
   During our days here, we are traveling to historic sites such as
the home of William Carey in Moulton. He is regarded as the founder
of the modern Baptist missionary movement.
</P>
<P>
   We visited the Bedford, England, home of John Bunyan, the writer
of ``Pilgrim's Progress.'' Also, we went to a church in Olney,
England, where John Newton, a former slave-ship captain, was an
Anglican priest.
</P>
<P>
   Near Newton's old pulpit, we sang what Newton wrote about God's
forgiving nature following Newton's conversion to Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   The words of ``Amazing Grace'' echoing through the ancient
church never had so sweet a sound.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
