r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROFESSIONALGREETERS-     07-30 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFESSIONALGREETERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERE'S A DREAM JOB: GET PAID TO SAY HELLO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He could've been just another Wal-Mart shopper that day in
Crowley, La.
</P>
<P>
   But this was no ordinary customer. This was Sam Walton, the
legendary founder of the Arkansas-based chain, entering the store
with one of his executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi, how are you, glad to see you,'' an old gentleman stationed
at the store's entrance said to Walton. ``If there's anything I can
tell you about our store, let me know.''
</P>
<P>
   That was nearly 20 years ago, says John Bisio, a Wal-Mart
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Bisio adds, ``Mr. Walton was inspired by the idea and wanted to
expand it.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, at least one ``greeter'' _ usually a senior citizen _
works at each of the chain's 2,450 stores, and the concept is
catching on nationwide as businesses try to survive in a more
competitive marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a growing trend over the last several years,'' says
Scott Krugman, spokesman for the National Retail Federation in
Washington, D.C. ``It gives customers a good feeling as they walk
into the store.''
</P>
<P>
   Greeters range from senior citizens to young up-and-coming
managers to students working part time.
</P>
<P>
   At some restaurants, the greeters are former restaurant owners
who want to fulfill a need to be around people.
</P>
<P>
   Willis ``Mac'' McIntosh and Walter Kaufmann, both longtime Fort
Worth restaurateurs, say greeting customers gives them a chance to
stay in touch with the people they've met over the years and to
continue to be a part of the hustle and bustle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing with the restaurant business, you get addicted to
it,'' says Kaufmann, who is 70 and owned the Old Swiss House for 30
years. ``Playing golf is not that fulfilling. You have to have a
purpose in life, and for me it's being around people.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether it is at upscale restaurants, a sporting-goods store or
the local Wal-Mart, businesses want employees to be ``friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   At Luke's Running Store in Dallas' Oak Lawn neighborhood,
co-owner Sharon Lucas says she requires all her salespeople to
greet customers, not just the person standing closest to the door.
Usually, that is 39-year-old Brad Urschel, a self-described
``customer greeter,'' who has made welcoming customers his
specialty.
</P>
<P>
   Urschel was a college track star whose career was cut short
after an accident in which he was thrown from a car.
</P>
<P>
   The accident occurred Nov. 30, 1983. Urschel was 23 and had
graduated from Princeton University, where he earned a bachelor of
arts degree in neuropsychology.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were en route to a track meet,'' he says. ``The car got on
to the soft shoulder of the highway and flipped over one-and-a-half
times. I landed in the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Urschel was in a coma for a month but fought his way back. He
still walks with a limp, but on most days, the father of two rides
his bicycle to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's being myself,'' Urschel says of his job. ``It's how I am.
I like to be friendly. I like to make a statement, in the way that
I dress, in my personality. It's an excitement for life.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas says, ``We value him so much because he is very friendly
and genuine. He's the kind of person you really like for people to
interface with when they come through your door.''
</P>
<P>
   Urschel, who has worked at Luke's for five years, says he tries
to determine what customers want so that he can direct them to the
person best qualified to help. He tries not to be intrusive or
overbearing.
</P>
<P>
   Although customer service has long been considered a benchmark
for successful businesses, not all establishments employ people for
the sole purpose of greeting customers. In area malls, for
instance, shoppers can walk in and out of many stores unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   Bisio of Wal-Mart says, ``I think now the incarnation of store
greeters is really primarily for someone to send the message that
we're glad you're here and point you in the right direction when
you walk into a Wal-Mart.''
</P>
<P>
   That's 72-year-old Bill Webb's goal when he dons his blue vest
and stands at the entrance of the Wal-Mart in Arlington, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tickled to death,'' says Webb, a greeter for five years.
``I love people. I find conversation easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Webb says that his conversations with customers range from small
talk to directing them to items in the store.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's 95 percent of my job,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   You might say that no one works a room quite like Sean Minto,
``all-around nice guy'' who is assistant general manager of
Angeluna, an upscale Fort Worth restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being on the door is important. I see people. I greet them and
make sure they are enjoying themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of Minto's charm is his English accent. Part of it is his
quick wit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watch your step. I wouldn't want you to break your leg before
the show,'' he says, leading a dinner guest to a table.
</P>
<P>
   The show he's referring to is ``Chicago,'' scheduled to start in
an hour at Bass Performance Hall across the street.
</P>
<P>
   Minto doesn't miss a beat. He seats another couple and is back
at the front door before leading a group of diners to a window
seat. In the next moment, he's making small talk with Dr. Felipe
Garcia, seated with his date, Michelle Moquin, and his parents,
Felipe Sr. and Hortensia.
</P>
<P>
   Minto says that when he visits with patrons at their tables, he
does so ``without being too nosy or prying to much into people's
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   For Garcia, greeters represent a welcome change from the old
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time when everything was quick and get out,'' he
says, snapping his fingers. ``The pendulum is swinging back now.''
</P>
<P>
   He likes Angeluna, where he says the customer is made to feel
special. And he is well aware that Minto knows him by name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love people who know me, stroke me,'' Garcia says. ``That's
why I come back.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
