<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PARENTAL BOOST EARLY IN LIFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Catherine Marie Westerlage. Baylee Paige, Joshua Lane and
Zachary Broc Hawkins. Sawyer West Blackman. Alexander Morris
Cochrum. Brian Avery Kaye.
</P>
<P>
   These precious miracles all made their Texas debuts this month
to family, friends and colleagues of mine. Never in my adult life
have so many people I know had babies within days.
</P>
<P>
   What triggered this baby boomlet in July? According to the
obstetrics staff on the maternity wings at Arlington Memorial
Hospital, blame it on El Nino. Count back nine months, and Texans
were celebrating the first sustained cold snap after the
depressingly hot summer of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   It's as good as any explanation, I guess, for this spate of
first-time parents, parents adding to already sizable broods, even
parents with grown-up offspring.
</P>
<P>
   All that enormous potential wrapped inside blue, pink and yellow
blankets. Little porous sponges of humanity, ready to soak up the
wonders that this world has to offer. And each one blessed with
families standing ready to make sure no harm comes to the newest
cherubs on God's earthly team.
</P>
<P>
   I confess that the sadness experienced by many Americans in the
past weeks after the deaths of John F. Kennedy Jr., his wife and
his sister-in-law skipped our house. It was difficult to pay much
attention to eulogies for people I've never met and only read about
in glossy magazines when so many new arrivals had come into our
lives.
</P>
<P>
   One of my dearest friends and her husband gave birth to their
first child July 11. Forty-eight hours later, my husband became a
grandfather three times over within four minutes' time when his
stepdaughter and her husband gave birth to triplets.
</P>
<P>
   These things had a way of drawing one's focus to the here and
now and away from media trucks and naval search vessels
congregating along the Eastern seashore.
</P>
<P>
   Each one of these new Texans already has a leg up on the world _
a mommy and a daddy at home. Plenty of research exists to show that
married two-parent families provide the healthiest, safest
environments in which to raise children. Forty percent of America's
children _ 25 million kids under the age of 18, according to the
National Center for Fathering _ aren't as fortunate; their fathers
don't live in the same house. And the harsh consequences of broken
homes and single-parent families can be seen in the equally stark
statistics.
</P>
<P>
   The likelihood of a girl becoming a teen mother increases five
times if she is raised by an unmarried or divorced mother. The
chances of going to prison doubles for a boy growing up without a
father in the house.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that every single-parent family is doomed to
fail, or that dinner time with every two-parent family is like
watching reruns of ``Father Knows Best.'' But the odds are
definitely in the favor of those children being raised by Mom and
Dad under one roof.
</P>
<P>
   Which completely discounts the ridiculously unscientific and
politically biased report found in the June issue of American
Psychologist titled ``Deconstructing the Essential Father.'' Boston
Globe columnist Jeff Jacoby brought this piece to America's
attention earlier this week when he wrote about the article's
politically motivated attack on fatherhood and marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond providing sperm and child support payments, fathers
apparently aren't essential, according to psychologists Louise
Silverstein and Carl Auerbach, who advocate for a broader welfare
system in this country. Dads don't contribute anything unique to a
child's development, and no empirical data exist to show that the
institution of marriage helps men be better people in general and
fathers in particular.
</P>
<P>
   Tell that to the researchers for the National Fatherhood
Initiative, the Fatherhood Project at the Families and Work
Institute, the American Coalition for Fathers and Children, and any
number of nonprofit groups specializing in the important role that
fathers play in their children's lives. Children without a father
in the same house show a dramatic increase in drug and alcohol
abuse, behavioral problems, poverty, suicide, dropping out of
school ...
</P>
<P>
   Geez, enough negatives. Let's look at what Catherine and Baylee,
Joshua and Zachary, Sawyer, Alexander and Brian have to look
forward to. Interaction between father and child promotes the
child's physical well-being, perceptual abilities and overall
competency. Grades improve when Dad is involved in school
activities. Dads who spend time alone with their children doing
routine child-care activities _ bathing, dressing, changing
diapers, singing them to sleep _ are helping to raise more
compassionate adults.
</P>
<P>
   Such tremendous potential wrapped inside blue, pink and yellow
blankets. Such giant head starts toward successful lives because
Mom AND Dad are standing by the crib.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and a columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. She can be reached via e-mail at
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com or by phone at (817) 390-7599. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
