<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0042 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     07-30 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRONG WORD TO DESCRIBE TAX REDUCTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the most annoying aspects of the ongoing debate over tax
cuts is the description of tax cuts as ``spending'' _ as if tax
relief were some sort of government giveaway program.
</P>
<P>
   Think about it. Ever since the possibility was raised that the
federal government might be racking up gigantic budget surpluses in
coming years, the politicians and the media have been babbling
about the best way to ``spend'' all the extra money.
</P>
<P>
   You know how it goes. The Democrats want to ``spend'' the budget
surplus on Social Security, Medicare, education, etc. The
Republicans want to ``spend'' the surplus on tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The whole argument revolves around ``spending.''
</P>
<P>
   An article in Thursday's Wall Street Journal, for example,
referred to the possible use of the surplus ``to finance tax
cuts.''
</P>
<P>
   And the article quoted Rep. Barney Frank of Massachusetts: ``The
question is whether it should be spent on private goods or public
goods.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank, a Democrat who embodies the phrase ``tax-and-spend
liberal,'' would obviously prefer that the surplus be spent on
``public goods'' _ government programs, in other words _ rather
than on ``private goods,'' which is a synonym for ``tax cuts.''
</P>
<P>
   That politicians of either party want to spend the public's
money should not surprise us. But it is surprising, maybe even
shocking, that the word ``spend'' could come into play regarding
tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Have we forgotten how the system works? Government collects
money from the citizenry for the purpose of providing certain
services that citizens can't provide, or don't wish to provide, for
themselves. This money belongs to the people, not to the
government; if more money is collected than the government needs to
deliver the designated services, then the money must be returned to
the people.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't a subject for debate. It isn't some philosophical
concept that can be reasonably argued from various points of view.
It's a fact: If the federal government has a budget surplus, it
means that the government has collected too much money from the
taxpayers and therefore ``owes'' them a refund.
</P>
<P>
   The premise involved here is so fundamental that it's impossible
to comprehend how so many people could be so hopelessly ignorant of
how it works.
</P>
<P>
   So. We must conclude that ignorance has nothing to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   We know that the president of the United States _ to name just
one offender _ has no qualms about misinforming, misstating,
misrepresenting or just plain lying through his teeth where matters
of public import are concerned. And we know that he is a highly
intelligent man who is a lifelong student of government as well as
the ins and outs of politics.
</P>
<P>
   It would only seem fair, then, to assume that Bill Clinton knows
perfectly well that cutting taxes is not spending but is in fact a
simple matter of returning the people's money to its rightful
owners. Clinton knows it, and so do all the other politicians and
pundits who are fostering the misconception that a tax cut is a
gift given by the government to the people.
</P>
<P>
   But the misconception seems to be taking hold. A Wall Street
Journal/NBC News poll suggests that most Americans don't want a tax
cut because they apparently buy into the Clintonian idea that
everyone would be better off if we let the politicians fritter away
all the extra money that we have forked over to the government.
</P>
<P>
   OK. Here's a suggestion. Let's make the tax cut voluntary.
</P>
<P>
   If there are all these high-minded _ naive? gullible? dumb? _
taxpayers who don't want their money back, they can notify the
Internal Revenue Service that they truly desire to continue paying
taxes at the current exorbitant rates and will not accept any
reduction in their tax bills. Clinton and the tax-and-spenders can
spend those folks' money till the cows home.
</P>
<P>
   But the rest of us will be expecting Congress and the president
to reduce our tax bills in direct proportion to our share of the
budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   We will accept cash or checks; no credit cards, please.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
