 Attn: Style and Leisure Editors:  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following articles
from the Style section for use Sunday, Aug. 1, and thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   NY-PERELMAN (New York) _ The scorekeepers of the world might
credit Ronald Owen Perelman with having it all. A net worth of $4.2
billion, by Forbes's last count. Palatial residences in Manhattan,
East Hampton and Palm Beach wallpapered with modern art. A jet, a
yacht, all the toys. And now, Ellen Barkin _ the sultry 45-year-old
actress who is expected to become his fourth wife. But for these
riches, the very private Perelman, 56, has paid an expensively
public price. Many of his business and personal affairs have ended
in courtroom dramas over the years. By Rick Marin.
</P>
<P>
   RICKY`S-DRUGSTORE (New York) _ Ricky's drugstore might not
attract lunch-hour shoppers rushing out for staples or the Upper
East Siders who browse at pharmacies like Zitomer and Boyd's. But
it has become a crossroads for New York's funky, flamboyant masses:
makeup artists, actors, club kids and drag queens. By Nancy Hass.
Photo.
</P>
<P>
   FAD-DIETS (Undated) _ Over the last two decades, I have tried
every diet from Cambridge to Scarsdale and every weight-loss
gimmick from inflatable leg massagers to acupuncture needles in my
ears (which were supposed to enhance serotonin and suppress my
appetite). My motivation was both personal (I am a former chemistry
nerd who truly loves nutrition) and professional (for years, I was
a beauty and health editor at a women's magazine, where it was my
duty to experience the latest and greatest). By Martha McCully.
</P>
<P>
   THEME-PARTYNIGHTS (New York) _ As if New York's bars and clubs
didn't have enough singles rubbing elbows and noses, some of them
are taking mating-mixology to the next level: mixer bashes
disguised as theme nights. Downtown weekly events like ``Punk Rock
Karaoke,'' held at Arlene's Grocery, and the Hula Hoop competition
at the Tortilla Flats restaurant, have a decidedly kitschy edge. By
Julia Chaplin.
</P>
<P>
   NITEOUT-LOEB (New York) _ At Damian Loeb's spare TriBeCa studio
on a recent Saturday night, Loeb, a painter, was putting some final
strokes on a work for an upcoming show in London. His best friend,
Richard Hall, the electronic music star known as Moby, zoned out
before a large-screen television hooked up to a spy camera,
allowing him to watch people walking by on the street, a form of
entertainment that Loeb prefers to real television. When they get
together, the two friends refer to themselves as a sort of ``Beavis
and Butt-head'' of the downtown art scene. By Anthony Lappe. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sumac (pronounced SOO-mack or
SHOO-mack, whichever you prefer) is a native shrub throughout most
of the United States, thriving on roadsides, in abandoned fields
and in undisturbed, sunny and well-drained places. It has shiny
green leaves in pairs along the stem, like locust trees, and in
late summer the most common varieties bear fat spikes of small,
clustered red berries. By Cass Peterson.
</P>
