<HEADLINE>
SUMACS, FOR BURSTS OF SCARLET AND LEMONADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 1)  
 (bl)  
 By CASS PETERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I bought the country acreage I now call home, the road
frontage to the west of the house was edged by a couple of wild
cherry trees draped with poison ivy, a random specimen or two of
multiflora rose, a few elderberry bushes and a thicket of sumac.
</P>
<P>
   The neighbors counseled me to clear it out, a formidable chore
that would have required the chain saw, heavy shears and hours of
toil that I preferred to spend on other tasks that also needed
doing.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen years later, the fencerow _ the growth is called a
fencerow even though there is no fence there and never was _ has
finally made it to the top of the end-of-season chore list. Given a
reasonable period of time this year between the falling of the
leaves and the falling of the snow, I will hack my way through the
multiflora roses and elderberries, and gingerly remove the poison
ivy vines.
</P>
<P>
   The benefit of waiting is that I now know enough to leave the
wild cherry trees alone (their fruit lures birds away from my
blueberries), and to do nothing more to the sumac thicket than cut
the wild brambles that threaten to obscure my view of it. What a
mistake it would have been to clear out that sumac.
</P>
<P>
   Sumac (pronounced SOO-mack or SHOO-mack, whichever you prefer)
is a native shrub throughout most of the United States, thriving on
roadsides, in abandoned fields and in undisturbed, sunny and
well-drained places. It has shiny green leaves in pairs along the
stem, like locust trees, and in late summer the most common
varieties bear fat spikes of small, clustered red berries.
</P>
<P>
   Even urban dwellers who never get close enough to examine the
leaves or berries have undoubtedly seen sumac. It's one of the
first deciduous shrubs to turn color in autumn, and its flaming
scarlet foliage is hard to miss even when you're speeding by at 60
miles an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The spectacle is even better at the speed of a stroll, because
the autumn shrubs are often adorned with birds _ tanagers,
flickers, cedar waxwings and others _ clinging to the woody stems
while they gorge themselves on sumac berries.
</P>
<P>
   You can use the berries yourself to make sumac lemonade, a
passable substitute for pink lemonade. To do that, gather the fully
colored berries in late summer or fall, rub them gently to crush
them, and soak them for 15 minutes or so in cold water. Strain the
pink juice through cheesecloth and sweeten it to taste.
</P>
<P>
   For two bad reasons and one good one, sumac isn't often planted
as an ornamental. Among the bad reasons is the erroneous notion
that it's poisonous. Sumacs belong to the cashew family,
Anacardiaceae, and to the genus Rhus, which also used to be the
taxonomical home of poison ivy (formerly R. radicans) and poison
sumac (formerly R. vernix).
</P>
<P>
   Taxonomists have since moved both of the itchy sisters to the
genus Toxicodendron, but the unfortunate association of ``poison''
with ``sumac'' lives on. Poison sumac foliage superficially
resembles that of the innocent sumacs, but it grows in swampy, wet
areas instead of dry spots and has grayish-white berries instead of
red ones.
</P>
<P>
   A second bad reason for not planting sumac is its nativeness.
Gardeners tend to weed out what grows naturally, not plant it. This
is good reasoning when applied to dandelions and chickweed; when
applied to herbaceous and woody perennials, it eliminates fine
plants like native day lilies and asters, wild yarrow and
goldenrod, serviceberry and sumac.
</P>
<P>
   An arguably good reason for not planting sumac is lack of space.
Depending on variety, native sumacs grow from 15 to 25 feet tall,
but they look best if allowed to sucker freely and form dense
thickets. Even as a specimen plant, though, a single sumac is still
worth growing.
</P>
<P>
   The best-known native sumac is staghorn sumac (R. typhina). Many
gardeners suppose the common name comes from the forked branches,
which do indeed _ especially when they are bare of foliage in the
winter _ look like a fine rack of antlers. But the name really
refers to the fact that staghorn sumac has twigs and leaflets
covered with fine, downy hairs, like the velvet that covers a
deer's antlers in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Almost as common in the East is smooth sumac, which has the same
forked branches but lacks the velvety hairs of staghorn sumac.
Smooth sumac also tends to be lower-growing than the staghorn
variety. Both staghorn and smooth sumac are available in forms
called Lacianata, with finely cut leaves that add to their
ornamental value.
</P>
<P>
   There are other species of sumac suitable for the garden,
including fragrant sumac (R. aromatica) and Chinese sumac (R.
chinensis).
</P>
<P>
   Fragrant sumac is smaller than staghorn or smooth sumac, growing
to a maximum height and spread of about six feet. Its yellow
flowers are showier in the spring than those of the native species,
but you'll get the spring show at the sacrifice of the autumn show.
Its fall foliage is not as flashy as the native species'.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese sumac produces cream-colored flowers in summer, and
grows to around 25 feet. It's a nice ornamental, but its orange
berries don't make very good pink lemonade and don't seem as
attractive to birds.
</P>
<P>
   Since I'll be closing down part of their smorgasbord by
eliminating the rose hips, the elderberries and the poison ivy
berries, I really feel I owe the birds their fencerow sumac.
</P>
<P>
   A wide variety of sumacs is available from Forest Farm, 990
Tetherow Road, Williams, Ore. 97544; (541) 846-7269; catalog $4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
