<P>
   BALKANS-U.S. (Sarajevo, Bosnia-Herzegovina) _ President Clinton
on Friday proposed an economic package worth nearly $700 million to
promote a stable and prosperous Balkan future, but he said Serbia
would only be part of that future when President Slobodan Milosevic
was gone. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-EMBASSY (Beijing) _ Ending more than two months of bitter
acrimony, the United States and China agreed here Friday that
Washington will pay $4.5 million in compensation for NATO's bombing
of the Chinese embassy in Yugoslavia on May 7. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SECT (Beijing) _ Chinese authorities revealed Friday that
a retired senior army officer, the highest-ranking leader of the
spiritual movement that was banned last week, has confessed his
``mistakes'' and renounced his allegiance to the movement, Falun
Gong. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TAX-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The Senate passed a $792 billion
Republican tax cut Friday, moving Congress toward a showdown with
President Clinton over how the nation can best use trillions of
dollars in projected federal budget surpluses. The vote was 57 to
43. Four Democrats joined 53 Republicans in support of the bill,
while two Republicans and 41 Democrats voted against it. By Richard
W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   THE SPEND-CONGRESS STORY WILL HOLD IF IT DOES NOT MAKE PAGE ONE.
</P>
<P>
   SPEND-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Congress, determined to increase
military spending and unable to cut the rest of the budget deeper
than it has already done, is certain to wipe out the projected
$14.5 billion surplus in coming weeks. Now the Republican
leadership is scouring the entire federal budget, seeking unspent
money from programs like Medicaid, welfare benefits and interstate
highway funds to fill a spending gap that is running upwards of $15
billion. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
