<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0088 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     07-30 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOCHCO TO THE RESCUE: WHAT IT TAKES TO GET BLACKS ON NETWORK TV
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ When I first heard about a new black drama
supervised by superproducer Steven Bochco, my heart raced just
imagining that a series with more than two tokens-of-color would
have a fighting chance. Bochco, he of ``Hill Street Blues,'' of
``L.A. Law,'' of ``NYPD Blue,'' is a god in an industry that
worships ratings, money, power and the perception of talent.
</P>
<P>
   What Bochco says goes. And for at least 13 episodes.
</P>
<P>
   But anyone who has even a passing interest in television and its
players realizes this pitiful fact: It takes a white producer to
make a black-oriented television drama.
</P>
<P>
   Paris Barclay, the respected, black writer/producer of ``NYPD
Blue,'' is a co-creator with Bochco of the new ``City of Angels.''
But even he is quick to acknowledge that the series wouldn't be on
a network's midseason schedule if the Tommy Hilfiger of network TV
hadn't used his name to sell the thing.
</P>
<P>
   Now Bochco's hour-long series, focusing on an underfunded,
understaffed, underappreciated hospital that employs mostly black
and Hispanic doctors and serves a minority-majority neighborhood,
is set for production _ and ready for its racial litmus test.
</P>
<P>
   In a town where blacks and Hispanics have been devalued and
essentially ignored _ not just this season, but ALWAYS _ the mere
``announcement'' from the Bochco camp made people wonder about the
show's Madison Avenue clout, worry about its casting, and place it
neatly in the ``promising'' and ``long-awaited'' categories.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder CBS is pumped at the prospect of getting this series
on air in January or shortly thereafter. ``City of Angels,'' which
has signed Blair Underwood, Michael Warren and Vivica A. Fox
(getting A-list black talent isn't hard when everyone's available),
already carries name recognition without the press seeing a second
of production tape.
</P>
<P>
   Call me picky, pessimistic, or a chronically displeased race
zealot. But it's unsettling to see the industry and the press jump
aboard this project sight unseen _ especially as we've seen other
dramas featuring largely black and Hispanic casts, such as Thomas
Carter's family tale ``Under One Roof,'' Damon Wayans' ``413 Hope
Street,'' and Kevin Arkadie's ``New York Undercover,'' die quick or
mysterious deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the urgency involves our present atmosphere of minority
exclusion. In this climate, any series with a predominantly black
or Hispanic cast will be singled out, particularly within the drama
genre.
</P>
<P>
   But interviews with black writers, producers and stars over the
past three weeks have made it obvious to me that we are stepping
over the real issues, which go much deeper than mere on-camera
representation.
</P>
<P>
   This is a town where power rules. And what ``City of Angels''
represents is the lack of power for people of color. One actor told
me he felt an odd mixture of hope, thanks, anger and envy when
learning of the Bochco project. Though he thought it was a step in
the right direction, he also felt a twinge of disappointment over
the Bochco image as All-Mighty Savior.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few years ago, it was disheartening to see the
overwhelming number of black-cast shows being fronted by white
producers, who mounted the interview stages like parents toting
their young. As black writers rose to supervising producers and
then to executive producers with the power to create and run their
own projects, the image shifted, at least within the comedy genre.
</P>
<P>
   ``City of Angels'' would have to be a complete failure to keep
Barclay from getting a toehold within this power structure. Maybe
he can return to do more shows, hiring other people of color who
could then rise through the ranks as he did. The cycle would
continue.
</P>
<P>
   Or else the current one will stay in place. One of the greatest
failings of this town is its segregation, physical and mental and
emotional. As Barclay says, ``People are afraid. They're afraid of
what they don't know and, if you don't know a lot of different
people, you're not going to write them, you're not going to invite
them to be in the room with you to create shows, and the shows
aren't going to get on the air, because they're not going to be the
things that the networks have to choose from.''
</P>
<P>
   This becomes even more clear when you consider producers like
Kevin Williamson. He has turned his life experience into two
series, ``Dawson's Creek'' and the new ``Wasteland,'' an ABC show
about singles navigating New York City life.
</P>
<P>
   Williamson was criticized for the absence of black and brown
faces in ``Wasteland,'' with people noting that you couldn't go to
New York without seeing a melting pot.
</P>
<P>
   I disagree. Williamson's reality is a world without people of
color, and he's simply showing that world.
</P>
<P>
   It's neither right nor wrong. It's just unfortunate in a medium
where there are simply too many Williamsons and too few Barclays
with the power to put their lives onscreen.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You cdan call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
