<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-PRESCRIPTIONS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 FDA SAYS IT WILL CRACK DOWN ON ILLEGAL INTERNET DRUG SALES
 (EDS: Filed in ``w'' and ``f'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The federal Food and Drug Administration told
Congress Friday it plans to crack down on Internet sites that sell
prescription drugs illegally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patients who buy prescription drugs from an illegitimate site
are at risk of suffering life-threatening adverse events,'' said
Janet Woodcock, FDA's director of drug planning and research. She
said the agency intends to ``significantly expand its enforcement
activities'' for online sales.
</P>
<P>
   Woodcock announced the FDA's plans at a House Commerce
Subcommittee on Investigations and Oversight hearing on Internet
prescription drug sales. The FDA has authority to bring action
against anyone who sells prescription drugs without a valid
prescription.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Fred Upton, R-Mich., chairman of the panel, said there are
about 400 Internet retailers that may be illegally selling
prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of these sites today allow consumers to order
prescription medication, even without ever seeing a doctor
face-to-face and sometimes even without a valid prescription,''
Upton said.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers expressed alarm that the Food and Drug
Administration is only now announcing a crack down on such Internet
drug sellers.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bart Stupak, D-Mich., said there were only about 26
suspicious Internet drug sites when committee staffers began
looking into the issue in January but that the number keeps growing
by dozens each week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where's the cop on the beat?'' he asked. ``Next month there
will be 500 sites.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodcock said there are a ``large number of cases'' under
investigation. She also said the FDA will double the number of
Internet drug investigators from 10 to 20.
</P>
<P>
   She admitted that the FDA is struggling to keep up with the
proliferation of Internet sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unique qualities of the Internet, including its broad
reach and ability for anonymity, pose new challenges for
enforcement of existing laws,'' Woodcock said. ``FDA is grappling
with the challenges posed by online drug sales.''
</P>
<P>
   Until the illegal sites are shut down, Woodcock said consumers
can protect themselves by staying away from Internet drug sites
altogether or asking their physicians for the name of a reputable
site.
</P>
<P>
   It is illegal for people to order medicine from the Internet
without a valid prescription, she said.
</P>
<P>
   To obtain a prescription drug legally, Woodcock said, a person
must visit a doctor or other licensed health care practitioner who
will then write a prescription if it's medically necessary. A
patient must take that prescription, or have a doctor phone it in,
to a state-licensed pharmacy to have it filled. The pharmacy then
calls the doctor to ensure the prescription is valid.
</P>
<P>
   There are also legitimate Internet web sites such as
drugstore.com or PlanetRx.com in which a physician can call or fax
a prescription to that Internet site. Drugstore.com and PlantRx.com
are licensed to sell drugs in each state.
</P>
<P>
   The state of Kansas recently sued six Internet drug operators
for selling drugs without a state license. The cases are still
pending.
</P>
<P>
   Carla Stovall, Kansas's attorney general, said the most
difficult thing for her investigators was tracking down who was
actually behind the Internet site, which usually do not contain a
valid company name or address.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had to sort through multiple shell corporations,
addresses that turned out to be mail drops, overlapping addresses
shared by different entities and similar evasive tactics,'' Stovall
said.
</P>
<P>
   To stem the flow of illegal Internet drugs, Stovall said the
states and the federal government would have to sharply increase
the number of investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Upton said he would like to see increased cooperation between
state and federal authorities in order to limit the growth of
Internet drug sites, but other lawmakers were skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not convinced that either the states or the federal
government is even close to having a handle on this,'' said Rep.
Ron Klink, D-Pa.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at 202-298-6920 and at
jennifer(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
