<HEADLINE>
FLAMBOYANT MEETS FUNKY IN A DRUGSTORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 1)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By NANCY HASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While the entrance to the average Duane Reade has a
Pepsi display and a bin of Tylenol gel caps, the Ricky's drugstore
on Broadway in Greenwich Village has a showcase of studded collars
and cuffs labeled ``Ricky's Fantasy Cabinet'' and a wall of more
than 125 multicolor synthetic wigs, including a kelly green pageboy
and a white Marie Antoinette do.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there is the usual complement of toothpaste and shampoo,
but instead of Prell, Head &AMP; Shoulders and Aqua-Fresh, the brands
are obscure products in exotic packages. Along one wall are more
than 100 styles of false eyelashes, and down a nearby aisle in the
corner, under a disco ball, is a section devoted to erotic
novelties and cheesy lingerie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably not a place that your grandmother would feel
comfortable,'' said Ricky Kenig, who with his family owns the
store, the flagship of a five-drugstore chain. ``Though we would
try hard to make her feel at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Ricky's might not attract lunch-hour shoppers rushing out for
staples or the Upper East Siders who browse at pharmacies like
Zitomer and Boyd's. But it has become a crossroads for New York's
funky, flamboyant masses: makeup artists, actors, club kids and
drag queens.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky's stores, strategically situated in Manhattan's more hip
and touristy neighborhoods (Soho, the Village, midtown), are as
different from Rite Aid as the Strand is from Barnes &AMP; Noble. With
neon and custom-graffitied signs pointing the way to the hair
brushes, rap and R &AMP; B ballads booming in the background and
merchandise that glitters, Ricky's stores are the opposite of
corporate retailing: eccentric, stylish, brimming with local
flavor.
</P>
<P>
   In the decade since the first Ricky's opened on Broadway near
Washington Place, the stores have become a favorite of fashion
designers and stylists. The house cosmetics line, Mattese
(pronounced inexplicably like the artist Matisse), is widely used
by makeup artists, who pair its vivid, modestly priced products
with high-end brands like Chanel.
</P>
<P>
   The celebrity makeup artist Kevin Aucoin says he goes in as
often as three times a month to buy the house brand of cotton swabs
and other tools of the trade. ``I love it from the minute you walk
in,'' he said, alluding to the sign over the door, a huge,
undulating sequined tube of toothpaste.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky's not only is the first to get new beauty products and
downtown looks on its shelves, but also, some fashion insiders say,
sometimes starts trends. ``They are really phenomenally forward,''
the designer Betsey Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   The makeup artist Bobbi Brown, whose line of cosmetics is sold
at Barneys and Saks Fifth Avenue, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricky's is like our version of going to all those little
cosmetic places in Paris,'' she said. ``It's very specifically New
York.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing the store is not, however, is a bargain bin.
Conventional products like toothpaste and aspirin are priced lower
than at tony emporiums like Bigelow Pharmacy in the Village, but
higher than at discount chains like CVS.
</P>
<P>
   In an era when chains are driving many independent drugstores
out of business, Ricky's strategy for survival is to offer a wider,
and wilder, selection of merchandise at premium prices. ``You
really can't make money selling aspirin,'' Kenig said. ``But you
can make money selling body paint and vibrators.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the NC-17 tinge of some merchandise, it may be surprising
to learn that Ricky's is a family business. Al Kenig, Ricky Kenig's
father, is a former junkyard owner, who opened one of the first
discount beauty stores in the Bronx in the early 1970s after a
customer started paying him in truckloads of fragrances. Later, he
and a group of partners started Love's, a 25-store discount drug
chain in New York, which capitalized on the growing market for hair
and skin-care products.
</P>
<P>
   Al Kenig, 63, was never a conventional role model, either for
his children or for how to run a business. To advertise Love's, he
became a sponsor of Robin Byrd's cable television show on which
guests were interviewed nude. His first Love's, on Third Avenue
near 64th Street, was originally named Linda Love after Linda
Lovelace.
</P>
<P>
   Al Kenig made his two sons and two daughters work in the
business as they were growing up. Ricky Kenig recalled, like a
Rockefeller nostalgic about Standard Oil's early days, ``When he
had the store in the Bronx, he would send us out to buy up all the
Excedrin and Pepto-Bismol we could find at Kmart and then he'd mark
it up and resell it.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Al Kenig sold his share in Love's and soon after opened
the first Ricky's, named for his older son, who dropped out of
college to manage it. He gave all the children shares in the store,
but the largest, 50 percent chunk, went to Ricky. It was Ricky's
idea, his father said, to cater to a downtown market and build ``an
antichain.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, in addition to the original store, Ricky Kenig owns the
controlling share of the Soho store on Broadway, near Houston
Street. Todd Kenig, 35, his younger brother, owns half of the
stores on Broadway and 58th Street and at Eighth Street near Greene
Street.
</P>
<P>
   Al Kenig and another partner from the Love's days own one other
Ricky's, on Avenue of the Americas near 11th Street. ``Mostly these
days I just try to provide a little inspiration,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Staying tirelessly trendy is a full-time job for the Kenigs. The
displays in the stores change almost every week, with merchandise
categories shifting to match the hipness food chain. (Hair
accessories are moving steadily toward the back after a year in the
prime spot near the door.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The hair butterflies, we had them two years ago,'' Ricky Kenig
said. ``The chains just got them, like, last month. And yo-yos? I
heard some of the hard-core rappers mention them in the songs, so I
got them in here. Now, when they are totally over, Duane Reade is
getting them in.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of weeks ago when he was vacationing on Fire Island,
Ricky saw that the old-fashioned general store in Fair Harbor
carried penny candy. He decided on the spot it was time for the
retro-sweets to make a comeback among his jaded teen-age customers.
Next week, he will open a 10-foot section with everything from
edible wax lips, pixie sticks and those sugar dots on paper. ``Ten
minutes after I saw it out there, I knew it was right,'' he said.
``And I was on the phone a minute later setting it up. If you don't
move fast in a business like this, it's over before it begins.''
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Kenig's ambition is to export his quirky New York chain to
the rest of the world. Tourists already clog the stores, gripping
articles ripped from fashion magazines that mention the store.
Mattese is sold in 96 stores in Japan, and the Kenigs are working
on a deal to take a selection of snazzily packaged Ricky's New York
products to London. They think stores would work in Los Angeles and
Seattle, too.
</P>
<P>
   One thing they are sure of is that watering down the stores'
funk quotient would not be wise. In the mid-1990s, they opened
stores in neighborhoods like Murray Hill and the Upper West Side.
They let the managers tailor the product mix to a mainstream
clientele. Last year, they closed all six stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we did wrong was try to compete with the chain stores
nearby,'' Ricky Kenig said. ``That was a complete mistake. What we
came to realize is that the further we get from doing what they do,
the better it is for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
