<HEADER>
A0145 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEFENSE-WASTE-0731-CO     07-30 0488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEFENSE-WASTE-0731-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PENTAGON OVERPAYS CONTRACTORS
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. Defense Department overpaid its top
contractors who then took an average of a year to refund $56
million to the government, says a new congressional investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The study of 13 major contractors disclosed that some companies
retained overpayments for months after they were discovered by
their accounting departments because the government did not ask for
refunds. One contractor accumulated excess payments of $627,000
dating back seven years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some cases, government personnel were aware of
overpayments, but they did not take timely action to obtain
recovery,'' said the report, issued Friday by the General
Accounting Office, the investigative arm of Congress. The study
noted that federal law does not require a company to return the
funds until the government demands a refund.
</P>
<P>
   The report, the latest detailing double payments and other
accounting problems in the department, focused on the Defense
Finance and Accounting Service at Columbus, Ohio, which pays most
of the Pentagon's bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``These accounting oversights are inexcusable,'' said Sen. Tom
Harkin, D-Iowa, a member of the Senate Defense Appropriations
subcommittee. The Department of Defense ``should hunt down these
overpaid contractors and say, 'show me the money,' `` Harkin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department, responding to the congressional report,
agreed that it could identify excess payments more efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   Such accounting shortcomings are not new. Between 1994 and 1998,
defense contractors returned about $4.6 billion to the Columbus
center, which has attributed most of the overspending to factors
outside of its control. However, the congressional study said that
some payment errors were made at the center.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the report cited a ``growing backlog of contracts''
that have not been examined for possible overpayments. As of last
January, more than 2,450 contracts were still not reconciled by
defense officials. The longer it takes to reconcile those accounts,
the longer it will take to discover excess payments and obtain
refunds, the congressional study said.
</P>
<P>
   The 13 companies that were the focus of the latest study
represent only a microcosm of the overpayment problem at the
Defense Department. Contractors are paid hundreds of millions of
dollars in excess each year, with the total of refunds to the
Columbus center reaching $746 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Among the companies in the study: Lockheed Martin's Tactical
Aircraft Systems and Bell Helicopter's Textron division, both of
Fort Worth, Texas; Harris Corporation's Electronic Systems Sector
of Melbourne, Fla., Raytheon of Bedford, Mass.; and Boeing's Long
Beach, Calif., division.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
