<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0149 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYT     07-30 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THEIR SCRAMBLE TO FUND PROGRAMS, REPUBLICANS CRY EMERGENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Southern Exposure is the weekly political column from the
Washington Bureau)  
 (bl)  
 New York Times Regional Newspapers   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It's shell game time on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   With lawmakers in the midst of passing the 13 annual spending
bills, Republicans who control both houses are finding it hard to
meet their goals of boosting the defense budget, protecting Social
Security, funding a host of domestic programs and delivering a
major tax cut, all while staying within their own self-imposed
budget caps.
</P>
<P>
   So, what are they doing? They're declaring that some of the
spending they want qualifies as an ``emergency,'' a designation
that conveniently allows lawmakers to ignore those budget caps.
</P>
<P>
   For example, they're counting as an emergency $4.5 billion in
census spending, along with $3 billion for veterans' health care
for next year.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, who favor a more modest tax cut, are having a field
day mocking Republicans, saying it's ridiculous to suggest that
either item qualifies as an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decennial census?'' asked House Minority Leader Dick
Gephardt, noting that it must be conducted every 10 years. ``What's
unforeseen about that?''
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, Sen. Fritz Hollings, D-S.C., said the semantic
gymnastics only underscore what he sees at the ultimate fallacy in
the tax-cut debate - that there is a budget surplus to enjoy.
Indeed, the so-called surplus only exists because lawmakers count
the revenues from various trust funds, including Social Security,
which are supposed to be off limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cut out the monkeyshine,'' Hollings declared. ``We don't have
any revenues to lose. Everybody knows that.''
</P>
<P>
   TAXING TIMES
</P>
<P>
   It is a tough time for Southern Democratic conservatives and
moderates in Congress. They want to back some tax cuts and they
want to go a little farther than some of their Democratic
colleagues. But they don't want to sign on to what they see as a
fiscally reckless $792 billion proposal embraced by Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to broker a deal, some joined forces with
like-minded GOP moderates in the Senate to advance a compromise
$500 billion package they described as the middle ground between
the GOP position and the Democratic and Clinton administration
approach. Without each side giving a little ground, said Sen. John
Breaux, D-La., nothing is likely to be signed into law.
</P>
<P>
   ``We, in a bipartisan way, can avoid the financial train
wreck,'' said Breaux, who was joined in advancing his proposal by
Louisiana colleague Mary Landrieu and Sen. John Edwards, D-N.C.,
among others.
</P>
<P>
   Other Southerners believe Congress should not offer any tax
relief until it guarantees the survival of both Social Security and
Medicare and pays down the debt. In the House, members of the Blue
Dog Coalition, including such conservative Democrats as Bud Cramer
of Alabama, Chris John of Louisiana and Mike McIntyre of North
Carolina, opposed the GOP tax cut package.
</P>
<P>
   With midsummer policy fights reaching a fever pitch on Capitol
Hill, Breaux proposed a cooling-off period.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suggest that before we pass an $800 billion tax bill and
send it to the president for a certain veto, we take a break and
spend the August recess listening to our constituents,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   GRIM HARVEST
</P>
<P>
   With low prices and restricted access to foreign markets,
farmers everywhere are suffering this summer. And Southern
lawmakers feel their pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Farmers are having a very rough time,'' said Democratic Rep.
Mike McIntyre, who said that his nine-county district in
southeastern North Carolina has lost 706 farms over six years.
</P>
<P>
   McIntyre and other lawmakers blame the Freedom to Farm Act,
which was enacted in 1996 and eliminated price supports and
guarantees for most crops.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is we are in a global economy and other countries
around the world continue to subsidize their farmers at rates
between 30 and 40 percent,'' McIntyre said. ``Other countries also
have strict quotas and tariffs on imports. As long as they do that,
we don't have a level playing field.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers are working on a variety of remedies, including some
short-term loan relief and expanding a conservation program that
compensates farmers who limit their production.
</P>
<P>
   A more permanent solution, McIntyre said, lies in revamping the
Freedom to Farm Act, which comes up for renewal in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't wait that long,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   GET DOWN, GET DOWN
</P>
<P>
   Oh those funky Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to demonstrate their hipness, Florida GOP leaders have
lined up a name musical act for their October convention in Orlando
_ site of a presidential candidate's forum. Their choice? Kool and
the Gang, a 70s disco group best known for the song, ``Celebrate.''
</P>
<P>
   That should stop all the talk about Republicans not being
terribly with it.
</P>
<P>
   (Compiled from reports by Sean Loughlin and Carl Hulse in the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.
This article was distributed by The New York Times News Service.)
</P>
</TEXT>
