<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990730.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0166 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-CONVERTS-1ST     07-30 1917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-CONVERTS-1STTAKE01-CO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Committed communists find God
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, August 1.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALTANTA _ The gray-haired man in the 11th pew touched the tips
of his fingers to his forehead and to his breast, and then to each
shoulder. Many were making the sign of the cross in a hurried blur,
something done out of long habit, but Eugene Genovese made it with
the deliberation of a man who had given it hard thought. And when
he finished he knelt, head bowed, hands folded in prayer.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Saturday evening before the Fourth of July, and the
Cathedral of Christ the King in Buckhead was close to full.
Genovese had taken Holy Communion, as he does each week. At the
altar, his wife, Elizabeth Fox-Genovese, a Eucharistic minister,
offered one communicant after another the wafer that Catholics
believe is the body of Jesus Christ.
</P>
<P>
   It is a well-to-do parish, the collection basket brimming with
tens, twenties, fifties and, on this particular Saturday, a check
for $100. In the back of the church a basket for the poor was
having to settle for one-dollar bills and a scattering of coins,
but few seemed to notice. Fewer still would have known that the
worshipper in their midst was, not so many years ago, a committed
Communist and his wife a feminist scholar with a Marxist point of
view. Not only that, but they had been nonbelievers most of their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   Long before they moved to Atlanta in 1986, Gene Genovese was
perhaps the best-known Marxist intellectual in the country. In the
1960s, President Richard Nixon tried to get him removed from the
faculty at Rutgers University because of his open support of the
Viet Cong. He joined the Communist Party of the United States of
America at age 15 and was a party organizer in New York City at 17.
Even in his mature years, he was a defender of Josef Stalin and of
the Soviet Union. He defended it, he says, ``until there was
nothing left to defend.''
</P>
<P>
   She is a historian who came to Atlanta as founder of the women's
studies program at Emory University, an intellectual who 20 years
ago was writing articles on the political dimensions of fashion for
journals such as Marxist Perspectives and Socialist Review.
</P>
<P>
   In May he turned 69 and she turned 58. He has retired, living
almost unnoticed in a money-minded city he calls gracious and
civilized, writing for a variety of periodicals, enjoying the
company of intellectuals on the right. But he is hardly a convert
to the free market _ which he says ``perverts the principle of
personal responsibility and promotes consumer choice as the arbiter
of moral and even spiritual values'' _ and he scoffs at those on
the left who think he has sold out. The conservatism he articulates
is rooted in the thoughts of John C. Calhoun and other antebellum
thinkers, not Newt Gingrich or Trent Lott.
</P>
<P>
   She still teaches history at Emory and still has an eye for
fashion, and wears plenty of it. But the convictions they live by
are grounded in an authority their old friends would have mocked.
The linchpin of those convictions, they will forthrightly tell you,
is the immortal soul.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look,'' he says in his assertive way, ``if your conscience is
not the impress of the Holy Spirit, it's nothing more than an
opinion. And your opinion is no better than mine or the next
person's.''
</P>
<P>
   Even while he declared himself an atheist and professed
allegiance to Marx, something nagged at Genovese. ``I had long been
troubled by the lack of a moral foundation in Marxism,'' he says.
``It wasn't clear to me that you could have that foundation without
a belief in God. I mean, you can be an atheist and live a perfectly
moral life, but what is it grounded in?
</P>
<P>
   ``But disavowing Marxism and atheism _ that was an intellectual
decision. The question of faith is separate altogether. You can
decide to become a Christian, but you can't have faith if you don't
feel it. I didn't re-enter the church until I could feel myself in
grace. It didn't come at a particular moment; there was no road to
Damascus. It came slowly, and I think that would probably be
difficult for Protestants to understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Many have pointed out the coincidence of his re-entering the
church only when the Soviet Union collapsed, and Genovese does not
deflect the suggestion that he needed an anchor. ``That may very
well be so,'' he says. ``I'm institutionally oriented, but I fail
to see what that has to do with the church and with faith. I know
former comrades who became Protestants, who became social
democrats, who became a lot of other things but not Roman
Catholics.''
</P>
<P>
   If he is a different man from the one old comrades on the left
once thought they knew, it's because he sees the relationship
between political philosophy and life differently. ``The horrors
(of Soviet communism),'' he wrote a few years ago, ``did not arise
from perversions of radical ideology but from the ideology itself.
We were led into complicity with mass murder and the desecration of
our professed ideals not by Stalinist or other corruptions of high
ideals, much less by unfortunate twists in some presumably
objective course of historical development, but by a deep flaw in
our understanding of human nature. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Confronting the basics
</P>
<P>
   Gene Genovese grew up in the Bensonhurst section of Brooklyn,
the son of a dockworker who didn't go to church and a mother who
prayed daily to St. Anthony. Betsey Fox grew up the culturally
privileged daughter of nonbelievers who instilled in her Calvinist
virtues of honesty and rectitude _ a precondition, she says, for
her eventual acceptance of faith.
</P>
<P>
   They were married on June 6, 1969. He was 39, and she was 28.
But the date that marks their lives today is Dec. 9, 1995. That was
the day Betsey Fox-Genovese received, in little more than an hour,
four sacraments of the Roman Catholic Church. She had recently been
baptized and now she was making her confession, receiving Communion
for the first time, being confirmed and _ after a quarter-century
of marriage in the eyes of the state _ being married to Gene
Genovese by a priest.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me,'' she would write, ``that day wove together the
essential threads of the preceding 53 years of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   She had been a feminist who was wrestling with doubts. ``There's
nothing like contemporary feminism,'' she says, ``to bring you up
against the basics of human existence. I was writing a lot about
abortion and took it as a given, as someone who was pro-woman, that
it was a matter of rights. But the more I wrote, the more I had
trouble with the language in which the issue was always framed.
What I came to see was that the rights of women and the rights of
the fetus were not the issue. It was about the sanctity of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Once she came to that view, its ``full implications gradually
pulled me toward church membership and faith.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, Sheila O'Connor-Ambrose was one of
Fox-Genovese's graduate students _ and the only Catholic, she says,
in the women's studies program. ``My faith was central to my
identity,'' O'Connor-Ambrose says. ``I was very open about it, both
intellectually and devotionally.''
</P>
<P>
   But the church, with its stand against abortion and its
injunction against premarital sex, was fair game, and not just for
feminists. The one open-minded listener O'Connor-Ambrose found was
Elizabeth Fox-Genovese. ``At the time she was agnostic, if not
atheist. But she made me feel comfortable. I remember her telling
me, `Sheila, if you can't be who you are, then what is the
point?'''
</P>
<P>
   Not long after, Fox-Genovese resigned as director of Emory's
women's studies program _ her resignation forced, she believes,
because of a lawsuit accusing her of violating a subordinate's
civil rights. In her suit, Virginia Gould, a middle-aged woman who
had been one of Fox-Genovese's graduate students, contended that
she had been asked to perform duties that wouldn't have been asked
of a male subordinate and had been verbally abused. The lawsuit was
settled before it went to a jury.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor-Ambrose believes that experience was pivotal for both
of the Genoveses. ``Neither of them is even faintly postmodern,''
she says. ``They both believe there is a truth, that human nature
has meaning and that life has a purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox-Genovese calls it an unfolding more than a conversion.
Sitting in their DeKalb County townhouse, she likens it to a
person's realizing finally who she is and what she is about. ``It's
when you know the outside and the inside have met,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Their joint journey began in 1968, when Genovese, twice
divorced, the subject of FBI dossiers and wiretaps, showed up at
Betsey Fox's door with two dozen red roses. She was a graduate
student at Harvard, and ``had never even heard of Eugene
Genovese,'' when a mutual friend arranged a blind date. It amuses
her now that she hadn't. He had not yet published his path-breaking
book ``Roll, Jordan, Roll: The World the Slaves Made,'' but he had
done important scholarly work in the history of the antebellum
South. And if that were not reason enough, his notoriety as a
Marxist was.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how naive I was,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   From their kitchen table, papers spread before him, Gene
Genovese looks up from his work and replies, ``That's Harvard for
you.''
</P>
<P>
   He would not be a welcome presence in the faculty lounge these
days _ and as far as he's concerned, that's just as well. He has
only contempt for the postmodernism, the secularism, the political
correctness he sees on college campuses. Back then, he was a
dissident merely by being from the left. Now anyone not on the left
is a dissident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned fast enough that he was a big deal,'' Betsey
Fox-Genovese says. ``He was unlike anyone I had ever met. He had
dated women more sophisticated than I was. He had great charm, he
was magnetic and, let's face it, he was a good-looking man.''
</P>
<P>
   Her own feminism was still taking shape, but she remembers his
bringing her back to her apartment that night. ``He kissed me on
the forehead and he left,'' she says. ``I remember shutting that
door and having this absolutely still feeling. I thought, `This is
the one.'''
</P>
<P>
   Her father, the historian Edward Whiting Fox, who was an atheist
but no Marxist, was taken aback at first. ``I was a guy who'd been
married twice and had the FBI after me,'' Genovese says. ``I mean,
I wasn't the best prospect around.''
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Betsey Fox had seen what she needed to see. ``I
couldn't have fallen in love with a man who didn't stand for
something, whose character I didn't respect. I knew he'd been
married before _ of course I knew that.'' She collects her thoughts
and says, ``But I let his past go.''
</P>
<P>
   After 30 years, Gene Genovese ``can't say we've had more than
half a dozen real fights. Temperamentally, we're very different
people _ you must have noticed that. I shoot from the hip; Betsey's
more measured in what she says. There've been times when maybe I've
wanted her to be bolder, to let the chips fall where they may. But
on the other hand, when we've worked together politically, Betsey's
saved me from very many tactical errors.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife describes their differences this way: ``He broods, he
talks to himself, he gets angry. I'm not a great brooder. I don't
often get angry. And when I do, my voice doesn't tend to rise. I
get icy.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
