<HEADER>
A0168 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHURCH-WOMEN28-COX     07-30 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCH-WOMEN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A Dallas minister's wish to help women has burgeoned into a
national mega-revival that changes lives and heals hurts
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It started when a small-town preacher played a hunch
and held a special Bible study that drew 40 curious women.
</P>
<P>
   It has mushroomed into a national revival that's expected to
draw tens of thousands of women to the Georgia Dome on Thursday,
Friday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Woman Thou Art Loosed!'' revival, led by Bishop T.D.
Jakes, has become the theological equivalent of Microsoft stock _
the payoff gets bigger every year.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the revival has filled stadiums and spawned a
best-selling book, a theatrical play, a special-edition Bible and a
CD.
</P>
<P>
   Yet few know that it was sparked by a whim, a spur-of-the-moment
decison to hold a Sunday school class just for women.
</P>
<P>
   The idea came in the early '90s, when Jakes was pastor of a
church in Charleston, W.Va. He discovered during counseling
sessions that women in his church were grappling with similar
problems. The Sunday school class idea seemed to be a good way to
address common issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called it a form of mass counseling,'' said Jakes, 42. ``I
thought they could benefit from being exposed to one another.''
</P>
<P>
   About 40 women attended the first study. Attendance doubled the
following week. Intrigued, Jakes held a third class the following
week. He was shocked at what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked around the church and it was filled with women
standing outside,'' Jakes said. ``I didn't even have a name for
it.'' He does now.
</P>
<P>
   Jakes went to the 13th chapter of Luke and found the story where
Jesus heals an enfeebled woman by declaring, ``Woman, thou art
loosed from thine infirmity.'' Thus was born the ``Woman Thou Art
Loosed!'' revival.
</P>
<P>
   Jakes' fame within the black community has grown along with the
success of the revival. He is the senior pastor of the Potter's
House in Dallas, a nondenominational mega-church with 18,000
members, including celebrities such as NFL star Deion Sanders. He
lectures regularly and leads revivals across the country, has
written 14 books and is known around the world through his
television show, ``Get Ready.'' He and his wife, Serita, have five
children.
</P>
<P>
   Today, many African-American women claim that the revivals have
delivered them from the same problems Jakes uncovered during
counseling sessions with members of his church _ low self-esteem,
bad relationships, sexual abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lifted the scales off of my eyes,'' said Mettye Mero, 76,
of Stone Mountain (Ga.), who heard Jakes preach at the Georgia Dome
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Like those first special Sunday school classes, the revivals
still feel like a form of mass counseling. It's not uncommon to see
women _ some traveling from as far away as Asia and Europe _ cry,
dance, collapse and hug total strangers. Jakes is widely considered
a master preacher, someone who blends therapy and theology with a
dramatic delivery. But his greatest gift may be his vulnerability,
his willingness to preach about his insecurities over his
appearance _ he recently lost 100 pounds _ and the devastating
childhood loss of his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're looking for Superman,'' Jakes said during
a phone interview from his Dallas church. ``We're looking for Clark
Kent, just down-to-earth people, people who've had their scrapes
and scars but can say, 'I'm only here by the grace of God.'''
</P>
<P>
   Such a message helped Wanda Kelley, 39, of Atlanta recover from
the end of a painful relationship. Kelley, a nurse, was walking
through a grocery store when she spotted a book written by Jakes.
After reading only a few pages, she left the supermarket in tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went to my car and sat down, I couldn't even leave the
parking lot, `` Kelley said. ``I read a fourth of the book in the
parking lot. I couldn't move.''
</P>
<P>
   Jakes has also become popular and respected for his willingness
to let women take part in his church and revivals.
</P>
<P>
   While some churches still do not allow women to preach, Jakes
invites women pastors to preach alongside him at his revivals and
constantly tells women that they are ``survivors'' and a
``beautiful piece of artwork.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He treats us like we're queens,'' said Pam Tarvin, 34, an
Atlanta minister who left her church after learning women couldn't
preach there. ``We can be heard (at Jakes' revivals). That helps a
lot, to know that we're important, just like the men.''
</P>
<P>
   By reaching women, Jakes has awakened the group that fills most
churches in the black community on a regular basis. That's why he
gets such large crowds at his revivals, said Teresa Fry-Brown, an
ordained minister and teacher of preaching at Emory University.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you consider the makeup of the churches, the preponderance
of people in the church are usually women, though the leadership is
decidedly male,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't see any of that changing any time soon, even with
the success of Jakes' revivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been at this thing for 18 years, and it's slow going,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jakes, however, said his success has at least shown other
preachers that they can talk about personal pain in the pulpit.
``I'm not standing alone,'' he said. ``I just gave people the
permission to talk about something people always wanted to talk
about.''
</P>
<P>
   John Blake writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
