<HEADER>
A0169 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARTHAWHITE01-COX     07-30 0429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARTHAWHITE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    27 bands rise to the occasion for Martha White anniversary
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Aug. 1.
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's hard to say which is tastier: Martha White biscuits or the
bluegrass jingle advertising Martha White self-rising flour with
``Hot Rize.''
</P>
<P>
   Lester Flatt and Earl Scruggs performed the ditty for years on
the Grand Ole Opry, Earl's banjo racing as Lester praised ``the
finest biscuits ever was.'' When Garrison Keillor made his first
pilgrimage to Nashville and heard them at the Opry, he was so
inspired that he invented a fictitious sponsor _ Powdermilk
Biscuits _ for his own radio show, ``A Prairie Home Companion.''
</P>
<P>
   This summer, to mark its 100th anniversary, Martha White Foods
has dusted off the old tune and made it the centerpiece of the
celebration. The company invited bluegrass bands to submit tapes of
themselves playing the jingle; the winner would get to perform it
on the Opry, where Martha White has sponsored a segment since 1948.
A new Martha White cookbook, ``Southern Traditions,'' is due out
this month as well.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Betty Crocker or Aunt Jemima, Martha White Lindsey was a
real person. Her father, who owned Nashville's Royal Mill, named
his best flour for his 3-year-old daughter and put her darling face
on the package. It's still there, in heirloom black and white.
</P>
<P>
   Martha married an orthodontist, moved to Memphis and died in
1949. But she lived long enough to see her father's mill sold and
the new owner rename the company for its best-known product. Today
it's part of the Pillsbury empire, though the offices remain in
Nashville and the flour and cornmeal are milled in Jackson, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the Martha White jingle has been sung by
everyone from Porter Wagoner to Marty Stuart to Allison Krause. One
band even named itself Hot Rize, Martha White's trademarked name
for leavening.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-seven bands from as far away as Switzerland entered the
100th-birthday contest. The winner, a Virginia ensemble called Big
Country Bluegrass, performed the song on the Opry in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the longest version we've ever heard,'' says company
spokeswoman Linda Carman.
</P>
<P>
   But that's OK. To fans of biscuits and bluegrass, the Martha
White theme is downright classical. Or, as Keillor once put it,
it's ``the Aristotle Contemplating the Bust of Homer of bluegrass
jingles.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Auchmutey writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
