<HEADER>
A0170 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-CONVERTS-2ND     07-30 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-CONVERTS-2NDTAKE01-CO </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA: I get icy.''
</P>
<P>
   From communism
</P>
<P>
   to Communion
</P>
<P>
   It's midday on a Friday, and Genovese has returned from Happy
Herman's on Cheshire Bridge Road with a split-loaf deli sandwich
and two bottles of wine. He likes good Chiantis, but an Argentine
red has struck his curiosity. He opens it for lunch and, without
making a show of it, says grace before his guest has joined him at
the table. ``Look,'' he says moments later, ``the critical question
is whether you believe in the immortal soul. I accept the promise
of faith _ as a mystery to be unraveled in due time.''
</P>
<P>
   You can find old Marxists anywhere, their all-encompassing views
of history rusted and lying about like old Camaros on cinder
blocks. It's harder to catch one taking Communion. ``The question
of atheism,'' Genovese says, ``was a philosophical one. The rest _
the acceptance of the church, receiving Communion and so forth _
was a matter of grace. It becomes a question of faith, of whether
you can feel the faith.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife's journey, he thinks, had fewer obstacles. She had been
a nonbeliever, but her father's background was Calvinist and she
had always had an intellectual interest in religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought she might become a Presbyterian,'' he says. ``When
she said Catholic, I gulped. I was surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was his own change of heart that surprised people. Their
friend John Shelton Reed, a writer and sociologist at the
University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, had known for 15 years
that Genovese's Marxism was coming loose from its moorings. But he
hadn't expected him to be kneeling in a pew. ``I guess he got tired
of waiting out in the car while Betsey was in church,'' Reed says.
</P>
<P>
   There was more gallantry in it than that. Once Betsey began
going to Mass, Gene _ still calling himself an atheist _ went ``in
the belief that a man should go with his wife to church.''
</P>
<P>
   Within a year he was asking Father Richard Lopez, the priest who
had given his wife instruction in the faith, to hear his
confession. He had been away for 50 years, but not in the eyes of
the church. ``It was not an inordinately long confession,''
Genovese says. ``Think about that for a minute. That first
confession after 50 years was a piece of cake. It's the next one
you have to worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   He has heard what his critics think _ that in trading Marxism
for Catholicism, he merely traded one system of absolutes for
another. John Womack, a historian at Harvard University and himself
a Marxist and one-time Catholic, is at a loss to explain it but
speculates that on one level it's perhaps an evolution of ideas
Genovese has had for many years. ``One of the things he was
interested in 20 years ago,'' Womack says, ``was Euro-communism and
the role of the Catholic Church. There is a particular strain of
Catholicism that gets revived from time to time that's very
egalitarian and in many ways sympathetic to Marxism. I don't know,
it may just be that these ideas just kept working in his head.''
</P>
<P>
   But Genovese has gone from categorical atheism to the Baltimore
catechism, and Womack grants the implied point. ``Anyone who'd
known Gene over the years probably thought, `Good God, this is one
more strange thing he's done.'''
</P>
<P>
   An explanation often heard is that once the Soviet Union
collapsed, Genovese needed a spiritual anchor as much as a
political faith. Even Sheila O'Connor-Ambrose, no Marxist, says,
``I think they're both comfortable with authority and
institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   But none of their friends sees it as trading one faith for
another. O'Connor-Ambrose's husband, Douglas, who teaches history
at Hamilton College in Utica, N.Y., underwent a journey of his own,
from Catholicism to Marxism and back. He says of the experience:
``What's involved in that shift is so fundamental. It involves an
entirely different understanding of the meaning of life. With
Marxism, you had the idea that you could determine the processes of
history, that you could know how it would end. But faith accepts
the limitations of human reason. It accepts the existence of
mystery in our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those mysteries is the Trinity, the Christian idea of God,
Jesus Christ and the Holy Spirit as one. Even when he was still an
atheist, only five years ago, Genovese was writing:
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot understand how Christians, without ceasing to be
Christians, can retreat one inch from a belief that Jesus is the
second person of a triune God, the Christ, the Redeemer. If other
religions offer equally valid ways to salvation and if Christianity
itself may be understood solely as a code of morals and ethics,
then we may as well all become Buddhists or, better, atheists. I
intend no offense, but it takes one to know one.''
</P>
<P>
   More recently, he was rising from his knees with hundreds of
others at the Cathedral of Christ the King, making the sign of the
cross and accepting the blessing of Father Ronald Higgins. ``Go in
peace,'' Higgins bade them.
</P>
<P>
   Mass had ended, and the organist began playing ``America the
Beautiful.'' For a moment, at least, the wall between church and
state was lowered, and all sang as one as they filed out on a
Saturday evening, their voices filling the huge cathedral. Turning
from his pew into the aisle, Gene Genovese sang as he prayed,
devoutly as only a true believer can.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
