<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0171 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-JAKES31-COX     07-30 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JAKES31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A message of hope _ that's bedrock for the well-known evangelist
from Dallas, who has drawn thousands of women to the Georgia Dome
this week
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Get ready with T.D. Jakes!''
</P>
<P>
   That's the welcome offered to thousands of people who tune in to
Bishop T.D. Jakes' cable television show. But it could also serve
as a rallying cry for the charismatic evangelist as he makes
himself at home in Atlanta this week.
</P>
<P>
   Since arriving here Monday night for his fourth annual ``Woman,
Thou Art Loosed!'' conference, Jakes has been treated like a hero.
Homeless women cried in his arms. Children hugged him. And
dignitaries such as Georgia Gov. Roy Barnes made time to meet him.
</P>
<P>
   But Jakes' most enthusiastic fans were the thousands of women
who filled the Georgia Dome Thursday and Friday night to hear him
preach. Many were expected to return to the dome at 11 a.m. today
for the close of the conference.
</P>
<P>
   Jakes, 42, the senior pastor of the Potter's House in Dallas, a
nondenominational megachurch with 18,000 members, began the
three-day event Thursday with a message of hope, despite the tragic
events that were playing out only a few miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does not matter what you go through,'' Jakes told the
Georgia Dome crowd, just a few hours after a man shot and killed
nine people in Atlanta before taking his own life outside a gas
station in Acworth (Ga.). ``It matters how you go through it.
Trouble doesn't have to stop for you to have victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebounding from tragedy is one of Jakes' favorite themes. The
conference, which began in the early '90s as a Sunday school
lesson, attempts to show women how they can transcend the mistakes
of their past through Jesus. Jakes delivers that message through a
blend of music, therapeutic advice and foot-stomping preaching.
</P>
<P>
   It's a message with broad appeal, attracting tens of thousands
of women _ black, white and Latino _ to the dome Thursday and
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to get women like this unless our needs are
being met,'' said Sheila Dalton of St. Louis. ``You don't come from
around the country to hear good cheerleading. You come for
healing.''
</P>
<P>
   Jakes knows how to offer such healing. He also knows how to play
to a crowd. Even though he warned the thousands of women packed
into the dome Thursday that he wasn't there to perform, he couldn't
help himself in the end.
</P>
<P>
   As he hurtled to the climax of his sermon, Jakes raised his arms
and did a jitterbug-like dance.
</P>
<P>
   Cheers fell like confetti as he twirled to a stop on the massive
stage.
</P>
<P>
   Jakes stayed busy earlier in the week, holding news conferences,
meeting with fans and offering prayers for those in need.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, he attended the premier of his play, ``Woman, Thou
Art Loosed,'' at the Atlanta Civic Center, where he met with a
handful of women from area homeless shelters. They were part of a
larger group Jakes had bused in to see the performance.
</P>
<P>
   One of his guests, LaToya Procter, 28, dabbed her eyes as she
shared her struggles with the pastor. She's been looking for work
while living in a shelter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no income, nothing coming in,'' she told Jakes. ``But I
pray to God every day before I leave that he will provide.''
</P>
<P>
   Jakes offered comfort, draping an arm around her shoulder. ``God
is a God of second chances,'' he told her.
</P>
<P>
   Jakes' wife, Serita, provided one of the week's most touching
moments when she was asked why her husband appeals so much to
women.
</P>
<P>
   After a moment of reflection, she recalled once sharing her
fears with her husband that she might not be able to handle the
public glare of being his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Jakes talked to her as a minister, she said, reminding her of
God's strength. She said she felt as if she had stumbled into a
fairy tale when she married.
</P>
<P>
   Jakes looked at his wife and smiled. He rubbed her shoulders as
she blushed. But Serita Jakes had one more thing to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was my husband's first 'Woman, Thou Art Loosed'
conference,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For once, Jakes was speechless.
</P>
<P>
   John Blake writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
