<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, July 31, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the high temperature at Havre, Mont., was 105
degrees. On Saturday, the mercury will struggle to reach the low
70s as a cooler Canadian air mass continues to build east-southeast
across the upper Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of thunderstorms will erupt across the Great Lakes
region along the leading edge of the Canadian air mass as very
humid air, which has stifled the region this week, is lifted by a
cool front. A few of the storms could become severe, with damaging
winds and large hail posing a threat in spots. Heavy rain is also
possible.
</P>
<P>
   The risk of heavy thunderstorms will heighten over parts of
Kansas, western Oklahoma and northwest Texas as a disturbance
associated with the monsoon pattern over Arizona and New Mexico
approaches the southern Plains and interacts with a front and humid
air from the Gulf of Mexico. The risk will be particularly high
Saturday night, when there will be a surge of moisture from the
Gulf of Mexico. Heavy rains are possible.
</P>
<P>
   Torrid heat and stifling humidity will continue to grip a large
region bounded by the Gulf Coast, Southeast and Middle Atlantic
states while intensifying in New York state and parts of southern
and western New England. Isolated thunderstorms will bring spotty,
temporary relief to a few places. Spotty storms will develop mainly
near Florida's Atlantic Coast and the Gulf Coast from northeast
Texas to Florida as the leading edge of the sea breeze moves inland
and lifts hot, humid air. A few storms will also speckle the
Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Sultry Chicago
</P>
<P>
   Record humidity stifled Chicago early Friday as the dew point
was stuck at 82 degrees for five hours. By definition, the dew
point is the threshold to which the air temperature must be lowered
to bring invisible water vapor to the brink of condensation. When
the dew point is 82 degrees, not much cooling is needed for
condensation, a sign of an extremely large amount of water vapor in
the air. As sultry dew points rise above 70 degrees, the rate of
evaporation of sweat from human skin is increasingly reduced,
thereby limiting the body's ability to cool itself. The air feels
stifling.
</P>
</TEXT>
