<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEME-PARTYNIGHTS-ART-2TAKES-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DATE NIGHT, N.Y.: FROM LUVSURVEYS TO HULA HOOPS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 1) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to append art note)   (ART ADV: Two photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By JULIA CHAPLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As if New York's bars and clubs didn't have enough
singles rubbing elbows and noses, some of them are taking
mating-mixology to the next level: mixer bashes disguised as theme
nights.
</P>
<P>
   Forget fern bars and zinfandel. Trendy night spots have been
giving singles parties a hipster makeover, with all the giggly
savvy of a generation weaned on too many episodes of ``The Dating
Game'' and MTV's bawdy update, ``Singled Out.''
</P>
<P>
   Downtown weekly events like ``Punk Rock Karaoke,'' held at
Arlene's Grocery, and the Hula Hoop competition at the Tortilla
Flats restaurant have a decidedly kitschy edge. They are a backlash
against chichi clubs, where locating your soul mate _ providing you
can make it past the velvet ropes _ can be as unnerving as a job
interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter if you're a fat old man or a model, it's
still hard to meet people in the city,'' said Trang Choung, 26, a
research editor at Marie Claire magazine, who gives campy Monday
night parties at the downtown club Veruka. ``We offer games and
alcohol to get the crowd past those first awkward stages, and then
they're left to their own devices.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the offerings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOTHRA (Monday nights at B Bar; 358 Bowery, at Fourth Street; $5
cover)
</P>
<P>
   At Mothra, the weekly social named after the radioactive insect
that battled Godzilla, Audrey Bernstein has been the hostess of ice
breakers like a retro ski party and an India-themed dress-up party.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, a contest sponsored by Playboy magazine was held
with prizes bestowed in the categories of ``hairiest chest,''
``shortest shorts'' and ``naughtiest nightgown.'' The actors
Laurence Fishburne and Tony Danza and 1964's Playmate of the Year
all came out for the spectacle, which featured a king-size bed
covered with red velvet, set up in the garden for photos by
Mothra's photographer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't find a date,'' lamented Jane Pratt, the editor in
chief of Jane magazine, who wore a low-cut dress and silver high
heels. ``But the cool part was you could pretend you were making
fun of everything but in reality you got to lie in a huge bed with
a cute guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Overheard pickup line: ``Will you pose for me?''
</P>
<P>
   Turn-ons: Possibility of meeting Gene Simmons of Kiss.
</P>
<P>
   Turnoffs: Possibility of going home with Gene Simmons.
</P>
<P>
   Soundtrack: Remixed retro classics like Madonna's 1980's hit
``Burning Up,'' played at low speed, and a dance hall version of
Barry Manilow's ``Copacabana.''
</P>
<P>
   Dress code: Retro sexy. For women, Daryl K hip-huggers and
slinky disco gold halter tops. For men, cheap Guayabera shirts and
$400 Gucci khakis, Ray-Ban aviator shades, sideburns optional.
</P>
<P>
   VERUKA (Monday nights; 525 Broome Street, at Thompson Street; no
cover)
</P>
<P>
   ``I never have trouble meeting girls anyway,'' sniffed Tim
Durant, 25, a model with a Hamptons' tan, nursing a martini at a
recent singles party at Veruka.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Durant volunteered for the makeshift ``Dating
Game,'' where he was asked questions like: ``If you were an animal,
what would your mating call be?'' Trang Chuong and Kathy
Szwedzinski have been throwing these love-connection fetes with a
'70s nostalgia feel for the last three months.
</P>
<P>
   Past events have included Twister floor games, a
bachelor/bachelorette party with kissing games like spin the bottle
and truth or dare, and a matchmaking exercise where revelers wear
numbered tags and check a bulletin board to see if any secret
admirers have left a message.
</P>
<P>
   Overheard pickup line: Too loud to hear.
</P>
<P>
   Turn-ons: Might get to kiss a model.
</P>
<P>
   Turnoffs: He/she might be wearing braces.
</P>
<P>
   Soundtrack: Bittersweet make-out anthems like Human League's
``Don't You Want Me?'' and Elvis' ``Crazy Little Thing Called
Love.''
</P>
<P>
   Dress code: Fashionably cute. For women, the models' favorite,
Earl Jeans (size 26 waist), and a DKNY tube top. For men, anything
by Helmut Lang, bright Nike sandals.
</P>
<P>
   LUVBUZZ (1438 Third Avenue, at 82d Street; no cover)
</P>
<P>
   This new Upper East Side bar promises ``the end of the frat boy
singles bar scene,'' but so far it attracts many more women than
men. Maybe the guys aren't that comfortable amid the suggestive
decor _ heart-colored love seats, Latex curtains and honeycomb
motifs _ surrounding the computer monitors and digital cameras that
are part of the bar's elaborate ``Date-a-Base'' system.
</P>
<P>
   Patrons are encouraged to fill out a Luvsurvey, which asks for
personal information like the celebrity you are most often compared
with. Your image is then fed into a computer, and a ``Luvhandle''
is assigned to you. If a match is made on line, either between
patrons across the room or those using the Web site from home, the
staff, or Luvbuzz bees, will arrange a date at Luvbuzz.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many people were sitting home behind their computers and
having online chats instead of face-to-face dating,'' said Cathy
Cervenka, the director for digital media and dating systems at
Luvbuzz, during a recent round of ``boozy bingo,'' one of the
quirky theme parties, held on Monday evenings.
</P>
<P>
   Overheard pickup line: ``I bet you own an iMac.''
</P>
<P>
   Turn-ons: Men manly enough to be seen slurping Buzz Cones, like
Sno-Kones with alcohol, through licorice whips.
</P>
<P>
   Turnoffs: Lovelorn singles with carpal tunnel syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Soundtrack: Sentimental favorites from Sarah McLachlan to Dean
Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Dress code: Office casual. For women, Prada nylon backpacks and
Calvin Klein solid-colored slimming separates. For men, Calvin
Klein's CK One cologne, loosened ties.
</P>
<P>
   TORTILLA FLATS (Wednesday night Hula Hoop competition; 767
Washington Street, at 12th Street; no cover)
</P>
<P>
   ``There hasn't been this much excitement since Siegfried met
Roy!'' said Steve Pagnotta, the pajama-clad emcee at the Hula Hoop
competition held at this Greenwich Village restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Here, under the dusty Christmas lights, secretaries, magazine
editors and stockbrokers gather with meat-packing district locals,
and attempt to twirl the hoop for a full three minutes without
knocking into platters of refried beans. (The winner gets
short-lived fame and a free pitcher of margaritas.)
</P>
<P>
   The scene on a recent Wednesday: a guy resembling Fabio with an
open-to-the-waist silk shirt gyrated a pink hoop to the Weather
Girls' hit ``It's Raining Men.''
</P>
<P>
   Overheard pickup line: ``Hey, baby, uh ...'' (too drunk to
complete the thought).
</P>
<P>
   Turn-ons: Hula Hoopers are surprisingly approachable.
</P>
<P>
   Turnoffs: Hula Hoopers too drunk to remember your name five
minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   Soundtrack: Led Zeppelin's ``When the Levee Breaks'' and ``Ring
My Bell'' by Anita Ward, blared to distortion.
</P>
<P>
   Dress code: Business dishabille. For women, office gear modified
for Hula Hooping, i.e. buttoned shirts tied in a French knot above
the navel, heels removed for lower center of gravity. For men, a
Brooks Brothers suit with the jacket dangling in spilt sour mix.
</P>
<P>
   PUNK ROCK KARAOKE (Monday nights at Arlene's Grocery; 95 Stanton
Street; no cover)
</P>
<P>
   When VH-1 recently taped a pilot show called ``Celebrity
Karaoke,'' based on the longstanding sing-along night at the Elbow
Room, a club in Greenwich Village, there were bound to be some
grumblings from the underground. The truly alternative Punk Rock
Karaoke, held at Arlene's Grocery, has become the place to be seen
and to make the scene for nostalgic punks and the grungy East
Village set.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the lo-fi nature of the genre, there's a grumpy
emcee with an English accent who insults would-be participants, and
a live band that accompanies the amateurs, who read songs off
homemade lyric sheets instead of monitors. Although Punk Rock
Karaoke is not specifically billed as a singles party, people do
turn out to mosh and mingle.
</P>
<P>
   For punk aficionados nothing seems to be sexier than seeing a
member of the opposite sex belt out ``God Save the Queen'' by the
Sex Pistols, said Trisha Mulcahy, the bleached-blond lead singer of
a band named Superlux. At a recent Monday night party, she wore
silver sequined pants and a white T-shirt that she ripped freshly
for the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time I tried very hard to look cool,'' Ms. Mulcahy
said, after a well-received version of the Clash hit ``I Fought the
Law.'' ``But then it got boring. Now, I find it much sexier to
snarl and scream at the top of your lungs.''
</P>
<P>
   Overheard pickup line: ``I bet you'd look fantastic singing Iggy
Pop's ``I Wanna Be Your Dog!''
</P>
<P>
   Turn-ons: Visualize yourself as the star of VH-1's ``Where Are
They Now?''
</P>
<P>
   Turnoffs: Good chance of sustaining irreversible hearing loss.
Creepy guys from failed punk rock bands trying to get a free beer.
</P>
<P>
   Soundtrack: Full catalog of songs from the Stooges and the
Misfits.
</P>
<P>
   Dress code: Clashing loudly. For women, either too much eyeliner
and ripped fishnets or the clean sexy look of the sitcom
``Friends.'' For men, combat boots, despite the heat, and torn
concert T-shirts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
