<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0189 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-30 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TWO SIDES OF FLAP OVER SAIPAN LABOR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Carmencita ``Chie'' Abad was an accounting clerk in
the Philippines when she paid a recruiter $2,000 so she could work
in a garment factory in Saipan, a U.S. territory in the Northern
Mariana Islands.
</P>
<P>
   Abad said she anticipated it would be a good job _ after all,
it's the United States _ but instead she said she toiled 84 to 100
hours a week for $2.15 an hour in a dust-filled factory that makes
clothes for the Gap.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese workers there have it worse, Abad said. They're
forced to live in barracks with no running water and no air
conditioning in a climate that's hotter than Houston's. Many also
have to take a loan to pay the recruiter's fee of $5,000 to $7,000,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Saipan is a U.S. territory, the minimum wage is
$3.05 an hour instead of the $5.15 on the mainland. When Saipan was
made a U.S. territory in 1976, the United States agreed that the
island could set its own minimum wage and its own immigration laws.
</P>
<P>
   Abad is in Houston for the next two weeks to put pressure on
U.S. Rep. Tom DeLay, R-Texas, to stop blocking, as Abad put it, a
bill that would extend the $5.15 minimum wage to Saipan. The bill
also would require the island to adhere to U.S. immigration laws
and require factories in the Northern Mariana Islands to abide by
U.S. labor laws. Otherwise, they would be unable to continue using
the label ``Made in the USA.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. George Miller, D-Calif., who introduced the
legislation, has been told by the Republican House leadership the
bill won't go forward, said Miller's spokesman, Daniel Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DeLAY SAYS FACTORIES OK &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The bill doesn't have much support, so DeLay isn't holding up
anything, said Tony Rudy, DeLay's deputy chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   Rudy said DeLay opposes the bill because bureaucrats 12,000
miles away in Washington shouldn't be trampling on the sovereignty
of the islands, which have the right to set their own minimum wage
and immigration laws.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the factories aren't bad, he said. DeLay traveled to
Saipan last year. He said he found them better than garment
factories in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Rudy speculated that the factories will move to mainland China
and Bangladesh if the minimum wage is increased to $5.15.
</P>
<P>
   It's truly remarkable how partisan this has become, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The left sees it as capitalism run amuck, and the right sees
it as a free market that works,'' Rudy said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariana Islands became a U.S. territory primarily for trade
reasons. Companies don't have to pay import tariffs on products
made there, said Bob Buzzanco, a University of Houston assistant
professor who specializes in global history. They can get away with
a lot of things, such as skirting U.S. labor laws, that they can't
get away with on the mainland, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Garment workers in Saipan have filed a class action in Los
Angeles against 18 major retailers and 11 contractors for what San
Diego lawyer Patrick Daniels said is indentured servitude of the
guest workers. The Gap is one of the retailers that has been sued.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CHINESE GET MONEY, FAITH &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gap spokesman Alan Marks said many of the allegations Abad made
are in the lawsuit, and thus he can't comment on them. But he
pointed to the Gap's code of vendor conduct, which prohibits its
contractors from using forced labor, paying less than the local
minimum wage or requiring employees to work more than 60 hours a
week on a regular basis. In addition, factories must be
well-ventilated and employees must get one day off a week.
</P>
<P>
   Gap employees also monitor the factories, Marks said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Lou Sheldon, chairman of the Traditional Values
Coalition, a Christian lobbying group on Capitol Hill, said he has
visited Saipan twice and found the factories and dorms clean and
safe.
</P>
<P>
   In three to four years _ even after paying recruiting fees _ the
workers can earn more in Saipan than they can in their entire lives
in China, Sheldon said. They take the money back to China and live
comfortable lives.
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon, who represents 43,000 churches, said he is opposed to
the Miller bill because the churches have a vested interest in
keeping the factories humming. The influx of factory workers opens
up a great opportunity to preach to people whose countries, such as
China, have made it next to impossible for evangelists to preach,
he said. So the workers go back to China with money and full of
faith.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
