<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TAIWAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN'S CHINA ENVOY REAFFIRMS SEPARATE-AND-EQUAL STANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SETH FAISON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Taiwan's special envoy to China delivered a
long-awaited statement Friday on Taiwan-China relations, saying
that President Lee Teng-hui's call for ``special state-to-state''
ties with Beijing did not rule out eventual reunification.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the envoy, Koo Chen-fu, endorsed Taiwan's new position that
it will continue talks with China only under the guise of a meeting
of two equal and separate states, a position that has infuriated
leaders in Beijing, who see that as a move away from, and not
toward, reunification.
</P>
<P>
   Koo's statement appeared to scotch any chance that Beijing would
go ahead with a visit to Taiwan by China's top Taiwan negotiator,
Wang Daohan, who would have been the most senior Chinese official
to visit Taiwan if he were to go, as originally scheduled, in
October.
</P>
<P>
   In Beijing, Chinese officials immediately denounced Koo's
statement as a clear violation of a 1992 agreement between China
and Taiwan to conduct negotiations on the basis that both sides
recognized the principle of a single Chinese nation, or ``one
China,'' with the goal of negotiations being eventual
reunification.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing did not formally cancel Wang's visit, at least not yet.
But its declaration that the basis of all contacts, exchanges and
dialogue now ceased to exist points to a serious deterioration in
China-Taiwan relations.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidentally, Taiwan was swept with rumors that China was
launching a missile attack overnight, because the entire island
succumbed to a blackout that began late Thursday, the worst
electricity shortage in decades. Power was restored in Taipei
before dawn on Friday, and the authorities reassured countless
worried callers that the blackout had nothing to do with politics
or war.
</P>
<P>
   Although the chances of military conflict between China and
Taiwan now appear to be small, Washington has said a breakdown in
talks is dangerous for security in the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials have said it is critical to keep China-Taiwan
negotiations moving forward to keep the potential for military
conflict at bay. Over the last year, Washington has increasingly
pressured Taiwan to agree to more substantive talks, and some
analysts said they believed that a reason that Lee changed his
stance was to block additional talks, which he judged to be
detrimental to the Taiwan side.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Koo repeated Taiwan's mixed message of a desire for
greater separation from China at the same time that he pledged a
commitment to eventual reunification.
</P>
<P>
   ``The existing policy toward unification has not changed,'' Koo
told a news briefing Friday afternoon in Taipei. ``What we see as
`one China' is something for the future, since China at present is
divided and ruled separately by two equal sovereign states in
existence at the same time, hence a special state-to-state
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Koo urged his Chinese counterpart to still consider going to
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Again, I would like to take the opportunity to extend my most
sincere welcome to Wang, because communication is more urgently
needed especially when there are differences,'' said Koo, who is
chairman of the Straits Exchange Foundation in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Wading into the semantical jungle that has confused the new
position since Lee announced it on July 9, Koo argued that it was
not technically correct to refer to the stand as a ``two state
theory,'' the phrase favored by the Taiwan media to describe his
demand that Beijing accord equal status to Taipei in talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``To oversimplify President Lee's statement as a two-state
theory is a distortion that can easily cause misunderstanding,''
Koo said. ``We want to pursue future unification of China based on
equality in negotiations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
