<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0194 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIGITAL-LA-LADN     07-30 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-LA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM BOTS TO ZEN IN CYBERSPACE 
</HEADLINE>
 (Weekly Digital L.A. column)  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ I see a lot of books these days related to
technology and entertainment, some of which I'd suggest you check
out. Among them:
</P>
<P>
   _ One useful reference, though doomed to be outdated almost
immediately, is ``BotGuide,'' by Michael Wolff and Peter Rutten
(258 pages, Harper San Francisco; $19.95).
</P>
<P>
   The creators of the ``NetGuide'' series now have dived into the
brave new world of bots, little software programs that go out on
the Internet and do things for you. The guide reviews hundreds of
bots, from all kinds of Web sites and for all kinds of purposes,
and tells you how to use them to simplify your life on the Net.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Fat Tire, A Celebration of the Mountain Bike'' (141 pages,
Chronicle Books; $24.95) is a fun, funky look at one very high-tech
corner of our leisure world, the mountain bike.
</P>
<P>
   From the tire tread glued to the cover to the examinations of
such biking subcultures as soul riders and bike messengers, it
covers almost as much ground as an extreme racer. There are
sections on the history and anatomy of bikes, interviews with world
champions, dissections of great mountain biking destinations and
lots of great photos.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Zen Computer: Mindfulness and the Machine'' by Philip Toshio
Sudo (209 pages, Simon &AMP; Schuster; $22) is a delightful little book
about finding harmony with your computer. Sudo, a musician and
martial artist from Hawaii, squeezes his advice into near
epigrammatic prose, finding soul in the new machine.
</P>
<P>
   It's a wonderful antidote to the craziness of a world sliced
into milliseconds, urging a calmness and peace that can even be
found in what we may think is the exact opposite of Zen, a
computer. Even with technology, Sudo argues, we can learn how one
 &UR; !ital! &LR; can &UR; !off! &LR;  equal zero.
</P>
<P>
   GIVE 'EM THE CHAIR: One of the coolest gaming, or any other
entertainment, accessories that I've come across in recent times is
the Intensor chair, from a company that was called BSG but recently
changed its name to Imeron and moved to Cary, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   In the Intensor's LX configuration, it looks something like a
normal office chair, except for the 9-foot cable connecting it to a
foot-square amplifier.
</P>
<P>
   Plug the $179 LX in, connect it to your favorite gaming console,
PC, stereo or home theater system, and you're about to get
physically immersed in sound.
</P>
<P>
   The chair has a huge speaker located between your legs and two
others on the outside of your thighs. Another speaker is hidden
under the slim cushion of the back and two more speakers are higher
on the back.
</P>
<P>
   Two tiny slider controls on the side change the volume and
``rumble'' effect. The result is remarkable, punching a game's
sound through your gut with every rev of a race car engine or
report of a gun.
</P>
<P>
   I do have to say the chair isn't perfect, however. The volume
slider control on the chair I tested had come off during shipment
and required a slight amount of ingenuity to make it work.
</P>
<P>
   And the company offers a ``free'' extra cushion for the chair
(you have to send in $3.50 to cover shipping). Given the
vibrational pounding you'll take from a couple of hours of Quake II
or Gran Turismo in the chair, or the wear and tear of watching a
couple of movies in it, you should get the cushion. But it just
seems silly that the company makes people send away for it.
</P>
<P>
   BSG/Imeron also offers the chair in a much cheaper FX
configuration, basically without the office chair base. Instead, it
folds like a clamshell, with a sturdy handle at the hinge so you
can more easily move around the 19-pound seat. Overall, I'd give
the product a very strong A-minus.
</P>
<P>
   STAYING ALIVE: One of the more remarkable side projects that
Steven Spielberg has been involved in since creating the
much-lauded ``Schindler's List'' in 1993 is his Survivors of the
Shoah Visual History Foundation, which has videotaped the stories
of more than 50,000 survivors of Nazi Germany's attempts to
exterminate Jews and others during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Now the foundation has released a CD-ROM called Survivors:
Testimonies of the Holocaust through Knowledge Adventure and Simon
&AMP; Schuster Interactive. It is hosted by Winona Ryder and Leonardo
DiCaprio and features the videotaped stories of four of the people
taped in the Survivors project.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't light viewing, and in fact the disc is rated for
teens and above. Along with the 80 minutes of videotaped stories,
it includes a link to a Web site, a timeline, a map that follows
the trail of the four speakers, a searchable glossary and more. It
will run on either a Power Macintosh or Windows 95 or 98 system.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors say never forget, and Spielberg certainly is trying to
make sure that doesn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   NOTES FROM THE UNDERGROUND: You won't find the latest Civil War
simulation from the great Sid Meier on store shelves anywhere.
Instead, Antietam! _ based on the game system in Meier's
much-lauded Gettysburg! _ will be available this fall through the
Web site ( &UR; !bold! &LR; www.firaxis.com &UR; !off! &LR; ) of Meier's company,
Firaxis Games.
</P>
<P>
   It's the first title in Meier's Great Battles series of games.
Meier is promising several new kinds of troops (they even have
red-pantalooned Zouaves), better terrain and artificial opponents,
and a variety of kinds of engagements, from small skirmishes to the
entire battle, one of the bloodiest and most critical of the Civil
War.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE CALENDAR: Among the significant events coming up in the
next several days:
</P>
<P>
   _ Herring on Hollywood. The Internet business magazine Red
Herring comes to the Century Plaza Hotel in Century City from
Sunday to Tuesday to ponder entertainment and technology. Pricey
gathering, but lots of well-placed decision-makers on both sides of
that chasm, if last year's confab in Newport Beach is any guide. Go
to Red Herring's Web site at
 &UR; !bold! &LR; www.herring.com/events/home.html &UR; !off! &LR;  for more
information.
</P>
<P>
   _ The American Film Institute in Los Feliz holds its monthly
salon on entertainment technology on Thursday, focusing this month
on creature effects. The seminars, usually held at 7:30 p.m. on the
first Thursday of the month, are routinely engaging, with a pretty
remarkable array of speakers. Go to  &UR; !bold! &LR; www.afi.org &UR; !off! &LR;  for
more information.
</P>
<P>
   _ Venice Interactive Community, or VIC, will sponsor a seminar
on online interactive learning systems, featuring three companies
that specialize in distance learning software. The event includes
the usual VIC socializing and networking beforehand, tables with
information about event sponsors, plus the presentations from 7 to
10 p.m. Tuesday at the Skirball Cultural Center, 2701 N. Sepulveda
Blvd., Los Angeles, at the top of the Sepulveda Pass.
</P>
<P>
   (To reach David Bloom with stories, tips and other information
on the intersection of art, entertainment and technology, e-mail
him at davidbloom(at)earthlink.net, or call (818) 713-3678.)
</P>
</TEXT>
