<P>
   TAX-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The Senate passes a $792 billion
Republican tax cut, moving Congress toward a showdown with
President Clinton over how the nation can best use trillions of
dollars in projected federal budget surpluses. The vote was 57-43.
Four Democrats joined 53 Republicans in support of the bill, while
two Republicans and 41 Democrats voted against it. By Richard W.
Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   SPEND-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Congress, determined to increase
military spending and unable to cut the rest of the budget deeper
than it has already done, is certain to wipe out the projected
$14.5 billion surplus in coming weeks. Now the Republican
leadership is scouring the entire federal budget, seeking unspent
money from programs like Medicaid, welfare benefits and interstate
highway funds to fill a spending gap that is running upwards of $15
billion. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-EMBASSY (Beijing) _ Ending more than two months of bitter
acrimony, the United States and China agree that Washington will
pay $4.5 million in compensation for NATO's bombing of the Chinese
embassy in Yugoslavia on May 7. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   BALKANS-U.S. (Sarajevo, Bosnia-Herzegovina) _ President Clinton
proposes an economic package worth nearly $700 million to promote a
stable and prosperous Balkan future, but he says Serbia will only
be part of that future when President Slobodan Milosevic is gone.
By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   GA-SHOOT-RDP (Atlanta) _ Ledeall: Developments in the shooting
and suicide, including more on the motive behind the shooting, why
the suspect was never charged in the earlier killing of his wife
and mother-in-law, what is in the notes. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   TRIPP-INDICT (Ellicott City, Md.) _ Linda Tripp i indicted by a
state grand jury for secretly taping phone conversations with
Monica Lewinsky. By David Johnston. (With photo.)
</P>
