<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HINDUTEMPLE-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HINDU TEMPLE EXPANDS ITS COMPLEX TO ACCOMMODATE A DIVERSE
COMMUNITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TARA DOOLEY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ At the D/FW Hindu Temple Society, worshippers
navigate their way around the yellow tape that cautions them as
they travel through the construction site attached to their main
temple of prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Dirt is turning at the Hindu Temple complex. And temple society
organizers are making room for a community of Hindus that began
with a few families meeting north of Dallas nearly 20 years ago and
now draws more than 1,260 members from throughout Fort
Worth-Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The temple, at 1605 N. Britain Road, has become an open door for
area Hindus seeking a place of refuge and worship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what has happened is that we have been in a constant
state of expansion ever since we started,'' said Arlington resident
Phillip M. Ramsaroop, a member and past president of the temple
society. ``We have not stopped what we are doing, but we have
increased our activities. This, as far as I can see, will
continue.''
</P>
<P>
   To accommodate continued growth in the area's Hindu community,
the temple society has undertaken a $1.5 million expansion project,
expected to be completed in about two years, said Fort Worth
resident Vinoda Kumar, a vice president of the temple society.
</P>
<P>
   When done, capacity in the main temple used for prayer will
increase from 600 to 850. In addition, the concrete-block buildings
will be shaped into a traditional Hindu-style temple by artists and
architects from India, said Padmakar Kulkarni, chairman of the
society's board of trustees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have big plans,'' Kulkarni said. ``It all depends on the
funds. We are careful not to do too much at one time.''
</P>
<P>
   The society's history demonstrates that point.
</P>
<P>
   It became official in 1983, meeting in rental properties in
Plano, north of Dallas. It bought property in Irving on the
northwestern outskirts of Dallas, about 11 years ago and moved
operations to an old house on the land before building a new temple
in 1991. Two years later, the society added a cultural center with
classrooms for religious education and language classes and a large
auditorium for meetings and wedding receptions.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the key to the society's continued growth has been
its openness to various expressions of Hinduism.
</P>
<P>
   The temple differs from others in India and in the United States
because it is not devoted to one deity, society organizers said. In
addition, instead of focusing on one set of traditions, it offers
communities from different Indian states and South America a place
to practice their individual rituals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a varied community, but at the same time, they are all
coming together,'' Kulkarni said. ``Here, everyone comes together
to make a united temple. Our constitution demands that everyone is
represented.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the temple society is an umbrella organization
that offers space and services to groups who trace their roots to
the Tamil, Bengali and Gujarati communities of India or Guyana, for
example.
</P>
<P>
   Events at the temple are open to the entire community, and there
are statues of 14 deities of varying importance to the different
Indian communities represented at the temple. For example, the
Kerala community might organize an event to honor the deity Shri
Ayyappa, particularly important to traditions from the Kerala state
in India.
</P>
<P>
   However, events such as the Sept. 3 birthday celebration of Sri
Krishna will probably be attended by much of the membership,
organizers said.
</P>
<P>
   For Ramsaroop, who was born in Guyana and whose family
originally comes from northern India, being involved in the temple
has introduced him to Hindu traditions that he had only heard of in
passing.
</P>
<P>
   ``By associating myself with this community and seeing what they
do ... I recognize that we are not worshipping any different God,''
Ramsaroop said. ``It has made me a stronger person in my beliefs.
It has made me a better person.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the temple society plan to continue building on that
foundation by adding facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Once the temple expansion is complete, the society hopes to add
a youth center and a meditation center, and to expand the temple's
library.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it looks like a messy place,'' Kulkarni said. ``But give
us some time. You will see it taking shape.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
