<HEADER>
A0208 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-     07-30 1267
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW LINCOLN SEDAN APPEALS TO YOUNGER SET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Finally, there's a Lincoln sedan that ought to appeal to upscale
consumers whose hair is just beginning to gray.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 LS, a sporty performance sedan in the same vein as the
Lexus GS 400, represents a departure from past Lincolns and should
give Ford Motor Co. and its Lincoln-Mercury Division dealers some
hope for the future.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not ready to pronounce the LS as good as a GS 400, but
that's OK. It costs about $10,000 less when comparably equipped.
And the LS brings to the market an American luxury car that
combines sporty performance, comfort and Japanese/European styling.
</P>
<P>
   There is a quick explanation for this unique combination:
Underneath, the Lincoln LS is really a Jaguar. It's based on the
same chassis as the all-new Jag S-series sedans. Ford says the two
vehicles share about 45 percent of their parts, although there are
significant styling differences and some differences in the way the
engines are built.
</P>
<P>
   The LS, whose styling was left to Lincoln-Mercury's California
design studio, is the first Lincoln product introduced since the
division pulled out of Detroit and moved to Southern California a
couple years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The LS and the new Jaguar XJS represent the first combined
efforts of Jag and Ford since Ford Motor Co. bought the English
carmaker in 1995. (The new Ford Thunderbird, which will be on its
way to market soon, is another vehicle that will share major
components with the Jaguar.)
</P>
<P>
   Along with the best-selling Lincoln Navigator sport-utility
wagon, the LS gives Lincoln dealers a two-vehicle arsenal with
which to attract affluent, professional baby boomers.
</P>
<P>
   That's a radical departure from Lincoln's image during the past
quarter-century as a manufacturer of boatsize luxury cars that
attracted primarily blue-collar consumers at or near retirement
age.
</P>
<P>
   The LS is the car that Lincoln had to build, but it took way too
long. During the past 10 years, U.S. automakers have stood aside
wringing their hands in frustration as Japanese and European
luxury-car makers have taken solid control of one of the most
lucrative market segments.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Lexus, the upscale arm of Japan's Toyota, this revival
and expansion of the luxury-car market has largely left the
old-line U.S. luxury vehicles behind. Nothing from Cadillac or
Lincoln has come close to the best of Lexus, Honda's Acura,
Nissan's Infiniti, BMW or Mercedes-Benz.
</P>
<P>
   The image of the American luxury car as a huge, lumbering, cushy
vehicle loaded with glued-on gratuitous, gaudy trim has so
completely turned off affluent, still-somewhat-youthful buyers that
Cadillac and Lincoln dealers rarely saw anyone younger than 60 in
their showrooms.
</P>
<P>
   But this new LS is aimed at changing that. If Lincoln-Mercury
can get the message across, this car could be a hit.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Lexus GS sedans, the Lincoln LS comes in V-6 and V-8
models, and with the V-6, you can order a five-speed manual
transmission and sport package that turns the vehicle into a real
fun machine.
</P>
<P>
   Although the V-8 model isn't available with the manual gearbox,
there is an optional five-speed ``Selectshift'' automatic
transmission that allows the driver to shift manually without
having to bother with a clutch, similar to the Tiptronic automatic
in the Porsche 911.
</P>
<P>
   Prices are more than reasonable, beginning at $31,450 (plus $535
transportation) for a V-6 model with a five-speed automatic
transmission (without the Selectshift feature). The LS V-6 with
manual transmission and sport package lists for $32,250, and the
V-8 with regular five- speed automatic, which we tested, carries a
base sticker of just $35,225 (plus transportation).
</P>
<P>
   Even without adding anything, these cars come well-equipped.
Standard on all are automatic air-conditioning, 16-inch aluminum
wheels, power windows/door locks/driver's seat, premium
AM/FM/cassette stereo and cruise control.
</P>
<P>
   Under the hood, the choice is a 3.0-liter, double-overhead-cam
V-6 engine with 210 horsepower and 205 foot-pounds of torque; or
the 3.9-liter V-8, which cranks out 252 horsepower and 267
foot-pounds of torque. The V-8 is a modified version of Jaguar's
4.0-liter V-8. It's different enough to keep Jag owners happy that
their engine isn't in another vehicle that costs considerably less.
</P>
<P>
   I haven't driven the V-6 model, but the V-8 has plenty of power
even if it isn't as hot as the Jaguar. Road-handling
characteristics of the LS are decidedly un-Lincoln-like. This
vehicle handles more like a Jag than a Lincoln, cornering easily
and holding to curves like a sports car.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the LS is roomy and comfortable in a Lexus-style,
understated kind of way. There are two leather bucket seats up
front and a leather bench seat in the rear. Five adults can ride
comfortably, and there is a huge trunk for lots of suitcases.
</P>
<P>
   My only complaint with the LS is the limited visibility to the
sides because of large ``B'' and ``C'' pillars, those structural
supports between the front and back doors and at the sides of the
rear window of most sedans. They're just too wide.
</P>
<P>
   Extras on the LS cars include the convenience package ($850 on
V-6 models, standard on V-8), which brings automatic-dimming
rearview mirror, universal garage-door opener, moisture-sensitive
windshield wipers, a memory driver's seat, and power lumbar support
for driver and front passenger.
</P>
<P>
   The sport package ($1,000 on V-6 and V-8 automatics) adds
17-inch aluminum wheels with matching spare, a European-inspired
sport suspension system, the Selectshift automatic transmission,
body-color bumpers, an oil cooler, and a leather-wrapped steering
wheel and shift knob.
</P>
<P>
   A sun roof is available for $995, and a vehicle emergency
message system with built-in cellular phone lists for $960. Stereo
upgrades include the audiophile system ($565) and a six-disc, glove
box-mounted CD changer ($595).
</P>
<P>
   EPA fuel-economy ratings are 18 miles per gallon in the city and
25 mpg on the highway for the V-6 automatics, and the tank holds
18.1 gallons. Ratings for the V-8 were not provided.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   AT A GLANCE: 1999 Lincoln LS sedan
</P>
<P>
   THE PACKAGE: Full-size, four-door, five-passenger, V-6 or
V-8-powered, rear-wheel-drive, luxury performance sedan. An all-new
model from Lincoln based on the vehicle platform of the new Jaguar
S-series.
</P>
<P>
   HIGHLIGHTS: Built to take on the Japanese and European
competition and attract affluent baby-boomers into Lincoln-Mercury
showrooms, this is the first American car to come close to the
styling and performance standards of imported luxury cars. There is
no silly gratuitous luxury. The LS is a no-nonsense sport sedan
that is comfortable yet fun to drive.
</P>
<P>
   NEGATIVES: Side pillars between front and rear doors and at the
sides of the rear window block the driver's view to the sides, a
safety hazard. Major competitors: Lexus GS 300/400, Lexus ES 300,
Infiniti I30, Acura TL/RL, Mercedes-Benz E-class, BMW 5-series.
</P>
<P>
   FUEL ECONOMY: 18 miles per gallon city, 25 highway (V-6
automatic). Base price range: $31,450 to $35,225 plus $535
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE ROAD RATING: A.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (G. Chambers Williams III is transportation writer and
automotive columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Contact him
at 3201 Airport Freeway, Suite 108, Bedford, TX 76022; telephone
(817) 685-3810; e-mail chambers(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
