A0209 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TVTOUR-NBC31-COX     07-30 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TVTOUR-NBC31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SNL celebrates 25th season
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pasadena, Calif. _ No TV show invites more comparisons to its
own past than ``Saturday Night Live,'' where each year is compared
unfavorably to the years before it, until enough time passes and
even a season that was panned is lumped in with the classics.
</P>
<P>
   To Lorne Michaels, the show's creator and executive producer,
it's the nature of ``SNL,'' which this year begins its 25th season.
A two-and-a-half hour anniversary special, featuring past cast
members, hosts and musical guests, airs Sept. 26 at 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   (The special airs, weirdly, on a Sunday, a kind of homage to
Brandon Tartikoff, the late NBC entertainment president who decided
to air the 15th anniversary special on a Sunday.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to say in the '70s that I thought the word `uneven'
would be on my tombstone, because it was in every review _ part of
the first sentence always involved the word `uneven,''' Michaels
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were starting, (baby boomers) felt we got it and an
older generation didn't. And then when things began to shift about
10 years ago and another generation began to express itself, the
baby boomers were just as intolerant as the generation before. And
we took an enormous amount of heat as a show from the press in 1993
and '94, about most of the people who now have movies out that are
successful this summer, and over the last couple summers (Adam
Sandler, Mike Myers).
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a shift in generations, and I think it is
natural for what was once sort of music that you loved to turn into
`turn down that noise,''' Michaels added. ``If we were still doing
the show that we did in 1975, we'd be on TV Land.''
</P>
<P>
   Since it became a late-night phenomenon, then an institution, in
the mid-'70s, ``SNL'' has never been seriously challenged in its
time slot. Its main competitors now are ``Mad TV'' and, in some
markets, Howard Stern's show.
</P>
<P>
   Michaels said he had no idea how much longer the show could go
on, but that the real threat to ``SNL's'' future is probably not
another competitor, but the 500-channel universe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The power of `Saturday Night Live' was the power of network
television, that people could talk about it the following day and
they'd all have the same experience,'' he said. ``As long as that
remains something Americans do, I think we'll be on the air. But I
think it will not be so much another show like us that knocks us
off. I think it will just be that there's more choices late at
night.''
</P>
<P>
   The show's 25th anniversary is bittersweet for Michaels. Besides
being enormously successful, it has launched the careers of two
generations of comedic stars, from Bill Murray and Eddie Murphy, to
Dana Carvey and David Spade. But it has also produced some of the
comedic world's biggest tragedies, including John Belushi, Gilda
Radner and Chris Farley, all of whom died untimely deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first five years _ because nothing bad happened and we
sort of did it and then all went our separate ways _ there was sort
of a `Championship Season' feeling to it,'' Michaels said. ``On a
certain level, because people have been coming back and forth for
so long, you just sort of expect that you'll see people. And then
you go, `Oh, right.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't something I deal with on a day-to-day level. It's
just when I think about it, I get sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Drew Jubera writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
