A0213 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARMY-SCHOOL-COX     07-30 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMY-SCHOOL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    House cuts training funds for School of Americas
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For years, the School of the Americas at Fort
Benning, Ga., which is meant to teaching combat skills to Latin
American soldiers, has come under political attack.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Cynthia McKinney (D-Ga.) has gone so far as to call it the
``School of Assassins'' because of human rights abuses she says
were committed by some of its graduates.
</P>
<P>
   But the school's federal funding has never been in jeopardy _
until now.
</P>
<P>
   The House cut funding late Thursday that would pay for training
soldiers from South America, Central America and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Despite efforts by Reps. Sanford Bishop (D-Ga.) and Mac Collins
(R-Ga.) to win support for the school's $1.3 million training
program next year, the House voted 230-197 to cut the program.
</P>
<P>
   The vote marked the first funding setback in the school's
45-year history. But the House action would eliminate only about 10
percent of the $20 million in federal funds earmarked for the
school. The rest of its funding is included in the Pentagon budget.
</P>
<P>
   The school's funding request is a mere sliver of the overall
$12.6 billion in the foreign operations appropriations bill, yet it
is one of the most controversial.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, the school trains 800 to 1,000 soldiers at its
Georgia campus near Columbus. Critics say it teaches terrorism and
torture.
</P>
<P>
   ``The accusations about teaching murder and torture ... are
based on pure propaganda and not on facts,'' Bishop said in a
heated floor speech Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The school has undergone 12 congressional investigations into
allegations that it teaches torture and murder, Bishop said. ``All
came to the same conclusion _ these charges are false.''
</P>
<P>
   Rising to oppose the school, Rep. John Lewis (D-Ga.) said it was
``hard and difficult to differ from his colleague, friend and
brother from Georgia,'' but he could not support funding the
training program.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been involved in some of the most outrageous
violations of human rights,'' Lewis said of the school's graduates.
``This is the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis and McKinney were the only Georgians to support the
funding cut.
</P>
<P>
   Army Col. Glenn Weidner, who runs the Fort Benning school, said
there is ``no doubt that terrible things'' have happened in Latin
America. But, he said, fewer than 1 percent of the school's 60,000
graduates have been linked to atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   One of the main purposes of the school is to prevent atrocities
and establish stability in the region, Weidner said. The school
aims to foster camaraderie between the United States and Latin
America through the school's graduates, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hope is to bring them here to train with us and that our
values will be absorbed by them,'' Weidner said. ``I deny
categorically that we train them to be terrorists. We are the U.S.
Army.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins said he hoped that the funding would be restored when
the foreign operations bill moves to a House and Senate committee
for approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would probably have a lot more conflict in that region if
it weren't for the school,'' Collins said. ``I don't think the
school will be closed. It is too important to our national
security.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not how McKinney sees it. She has been one of the
school's staunch opponents since her arrival in Congress in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am extremely frustrated by the dismissive attitude of some
of our military establishment to the revelations that our soldiers
trained others to murder torture and terrorize civilians,''
McKinney said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jack Kingston (R-Ga.), a member of the appropriations panel
in charge of funding the school's training program, said the school
has fallen prey to special interest politics.
</P>
<P>
   Kingston said he found it ``hypocritical'' of lawmakers to
salute members of the armed services on Memorial Day and then vote
to close an Army training school because opponents of the school
say ``the same members of the United States Army are training
terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   The notion that it trains terrorists is ``plain malarkey,''
Kingston said.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters display crosses with the names of Latin American
countries where the School of Americas allegedly operated on
Saturday, May 1, 1999, in Washington, D.C. Protesters from across
the country have come to the nation's capital in the wake of what
is claimed to be new evidence tying the U.S. Army training facility
at the U.S. Army's School of the Americas at Fort Benning, Ga., to
widespread torture and killings in Guatemala, Colombia, and Chile.
(AP Photo/Khue Bui)
</P>
<P>
   KHUE BUI / Associated Press
</P>
<P>
   A group marches last spring in Washington to protest continued
funding of the School of the Americas. Protests also have been
frequent at Fort Benning. Critics blame the school for crimes by
its graduates. Defenders say its impact is positive.
</P>
<P>
   display crosses with the names of Latin American countries where
the School of Americas allegedly operated on Saturday, May 1, 1999,
in Washington, D.C. FILL OUT THIS CUTLINEWITH RECENT INFO.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
