<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TOUR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBC TEEN SHOW SEEKS REALISTIC LOOK IN CASTING ACTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Talk about diversity! Let's hope the cast of
``Freaks and Geeks'' doesn't take offense too easily.
</P>
<P>
   The new NBC dramatic series about high school life in 1980 has a
charming young cast, but they don't necessarily look as if they
stepped out of central casting. Producer Judd Apatow says it's by
design. ``At the beginning of the casting process,'' he explained,
``we just wanted to do a high school show that actually looked like
high school. My high school didn't look like any of the shows that
are on TV. There was maybe one gorgeous girl in school and, looking
back, she wasn't that hot, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Apatow said he and creator Paul Feig simply made a commitment to
cast accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you open up (the casting process) for what people really
look like,'' Apatow said, ``there's an enormous amount of really
talented people that might not, you know, get work on `Dawson's
Creek.'''
</P>
<P>
   _Aside from George Clooney, who left ``ER'' in the middle of
last season, the nation's most popular dramatic series has its full
complement of regulars returning for season No. 6. But it may not
be so easy to keep track of them. Garth Ancier, the new president
of NBC Entertainment, says three new characters are being added to
the show, another character from the first season is returning, a
recurring character from the past couple of years is becoming a
regular, and two prominent stars will make significant guest
appearances during the season.
</P>
<P>
   Scorecard ready? Here goes: The newcomers are Michael Michele
(``Homicide: Life on the Street'') as a second-year resident; Maura
Tierney (``NewsRadio'') as a charge nurse transferred from
intensive care, and Goran Visnjic (``Welcome to Sarajevo'') as a
Croatian physician who survived the Bosnian war. The returnee is
Ming-Na, formerly Ming-Na Wen, who will reprise the character of
Deb Chen from the first season. The new regular is Paul McCrane
(``The Shawshank Redemption''), who has played the slimy Dr. Romano
the past two seasons. And the prominent guest stars are Rebecca
DeMornay and Alan Alda, whose story lines Ancier declined to
reveal. He did say DeMornay's character will appear over a
five-show arc at the start of the season, and Alda's will be in
``many, many episodes.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Odds 'n' ends: Now that ``Melrose Place'' is shuttered,
Heather Locklear will join the cast of ``Spin City'' for its fourth
season. She'll play Caitlin Moore, campaign manager of Mayor
Winston (Barry Bostwick), who has decided to run for the U.S.
Senate. Caitlin, we're told, won't get along too well with deputy
mayor Michael Flaherty (Michael J. Fox). ... Eunice Kennedy Shriver
and her son, Bobby, are executive producers of ``Mary &AMP; Jesus,'' a
two-hour movie slated for a November airing on NBC. Bobby Shriver
says it is not a duplication of CBS's four-hour miniseries,
``Jesus,'' also planned for next season. Shriver says his project
is mostly about Mary, and probably should be titled ``Mary of
Nazareth.'' Swedish actress Pernilla August plays Mary in the
Shriver project; Jacqueline Bisset will do the honors on CBS. The
non-dueling Jesuses are Christian Bale, a Welshman, on NBC, and
Jeremy Sisto, an American, on CBS. ... Martin Sheen plays the
president of the United States in Aaron Sorkin's new NBC drama,
``The West Wing.'' Sheen is proud of his Spanish-Irish heritage _
the name on his driver's license is Ramon Estevez _ but he doesn't
see himself as a standard bearer for minority actors, even though
NBC West Coast president Scott Sassa mentioned Sheen's Hispanic
heritage as a minority component of the ``West Wing'' cast. ``I've
been an actor for 40 years and I've played all kinds of parts,''
said the man who has portrayed both John Kennedy and Robert Kennedy
in films. ``I'm Hispanic by birth and I'm Irish by trade.''
</P>
</TEXT>
