<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0219 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-COLUMN-ART-$AD     07-30 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-COLUMN-ART-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOSENING THE YOKE OF THE BENCHMARK  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 1) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ill.)  (ART ADV: Graphic of S&AMP;P 500 funds as a poercentage of total equity
funds is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By MARK HULBERT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's call a truce in the seemingly never-ending war between
those who think the market can be beaten and those who don't. Here
are the terms: First, all investors must agree to invest major
portions of their portfolios _ half or more _ in index funds.
Second, devotees of index funds must stop demanding that we sink
every single penny into them and, instead, allow us to use active
fund managers, those who try to beat the market, for part of our
investing.
</P>
<P>
   Because of certain benefits that attend the partial-indexing
approach, I believe it would have a good chance of beating both an
all-indexing and an all-active-management approach
</P>
<P>
   Rather than viewing indexing as the enemy, active money managers
should see it as an ally that lets them do what they do best in a
climate that is shaped partly by two investor obsessions.
</P>
<P>
   The first of those obsessions is short-term focus. To be sure,
investors have never maintained the long-range perspective that
statisticians say is necessary for meaningful assessments of
portfolio managers' skills. But their focus has shortened markedly
over the last two decades _ especially in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   According to a 1996 study by Galt Technologies, a data-providing
subsidiary of Intuit, 77 percent of investors who follow their
investments online check their portfolios' worth at least once a
week, and 21 percent check more than once a day.
</P>
<P>
   That constant checking of performance is not benign. Many
studies have shown that investors who do so are more likely to make
frequent and major changes and hence ignore the long-term picture.
</P>
<P>
   Portfolio managers today know that they are being judged on
their recent short-term returns. Investors often decide whether to
keep or drop a fund by looking at its performance over just a few
months. Indeed, some investment newsletters recommend doing so. Yet
I'm aware of no research showing that track records of a year or
less are meaningful.
</P>
<P>
   The other obsession is with so-called tracking error _ the
amount by which a manager's performance varies from a benchmark
like the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index. Managers know they may
be dismissed if they fall too far behind benchmarks they've been
hired to beat. As a result, many managers don't stray far from the
stocks in their chosen index.
</P>
<P>
   Three finance professors _ Charles Cuny at the London Business
School, Mark Fedenia at the University of Wisconsin at Madison and
Robert Haugen, formerly at the University of California at Irvine,
researched the contents of fund portfolios, focusing on the 1969-89
period. They found that as Dec. 31 approached each year, managers
tended to make their portfolios look more like the stocks in the
indexes they follow. Year-end is also the time when many managers'
performance is judged.
</P>
<P>
   Combined, the two investor obsessions make managers less willing
to take the risks needed to beat the market. The incentive to make
more money for clients is often outweighed by the disincentive to
allow performance to fall too far below a benchmark's. Some
managers prefer to fail conventionally than to succeed
unconventionally.
</P>
<P>
   Now imagine a world in which investors put at least half of
their portfolios in index funds. Immediately, tracking error will
become less important to them, because only the rest of their
portfolios can deviate from the index. And because they will worry
less, they will give more freedom to an active manager to invest
that remainder.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, investors will loosen the straitjacket they have
placed on that manager, by reducing the short-term pressure to beat
an index. That will foster a healthier relationship between
investors and managers, in which the managers can take the risks
needed to have a fighting chance of beating the market long term.
</P>
<P>
   Widespread adoption of partial indexing does not guarantee, of
course, that active managers will beat the market; that remains a
difficult task. But it does create the conditions that improve the
chances of market-beating performance. Investors must be willing to
let managers take the long-term bets that will make them winners. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mark Hulbert is editor of The Hulbert Financial Digest, a
newsletter based in Alexandria, Va. His column on investment
strategies appears every other week. E-mail:
strategy(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
