<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0220 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HISPANICS-POLITICS-$A     07-30 1407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANICS-POLITICS-$ADV01-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS CANDIDATES SPEAK, AWED HISPANICS LISTEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Aug. 1)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAIME CATILLO  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Raised in the Depression and educated a
half-century ago in a South Texas few Hispanics can forget, Joe
Bernal has a special interest in the 2000 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bernal, 72, recalls when minority outreach by political
candidates consisted of paying a person's poll tax and, on good
days, getting some tamales and beer to wash down the ignominy of
casting a ballot for the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   At the local schoolhouse, ``no se habla Espanol'' (``Spanish is
not spoken here'') was the mantra and attempts to eradicate the
language from campuses across the Southwest were a constant
reminder that the United States was not run by people with names
like Gonzalez or Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was psychologically very damaging,'' Bernal said of the
efforts to bar native Spanish speakers from using their mother
tongue.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they were doing was making you believe that somehow or
another, your parents at home were giving you something that was
not good for you,'' said Bernal, a former state senator and current
member of the Texas Board of Education.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 55 years after he last walked the halls of Lanier High
School wearing a ribbon that read, ``I speak English. I'm a good
American,'' Bernal is part of a generation of older Hispanics who
are at the same time amused and bemused by the current presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   They are watching and listening as the apparent front-runners in
the 2000 presidential race, Vice President Al Gore and Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas, create history by speaking Spanish at every
politically opportune moment.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, a Republican, won close to half the Hispanic vote in his
re-election as governor last year, leading Gore to campaign
rigorously to retain a traditionally Democratic voting bloc.
</P>
<P>
   Other presidential hopefuls, including Republican Sen. John
McCain of Arizona, are trying their best in English to woo the
nation's fastest-growing minority.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Barrera Sr., a San Antonio lawyer who was appointed Texas
secretary of state in 1968, said he never could have imagined as a
child that presidential candidates from both parties would be
freely using Spanish on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely not,'' the 72-year-old said. ``We were so
accustomed to believing that national candidates were something
other than Hispanic.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Chavez-Thompson, who worked as a child in the cotton
fields in the Texas Panhandle before becoming the highest-ranking
Hispanic woman in the nation's largest labor union, said her
81-year-old mother has been glued to Spanish-language television
for news about the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother has been so pleasantly surprised that she is seeing
two presidential candidates speaking her language,'' said
Chavez-Thompson, 54, the executive vice president of the AFL-CIO.
``Even me and my sisters, we're finding it absolutely enthralling
to hear it as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Others are more skeptical and waiting for substantive issues to
match the rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   ``Speaking Spanish is one thing. But if you are bad on the
issues, it doesn't matter if you speak Spanish, Chinese and
German,'' said Albert Pena, 81, a former municipal court judge in
San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Ruben Munguia, 81, who has supplied a generation of political
candidates with campaign signs from his San Antonio print shop,
said he views Spanish-speaking efforts by candidates who are less
than fluent in the language as ``paternalistic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I going to be swayed by Governor Bush and Vice President
Gore speaking a few words in Spanish? I'm not buying it. Speak to
me in the language of the land,'' said Munguia, who is the uncle of
Henry Cisneros, the former secretary of the Department of Housing
and Urban Development.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Hernandez, a visiting lecturer at St. Mary's University in
San Antonio who is writing a book about the Hispanic electorate,
said candidates risk a backlash if they don't soon move beyond the
symbolism of reaching out in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Latino voters are very sophisticated about this,''
Hernandez said. ``It's no a contest of who can say the most in
Spanish, but who says the most meaningful things.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the political motives, Hispanics are being courted
like never before _ and with good reason, some analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Once projected to become the largest minority group in the
United States by 2005, Hispanics are now expected to take over the
mantle with more than 32 million residents as soon as the 2000
Census is completed.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanic buying power in the United States also has risen to
$383 billion this year, a whopping 84 percent increase since 1990,
according to the Selig Center for Economic Growth at the University
of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   In short, it is a numbers game and not, as Bernal puts it,
``that they (the country's political power brokers) love
`mexicanos' all in the sudden.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Rocha, a political scientist at the University of Texas
at El Paso, said the pragmatic thing for any national candidate to
do from now on is to try to shore up the Hispanic vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just indicative of changing demographics. The complexion
of the nation is getting darker,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Once referred to by academic number crunchers as the ``sleeping
giant,'' the nation's Hispanic population also has shown in recent
elections that it can pack a political punch, said Lisa Navarrete,
spokeswoman for the National Council of La Raza.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think what has occurred is that the sleeping giant
has acquired some teeth,'' Navarrete said.
</P>
<P>
   It showed itself in 1994 in California when Republicans
miscalculated by thinking they could win back so-called Reagan
Democrats by taking an anti-immigrant posture.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of creating a pro-American wave, the tactic ignited
minorities and legal immigrants who applied for citizenship in
record numbers, registered to vote and eventually hit the ballot
boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, minorities bristled at accusations that newly
elected Rep. Loretta Sanchez, D-Calif., needed the help of
ineligible voters to defeat incumbent Republican Robert Dornan.
</P>
<P>
   California voters, driven at least in part by the anti-immigrant
posture taken by some prominent Republicans, swept Democrats into
virtually every important position in the state in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have never been able to do is punish our enemies,''
said Hernandez, the college lecturer. ``Now we have demonstrated
that we can take people out.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has certainly taken notice. He has made an obvious point of
distancing himself from former California Gov. Pete Wilson, a
Republican who led a short-lived campaign for the presidential
nomination in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The other presidential candidates, meanwhile, also have been
careful not to incorporate inflammatory rhetoric thus far in the
race.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of political influence is foreign territory for many
older Hispanics who remember when Hispanic voters weren't consulted
and Hispanic candidates were few and far between.
</P>
<P>
   Former Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez, D-Texas, often repeats the story
about the ethnic and racial barriers he encountered during his
failed bid for governor of Texas in 1958, a typical lament of
Hispanics of that time.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning out of a pickup, Gonzalez encountered a white ranch
owner on a dusty road in South Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Noticing the campaign memorabilia in the truck, the man asked:
``Son, what are you running for?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor,'' Gonzalez replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of Texas?'' the man said, his stoic face turning into a wide
smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, of Texas,'' Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Son, you don't have a Chinaman's chance,'' the man concluded
through a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want a Chinaman's chance,'' the irascible Gonzalez
shot back. ``I want a Mexican's chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, then a state senator, lost the Democrat primary 3-to-1
but the loss only emboldened his political ambition.
</P>
<P>
   Forty years later, while Hispanics seem to have the ear of the
candidates for president, people like Barrera are appreciative.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least now they're trying to make an effort to identify with
us,'' Barrera said. ``The `portilla' (window of opportunity) has
arrived. It's pleasant, and it's comforting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
