<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-VIEQUES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANCER STUDY ON VIEQUES COULD DELAY WHITE HOUSE DECISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Filed in ``w'' and ``p'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal cancer-monitoring agency has opened an
investigation into Puerto Ricans' allegations that U.S. bombing
exercises have caused high levels of cancer on the Caribbean island
of Vieques, officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The action by the Agency for Toxic Substances and Disease
Registry could delay a White House decision on the fate of a
bombing range that the Navy and Marine Corps have used for 58 years
to prepare Atlantic-based forces for deployment to Europe and the
Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   Some Puerto Rican-born politicians, including Rep. Jose E.
Serrano, D-N.Y., and Delegate Carlos Romero-Barcelo, D-Puerto Rico,
say the White House decision could influence Puerto Rican political
support for Vice President Al Gore in his 2000 presidential
campaign and for First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton in her
exploratory U.S. Senate campaign from New York.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday Rear Adm. Andrew A. Granuzzo, the Navy's top
environmental protection officer, disclosed the Vieques cancer
inquiry in testimony before a Pentagon panel appointed at the
request of President Clinton to weigh continued live-fire training
on the island. Some 9,300 civilians live there adjacent to a
22,000-acre military bombing and ground maneuvers site.
</P>
<P>
   Citing ``allegations of an increased rate of cancer for Vieques
citizens,'' Granuzzo said the Navy will work with the federal
cancer-monitoring agency to ``support their independent
investigation regarding this allegation .... even though there is
no reason to believe that Navy actions are involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Block, the New York-based regional administrator for the
disease monitoring agency who has responsibility for Puerto Rico,
went there last week to meet with Navy officials, an agency
official said in New York.
</P>
<P>
   A team from the agency plans to visit Vieques next month. The
agency has 180 days to act on the citizen's request for an
investigation. A comprehensive study might take another year.
</P>
<P>
   Bombing and other combat-style exercises have been suspended on
the island since a Puerto Rican civilian employee of the Navy was
killed and four others were injured when a Marine pilot mistakenly
dropped two 500-pound bombs on an observation post during night
training.
</P>
<P>
   Navy and Marine Corps' officials, hoping to gain President
Clinton's go-ahead to resume live-fire training, insist that there
is not any scientific proof to support claims of high rates of
cancer raised by Puerto Rico's political leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But members of the Pentagon fact-finding panel who visited
Vieques last week said they heard vivid testimony about the high
rate of cancer. Local authorities described a neighborhood
devastated by the disease and said that infant mortality is higher
on Vieques than on the main island of Puerto Rico eight miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Rico Gov. Pedro Rossello, noting that the cancer risk is
``greater on Vieques than in any other municipality in Puerto
Rico,'' has urged the panel to launch a comprehensive health study
to determine if there is a connection with the chemicals contained
in the munitions, bombs, naval gunfire and Marine Corps' artillery
and mortar fire that are unleashed on Vieques each year.
</P>
<P>
   Panel members said the question of the incidence of cancer on
Vieques must be answered before Navy and Marine Corps' operations
can resume.
</P>
<P>
   One panel member, retired Marine Corps Gen. Richard Neal, noted
that Puerto Rico's citizens have voiced concern over a possible
increased cancer risk on Vieques for more than a decade without
gaining Navy attention.
</P>
<P>
   Another panel member, retired Rep. Lee H. Hamilton, D-Ind.,
asked the Navy's environmental specialist what the Navy would do if
studies were to detect a link between the bombing and cancer on the
island.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect we would have to modify our operations somewhat,''
replied Granuzzo, director of the environmental protection, safety
and occupational health division of the Chief of Naval Operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope so,'' Hamilton replied curtly. ``Obviously this
is something of extremely high sensitivity that we have to go
into.''
</P>
<P>
   Retired Navy Vice Adm. Diego Hernandez, a Puerto Rico-born panel
member who formerly served as commander of the U.S. Caribbean
fleet, challenged Granuzzo's reply.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez invited Granuzzo to revise his statement that Navy
operations would merely be ``modified somewhat'' if federal health
studies conclude U.S. military exercises are causing a high
incidence of cancer among Puerto Rican civilians, who are U.S.
citizens by birth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you want to let that stand in the record,''
Hernandez told Granuzzo. ``If there is cause and effect, the Navy
operation on Vieques is ended _ not `modified somewhat.'''
</P>
<P>
   Granuzzo did not change his statement.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez later told reporters he initially thought that
Granuzzo was ``being perhaps facetious,'' adding: ``That is an
absolutely impossible statement to accept on the part of anyone. If
there is a cause and effect relationship between Navy activities
and cancer on Vieques, operations are ended, liabilities are huge
and the human factor is indescribably difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez said the Pentagon panel will have to submit its
recommendations on the future use of the Vieques bombing range to
the president by the end of August before the health studies are
complete.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Puerto Rican political leaders have united behind demands for a
permanent cessation of U.S. military operations on the 33,000-acre
island and the withdrawal of the Navy from the bombing range that
takes up two thirds of the island.
</P>
<P>
   Serrano, the most senior Puerto Rican native in Congress, has
said the 2 million Puerto Ricans living in New York are watching to
see whether the president, the first lady and the vice president
support their demands for the Navy's eviction from Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   Alcides Ortiz, executive director and general counsel of the
Puerto Rico Federal Affairs Administration, which handles the
islands' dealings with the federal government, has said Puerto
Rican voters in the United States will take the outcome on Vieques
into account when they vote for senator in New York or president in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
e-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
