<HEADER>
A0232 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LONDON-MARKET-ART-NYT     07-30 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONDON-MARKET-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONDON STOCK EXCHANGE TO ISSUE SHARES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(yn) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ With the world's stock exchanges increasingly
challenged by upstart electronic trading networks, the august
London Stock Exchange on Friday announced plans to end almost two
centuries of clubby mutual ownership by issuing tradeable shares to
its members.
</P>
<P>
   The move, depicted by the exchange as part of a quest for a new
corporate agility, is similar to steps announced by the New York
Stock Exchange and the Nasdaq Stock Market, which face even greater
threats than European exchanges from electronic communications
networks, known by their initials ECNs.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's announcement by the London exchange, which claims to be
the world's oldest, raised questions about the future of stalled
efforts led by the London and Frankfurt exchanges to create a
pan-European stock exchange from eight existing institutions. The
year-old negotiations have come to a halt amid disputes over
ownership and technology.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some bankers said that rapid technological advances
facilitating smaller, cheaper and more nimble electronic trading
platforms could eclipse the more staid, traditional exchanges by
creating pan-European networks of their own. ``If the major
exchanges don't move quickly enough, the ECNs will,'' said Ronald
Cohen, chairman of Apax Partners &AMP; Co., a private equity company
with minority stakes in two electronic trading outfits _ the
Tradepoint alternative stock exchange in Britain, and Easdaq, a
pan-European market for high-growth stocks that plans to list its
stock on Nasdaq in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The planned changes at the London Stock Exchange, which need
approval from 75 percent of its 294 members, represent the biggest
shift in the way the organization is run since the so-called Big
Bang of 1986 when it moved away from the floor trading system still
used at the New York Stock Exchange to screen-based trading.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Muncer, a spokesman for the London Stock Exchange, said the
detailed workings of the new system still had to be formulated and
he indicated that London exchange officials were not at present
contemplating the same full public stock offering as the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the move was designed to give the London Stock
Exchange more flexibility in raising capital for new, competitive
ventures and in accelerating decision-making.
</P>
<P>
   Gavin Casey, the chief executive of the London Stock Exchange,
said that ``greater speed and flexibility than ever before'' were
needed ``for London to stay ahead in today's technology-driven
market-place.''
</P>
<P>
   Some American investment firms with big trading operations here
welcomed the move. Tom Troy, head of European equities at Merrill
Lynch, said the firm was ``very supportive of its
demutualization.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Market structures globally are evolving quickly,'' he added,
``and the London Stock Exchange's move to further modernize itself
will provide it with the commercial edge needed to compete in the
new order.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the quandary facing the London exchange was part of a
much broader contest between the established national exchanges and
the technology that is reshaping the international marketplace for
stocks. ``This isn't a phenomenon of just the London Stock Exchange
or the City of London,'' he said. ``This is a global phenomenon
that's affecting all the major exchanges around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, for instance, 30 percent of trades in
companies listed on the Nasdaq exchange are done through electronic
communication networks. Around 15 percent of all trades are done in
on-line trading. The European figures are far less but growing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you'll see the volume of day-trading and retail
in quite the way as in the U.S.,'' said Richard Kilsby, chief
executive of the Tradepoint exchange, which was recently
recapitalized by a consortium of United States and other investment
banks and institutions. ``But I do think there's great latent
demand and volume for European stocks. It's not just around the
corner. But it's not far away.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Thursday, 19 institutions here including Barclays Global
Investors Ltd. and Merrill Lynch Mercury Asset Management,
announced plans to create a European trading network called
E-Crossnet Ltd., designed to undercut existing transaction costs.
In the United States last week, the Charles Schwab Corp. on and
Fidelity Investments, the leading mutual funds investment company,
started an electronic network with two other companies, reflecting
the boom in retail, on-line trading that has helped fuel Wall
Street's bull run.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the traditional exchanges are challenged by such
institutions as the Instinet Corp., owned by Reuters Group PLC, and
Tradebook, owned by Bloomberg LP.
</P>
<P>
   The rapid expansion of electronic trading contrasts sharply with
the ponderous negotiations to fuse Europe's existing stock
exchanges into a single system, a move initially inspired by the
approach of the euro single currency, which was introduced in 11
European countries last January.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations between the London Stock Exchange and Frankfurt's
Deutsche Borse, which have made progress in such areas as
harmonized working hours, are close to deadlock on several other
issues, people close to those discussions said. The two exchanges,
these people said, have failed to agree on a common trading
technology.
</P>
<P>
   That has inspired sentiment that the discussions will be
overtaken by technologically driven market forces. ``If London and
Frankfurt, in a very timely manner, are not able to come up with a
credible structure then I think the alternative trading systems
will do that,'' said Troy at Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   The disarray among the European exchanges is accentuated by wide
differences in their ownership structures. Of all eight, for
instance, only Sweden's Stock Exchange is owned by a traded company
_ OM Gruppen AB. Others, such as the Frankfurt and Zurich exchanges
are dominated by German and Swiss banks and have said they have no
plans to go public. The Amsterdam exchange demutualized in 1997 and
plans to issue shares by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's move by the London exchange, however, raised
speculation that all will come under pressure to change along the
same lines. The exchanges, said Cohen of Apax Partners, ``find it
difficult to go beyond national borders.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are symbols of national pride and don't operate like a
normal company,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   But, after Friday's development, he said, ``my guess is that
this will start a chain reaction of all European exchanges
demutualizing, moving away from politics and into business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
