<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETHICS-COLUMN-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLD FACTS ABOUT CHILD LABOR  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 1) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DANIEL AKST   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few of the world's ills arouse such revulsion as child labor.
When we learn that children are sewing soccer balls instead of
studying, we are aghast. Kathie Lee Gifford, stung by allegations
that her line of clothing at Wal-Mart was tainted by child labor,
condemned the practice before Congress.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton addressed the International Labor Organization
on the same terrible subject.
</P>
<P>
   So it is with some trepidation that I raise a small voice in
dissent from therse noble efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Of course we're all against children being chained to machinery
and forced to work day and night in unsanitary conditions for
pennies a week. Alas, there is more to it than that, and the whole
subject is so clouded by myth and sentiment that some hard truths
have been lost in the haze.
</P>
<P>
   The hardest is that laboring children in Pakistan, Honduras,
Guatemala and similarly impoverished places generally work to
support their families, and the people devoted to rescuing them
haven't the slightest hope of offering an alternative. For the
unfortunate children, living in lands without a social safety net
and in households where the adults cannot provide for them, the
alternative isn't school; it's starvation.
</P>
<P>
   What the poorest nations need most is economic development, the
only known route to the enlightened social and economic system _
complete with women's rights, environmental protection, and yes, a
ban on child labor _ that all of us want for these children in the
first place.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, the labor of children has been an inevitable
ingredient in economic development, and kids at work are far from a
shocking new consequence of the dark forces of globalization (you
know, the forces that are doing more for world prosperity and peace
than any government ever has). Not only have children always
worked, but for much of history, labor was the point of children,
who invariably helped in the fields.
</P>
<P>
   When families left the farms, children worked with their parents
at whatever trade the adults took up. As grown-ups went to work in
factories, children followed. Like most revolutions, the industrial
one wasn't pretty, but one of its many eventual benefits was
raising incomes high enough to afford the ideal of the sheltered
childhood, a golden time set aside for play, study and parental
dependence. The best childhood, in other words, that money could
buy.
</P>
<P>
   My own sons, I hope, will not have to work in order to eat until
they are adults. Along with practically everyone else in the world,
I fervently wish for the day when all children are free of this
burden and can obsess instead over the year's hottest new toy or
teen idol. But it's a fact that forbidding child labor in the
Pakistans or Guatemalas of today will not hasten that happy day.
</P>
<P>
   Strangely enough, there is a country where children routinely
work not to put food on the table, but merely to leap all the
sooner onto the treadmill of consumption. In this benighted land,
57 percent of the 14-year-olds are working for money; among white
14-year-olds, the most affluent subset, the rate is higher still.
</P>
<P>
   And while the children of this land, by some measures the
world's richest nation, busy themselves flipping burgers and
stocking grocery shelves, they score dismally as a group on
international tests of academic achievement.
</P>
<P>
   The country, of course, is the United States. And even here, the
alarm about children working instead of studying is misplaced. A
study by the Bureau of Labor Statistics found that American
children who work seem to do so instead of watching television.
</P>
<P>
   What the bureau didn't ask the teen-agers was how they spent
their money. It's a fair bet that some of it goes to buy stylish
apparel and shoes made in Third World countries _ by other
children.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe America's working kids deserve a pat on the back. By
spending their earnings at the mall, they are transferring some
wealth overseas to children who need it far more. Sure, much of it
is skimmed off along the way by middlemen and marketers. But the
track record of most conventional international development
programs is no better. At least we know that this mechanism works. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Akst is a novelist and financial journalist. His column
tilting at conventional business wisdom appears the first Sunday of
each month. E-mail: culmoney(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
