<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERBRIGHT-RESIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAIRMAN OF CHINESE FINANCIAL CONGLOMERATE IS REPLACED 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By SETH FAISON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ China Everbright Group, one of the nation's largest
financial conglomerates, announced Friday that its chairman had
resigned and been replaced by a deputy governor of the People's
Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
   The move, officially described as a normal transfer, appeared
instead to be one of several personnel moves related to the
shifting fortunes of Prime Minister Zhu Rongji, whose reform
program has been under attack from conservative rivals in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   The departing chairman of China Everbright, Zhu Xiaohua, was one
of China's most prominent executives, a relatively aggressive and
ambitious financial operative in an environment that favors
political caution and bureaucratic timidity.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu, China Everbright's chairman since 1996, was widely reported
to enjoy a close relationship with Prime Minister Zhu, who is no
relation. The prime minister has been trying to spearhead sharp
reform in China's lumbering financial sector, where state-run
companies are plagued by mismanagement and bureaucratic politics.
</P>
<P>
   Although China Everbright is considered one of the brighter
stars in the collection of Hong Kong-based, China-owned financial
companies, it is widely regarded as lacking the efficiency and
flexibility of private competitors in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   China Everbright runs a wide range of businesses that extend
from securities trading to banking to toll collection. It reports
directly to China's State Council, or cabinet. It has three
subsidiaries that are publicly listed in Hong Kong: China
Everbright, China Everbright Technology and China Everbright
International.
</P>
<P>
   Like other state-run companies, China Everbright does not
publicly report revenue or profit, and much of its other financial
data are not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   China Everbright's commercial banking arm, Everbright Bank of
China, had more than $10 billion in assets at the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong newspapers reported rumors that Zhu Xiaohua was under
investigation for his role in bad deals that had lost more than
$200 million.
</P>
<P>
   But in a field of state-owned financial companies where enormous
losses are routinely written off, other, still unclear factors may
also have been at play.
</P>
<P>
   An investment banker at another Chinese company said Zhu's
removal had more to do with Beijing politics than with China
Everbright's balance sheet. A related move, the banker said, is the
expected removal of Wang Qishan, deputy governor of Guangdong
Province, who was sent by Prime Minister Zhu to sort out the
financial mess left there by state-run companies, namely the
Guangdong International Trust and Investment Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't see what the whole picture is,'' the banker said.
``But these moves are all related.''
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Zhu's aggressive reform program is said to have
been sharply criticized by fellow Politburo members in Beijing,
where the political atmosphere has become unusually tense and
volatile. Leaders are currently confronted with crises over Taiwan,
the spiritual movement Falun Gong, and strained U.S.-China
relations, on top of a vulnerable economy and rising unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   China Everbright's new chairman, Liu Mingkang, served for 11
years as a deputy governor of China's central bank.
</P>
<P>
   Yet his background is as much in politics as in finance. Before
joining the People's Bank, Liu was a vice governor of Fujian
province. He has an MBA from London's City University.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Hong Kong, where Everbright is based,
Liu said he would not change his predecessor's strategy of focusing
on financial services businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The financial industry is our core business,'' Liu said.
``That means commercial banking _ including personal banking,
institutional banking, corporate banking _ and I am very happy to
see that our commercial banking is getting stronger and stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   He denied that Zhu's removal was unusual in any way.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned, this is part of normal operations,
nothing more, nothing less,'' Liu said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
