<SLUG> BC-BIZ-DIARY-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ABOUT SURVEYS, RESEARCH, NEW PRODUCTS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 1) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AN INITIAL GAIN IN AN AD CAMPAIGN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There it is, in bold type in a newspaper ad: ``HRC. Because New
Yorkers expect the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Many a New Yorker might have done a double take; after all,
Hillary Rodham Clinton's all-but-announced campaign for the Senate
hasn't officially begun. But the ads are actually promoting the New
York Health and Racquet Club, a chain in the city whose HRC logo
looks as if it could be the first lady's monogram.
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Dickinson, a spokeswoman for the chain, said it never
intended to trade on the coincidence. The club is ``pleased to
support America in general,'' Ms. Dickinson said, but she stressed
that the chain is not at all political. ``We just happen to have
the same initials,'' she said. ``We sent her a T-shirt one time
because of the similarities.''
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Mrs. Clinton's camp hadn't noticed the ads but was
hardly complaining. ``It sounds like a pretty good slogan,'' said a
chuckling Howard Wolfson, Mrs. Clinton's campaign spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I will change my membership over there,'' Wolfson added.
After all, the club, unlike politics, offers a money-back
guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   Alisa Tang &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
