<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0248 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFE-SEX-HNS &LR;      07-30 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFE-SEX-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSMAN M.D. LECTURES INTERNS ABOUT SAFE SEX 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Filed in ``w'' and ``l'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While congressional committees met Friday to
discuss Internet commerce, drug addiction and international
affairs, Rep. Tom Coburngathered some 300 young congressional
interns to eat pizza and listen to his lecture about safe sex.
</P>
<P>
   The message from the three-term Republican from Oklahoma _ who
also is a physician: If you want to avoid painful, debilitating and
potentially deadly sexually transmitted diseases, or STDs, abstain
from sex until marriage.
</P>
<P>
   In a U.S. Capitol hall usually reserved for lectures on
economics and national security and resplendent with photographs of
official Washington, Coburn punctuated his presentation with a
graphic slide show detailing the ravages of chlamydia, gonorrhea,
herpes and the human papillomavirus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an epidemic of STDs,'' said Coburn, who specializes in
family medicine and obstetrics back home in his rural northeastern
Oklahoma district. ``The problem is that not many people know
there's an epidemic.''
</P>
<P>
   One problem with many of the 25 known STDs, he said, is that
they often go undetected.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional internships are an prized institution, often
sought by college students and recent graduates hoping to break
into the politics industry. The internships provide free labor to
lawmakers, while giving young adults a first-hand look at the inner
workings of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn has given his safe-sex lecture to interns for the last
five summers. He says his audience is in the age group which STDs
strike with a vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   In Coburn's slide presentation, a picture tells the story more
vividly than statistics: Images of genital warts erupting on male
and female genitals, a swollen and cracked cervix infected with
virulent chlamydia, a penis consumed by a bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   Several interns stopped eating their pizza, while some others
groaned aloud as the slides flashed on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn, a social conservative from the House class of 1994 that
wrested control of Congress from Democrats, argued that sexual
abstinence was the only sure way to avoid infection. Condoms, he
said, don't stop the spread of HPV because the virus can be
transmitted by contact with an infected scrotum, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn, who will relinquish his seat at the end of his term,
said HPV was ``the meanest virus I have ever dealt with.''
</P>
<P>
   His slides showed these statistics culled from the Centers for
Disease Control, the Journal of the American Medical Association
and the Institute of Medicine, a private medical group that advises
the U.S. government:
</P>
<P>
   _ About 15 million new cases of STD infections are reported each
year, and approximately two-thirds occur in people under 25 years
old.
</P>
<P>
   _ Twenty-five percent of all new infections from HIV, the virus
that causes AIDS, are in people under 22 years old.
</P>
<P>
   _ A higher percentage of 15-19 year-olds are infected with
gonorrhea than any other age group.
</P>
<P>
   The interns ``are very appreciative because many have never been
taught these things by health teachers,'' said John Hart, a
spokesman for Coburn. ``You don't see this on an episode of `Bay
Watch' or `Melrose Place,''' he said, referring to TV shows with
sexual content.
</P>
<P>
   One 20-year old female intern from Florida, who already has
learned the tried-and-true Washington practice of declining to be
named in a news article, told a reporter that the presentation was
``really scary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll definitely see my doctor more often,'' she said. But she
quickly added that she won't give up her sex life.
</P>
<P>
   A 19-year-old male intern from Arizona said the presentation was
illuminating. ``I didn't know about most of that stuff,'' he said,
adding that he'll think more about abstinence.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 and at the email
address eric(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
