<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0253 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-ORGANIC-MILK-ART-     07-30 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-ORGANIC-MILK-ART-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE BUYERS ASKING: GOT MILK WITHOUT CHEMICALS? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Mass., Ill., N.H., Wis., Colo., Texas, Minn.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 1)  
 (af)  
 By KATE MURPHY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Times were tough in 1994 at the Straus Family Creamery. ``The
price we were getting for our milk wasn't paying the cost of
production,'' said Vivien E. Straus, who struggled along with her
father and brother to keep their then 50-year-old farm in Marshall,
Calif., solvent.
</P>
<P>
   So they decided to go organic, and their fortunes turned up in a
hurry. Today, they are scrambling to satisfy booming demand for
premium-priced organic milk, cheese and butter.
</P>
<P>
   To consumers, ``organic'' means that the cows are not treated
with hormones or antibiotics and are given feed grown without
synthetic fertilizers or pesticides. To marketers, ``organic''
means money.
</P>
<P>
   From ice cream sandwiches to ricotta cheese, more organic dairy
products than ever are found in grocers' dairy cases, and not just
from small regional brands like Straus, whose sales last year
totaled $4 million. At least three specialist producers _ the
Horizon Organic Holding Corp., Organic Valley Cooperative and
Stonyfield Farm _ are distributing their products nationwide, and
bigger dairy producers are edging into the field. Sales of organic
milk products nearly doubled last year, according to the Organic
Trade Association in Greenfield, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Organic dairy products are still a small niche _ just 0.3
percent of the $75 billion American dairy market _ but the
predicted growth rate is phenomenal: Analysts say organics could
reach 2 percent by 2005, a nearly seven-fold increase. ``It's
booming,'' said Karen Raterman, editor of Natural Foods
Merchandiser, a publication that tracks organic and natural-food
sales.
</P>
<P>
   And the range of organic products has expanded from plain milk
and yogurt to include specialty items like jalapeno cheddar cheese
and chocolate chip ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   Demand began to take off in 1993, after the Food and Drug
Administration approved the use of rBGH, a genetically engineered
hormone manufactured by Monsanto and marketed under the name
Prosilec. Cows treated with the hormone produce as much as 25
percent more milk daily.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups questioned the adequacy of safety studies, done
on rats, that were offered as proof that milk from hormone-treated
cows is safe for human consumption. Animal-rights activists say
cattle given the drug tend to get more udder infections than
untreated cows.
</P>
<P>
   Some scientists worry that increased use of antibiotics to treat
the udder infections will promote antibiotic resistance in bacteria
that can infect humans. In January, the Canadian government
rejected the hormone on animal-safety grounds.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA and Monsanto contend that use of the hormone is benign
for both cows and people. ``We review all new evidence as it comes
to light, and so far nothing has caused us to believe rBGH is a
hazard,'' said Dr. Stephen F. Sundlof, director of the agency's
center for veterinary medicine.
</P>
<P>
   But some consumers remain skeptical. ``There has been a lot of
switching'' from conventional to organic dairy products since the
approval of the hormone, said Jerry Dryer, a dairy industry
consultant in Chicago. ``People would rather be safe than sorry,''
he said, even if it may mean paying 50 percent more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The speed of change in the industry has been staggering,''
said Gary Hirschberg, president of Stonyfield Farm in Londonderry,
N.H., which began selling organic yogurt in 1983. Before the FDA
approved the hormone treatment, Stonyfield's sales averaged $5
million a year, and product managers at mainstream grocery stores
``chuckled among themselves about these ex-hippies coming in,
trying to sell their yogurt,'' Hirschberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, Kroger and Safeway are calling us saying, `Can you get us
some of that hormone-free yogurt?''' he said. Stonyfield's sales
exceeded $42 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   Organic Valley, a 10-year-old cooperative in La Farge, Wis.,
that now has 135 member farms, has also seen sales rocket to eight
times what they were before the hormone was introduced.
</P>
<P>
   Those gains are built partly on eye-catching advertising and
marketing, a departure for an industry that mostly advertises
collectively (the ``Got Milk?'' campaign is the latest) and treats
its main product as a commodity. Horizon Organic, the largest
organic dairy producer, with $49.4 million in sales, and the only
one publicly traded, uses polychromatic packaging showing a leaping
cartoon cow.
</P>
<P>
   ``They stand out in that boring field of white you see in the
dairy case,'' said Donna M. Berry, senior editor of Dairy Foods, an
industry trade publication. Horizon also advertises in magazines
like Parenting and on cable television programs like ``Healthy
Kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Based in Longmont, Colo., Horizon Organic expects to double its
sales next year, to $100 million, a growth trajectory that caught
the attention of the Dallas-based Suiza Foods, one of the nation's
largest dairy processors and distributors. Suiza bought a 12
percent stake in Horizon in July 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Suiza's biggest competitors, Dean Foods of Franklin Park, Ill.,
and General Mills of Minneapolis, are also jumping on the organic
bandwagon with acquisitions. (Dean bought Alta Dena Certified Dairy
of City of Industry, Calif., in May) or line extensions (two new
organic flavors of Yoplait yogurt). Analysts say these crossover
players will earn 30 percent to 40 percent higher profit margins on
their organic items.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's remarkable how much consumers are willing to pay for
organic products,'' Ms. Berry said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
