u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SERB-DEATHS-NY     07-30 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SERB-DEATHS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO POLICE HOLD 3 ALBANIAN SUSPECTS IN MASSACRE OF SERB FARMERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ NATO police are holding three Albanians
as suspects in the July 23 murders of 14 Serb farmers from the
village of Gracko, and NATO has sent weapons, ammunition and
clothing to Britain for forensic analysis, officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   House-to-house canvassing and raids followed the killings, said
Col. Ian Waters, provost marshal and chief of the military police
in Kosovo, and resulted in the arrests Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The deaths raised concerns that NATO forces were failing to
provide security for the Serb minority in the crime-racked
province, and catching the culprits became a priority for NATO
commanders.
</P>
<P>
   The three suspects have denied involvement in the murders and
add that they are not in the Kosovo Liberation Army, Waters said at
a news conference here. They were arrested in raids on houses in
villages in a six-mile radius of the murder scene, which was in the
fields and away from the village. The police are searching for
further suspects, the colonel said.
</P>
<P>
   The victims ``were caught by surprise,'' he reported, adding,
``Apparently they were in a group talking and chatting.''
</P>
<P>
   The murder victims died from gunshot wounds. One was holding a
cigarette between his fingers. Another had a gun in his pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a specific killing,'' the colonel said. ``The people
did what they were intending to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The senior investigating officer, Maj. John Woodbridge, said the
victims, who ranged from a teen-ager to an elderly man, were not
mutilated. Several were shot at close range, Woodbridge said, and
one was shot in the back three times as he sat on a tractor 150
yards from the others.
</P>
<P>
   The commander of the NATO force in Kosovo, Gen. Michael Jackson,
spoke last week of the possibility of an organized terror campaign
by Albanians to push the remaining Serbs to leave. His comments and
the detention of the three Albanians have raised suspicions that
members of the the Kosovo Liberation Army may have been involved in
the deaths. But Waters said the motive was not known.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrilla leadership has condemned the killings and denied
involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents of surrounding villages speculated that the
killers were most likely ordinary people who were taking revenge
for the killings by Serbs in the Kosovo conflict. Every Albanian
village in the area has dug graves to bury war dead and has
accounts of random killings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The war ended, and a lot of Albanians are coming down from
hiding in the woods and think the world is theirs,'' said Gezim
Emini, 21, a shopkeeper in Hallaq, across the fields from Gracko.
``They have a gun in their hands for the first time, and they are
doing bad things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
