<HEADER>
A0265 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TERRORISM-PANEL-NYT &LR;      07-30 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERRORISM-PANEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT LAWYER OF LEBANESE DESCENT NAMED TO TERRORISM
PANEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By LAURIE GOODSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Justice Department civil rights lawyer, an Arab-American, has
been named to serve on a national commission on terrorism as a
replacement for a Muslim-American whose nomination was withdrawn
under pressure from Jewish organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Rep. Dick Gephardt, the House minority
leader, withdrew the nomination of the Muslim, Salam Al-Marayati,
executive director of the Muslim Public Affairs Council in Los
Angeles, after an outcry from Jewish leaders who accused
Al-Marayati of condoning terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-member group has been given six months to review national
policy on preventing and punishing terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt maintained that he removed Al-Marayati from the
commission only because it would take too long to get him a
security clearance. But Al-Marayati pointed out that he had already
gone through security checks to visit the White House, fly on Air
Force II, and because his wife serves on a State Department
commission.
</P>
<P>
   The new nominee, Juliette N. Kayyem, already had a security
clearance. She has served as counsel in the office of the assistant
attorney general for civil rights. There she developed policies
that would ensure that airport antiterrorism measures did not
unjustly focus on _ or ``profile'' _ Arabs and Muslims. She also
reviewed Immigration and Naturalization Service policy on using
classified information in deportation proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   James Zogby, president of the Arab American Institute, said,
``She understands the disparate impact that some of this
anti-terrorism legislation has had on Arabs and Muslims in this
country. She understands when biases become bad policy. I think
she's going to make an important contribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still think that Salam was a remarkable choice and are very
disappointed in the way this was handled,'' Zogby said, ``but we
feel that Juliette is a very competent attorney with sound
perspective on civil rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kayyem, 29, who grew up in Los Angeles, is of Lebanese
Christian descent. She is married to a Jewish lawyer who recently
became a professor at Harvard Law School, and the two had just
moved to Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kayyem said, ``My experience in civil rights and profiling
and security issues is what brought other people's attention to me
for this commission, and no one group endorsed it, or said it was
OK, or she'll pass. I don't think that happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Jewish groups opposed Al-Marayati because of statements he or
his associates had made that blamed Israel for inciting
Palestinians to terrorism and condoned actions against Israeli
troops in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Ibrahim Hooper, spokesman for the Council on American-Islamic
Relations, said of Ms. Kayyem's appointment, ``We have nothing
against her personally, but we're disappointed that the commission
won't have a Muslim representative. This leaves the issue of Muslim
exclusion from the political process unresolved.''
</P>
<P>
   Al-Marayati and Ms. Kayyem spoke together by telephone Friday.
He congratulated her and said he would be glad to cooperate with
the commission, and she asked for his input.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Marayati also has asked Gephardt to address the lack of
Muslim-American perspective in public policy. Gephardt responded in
a letter that he and Rep. David Bonior would establish ``a forum''
where political leaders can ``discuss key issues'' with Muslim
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unsettled issue,'' Al-Marayati said, ``is that we have to
focus on the selection process and ensure there are no litmus tests
in the future on any candidates for government commissions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
