</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-DRUGS-0731-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESS EXPRESSES CONCERNS ABOUT ONLINE PHARMACIES
 &HT;    By JONATHAN HALL
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A congressional panel on Friday heard warnings that
patients may be at risk when they order prescription drugs from
online pharmacies.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, lawmakers were told at a hearing, there is no law
that requires a drug-dispensing Web site to post information about
itself. Consumers often are unaware whether the online pharmacies
use the services of physicians or licensed druggists, or whether
they accurately dispense medication.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these sites operate for a short period of time at one
Web site address before disappearing and showing up under another
name, making it difficult for anyone to track them down,'' said
Rep. Fred Upton, R-Mich., chairman of the House subcommittee on
Oversight and Investigations. ``Among the concerns is the product
quality of these drugs and whether patients may be at risk of
serious and even fatal drug reactions due to lack of oversight from
a doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee staff has identified nearly 200 Web sites, many
of which operate from abroad, that sell drugs from ranging from
Viagra and Propecia to potentially addictive pain killers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am concerned that a wild West world is unfolding, where many
consumers are accessing potentially dangerous drugs with little or
no practical guidance,'' said Rep. Ron Klink, D-Pa.
</P>
<P>
   The panel listened to testimony from two television reporters _
one from Pennsylvania, the other from Michigan _ who told of
investigative stories they had aired about online pharmacies. Both
described the ease with which they were able to order prescription
drugs over the Internet. In one case, a reporter ordered the
anti-impotency drug Viagra by filling out an ``online
consultation'' on behalf of his cat, Tom. Despite correctly listing
the cat's weight and height, the online pharmacy did not raise any
questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``My constituents _ and frankly all U.S. citizens _ deserve the
same level of protections with an online site that they have with a
corner drug store. Nothing more, nothing less,'' Klink said.
</P>
<P>
   The American Medical Association announced Friday that there is
``an urgent need to establish medical safeguards to restrict these
dangerous Internet prescribing practices.''
</P>
<P>
   The AMA recommends that in prescribing drugs:
</P>
<P>
   _ A physician should have reliable patient medical history
available.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dialogue must take place between the physician and patient
during treatment.
</P>
<P>
   _ The physician should inform the patient about risks and
benefits of the drug.
</P>
<P>
   _ A physician should have appropriate follow-up to the patient's
outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Friday, the Federal Trade Commission urged Congress to
require Internet sites that sell prescription drugs to disclose
more information about their businesses and doctors.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC said the sites should contain the name, address and
phone number of the pharmacy that will dispense the drugs and where
that pharmacy is licensed to do business. Similar information
should be provided about physicians who prescribe drugs over the
Internet _ often after an online ``consultation'' with a consumer _
as well as the states where that physician is licensed or
authorized to practice medicine.
</P>
<P>
   There should also be information about any Internet operator _
separate from the doctor or pharmacy _ that is offering the drugs
for sale, including the principal owners of the business.
</P>
<P>
   The site should tell consumers the states from which it will
accept orders, the FTC urged.
</P>
<P>
   (The Associated Press contributed to this report)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
