<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0275 &Cx1f; taf-z
s a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRAD-TEACHING-EDLIFE-     07-30 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAD-TEACHING-EDLIFE-ART-850(3TAKES)-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRADUATE TEACHING ASSISTANTS: EMPLOYEES OR STUDENTS? 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was mid-June, and so Virginia Parks, a teaching
assistant in the geography department at the University of
California at Los Angeles, was singing the usual end-of-semester
blues. She had to grade roughly 80 final exams, each of them 8 to
10 pages, for a course on race and employment in cities.
</P>
<P>
   To earn extra money, she was also helping with a biogeography
class, and had to grade final exams for some of its 100
undergraduates, as well as a handful of their final presentations.
</P>
<P>
   For both courses, Ms. Parks is paid about $1,700 a month.
</P>
<P>
   It was a heavy burden, but those were just half of her
responsibilities; in addition, Ms. Parks is working on her Ph.D.
The day before administering the first of the undergraduate exams,
she had to take her own final in statistics. And days after grading
the last of the undergraduate exams, she would have to sit for a
grueling week of what are known as qualifying exams, the last step
before beginning a thesis. She had four hours of written exams on a
Monday, eight hours on Tuesday, four more on Wednesday, and then a
48-hour endurance test of an exam in which she had to research and
write a 30-page paper outlining a thesis plan for a hypothetical
topic that would be given to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little bit freaked,'' said Ms. Parks, 28, sounding
surprisingly cheerful nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Graduate student life has always been, to put it mildly, a time
of sacrifice. But that is part of the strategy: students are
regarded as apprentices, both scholars and educators in the making,
with tenured faculty wielding considerable power over their
futures. Teaching is seen as part of the training for a life in the
Academy. The modest wages are considered almost a bonus.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Parks and her fellow teaching assistants, or TAs, have
rejected this traditional academic model.
</P>
<P>
   In a shift that could have subtle yet far-reaching implications,
the teaching assistants at the University of California _ one of
the largest state university complexes in the country, with 170,000
graduate and undergraduate students on nine campuses _ elected this
spring to form unions to demand better conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``For these students, teaching is a job,'' said Elizabeth Bunn,
a vice president of the United Automobile Workers in Detroit who
has been overseeing TA unionization efforts. ``We've never accepted
the argument that there is a difference between the university and
other kinds of workplaces when the issue is work. The workers are
not asking to be paid for their work as students. They are asking
to be paid fairly when they work as employees of the
universities.''
</P>
<P>
   The California campuses are by far the biggest prize in a
movement that has been slowly gaining momentum around the country
for years. Twelve campuses, including three at the State University
of New York, had TA unions three years ago, according to the
AFL-CIO. Today, there are 23 unionized campuses, with serious
movements under way at institutions like Yale, Temple, Oregon State
and New York University.
</P>
<P>
   So far, only students at public universities, which are governed
by state labor laws rather than federal law, have succeeded in
forming unions, after being recognized as public employees.
</P>
<P>
   Unions hope the next breakthrough will be at a private
university. The National Labor Relations Board is considering a
case filed on behalf of New york University graduate students. If
the board decides that, under federal law, the TAs are employees
rather than students, it would open the way for a union vote in the
next academic year at NYU. It would also reverse a 25-year-old
interpretation of the law and enable union elections at other
private institutions.
</P>
<P>
   This shift is part of a broader change in university
instruction. Over the last several decades, tenured or tenure-track
faculty members have been teaching an ever-shrinking proportion of
undergraduate classes. The number of part-time faculty and teaching
assistants has increased to 47 percent in 1995 from 22 percent in
the mid-1970s, according to the Department of Education. The change
was motivated largely by the need to reduce costs, said Cary
Nelson, a professor at the University of Illinois who has written
extensively on this shift.
</P>
<P>
   Now, of course, most universities are prospering in a robust
economy, but the trend of relying on low-paid part-timers and TAs
is still growing, surprising researchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expected that when the financial situation improved it
would go away,'' said Dr. Jay Chronister, a professor of education
at the University of Virginia and co-author of a recent study on
this trend in teaching responsibilities. ``That has not been the
case at most institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason, Chronister said, is fear that graduate enrollment
would drop if TA positions were cut back. Also, some universities
want full professors focusing on scholarship and research. ``We
assess the quality of a faculty member, correctly or incorrectly,
through the quality of publications and grants they can bring in,''
said Chronister. ``We don't build our national reputation on
teaching.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Parks met with her six biogeography students in a classroom
off a palm-shaded courtyard. One by one they stood and, somewhat
nervously, gave presentations they had been assigned weeks earlier.
Each had been asked to critique an academic article assessing the
effects of development on various environments, from a national
park in Africa to a reef off South America.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Parks _ slight, energetic, with a droll sense of humor _
stretched out in a chair, a battered pair of eyeglasses sliding
down her nose. She listened patiently and asked questions to
stimulate discussion and draw out the students. After class, with
union organizing posters as backdrop and a bare table as a desk,
she spent an hour in the office she shares with other TAs, making
herself available to any student who strolled in, as she is obliged
to do.
</P>
<P>
   The biogeography class had been particularly time consuming, she
said, because it was outside her area of concentration, economic
geography. For instance, she needed to study the six articles she
had assigned the students, and regularly put in far more than the
20 hours a week the university sets as a guideline for TA work.
</P>
<P>
   Her real interest is economic development in the inner city _
social justice, as she puts it _ which is why she got a master's
degree in urban planning before embarking on a Ph.D. With
tenure-track positions much sought after and in short supply, she
said she is leaving open the possibility that she might end up
working for a think tank or nonprofit foundation after completing
her studies.
</P>
<P>
   She is convinced that one of the greatest obstacles to achieving
her goals is the teaching. But it is essential because she needs
the income. ``What's falling behind is my own research,'' Ms. Parks
said. She has had to delay for more than a year a paper on changing
patterns of immigrant labor within cities because she cannot find
the time. ``I would catch up over the summer, but I have to find a
job and work over the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some students who oppose the aggressive unionization
efforts agree that teaching can prolong graduate studies and make
it a more trying experience.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Young, a graduate student in geology, said she had lost
about a year in her studies because of her teaching load. But she
worries that undergraduates will suffer if TAs limit their work
hours, one of the union's main goals. ``It wouldn't be possible to
do a good job on just 20 hours a week,'' Ms. Young said. ``I would
feel like I was gypping the students if I didn't put more time into
it.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, tenured professors say they do not monitor the
hours that TAs put in, but do expect competent and full work in the
classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's sort of `Don't ask, don't tell,' '' said Mark
Ellis, Ms. Parks's adviser in the geography department and a
supporter of the union cause.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Savage, the professor with overall responsibility for
the biogeography course that Ms. Parks was helping with, calls the
system archaic. ``At one time, graduate students were really
captives of the faculty,'' she said. ``They had to do a great many
things for nothing. That sort of thing is frowned on now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Universities are increasingly like the corporate world,''
Professor Savage added. ``The perception of the university as a
protected place, as a place set aside from the hurly-burly of life,
is no longer true.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, university administrators disagree. They say
their greatest concern is that unionization would upset the
traditional, informal relationship between student and professor on
which graduate education has long depended.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, the concern for me is the possible establishment of an
adversarial relationship of two groups who should be involved in
nurturing and mentoring relationships,'' said Dr. Claudia
Mitchell-Kernan, UCLA's dean of graduate studies. ``We have felt
that the teaching experience was part of the education, and we
continue to feel that the educational component of the TA-ship is
primary, particularly for those preparing to go on to academic
careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's really the question,'' she said. ``Where the balance
lies.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Berne, NYU's vice president for academic development, who
has been the point man in the battle against unionization on that
campus, said the university's resistance has little to do with
finances. Instead, he said, the issue is flexibility and the role
of the professor as mentor, guide and sometimes colleague.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are students and the activities associated with a union
would harm that,'' Berne said. ``The fundamental academic
enterprise would be negatively affected in a number of different
ways. The work in graduate school is really individual and it
depends on a relationship with professors that the union would
homogenize.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Young, the geology student, believes unionization would be a
violation of a code of honor. ``By joining the union,'' she said,
``I feel like I'd be slapping the department in the face.''
</P>
<P>
   Last December, the organization behind the union drive at UCLA,
the Student Association of Graduate Employees, or SAGE, called a
strike for semester's end, the busiest time. Some TAs broke ranks
and taught their courses anyway. Some held classes off campus.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Parks chose not to go to class or grade any papers. She
described it as a difficult but necessary step.
</P>
<P>
   ``You heard a lot of people saying, `Oh, we're so dedicated.
This isn't really work. It's this higher calling,' '' she said. ``I
am totally committed to it, but it's a job. I just felt we really
had to stick with it. I believed the action meant totally
withholding our labor.''
</P>
<P>
   The action lasted four days, with the state Legislature stepping
in and calling for a cooling-off period. The university docked the
strikers' pay for the days missed, including Ms. Parks' wages. Ms.
Parks objected, because the work she would have done was merely put
aside for her to do when she returned. With the support of her
department, she was ultimately given full pay.
</P>
<P>
   The strike, though short-lived, underscored for many people how
strong the movement had become. It had taken 15 years to get that
far.
</P>
<P>
   The unionization drive in California began in 1983 at Berkeley.
Four years later it became affiliated with the UAW, which had been
trying to organize white-collar workers.
</P>
<P>
   After a two-day strike in 1989, the organization began
collective bargaining with the administration. It won two benefits
for teaching assistants: a partial remission of graduate student
fees and paid health care, excluding eye and dental care.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Parks met with her six biogeography students in a classroom
off a palm-shaded courtyard. One by one they stood and, somewhat
nervously, gave presentations they had been assigned weeks earlier.
Each had been asked to critique an academic article assessing the
effects of development on various environments, from a national
park in Africa to a reef off South America.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Parks _ slight, energetic, with a droll sense of humor _
stretched out in a chair, a battered pair of eyeglasses sliding
down her nose. She listened patiently and asked questions to
stimulate discussion and draw out the students. After class, with
union organizing posters as backdrop and a bare table as a desk,
she spent an hour in the office she shares with other TAs, making
herself available to any student who strolled in, as she is obliged
to do.
</P>
<P>
   The biogeography class had been particularly time consuming, she
said, because it was outside her area of concentration, economic
geography. For instance, she needed to study the six articles she
had assigned the students, and regularly put in far more than the
20 hours a week the university sets as a guideline for TA work.
</P>
<P>
   Her real interest is economic development in the inner city _
social justice, as she puts it _ which is why she got a master's
degree in urban planning before embarking on a Ph.D. With
tenure-track positions much sought after and in short supply, she
said she is leaving open the possibility that she might end up
working for a think tank or nonprofit foundation after completing
her studies.
</P>
<P>
   She is convinced that one of the greatest obstacles to achieving
her goals is the teaching. But it is essential because she needs
the income. ``What's falling behind is my own research,'' Ms. Parks
said. She has had to delay for more than a year a paper on changing
patterns of immigrant labor within cities because she cannot find
the time. ``I would catch up over the summer, but I have to find a
job and work over the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some students who oppose the aggressive unionization
efforts agree that teaching can prolong graduate studies and make
it a more trying experience.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Young, a graduate student in geology, said she had lost
about a year in her studies because of her teaching load. But she
worries that undergraduates will suffer if TAs limit their work
hours, one of the union's main goals. ``It wouldn't be possible to
do a good job on just 20 hours a week,'' Ms. Young said. ``I would
feel like I was gypping the students if I didn't put more time into
it.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, tenured professors say they do not monitor the
hours that TAs put in, but do expect competent and full work in the
classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's sort of `Don't ask, don't tell,' '' said Mark
Ellis, Ms. Parks's adviser in the geography department and a
supporter of the union cause.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Savage, the professor with overall responsibility for
the biogeography course that Ms. Parks was helping with, calls the
system archaic. ``At one time, graduate students were really
captives of the faculty,'' she said. ``They had to do a great many
things for nothing. That sort of thing is frowned on now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Universities are increasingly like the corporate world,''
Professor Savage added. ``The perception of the university as a
protected place, as a place set aside from the hurly-burly of life,
is no longer true.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, university administrators disagree. They say
their greatest concern is that unionization would upset the
traditional, informal relationship between student and professor on
which graduate education has long depended.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, the concern for me is the possible establishment of an
adversarial relationship of two groups who should be involved in
nurturing and mentoring relationships,'' said Dr. Claudia
Mitchell-Kernan, UCLA's dean of graduate studies. ``We have felt
that the teaching experience was part of the education, and we
continue to feel that the educational component of the TA-ship is
primary, particularly for those preparing to go on to academic
careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's really the question,'' she said. ``Where the balance
lies.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Berne, NYU's vice president for academic development, who
has been the point man in the battle against unionization on that
campus, said the university's resistance has little to do with
finances. Instead, he said, the issue is flexibility and the role
of the professor as mentor, guide and sometimes colleague.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are students and the activities associated with a union
would harm that,'' Berne said. ``The fundamental academic
enterprise would be negatively affected in a number of different
ways. The work in graduate school is really individual and it
depends on a relationship with professors that the union would
homogenize.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Young, the geology student, believes unionization would be a
violation of a code of honor. ``By joining the union,'' she said,
``I feel like I'd be slapping the department in the face.''
</P>
<P>
   Last December, the organization behind the union drive at UCLA,
the Student Association of Graduate Employees, or SAGE, called a
strike for semester's end, the busiest time. Some TAs broke ranks
and taught their courses anyway. Some held classes off campus.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Parks chose not to go to class or grade any papers. She
described it as a difficult but necessary step.
</P>
<P>
   ``You heard a lot of people saying, `Oh, we're so dedicated.
This isn't really work. It's this higher calling,' '' she said. ``I
am totally committed to it, but it's a job. I just felt we really
had to stick with it. I believed the action meant totally
withholding our labor.''
</P>
<P>
   The action lasted four days, with the state Legislature stepping
in and calling for a cooling-off period. The university docked the
strikers' pay for the days missed, including Ms. Parks' wages. Ms.
Parks objected, because the work she would have done was merely put
aside for her to do when she returned. With the support of her
department, she was ultimately given full pay.
</P>
<P>
   The strike, though short-lived, underscored for many people how
strong the movement had become. It had taken 15 years to get that
far.
</P>
<P>
   The unionization drive in California began in 1983 at Berkeley.
Four years later it became affiliated with the UAW, which had been
trying to organize white-collar workers.
</P>
<P>
   After a two-day strike in 1989, the organization began
collective bargaining with the administration. It won two benefits
for teaching assistants: a partial remission of graduate student
fees and paid health care, excluding eye and dental care.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-99 1900EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990730.0244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0278 &Cx1f; taf-z
s a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRAD-TEACHING-EDLIFE-     07-30 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAD-TEACHING-EDLIFE-ART-3RDTAKE-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LOS ANGELES: dental care. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The biggest break came last December, after years of litigation,
when UCLA's SAGE chapter won a ruling by California's Public
Employment Relations Board that declared teaching assistants were
state employees, not just students.
</P>
<P>
   A vote was ordered to determine if the TAs wanted to be
represented by the union. The union won the vote at UCLA in March,
followed a month later by Berkeley and then the remaining campuses.
A total of 68 percent who voted were in favor.
</P>
<P>
   Among the priorities are limiting work hours to 20 hours a week
(an unlikely prospect, all agree) or getting paid for time put in;
extending health insurance to include dental care and eyewear;
seeking a full remission of fees (they currently get 60 percent of
about $5,000 a year) and improving the grievance process so that
graduate students do not find their academic standing jeopardized
if they complain about abusive conditions or harassment on the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are doing is not going to make graduate student life
idyllic,'' said Ricardo Ochoa, a law student and president of the
Association of Graduate Student Employees at Berkeley. ``But it has
the potential for easing some of the pressures.''
</P>
<P>
   Students expect their lives to remain a constant balancing act.
Ms. Parks receives no financial assistance from her family. She and
her boyfriend, also a graduate student in geography, share the $550
rent on a small one-bedroom apartment in Venice. It is about seven
and a half miles from the UCLA campus, and Ms. Parks, a former
bicycle racer on the UCLA team, pedals her old bike to school most
days.
</P>
<P>
   Existence is Spartan, with a meal out a rarity. She and her
boyfriend go to movie matinees because they are a few dollars
cheaper, and they rarely socialize in bars or other venues that
cost money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you where all the free things are in L.A.,'' Ms.
Parks said.
</P>
<P>
   She is relatively sanguine about her financial restrictions, but
the issue is a sore one for many students tired of the economic
sacrifices. ``I feel like I should be a grown-up by now, with a car
that doesn't always break down,'' said Elizabeth Schirmer, 28, who
is working on her Ph.D. in English at Berkeley. ``It gets old.''
</P>
<P>
   Teaching assistants are buffeted by several high-pressure
cross-currents.
</P>
<P>
   Grievances against professors, for instance, have the potential
for wrecking academic careers, graduate students say. As it stands,
complaints must be taken to the chairman of the department
involved. There is no neutral third party to hear them.
</P>
<P>
   It is a little discussed subject, but anecdotes circulate about
graduate students who have faced some form of retribution after
complaining about a professor _ a poor letter of recommendation or
a refusal to transfer a graduate student to a different adviser.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could damage the position of a student and employment
prospects,'' Ms. Parks said.
</P>
<P>
   Rhoda Janzen, a poet who is getting her Ph.D. in English at
UCLA, agrees. ``The tenured professor has an unusual and even a
dangerous amount of power,'' she said. ``It's awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Teaching assistants also face pressure in grading
undergraduates. On the one hand, if the grading is not tough, it
can harm the TA's reputation as well as the professor's, Ms. Parks
said. Yet tough grading can be even more hazardous. Undergraduates,
increasingly worried about getting into professional schools, have
grown more aggressive in challenging teachers about grades.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be a tough grader you have to be willing to put in more
time explaining better what you did, giving students more time to
do their work,'' Ms. Parks said. ``You're sort of betwixt and
between.''
</P>
<P>
   The pressure ``isn't subtle, it's overt,'' Ms. Janzen said. She
was once threatened with a lawsuit by a student to whom she had
given a B. In general, professors back them up in disputes, Ms.
Janzen said, but it's important to be careful not to embarrass
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to tiptoe around the tenured professors as well as
the students,'' Ms. Janzen said.
</P>
<P>
   But undergraduate students face a similar situation with their
teaching assistants. Ms. Parks recently wrote a recommendation for
a student who was seeking to transfer to Stanford. The letter made
her realize the responsibility and power she had.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, I'm the one who knows the student,'' Ms. Parks
said. ``I'm the one writing the letter of recommendation, and
there's no recognition in the system for the role we play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
