<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0317 &Cx1f; taf-z
s a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWARTHMORE-FOOTBALL-E     07-30 1281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTHMORE-FOOTBALL-EDLIFE-ART-3TAKES-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWARTHMORE FOOTBALL: IS IT ONLY A GAME? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 1)  
 (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SWARTHMORE, Pa. _ Right in the middle of a game, Brian Bell
realized he had lost his motivation to play football.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never had I felt so helpless, where your actions don't make a
difference,'' Bell said, recalling his disillusionment with the
administration at Swarthmore College. ``If they are not committed,
then what's the point?''
</P>
<P>
   If a highly motivated student and athlete like Brian Bell was
unhappy, then football was in big trouble at Swarthmore, which
first fielded a team in 1878.
</P>
<P>
   By that 1997 season, Swarthmore was unable to compete even on a
modest scale. It was losing badly, its little stadium was
practically empty, recruiting had fallen off, and players were
quitting in the middle of the season, if not actually in the middle
of games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt the school could do away with football and it probably
wouldn't make the front page of the school newspaper,'' said J.P.
Harris, the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   There were, perhaps, enough reasons for Swarthmore to end
football, as other schools have done. But the college, invoking its
Quaker tradition of talking things over, began an internal debate
about whether football had any educational and communal value to
one of the more distinguished private colleges in America.
</P>
<P>
   The response was an open-ended commitment to upgrade the
program, using more aggressive recruiting and more money, in
particular an anonymous $100,000 gift from an alumnus to underwrite
some of the major costs like feeding and transporting these
large-sized undergraduates.
</P>
<P>
   Success has not been immediate for the Garnet Tide. In the first
year, the team still lost every game, and its losing streak has now
reached 28 straight games _ the longest in the country.
</P>
<P>
   When they talk about football, Swarthmore administrators sound a
little like bemused relatives who inherit a clunky heirloom from
honored ancestors. They try to respect it, to maintain it, but this
is not exactly a place where people go around chanting, ``Goin' to
Pasadena! In a Winnebago!'' as they might at a Big 10 mega-campus
on its way to the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   (At Notre Dame, in the fall, one could attend the most serious
convocation on liberation theology and soon be aware of whom the
Fighting Irish were playing next Saturday.)
</P>
<P>
   The costs and demands have begun to impress themselves on
Swarthmore's leaders. The reality is that football is more high
maintenance than any other activity on campus. It involves coaches,
equipment, food, travel, open fields, hard afternoons of practice,
recruiting trips and _ perhaps most important _ an admissions
department that sees something positive in young male applicants
with broad shoulders and a certain inclination to whack other
people around on autumn afternoons.
</P>
<P>
   Must there be a place for this sport at a small, elite college
like Swarthmore? Just exactly where is the law that says higher
education needs a football team to, pardon the expression, kick off
the academic year? Some Swatties, as they are known, ask that
question.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me the choice was either go to the library to study or go
to a football game _ so I chose the library,'' said Ethan Devine,
who graduated in the spring and works as a Latin American equities
research analyst for Goldman Sachs in New York City. ``I remember a
lot of people saying they were happy they graduated and the
football team hadn't won a game,'' he said. ``They think the whole
thing should be abandoned, and they're pretty bitter that that much
energy is put into it.'' Devine has never attended a game.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Wu, president of the campus Asian Society, also thinks
funds could be better utilized. He suggests new faculty members and
a student center. ``It's an academically focused institution,'' he
said. ``Focusing our money on sports is not beneficial for most of
the people at Swarthmore.''
</P>
<P>
   Swarthmore's tiny and peaceful campus, in a leafy suburb of
Philadelphia, has a decidedly 19th-century feel. The old main
building, Parrish Hall, looms at the top of a long, graceful hill.
By contrast, the athletic department is at the bottom of the hill,
separated from the main campus by a railroad line.
</P>
<P>
   The 1,300 eclectic students have things to do other than watch
football. A school brochure includes a sampling of campus
activities: several a cappella groups, the Civil Liberties Society,
Conscious Consumers, Earthlust (an environmental group),
Firefighters, Martial Arts, Mad Wriggles (madrigal singers) and
Swarming Earthworms (Men's Ultimate), a highly physical version of
Frisbee. The campus is a registered arboretum, and every April
Fools' Day _ how typically Swarthmore _ students change the names
of the plants and trees with fake placards, sometimes using arcane
Latin puns.
</P>
<P>
   The Princeton Review's ``Best Colleges'' 1999 edition says of
Swarthmore: ``What's Hot: Campus is beautiful, honesty, school runs
like butter, left-wing politics, dorms. What's Not Hot: religion,
hard liquor, drugs, beer, Greeks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anywhere else it would be a Ph.D.'' is the semiofficial slogan
of the bachelor program at Swarthmore, which U.S. News &AMP; World
Report ranks just behind Amherst as the country's top liberal arts
college. Grading is so tough some students complain they are
hindered in acceptance to graduate schools.
</P>
<P>
   Football has somehow managed to survive here. Early in the
century, Swarthmore competed with many major Eastern schools, but
as the sport became a powerhouse at some of them, the college
settled for the modest Division III, with its lack of athletic
scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Hall played football here in the early 1950s and later
pitched 14 seasons in the major leagues, mostly with the Baltimore
Orioles. Now a semiretired accountant in Timonium, Md., the lanky
Hall recalls with amusement a later period when Swarthmore ``hired
a good coach, and there was a question of whether they were winning
too much.''
</P>
<P>
   This ambivalence seems a recurrent theme. Neil Austrian, now the
president of the National Football League, was Swarthmore's captain
and quarterback in 1960. ``If I followed everybody else on a
Saturday afternoon, I would have wound up in the library,'' he said
recently. In Austrian's day, one of the big rivals was Haverford,
on the Main Line of Philadelphia, but that school gave up the game
in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football consumes a disproportionate amount of resources,
certainly the financial resources, time and the energy to do it
right,'' said Greg Kannerstein, the athletic director at Haverford
College. Kannerstein admitted he missed football as a community
event but said it was too difficult to recruit 60 to 80 men out of
a male enrollment of 550.
</P>
<P>
   At least 22 colleges or universities have dropped football in
the '90s, mostly for economic reasons. Officials at Boston
University emphasize that Title IX, the federal law mandating
gender equity in school sports, was not behind its decision to
close its program in 1997, as was frequently reported. It folded
football because of lack of interest. In the final season, an
average of 2,500 fans attended home games in the 13,000-seat
Nickerson Field. Boston University, which played Division 1-AA, a
higher level than Swarthmore, had just two winning seasons from
1985 to 1997, not enough for it to justify spending $3 million a
year in scholarships and operational costs.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he missed football, Boston's athletic director,
Gary Strickler, said, ``Yes, I do personally, but I don't know that
it's been a great void in our program, to be honest.'' There was a
fervent and angry and small group of football supporters, but
administrators say it has not remained a presence. The sport will
not be back, or certainly not anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   The trend is downward. According to the National Collegiate
Athletic Association, its membership and the number of football
teams is growing. But the rate of participation is declining. In
1956, 80 percent of member schools fielded a team. That percentage
dipped to 70 percent by 1971, 63.1 percent by 1981 and 58.6 percent
by 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, football has a huge psychic hold on America. Many
campuses embrace it with zeal, and the resources of a Fortune 500
company. There is the old story about the college president who
wants to have an institution the football team can be proud of.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Chicago, Fordham and Villanova gave up
football and then started it anew. They decided something had been
lost in campus life. And after 135 years of existence, little
Bryant College, a business school in Rhode Island, decided to field
its first team last year, hoping it might draw people onto campus
in the fall and attract students.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Bell, a wiry 6-foot-1, 190-pounder from Laurel, Del., had
played in two state championship games in high school. He was
recruited by the University of Delaware but worried that he might
not have been first string until his senior year. He met a
Swarthmore alumnus through an enrichment program in his hometown
and is sure he chose the right college, but his love of football
was sorely tested by the lack of success.
</P>
<P>
   In fall 1997, Swarthmore lost its first five games by margins of
56, 73, 49, 31 and 46 points, and Bell fought the urge to walk off
the field. Then the Tide went to California to play Pomona-Pitzer,
the team representing two of the prestigious Claremont colleges,
and was beaten by 64 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were making light of it, and that really hurt,'' said
J.P. Harris, the quarterback. ``We felt we were on our own. The
school spits out a lot of rhetoric on excellence, but we didn't
feel they were doing that on athletics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, losing was our fault. I'm never going to blame
anybody else. If you look at it, playing ball is a full-time job,
30 hours a week. Nobody is holding a gun to your head, but we
didn't feel that the effort was being reciprocated.''
</P>
<P>
   There were just not enough football players coming in, and some
already there were defecting. Feeling overmatched, at least seven
quit. ``Guys were doing a cost-benefit analysis about playing
football,'' recalled Bell, now beginning a career with Arthur
Andersen, the accounting firm. ``I had to make a decision myself.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``One thing I learned from football was commitment.
These are the moments that define you. You started something. What
are the messages you are sending to younger guys if you quit?''
</P>
<P>
   As the 1997 season ended with four more lopsided losses,
Swarthmore president Alfred H. Bloom considered ending the program.
``If I had felt it was necessary, I could have recommended it,''
said Bloom, who said he had extremely limited experience with
football.
</P>
<P>
   ``The students came to me, disheartened,'' he said. ``Football
was not living up to their expectations. I spoke to several alums.
It was clear to me that we would be in a better position to attract
people if we had football, but Swarthmore was letting them down by
not having an exciting program.''
</P>
<P>
   The school acknowledged a general malaise among students, and
found critics on the faculty.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Schwartz, a psychology professor and onetime associate
provost, is knowledgeable about sports but skeptical about
football's value.
</P>
<P>
   ``The students are worried that the need for bodies on the team
will skew the admissions process,'' he said, adding: ``Diversity is
a good thing. It's hard to sustain it if you need 75 people on the
football team.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most eloquent defenders of the sport turned out to be
Jennie Keith, the provost, a Quaker, an anthropologist and
decidedly not a football fan. ``We are an extraordinarily cerebral
place, but there is a pitfall in going beyond cerebral to
disdaining what is not of the brain,'' she said. ``It is against
the Quaker tradition to stereotype people. When people talk about
football, I stop to remember that my brother played center in high
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football brings us some kids who would not have us on their
radar screen,'' Dr. Keith added. ``We do intellectual work, trying
to understand life, but we need to combine this with some action in
the more messy world.''
</P>
<P>
   The players, quite naturally, felt threatened by even a debate.
``They throw around the word `diversity' and that applies to
everybody but athletes,'' said Harris, a political science major
from Derry, N.H., who will attend Catholic University Law School
this fall. ``Athletes are a minority here. You hear about 20
athletes being admitted, 10 percent, isn't that high? The
implication is, Are you really worthy?''
</P>
<P>
   Harris rallied his teammates. He and several other players
sought out Austrian, a member of the board. He reassured the
players that trustees still wanted football. There was a consensus
that the sport needed affirmation if it was to continue.
</P>
<P>
   After much discussion, the hierarchy did exactly the same thing
big-time foundries do _ it removed the coach, Karl Miran, whose
record was 25 victories, 51 losses and 1 tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was very uncharacteristic of Swarthmore College,'' said
athletic director Robert Williams. ``We agonized over the decision,
but if we were going to continue, we were going to have to bring in
new leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   The new coach was Peter Alvanos, 33, who had been an assistant
at the University of Chicago. Impressing people with his energy,
Alvanos, young, fiery and ambitious, was able to gain some perks
Miran surely would have loved.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of two and a half coaching positions, Alvanos now has
four (two of them doubling as track and field assistants), plus
several part-timers. According to Williams, coaching costs are
about $150,000 a year, close to double what they were two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football is somewhat more expensive than other intercollegiate
athletic programs at Swarthmore,'' said Dr. Keith. ``That greater
cost is one of the challenges in maintaining a football program
here.''
</P>
<P>
   For the 1997-98 school year, Swarthmore spent $47,116 for
travel, equipment and to hire game officials _ roughly one-quarter
the cost of all 12 men's teams. An undisclosed portion of $10.9
million in financial aid goes to players. There is no tangible
revenue, as there is at universities that charge admission to games
or have television income.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Williams expects the upgraded program to become more expensive
in the near future. The school has allocated $20,000 for a new look
in uniforms and equipment _ a sore point to other campus teams.
(Xiang Lan Zhou, 21, an engineering major who plays on the
badminton team, complains about the struggle to get money for
birdies.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been playing football with under 40 student athletes,''
Williams said. ``If this is successful, we'll have 65 to 70
athletes. That will mean more equipment, more beds, more food.
Instead of one bus, we'll need a bus and a van. It doesn't just
stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Money, however, is only one factor in football success. The
other is recruiting. At most colleges and universities, coaches
shake their fists at the sacrosanct admissions office, telling
horror stories of the brilliant blue-chip recruit who got away.
Before Swarthmore's new coach was hired, the athletic director read
him the facts of life: the only legitimate recruiting agent on
campus is the admissions office.
</P>
<P>
   At Swarthmore, the new dean of admissions is Robin Mamlet, who
worked at Occidental College, Pomona and Sarah Lawrence without
gaining much feel for football. ``You listen to the voices of the
institution, and they come from different places,'' Ms. Mamlet
said. ``We've always been proud of an engineering degree at a
liberal arts college. That's a voice. The football voice? That is
nebulous.''
</P>
<P>
   When they began talking about the future of football, Ms. Mamlet
said, ``we asked, `What is our responsibility?' '' The answer was:
``At least make it moderately safe'' _ meaning enough bodies so the
players would not be overwhelmed and exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   The goal was to start each season with 65 to 75 players, to
account for practice, backup for injuries and attrition. The hope
was that there would be 20 bona fide players among the 180 young
men accepted each year, about 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is significant,'' Ms. Mamlet said. ``That gets your
attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the school year ended in 1998, Alvanos assembled the
players who would be returning in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will never forget his first words,'' said Harris, then going
into his senior year. ``He said, `Take off your hats and sit up
straight!' The room fell dead silent, and that's when I knew things
were going to be different.'' (As it happens, those were pretty
much the first words of Lou Holtz when he began his epic regime at
Notre Dame.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen guys work out so hard,'' the quarterback said.
``I didn't think we were any more gifted, but the improvement was
attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvanos began involving the community, asking a marching band
from a local high school to play, and invited faculty members to be
his assistant for a game. Ms. Mamlet was on the sideline for a
wrenching 21-13 loss to Ursinus.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are kids I know,'' Ms. Mamlet said. ``I admitted them. I
was watching them do something that turned out unsuccessfully, but
there was so much drama when the coach sent them out there. It made
me realize even more that athletics have their place, to watch our
kids having fun, pouring their hearts into something physical.''
</P>
<P>
   When a dubious pass interference call set up a last-minute
winning touchdown by Franklin and Marshall College, they railed
against the officials with uncharacteristic volume and language
that would have been appropriate at a Philadelphia Eagles game.
</P>
<P>
   Alvanos' final 1998 record was eight straight losses, but Bell
called the season ``awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   At football powerhouses, on the morning after the last game,
coaches fan out all over the continent in search of new behemoths,
trying to charm the mothers and fathers of prospective recruits.
Williams, who began his coaching career at Rutgers University, said
with a chuckle: ``You can't really call what we do recruiting.''
Alvanos and his assistants tend to travel by car three to four
hours from campus. For the rest of the country, they rely on
recommendations, with candidates visiting campus on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Alvanos said he does not even begin to recruit a player unless
he has an SAT score of 1250. Ms. Mamlet said 1300 sounds a bit more
like it. She said the median SAT score at Swarthmore is 1440, and
though there is slight leeway for students with special skills or
gifts, football players fall within the norm, in potential as well
as in performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The final call is hers, and we respect that,'' Alvanos said.
``If she says, `Coach, you're wasting your time,' we're going to
cut him loose. If she says, `Coach, this one looks good,' we go
after him.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvanos is delighted to have recruited, by long distance, a
couple of backs who were sought by rival schools, as well as two
offensive linemen from the South, both around 6 feet 3, 265 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harvard has proven to me, personally, that football can be
played at every top-notch institution in America, if they do it
within the philosophy of that college,'' Alvanos said. ``We didn't
come here to make football bigger than the college. It's an outlet
for the kids, a way to let their hair down, let their minds be at
peace for two hours at practice, get rid of frustration or anxiety.
Some people go for walks, some people read books to relax, these
kids come here to play football.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is value to the participants, what is the value to the
campus?
</P>
<P>
   Community building is the rationale for football at many
colleges. You hear it everywhere, including here. ``Look at it this
way,'' Alvanos said. ``The only sport I know that has homecoming is
football, and that happens in the fall. It sets the tone for the
academic year. It brings people together. A Saturday afternoon of
enjoyment _ if you win, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bloom was asked whether he could see himself pulling the
plug on football somewhere down the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not yet the time to talk about it,'' he said. ``This
is still an experiment. I have full confidence it will succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Swarthmore's new season begins Sept. 4, when it matches its
28-game winless streak against Oberlin of Ohio. Oberlin has not won
in 19 straight games (following a previous 40-game streak).
Something has to give.
</P>
<P>
   The classic definition of football comes from Vince Lombardi of
Green Bay Packer fame: ``Winning isn't everything, it's the only
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Swarthmore's version comes from Dr. Keith (who has indeed heard
of Vince Lombardi): Winning isn't everything _ but it is certainly
something.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
