<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0326 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTING-DIAL-SON-HNS     07-30 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-DIAL-SON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SON OF FORMER FOOTBALL GREAT DIES IN ATLANTA RAMPAGE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn. Ga., Pa.) 
 
By ERIC HANSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ For several hours, Kevin Dial's relatives hoped and
prayed that he had survived the gunfire at his Atlanta office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew he had been shot but were hoping he would make it,''
Dial's aunt, Carolyn Burris, said Friday in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Dial, son of former college and professional football star Buddy
Dial, worked for Houston-based Momentum Securities and had moved to
Atlanta to help establish the company's office there. He was among
nine people shot to death during an investor's rampage Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Upset over stock trading losses, the investor killed the nine at
two Atlanta office buildings after he had killed his wife and two
children. He committed suicide when police were about to arrest
him.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Dial, 37, was a graduate of the University of Texas and
worked in Tyler, Texas, before transferring to Atlanta about a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Before word of the rampage hit the television news around 2 p.m.
CDT, Burris said, someone in the Atlanta office called Momentum's
Dallas office and told Kevin's brother, David, that Kevin had been
shot and was probably dead.
</P>
<P>
   Burris said her own son then began calling every Atlanta-area
hospital hoping to hear that Kevin, who had never married, was
being treated at an emergency room.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he couldn't find him registered anywhere by 5:30 p.m.
yesterday, he felt Kevin was dead,'' she said. ``He kept that to
himself because we were still hoping. The hope went away last night
at 11:30 p.m.''
</P>
<P>
   Burris said Kevin's identification was delayed because he
usually put his wallet in his desk shortly after arriving at work.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, we never lost hope until it was actually verified,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   She said Kevin had been busy lately working out the details to
transfer to Austin, Texas, where his mother lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sister is just devastated by this, '' Burris said.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime friend Howard Castleberry said Momentum's Tyler office
was doing well and that the company had asked him to help set up a
new branch in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a success,'' Castleberry said. ``The ironic thing is
that he wanted to come back to Houston or Austin badly and was
scheduled to come back to Texas on July 1.''
</P>
<P>
   The transfer was delayed however until later in the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was disappointed but was willing to wait,'' Castleberry
said. ``Instead, he's coming back in a box.``
</P>
<P>
   Castleberry said Dial's friends in Houston and Austin were
shocked and bewildered. ``He was one of the most loving guys you
could ever meet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't care for Atlanta too much,'' said another friend,
Tim Collins. ``He was homesick because all his friends and family
were here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it is a cliche, but he really was one of the finest
people you ever would want to meet.''
</P>
<P>
   Burris, too, said Kevin was widely loved and respected. ``He had
so many friends,'' she said. ''Hundreds of people are grieving.''
</P>
<P>
   A Momentum official in Houston said Friday that the last 24
hours had been ``hell for our employees and customers.''
</P>
<P>
   James Lee, principal of Momentum, described Dial as a loyal
office manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're devastated by this,'' Lee told a news conference. ``We
don't know why it happened. We'll probably never know. We're
grieving for our employees, our customers, their families and their
loved ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee did not take reporters' questions.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling her nephew's good deeds, Burris said he would often
take his 82-year-old grandmother, Verneda Howell, to church
banquets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those little old ladies up there just thought he was the most
precious thing in the world,'' she said. ``He called just a day ago
and left a message on her recorder that he loved her and would call
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of the most outgoing, loving people you would ever
want to meet.''
</P>
<P>
   About 19 months ago, Burris said, her nephew ``was diagnosed
with an inoperable brain tumor and had been taking medicine to try
and prevent seizures.``
</P>
<P>
   ``Here of late, '' she said, ``he had been having quite a few
more seizures. We feel like the Lord took him this way rather than
letting him suffer with a stroke or being paralyzed or crippled or
whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   Burris said she could not understand why a disgruntled person
would take out his frustrations on others.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he was so angry, why didn't he just shoot himself?'' she
said sobbing. ``Why did he go out and kill all these innocent
people? It is so sick.''
</P>
<P>
   Buddy Dial was unavailable for comment, said a family friend who
answered the former football player's telephone in Tomball, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Dial, 62, was an All-American end at Rice University before
playing for the Pittsburgh Steelers from 1959-63 and the Dallas
Cowboys from 1964-66.
</P>
<P>
   His playing days were cut short by injuries that have left him
in almost constant pain. Earlier this year, a federal appeals court
vacated an order that allowed him to recover full benefits from the
National Football League's disability plan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
