<DOCNO> NYT19990730.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0332 &Cx1f; tad-z
a p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-WOMEN1-COX     07-30 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-WOMEN1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lake hired to help Gore develop winning message with women
 &HT;    Moving in national and political categories for release on Aug.
1. w/photo.
 &HT;    By Scott Shepard
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The recent hiring of pollster Celinda Lake is the
strongest signal yet that Vice President Al Gore recognizes the
importance of women to his White House hopes.
</P>
<P>
   But don't try to categorize Lake as simply specializing in
``women's issues.'' Lake has been polling for Democrats for more
than two decades and has advised candidates in Eastern European
countries and South Africa. Today, she is one of the Democratic
Party's leading political strategists, and even those on the
opposite side acknowledge that she has keen insights and skills in
developing a winning message for politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is one of the best at peeling the skin off the onion,
getting to the root of the problem and creating a message,'' said
Jeff Lewis, a lifelong Republican who has occasionally hired Lake
in his role as executive director of the Teresa and H. John Heinz
III Foundation. ``I suspect that's why Gore wants her on board.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore campaign officials declined to discuss what role Lake would
have in the vice president's campaign. Gore already has a chief
pollster, Mark Penn, who also did polling for President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Lake indicated during an interview last week that her
role in the Gore campaign was still being negotiated and she would
not discuss that.
</P>
<P>
   Still, her comments, as well as her recent polling, provided
clear enough evidence of what Lake's chief advice to Gore is going
to be: If you expect to beat Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the
likely Republican nominee next year, you're going to have to win
the vote of women, first, and seniors, second.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can lose the men and win, but we can't lose the men and
women and win,'' she said. ``And seniors have to be a big target
group, if not the target group, for Democrats across the board.''
</P>
<P>
   Lake objects to the ``stereotyping'' of her as specializing in
women's issues. A baby boomer native of Montana, she has always
worked for ``progressive'' candidates, regardless of gender.
</P>
<P>
   But the so-called ``gender gap'' that has developed in modern
politics has, quite naturally, led her to focus increasingly on
women's issues and women candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a majority of the electorate, two-thirds of the swing
vote and two-thirds of the late swing vote (voters who decide in
the final two weeks of a campaign),'' she said. And while many
Americans are increasingly dismayed by politics, ``women are often
the ones who are paying attention,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   The ``gender gap,'' the differences between women and men in
political attitudes and voting choices, has been evident since
1980, when Ronald Reagan won the presidency largely on the strength
of his appeal to men.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two presidential elections, Clinton received his
winning margin from women: 54 to 43 percent over Bob Dole in 1996
and 45 to 41 percent over President George H.W. Bush in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent months, the Gore campaign has been shocked by
polls showing the vice president trailing the Texas governor, even
among women.
</P>
<P>
   In late May, for example, Gore trailed Bush 52 to 42 percent
among women in a CNN/USA Today/Gallup poll. Within a week, the Gore
campaign hosted a rally in which Gore and his wife Tipper,
surrounded by dozens of women elected officials, invoked his role
as a son, husband and father.
</P>
<P>
   The rally also featured first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton
endorsing the vice president with praise for being ``out front for
women, for children, for families throughout his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's speeches also increasingly included references to his
mother, Pauline, as a major inspiration in his life _ a woman who
graduated from Vanderbilt law school while living at the YWCA and
working as a waitress for 25-cent tips.
</P>
<P>
   And Gore has repeatedly lashed out at the gun lobby in pushing
for stricter gun controls, an issue that women in both parties
overwhelmingly support.
</P>
<P>
   But in late June, in the ``Battleground'' poll Lake periodically
conducts with Republican Ed Goeas, Gore lost to Bush 48 to 39
percent among women. Lake's conclusion: ``It is a formidable
presidential contest.'' And not long after that, the Gore campaign
asked Lake to sign on.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lake's ``Battleground'' analysis, Bush's popularity
with women voters is based largely on a perception that the Texas
governor has improved education in his state. ``They don't know
much about him except that,'' she said. And nothing ranks higher
than education among women voters.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has already called for ``revolutionary'' changes to improve
the public school system. But how does that get transformed from a
stump speech applause line into a campaign message that grabs
voters? ``That's what Celinda does best,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Lake has to figure out how to pull back seniors from
Bush. In the ``Battleground'' poll, voters age 60 to 69 favored
Bush over Gore by 18 points. And surprisingly, the top issue to
these seniors was not Social Security, as in the past, but values
and taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Lake traces this development to the aging of Reagan Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The voter who was 45 years old when Ronald Reagan was first
elected (in 1980) is going to be 65 in the 2000 presidential
election,'' she said. ``The Roosevelt seniors are dead. We've got
the Truman and Kennedy seniors, but the Reagan seniors are very
different.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's conduct in office has helped to sway these seniors to
Bush, but Lake thinks Gore has the opportunity to reverse that
trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore has some independent credibility on values,'' she said.
``He has established himself with these voters as having more faith
in God than the average Democrat.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Gore, a former seminarian, has called for government
subsidies for faith-based organizations to help with social welfare
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Lake believes the congressional Republicans' tax cuts and their
``lock box'' approach to Social Security reform are aimed primarily
at seniors. ``They've done a terrific job of targeting seniors,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a credible counter for Gore: He can warn that the
tax cuts could drain the budget surplus and jeopardize Social
Security. ``I tell Democrats don't be against the lock box. But we
don't want to lock an empty box,'' Lake said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
