<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-EMBASSY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TO PAY $4.5 MILLION TO COMPENSATE VICTIMS OF CHINESE EMBASSY
BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By SETH FAISON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ The United States and China agreed here Friday that
Washington will pay $4.5 million to compensate the victims of
NATO's May 7 bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement removes one of the biggest obstacles to improved
relations between Washington and Beijing. Several sensitive issues
_ Taiwan and trade, above all _ remain on the table as the two
countries prepare for the Asia Pacific Economic Conference in New
Zealand in September. President Clinton and China's president,
Jiang Zemin, are scheduled to attend that meeting.
</P>
<P>
   David Andrews, a legal adviser to the State Department who led
the American side in the negotiations, said Friday's agreement
reflected what he called ``the critical importance of the
U.S.-China relationship.'' Andrews said the money would be paid as
soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement does not resolve questions about compensation for
property damage to the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade or to the U.S.
Embassy and consulates in China in days of violent protest
following the bombing. Talks on property damage will begin in late
August, Andrews said.
</P>
<P>
   Andrews said the Chinese government would decide how the
compensation will be divided among the families of the three people
who were killed and 27 who were wounded. China will also distribute
the money.
</P>
<P>
   An administration official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said in Washington that the agreement was an ``important step in
putting this issue behind us and mending the relationship with
Beijing _ obviously it's very significant.''
</P>
<P>
   The bombing was viewed by Chinese leaders and citizens alike as
a grave affront to national dignity.
</P>
<P>
   Scheduled meetings on human rights, security issues and China's
effort to join the World Trade Organization were all postponed.
</P>
<P>
   Following the bombing, China's leaders adopted a stern line in
all contacts with the United States. They demanded a full apology,
a detailed accounting on how the bombing occurred and punishment
for those responsible as conditions to restoring normal ties.
</P>
<P>
   To date, Beijing's official position is that Washington's
explanation _ that the bombing was caused by faulty planning and
poor intelligence _ is insufficient. But American officials said
that in recent weeks they have detected efforts by Chinese
officials to find a way past their earlier, more confrontational
demands.
</P>
<P>
   China's state media gave wide coverage to phone calls that
President Clinton made to Jiang. The two presidents spoke when
teams from the two nations played each other in the Women's World
Cup Final on July 10.
</P>
<P>
   They conferred again last week after Taiwan's president, Lee
Teng-hui, infuriated Beijing with remarks widely interpreted as
nudging Taiwan closer to formal independence _ something China has
vowed to block with military force if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Minor progress was made in the compensation talks, Andrews said.
Previously, China was unwilling to discuss compensation for damage
to the U.S. Embassy and consulates in China, arguing that it was
caused by student demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   But Andrews said Friday that Yin Yubiao, the Chinese Foreign
Ministry's director-general for treaties and law, agreed to hold
simultaneous discussions about compensation for damage to each
side's property.
</P>
<P>
   Andrews stressed Friday that the $4.5 million compensation
payment is voluntary and does not represent an admission of
liability on the part of the United States. Washington has insisted
that the bombing was unintentional.
</P>
<P>
   ``This payment will not create any precedents,'' Andrews said,
apparently to quell concern about possible claims against the
United States that might arise from future military action.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most pressing issue in the coming months will be
China's desire to enter the World Trade Organization. With limited
time in a complex schedule of hurdles that have to be crossed to
win U.S. support for China's entry to the organization, American
officials said the talks would have to restart before the September
summit between Clinton and Jiang.
</P>
<P>
   So far, China has been unwilling to resume negotiations. The
compensation talks had been considered the primary obstacle, but
American officials say they will not know until they actually sit
down again at a negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the official New China News Agency reiterated China's
position that the bombing was indefensible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese side stressed that the U.S. bombing of the Chinese
Embassy in Yugoslavia caused serious personnel casualties and
property losses and grossly violated the international law and the
norms governing the international relations,'' the agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. side must bear all the responsibilities for this and
make immediate, adequate and effective compensations for all the
losses occurred to the Chinese side.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
