<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0339 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIOPURE-IPO-BOS &LR;      07-30 0495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOPURE-IPO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOPURE IPO BRINGS $30 MILLION LESS THAN EXPECTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Biopure Corp. had a rocky debut as a public company Thursday,
scaling back its stock offering and raising about $30 million less
than it had initially hoped to pay for clinical trials on a blood
substitute for humans.
</P>
<P>
   Biopure sold 3.5 million shares, 1 million fewer than the
Cambridge, Mass. company had planned, during its first public sale
of stock. The shares also sold at a slightly lower price than
anticipated. The deal, initially priced by Biopure's investment
bankers at $15.50 to $17.50 a share, sold at $12 each, raising $42
million.
</P>
<P>
   Biotech executives said it has become extremely difficult for
them to raise money, because they can't compete with Internet
stocks that are giving bigger _ and faster _ payoffs to investors.
</P>
<P>
   Biopure is among fewer than a handful of daring biotech firms
that have gone public this year, and analysts have been awaiting
its outcome for clues to the industry's ability to raise funds in
the near future.
</P>
<P>
   The conclusion: ``They did OK,'' Peter Feinstein, a consultant
with Feinstein Kean Partners Inc. in Boston, said Thursday.
``That's a lot of money. It's an average offering and it's the
middle of the summer and they did all right.''
</P>
<P>
   During Biopure's first day of trading under the symbol BPUR, the
stock closed at 10 1/4 a share, down 1 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   The disappointing first day came amid a week that was generally
favorable for biotech companies. The American Stock Exchange's
Biotech Index came within a few points of its all-time high
Thursday, as some larger companies reported record second-quarter
profits and investors turned bullish on the industry's growth
potential.
</P>
<P>
   Biopure's offering will allow the company to pay off loans to
Pharmacia and Upjohn Inc. More importantly, Biopure will be able to
continue the costly clinical trials, now in their final stages, for
a blood substitute that would be useful, if successful, in
emergencies and during surgeries.
</P>
<P>
   The blood substitute, Hemopure, is a product that will be
pivotal to the company's success. A canine blood substitute
manufactured by Biopure is already on the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a very tough market for development-stage IPOs,''
said Katherine Martinelli, a vice president at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
in Boston. A scaled back IPO is ``not necessarily indicative of
anything inherent in the Biopure story.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Hammer, a managing direct of Adams Harkness &AMP; Hill, one
of Biopure's underwriters, said the decision to sell fewer shares
was made the day prior to the offering. He conceded that the
strength of the Internet stocks has made biotech a tougher story to
sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would've liked a higher price, but we're happy that we
successfully completed our offering and are a public company,''
said Doug Sayles, Biopure's spokesman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-99 1934EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
