<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0341 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UPS-JOBS-BOS &LR;      07-30 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UPS-JOBS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAMSTERS SAY UPS NOT LIVING UP TO STRIKE SETTLEMENT PACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two years after the International Brotherhood of Teamsters
struck United Parcel Service of America Inc., angry members of a
dissident union group are demanding that the company adhere to a
contract requiring the creation of 10,000 full-time jobs over five
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The need for full-time jobs was a major issue in the strike,''
noted Bob Machado, an organizer at Teamsters for a Democratic Union
in Detroit, a 10,000-member faction within the union that sent out
press releases Thursday announcing that the contract provision has
stalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were concerned then that too many people were working
part-time with no chance of ever becoming full-time. We wanted to
create full-time jobs with full-time pay, but that is not
happening.''
</P>
<P>
   UPS spokesman Robert Godlewski &UR;  &LR; said the company will not add
full-time jobs until it has recovered package volume lost in the
1997 strike. The company maintains package volume has dropped to
11.5 million packages per day worldwide, down from about 12 million
prior to the strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Teamsters went on strike, the volume went down,''
said Godlewski. ``The contract clearly states that we have to be at
pre-strike package levels before we can create those full-time
jobs. We are not there. During the strike, people went to other
shippers.''
</P>
<P>
   Teamsters spokesman Bret &UR;  &LR; Caldwell said the union and the
company have been involved in arbitration over the matter for some
time.
</P>
<P>
   Under the contract signed after a bitter strike two years ago,
UPS agreed to add 2,000 full-time jobs annually by July 31, the
anniversary of the contract. A total of 10,000 full-time jobs were
to be created under the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``UPS has continued to delay the implementation of the terms of
the contract,'' Caldwell said Thursday. He added that Teamsters
president James Hoffa is ``committed to making sure that UPS meets
the obligations required in the contract.''
</P>
<P>
   The company employs 330,000 worldwide. Of those, 300,000 are in
the United States, and the vast majority are part-time workers.
``About 50 percent of the people who work in the hubs are
part-time,'' said Godlewski. ``That is the nature of the business.
These are people who work in four-hour stints, sorting packages and
documents on conveyors belts.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite lower package volume, UPS reported last week that
domestic packaging operating profits rose 17.5 percent to $878
million during the second quarter of this year, up from $747
million in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the Atlanta-based company's net income rose 28.4
percent, an indication of strong profits and a healthy balance
sheet. UPS, privately held since its creation more than 90 years
ago, also has announced plans to create a publicly traded equity
security.
</P>
<P>
   Godlewski attributed the company's increased income to greater
efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, during a speech at the Chief Executives Club of
Boston, UPS chief executive and chairman James P. Kelly said ground
volume was down 3.5 to 4 percent compared to pre-strike levels, but
ground delivery and international express had rebounded.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Kelly said the company was expecting significant
growth in the company's worlwide logistics business.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
