<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLOY LOOKS OVER THE FIELD AND DOESN'T LIKE WHAT HE SEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ A little background on Lawyer Milloy's anger
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   One of the people who has taught him more than anyone and whom
he's respected in his three years in the league _ Willie Clay _ was
cut by the Patriots Wednesday. Then, he sees his other friend, Ty
Law, trying to negotiate a huge contract extension _ for upwards of
seven years for more than $30 million and a signing bonus that
would be over $6 million _ while the Patriots have told him they
won't be able to do anything for him this year unless he agrees to
their deal, which Milloy feels is unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Patriots) like the $490,000 cap number,'' said Ray
Anderson, Milloy's agent. ``They're trying to get Law done, and
they have told us they can't do anything for us this year.''
</P>
<P>
   And so Milloy, an All-Pro, a fiery, loyal kid who plays at 100
miles per hour every Sunday, was perturbed.
</P>
<P>
   Did he think the Patriots made the wrong decision?
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you think? It's crazy,'' he said. ``How can you get
rid of someone who's played every single play for you? No matter
what everybody thinks. You're supposed to build around people you
can depend on. I don't care about one spectacular season somebody
had . . . you're depending on him coming back hurt and being
injured all the time every year (Willie McGinest?).
</P>
<P>
   ``You count on the people you can trust to be out there all the
time _ full go. I'm really upset right now. The way I play, I think
I've gained my respect from being out there every play, every snap,
barring injury. To lose somebody out there that I always want to go
to war with in the fourth quarter, not knowing he's going to be
there, is a big blow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a good move. It hurts us. I hope we get through it,
but I don't understand it. Willie was out there every play when all
of our money guys were sitting on the bench. Management doesn't
understand that we go to war out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Milloy left no prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids who wear everybody's jerseys, those are not the true
football players on our team. They let the true football players
go. It's getting ridiculous around here.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Patriots announced Clay's release, coach Pete Carroll
said he felt Milloy was ready to take the leadership role. Carroll
even said that his strong safety position and the free safety spot
could be interchangeable and that Milloy could wind up playing some
free safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in negotiations and they're contradicting
themselves,'' Milloy said. ``They're so quick to point out that
safeties are the lowest-paid positions. Now, I'm supposed to be the
leader and carry everybody?''
</P>
<P>
   Clay was touched by Milloy's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciate that from Lawyer,'' said Clay Thursday. ``That
means a lot to me. He's a great young player who really appreciated
what we had and we were building with our defense. Lawyer wanted
everyone to stay in their own roles because that was the best way
for our team to be a champion. Unfortunately that didn't happen and
Lawyer is upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll say this: I would have done the same for Lawyer or for Ty
if something had happened to them that happened to me. We were
close. We helped each other and I think Lawyer appreciates the help
I gave to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Milloy was not alone in his dismay over Clay's release. Law was
as well. Both have spoken at length to Clay the past two days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely don't want to see him go but whoever replaces
him, he'd better step up and we can't miss a beat,'' said Law.
</P>
<P>
   Law wasn't about to say much more in Clay's defense. He's in the
middle of sensitive negotiations with the Patriots that could earn
him a megadeal. Law's agent, Carl Poston, met with the Patriots
Thursday and again Thursday, and then left town without an
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Law said he was not discouraged, but he did say, ``After
training camp, I appreciate not talking about it. I'm calling off
all negotiations. I can't afford to play ball and talk about
contracts. My focus has to be on Keyshawn Johnson, not on my
contract. I'm not discouraged at all. I've made decent money
anyway. Where I come from, that's a lot of money, but among my
peers, I'm probably not in the top 20. I thought I played as good
as anyone in the top 10 two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully they'll come up with something. You want to keep the
best players on the field, but sometimes they let the best players
go. I've never asked for more money. I never said I was going to
hold out. I never asked for anything. I'm looking for big things.''
</P>
<P>
   Law said the deal will come down to the size of the signing
bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It always comes down to that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Law was peeved by the notion that because his deal hasn't been
restructured, the Patriots had to release his friend, Clay. ``I
don't understand that salary cap stuff,'' said Law. ``All I know
is, I've never asked for anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
