<SLUG> BC-NASA-SHUTTLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOSE PIN LIKELY CAUSED HYDROGEN LEAK, NASA SAYS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A hydrogen fuel leak on the space shuttle Columbia likely was
caused by a loose pin that was hurled from the shuttle's rocket
engines, NASA said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is still a work in progress,'' NASA's Bill Gerstenmaier,
a shuttle program official, said of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Gerstenmaier is coordinating the agency's investigation into the
leak and an electrical short that occurred five seconds after
Columbia lifted off. Had they worsened, either could have forced
Columbia's crew, led by Eileen Collins, the first woman spacecraft
commander, to attempt an unprecedented emergency landing.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia's five-day mission to deploy the $1.55 billion Chandra
X-ray Observatory ended successfully Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of Columbia's return to Earth, shuttle engineers
had confirmed their suspicions of a small fuel leak in the right
engine nozzle. They believe the leak contributed to a one second
early engine shutdown that left the Columbia in a slightly lower
orbit than intended.
</P>
<P>
   Gerstenmaier suspects a 7/8ths-inch-long, 1/8th-inch-wide, steel
alloy pin called an ``oxidizer port plug'' dislodged and flowed
into the right engine's combustion chamber. As it emerged in the
high-velocity exhaust flow, the gold-plated pin struck three of the
more than 1,000 stainless steel cooling tubes that line the nozzle
of the engine. The pin was missing after the flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears pretty conclusively that we were impacted by some
type of debris,'' said Gerstenmaier as he referred to a series of
photographs taken of the damaged cooling lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you see is evidence of an impact that scraped away some
of the metal or pushed some of the metal and thinned it out enough
that the tube could no longer hold pressure,'' he said. ``The tubes
ruptured, creating the three holes we see.''
</P>
<P>
   In a diagonal line about the length of three dimes placed side
by side, the holes in the damaged cooling tubes correspond to a
previously computed leak rate of five pounds of hydrogen a second,
NASA said.
</P>
<P>
   Film of the liftoff taken by launch pad cameras also shows a
bright flash in the nozzle, though engineers were not sure Friday
whether it was caused by the impact of the pin or with the first
flow of hydrogen from the leak.
</P>
<P>
   Pins of the kind under suspicion are used by shuttle rocket
engine technicians to plug fouled ports in the powerheads of the
combustion chamber. More than 600 of the ports channel liquid
oxygen propellent into the chamber where it is combined with
hydrogen.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Columbia's right rocket engine, two of the ports
had been plugged prior to the flight, said George Hobson, a
propulsion expert from NASA's Marshall Space Flight Center. Though
seldom used, the plugs permit an engine with a slight flaw in a
port to be used, Hobson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Chandra telescope was the heaviest payload every taken to
orbit by a space shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   In order to accommodate the observatory, the weight of Columbia
was reduced by several thousand pounds. Shuttle managers decided to
contribute to the weight savings by using older rocket engines,
models without safer but heavier propellant pumps and combustion
components.
</P>
<P>
   All three of Columbia's main engines were older. The right
engine was the oldest, having been used in 18 launches, the first
in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not say that we tried to run this engine too long,''
he said. ``We have very strict criteria on how long we use an
engine and in what condition we can use it in. We very carefully
review these engines prior to flight,'' said Gerstenmaier. ``These
were perfectly acceptable to use and more middle of the road even
than some of the other engines we have flown.''
</P>
<P>
   NASA said it was too early to determine whether the next shuttle
flight, scheduled for a mid-September liftoff, would be affected by
the findings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
