<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0358 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOT-PSYCH-COX     07-30 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOT-PSYCH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eds: WITH SHOOT-LEAD, SHOOT-CHRONO, SHOOT-LIST, SHOOT-PROFILE,
SHOOT-DAYTRADERS
 &HT;    Psychologist said Barton capable of 1993 killings
 &HT;    By Jane O. Hansen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Soon after the September 1993 murders of Mark Barton's
first wife and her mother, a Cobb County, Ga., psychologist who had
interviewed him told state officials that Barton was capable of
committing the killings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recall it as if it were yesterday,'' Douglas County District
Attorney David McDade said Friday, ``because he said it was his
opinion that Mr. Barton was capable of homicidal acts and thoughts.
Ideations is the word I think he used.''
</P>
<P>
   Barton was the chief suspect in the Labor Day murders, but no
charges were ever brought by Alabama authorities, who had legal
jurisdiction in the case. This week Barton went on a killing spree
in Buckhead and Stockbridge that claimed 13 lives, including his
own by suicide, in the biggest mass murder in Georgia history.
</P>
<P>
   McDade said that in February 1994 the psychologist, whom he
would not name, had called in his findings to a social worker with
the Douglas Department of Family and Children Services. The agency
had consulted the psychologist after receiving a complaint that
Barton may have sexually abused his daughter Mychelle, then about 2
1/2. A day care worker had reported the alleged abuse less than
four months after the bodies of the child's mother and grandmother
_ Debra Spivey Barton and Eloise Powell Spivey _ had been found in
a bloody trailer at Weiss Lake in Alabama, McDade said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, 7-year-old Mychelle, her 11-year-old brother
Matthew and Barton's second wife, Leigh Ann, were also found dead
in their Stockbridge, Ga., apartment.
</P>
<P>
   The psychologist said nothing in his written report about his
suspicions, McDade and child welfare officials said. His only
written observations about Barton were that he appeared, ``perhaps
understandably, irritated by the insistent suspicion of authority
figures and by these new allegations of possible sexual abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He appeared somewhat controlling, power oriented and very
suspicious,'' the psychologist wrote. ``He appears to have been
irritated by living in a household with a woman he considered much
brighter than he and a woman around whom he felt he had to be
`perfect.''' Upon hearing of their deaths Thursday, a distraught
Cathy Bitterman, the social worker involved in the case five years
ago, called McDade. ``She said, 'David, David, David, we knew
it,''' McDade said, quoting Bitterman. ``'Do you remember what the
doctor said?' I said, 'Oh yes, I remember it very well.' ``
Bitterman could not be reached Friday for comment.
</P>
<P>
   But according to her notes from a 1994 telephone call, Bitterman
wrote that Barton was angry he was being investigated as a possible
child molester. He also referred to his first wife's murder. ``He
stated that he was home with his kids when his wife was murdered,''
Bitterman wrote. ``But law enforcement treated him like a 'ghetto
nigger,' and that is also the way he described being treated by
DFCS (Department of Family and Children Services).''
</P>
<P>
   Based on the psychologist's evaluations of the two children, the
allegation of sexual abuse was ruled out, said Peg Peters, director
of the state Division of Family and Children Services. ``There was
no evidence to support it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sexual abuse, especially involving a very young child, is often
tricky to prove if there is no physical evidence. Social workers
often seek the outside evaluation of a professional to guide them
in their investigation. According to McDade, the day care worker
had reported to the child welfare agency that the child had told
her ``her daddy played with her boo-boo.'' Asked what she meant,
the child pointed to her vaginal area, McDade said.
</P>
<P>
   Once child protective services workers ruled out sexual abuse,
they closed their case. But, McDade said, he remained interested in
the psychologist's statement that Barton was capable of murder.
``Everybody in this community knew that Mr. Barton was the prime
suspect in the murder (of his first wife and mother-in-law). So it
wasn't like a new revelation, but it confirmed our gut feeling. It
was just another piece of circumstantial evidence to add to the
mix.''
</P>
<P>
   And he defended the decision by the Department of Family and
Children Services to close the case. Bitterman, he said, is ``an
excellent DFCS worker. She's as good as they come. She lives and
breathes these cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyce Goldberg, communications director for the Department of
Human Resources, said Bitterman had no choice but to close the case
because there was no evidence of sexual abuse. ``We had no way
legally to keep the case open,'' Goldberg said. ``She did the right
thing. She told law enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why the agency did not remain involved with the children
after hearing their father was capable of murder, Goldberg said the
psychologist never put his suspicions in writing. ``He did not go
on the record on that,'' she said. ``It was one of those
heart-to-heart kind of things. You know, 'I find nothing to
substantiate the sexual abuse, but I'll tell you what I feel.' If
he'd had a professional opinion, he would have put that in
writing.''
</P>
<P>
   The psychologist's written report instead focused on the sexual
abuse allegations, which he said were unsubstantiated. He said
Mychelle had been traumatized by the deaths of her mother and
grandmother and the suspicion that her father was their murderer.
</P>
<P>
   McDade refused to criticize prosecutors in Alabama for not
charging Barton with the 1993 killings. Douglas County law
enforcement had helped in the investigation because the victims
lived there. Richard Igou, former district attorney in Cherokee
County, Ala., said Wednesday there was no forensic evidence, but
McDade said there was some, just not much.
</P>
<P>
   He said that when investigators examined Barton's car, they had
sprayed it with Luminol _ a chemical that reacts with enzymes in
the blood. A positive reaction indicated blood on the brake pedal,
McDade said, but not enough to do further genetic testing to
determine whose blood, or even if it was human.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not questioning their decision at all,'' McDade said about
Alabama authorities. ``I think at best it was a circumstantial case
and circumstantial cases are always very difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Hansen writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
