<SLUG> BC-MIT-FRATERNITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIT WITHDRAWS DIPLOMA OF BINGE-DRINKING LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The Massachusetts Institute of Technology has
withdrawn the diploma of the fraternity member accused of leading
the forced drinking binge that caused the 1997 death of pledge
Scott Krueger.
</P>
<P>
   The diploma will be reinstated after five years, the institute
said. But an attorney for the fraternity member said his client,
who graduated from MIT 14 months ago, intends to go to graduate
school and will sue to have the diploma reinstated immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The fraternity member, 23-year-old Charles Yoo, was dubbed the
``pledge trainer'' during the event where Krueger went into an
alcohol-induced coma.
</P>
<P>
   Krueger started drinking the night of Sept. 27, 1997, at a party
at the Phi Gamma Delta fraternity in the Fenway. During the party,
according to the Suffolk County district attorney's office, Yoo
told Krueger and the other 11 pledges at the fraternity to watch
the film ``Animal House,'' the 1978 comedy about a raucous
fraternity, then drink beer and a bottle of Jack Daniels. The
pledges were then told to go in a room where their ``big brothers''
presented them with a bottle of alcohol and told them to drink it,
according to the district attorney's investigation.
</P>
<P>
   After drinking his bottle of spiced rum, Krueger complained of
nausea and was carried to his bed. When he was found later, he had
choked on his vomit. He was taken to Beth Israel Deaconess Medical
Center, where he went into a coma and died 40 hours later. His
blood alcohol level was five times the legal limit.
</P>
<P>
   Suffolk County District Attorney Ralph C. Martin II sued the
fraternity a year later. But the fraternity's Boston chapter had
already dissolved, and the district attorney's office acknowledged
that the case was moot without a defendant.
</P>
<P>
   The event prompted MIT, which had long relied on fraternities to
deal with a shortage of dormitory space, to announce plans to build
a new dorm and require freshmen to live on campus.
</P>
<P>
   The institute, under fire after reports that it ignored
students' warnings about excessive drinking at the fraternity,
voted to withdraw Yoo's diploma after a hearing Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Yoo's lawyer, Timothy Burke, said his client apologized at the
hearing. But Burke also said the institute had relied only on
hearsay in laying the blame on Yoo. The institute said Yoo provided
the alcohol and coerced the students to drink; Burke said MIT
provided no evidence that his client bought the liquor. Several
pledges, he said, also said there was no pressure to drink.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected that at the hearing, there would be some semblance
of fairness,'' Burke said, ``There was a complete lack of due
process.''
</P>
<P>
   MIT refused to comment on the case, saying student discipline
matters are confidential.
</P>
<P>
   Burke said he was not certain it was legal for MIT to withdraw
the diploma and that his client, now a stockbroker in Pennsylvania,
would likely sue to win it back.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a young man's life,'' he said. ``He's very bright,
very capable, and he never intended for this to happen. The
practical effect is, he's unable to continue his education.''
</P>
<P>
   James Borghesani, a spokesman for Martin said Thursday that his
office had no role in MIT's investigation of Yoo, and no role in
the school's decision to yank Yoo's diploma.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether MIT's disciplinary action against Yoo effectively
brings an end to the case, Borghesani demurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they'll ever be closure,'' he said. ``When an
incident involves a family member who dies, there is never
closure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
