<HEADER>
A0362 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-PERELMAN-$ADV01-2T     07-30 1291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PERELMAN-$ADV01-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RONALD PERELMAN, A MAN OF FEW WORDS, UNCLENCHES HIS TEETH 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release on Sunday, August 1) 
(DW) 
 By RICK MARIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The scorekeepers of the world might credit Ronald
Owen Perelman with having it all. A net worth of $4.2 billion, by
Forbes' last count. Palatial residences in Manhattan, East Hampton
and Palm Beach wallpapered with modern art. A jet, a yacht, all the
toys and now, Ellen Barkin _ the sultry 45-year-old actress who is
expected to become his fourth wife.
</P>
<P>
   For these riches, the very private Perelman, 56, has paid an
expensive public price. Many of his business and personal affairs
have ended in courtroom dramas. Because he almost never gives
interviews, his image has often been defined by his foes as that of
a volatile, womanizing corporate raider who budgeted his daughter's
diet at $3 a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a lot of misperceptions out there about me,
you know?'' he said in an interview in his office at MacAndrews &AMP;
Forbes, the holding company for his financial empire.
</P>
<P>
   Perelman is a complex, contradictory character. He hates the
press but can't seem to keep out of tabloid trouble, whether by
offering Monica Lewinsky a job or by giving New York's police
commissioner a private jet ride to the Oscars. He is obsessed with
his personal safety but goes out all the time, usually with highly
photogenic companions. His aura of maximum-security inaccessibility
only makes him more intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think sometimes I have been more mysterious than need be,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   After years of near silence, he now seems motivated to
straighten a few things out about his sometimes unflattering public
image.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do take a fat picture, but I've got a 28-inch waist!'' he
exclaimed. He wore a pair of tapered khakis and a neatly tucked-in
polo shirt. Short he is; fat he is not.
</P>
<P>
   A friend of Perelman was certain enough that he and Ms. Barkin
are getting married to name a wedding date of Dec. 1. Perelman
would confirm none of this _ not even that he and Ms. Barkin are
engaged. Asked if his pursuit of her had intensified, as one
bystander speculated, after Ms. Barkin took a younger man as her
date to Vanity Fair's Oscar party in March, Perelman declined to
discuss how they met or when the relationship began, except to say,
``We've known each other for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Best known for steaming up the scenery with Al Pacino in their
1989 movie, ``Sea of Love,'' Ms. Barkin is, for men of a certain
age, the ultimate sex symbol. The current cover of Smoke, a
quarterly for cigar aficionados, has her puffing a stogie above the
words ``powerfully sexy.'' Perelman is another famous cigar
chomper, and the reception area at MacAndrews &AMP; Forbes is stocked
with copies of Smoke.
</P>
<P>
   An audience with Perelman was granted with the stipulation that
it be an off-the-record discussion, only some of which could be
quoted on the record. James T. Conroy, a MacAndrews &AMP; Forbes vice
president who advises Perelman on public relations, took notes
throughout.
</P>
<P>
   This extreme wariness extends well beyond the town house from
which he controls 83 percent of Revlon Inc. and the rest of a
diverse empire that includes Technicolor, the film-processing
company, and a California savings and loan association that won a
$909 million settlement in April from the government.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous friends, foes and former wives declined to speak for
attribution, citing their fear of arousing Perelman's displeasure.
``You have no idea how powerful he is,'' said a former household
employee who, like everyone on the Perelman payroll, signed a
confidentiality agreement.
</P>
<P>
   One reason Perelman may be lifting the code of silence now is
the war with Patricia Duff over their daughter, Caleigh, 4. When
their child support trial resumes next week, the headlines likely
will, too.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Duff's beauty is matched by her facility with the news
media. Lately he has begun some counterspin of his own, counseled
by Conroy and high-powered public-relations Richelieus like Howard
Rubenstein and John Scanlon. Perelman wants to offset the image
that he said his former wife has disseminated of him as a
``domineering, manipulative, controlling, horrendous human being.''
</P>
<P>
   A profile of Ms. Duff, who declined to comment for this article,
appeared in the August issue of Vanity Fair, featuring some
surprisingly unguarded remarks by Perelman. ``She looks at you with
those eyes,'' he told the magazine. ``And she looks great, and she
moves great, and she smells great, and she sounds great. And I
thought, this is great.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last round of media coverage, Perelman was pilloried for
telling a lawyer for Ms. Duff that he could feed Caleigh on a few
dollars a day _ a remark he regrets making, but still will not say
was wrong. Friends portray him as a devoted father, especially to
his 9-year-old daughter with Claudia Cohen, Samantha, with whom he
vacationed in Europe two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the great socializers of all time,'' one of his
former wives said. Whether it's the recent 40th-anniversary party
for the Four Seasons restaurant _ which served as a kind of
coming-out party for him and Ms. Barkin _ or an invitation from the
hip-hop impresario Russell Simmons Perelman is there.
</P>
<P>
   He said that he showed up at the Four Seasons ``because of
Edgar,'' referring to Edgar Bronfman Jr., the Seagram Company
president, who owns the restaurant. ``And I went to the Russell
Simmons thing because of Russell. But I don't go to charity things
unless I'm obligated to, and I don't go to a lot of parties.''
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   Such obligations are closely intertwined with Perelman's
tricoastal web of friends and associates in New York, Los Angeles
and Washington. He spreads campaign contributions on both sides of
the aisle. He recently attended a dinner that Hillary Rodham
Clinton held in Washington for the prime minister of Israel. It was
President Clinton's friend Vernon E. Jordan Jr., a Revlon board
member, who asked Mr. Perelman for a job for Ms. Lewinsky in
December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   END OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   Society friends of Perelman say the media blow his night
crawling out of proportion.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Stern, the chairman of the Hartz pet food and real
estate empire, has known Perelman for 25 years and takes a similar
view. ``This is no playboy,'' Stern said. ``The opposite doesn't
mean you have to lead a boring life. He enjoys going out at night
for two hours _ fine!''
</P>
<P>
   John Sykes, the president of VH-1, recalled that after having
dinner in East Hampton with his wife, Perelman, Rod Stewart and
Rachel Hunter, Perelman invited everyone back to the Creeks, his
$25 million Hamptons home, to watch ``The Mask of Zorro'' in his
screening room, only to retire to bed almost as soon as the movie
started, leaving his guests reclining in their chaise longues. ``So
there I am lying next to Rod . . . '' Sykes said, still a little
perplexed.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart and Sykes are part of Perelman's aging rocker circle.
``He and I are both frustrated drummers,'' Sykes said. During
parties at Jimmy Buffett's house in the Hamptons, Perelman has been
known to get behind the drums and keep time for the likes of
Stewart and Billy Joel.
</P>
<P>
   A world he seems less interested in jamming with is the
high-society circuit adopted by many tycoons, often at the urging
of their socially ambitious wives. ``You won't see Ronald in a box
next to Mercedes Bass at opening night of the Metropolitan Opera,''
a close friend said. Perelman agreed. ``That kind of visibly social
activity has never interested me,'' he said, his gruff voice still
inflected with the vowels of his native Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
