u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-WELFARE-CLAIMS-BOS     07-30 0447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-WELFARE-CLAIMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELFARE CLAIMS IN BAY STATE DROP FOR 71ST MONTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DORIS SUE WONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Massachusetts had fewer than 50,000 families on
welfare this month, the smallest number in nearly three decades.
</P>
<P>
   In July, the welfare caseload dropped for the 71st consecutive
month to 49,711 families, a low not seen since the late 1960s,
according to the Department of Transitional Assistance.
</P>
<P>
   DTA spokesman Dick Powers said the continuing caseload freefall
is the product not only of Massachusetts' roaring economy but also
its 4-year-old welfare reform law. It requires able-bodied adults
to work 20 hours a week to remain eligible for cash aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is how we envisioned welfare reform would work at the
outset,'' Powers said. ``Namely, that able-bodied adults would get
off the rolls and go to work, leaving only those people who cannot
take care of themselves on the rolls.''
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for the poor said, however, the ongoing caseload
decline offers no reason to rejoice.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Albelda, a University of Massachusetts labor economist who
specializes in poverty issues, said the state's own study of former
welfare families, released in April, found that nearly three out of
10 did not have jobs a year after leaving the rolls. And of those
who were working, half had incomes below the federal poverty level.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Albelda said a large number of families dropped off
the rolls in recent months not because they had jobs, but because
they were forced off under welfare reform's time limit on benefits.
The time limit prohibits families from receiving more than 24
months of cash assistance in a five-year period if they are headed
by able-bodied adults and the youngest child has reached age 2.
</P>
<P>
   When the time limit began taking effect in December, the
caseload was just under 59,000. Since then, according to DTA's
records, about 6,800 families have lost their benefits under time
limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welfare sanction policies and welfare time limits have pushed
people off welfare,'' said Deborah Harris, a lawyer at the
Massachusetts Law Reform Institute. ``The question is into what?
These are the families with the most crises.''
</P>
<P>
   While DTA is in the midst of a long-term study of how those
families are faring, Powers said the welfare caseload has not
dropped faster since December than in previous months.
</P>
<P>
   As further evidence the law is working, Powers said that when
the reforms became law in February 1995, 22 percent of the 103,000
families on welfare were subject to the work-first requirement,
compared with only 9 percent today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
