<DOCNO> NYT19990730.0279 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0364 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-PERELMAN-$ADV01-NY     07-30 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PERELMAN-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
 
NEW YORK: native Philadelphia.
<TEXT>
<P>
   He has given away more than $100 million. He donated $20 million
to the University of Pennsylvania, one of his alma maters. He is on
the board of the Guggenheim Museum. . A major supporter of the
Hasidic Lubavitcher sect, he bankrolled a Jewish girls' school in
Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Perelman came to New York in 1978, with an M.B.A. from Wharton
and a $2 million stake in a jewelry company. He would use that
investment to buy MacAndrews &AMP; Forbes, a candy manufacturer whose
distinguished name he appropriated to open his assault on Wall
Street. A master of the junk-bond takeover universe in the 1980s,
he became better known for buying and selling companies than for
running them.
</P>
<P>
   After his leveraged buyout of the Marvel Entertainment Group,
the comic book publisher, in 1989, the company wound up in Chapter
11 and Perelman walked away $50 million richer. Revlon, for which
he paid $1.9 billion in 1985, is now estimated to be worth twice
that amount. He is openly seeking a buyer for all or part of the
company, whose shares and profits are lagging.
</P>
<P>
   Perelman is no stranger to litigation, lawsuits and countersuits
brought out of of personal and financial acrimony. In 1983, his
first wife, Faith Golding Perelman, took him to court over a
company whose ownership she claimed. In the case, Perelman was
represented by Roy Cohn; his wife, by the famously tough litigator
Stanley Arkin. Twelve years later, Perelman dismissed his chief
financial officer, Fred Tepperman, via fax while Tepperman was in
Florida on Christmas vacation caring for his ailing wife. Tepperman
sued. That time, Perelman hired Arkin to attack Tepperman's case as
he himself had been attacked a few years before.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Forbes listed Perelman's net worth at $180 million.
Since then, he has built a fief based in the side-by-side town
houses that contain his home and offices. ``The world revolves
around him,'' a former wife said. ``I've known a lot of powerful
people, wealthy people. I don't know anybody who has constructed a
whole world of his own. He is the boy in the bubble, he really is.
And he's manic about all of it. Living with him is like living with
a perpetual motion machine, which is how he stays very slim.''
</P>
<P>
   To secure this world, Perelman employs retired New York City
police officers and FBI men. He has been known to send armed
advance men to secure party sites before he arrives. A boater who
drifts too close to his waterfront property in East Hampton may be
rebuffed by a guard toting a submachine gun. A bitter point of
dispute with Ms. Duff has been the bodyguards who shadow Caleigh's
every move: he wants them, she doesn't. (Security was one of two
issues during the interview on which Perelman later refused to be
quoted. The other, the child support case, was kept off the record
at his lawyers' behest, Conroy said.)
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of Ms. Duff, Perelman has managed to remain
on good terms _ or regain them _ with his former wives and
girlfriends. He is close to Ms. Cohen again, who won an $80 million
settlement after their nine-year marriage ended in 1994, and with
his former girlfriend Elizabeth Saltzman, Vanity Fair's fashion
director. Mr. Perelman does not tend to squire mere models and
beauty-contest winners. ``He needs a woman who's independent and
has a big personality,'' said Larry Gagosian, Perelman's primary
art dealer. ``Or he gets bored.''
</P>
<P>
   A woman who dated Perelman for several months described his
formidable attentiveness and persistence. ``He leaned over the
table in the middle of a business meeting at Cipriani and said, `I
want to date you,''' she recalled. ``He focuses on you very
intently. He's a great listener. And it's not like he tells you
what you want to hear. He lends advice in a very constructive way.
That's the seduction process.''
</P>
<P>
   Perelman can, women who have enjoyed his attentions say, be fun.
</P>
<P>
   Something worked on Ms. Barkin, who is separated from and in the
process of divorcing the actor Gabriel Byrne, with whom she has two
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a very intelligent woman,'' said Harold Becker, who
directed her in ``Sea of Love.'' ``She's very strong-willed, and
she's her own person.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Barkin, through her publicity agent, refused requests for an
interview. But Gagosian, asked if Perelman had met his match, said,
``I don't know who I'd bet on in that one.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his immediate future with Ms. Barkin _ that is, whether
they were planning a trip to Europe together last week _ Perelman
would only squint his eyes suspiciously and ask, ``How do you know
where I'm going?''
</P>
</TEXT>
