last October. Under the amendment, anyone can write a request under
the Freedom of Information Act and get ``all data produced'' by a
published study paid for with any public dollars. Scientists and
university administrators are now alarmed, fearing that corporate
or political interests will use the law to hamper research on
controversial subjects, tie up scientists in red tape and
circumvent confidentiality agreements. By Philip J. Hilts.
(Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.) 1,700 words.
