<SLUG> BC-WARNERBROS-APPOINTMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARRY MEYER, COO OF WARNER BROS., IS EXPECTED TO HEAD STUDIO  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Barry M. Meyer, the chief operating officer at the
Warner Bros. studio, is expected to be promoted to the top
position, company executives said Friday. He would succeed Robert
A. Daly and Terry Semel, who ran the film, television and music
divisions for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, another insider, Alan Horn, chairman and chief
executive at Castle Rock Entertainment, has emerged as a top
candidate to run Warner's movie division, rival studio executives
and talent agents said. Horn is a friend and former associate of
Ted Turner, vice chairman and 11 percent owner of the studio's
parent company, Time Warner Inc.
</P>
<P>
   A Warner Bros. spokeswoman, Barbara Brogliatti, said no
decisions had been made about replacements for Daly and Semel, who
unexpectedly announced their resignations two weeks ago after an
enduring and generally successful partnership. But one senior
Warner Bros. executive said Meyer would soon be appointed to a top
job at the studio.
</P>
<P>
   In making known their decision to leave, Daly and Semel, who
have grown enormously wealthy, said they wanted to join forces as
entertainment entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   The promotion of Meyer, a low-keyed and respected lawyer who was
third in the studio's corporate command behind Daly and Semel,
would set off ripples across a studio that has been the most stable
one in Hollywood for decades.
</P>
<P>
   On one level, Meyer is not expected to have the full leverage of
Daly and Semel, who ran the studio, including the troubled music
division, with relative independence from Time Warner. Both Meyer
and Horn are expected to be less free-wheeling than their
predecessors, who also served under Gerald M. Levin, chairman of
Time Warner, as well as Turner.
</P>
<P>
   At another level, Meyer's promotion is expected to mark the
close of a somewhat flamboyant era at the studio started by Steven
J. Ross, the charismatic Time Warner chairman who died in 1992.
Daly and Semel, who were trained and guided by Ross, made
big-budget, often successful films, especially in the 1980s, and
were accustomed to spending lavishly on movies, producer and star
deals and perquisites. This is expected to end in the new regime.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer and Horn did not respond to phone calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer, 55, has worked on the business side of Warner Bros. for
28 years and has most recently overseen the company's television
production and distribution operations. He is also in charge of
legal affairs and strategic planning. A top talent agent said that
several senior Warner Bros. executives, responsible for such key
areas as the studio's stores and home video operations, had lobbied
for Meyer's promotion.
</P>
<P>
   A top Wall Street entertainment financier said Meyer was an
impressive, if little-known, figure, at the studio. ``He's done a
world-class job building Time Warner's television business, their
most successful business,'' the financier said. ``People on Wall
Street, and in the film business, don't really know him. He's very
mature and level-headed.''
</P>
<P>
   Once appointed, Meyer would face, along with Levin, an immediate
decision on how to deal with the struggling music group, which has
fallen to fourth place from first among the five biggest recording
companies in sales of current albums in the nation. This year,
Seagam's Universal Music Group, Sony and the Bertelsmann Music
Group have surpassed Warner Bros. in album sales. Warner Bros.
music has been struggling overseas, too.
</P>
<P>
   Several rival executives and talent agents said they expected
Levin to separate the music division and overhaul it. The music
unit has never quite recovered from the executive turmoil of the
mid-1990s when it was run first by Robert Morgado and then Michael
Fuchs, the former Home Box Office chairman. Daly and Semel took
over the music division in 1996, but it has floundered and
executives there have been criticized as out-of-touch with audience
tastes.
</P>
<P>
   Horn, 56, has had a mixed track record at Castle Rock, a
television and film division of Warner Bros.. Castle Rock's most
notable and biggest success by far was ``Seinfeld,'' whose nearly
200 episodes will run in syndication for years and will generate
perhaps $1.5 billion in revenue for Castle Rock. But the company
has fared poorly in movies, after a strong start with ``When Harry
Met Sally,'' ``City Slickers'' and ``Misery.'' Flops include
``Ghosts of Mississippi,'' ``An American President'' and ``Strip
Tease.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner Broadcasting, then owned by Turner, acquired Castle Rock
in 1993. After Time Warner acquired Turner in 1996, Castle Rock was
put up for sale by Levin, Daly and Semel. No buyers would pay the
price. So Castle Rock wound up as a division of Warner Bros.
studio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
