<HEADER>
A0379 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENATE-TAX-CUTS-HNS &LR;      07-30 1230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-TAX-CUTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE APPROVES $792 BILLION IN TAX CUTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID IVANOVICH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate approved its $792 billion tax-cut plan
Friday, and the leaders of the House and Senate now plan to
negotiate a compromise measure before the end of next week.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-controlled Senate approved the package by a 57 to
43 vote that was largely along party lines. The 10-year package
would hand U.S. taxpayers the most substantial tax break since the
Reagan cuts of 1981.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate package, authored by Sen. William Roth, R-Del., would
reduce the tax bite for those in the lowest income tax bracket,
do-away with the so-called ``marriage penalty'' and exempt some
capital gains income from taxation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people are entitled to relief,'' said Roth,
chairman of the Senate Finance Committee. ``What we are doing here
is restoring the excess taxes that have already been paid.''
</P>
<P>
   But Roth's bill differs significantly from the tax plan authored
by House Ways and Means Committee Chairman Bill Archer, R-Texas,
and passed last week by the House.
</P>
<P>
   Roth and Archer plan to meet Sunday to begin working out the
differences between their bills. They hope to craft a compromise,
and get approval from both houses before lawmakers leave for their
summer recess.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has repeatedly warned lawmakers he will veto
any tax reduction package of this magnitude. The White House wants
to limit tax cuts to no more than $300 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore on Friday compared the Senate bill to
``the trickle-down tragedies of the past,'' referring to derogatory
descriptions of the Reagan administration's 1980s tax cuts and the
idea that the money would ``trickle down'' to lower income people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leading economists agree that tax cuts of this magnitude, at a
time when the economy is so strong, is like putting lighter fluid
on white hot charcoals while the economy is cooking just fine,
thank you very much,'' Gore said. ``It could trigger up a dangerous
flare-up of inflation and singe the financial markets with higher
interest rates. And when the smoke clears, you've been burned.''
</P>
<P>
   With a presidential veto all but assured, lawmakers already are
gearing up for a new round of negotiations later this fall to pass
a tax reduction that will stick.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's early in the process,'' noted House Speaker Dennis
Hastert, R-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Thursday rejected an effort led by Sen. Phil
Gramm, R-Texas, and backed by Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott,
R-Miss., to push the Senate bill closer to Archer's version by
expanding the reductions in the tax brackets to all five tax rates.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill would lower the 15 percent tax bracket _ the
rate currently levied on the first $25,750 of any single filer's
income and the first $43,050 for joint filers _ to 14 percent
starting in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Archer's plan, however, would ratchet down all five income tax
brackets by 10 percent across the board over 10 years. His proposal
would reduce the 15 percent tax bracket to 13.5 percent, with the
first reduction to 14.85 percent coming in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill also would broaden the 15 percent tax bracket.
Starting in 2006, the total income taxed at that rate would rise by
$2,000 a year for singles and $4,000 a year for married couples.
</P>
<P>
   Together, these two changes would result in a tax savings of
about $450 a year for a family of four, Roth said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday afternoon, Lott said lawmakers are leaning toward
accepting Archer's across-the-board approach in the conference
committee. Roth wouldn't predict how the conferees would act,
saying only ``I find great merit to both approaches.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate overwhelmingly adopted an amendment sponsored by Sen.
Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, that would offer quicker relief from
the marriage penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The marriage penalty slams dual-income working couples, forcing
them to pay more income taxes than they would if they were each
filing as singles. These two-income families also pay more than
families where there's only one breadwinner earning a comparable
salary.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison's amendment, using language similar to that in the
House tax bill crafted by Archer, would raise the standard
deduction for married couples to twice that of singles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of this country who want to get married shouldn't
have to pay a $1,000 (more) in taxes just because they got
married,'' Hutchison said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   This measure would help an estimated 21 million couples,
including many families who don't face the marriage penalty now.
These couples would benefit from an increase in the standard
deduction.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison said many of those couples living on one income
deserve a break as well because they are taking care of children at
home.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison's amendment would kick in in 2001, although it would
not fully eliminate the marriage penalty. That would have to wait
until 2005, when a provision in Roth's original bill would take
effect doing away with penalty completely.
</P>
<P>
   To pay for earlier marriage penalty relief, lawmakers were
forced to delay other breaks in the tax bill to keep the cost below
the $792 billion ceiling. The broadening of the lowest tax bracket,
for example, was pushed back from 2005 to 2006.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Senate bill goes further than the House measure to
fully eliminate the marriage penalty, the conference committee
negotiators are likely to move toward the Senate version on that
provision, Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   Another amendment passed Friday was aimed at capital gains taxes
on profits on investments in stocks and other investments.
Conservatives had criticized Roth's bill for failing to address the
issue. The amendment would exempt the first $1,000 of capital gains
income from taxation starting in 2006.
</P>
<P>
   Archer's bill reduces the top tax rate individuals pay on
capital gains from 20 percent to 15 percent. His bill also would
lower the rate corporations pay on capital gains from the 35
percent now, to 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate tax bill also would eliminate the alternative minimum
tax _ the tax put into the code to ensure upper-income families
with numerous deductions pay at least some revenue to Uncle Sam _
for middle income families.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill contains numerous other provisions, including
eliminating income limits on Individual Retirement Accounts,
allowing changes to 401(k) savings plans, enhancing the tax
benefits for middle-income families trying to pay for child care,
and granting a 20 percent tax credit for renovating homes in
certain historic districts.
</P>
<P>
   The House also agreed to tie the tax cuts to reductions in the
national debt. If the country's debt load does not decrease each
year, later reductions in the income tax brackets would be delayed.
The Senate bill has no such provision, and Lott said there would be
opposition to adding it during the conference committee.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic lawmakers Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., the ranking
Democrat on the Senate Budget Committee, called the Republican tax
bill ``a magic show,'' a ``remarkable slight of hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont., a member of the Senate Finance
Committee, argued that if the bill were signed into law Congress
would be forced to raise taxes on to pay for budget deficits.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
