<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0382 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAX-CONGRESS-ART-900&AMP;     07-30 1351
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-CONGRESS-ART-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE PASSES $792 BILLION TAX CUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also SPEND-CONGRESS) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 1-888-603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(th) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate voted Friday to cut taxes by $792
billion over the next 10 years, moving the Republican-controlled
Congress toward a politically charged showdown with President
Clinton over how the nation can best use trillions of dollars in
projected federal budget surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was 57 to 43. Four Democrats joined 53 Republicans in
support of the bill, while two Republicans and 41 Democrats voted
against it.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would cut personal income taxes by reducing the lowest
tax rate starting in 2001. It would give a tax break to many
married couples, expand the Individual Retirement Account program,
create a deduction for some health insurance costs and reduce the
inheritance tax on large estates.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the bill's provisions, which also include breaks for
business and special-interest groups, would be phased in gradually
as the expected surpluses grow, and some would not be fully
effective until 2009. Of the total of $792 billion in tax
reductions over 10 years, only $4.1 billion would take effect next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. William V. Roth, R-Del., who was the main author of the
measure, said the Senate had taken ``a giant step forward to give
the American people a tax break.''
</P>
<P>
   The House passed a tax cut last week that is the same size as
the Senate's but has different provisions. Leaders of the
Republican majority from both houses met Friday even before the
Senate bill had been passed to begin reconciling the two versions.
They hope to complete their work next week before Congress leaves
for its summer vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said the momentum
within the party was toward adopting the centerpiece of the House
bill, a 10 percent reduction in all income tax rates. Such a move
would further harden objections to the tax bill among Democrats,
who say the House approach favors the wealthy even more
disproportionately than the Senate version.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has promised to veto the Republican tax bill in whatever
form it emerges from Congress. Along with most Democrats in
Congress and Vice President Al Gore, who laid out his own tax
proposal Friday, Clinton is pushing for a tax cut of no more than
$300 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the Republican approach would risk a return of big
budget deficits, forgo an opportunity for further reductions in the
national debt and leave too little of the anticipated surplus to
deal with Medicare, education, health care, the military and other
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``By pushing through a tax plan that is too big and too bloated,
the majority party has pushed aside our vital national
priorities,'' Clinton said in a statement released by the White
House as he returned to Washington from Bosnia. ``I will not sign a
tax plan that shortchanges our seniors and our young people. I will
not sign a plan that signs away our future.''
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, the House and Senate bills amount to the opening
gambit by Republicans in what is likely to be a high-stakes
negotiation between the White House and the congressional
leadership this fall over taxes, spending, Social Security and
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   To a considerable degree, any negotiations will be driven by
complex calculations within both parties about how a deal would
affect elections next year. With both the presidency and control of
the House up for grabs, some members of both parties would prefer
drawing lines in the sand and fighting out their differences on the
campaign trail. Others see a compromise as the best way of showing
that their party can be trusted to govern.
</P>
<P>
   But the fight will also reflect fundamentally different
ideological approaches to government and taxation.
</P>
<P>
   Even with a large tax cut, Republicans said, there is enough
money to deal with pressing problems like Medicare. And they said
returning as much of the government's excess revenues to the
taxpayers is the best way of insuring the economy's long-term
health, and the best defense against further growth in the size and
influence of the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you put a surplus on the table in this town, it gets
spent,'' Speaker Dennis Hastert said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said it is imprudent to lock in a big tax cut now when
there is no assurance that the anticipated surpluses will
materialize. They said the last big tax cut, in 1981, had sent the
nation into a spiral of rising deficits and debt from which it had
only just emerged.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is another riverboat gamble with the American economy,''
said Sen. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D.
</P>
<P>
   If the surpluses do materialize, Democrats said, they should be
divided among a variety of needs, including modest tax cuts for
low- and middle-income families, additional spending on vital
programs, reducing the national debt and shoring up the Medicare
system of health insurance for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   There is one point on which the two parties generally agree:
that the portion of the projected surplus generated by Social
Security payroll taxes _ about $1.9 trillion over the next 10 years
out of a total surplus of $2.9 trillion _ should go only to shoring
up Social Security's financial condition or revamping the
retirement program.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, they are fighting only over the remaining $1
trillion or so. After taking into account technical calculations
about the tax cut's effect on interest payments on the national
debt, the $792 billion Republican plan would use up nearly all of
the surplus.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the final hours of debate Friday, the Senate rejected or did
not take up scores of amendments intended to score political points
or secure a change that would benefit an interest group. But it
adopted a number of amendments.
</P>
<P>
   Among them was an expansion of the provisions intended to
eliminate the so-called marriage penalty, which leaves many
two-income couples paying more in taxes than they would if single.
The amendment, sponsored by Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas,
would add to the tax package an increase in the standard deduction
for couples filing jointly.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate also accepted an amendment offered by Sen. Robert
Torricelli, D-N.J., and Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga., to reduce
capital gains taxes. The measure would allow taxpayers to exempt
their first $1,000 in capital gains each year from capital gains
taxes, starting in 2006.
</P>
<P>
   Roth, the chairman of the Senate Finance Committee, and his
counterpart in the House, Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, chairman of
the Ways and Means Committee, are scheduled to meet Sunday to begin
negotiating in earnest over how to mesh their bills.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to reconciling different approaches to income taxes,
the marriage penalty, reductions in the inheritance tax and other
components of their packages, they will have to pick and choose
among a variety of much smaller provisions that are important to
politically influential constituencies.
</P>
<P>
   They will also have to steer their way around a number of
political dilemmas. Moderate Republicans in the House have
threatened to block the tax package if the final version does not
include a provision making the tax cuts dependent on keeping
interest payments on the national debt under control, a contingency
not included in the Senate bill.
</P>
<P>
   They could also be under pressure to delay those tax cuts that
take effect next year. Faced with an intense squeeze on spending
bills, the House is moving toward dipping into next year's budget
surplus to pay for government operations, meaning that money would
not be available for tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats who voted for the Senate tax cut were Torricelli;
Bob Kerrey of Nebraska, and John Breaux and Mary Landrieu, both of
Louisiana. The Republicans who voted against it were Arlen Specter
of Pennsylvania and George Voinovich of Ohio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
