u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARMY-SCHOOL-BOS &LR;      07-30 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMY-SCHOOL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOES OF ARMY TRAINING SCHOOL SUCCEED IN CUTTING FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EUN LEE KOH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After years of frustration, foes of the Army's
``School of the Americas'' won a key House vote Friday to cut
funding for the controversial facility, which they blame for
training Latin American military officers who trample human rights
at home.
</P>
<P>
   The 230-197 vote was the first congressional move against the
School of the Americas to win the support of the House, and marks a
significant victory for opponents who have tried to close the
school for more than a decade. Graduates of the school were linked
to the 1989 murder of six Jesuit priests in El Salvador, and to the
region's notorious death squads.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill would eliminate only about 10 percent of the $20
million in federal funds earmarked for the school, but the
relatively wide margin of victory signals trouble for the facility
_ which had survived four similar House votes since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't say the United States stands for human rights when we
are training terrorists right in our own country,'' said US Rep. J.
Jospeh Moakley, a South Boston Democrat who led the investigation
into the 1989 murders and sponsored Friday's amendment. ``This vote
sends a loud and clear message that we want this school closed.''
</P>
<P>
   The school, located at Fort Benning near Columbus, Ga., is a
military training ground for soldiers from Latin American
countries. Soldiers there learn tactics to combat communist
guerrillas and drug cartels.
</P>
<P>
   For years, opponents have argued for its closing because the
school has produced some of the worst violators of human rights in
Latin American history, including Panama dictator Manuel Noriega,
who is now imprisoned in Miami for drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which came as an amendment to the $12.7 billion
foreign aid bill, would withhold funds for recruiting and
transporting officers to the school, cutting the number of students
the school can admit per year. It passed the House after midnight
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This essentially means the school will gradually lose its
power,'' Moakley said. ``It will be forced to shut down if they
don't have any students.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Representative Joseph Kennedy, Moakley and other House
members have been mounting an aggressive campaign to shut down this
school since 1989, after 19 of the 26 people involved in the priest
murders were found to be graduates of the school.
</P>
<P>
   But proponents of the school argued that the investigations led
by Congress and the Pentagon over the past 10 years have failed to
prove allegations that the school teaches torture tactics to its
students.
</P>
<P>
   The school's supporters also argued that a majority of the
60,000 graduates have not been involved in human rights abuses. In
fact, many of its graduates promote human rights and support
democracy, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who persist in accusing the school of criminal and evil
conduct are turning their backs on the facts,'' Representative
Sanford Bishop, a Georgia Democrat, told the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Sonny Callahan, an Alabama Republican and
chairman of the foreign operations appropriations committee, said
he has sent investigators from his panel to Fort Benning to ensure
that it is not teaching terrorism tactics to its students.
</P>
<P>
   ``The school has cleaned up its act,'' Callahan said. ``The only
thing we hear year after year are the atrocities committed by
graduated of the school decades ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the bill argued human rights abuses by graduates of
the school are continuing even today, and that with the Cold War
over, the school is no longer needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This school not only trains effective soldiers, but effective
killers,'' said Representative James McGovern, a Massachusetts
Democrat, who as an aide to Moakley helped investigate the murder
of the Jesuit priests. ``Proponents will say that only a few bad
apples are causing trouble, but from where we stand, this school
graduates more than just a few bad apples.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside groups, particularly religious activists, have fought
against the school for years. Some opponents have launched hunger
fasts and have been jailed for their protests.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a historic first step towards shutting down the
school,'' said Carol Richardson, co-director of SOA Watch, a
watchdog group that has strongly opposed the school for the past
decade. ``This vote brings a message of hope to those who have
suffered at the hand of people who have attended this school.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
