<HEADLINE>
TAYLOR DEAL FAR FROM MADE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's the eve of what was expected to be the NBA's
relocation/reenlistment derby and there's big news from Los Angeles
Clipper Maurice Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they were trying too hard to shock everybody,'' said
the third-year power forward, who was not referring to team owner
Donald T. Sterling's anticipated reluctance to offer Taylor a
maximum contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, who dumped agent Norm Nixon for go-to rep David Falk
earlier this month, is seeking a prolonged Clipper contract worth
$70 million over six years.
</P>
<P>
   Such moves can be made starting Sunday, but during a recent
workout at Veteran's Sports Complex in Carson, Mo had other things
on his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too much foul language,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Was a contract the `language' topic of Taylor's review? No, the
topic was a movie, ``South Park: Bigger, Longer and Uncut.'' So
after spending some down time back home in Detroit, Taylor returned
to L.A. this week with a film critique and strong motivation to
resume voluntary, low-post oriented lessons from assistant coach
Jim Todd.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so the contract extension is an issue, but Taylor won't have
much to say on the matter until Falk returns from his African
vacation in another two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can say I'm optimistic,'' Taylor said, ``because I know the
coaching staff and most of the organization wants me around for a
while. But until David gets back, we'll have to sit and wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor has one season remaining on his opening, three-year deal,
but if the Clippers (Sterling) wait too long before making him an
offer he can't refuse, they (Sterling) risk opening the free-agent
door for many willing bidders.
</P>
<P>
   His final word on the the ``South Park'' flick?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it was as good as the TV show.''
</P>
<P>
   The Odom Watch: The updated ETA on Lamar Odom, the Clippers'
selection with the fourth pick in June's NBA Draft, is Aug. 8.
</P>
<P>
   The rumor network had the ex-Rhode Island star scheduled to play
in Magic Johnson' charity game Sunday at the Forum, but according
to the Clippers Odom never committed to participate. He had
intended to return to L.A. this month, but his grandmother recently
suffered a stroke, and Odom has remained in New York to be with
her.
</P>
<P>
   Travel plans: Sunday is a potential get-away day for several
Clipper free agents, but the intended escapees have a big problem.
</P>
<P>
   The league is virtually capped out.
</P>
<P>
   Forward/center Lorenzen Wright, whose agent has billed him as
one of the most-coveted free agents of the summer, has drawn
interest from the Indiana Pacers. But to bring in Wright for
anywhere near what his agent is asking, the Pacers would be
required to clear cap room by trading equivalent salaries back to
the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   One offer included point guard Travis Best and forward Austin
Croshere, but the Clips aren't wild about Best's shoot-first
reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Another possible Wright destination is Atlanta. The Hawks
reportedly may ship Steve Smith to Portland for tag-team shooting
guards J.R. Rider and Jimmy Jackson, then deal either Rider or
Jackson to the Clippers, who would sign Wright for a comparable sum
and send him to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers' free-agent list also includes small forward Lamond
Murray, who has drawn sign-and-trade interest from Miami (for
shooting guard Voshon Lenard) and Eric Piatkowski, a player the
Clips would like to bring back.
</P>
<P>
   Small forward Tyrone Nesby reportedly has piqued the interest of
several teams who realize the Clippers intend to match any offer
his agent can reel in. This also sabotages a sneaker contract from
a company that reportedly has offered Nesby a contract if he plays
for another team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
