<HEADLINE>
REP. FRANK STABLE AFTER BYPASS OPERATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ALOYSIUS FARRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ US Representative Barney Frank was said to be in
stable condition and resting comfortably Friday after doctors
performed coronary bypass surgery to clear five clogged blood
vessels in his heart.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Ferguson, the cardiologist who supervised the
operating team at the National Naval Medical Center in Bethesda,
Md., announced that Frank, 59, ``did very well during the
five-vessel bypass surgery, and is now stable and resting.''
</P>
<P>
   The procedure, in which blood vessels from Frank's legs were
transplanted to his heart, allows blood to bypass his clogged
coronary arteries.
</P>
<P>
   The Newton Democrat had a mild heart attack in 1990, and
suffered chest pains after exercise on several recent occasions. He
was given a stress test last week, and a heart catheterization
procedure on Wednesday, and was scheduled for surgery Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything went fine, as expected, and no problems are
forseen,'' said Peter Kovar, Frank's chief of staff. ``At this
point we are just focusing on getting him back on his feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank is expected to be discharged from the hospital next week,
and to make a full recovery, said Kovar.
</P>
<P>
   The congressman said before the operation that he hoped to
return to the House floor for votes next week, and to meet his
office appointments in Massachusetts during the August recess,
which begins on Aug. 7.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
