<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PERSONAL BUSINESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 1) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What Happens if Harriet Makes More Than Ozzie? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   American men, for the most part, no longer care if their wives
earn more than they do. But it seems their wives do care.
</P>
<P>
   While the caretaking housewife of 1950s television is no longer
the norm, a survey by Prudential Securities in New York found that
women are wary about stepping too far into the breadwinner role.
</P>
<P>
   In telephone calls to 851 randomly selected households, most men
said they were perfectly happy to have a high-earner wife: only 34
percent said they would find it a problem if their wives made more
on the job than they did. Yet 53 percent of women said they thought
there would be a problem in a marriage if the wife earned more than
the husband.
</P>
<P>
   So are men generally more liberated from traditional stereotypes
about financial roles? Perhaps. Asked whether a woman who earned
more than her husband should pay alimony after a divorce, 58
percent of men said yes, compared with only 48 percent of women. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Susan J. Wells &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fit for a New Start &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As more businesses find clients over the Internet, and as
customers increasingly take to the Web to compare prices and
offerings, traditional face-to-face sales representatives are
finding their jobs endangered. Two sales-intensive businesses where
the future may be dim are insurance and investments.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 10 months, nearly 13,000 job cuts have been
announced in these two sectors alone, according to Challenger Gray
&AMP; Christmas, an outplacement company based in Northbrook, Ill. But
John A. Challenger, chief executive of the company, says many of
the professionals set adrift in those cuts also have unusually
promising potential to find new success by starting their own
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Successful agents in insurance and investing are able to
develop a bond with their clients in order to learn what their
needs and goals are and then formulate a package of products and
services to meet them,'' Challenger said.
</P>
<P>
   That skill would be helpful in many kinds of businesses. But it
would be logical, Challenger said, for many of the displaced
workers in insurance and securities to become consultants in
financial planning _ a field that is likely to grow as more and
more people try to manage their investments, with the help of the
Internet, from their own homes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
