<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALKANS-SUMMIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADERS ENGAGE IN BACK-SLAPPING OVER BOSNIA SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO _ It may have been a courageous statement of faith, or
just an accidental irony: Bosnia, the nation hosting Friday's
high-level pow-wow on peace and stability in the Balkans, is so
dangerous that the State Department warns Americans against going
there.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't stop President Clinton and his fellow world leaders
from congratulating themselves on the end of the bloody wars in
Bosnia and Kosovo and touting the economic and political future of
one of the world's most troubled regions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Across most of central and southeastern Europe, the progress
of open societies and open markets has exceeded our most optimistic
hopes,'' Clinton told fellow heads-of-state in the recently rebuilt
_ and hastily gussied-up _ Zetra sports arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, they've done a remarkable, astonishing job of
rebuilding Sarajevo,'' Clinton added about the Sarajevans, who
endured a siege lasting more than three years. ``It doesn't even
look like the same place I visited two years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The scars of the 1992-95 war are still highly visible, though
some were bandaged-over for the meeting of scores of leaders of
nations and international financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the heavily-guarded arena is perhaps the most disturbing
example: What once had been a soccer field was turned into a
graveyard for the victims of the Bosnian war, a conflict that
killed 250,000.
</P>
<P>
   Most buildings are pock-marked from relentless shelling, and
others are in ruins. Land mines and booby-traps make many building
uninhabitable.
</P>
<P>
   The country itself is partitioned, and Bosnia-watchers believe
that the Serb-dominated Republika Srpska and the Bosnian Federation
_ home to mainly Muslims and Croats _ would ignite in war again if
international peace-keepers left.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders assembled Friday to come up with ideas to help keep
the fragile peace in Kosovo and Bosnia, and to make the rest of the
volatile region more stable _ a difficult task in an area that is
suffering from a series of wars, communist-era neglect, and added
economic fallout from the fiscal crisis in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton Friday presented a US plan to bring more foreign
investment to the region through a combined $350 million in
investment and loan money. The cash, operated by the US Overseas
Private Investment Corporation, would help businesses finance
investment in risky southeast Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But financial analysts are skeptical of the idea, saying that
the region is too political unstable and even dangerous for Western
companies to take a chance on them. The Clinton plan, they say, is
simply a bone to throw at US companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a very difficult time seeing anyone, other than the US
taxpayer, putting serious money into'' the region, said Spencer
Jakab, an emerging markets expert at Credit Suisse First Boston in
London.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not for any amount of money would I go anywhere where people
are walking around with AK-47s,'' Jakab said. ``You're not going to
see General Motors setting up an assembly plant in Pristina,'' the
provincial capital of Kosovo, Jakab said.
</P>
<P>
   The region still has serious, entrenched problems that make
things tough for investors, including communist-era legal systems,
cumbersome regulations, and corruption, said James Lyon, an analyst
with the Sarajevo-based International Crisis Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of what I'm seeing'' in the summit proposals ``is just a
whole lot of hand-holding,'' Lyon said.
</P>
<P>
   The region has some long-term possibilities; both Albania and
Kosovo have mineral reserves, and several Balkan nations have good
agricultural potential. But internal strike makes the countries
unpredictable. Albania has a serious criminal gang problem, for
example, and Montenegro threatens to explode in a civil war against
its fellow Yugoslav republic, Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's needed is a rule of law,'' said Kenneth Lefkowitz, an
investment analyst in Sofia, Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
   Bulgaria _ at the brink of both civil war and complete economic
collapse in 1997 _ has improved markedly since then. But it is only
because the International Monetary Fund forced a currency control
board and other strict financial rules on the still-emerging,
former Soviet satellite in exchange for the International Monetary
Fund's help, Lefkowitz said.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the Clinton plan forced the Balkan nations to make real,
fundamental reforms in their economic and legal systems, ``you're
just delaying the day of recovery,'' Lefkowitz said.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential economic adviser Gene Sperling said there was an
``inherent'' condition on the money, since would-be investors _
even with the nudging and financial help of the Overseas Private
Investment Corporation _ would not sink money into countries unless
those nations made reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Dangling the investment fund in front of southeastern Europe
will create an incentive for those nations to change, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cash is the dominant weapon in the Clinton administration
approach to making southeast Europe more democratic and safer.
Serbia, for example, is being ceremoniously cut out of any plans to
reconstruct in the Balkans _ an idea backed by the scores of world
political and financial leaders at the Stability Pact Summit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peace requires economic progress. Conversely, economic
progress requires peace,'' said Bodo Hombach, the summit's special
coordinator. ``The very second'' Yugoslavs dump their president,
indicted war criminal Slobodan Milosevic, and embrace democracy,
``the stability pact will start up as a partner for its
reconstruction.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from punishing Serbia, the Clinton administration wants to
help its opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro, whose government opposes Milosevic, will be eligible
for help, said Clinton National Security Advisor Samuel Berger. But
Berger could not explain how money could be funneled to Montenegro
without having it go through the federal government in Belgrade,
which might well siphon off some of the cash for itself.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also proposed spending $10 million to ``promote
democracy in Serbia,'' helping the feeble Serbian opposition to
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``A large majority of the people in Serbia would like to see new
leadership,'' Berger said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
