<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0399 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENATE-TAXCUT-BOS &LR;      07-30 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-TAXCUT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAX CUT OK'D IN SENATE; SHOWDOWN WITH CLINTON LOOMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate approved the largest tax cut in history
Friday, a proposed $792 billion break that creates a titanic
bargaining chip for Republican congressional leaders as they enter
crucial negotiations with President Clinton over the nation's
budget priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Clinton's veto threat, the Senate passed the huge
package, 57-43, after four days of heated debate and political
posturing, with leaders of both sides casting an eye toward the
2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Each side immediately sought to depict the other as out of step
with the nation's interests. The measure is expected to reach the
White House in September, after House and Senate leaders reconcile
their competing versions of a proposed tax break over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to cut taxes and the president wants to spend it,''
said the Senate majority leader, Trent Lott. ``That's what the
fighting is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House and many Democrats warned that the proposed tax
breaks are based on fragile projections of a $3 trillion surplus
over 10 years and are so exorbitant that many domestic programs
might need to be scaled back to subsidize the cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has said he would oppose any tax cuts greater than $300
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Senate made the wrong choice for America's future today,''
he said in a statement issued during his flight home from the
Bosnian capital of Sarajevo. ``By pushing through a tax plan that
is too big and too bloated, the majority party has pushed aside our
vital national priorities. The Republican tax cut is so large it
would undo our fiscal discipline and imperil our prosperity.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate measure would reduce the 15 percent tax bracket to 14
percent, ease the so-called ``marriage penalty,'' reduce
inheritance taxes, increase contribution limits for retirement
programs, and expand credits for education, health care, and child
care.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps the family and it helps the country,'' said Senator
William V. Roth, a Delaware Republican who is chairman of the
Finance Committee and the measure's chief architect.
</P>
<P>
   All but two of the Senate's 55 Republicans voted for the $792
billion break, joined by the New Hampshire Independent, Bob Smith,
and four Democrats: Robert G. Torricelli of New Jersey, Bob Kerrey
of Nebraska, and John B. Breaux and Mary L. Landrieu, both of
Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   The two Republican defectors were Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania
and George V. Voinovich of Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans fended off a flurry of last-minute attempts to amend
the bill, including an effort by Senator John F. Kerry to set aside
$20 billion of the projected surplus to increase Medicare
reimbursements to teaching hospitals, home health care agencies and
other Medicare providers that have been hit hard by cutbacks in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate narrowly defeated Kerry's measure, 51-49, as six
Republicans sided with Kerry and two Democrats defected. The GOP
supporters included the Maine senators _ Olympia J. Snowe and Susan
M. Collins _ and John H. Chafee of Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``I regret that on an issue that matters to so many in this
country, the Senate would side with a tax giveaway that benefits so
few,'' Kerry said after the vote. But Kerry expressed optimism
about securing the Medicare money before the budget showdown ends
later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Before the wrangling begins, though, the Senate and House must
reconcile their competing plans. Under the House plan, whose
centerpiece is a 10-percent cut in tax rates across the board, the
wealthy would reap a much larger portion of the tax savings than
they would under the Senate proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Lott expressed support for the across-the-board cut, calling the
plan ``the fairest'' because it would return the most money to the
taxpayers who contibrute the most.
</P>
<P>
   After a strategy session with House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert,
Lott said the two leaders hope to resolve differences in their
plans by the end of next week. But Lott said he will not send the
final package to the White House until Congress returns from its
summer recess in September.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for that, Lott said, is to prevent Clinton from
throwing ``a veto party'' while Congress is out of town.
</P>
<P>
   Once Clinton has vetoed the plan, negotiations will begin over
how best to allocate the projected surplus. The talks are expected
to touch on nearly every aspect of budget policy, from narrowly
targeted tax incentives to the long-term stability of the Medicare
and Social Security programs.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the struggle, supporters of a bipartisan alternative plan
to continue their push for $500 billion in tax cuts, which would
effectively split the difference between Clinton's $300 billion
limit and the GOP's $792 billion proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The plan's backers urged both sides to forgo a lengthy stalemate
that could end in a ``financial train wreck'' similar to the
goverment shutdown of 1995. ``All of this maneuvering could be
avoided by the acceptance now of this sensible, bipartisan
alternative,'' said Chafee, who is scheduled to appear on NBC's
``Meet the Press'' Sunday to rally support for the compromise.
</P>
<P>
   As a sign of the maneuvering, Democrats forced a number of
politically sensitive votes in the final hours of the tax-cut
debate, including Senator Edward M. Kennedy's push to raise the
minimum to $6.15 an hour by September 2000. The minimum wage is
currently $5.15.
</P>
<P>
   ``This amendment says that if you work 52 weeks a year, 40 hours
a week, you ought to be entitled not to live in poverty,'' Kennedy
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate defeated the measure, 54-46, on a procedural vote,
with Specter the only member Republican to join the unified
Democratic minority in the losing effort.
</P>
<P>
   Among the few amendments adopted without opposition was a
provision by Senator Judd Gregg, a New Hampshire Republican, to
expand eligibility for the child-care tax credit to all families
with children under age 1. Under current law, the credit applies
only to families who place their children in day care.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg said the change was aimed at ending discrimination against
parents who stay home to care for their children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
