s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-$A     07-30 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NUDGING OUT MIDDLEMEN WITH A CHIP  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 1) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   America's biggest securities exchanges are under attack for the
way they do business. The days of the buttonwood tree under which
the New York Stock Exchange was founded, in 1792, are long gone,
and the days of the specialist seem to be fading.
</P>
<P>
   The era of the button _ otherwise known as electronic
communications networks, or ECNs _ seems to be moving in fast.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Stock Exchange and the NASDAQ stock market, the big
boys on the block, are feeling the heat. Last week, NASDAQ's board
authorized stepped-up preparations for converting the exchange into
a publicly traded company. The Big Board is considering a similar
move.
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ's action came a day after Archipelago, an upstart ECN
that accounts for about 2 percent of NASDAQ's daily volume, said it
intends to become a stock exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Harold S. Bradley, a senior vice president at American Century
Investments, has had it with the status quo. He took some time last
week to speak his mind and to say why investors should care about
the exchanges' future. Here are excerpts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. This whole push for change at the stock exchanges seems to
have come suddenly. But you don't agree with that, do you? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, we started using Instinet, the first ECN, for our
customers in 1989. And in 1992, the Securities and Exchange
Commission put out its Market 2000 report, which contained a
section on changing technology and its impact on markets.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Congress was worried that ECNs like Instinet might
fragment, balkanize and segment the markets and asked for comment.
</P>
<P>
   We filed a 24- to 25-page response relating to our needs and
those of our investors. But we were one of only four investment
firms that responded to that report.
</P>
<P>
   So this has not happened overnight. The New York Stock Exchange
has been so immune to technology that people were saying they
didn't need to change. But the partners in Archipelago, and we are
one of them, are saying there is a need for new mechanisms. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why should John Q. Investor give a hoot? Why change? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. John Q. Investor should care because if he wants to save and
get good returns on his investments, he wants to get maximum return
on his invested dollar and not pay anyone any more than he has to.
Currently, intermediaries take an awful lot of money away from
those maximum returns.
</P>
<P>
   If someone is adding value to generate returns, I am happy to
pay them for it. But let me pay 2 people instead of 10. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Could you amplify on that? What kind of manpower is involved
in a Big Board trade? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. If you want to buy a stock, you call a broker, and you do
that on your own or through a mutual fund.
</P>
<P>
   My trading desk then calls a sales trader, who calls the
position trader who calls the floor broker, and then the floor
broker goes to the specialist.
</P>
<P>
   That is 6 people, which means 11 folks are involved once all is
said and done. I find that completely absurd in today's world, and
I have to pay each one of those people in that chain. A computer
chip can get me on the floor in a nanosecond.
</P>
<P>
   The New York exchange has spent a lot of money on technology,
and they can process trades extremely efficiently. But the way
stocks trade is still the same. They need to spend a lot on
point-of-sale technology. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you think the New York and NASDAQ markets would function
better as for-profit organizations? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I think they would become more efficient if they went public.
The only way to be successful in a public company is to align the
interests of your customers with your business model. NASDAQ and
the New York have some of the smartest people in the business. As I
said before, these problems are not new and not unstudied.
</P>
<P>
   But the staff at both is completely bridled and throttled by
their own members, who hamstring any innovation that might impede
their own economic self-interest. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Some have raised concerns about conflicts of interest if the
exchanges were for-profit entities. Do you share those worries? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I see far fewer conflicts of interest in a for-profit
exchange than under the current system. You would have public
owners and accountability. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. A month or so ago, Merrill Lynch upset its brokers when it
decided to offer its clients access to low-cost online trading.
Isn't this the other side of the same coin? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The Internet disintermediates. It takes out the middlemen who
are not creating value. Now, there is a lot of value added in the
process. But right now it is hard to figure out just what it costs
and where it resides.
</P>
<P>
   When you take intermediation out, it will wipe out those who are
adding marginal or no value. Archipelago is the functional
equivalent of Amazon.com for selling stocks. The New York Stock
Exchange has to figure out a way to be Barnes &AMP; Noble.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
