<HEADLINE>
TRIPP INDICTED FOR RECORDING LEWINSKY CALLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Maryland grand jury indicted Linda Tripp Friday
for secretly tape recording her conversations with Monica Lewinsky,
a step which could once more put a public spotlight on President
Clinton's relationship with the former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   The Maryland charges could be complicated by Tripp's immunity
deal with the federal office of independent counsel Kenneth Starr.
Tripp provided the tapes to Starr, who then investigated whether
Lewinsky had conspired with Clinton to cover-up their sexual
relationship. Tripp was given immunity by Starr in exchange for her
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   But Maryland prosecutors, after announcing the indictment of
Tripp, said that Tripp's immunity deal did not extend to a
violation of state law. It is illegal for a Maryland resident to
tape a telephone conversation without the consent of both parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always believed and still believe this is a
politically motivated prosecution,'' said Tripp's attorney, Joseph
Murtha.
</P>
<P>
   But Maryland prosecutor Stephen Montanarelli, a Democrat, denied
that there was any political motivation behind the case. ``I can't
help how it will be seen,'' he said. ``We've done our duty.''
</P>
<P>
   Tripp could invoke a ``whistle-blower defense,'' referring to
laws that encourage federal employees to expose federal misconduct.
Without Tripp's tape and her cooperation, it is possible that the
president's affair with Lewinsky _ and the alleged cover-up attempt
_ would never have become public. Now, it is possible that she will
be the only person in the matter to face jail time.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment against Tripp alleges that she taped a
conversation with Lewinsky on Dec. 22, 1997, after being informed
by her lawyer that it was illegal. The indictment also accuses her
illegally disclosing the conversation to Newsweek magazine. Tripp
faces a maximum of five years in prison and a $10,000 fine for each
offense.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky was questioned during the investigation and could be
called to testify if the case goes to trial, but it is unclear
whether Clinton would be called as a witness.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph diGenova, a Republican and former federal prosecutor,
expressed outrage at Friday's indictment, calling it ``legally
invalid.'' DiGenova, a frequent critic of Clinton, said that Tripp
made the tape recordings to protect herself against being drawn
into a conspiracy to obstruct justice.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp has said she made the recordings because she feared
Lewinsky and Clinton wanted her to lie about the president's
relationship with former White House volunteer Kathleen Willey.
Willey has alleged that Clinton made a sexual advance toward her at
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an outrageous abuse of prosecutorial discretion,''
diGenova said, predicting the case would be thrown out of court. He
said that even if it was illegal for Tripp to tape record the
conversations with Lewinsky, prosecutors often do not pursue
charges against an individual who has ``served a greater good. It
happens every day in prosecutors' offices. It is called
cooperation.''
</P>
<P>
   But another former federal prosecutor, Bruce Yannett, noted that
federal immunity does not affect state laws and he said that
``given the blatant nature of the taping, a prosecution would
appear reasonable under those circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Gillers, professor of legal ethics at New York
University, said that while Tripp might have broken the law, it
doesn't make sense to try to send her to prison. ``She already is
in her own little prison,'' he said. ``She is the friend who
betrayed her younger friend, and that is how people will remember
her. If you add up the winners and losers, she comes out in the
bottom of the loser category.''
</P>
<P>
   The laws on tape-recording telephone conversations vary from
state to state. For example, if Tripp had made the recording in
Washington, D.C.,which requires only the consent of one party, it
would have been legal, diGenova said.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment follows by one day a ruling by US District Judge
Susan Webber Wright that Clinton must pay a $90,686 penalty for
lying in a civil suit about his sexual relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   That suit was brought was by Paula Corbin Jones, who alleged
that Clinton had sexually harassed her when he was governor of
Arkansas. Jones's lawyers, seeking to establish Clinton's pattern
of conduct, asked the president whether he had a sexual
relationship with Lewinsky. The president denied having sex with
Lewinsky and indicated that he barely knew her. Later, the
president aide's said that Clinton did not believe that oral sex
fit under the judge's definition of a sexual relationship.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
