<SLUG> BC-PBS-LISTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLIC BROADCASTING AGENCY ACTS TO LIMIT LIST SHARING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   US public broadcasting officials moved Friday to end a national
controversy over stations sharing membership lists with political
fundraisers, announcing that stations must ban the practice if they
want to get any federal grants.
</P>
<P>
   The Corporation for Public Broadcasting's move came after weeks
of controversy about list sharing with both parties. It began with
disclosures in The Boston Globe earlier this month that a list of
some 200,000 members had been made available to Democratic National
Committee fundraisers in 1994 and 1996 by WGBH in Boston, despite a
station policy banning the practice.
</P>
<P>
   While some Capitol Hill Republicans seized on the first
disclosures as proof of a long-alleged left-wing tilt in public
broadcasting, it soon emerged that several public stations had
traded lists with both parties as well as Republican Bob Dole's
1996 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Corporation president Robert T. Coonrod said the group was
taking the ``unprecedented step'' of dictating policy to local
stations because ``our goal is to restore the public's trust in the
work public broadcasting does every day.''
</P>
<P>
   In the fiscal year that begins Oct. 1, the corporation plans to
distribute just under $200 million in grants from the federal
budget to the 1,000 US public radio and television stations,
including $150 million for television and $46.7 million for radio.
</P>
<P>
   The corporation acts as an umbrella group for local PBS
stations, coordinating federal grants to them.
</P>
<P>
   WGBH usually receives about $6 million in federal aid each year
through the corporation, including funds for its FM radio station,
Channel 2 and Channel 44, although the figure fluctuates.
</P>
<P>
   To qualify for grants, under the policy announced Friday,
stations must guarantee they will not ``sell, rent, lease, loan,
trade, give, donate, transfer or exchange membership or donor names
to, with, or from any candidate for public office, committees or
organizations supporting a candidate, political parties, or
organizations that solicit funds for use in political campaigns for
any purpose whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   The policy also requires that stations who do exchange or rent
lists to other non-profit groups ensure that members who do not
want their names shared have their wishes honored.
</P>
<P>
   WGBH's vice president for communications, Jeanne Hopkins, said:
</P>
<P>
   ``We welcome and endorse the CPB's policy and hope that it
offers reassurance for viewers and listeners that public
broadcasting really is committed to operating in a way that earns
their trust. We also hope it brings this issue to closure.''
</P>
<P>
   WGBH officials have blamed the 1994 and 1996 list swapping on
low-level development officials who, they said, did not know about
a station policy banning what list swaps with political parties.
The station also fired the outside list broker, whom it has refused
to identify, who assisted in making those names available to the
DNC.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins said the corporation's announcement is ``consistent''
with steps WGBH has already taken or plans to take to ensure no
repeat of the Democratic list-swapping flap.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, in a letter to station managers made
available Friday, Coonrod said that ``all of public broadcasting is
bein discredited'' by revelations at least two dozen stations
traded names with political fundraisers.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, a spokesman for Louisiana Republican Rep. Billy
Tauzin, chair of the House Commerce Subcommittee on
Telecommunications, said Tauzin welcomed public broadcasting's
steps but still favored a law expressly prohibiting list swaps,
either directly or through third-party broker businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a step in the right direction toward ending a very
unseemly and self-destructive practice,'' said spokesman Ken
Johnson. He said the PBS stations had ``undermined the integrity of
public broadcasting and the integrity of the American political
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the GOP gained control of Congress in 1994, some have
pushed to slash funding for PBS or privatize it. PBS has largely
escaped the budget ax since then, but faces a need for millions of
additional dollars to roll out high-definition television in coming
years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
