</P>
<P>
   SENATE-TAX-CUTS (Washington) _ The Senate approves its version
of a plan to cut taxes by $792 billion over 10 years, and the
leaders of the House and Senate now plan to negotiate a compromise
measure before the end of next week. The Senate proposal would,
among other things, eliminate the ``marriage penalty'' and reduce
the burden on people in the lowest tax bracket. By DAVID IVANOVICH.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-VIEQUES (Washington) _ A federal cancer-monitoring
agency has opened an investigation allegations by Puerto Ricans
that U.S. bombing exercises have caused high levels of cancer on
the island of Vieques. The action could delay a White House
decision on the fate of a bombing range that the Navy and Marine
Corps have used for 58 years. By STEWART M. POWELL. (Also filed in
the ``p'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-PRESCRIPTIONS (Washington) _ Food and Drug
Administration officials tell Congress they are starting to crack
down on Internet sites that sell prescription drugs illegally. By
JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN. (Also filed in the ``f'' category).
</P>
<P>
   SAFE-SEX (Washington) _ Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla., a physician,
lectures some 300 congressional interns. His message: If you want
to avoid painful sexually transmitted diseases, abstain from sex.
By ERIC ROSENBERG. (Also filed in the ``l'' category.)
</P>
