<HEADER>
A0407 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-MEDIA-COMPANIE     07-30 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-MEDIA-COMPANIES-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWERHOUSES HOLD SOME NEW CARDS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 1) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., N.Y.)   (af)  
 By ERIC QUINONES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Investors in search of long-term growth in Internet companies
may want to heed this adage: Brands rule.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, that may seem a subversive notion these days.
After all, scores of freshly minted dot-com stocks have climbed to
dizzying valuations, and many Web-focused investors have bypassed
the old-line media companies that control brand-name magazines,
music, movies and other so-called content with Internet potential.
</P>
<P>
   But Wall Street is betting that the situation is about to
change, as traditional media companies accelerate their efforts to
gain online advertisers and audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Three companies leading the charge are Time Warner, Walt Disney
and CBS. ``We know the products that they offer, and we've come to
expect a certain level of quality from them versus some newbie who
comes out of nowhere and claims that on the Web they're the hottest
thing,'' said Mark Hardie, a senior analyst with Forrester Research
in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   And these companies can cross-promote their efforts, giving them
a leg up on independent content providers.
</P>
<P>
   All three companies have announced deals in recent weeks that
add to their Internet assets, but the moves have caused little stir
in their stock prices. ``I'd say that value is not being recognized
in the marketplace right now.'' said Tom Barrett, an analyst with
MFS Investment Management, a money manager in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   So investors who hope to gain from such stocks may have to think
long-term. Tom Wolzein, an analyst at Sanford C. Bernstein in New
York, expects the percentage of cash flow that these companies
derive from the Web, an amount now negligible, to climb into the
double digits over the next four to five years as they expand their
online businesses. Cash flow is a good benchmark for media company
profitability.
</P>
<P>
   The online build-up is under way. Time Warner, for example, said
on July 13 that it would merge Columbia House, the record club it
owns with Sony, with the online music store CDnow. Time Warner will
own 37 percent of the new company, which by the end of the year
will offer music that can be downloaded directly from the Internet
_ the hot new market for music.
</P>
<P>
   After the CDnow deal was announced, Wolzein raised his 12-month
price target for Time Warner stock by 28 percent, to nearly $91 a
share, citing the company's overall Internet profit potential. The
shares closed Friday at $72.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming that the overall online advertising market continues to
flourish, Wolzien projected that in 2001, Time Warner would have
cash flow of $8.7 billion, of which 3 percent would be from
Internet businesses. By 2004, he said, cash flow would reach $12
billion, with the Internet portion climbing to 11 percent of the
total.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner has also moved to correct one misstep. It is phasing
out its Pathfinder site _ a platform for magazines including Time
and Money. Users tended to skip its home page and go directly to
the magazine Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the company will focus on hub sites for target
audiences, combining related magazines with links to the Web sites
of other Time Warner properties, including WarnerBros.com and
CNN.com.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's Internet business took a big leap last year, when the
company bought about 42 percent of Infoseek, an online search
service, and then created its own portal, the Go Network. Together,
the destinations are the fifth-most-popular Web property, according
to Media Metrix, an Internet research company in New York.
</P>
<P>
   On July 12, the company announced plans to buy the rest of
Infoseek and merge all of Disney's Internet holdings into a new
company that it will control, Go.com. Shares in the new company
will be offered publicly through a tracking stock _ meaning that
the assets continue to be owned by Disney but that the share price
effectively tracks the performance of those assets. Disney can use
the tracking stock for acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's stock has been struggling this year, in part because of
falling merchandise sales. But Jill S. Krutick, an analyst at
Salomon Smith Barney, expects the shares to rise from their current
$27.4375 to the mid-$30s in the next year, partly because of
Disney's Internet investments.
</P>
<P>
   Wolzien expects Disney's online business to account for 4
percent of $5.8 billion in cash flow in 2001, rising to 14 percent
of $8.6 billion in cash flow in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   At CBS, the strategy has been to tap into existing Web-based
businesses. The company bought positions in several specialized
Internet companies _ including Marketwatch.com, Sportsline USA,
Medscape and Rx.com _ in exchange for millions of dollars' worth of
promotion across its TV and radio properties. CBS is also
reportedly developing a portal similar to the Go Network.
</P>
<P>
   Wolzien projected that CBS would report cash flow of $2.5
billion in 2001, 5 percent of which would be from online holdings,
with cash flow rising to $4.1 billion in 2004, 10 percent of it
from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   James Marsh, an analyst at Prudential Securities, expects CBS
shares to hit $51 in 12 months, up from $43.9375 on Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
