</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-KOSOVO-BUILD-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. COMPANIES ARE WARY OF CONTRACTS IN THE BALKANS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 1) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (Eds: This is an added story)  
(af) 
 By VIVIENNE WALT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As government officials gathered in Washington and Brussels last
week to pledge billions of dollars in aid to reconstruct the
Balkans, American companies said the political deck appeared to be
stacked against their winning many lucrative rebuilding contracts,
and wondered whether some are even worth pursuing.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these projects are sinkholes,'' said Skip Richardson,
global vice president for acquisitions at Brown &AMP; Root Services, a
division of Halliburton. The company has a logistics contract with
the United States military in the Balkans worth $180 million a
year, but it has not decided whether to seek reconstruction
contracts in the war-torn region.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to determine whether these projects are
meaningful business opportunities,'' he said. ``If the money isn't
spent properly, you'll be doing the same things over again a year
later.''
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of some 60 countries as well as regional
organizations and aid agencies met in Brussels Wednesday and
pledged more than $2 billion to Kosovo, where fighting and ethnic
cleansing destroyed many thousands of houses and disabled
electricity and water systems. The funds are to be used for
land-mine clearance, water purification, home repairs and food aid.
</P>
<P>
   After the conference, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
visited Kosovo to view the damage first hand; though the bulk of
the $2 billion will come from European nations, the United States
will contribute $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the longer-term cost of rebuilding the province's
infrastructure of highways, railways, power grids, communications
networks and water supplies is likely to be far higher than those
numbers. The rebuilding figure, to be assessed in October at
another meeting of donors in Brussels, will yield much bigger
contracts for construction and engineering companies.
</P>
<P>
   But based on their experiences with other large-scale rebuilding
efforts in recent years, including the aftermaths of civil war in
Bosnia and Hurricane Mitch in Central America, American executives
say they have learned some hard lessons about labyrinthine
bureaucracies and political favoritism. This time around, they say,
they know better than to count on much cheer from the flood of
money.
</P>
<P>
   Like other engineering firms, Brown &AMP; Root rushed into Central
America last fall as $9 billion in aid was pledged in the aftermath
of Hurricane Mitch. The company opened an office in Tegucigalpa,
Honduras, and won several reconstruction contracts.
</P>
<P>
   But local political infighting has stalled nearly all major
rebuilding work in the country, Richardson said. ``We sent waves
and waves of teams down there,'' he said. ``We've spent hundreds of
thousands of dollars, and we don't have one revenue dollar to show
for it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Balkans, another kind of political threat looms, making
American companies fear that they will be shut out of Europe's
biggest rebuilding effort since the Marshall Plan after World War
II. The problem is an international hot potato called ``tied aid''
_ the practice of pledging aid on the condition that contracts be
awarded to companies from the donor country _ which is common in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   With bidding on actual contracts still months away, American
officials have already begun to rail against the convention,
arguing that while Europe should shoulder the majority of the cost
of rebuilding the Balkans, Americans paid much of the cost of
fighting the war itself, so American businesses are entitled to an
equal opportunity to profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be pressing hard for untied aid,'' said David Aaron,
under secretary of Commerce for international trade. ``We want
three principles: transparency, freedom from corruption and open
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   After the war in Bosnia, the World Bank raised more than $2
billion to rebuild the country, of which Washington has contributed
about $590 million. Yet American companies have won very little
work there, partly because neither American political officials nor
business executives arrived on the scene ``until it was too late,''
Aaron said. ``They lost out there.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, the Commerce Department plans to post an official in
Thessaloniki, Greece, in the fall to coordinate timely American
bids for Balkan contracts. ``I think it's important to learn from
mistakes,'' Aaron added.
</P>
<P>
   But that will not resolve all the political problems. Sanctions
against Yugoslavia block companies from the United States and other
countries from rebuilding in Serbia itself so long as Slobodan
Milosevic remains in power, cutting them off from some of the most
attractive potential contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Fluor Corp., the giant construction company, sees potentially
huge jobs in Serbia _ where NATO bombs shattered oil refineries,
power plants and chemical processing factories _ that would play to
the company's strengths.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the political questions will have to be worked through
before we would be interested in participating,'' said George
Palmer, Fluor's spokesman in Alisa Viejo, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   If reconstruction proceeds while Milosevic _ and the sanctions _
remain in place, ``the bulk of it will go to European companies,''
said Wayne Weiss, senior vice president for governmental affairs
for Black &AMP; Veatch, an engineering firm that operates in 90
countries. But there may still be time for political changes in
Belgrade to open the Serbian playing field to Americans, he said,
adding, ``Right now, there's a lot more hype than effort.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
