<HEADER>
A0410 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-CANADA-ART-2TA     07-30 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-CANADA-ART-2TAKES-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLLAR MAKES CANADA A LAND OF THE SPREE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 1) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., N.Y., Mont., Calif.)  (ART ADV: Graphic of Canadian dollar vs. dollar and examples of
price differences is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NIAGARA FALLS, Ontario _ Love brought them here, but the cheap
Canadian dollar kept them from leaving.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Carte and Annette Lovejoy drove for two days from their
home in Cottageville, W.Va., to Niagara Falls, N.Y., to get
married, but the prices they found on a brief tour on the Canadian
side of the Niagara River persuaded them to tie the knot here.
</P>
<P>
   The clincher was the exchange rate they received for their
American dollars at a local bank. ``We gave them $300,'' the new
bride exulted, ``and they gave us $432 back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian dollar, nicknamed the loonie (for the bird on the
back of the dollar coin), has been on a two-year descent that some
people say is a little bit crazy. Although it perked up a bit in
the first half of this year, gaining more than 3 American cents, to
68.9 cents on May 4, it has since turned down again, closing on
Friday at 66.4 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The longer-term decline, which economists attribute to the
continuing fallout from the 1997 world financial crisis, has
prompted a bargain-hunting boom by Americans. They are saving money
by boarding flights to the Caribbean from Canada, placing mail
orders in Canada, buying vacation homes in Canada and even sending
their children to college in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Homeless Americans, too, are discovering the Canadian advantage.
Sheridan Lee Taylor, 25, headed for Vancouver nine months ago from
Utah with $600 in his pocket and never looked back. ``It lasted me
quite some time,'' he said. ``Six hundred dollars American turned
into $1,000 here, easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not all things Canadian are bargains. Certain
products _ notably gasoline and alcohol _ remain far cheaper in the
United States because of higher Canadian taxes. And other goods are
routinely priced to reflect currency values; a book, for example,
might be stamped ``US $27.50/$45.00 CAN.''
</P>
<P>
   But whenever a currency is strong, there are good prices to be
had in markets away from home, and the United States dollar is king
around the world these days. Despite a recent surge, the euro has
fallen 8.2 percent against the greenback in 7 months, and countries
from Columbia to Thailand have found their currencies losing value
against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   The hegemony is making it cheaper for Americans to honeymoon in
Paris or to vacation in Brazil. But Canada is closer to home, so it
gets more than its share of American visitors out to get the
biggest bang for their bucks.
</P>
<P>
   Americans made a record 43.9 million visits to Canada last year,
up 8.4 percent from the previous record of 40.5 million in 1997,
when the Canadian dollar began its dive, according to the Canadian
government.
</P>
<P>
   The American visitors threw their money around, too, spending a
record $8.6 billion in 1998, up 24 percent from $6.9 billion in
1997, in United States dollars. And travel industry executives say
the numbers have almost certainly risen this year.
</P>
<P>
   American companies are also getting in on the action, spending
$12.7 billion (United States) on acquisitions in Canada last year,
up 70 percent from $7.5 billion in 1997 and nearly three times the
$4.4 billion in 1994, according to KPMG Corporate Finance of
Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, we're kind of another Mexico,'' said Ross H. Chafe,
the president of Flags Unlimited in Barrie, Ontario. Last year,
Aberdeen Fabrics of Aberdeen, N.C., bought a controlling stake in
the company, which makes a half-million Canadian flags a year. ``It
was relatively cheap for them to invest in Canada,'' Chafe said,
``and the dollar allows us to compete very well in the American
market.''
</P>
<P>
   But this is also a game for weekend warriors, not just big
players. Last year, about 20,000 Americans who live near the
Canadian border drove to Canadian airports to fly to places like
Jamaica, Cancun and Las Vegas on package tours sold by Signature
Vacations of Toronto, according to Chris C. Robinson, the company's
national marketing director. That's twice as many as in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're seeing is a very significant increase over the last
two years,'' Robinson said. He has been advertising in Rochester
and Buffalo newspapers to draw attention to the bargains. ``We've
really stepped that up over the last couple of years to ride the
wave,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Americans don't even have to leave home to take advantage of the
favorable exchange rate. Motorcycle riders, for example, can log
onto the Internet to order oil filters, luggage and other
accessories sent by mail from Wolf BMW in Alisa Craig, Ontario,
halfway between Detroit and Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mail-order business is something we got going about a year
and a half ago in response to the Canadian dollar being so weak,''
said Christine C. McQueen, a co-owner of Wolf BMW. ``We sell quite
a bit of stuff across the border.''
</P>
<P>
   American students are flocking to college in Canada, also
because the price is right. There were 2,917 Americans studying in
Canada during the 1997-98 academic year, according to the latest
available figures from the Association of Universities and Colleges
of Canada. That is up from about 2,400 a year in the early to
mid-'90s.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Reed, 18, of New Haven, N.Y., plans to attend the
University of Toronto, a prestigious Canadian school where a
partial scholarship will winnow down the costs to $8,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd been to Toronto and seen the school, but it wasn't really
playing into his thoughts much _ or ours,'' said his father,
William J. Reed. ``But in looking at the money and how far our
dollars would go, it made tremendous sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans are also buying vacation retreats in Canada. Keith D.
Hodson of Stevensville, Mont., a manager for Para-Chem, an
adhesives maker, just bought a third home, a two-bedroom
condominium 16 floors above downtown Vancouver in a building called
the Venice. The price was 280,000 loonies _ only $188,000 in
American money. The exchange rate ``just makes it a much better
buy,'' Hodson said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Brubeck, 38, of Berkeley, Calif., said he and his wife
were also considering buying a place in Canada. A cellist in the
band of the rock singer Sheryl Crow, Brubeck recently visited
Vancouver on the Lilith Fair concert tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we came up to Vancouver and bought property, we could get
an apartment in the city and a ranch 30 miles outside of the
city,'' Brubeck said. ``The American dollar being so strong would
definitely affect a decision to buy property in Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   As American tourists throw money around across the border, the
ever-polite Canadians are holding their noses as they pocket the
cash.
</P>
<P>
   Robin N. Rootes, 23, a waitress in Vancouver, says the big tips
she receives from American customers more than make up for their
sometimes arrogant attitudes. ``They come over and spend and say
they can spend as much as they want,'' Ms. Rootes said. ``Yes, they
are demanding, and yes, they are high-maintenance.'' But, compared
with the natives, they tend to leave more loonies and toonies (the
nickname for Canada's $2 coins) on the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite honestly, we're going to make money off of them,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ben C. Giles, 18, a recent high school graduate, is making his
money by handing out coupons for Circus World, a shop on the
tourist drag here on the Canadian side of the falls, working from a
post between the roaring water and an oversized Frankenstein
holding a hamburger.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many people are coming over, so a lot of the students get
jobs,'' said Giles, resplendent in white makeup, a clown suit and a
fuzzy wig with red, yellow, green, blue and purple stripes. Still,
he shakes his head in annoyance at the Americans who ask him what
time Niagara Falls is turned off.
</P>
<P>
   The weak dollar is good news for Canadian exporters, too,
because their goods cost less in American dollars. As a result,
Canada's trade surplus with the United States widened by 7.7
percent last year, to $16.65 billion. By the end of May this year _
the most recent figures available _ it had more than doubled, to
$11.2 billion from $5.3 billion in the comparable period last year.
</P>
<P>
   The losers, of course, are Canadian consumers, who have to pay
more for American imports and can only dream about the
bargain-hunting trips they once made south of the border. Maxinne
Cheng, who manages a store in Vancouver's tourist district, said
she missed her trips to Seattle, three hours away by car, where she
used to shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been an exact switch,'' Ms. Cheng said. ``Five years
ago, we would go down to Seattle to get good deals. Now the
Americans come here for shopping.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest figures from the Canadian government show that day
trips by Canadians to the United States dropped 11 percent last
year, to 31.9 million, the lowest level in more than a decade and
about half the 60 million in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   As the effects of the powerful American dollar reverberate
across Canada, Canadian nationalists are fuming about economic
imperialism. ``There has been a fire sale of Canadian assets and an
influx of foreign capital,'' said Peter S. Bleyer, executive
director of the Council of Canadians, a nonprofit advocacy group in
Ottawa. ``It is about taking existing economic assets out of the
hands of Canadians.''
</P>
<P>
   He fears that in times of trouble, American companies will let
their hearts overrule their wallets and close factories in Canada
before laying off employees at home.
</P>
<P>
   But these are good times for Americans, and for now, many of
them are gambling on the cheap Canadian dollar _ sometimes
literally, in the casinos in several high-traffic spots along the
border. Even those who win, though, may wonder if their returns are
all that great.
</P>
<P>
   Ike Baker, 56, recently made the one-hour drive from his home in
Depew, N.Y., to show Niagara Falls to visiting relatives, and he
tried his luck at craps at a casino here. ``I started with 40
Canadian dollars,'' Baker said. ``I won $150; I lost $50 back.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he cashed in his $100 winnings, received just $60 in
American currency, and asked himself this: ``Where's all the
money?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
