<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0416 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAX-CUT-$ADV01-HNS &LR;      07-30 1483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-CUT-$ADV01-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAGE SET FOR PARTISAN SHOWDOWN OVER BUDGET SURPLUS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, Aug. 1) 
 
By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Faced with the golden opportunity of deciding what
to do with a projected $3 trillion budget surplus over the next 10
years, Congress and the White House are engaged in a classic
struggle over tax and spend policies that appears headed for
high-stakes negotiations this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome, a final agreement on how to use the
estimated $1 trillion in non-Social Security surplus funds won't be
easy because of divisions among Republicans and Democrats over what
should be done with it.
</P>
<P>
   The pressures of the upcoming election year will also play a
role in the deal-making, as all the participants involved in the
talks try to reap the most political benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Republicans are hoping their plan to return $792
billion to taxpayers will eventually gain support from the American
people, a majority of whom are saying in public opinion polls that
they would prefer the surplus be used for debt reduction and
preserving Social Security and Medicare rather than tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Liberal Democrats and the Clinton administration, meanwhile, are
hoping that public opinion stays right where it is as they push
their own more modest $300 billion tax cut proposal that would also
reserve nearly $600 billion to be used for debt reduction,
increased education spending and $50 billion in new Medicare
benefits, including a prescription drug program.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a third group, calling itself ``the centrist coalition,'' is
floating a moderate bipartisan plan offering $500 billion in tax
cuts as a compromise aimed at avoiding what chief sponsor Sen. John
Breaux, D-La., says will be a certain ``train wreck'' with the
White House this fall if Congress fails to produce ``a sensible''
bill the president can sign.
</P>
<P>
   And a fourth, smaller group, made up primarily of Democrats, is
siding with Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan in cautioning
against major tax cuts or spending programs so that surplus funds
can be used to pay down the nation's $5.5 trillion debt, an action
that Greenspan says will help more than anything else to keep the
economic boom going.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time (since World War II), it appears that the
federal budget may actually go into a surplus _ if we let it. ...
So I ask, why not stay the course?'' said Sen. Joe Lieberman,
D-Conn., a leading proponent of the view that the best policy is to
do nothing and simply allow the surplus to go toward reducing the
government debt.
</P>
<P>
   But doing nothing doesn't appear to be an option as the 2000
election year approaches and Republicans and Democrats try to turn
the surplus projections, no matter how uncertain they may be, to
their best political advantage.
</P>
<P>
   House and Senate Republicans succeeded last week in passing
their own differing versions of tax relief, totaling $792 billion.
A final bill will be worked out in conference between the two
chambers in the coming weeks and sent on to President Clinton, who
has vowed to veto it.
</P>
<P>
   His certain veto means that Republicans and Democrats will spend
this fall fighting over tax and spend policy on the eve of an
election year, with each side hoping to win public support for
their positions.
</P>
<P>
   The political rhetoric and outright demagoguery is already
evident.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans charge that Clinton would simply spend the country
deeper into debt and plunder Social Security funds as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to cut taxes and the president wants to spend it.
That's what the fighting is all about,'' Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott, R-Miss., told reporters after the Senate approved the
GOP bill Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, meanwhile, is denouncing the Republican tax cut plans
as folly, saying they would not only jeopardize needed Medicare
spending for prescription drugs but would also put an end to some
school reading programs.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton charge enraged Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., who
called Clinton's comments a ``disgraceful'' display of ``shameless
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Domenici said the remarks proved that the Democrats are more
interested in having a political issue to use against Republicans
than supporting a significant tax cut for Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, who is hoping to capture his party's
presidential nomination, is also trashing the Republican bills in
an effort to win support for the administration plan that provides
$300 billion in tax relief, boosts Medicare spending and puts more
money into education and other programs.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is hoping to connect with aging baby boomers and the
elderly who were being told last fall that a reduction in Social
Security, Medicare and other benefits was inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the budget windfall projections of $1.9 trillion from
Social Security taxes and nearly $1 trillion more in discretionary
funds, Gore and Clinton contend that spending on Medicare and some
other programs can actually be increased beyond what would normally
be required to keep up with inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The surplus projections are forcing Republicans to rethink their
own fiscal policy positions as well, beginning with the question of
just how big government should be. Like the Democrats, they're
looking for a way to use tax cuts and moderate spending proposals,
which would be paid for out of the estimated non-Social Security
surplus of $1 trillion, to their advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP mantra for years has been ``less government spending''
and more tax cuts. But in the interest of protecting their majority
hold on Congress, moderate Republicans are pushing new spending
proposals this year that could end up breaking the budget caps
agreed to by Congress and Clinton in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In order to please some elements of their constituency, GOP
lawmakers are using accounting gimmicks and emergency declarations
to raise spending on defense and other areas. Even Senate Budget
Committee Chairman Phil Gramm, R-Texas, acknowledged last week that
both the House and Senate budget proposals this year will surpass
the spending limit caps by about $21 billion to $30 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Republican tax cut plans assume that Congress will
live within the 1997 spending agreement, the question arises: Why
offer a tax cut at all if the future, despite projections, is so
uncertain?
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan made that point in testimony before Congress a few
days ago in which he cautioned against new tax cuts and spending
until economic projections for the next 10 years are a little more
stable.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans mostly ignored the federal reserve chairman's
advice, or sought to spin his comments about tax cuts being his
``second choice'' for what to do with the surplus as an endorsement
for a big tax reduction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans believe it's a matter of principle to return
excess tax money ... to families and workers who sent it here,''
House Ways and Means Committee Chairman Bill Archer, R-Texas, said
in summing up the GOP's general position on how to handle the
surplus.
</P>
<P>
   But where Republicans see an overtaxed public that sometimes
grumbles about excessive government programs, many Democrats see a
public that seems satisfied for now with the nation's state of
affairs and favors using the surplus to increase spending on
education, defense and health care rather than tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand this bidding war on tax cuts,'' Sen. Paul
Wellstone, D-Minn., said before the Senate passed by a narrow
margin its own $790 billion tax cut measure. ``I really think the
vast majority of the American people are saying ... this belongs
not to us but to our children and grandchildren.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about investing for their children's future,'' he
said, ``not about getting back some small tax cut that's not going
to help them much while the economy is doing well.''
</P>
<P>
   With a showdown over what to do with the surplus all but
certain, a handful of Republicans and Democrats led by Breaux are
trying to convince their colleagues to compromise with the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is time for a reality check about where we are and what we
need to do,'' Breaux told the Senate last week during debate on the
GOP bill.
</P>
<P>
   Without a compromise tax cut package, he said, ``We will end up
with nothing more than a political argument that we'll use against
each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Using the 2000 election to have that argument is just fine with
some Republicans. Gramm, for instance, said in a television
interview last week that he would prefer to gamble on Texas Gov.
George W. Bush, the leading contender for the Republican
nomination, being elected president next year rather than negotiate
this fall with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would simply wait, have a presidential election and then
have a tax cut, if people voted for one,'' Gramm said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
