<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0418 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPEND-CONGRESS-NYT &LR;      07-30 1199
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEND-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEFORE IT MATERIALIZES, CONGRESS ALREADY HAS PLANS TO SPEND THE
SURPLUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With TAX-CONGRESS.) 
(th) 
 By TIM WEINER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress is primed to break its own rules and spend
the $14 billion budget surplus promised for next year, according to
senior members of the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Determined to spend billions more on the military, dubious of
cutting domestic programs any deeper and driven to finance members'
favorite projects in all 50 states, Congress already has proved
itself unable to live within the strict budget limits it imposed in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Those spending caps helped balance the budget, but they are now
squeezing too tight, members say. Congress broke the caps in a
last-minute $21 billion spending spree last year, declaring the
money ``emergency'' spending.
</P>
<P>
   Congress seems so likely to exceed the caps again this year that
Republicans and Democrats are now saying that they must rewrite the
law and lift the caps in order pass the spending bills required to
run the government. If the bills do not pass by Sept. 30, a
government shutdown looms.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to change the law'' that set the caps, said Rep. John
E. Porter, R-Ill., a senior member of the House Appropriations
Committee. Many Republicans and Democrats in both houses of
Congress agree.
</P>
<P>
   But if the caps are lifted, members are ready with more than $20
billion in new spending programs. That would create a budget
deficit next year _ and that, in turn, could call into question
Republican plans for a tax cut in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the caps still make sense, Rep. Bill Young, R-Fla., the
chairman of the House Appropriations Committee, took a long pause
and let out a deep sigh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good question,'' he said, and changed the subject.
</P>
<P>
   If the limits remain, Congress will have to cut billions of
dollars deeper into domestic programs next year and the year after
that. Under the caps, it slashed nondefense spending by 11 percent,
or about $26 billion, this year.
</P>
<P>
   The caps brought federal spending on government agencies down to
$538 billion for the coming fiscal year. Congress will give half to
the Pentagon and divide the rest among every other federal agency.
</P>
<P>
   The strict spending limits, the Republicans say, will put the
federal budget about $14.5 billion in the black next year, not
counting Social Security surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   But the Republican tax cut plan would take $4.5 billion out of
next year's anticipated surplus. That would bring it down to about
$10 billion. And members are already poised to spend that money,
and more.
</P>
<P>
   House Republican leaders are scouring the entire federal budget,
seeking unspent billions from mandatory programs like Medicaid,
welfare benefits and interstate highway funds to try to find more
money that could legally evade the limits on domestic spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``A million here, a million there, maybe it'll add up and nobody
will notice,'' said John Feehrey, spokesman for Speaker Dennis
Hastert, who along with the majority whip, Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas,
is dictating many of the creative budgetary and spending strategies
being used this year.
</P>
<P>
   They are increasingly resorting to accounting tricks and fiscal
gimmicks to preserve the appearance that both the anticipated
surplus and the strict spending limits will remain intact. Rep.
David Obey of Wisconsin, the House Appropriations Committee's
ranking Democrat, calls that appearance ``a public lie''
promulgated by Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are absolutely no rules that govern the budget
process,'' Obey said Friday at an appropriations subcommittee
meeting. ``The rules are whatever the majority leadership says they
are at any given nanosecond.''
</P>
<P>
   At that meeting, House Republicans ruled, fought and won in two
procedural battles to declare the $4.5 billion cost of the year
2000 census an emergency, erasing it from the budget's bottom line.
The law says emergency spending must be for ``unforeseen,
unpredictable and unanticipated'' needs; the Constitution says the
census must be taken every 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The House Republicans are also considering delaying billions of
dollars of Medicaid payments to the states due in September 2000.
The fiscal year ends on Sept. 30, so if the payments are delayed,
the Republicans figure they can spend the money in the fiscal 2000
budget and make it up later, in fiscal 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are really playing with fire,'' said Minority Leader Dick
Gephardt, D-Mo. ``They can't pass the appropriations bills without
going through a lot of gimmickry.''
</P>
<P>
   Those gimmicks, he said, ``will call into question in the
financial communities whether we can handle our financial affairs
here with any credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   There may be attempts to cut domestic spending deeper. The
leader of the most fiscally conservative caucus in the Republican
Party, Rep. Tom Coburn of Oklahoma, has already trimmed about $1.7
billion from seven spending bills on the floor, and he says he will
continue.
</P>
<P>
   But others want to put much more money back. The pressure to
break the caps is strong. Republicans, clinging to a tenuous
majority in the House, where all spending bills originate, are
painfully aware of polls suggesting that Americans want increased
social spending more than they want a tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans still want a tax cut badly. But, like the Democrats,
they want to spend more, too.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, they added an extra $700 million for veterans, raising
the ante on Vice President Al Gore, who this week announced that
the Clinton administration would seek an extra $1 billion for
veterans' health _ money the House had quietly added days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, senators from farm states are going to seek $9
billion in emergency spending for agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Porter said his subcommittee, which finances labor, education,
and health and human services programs, will not approve its
spending bill unless most or all of some $15 billion in cuts are
restored.
</P>
<P>
   And in September, in closed-door conferences where differences
between House and Senate spending bills are reconciled, anything is
possible. A billion here, a billion there, as the late Sen. Everett
Dirksen of Illinois used to say, and the anticipated surplus
disappears.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats and some Republicans now question whether the
projected surplus was ever realistic.
</P>
<P>
   Though its appearance was proudly proclaimed by the nation's
leading politicians, it was always an illusion, the Congressional
Budget Office said earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   The White House budget office projected that spending will be
$14 billion less than expenditures next year, above and beyond
surpluses in the Social Security account.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans looked at the congressional estimate of
revenues, compared it with the president's estimate of spending,
and called the difference a surplus.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're keeping two sets of books,'' Obey fumed.
</P>
<P>
   And he pointed to a page in the newly drafted $70 billion
spending bill for veterans, housing and other programs as a sign of
what the spending process has become. Under the heading ``Fiscal
Year 2000 Rationale,'' it reads: ``Copy to come.'' The rest is
blank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-99 2013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
