<DOCNO> NYT19990730.0308 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0423 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-BRITAIN-NYT &LR;      07-30 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-BRITAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH OFFICIAL IS FRONT-RUNNER FOR TOP NATO JOB 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Britain's defense secretary, George Robertson, a
Scottish labor union veteran whose vigorous denunciations of
Yugoslav military actions in Kosovo were almost as intense as
NATO's bombing campaign this spring, became his country's candidate
Friday for NATO secretary-general.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson, 53, immediately became the front-runner to succeed
Javier Solana, who is soon to leave the NATO job in Brussels,
Belgium, to become the European Union's coordinator for foreign and
defense policy.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Tony Blair announced Robertson's nomination in
Sarajevo, Bosnia-Herzegovina, at a summit meeting on the Balkans.
``He would do an excellent job, and we will be pressing his case
very hard,'' Blair said.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister's spokesman, Alastair Campbell, said Blair
had received ``positive responses'' from President Clinton,
President Jacques Chirac of France, Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema
of Italy and Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar of Spain, the British
Press Association news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   NATO diplomats said Blair had come under intense pressure from
Clinton and Secretary of Defense William Cohen to nominate
Robertson for the job after Germany's defense minister, Rudolf
Scharping, took himself out of the running earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robertson is very well regarded in Washington and is extremely
close to Cohen,'' a ranking alliance official said. ``The British
strategic defense review, which lays out a plan to make British
armed forces more maneuverable and easily deployable in rapid
response situations like Kosovo, is regarded as a model for other
countries like Germany to follow.''
</P>
<P>
   The nomination of Robertson came just after the first
reshuffling of Blair's Cabinet this week.
</P>
<P>
   Other potential nominees had aroused little enthusiasm in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The British Liberal Democratic Party leader, Paddy Ashdown, a
former paratrooper and a strong supporter of the bombing of Kosovo,
had been suggested, but allied officials worried that he had never
held a high government post and would be at a disadvantage dealing
with alliance defense and foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
   Denmark's defense minister, Hans Haekkerup, was well enough
thought of in Washington, but officials in Paris ruled him out
because Denmark is not a full member of the Western European Union,
a military organization that is to be absorbed into the European
Union and, under Solana's leadership, develop close operational
ties with NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Belgium had suggested former Prime Minister Jean-Luc Dehaene,
who was defeated in elections in June after a major scandal over
foods tainted with cancer-causing dioxin. But with still-fresh
memories of the resignation four years ago of another Belgian
secretary-general, Willy Claes, in an arms corruption scandal, few
people at NATO thought Dehaene was a strong candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has never held the job because NATO's supreme
allied commander in Europe, now Gen. Wesley Clark, has always been
an American.
</P>
<P>
   Clark learned this week that he would be leaving next April,
three months early, to make room for Gen. Joseph Ralston, now vice
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
   Though some reports in Washington suggested that Cohen and
Pentagon military chiefs had had less than cordial relations with
Clark, Solana described him Thursday as ``a truly outstanding
supreme allied commander'' during ``the most difficult and testing
time for the alliance,'' and said he would continue to shape the
alliance for the 21st century until he left next spring.
</P>
<P>
   The nomination of Ralston, an Air Force officer, coming hard on
the heels of a NATO bombing campaign dominated by sophisticated
U.S. planes and weapons that succeeded without use of ground troops
in getting Yugoslav forces out of Kosovo, is widely regarded in
Europe as a sign of things to come.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, in this view, will be less and less likely in
the future to become involved with ground troops in European
peacekeeping operations like the one now under way in Kosovo, and
more inclined to let the European allies sort things out on the
ground while Americans hover in the air.
</P>
<P>
   And with Britain and France now committed to taking the lead to
strengthen European defenses and hold up their side of the
trans-Atlantic defense bargain, Robertson seemed likely to have
French support for the NATO post.
</P>
<P>
   Solana's term ends formally at the end of the year, but he has
made clear that he would leave earlier once his successor was
agreed on. That could happen as early as August if allied
representatives in Brussels determine that there is consensus among
all 19 member countries on Robertson, an official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
