<SLUG> BC-INSURE-CHILDREN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTEMPT TO FUND CHILDREN'S HEALTH COVERAGE LAGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes enrollment text table)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since the US government made $24 billion available two years ago
to help states provide health care coverage for at least five
million uninsured children by the year 2002, just a little more
than a million have been signed up, according to a national report
released Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration had expected three million children
to be enrolled by now, but health officials said Friday that they
were nonetheless encouraged by the strides made so far toward
insuring the nation's children.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very large and very significant increase in a very
short period of time,'' said Vernon K. Smith, author of the
national report, which was commissioned by the Kaiser Commission on
Medicaid and the Uninsured and presented Friday at a forum in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The Children's Health Insurance Program (CHIP) was created in
1997 to provide $24 billion in federal matching funds to states
over five years, with the hopes of addressing one of the symptoms
of the nation's ailing health system _ children who go without
needed medical care because they have no insurance.
</P>
<P>
   It represents one of the most comprehensive attempts to change
the way the nation covers children since the Medicaid program began
three decades ago. States were given the flexibility to use the
CHIP money to expand their existing Medicaid programs, or to create
totally new programs for reaching uninsured youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the states were to make that goal of insuring five
million children by the year 2002, set by federal officials when
the program began, there could still be as many as six million
children without coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The latest analysis of Census figures indicates that 11 million,
or 15 percent of all children in the United States, are uninsured
at any one time.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, where just over 46,800 are enrolled in
CHIP-funded programs as of the end of June, more than 100,000
children still remain without coverage, according to state figures.
</P>
<P>
   But Rich Copp, spokesman for the state Executive Office of
Health and Human Services, said that 46,800, along with another
approximately 41,200 children enrolled since 1997 in the state's
Medicaid program, represent a major achievement in a relatively
short period of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the numbers speak for themselves. We have 88,000 more
insured children than two years ago,'' Copp said. ``The outreach
that the administration has done has resulted in almost 90,000 new
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Copp also pointed to another 19,000 children enrolled in a
separate state program, called the Children's Medical Security
Plan, which provides outpatient benefits and no hospital coverage
to those who do not meet Medicaid or CHIP eligibility guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Children who are disabled or whose family incomes range as high
as 200 percent of the federal poverty level can either qualify for
Medicaid, now known as MassHealth, or the state's new CHIP-funded
program to help pay for private insurance premiums.
</P>
<P>
   All told, Copp said, these various expansions have helped shrink
the percentage of uninsured children in Massachusetts from about 11
percent in 1995 to about 6 percent in 1998, according to a recent
state survey.
</P>
<P>
   Health care advocate Allison Staton agreed that the state has
done a good job expanding health coverage to children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing pretty well in Massachusetts. The CHIP expansion
is going really well. It's exciting,'' said Staton, deputy director
of policy for Health Care For All, a Boston-based advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   But she acknowledged that ``not every kid who is eligible is
enrolled'' in CHIP. ``Even if it's less than 5 percent, that's 5
percent too many.''
</P>
<P>
