<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALKANS-U.S.-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
39 WORLD LEADERS MEET TO PLAN BALKANS RECONSTRUCTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina _ Adjacent to a graveyard of
Bosnia's war dead, 39 world leaders, including President Clinton,
met here Friday to inaugurate an effort to rebuild southeastern
Europe and its economy from the ravages of a decade of war.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, the only leader to pledge specific aid Friday,
announced an economic package of about $700 million in aid, trade
initiatives and business incentives to generate investment in the
Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
   The Balkan package is in addition to $500 million in relief
assistance earmarked specifically for Kosovo that the United States
pledged on Wednesday in Brussels, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   The aid flowing to the region is intended to address both long-
and short-term problems. In the short term, the $500 million
pledged by the United States, as well as larger sums by other
countries, will go to rebuild Kosovo and repair the damage caused
by the war, as well as to compensate neighboring countries who
housed refugees or suffered economic harm.
</P>
<P>
   More broadly, the leaders gathered here Friday are seeking to
avert future conflicts in the Balkans through longer-term economic
reconstruction. The eventual scope of the effort, which began with
the U.S. contribution of $700 million, is not yet clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not enough to end a war,'' Clinton told students at a
Sarajevo school during his trip here. ``We must build the peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Having chosen this re-emerging but still shell-pocked city as a
hopeful symbol, the president and other leaders Friday agreed to
what they called a ``Stability Pact'' to rebuild and develop the
region at a one-day summit meeting of heads of state from the
Balkans and industrialized countries.
</P>
<P>
   The horrors visited upon this city and the region must be
``consigned to history,'' Martti Ahtisaari, the president of
Finland and of the European Union, said as he opened the
conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is high time for the region to make up for lost time,''
said Ahtisaari, who helped negotiate the peace in Kosovo. ``The
Stability Pact envisions a Europe at long last undivided,
prosperous and free. A Europe where war becomes unthinkable.''
</P>
<P>
   The main goal of the summit meeting was for the nations to
promote peace and economic assistance for the region. But they also
pointedly wanted to try to isolate Slobodan Milosevic, the
president of Yugoslavia, who was not invited. The leaders here said
that as long as Milosevic remained in power, they would not
contribute to the rebuilding of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   As President Clinton put it: ``I do not believe that we should
give reconstruction aid to Serbia as long as it rejects democracy
and as long as Mr. Milosevic is in power. We have had enough of
`ethnic cleansing.'''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Russian prime minister, Sergei Stepashin, repeated
objections he had raised earlier in the week over the decision by
Clinton and European leaders to deny aid to the Serbian people
because of Milosevic. Again, he reminded the conference that
failure to provide aid could lead to ``very complicated and
unpredictable'' consequences for Yugoslavia's 10 million people as
winter approaches. He predicted a human ``catastrophe'' if the
Serbs do not receive aid.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his criticisms, he signed the pact because he did not
want to ruin the summit, Russian officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not have any serious apprehensions about this pact,''
Stepashin said here.
</P>
<P>
   The $500 million in immediate aid to Kosovo pledged by the
United States was in part offered to to head off such criticism.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not want to see the Serb people freeze or suffer during
the coming winter,'' Barry Toiv, a spokesman for President Clinton,
said after the summit. But he said that the United States and its
allies would ``work through'' the distinction between relief aid
and reconstruction assistance, saying it would provide the former
but not the latter.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the United States pledged $10 million to ``promote
democracy'' in Serbia. The money will go to the democratic
opposition to Milosevic and to encircle Serbia with a ring of
transmitters for the Voice of America and Radio Free Europe to
counter Milosevic's state-run propaganda machine.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   There was no price tag on the total amount that the 39 countries
plus several international institutions like the World Bank would
spend on the rebuilding of southeastern Europe. The United States
has estimated that its cost for the air war was anywhere from $3
billion to $6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Costs to the countries surrounding Yugoslavia have been
considerable, since their trade was disrupted and since they
absorbed thousands of refugees. The International Monetary Fund had
estimated this summer that helping Montenegro and Kosovo, both of
which are part of Yugoslavia, and Albania, Macedonia, Romania and
Bulgaria could cost $1.25 billion to $2.25 billion a year for
several years.
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting in Brussels on Wednesday, the European Commission
and the World Bank said pledges of up to $2 billion had been made
toward reconstruction in Kosovo, although commission members
questioned the figure, saying some of that money had already been
collected and disbursed. Estimates of the cost of rebuilding Kosovo
have varied widely, but have been somewhat reduced by the lessening
of assessments of damage to the province.
</P>
<P>
   Among the aid itemized in Brussels was $200 million for
immediate needs identified by the United Nations, $45 million to
cover Kosovo's budget deficit, and $318 million for reconstruction
in the province based on initial estimates by the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Among Clinton's pledges announced Friday are business and trade
initiatives including a plan to have the Overseas Private
Investment Corp., a U.S. agency, establish a $150 million
investment fund for the Balkans and provide an additional $200
million in credit for U.S. companies seeking to set up operations
in the region. To promote trade, Clinton also announced an
initiative that would grant duty-free status to some exports to the
United States. The United States also plans to contribute up to $50
million to the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development to
encourage business ventures, provided the bank targets an
additional $80 million for the region.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he would ask Congress to reduce the tariffs for
exports, such as shoes, from the Balkans to U.S. markets. The cost
of the lower revenue over five years is estimated at between $50
million and $80 million.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has already approved the $500 million in relief aid to
Kosovo, and its approval is needed only for the duty-free imports
portion of the package.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Berger, Clinton's national security adviser, told
reporters that America had a direct interest in the reconstruction.
``Helping the region is strongly in our national interest by
reducing the risk that our troops will have to fight another, far
costlier European conflict down the road and helping to make the
whole of Europe a stronger partner for advancing our security, our
prosperity and our values.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and other leaders like Prime Minister Tony Blair of
Britain and Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder of Germany did not address
the main summit meeting, leaving the limelight to the nations of
the region to underscore the idea that the reconstruction is
something the leaders of the region are seeking, not something
imposed by richer countries.
</P>
<P>
   But in remarks afterward, Clinton acknowledged problems with the
reconstruction efforts in Sarajevo after its own civil war earlier
this decade. ``The Dayton agreement in 1995 did not rid Bosnia of
all anger and fear or frustrating problems like high unemployment,
corruption and crime,'' Clinton said. ``But Dayton did offer all
the people of Bosnia peaceful means to resolve their differences
and move forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' he said, Sarajevo can boast of ``fair elections, a free
press, reformed courts, a new single currency, the beginning of
economic growth, better ties with your neighbors, war criminals out
of power.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that refugees were still returning, and he found at
Friday's meeting that the three leaders of Bosnia were speaking
``with one single united voice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
