</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAYTRADING-REGULATION-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGULATORS TAKING A LONG LOOK AT DAY TRADING INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Texas) (With GA-SHOOT-RDP) 
(rk) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Compared with the nation's largest and most
well-known brokerage firms like Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. and Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter, day trading companies like those in Atlanta
where a gunman killed nine people on Thursday have operated in near
obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, securities regulators say, hordes of investors
have taken up day trading in recent years, hoping to profit from
the minute-by-minute fluctuations in stock prices. Many of these
people are investing novices, armed with little more than hope,
some cash and access to a computer.
</P>
<P>
   But officials who have examined the books and records of several
day trading firms say that more than 90 percent of the people who
engage in day trading lose money.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the killings in Atlanta, state securities regulators
were growing increasingly concerned about the burgeoning numbers of
day traders in the United States and the companies that cater to
them. In late November, the North American Securities
Administrators Association, which consists of all state and
provincial regulators in the United States, Canada and Mexico,
warned investors against day trading, calling it a form of
gambling, not investing. The organization also announced that it
was forming a task force to investigate the day trading phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike full-service brokerage companies that sell stocks and
bonds and other securities to investors, day trading companies are
essentially selling access to the market and training people how to
trade. But this does not make them any less accountable to
investors, regulators say, and their operations must adhere to
securities laws and regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, what these officials say they have found at many
day trading firms is a scary combination of unsophisticated
investors lured into the practice of day trading by talk of hefty
gains and minimal risks. They also say that many day trading firms
skirt securities laws and regulations designed to protect
investors.
</P>
<P>
   Denise Voigt Crawford, Texas Securities Commissioner, has
brought three actions against day trading firms in her state. She
said that more enforcement actions are coming. ``Every single day
trading firm that we have examined in the state of Texas has
problems,'' Ms. Crawford said. ``And most are serious problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the Atlanta shootings, day trading firms argued that the
increased regulatory scrutiny coming to bear on them was unfair and
an outgrowth of increased competition for business the day trading
firms are bringing to Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   In a June 1 article published on the Web site of the Electronic
Traders Association, a day trading lobbying group, Saul S. Cohen, a
partner at the law firm of Proskauer Rose LLP in New York, wrote
that the once unchallenged empires of stock markets, traditional
brokers, institutional firms and regulators feel menaced by day
trading. ``Being threatened, these parties are waging a war against
day traders both through public relations and regulatory
intimidation,'' Cohen wrote.
</P>
<P>
   While it is unclear exactly how many people are active day
traders, Harvey Houtkin, chief executive of All-Tech Investment
Group, said in a television interview Thursday that as many as 10
million people could be considered day traders. That number is
almost certainly too high. But there are an estimated 100 firms
devoted to day trading; as of November, All-Tech alone had more
than 1,500 customers.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Electronic Traders Association, a day traders'
lobbying group, these traders average 35 trades per day and account
for about 15 percent of trading volume in Nasdaq stocks. Few day
traders buy and sell New York Stock Exchange-listed shares.
</P>
<P>
   Securities regulators say that while most of those who become
day traders are men, participants come from a broad spectrum of
economic and professional backgrounds. Many are young, with little
in the way of job experience but older, more established doctors,
lawyers and former salespeople are also among those trading. More
women are joining the ranks of day traders too. Day traders
typically must put down $50,000 to begin trading.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One of the problems with some day trading firms, state
investigators say, is that their managements downplay the risk
associated with the practice. Although customers are asked to sign
documents that outline the risks, at the same time they are often
told that if they follow the trading practices recommended by the
firm in its training programs, their risks are vastly reduced.
Professional traders say this is not so.
</P>
<P>
   Certain day trading houses also skirt rules on how much money
they can lend to their customers to buy stocks. Traditional firms
offer to lend their clients 50 percent of a transaction's value,
known as margin lending. When stocks fall and the amount of cash
the customer invested initially drops below 35 percent of the
portfolio's value, certain day trading firms loan additional funds
to get the account above water.
</P>
<P>
   If the stocks held in the portfolio continue to plunge, the
investor who has borrowed more than the 50 percent that is typical
could stand to lose more than double his or her initial investment.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, regulators say they have seen former clients of day
trading firms leave owing as much as $100,000 to the operation.
</P>
<P>
   Some clients of day trading firms may open accounts there to
circumvent registering as an investment adviser with the Securities
and Exchange Commission or state officials, a law enforcement
source said. In these cases, day traders improperly pool customer
accounts and fail to disclose the risks inherent in their trading
practices.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the carnage in Atlanta, scrutiny on day
trading firms will almost certainly be stepped up. One securities
regulator who requested anonymity said that criminal proceedings
would be brought against a day trading firm in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Several brokerage houses sought Friday to distance themselves
from the day-trading phenomenon. Rebecca Metz, spokeswoman for
Charles Schwab &AMP; Co., said the San Francisco company defines itself
as a ``buy and hold'' company. She said the cost of a trade on the
Schwab site, $29.95, ``isn't attractive to day traders,'' who can
pay $5 to $10 on other sites. Still, she said 2 to 3 percent of
Schwab's 6.2 million account holders are day traders, which would
put the number between 124,000 and 186,000 on Schwab alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem with day trading is that people are
exposed to something where they can lose an awful lot of money very
quickly but they don't understand it,'' said Maryland Securities
Commissioner Melanie Senter Lubin, . ``People don't understand that
stocks don't always go up. A lot of people do this because they
don't have a job. This is a very risky way to try to make money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
