<HEADER>
A0435 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEPSI-POWER-AISLE-ART     07-30 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEPSI-POWER-AISLE-ART-890&AMP;ADD-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEPSICO STRATEGY RESTS ON THE POWER OF ONE PROMOTIONAL AISLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036. 
(yn) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSFIELD, Mass. _ Here in the sprawling Price Chopper
supermarket, between Aisle 6, devoted to detergents and dog food,
and Aisle 9, the home of peanut butter and jelly, Roger A. Enrico's
vision of the future is on display.
</P>
<P>
   Enrico is the chairman of Pepsico. In April, store workers and
Pepsi sales representatives tore apart Aisles 7 and 8, creating a
large space stocked with mostly Pepsi soft drinks and Frito-Lay
snack food. With an inflatable Star Wars pod racer dangling from
the ceiling, and large color photographs of adults and children
tucking into Pepsi products, the ``Power Aisle'' is hard to miss.
Pepsi hopes shoppers looking for a two-liter bottle of Mountain Dew
will grab a bag of Cool Ranch Doritos as well, or vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   It is all part of the company's marketing strategy known as the
Power of One, a New Age-sounding slogan for selling soda and snack
food together and maybe Pepsi's other core product _ fruit juice _
too.
</P>
<P>
   The goal, of course, is to pump up Pepsi's sales and profits by
taking advantage of some synergies unavailable to its rival, Coke,
and thereby boost its lagging share price.
</P>
<P>
   The Power of One doesn't just involve physically stacking
12-packs of Pepsi next to nacho cheese Wow Doritos (Enrico's
favorite) on one side and calcium-fortified Tropicana orange juice
on the other.
</P>
<P>
   It also means touting the combined profit potential of Pepsi's
array of products to supermarket managers in negotiations for
precious shelf space. And it means fortifying those deals with
Pepsi-paid promotions that will translate into tidy profits for the
stores.
</P>
<P>
   The idea has been kicking around Pepsico's divisions for years
now. In fact, displaying salty products next to thirst-quenchers is
so obvious that some regional managers have been pushing the
practice for a long time. But in the last few months, with the
appointment of a senior marketing executive to oversee it, the
concept has truly caught fire inside the company.
</P>
<P>
   One reason executives like it so much is that it plays to a
Pepsi strength _ product diversity _ that Coke, with its exclusive
focus on soft drinks, has no immediate hope of matching.
</P>
<P>
   Another is that the consolidation of the food industry in recent
years has reduced the number of big supermarket chains to half a
dozen from 20, meaning that selling just one major customer on the
Power of One could result in a huge boost to the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today five customers will do 44 percent of our supermarket
business,'' said Al Carey, a senior vice president at Pepsico whom
Enrico named last year to oversee the strategy. ``What ends up
happening is that you have a more demanding customer, and a
customer who wants things they don't have, in terms of data mining,
category management, and telling them which promotions are
successful and which are not.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Pepsi hopes to become more or less married to
its major retail customers _ helping them sell Pepsi products,
using techniques that Pepsi will develop and pay for. Enrico even
dreams about stationing Pepsico employees full time in some big
supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can have a person from Pepsico who is there all day,'' he
said enthusiastically in an interview last month, looking tanned
and fit after a summer weekend in Montana. ``That person would
order the Frito-Lay products, as well as Pepsi and Tropicana
products, schedule the deliveries, do the merchandising and the
in-store category management.''
</P>
<P>
   And would store managers be happy about such outsiders coming in
and poking around their aisles? Of course they would, Enrico said.
``Anything we can do with these large and profitable categories for
retailers has tremendous leverage effect on a retailer's bottom
line,'' he said. Why, when he mentions putting a Pepsico employee
in a store full time to supermarket executives, he declared,
``their eyes light up _ they just love this.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe some of them do. Others don't sound totally sold on the
idea. Even Price Chopper, which let Pepsi loose in its store here,
has some reservations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Pepsi's sales grow at the expense of Coke's, then I've
gained nothing,'' said Jim Mizeur, a vice president at Price
Chopper's Schenectady, N.Y., headquarters. Besides, he added, ``If
Pepsi does it, do you do it with your Budweiser guy and your
Campbell's guy?''
</P>
<P>
   But if there is a tangible advantage for the store, then Mizeur
said he would not rule out such collaboration. ``The position we
take is if it grows the category, then we're in favor of it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Such a condition is music to Pepsi's ears. In stores where the
company has run trials, Enrico said, sales of Frito-Lay products
rose 21 percent, and sales of soft drinks _ all kinds, not just
Pepsi's _ increased, though not as much. People who have both salty
snacks and soft drinks in their homes, he noted, tend to consume
them together; the Power of One program is supposed to reinforce
what he already considers ``fundamental consumer behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts have become believers as well. Bill Pecoriello,
who covers Pepsico and other beverage companies for Sanford C.
Bernstein, says the strategy should help Pepsi move more soft
drinks and snacks out the door. ``We're convinced that it's a good
idea,'' he said. ``The question is, why didn't they do this 30
years ago?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The strategy's current prominence goes back to Pepsico's
decision in 1996 to cast off its peripheral businesses and
concentrate on drinks and snacks. First, it spun off its restaurant
division. Then, Enrico pounced on Tropicana, paying $3.3 billion to
acquire it last summer from Seagram. Finally, Pepsi made its
bottling division into a separate, publicly traded company.
</P>
<P>
   Retail experts generally think the company is on the right
track. ``In this day of precious shelf space and the desire of all
retailers to cut product costs, I would think they would be
amenable to the idea at least, if it meant a savings to them and if
there were heavy promotional dollars behind it,'' said Paul
Bernish, a former supermarket executive who now runs a consulting
firm.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he added, ``There are a lot of suppliers who
are trying similar things.''
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics note that Pepsi can only fight for shelf space, not own
it. Even the Power Aisle here displays Rubbermaid plastic pitchers
and jugs of fruit-flavored wine in addition to Pepsi products. And
a big island of Coca-Cola 12-packs appeared recently, on sale for
$1.98. Considering the aisle is meant to display all kinds of soft
drinks, the Coke space is logical, but probably not what the Pepsi
designers had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   There may be more of that in store from Coke, which dwarfs Pepsi
in the $56 billion carbonated soft-drink business with 45 percent
of the market, vs. 31 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were the largest account for Coke in this area,'' said the
store's grocery manager, Jim Collins, adding that when the Power
Aisle opened up, ``Coke wasn't happy with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Coke executives have been trooping in to see it, he added, and
he expects the company will come up with some competing version
before long.
</P>
<P>
   Coke has already begun to fire back with some in-store programs
of its own, said Polly Howes, a spokeswoman for the company. These
include a plan that offers shoppers Cokes as they walk into stores
(they have to pay for them on their way out, of course) and a red
``cart caddy'' that hooks onto shopping carts and includes a bottle
holder. Coke also has begun to promote its products with DiGiorno
pizza, Oreo cookies and other foods, all designed to increase sales
across the board.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that the soft-drink category in and of itself is a
great profit generator for retailers,'' Ms. Howes said. ``And
consumers have been telling us for years that they link Coca-Cola
with all kinds of foods.'' In other words, not just potato chips.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the market seems to regard the Power of One as a
98-pound weakling when it comes to lifting Pepsi's share price.
With a price-earnings multiple of 30, compared with 47 for
Coca-Cola, Pepsi is hardly one of Wall Street's darlings, despite
its elaborate makeover.
</P>
<P>
   And investors bolted from Pepsico stock in late March after
Coke, not Pepsi, revealed that it was having a terrible quarter, a
fallout that Enrico finds puzzling since soft drinks account for
less than half of Pepsi's profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest issue with the share price is convincing investors
that they can deliver consistent 12 percent to 13 percent earnings
growth,'' said Pecoriello, the Wall Street analyst. ``Power of One
is one component of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Enrico has been basking in grocery-store scanner data
that show Pepsi growing faster than Coke (though at the same time
sales of the company's heavily promoted Wow chips are falling). And
he insists Pepsi stock will jump once the company shows growth
across several quarters. The company showed solid results in nearly
every operating group in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pepsico has moved from being a conglomerate to being an
operating company,'' Enrico said. ``We had a slightly decentralized
culture here, and that's one of the changes we've made. We don't
try to run the businesses from here, but we do try to work with
them to set the strategic agenda from here.''
</P>
<P>
   Enrico's biggest fear seems to be unrolling the program too
fast, forcing too much change on subordinates long accustomed to
working independently. What would be bad, he said, was if ``somehow
we pushed the pendulum too far on Power of One, and the divisions
don't drive their own agendas optimally, or if people lose their
sense of ownership over the end result.''
</P>
<P>
   The separate fiefdoms that made up Pepsico for years have not
exactly disappeared from the scene, and the risk remains that they
will resist pulling together toward the same objectives.
</P>
<P>
   Yet at the same time, some inside Pepsico have complained that
the program isn't moving fast enough. ``I get criticized
internally, `Why aren't we moving on this?''' he said. ``My answer
is, this is of such strategic consequence, I don't want it to get
lost.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
