<HEADER>
A0438 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCIETY-GUNS-BOS &LR;      07-30 1310
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIETY-GUNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHORITIES SAY DEADLY AGGRESSION NOT LINKED TO GUN AVAILABILITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Heavily armed and burning for revenge, a gunman spends days
readying himself for a personal war before returning to the scene
of his worst humiliations. He murders as many people as his bullets
can reach, then, with police closing in, kills himself.
</P>
<P>
   In the past three months, the roster of men for whom that
description applies has grown by tragic &UR;  &LR; proportions. In April in
Littleton, Colo., it was Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold at Columbine
High School. Then, earlier this month in Illinois and Indiana, it
was white supremacist Benjamin Nathaniel Smith.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday in Atlanta, Mark O. Barton joined the twisted club
by carrying out a plan ``to kill as many of the people that
greedily sought my destruction,'' as he wrote in a note he left at
his home, near the bodies of his wife and two children.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities on aggression, violence and culture say Barton's
vengeful assault reflected a pattern of particularly destructive _
and self-destructive _ responses to modern stresses, though several
cautioned against drawing sweeping conclusions about what such
attacks reveal about the United States at the end of the
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities also differed markedly about how much emphasis
should be placed on the guns used by Barton and the other killers.
Some argued that the easy availability of handheld firearms
deserves a significant amount of blame, while others said Barton
and other killers might well have been stopped sooner if more
people were allowed to carry guns. Several of the gun control
skeptics noted that in the absence of guns, they might have chosen
other methods _ their cars or bombs _ to carry out their deadly
goals.
</P>
<P>
   There was widespread agreement, however, that the recent cluster
of multiple murders by suicidal men would likely be remembered not
as an aberration but as part of an ongoing, if sporadic, trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see a real end in sight to this, and I don't know that
there is any intervention that we can think of that is going to
prevent this level of violence,'' said Dr. Terence Keane, director
of the National Center for Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder at the
Veterans Administration's Boston Health Care System.
</P>
<P>
   Keane said he views the Atlanta case and other similar shootings
as proof of Winston Churchill's comment that the veneer of
civilization is very thin.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have situations where people experience shame or
humiliation or loss and they can assign responsibility to others
for that, the boundaries of their aggression are limitless,'' he
said. What ultimately separates killers from the rest of society
are factors including the depth of shame, a lowered threshold for
acting out, substance abuse, and ``impulse disorders'' that
eliminate societal and personal fail-safe measures, Keane said.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Goldstein, a psychologist at Syracuse University who runs
the Center for Research on Aggression, said Barton's case might be
different from the Columbine High School killings in that the
Atlanta killer's primary motive might have been ``mental
disturbance,'' as opposed to a variety of factors including media
influence and parental neglect.
</P>
<P>
   Mental disturbance and aggression do not necessarily go
together, Goldstein said. ``For the most part, people who are
disturbed, who have psychiatric disorders, are not more
aggressive,'' he said. ``But there might be more of an air of
irrationality to this case. He may have been thinking, `I'm going
down and I'm taking as many people as I can with me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein cautioned against seeing the recent spate of cases as
indicators of heightened societal aggression.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, aggression is hard to explain and predict because,
first of all, it's a low-frequency event. The second part is that
far too often, in trying to predict and understand and control
aggression, you have a difficult time puzzling over what went on in
the person,'' Goldstein said. ``Every behavior, aggression or
whatever, is a function of things in the individual and things in
the environment. We might never know what it was in this
individual's history and environment that caused him to turn to
aggression.''
</P>
<P>
   Alice Eagly, a social psychologist who is a professor of
psychology at Northwestern University, said the cultural factors at
issue include ``glorification of violence in the mass media and
family structures that are less stable, so that people are less
linked-in effectively to families where a variety of positive
influences might occur.''
</P>
<P>
   She was among several authorities who noted that the sprees of
deadly violence are almost invariably the work of men. ``This sort
of behavior has been part of the male role as it has been construed
in US culture, from the frontier tradition on,'' Eagly said.
</P>
<P>
   In her view, the most effective immediate response would be
increased gun control. ``Not only would there be fewer guns, it
would be an expression of public sentiment that we want less
violence. That would change the cultural climate,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That view was seconded by Kristen Rand, director of federal
policy at the Violence Policy Center, a gun-control advocacy
organization in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really believe this is going to be America's future unless
we decide to get serious about regulating guns, and from our
perspective that means a handgun ban,'' Rand said. In light of
congressional opposition to increased handgun controls, however,
Rand said she doubted any significant changes would result from the
horror at Barton's attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``This level of incident can go on forever and it won't get
through to people. I personally think it's going to take something
three times as horrific as Littleton, and I think we can count on
that happening,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the National Rifle Association, the Violence
Policy Center's most frequent nemesis on federal legislative
efforts, said the NRA would have no comment on the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still things we don't know about this tragedy, and
there will be a time and a place to debate public policy,'' said
NRA spokesman Jim Manown.
</P>
<P>
   Several academic authorities said it would be an error to
conclude that the Atlanta episode offers a clear argument for
greater gun control.
</P>
<P>
   John Lott, a professor at the University of Chicago School of
Law, said a better argument could be made for allowing more people
to carry concealed weapons. He said his research has found that
so-called right-to-carry laws have a demonstrable deterrent effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many attacks just don't take place, and to the extent they do
take place the amount of harm is mitigated by someone there with a
gun,'' said Lott, author of ``More Guns, Less Crime'' (University
of Chicago Press, 1998).
</P>
<P>
   Roger Lane, a Haverford College historian and author of ``Murder
in America'' (Ohio State University Press, 1998), said the Atlanta,
Colorado, and Midwest cases reflect a particular kind of murderer
who is resigned to his own death.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the kinds of people whose psychological profiles
more nearly resemble suicides than murderers,'' Lane said. ``What
mass murder does is both. It's suicidal, you never get away with
it, and you know that from the start. Either you're caught
instantly or killed instantly or you kill yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Lane was among the authorities who said a key change from the
past was the availability of guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mechanisms that trigger homicial aggression have always
been with us, and homicidal aggression has always been with us. But
now the weapons of mass murder are a lot more accessible.
Technology is responsible for these killings, and as a result we
are going to see more of them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
