<SLUG> BC-TAX-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE PROPOSES TAX BREAKS AIMED AT MIDDLE CLASS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn.)  (See also TAX-CONGRESS) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ At odds with Republicans in Congress and with Bill
Bradley, his rival for the Democratic presidential nomination, Vice
President Al Gore on Friday proposed a long list of tax breaks to
address specific social goals like making health care and education
more affordable.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd better believe America's middle class deserves a tax
break,'' Gore said in what his staff billed as a major policy
speech.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at the Minnesota Community Technical College after a
fund-raising event here Thursday night, the vice president said
Republican tax plans like the one approved by the Senate on Friday
and the one passed by the House last week offered ``too much for
too few at the expense of too many.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's list _ ``carefully targeted,'' he said, ``to the
hard-working middle class'' _ would allow new tax deductions or
credits for education and retirement savings, medical expenses,
nursing-home costs, corporate research and development, child care,
low-income housing, energy conservation, school construction and
investments in poor neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, the former senator from New Jersey, did not respond to
the Gore speech. His staff said he was not running a campaign
geared to reacting to the vice president. And Bradley has not
himself delivered a campaign address detailing his tax policies.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley's philosophy is well known. He was a central figure
in putting together the Tax Reform Act of 1986, the most
comprehensive tax law in the last half of the 20th century. He is
adamantly opposed to narrow tax breaks like those offered by Gore,
arguing instead that most, if not all, tax credits and deductions
should be abolished and that the money saved should be used to make
tax rates _ the percentage of income paid in taxes _ as low as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Bradley holds, if the government wants to promote a
particular social goal like education, it should spend the money
directly. Doing it through the tax code, he believes, is wasteful.
</P>
<P>
   Many tax breaks on Gore's list, like those for school
construction and child care, have been part of the Clinton
administration's budget and have generated little interest in the
Republican-controlled Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore offered two new proposals Friday. One would be tax-free
savings accounts to allow workers to put aside money for education.
The other would be an increase in the standard deduction for
married couples who do not itemize deductions, so the couple's
deduction would be the same as if the two were single and filed
separate tax returns, eliminating the so-called marriage penalty in
the current law.
</P>
<P>
   Students, parents and grandparents could have up to $2,500
withheld from their pay and placed in the accounts. Employers would
be allowed to match the contribution. And taxpayers with incomes
below $40,000 would get an additional tax credit offsetting half
the money they placed in their accounts. The money could be
withdrawn tax-free to meet education expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president's speech Friday was the latest of several in
which he has set forth detailed positions on issues, including
education, crime, cancer research and aid to religious institutions
to help combat social problems.
</P>
<P>
   On taxes, Gore has a fundamental philosophical difference with
Republicans that echoes through the running budget conflict between
the Clinton administration and Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans want to keep taxes low with the explicit goal of
reducing the size of the government. The administration favors
using much of the budget surplus to maintain and even expand
government programs. Gore described the difference this way:
</P>
<P>
   ``Proponents of the Republican tax scheme will tell us: `It's
your money, and you should have it back.' It is our money. But it
is also our Social Security. It is our Medicare. It is our good
jobs and our stable economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's philosophical difference with Bradley is more
sophisticated.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president, his staff says, believes that the government
will never provide the money directly to reach important social
policy goals and that the way to accomplish them is through
targeted tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley views that as an inefficient approach. People and
companies would adjust their finances to achieve tax savings, and
much of the cost to the government would go to taxpayers who are
not necessarily the ones the government is trying to help.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all politicians, whatever their party or ideology, agree
with the Gore approach, though they disagree over what the specific
tax breaks should be. Almost all academic experts on tax policy
agree with the Bradley approach of the fewest possible deductions
and exemptions and the lowest possible tax rates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
