<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR SATURDAY, JULY 31
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Saturday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-AID-CONGRESS-NYT (moved on Thursday, July 29)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, July 29,
about House consideration of a foreign aid bill referred
incorrectly in some copies to the outcome of a vote on a bipartisan
amendment that would bar funds for organizations that lobby for or
against abortions or promote abortion as a method of family
planning. The amendment was passed, not defeated, by the 221-to-208
vote.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CALIF-DANGEROUS-SCHOOL-NYT (moved on Tuesday, July 27)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, July 27,
about the Los Angeles Board of Education's debate over whether to
abandon a $200 million school project because of concerns about its
environmental safely misstated the views of an outside lawyer for
the school district. The lawyer, David Cartwright of the law firm
O'Melveny &AMP; Myers, assured the board that it was safe to build the
school on land adjoining a former oilfield only after a full
environmental review and an analysis of recommended safety measures
had been completed. He did not say the project would be safe
without such a study.
</P>
<P>
   The article also incompletely described the law firm's role in
representing the district and the project's developer, Kajima Urban
Development. The firm represented the developer on other matters,
not the school project. Both clients were aware of and agreed to
this arrangement and it was disclosed before negotiations on the
project, not afterward.
</P>
<P>
   BC-FAT-IMAGE-NYT (moved on Wednesday, July 28)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, July
28, about a convention of the National Association to Advance Fat
Acceptance referred incorrectly to Jody Abrams, a member of the
group. She is a woman, not a man.
</P>
<P>
   BC-WIRELESS-EUROPE-NYT (moved on Monday, July 26)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, July 26,
about wireless data services in Europe misstated the position of
two American companies on a proposed standard for new wireless
technology. The companies, Sprint and Bell Atlantic, support a
proposal called C.D.M.A. 2000, which would be compatible with a
current technology known as C.D.M.A., for code division multiple
access; they do not endorse wideband C.D.M.A., which is a rival
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CIR-WALKMAN-CYBER-NYT (moved on Wednesday, July 28)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, July
28, about the origin of the word ``cyberspace'' misidentified the
work by the writer William Gibson in which the word first appeared.
It was ``Burning Chrome,'' a 1982 short story, not the 1984 novel
``Neuromancer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
