<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-NASA-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS FEAR DEEP BUDGET CUTS WILL KEEP NASA EARTHBOUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By WARREN E. LEARY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A surprise budget cut proposed for the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration would devastate the agency's
science programs and possibly force the closings of two of its
major space centers, program administrators and scientists say.
</P>
<P>
   As members of Congress from both political parties who are
friendly to the space program maneuvered to temper a proposed deep
cut in the space agency's budget for the coming year, scientists
said they feared that any substantial reduction would
disproportionately affect critical science projects for years to
come.
</P>
<P>
   The House Appropriations Committee voted Friday to reduce NASA's
budget by about $1 billion, passing legislation that would finance
the agency at $12.6 billion, about an 8 percent reduction from this
year's spending levels. At the urging of members of Congress with
major NASA centers in their states, the panel restored almost $400
million that a subcommittee earlier recommended cutting.
</P>
<P>
   ``A $1 billion cut to NASA is still disastrous, both to managing
the current program and future exploration,'' said Dr. Louis
Friedman, executive director of the Planetary Society, a national
space advocacy group, ``NASA's budget has been reduced every year
since 1992, and the agency has dealt with it. But this is too
much.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the House Appropriations subcommittee that oversees
money for veterans affairs, housing and independent agencies,
including NASA, recommended that NASA's financing for the 2000
fiscal year be $12.3 billion, about $1.3 billion, or 10 percent,
below the Clinton administration's request. This is also $1.4
billion below what the agency received this year.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the full committee passed by voice vote an amendment
to restore some money that was offered by the chairman of the
subcommittee that originally deleted the NASA money, Rep. James
Walsh, R-N.Y. Walsh's amendment restored $225 million for space
research and technology development, $100 million for the Space
Infrared Telescope Facility, the last of four major orbiting
observatories that the agency wants to orbit the Earth, and $75
million for future robotic missions to Mars.
</P>
<P>
   But the measure called for the additional money to come out of
the budget of the Americorp program, and the White House has said
that President Clinton will veto any bill that cut financing for
this program.
</P>
<P>
   The completed bill is to be voted upon by the full House next
week. Some NASA supporters say there may be more efforts then to
restore more money to the agency.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts for NASA and other agencies are the result of House
Republicans trying to find money to fund 13 spending bills required
to run the government that must be passed before the congressional
recess on Aug. 6. Even in a period of federal budget surpluses, the
lawmakers are trying to stay within spending caps imposed by a 1997
balanced budget agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel S. Goldin, the NASA administrator, lashed out at the
appropriations subcommittee cuts, saying such reductions would be
``devastating'' to an agency he said had been a model for cutting
costs and doing more with less. Reductions of this magnitude would
mean closing two or three space centers and personnel layoffs, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James Sensenbrenner, R-Wis., who chairs the House Science
Committee, said he also was disappointed about NASA's funding, but
decried as ``scare tactics'' charges by Vice President Al Gore and
others that the latest reductions would result in closing centers
and layoffs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
