<HEADER>
A0452 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOT-GUN-COX     07-30 0363
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOT-GUN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Guns apparently obtained legally
 &HT;    By Lyda Longa
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Police dubbed him the double-fisted shooter who
brandished a gun in each hand as he pumped 40 bullets into 22
people, killing nine.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, he pulled out the same two weapons, pointed them to
either side of his head and fired once, killing himself instantly.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Orrin Barton was well-armed Thursday afternoon as he fled
from the scene of one of Atlanta's grisliest killings in the heart
of the Piedmont Road business district.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the Colt .45 caliber semiautomatic and Glock 9mm
semiautomatic pistols police say Barton used for the mass killings,
the shooter also had a Raven .26 caliber semiautomatic pistol and a
.22 caliber Harrington Richardson revolver buried deep inside a
duffel bag found in his Ford Aerostar van late Thursday afternoon,
police and Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   At least 200 rounds of .45 caliber ammunition and two sets of
handcuffs, also were found in the bag, said Atlanta police
spokesman John Quigley.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Potter, an associate special agent in charge at the ATF's
Atlanta office, said Barton purchased the Glock in 1993 from the a
now-defunct gun shop in Warner Robbins. The 45-caliber handgun was
purchased in 1983 by a man in Richardson, Texas. Police believe
Barton may have obtained the gun through a private sale. The gun
has never been reported stolen. The Raven pistol was purchased in
1982 by another person, but ATF officials are not certain where the
gun, also not reported stolen, was purchased. The Harrington
Richardson revolver will be the most difficult to trace because it
was made 20 years ago, Potter said.
</P>
<P>
   The firearms, as far as ATF officials know, were obtained by
Barton legally and have not been used in any other crimes, Potter
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no problems and no prohibitions placed on the
purchases of these guns,'' Potter said. ``In fact, because he had
no criminal record, Barton could have purchased guns the day he
killed all these people.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
