<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS SHOULD GUIDE VIDEO GAME USE
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: The (AT) in the tagline stands in for the symbol) 
(yn) 
 By LONNIE BROWN   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's the difference between a Furby, Pokemon, Game Boy and a
NEOGEO?
</P>
<P>
   It's a question posed, and answered, in the current issue
(July/August) of Children's Software Revue. It's part of the
issue's cover story: ``Friend or Foe? Every Parent's Videogame
Primer.''
</P>
<P>
   So you won't go away without the answers:
</P>
<P>
   Furby is an animatronic troll-like doll with large eyes. It uses
infrared signals to communicate. About $30.
</P>
<P>
   Pokemon is short for ``pocket monster.'' It's based on a popular
television series, and the little monsters can be ``raised'' by the
child. Some models can fight against one another.
</P>
<P>
   Game Boy is a pocket-size, game-playing machine with a small
screen, available in both black and white and color models. There
are about 500 titles for the machine, although most are not in
color. The Game Boy Color was introduced in the fall of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   NEOGEO, from SNK Corp. of America, is designed to compete
against Nintendo's Game Boy. A color model will be available in
August. CSR said its child testers liked it better than the Game
Boy, although there are not as many cartridges available.
</P>
<P>
   The Revue's article on dealing with video games suggests seven
ways parents can make these games friends instead of foes:
</P>
<P>
   1. Put rules in place and abide by them. Be consistent with
time, and set examples.
</P>
<P>
   2. Know the issue and how to control it. ``A child gets into
trouble when video games become the substitute for sports, friends
and family,'' Arthur Pober, executive director of the Entertainment
Software Rating Board, told CSR.
</P>
<P>
   3. Video games can be noisy, but don't make the mistake of
relegating them to a remote corner of the house or letting the
child wear headphones. ``It is recommended that the games be kept
in an open, well-traveled part of the house, so the activity
becomes everyone's concern,'' the article recommends.
</P>
<P>
   4. Get involved. Join your children and understand what they're
playing and why.
</P>
<P>
   5. Provide a balanced media diet. Remember that only 7 percent
of the video games get an ``M'' rating reserved for the most
violent. There are hundreds of them that involve math, logic and
language.
</P>
<P>
   6. Increase alternatives. Supply and encourage creative
projects. Children have unlimited energy. Parents can channel it.
</P>
<P>
   7. Set firm limits. Play for an extra hour when nothing's been
done to merit it? What about a game title loaded with violence?
Think about those questions. Who provides the answer? You or the
child?
</P>
<P>
   For more information: www.childrenssoftware.com. For
subscription information: (800) 993-9499.
</P>
<P>
   (Lonnie Brown is The Ledger's associate editor. He can be
reached by e-mail at LonnieB001(AT)aol.com. The Ledger in Lakeland,
Fla., is part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
