<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Saturday,
July 31, 1999. If you have any questions, please call Miranda
Kennedy on the Star's News Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   HEAT-WAVE: Another sizzler in the frying pan for Kansas City.
Temps again expected to hit 104 with heat indexes of 116 this
afternoon. We'll fan out into the newly opened cooling shelters to
talk to people trying to escape the blast furnace, and check out
hospital emergency rooms as the death toll is expected to continue
climbing to 14. Now have 27 dead in Missouri, the most in the
nation. Also will profile some of the victims who've already died;
one was a 75-year-old KC man who mistakenly turned the heat on,
instead of the AC. By Ruth Igoe. Story will move in the ``a''
category.
</P>
<P>
   HEAT-HISTORY: In the midst of the current heat wave, the worst
of the 90s in KC, we take a historical look back at the other
killer heat waves, including the one in 1980 which claimed 176
lives. What's changed over and the years and what hasn't? By Brian
Burnes. Story will move in the ``a'' category.
</P>
<P>
   WILD-HEAT: Birds are out of the treetops and squirrels are
prostrating themselves to keep cool. We look at the effects of the
weather on wildlife. By Bill Graham.
</P>
<P>
   CELTIC-MUSIC: StarJournal feature about local songstress Connie
Dover and her cohort, Scotland's Phil Cunningham, late of
Inverness, who has come to America to produce her new CD and to
discuss the evolution of Celtic music in America. In this edition
of the journal, we find them discussing the intricacies and trends
of musicology in America. By Joe Popper. Story will move in the
``a'' category.
</P>
<P>
   WWF-LAWSUIT: Jackson County Prosecutor Bob Beaird says he will
not file criminal charges in the death of professional wrestler
Owen Hart. Hart fell to his death at Kemper earlier this summer. By
Joe Lambe. Story will move in the ``a'' category.
</P>
<P>
   DC-BUDGET: The House passed a budget for DC this week that once
again banned a needle exchange program for AIDS users, and Rep.
Todd Tiahrt again led the charge. But the measure also allowed the
results of last fall's referendum on the medical use of marijuana
to be released. The measure is believed to have passed, but
Congress ordered the outcome sealed in the election board
computers. By David Goldstein. Story will move in the ``w''
category.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-COMPETE: Small video store owners are trying various
strategies to compete with big chains. By Jennifer Mann. Story will
move in the ``f'' category.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-COLUMN: Weekly column by David Hayes and Finn Buller. Story
will move in the ``f'' category.
</P>
<P>
   HEASTER-COLUMN: Business column by Jerry Heaster. Story will
move in the ``f'' category.
</P>
