<DOCNO> NYT19990730.0327 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0457 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRIPP-INDICT-ART-750&AMP;     07-30 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIPP-INDICT-ART-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIPP IS INDICTED FOR ILLEGALLY TAPING CONVERSATIONS WITH
LEWINSKY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 1-888-603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(th) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELLICOTT CITY, Md. _ Linda Tripp, whose secretly recorded
conversations with an impressionable young friend exposed an affair
that led to President Clinton's impeachment, was indicted on two
criminal charges by a Maryland grand jury Friday for illegally
taping the telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   The charges seemed to bring the Monica Lewinsky saga to an
improbable and dizzying full circle. Mrs. Tripp, who for many
became a reviled symbol of betrayal, found herself accused of a
crime 18 months after she entered the case as an accuser, bringing
to federal authorities the tape recordings that first alerted them
to Ms. Lewinsky's relationship with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Tripp's tapes ignited the most serious Oval Office scandal
since Watergate and unleashed a criminal grand jury inquiry by
Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater independent counsel, that culminated
in the president's impeachment by the House and his trial and
ultimate acquittal in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, Mrs. Tripp faces a maximum penalty on each count
of five years years in prison and a $10,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's indictment charged that Mrs. Tripp violated Maryland
wiretap laws that make it illegal for one person to tape record a
conversation with another person without the other person's
consent, assuming that the one making the recording knows that the
state's statutes forbid it. Federal law and the laws of some other
states do not require such a notification.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said in the indictment that Mrs. Tripp, a civilian
Pentagon employee, illegally taped a telephone conversation with
Ms. Lewinsky on Dec. 22, 1997, without the permission of the former
White House intern after Mrs. Tripp had been told by her lawyer
that secret taping was illegal.
</P>
<P>
   In the conversations that day, the two women discussed what they
should say about Ms. Lewinsky's sexual relationship with Clinton in
the testimony that each expected to give in a sexual harassment
suit against Clinton brought by Paula Jones, a former Arkansas
state employee.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors also accused Mrs. Tripp of illegally disclosing
the contents of that conversation to Newsweek Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Tripp was not present Friday at the Howard County
Courthouse, but her spokesman, Philip Coughter, told reporters that
Mrs. Tripp had become the victim of a ``shameful vendetta'' and
that the charges against her amounted to ``the most disgracefully
transparent campaign of politically motivated vengeance in recent
American history.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What does it say,'' Coughter said, repeating his charge that
the inquiry had been sought by more than 40 Democratic state
lawmakers in Maryland, ``that the only person still facing legal
jeopardy is the only one telling the truth?''
</P>
<P>
   Only one other peripheral figure in the Lewinsky investigation,
Julie Hiatt Steele, has ever faced criminal charges. Ms. Steele was
tried for allegedly obstructing Starr's inquiry of Clinton. But the
jury deadlocked on the charges and Starr decided not to retry the
case.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Tripp's lawyer, Joseph Murtha, said that she would plead
not guilty at her arraignment, which has not yet been scheduled. He
said that Mrs. Tripp was disappointed by the decision, but expected
to be charged.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the White House, representatives of Ms. Lewinsky nor
prosecutors in Starr's office would comment on the indictment.
</P>
<P>
   The county's top prosecutor, Marna McLendon, said the decision
to prosecute followed a year-long investigation into the matter
that was followed by a dispassionate analysis of the facts and law.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that the county had ``never had a case like
this,'' she said that prosecutors had no choice but to investigate.
``Lots of people knew these tapes were allegedly made,'' she said,
adding, ``Prosecutors can't turn away. The public is watching.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McLendon said that prosecutors considered Mrs. Tripp's
possible defenses before concluding that the charges could be
proven beyond a reasonable doubt. But several potential legal
hurdles could seriously complicate the prosecution, like the
immunity agreement that Mrs. Tripp obtained from federal
prosecutors before she agreed to become a witness for Starr.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Stephen Montanarelli, the state prosecutor who
conducted the investigation, acknowledged that the broad federal
immunity grant could pose difficulties for state prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Immunity will be a problem, but we will face it in the
future,'' he said, suggesting that it would be an issue for the
trial judge to resolve.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Legal experts said that a federal immunity deal does not
absolutely insulate Mrs. Tripp from a state prosecution such as she
now faces in Maryland, but does indirectly offer some protection.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McLendon, the top prosecutor in the county in which Mrs.
Tripp resides, turned the inquiry over to Montanarelli, who heads
an office of the State Attorney General that investigates cases of
public corruption and white collar crime cases.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McLendon said Friday that with her decision to transfer the
case to Montanarelli, ``the cloud of partisan emotion has been
removed.''
</P>
<P>
   In interviews earlier this year, Mrs. Tripp said that she had
sought to protect Ms. Lewinsky as a surrogate mother and feared at
times that the younger woman was so distraught about her
relationship with Clinton that she might do herself harm. She said
she betrayed Ms. Lewinsky only to save her from being abused by
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Tripp said in interviews that she made the secret
recordings and the decision to turn the tapes over to Starr's
prosecutors out of a combination of fear and outrage over the
president's conduct.
</P>
<P>
   In one interview she said that she believed that Clinton was
communicating through Ms. Lewinsky ``threats to my life, threats to
the lives of my children,'' an assertion that the White House
officials dismissed as ludicrous.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
