A0460 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-WATCH-ART-$ADV     07-30 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-WATCH-ART-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAY TRADING'S UNDERBELLY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 1) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Texas)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Few, if any, people have ever quit their day jobs to
go to Las Vegas and earn a living playing blackjack. So why have
thousands of people from many walks of life decided to junk their
jobs and trade stocks all day to pay the mortgage and the gas bill?
</P>
<P>
   The question is surely crossing the minds of many who first
learned about day trading on Thursday as the nightmarish story of
the Atlanta brokerage-office shootings unfolded. Day traders buy
and sell stocks by computer many times during the day to try to
capitalize on tiny price movements.
</P>
<P>
   Well before the shocking news from Atlanta, the increasing
popularity of day trading in recent years mystified many Wall
Street professionals. After all, trading stocks profitably is a
mighty difficult business that has humbled even the most
experienced and knowledgeable traders.
</P>
<P>
   Day trading is, first and foremost, an outgrowth of the almost
decade-long bull market in stocks. Because most day traders try to
ride stocks that are rising, if shares were falling, the practice
would be ludicrous.
</P>
<P>
   But day trading is much more than a bull-market phenomenon.
Indeed, its popularity is very much a fin de siecle happening.
</P>
<P>
   Day trading has at its heart two very current American loves:
technology and the promise it holds, and the
do-it-yourself-investing craze.
</P>
<P>
   Who wouldn't like to think that she could beat the professionals
at their own game? And if the pitch is that advanced computer
technology now puts the game of investing on a level playing field
for individual investors, an otherwise skeptical person might warm
to the concept.
</P>
<P>
   But when the day-trading phenomenon ends _ and end it will _ its
legacy could be investor losses exceeding even those taken by
people in the 1987 crash.
</P>
<P>
   What is particularly offensive about many of the firms
specializing in day trading today are their claims to be helping
the small investor beat out the big guys on Wall Street. Make no
mistake: these firms are really in the business of getting clients
to trade, and to pay commissions of as much as $25 a transaction
for the privilege. Whether the trades turn out to be home runs or
debacles is almost beside the point.
</P>
<P>
   In their eagerness to keep day traders active and interested,
regulators say, many of these firms minimize the risks associated
with day trading. Here's what the books, Web sites and gushing
media stories about day trading don't tell investors.
</P>
<P>
   The practice has exceptionally high washout rates. Regulators
who have examined the books of day-trading firms say that more than
9 out of 10 traders wind up losing money. Because most of these
people disappear quietly when their cash runs out, few who replace
them in the trading rooms know about them or their failures.
</P>
<P>
   Securities cops also say that some day-trading houses skirt
margin rules, lending investors more than the 50 percent of the
value of securities in a purchase that is the limit recommended by
the Federal Reserve Board. With the extra money, customers who
would otherwise have their positions liquidated by the firm to
satisfy margin requirements get to keep trading and generating
commissions to the brokerage firm.
</P>
<P>
   But excessive borrowing means that these traders can lose much
more than their original investments if their stocks go down. They
can wind up not just wiped out but deeply in debt to the
day-trading house.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators also say that some day-trading houses ignore
requirements that people who trade money on behalf of friends,
relatives or strangers register as investment advisers. If they
register, they are required to disclose the risks of any investing
strategies they pursue.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators say that such disclosures are not being made by day
traders. Another issue state officials want addressed is how those
people trading for others are being compensated.
</P>
<P>
   State securities regulators in Massachusetts and Texas have
already brought several actions against day-trading firms. And
these probably won't be the last.
</P>
<P>
   ``Day-trading firms have got to do a better job of disclosing
the risks as well as screening their customers,'' said Marc
Beauchamp, spokesman at the North American Securities
Administrators Association. ``Until they do, they should expect
more enforcement actions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
