<SLUG> BC-WWF-NOCHARGES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO CRIMINAL CHARGES IN FATAL FALL OF WRESTLER OWEN HART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE LAMBE  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- Jackson County Prosecutor Bob Beaird
announced Friday that he would not file criminal charges in the
death of professional wrestler Owen Hart.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City police investigated the case after Hart fell more
than 70 feet May 23 while waiting to be lowered into the ring at
Kemper Arena. Hart, 34, died in a World Wrestling Federation show
after a quick-release mechanism on his harness opened.
</P>
<P>
   Beaird said the police investigation centered on a rigger who
set up the stunt and the possible charge was involuntary
manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Beaird said the legal requirement for the charge was
``substantial and unjustifiable risk of death, (and) that such risk
was disregarded, and that such disregard was a gross deviation from
what a reasonable person would do.''
</P>
<P>
   Beaird called the death an accident and said there was no
evidence of a crime. He declined to reveal details of the
investigation or comment on a pending wrongful-death lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was filed in Jackson County Circuit Court on behalf
of Hart's widow, Martha Hart, their two children, ages 7 and 3, and
Owen Hart's parents, all of Calgary, Alberta.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit lists 13 defendants, including the World Wrestling
Federation. Among the allegations was that the quick-release
mechanism was defective and that the stunt was dangerous and poorly
planned.
</P>
<P>
   World Wrestling Federation spokesman Jim Byrne said Friday: ``We
applaud the decision which confirms what we've believed all along.
That is, none of our actions were negligent.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrne declined to comment on the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Robb, attorney for the Hart family, spoke for his clients
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They appreciate the professionalism of the KCPD and the
prosecutor's office,'' Robb said, but ``their decision in no way
excuses the WWF from civil liability. We plan to move aggressively
forward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
