<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-PASTRANA-$ADV01-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLOMBIA'S PASTRANA URGES PATIENCE IN SOLVING COUNTRY'S PROBLEMS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, Aug. 1) 
 
By JOHN OTIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia _ A popular Colombian cartoonist likes to draw
President Andres Pastrana as a pint-sized politician lost in the
folds of a huge suit of clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Fairly or not, this notion that the job is too big for the man
appears to be spreading. As Colombia's civil war intensifies and as
the country's economy sinks, public support for Pastrana, who was
sworn in one year ago this month, is evaporating.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been in office almost a year, and nothing is going
well,'' said Joel Korn, a Colombia representative for the
Inter-American Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a recent Gallup poll that put Pastrana's job-approval
rating at just 16 percent, he was upbeat during an interview last
week with foreign correspondents.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana, a 44-year-old former TV reporter, senator and Bogota
mayor, said that Colombians must not expect quick fixes to problems
that have plagued this nation of 38 million people for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are on the right path, and that's why we are
telling the Colombian people that they must have patience,'' said
Pastrana. ``The truth is that, during this first year, we have
begun to put the house in order.''
</P>
<P>
   After handily winning the 1998 election and taking the oath of
office Aug. 7 for a four-year term, Pastrana set out to polish
Colombia's battered image.
</P>
<P>
   Outgoing President Ernesto Samper was accused of accepting $6.1
million from the Cali drug cartel when he defeated Pastrana in the
1994 election. The U.S. State Department blacklisted Colombia as
uncooperative in the war on drugs, and the Clinton administration
imposed economic sanctions. Foreign leaders shunned Samper and
canceled state visits to Bogota.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana, over the course of 18 trips abroad, has forged close
ties to the Clinton administration as well as with European and
Asian governments. He has attracted billions of dollars in foreign
aid and investment.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in five years, Colombia received full
``certification`` from the State Department this year as a drug-war
ally. And unlike Samper, Pastrana is viewed as honest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, we feel proud to be Colombians, to be able to travel
around the world, and to be received in the White House,'' Pastrana
said. ``We are viewed in a totally different light.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pastrana was elected largely on his promises to direct an
economic recovery and to end the 35-year war against Marxist
rebels. Analysts say the president is foundering on both issues.
</P>
<P>
   To convince the rebels of the Revolutionary Armed Forces of
Colombia, or FARC, to negotiate, Pastrana ventured into the jungle
to meet with the group's reclusive leader Manuel ``Sureshot''
Marulanda. In a goodwill gesture, the Colombian president also
withdrew government troops from an expanse of land in southern
Colombia the size of Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of talking, the rebels have used the demilitarized
zone to launch attacks, run drugs and hide kidnapping victims.
During a rebel raid last month, the guerrillas came within 25 miles
of Bogota.
</P>
<P>
   Such rebel abuses and the lack of any concessions from the FARC
prompted Defense Minister Rodrigo Lloreda, one of Pastrana's most
respected Cabinet members, to step down in May. Hundreds of
military officers threatened to resign in solidarity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pastrana has spent all of his time hugging `Sureshot.' All
they do is pat each other on the back,'' said Pablo Romero, who
owns a hardware store in Bogota.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to negotiate with the National Liberation Army, a
smaller rebel group, broke off after the guerrillas hijacked an
Avianca domestic flight in April and kidnapped more than 100
worshippers in May during Mass at a church in Cali.
</P>
<P>
   Now, support for negotiations is flagging. In a poll of
Colombians by Semana magazine, 68 percent disapproved of the way
Pastrana has handled the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts believe that the government is gearing up for a
wider war, a strategy known as ``Plan B.'' During a visit to
Washington last month, Colombian officials requested $500 million
in military aid from Washington over the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   However, Pastrana claims that there is no ``Plan B.'' He also
said that snags in the peace process must be expected and that
initiatives to end other wars have dragged on for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the Vietnam War, it took two years just to form the
negotiating table,'' Pastrana said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are waiting for are small gestures of peace'' by the
FARC, he said. ``I have made good on my word and on what we have
promised to the FARC. That's why we hope that Sureshot honors his
word and his promises.''
</P>
<P>
   Jaime Ruiz, the government's planning director and a close
friend of the president's insists that Pastrana is convinced that
his government must search for peace. ``But he never said that he
would make peace in one year,'' Ruiz added. ``He is not naive.''
</P>
<P>
   While many Colombians believed all along that the peace process
could turn into a frustrating and drawn-out affair, few forecasted
the nation's deep economic slump.
</P>
<P>
   After decades of robust growth, the economy's Gross Domestic
Product _ the total output of goods and services produced within
the country _ is expected to shrink by as much as 2 percent this
year. It would be Colombia's worst economic performance since the
Great Depression.
</P>
<P>
   Since Pastrana took office, unemployment has jumped to 19
percent from 15 percent, while the Colombian peso has lost
one-third of its value against the U.S. dollar. Romero, the
hardware store owner, said that his sales are down this year by 50
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president knows that people are suffering,'' Ruiz said.
``Every day he asks me: `When will the economy start growing? When
will we see results?'''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the problems, such as a 5 percent budget deficit, were
inherited from the Samper administration and have forced the
government to cut spending and enact other unpopular austerity
measures.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the western coffee-growing region was rocked by an
earthquake that killed more than 1,000 people, left 250,000
homeless and caused $1.5 billion in damages. Colombia also was hurt
by a series of bank failures and the recession in neighboring
Brazil, which provoked capital flight throughout Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pulling the country out of bankruptcy,'' Pastrana said.
``It would be easy to take short-term measures in order to win more
support. But one must not govern on the basis of public opinion
polls.''
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana's economic plan has won the backing of financial
organizations such as the World Bank and the International Monetary
Fund, which agreed last month to extend Colombia a $3 billion line
of credit.
</P>
<P>
   Even opposition politicians say that there are few alternatives.
But some believe that Pastrana should have seen the crisis coming
and complain that he ignored problems at home while spending much
of his time traveling overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem, others say, is that Pastrana has surrounded
himself with close friends rather than naming seasoned politicians
to high government posts. In recent months, there have been rumors
that Pastrana is preparing to sack most of his Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana, the son of a former president, is often described as
being somewhat arrogant and out-of-touch with average Colombians.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the most common errors of presidents is that they lose
contact with reality,'' according to Juan Manuel Santos, a former
presidential candidate. ``They are closed off in a glass house and
only listen to those they want to hear.''
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana admits that his job is turning out to be more difficult
than he expected. But he also says Colombians should take stock of
his performance once he has completed his term in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a difficult time due to everything that is happening
to us,`` Pastrana said. ``But we know where we are going, we have
international backing, and we will move forward. I insist that
presidents should be judged at the end of their term and not at the
beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
