<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV01-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FRONTIERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing)  
 (For release Sunday, August 01, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aug. 1 is the date traditionally reserved for writing about
summer reading, but I suggest that you pick up a thriller instead
of a business book. Myself, I am reading ``Charlotte Gray,'' by
Sebastian Faulks, a provocative novel of England and France during
World War II. ``A Dangerous Friend,'' about Vietnam, by Ward Just,
is next on my list.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as though really good books about business and
economics are hard to find. Edward Chancellor's ``Devil Take The
Hindmost: A History of Financial Speculation'' is elegant and
edifying. And Niall Ferguson's long but lively ``The House of
Rothschild: Money's Prophets 1798-1848'' rests heavy on the shelf.
</P>
<P>
   But I have something else in mind. ``The Frontiers of Research
in Economic Theory: The Nancy L. Schwartz Memorial Lectures,
1983-1997'' (Cambridge University Press, paperback) is not beach
reading, unless you are genuinely curious about where technical
economics is going.
</P>
<P>
   But if you are fortunate enough to belong to a reading group
whose purpose is to stiffen the resolve of members to undertake
somewhat harder tasks, then it is the best thing to come along in a
good many years. Indeed, if you abstain from heavy reading this
summer and invest an equivalent amount of time this fall, it will
stand you in good stead for many years into the future.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Schwartz, fresh out of Oberlin College, spent the early
1960s doing a dissertation at Purdue University on the optimal
scheduling of tugboats and barges along a river with multiple
branches. That may sound kind of tame, until you reflect that such
planning techniques have great practical value in industry. It got
her hired to teach at Carnegie Mellon University in 1964 _ part of
an influx of economic talent that included Robert Lucas, Thomas
Sargent, Lester Lave, and Robert Kaplan, among many others.
</P>
<P>
   Those were the years in which knowledge of mathematical
programming was exploding among scientists and engineers. Amid
great excitement, the new techniques were being applied for the
first time to all kinds of economic problems involving sequential
choices _ even those involving expectations. The painfully shy
Schwartz formed a working partnership with the voluble Morton
Kamien, and together they applied the new mathematical tools to
problems of innovation and market structure.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970 the pair moved to Nortwestern, and a significant part of
the reason the Kellogg Graduate School of Management ascended to
the top ranks of business schools, a rival to Stanford and Harvard,
stemmed from Schwartz's stewardship of its PhD program. Top-flight
economists came and went, but mostly stayed. In 1981, Kamien and
Schwartz published ``Dynamic Optimization: Calculus of Variations
and Optimal Control in Economics and Management Science.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, without warning, and for no apparent reason, Schwartz took
her own life. She was 41. Her friends, led by Kamien, decided that
a distinguished lecture series would be the best memorial.
</P>
<P>
   The first lecturer in 1983 was Hugo Sonnenshein, Schwartz's
Purdue classmate. (Sonnenschein has let it be known that he will
step down as president of the University of Chicago next year.)
</P>
<P>
   In a 1983 talk called ``The Economics of Incentives,''
Sonnenschein surveyed a 50-year difference of opinion about the
provision of public goods. Paul Samuelson had been too pessimistic
about the ease with which sidewalks and streetlights would be
forthcoming, believing that government nearly always must be
involved; Ronald Coase had been too sanguine, arguing that citizens
would nearly always bargain out matters for themselves. Specialists
in the new field of mechanism design would have a field day in the
years ahead, Sonnenshein predicted _ and so they have.
</P>
<P>
   There have followed sixteen annual lectures by some of the
foremost names in scientific economics. Fourteen are collected in
this book. Andreu Mas-Colell on theory of perfect competition;
Menahem Yaari on the role of ``Dutch books'' in choice under risk;
Robert Aumann on the formal possibilities flowing out of the
psychological assumptions known as ``bounded rationality;'' Lucas
on the economics of new ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Also included are Truman Bewley on the differences between risk
and uncertainty; Reinhard Selten on evolution and learning; Vernon
Smith on experimental economics; Gary Becker on the significance of
habits, addictions, and traditions; Robert Wilson on negotiation in
litigation and strikes; Roy Radner on economic survival; Peter
Diamond on the nature of social insurance; Nancy Stokey on the
economics of social mobility; and David Kreps on learning to
cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   None of these essays is what you would call journalistic. Most
contain some mathematics and some contain a lot. Almost all,
however, are written in clear language that will be accessible to
anyone with a fond memory of college-level economics.
</P>
<P>
   The hardest is Yaari's talk about the significance of those
complicated heads-I-win-tails-you-lose contracts known to
speculators as ``Dutch books.'' The freshest is Wilson's essay on
pitfalls in the analysis of signaling. The most recent talks (not
included in the book) have been by Ariel Rubinstein on language as
a bargaining problem and Joseph Stiglitz on bankruptcy and
development.
</P>
<P>
   There is no synthesizing hand at work in this volume, though the
emphasis on the use of the most promising mathematical and game
theoretic tools narrows the focus a good bit.
</P>
<P>
   The invitation list also reflects a determination to showcase
important work somewhat more quickly than usually has been required
to become a Famous Economist _ witness the fact that only three of
the Schwartz lecturers have as yet been awakened by a call from
Stockholm.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Northwestern is pleased. The community of
lecturers ``is like a family,'' says Kellogg school dean Donald
Jacobs who, with Kamien and Ehud Kalai, edited the volume.
</P>
<P>
   I'm satisfied too. But on my Michigan beach, I plan to
contemplate risk and uncertainty, addiction and tradition, in
strictly anecdotal form.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
