<HEADER>
A0477 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOT-ALABAMA-COX     07-30 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOT-ALABAMA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Criticism about Alabama case
 &HT;    By Bill Torpy and Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Capt. Jerry Wynn spent Friday morning crying, dwelling
on the bitter should-haves and could-haves surrounding the 1993
slayings of Debra Barton and her mother, Eloise Spivey.
</P>
<P>
   Wynn, a Douglas County investigator and veteran of many
successful homicide prosecutions, said he knew from the start that
Mark O. Barton was the killer and even compiled plenty of damning
evidence on the suspect. But he said he watched helplessly in
mounting frustration as an out-of-state department with
jurisdiction in the case conducted an investigation he calls
pathetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``They needed seasoned investigators from the start; if they did
so, 12 people wouldn't be dead today,'' said Wynn, who was in a
Texas motel watching CNN when he saw Barton's photo flash across
the screen as the Atlanta massacre was broadcast worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The two dead women ``deserved a better investigation than they
got,'' said Wynn, who works in the county where the Barton and the
Spivey families lived. ``But in rural America, you're not assured
of a proper investigation if there's a homicide. Sometimes it's up
to dirt-road deputies.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael O'Dell, district attorney in Cherokee County, Alabama,
where the murders occurred, called the accusations ``bunk.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I see part of the impetus behind this is Bill Spivey. His wife
and daughter were the ones killed by Mr. Barton. But he was a
strong supporter of Mr. Barton in the early going,'' said O'Dell.
`` If he thinks there's a ton of evidence against his son-in-law,
then perhaps he should find some solace in the fact that his
son-in-law has paid the ultimate price for his actions.''
</P>
<P>
   In September 1993, the two women were beaten to death in a
trailer at Weiss Lake in Cherokee County, a northern Alabama county
with 22,000 residents where the Spiveys were on a fishing getaway.
The sheriff's department overseeing the investigation had just 15
lawmen _ including the sheriff _ and only one detective at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   Wynn and Douglas County Sheriff Tommy Waldrop have a list of
complaints about the Alabama investigation:
</P>
<P>
   _ Wynn said Cherokee investigators called Barton to come to the
murder scene, but then allowed him leave with his car. ``They said
(to Barton), `Don't clean this car.' They did not process it
then,'' said Wynn. ``When they did process the car, it was
spotless.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Wynn said the Alabama department did not retrieve a ``box of
love letters'' between Barton and his mistress that Wynnlocated in
Macon.
</P>
<P>
   _ A company that manufactures Luminol, a solvent used by
detectives to find traces of blood at crime scenes, called Wynn to
say Barton was calling them asking them questions about their
product. Wynn said that lead was not followed up.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wynn said it was he, not Cherokee investigators, who
discovered that Barton had just taken out a $600,000 policy on his
wife several weeks before she was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Cherokee County officials could not be reached for comment
Friday evening on those criticisms. Earlier in the day, O'Dell did
take issue with Waldrop's contention that Cherokee officials
bristled when Douglas investigators called to offer help or
sugestions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we'd call them, it would irritate them,'' said
Waldrop, who said the Alabama investigators did not have strong
emotional ties to the case. ``The victims were just not from that
area. And they had another case they were investigating.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We never blocked anybody; we asked for any help we could
get,'' said O'Dell. ``We took whatever help and information we
could get from any quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   In Alabama, as in Georgia, small law enforcement agencies
feeling overmatched by major crimes like a homicide can call the
state's bureau of investigation. But Alabama state authorities said
Cherokee investigators did not call them for more than half a year.
``We did not handle that case; we did not collect any evidence in
this,'' said Alabama Bureau of Investigation spokeswoman Mary
Hasselwander. ``The Department of Public Safety routinely assists
counties in their investigations. But that is done at the request
of the local authorities.''
</P>
<P>
   Cherokee County did not seek assistance from the ABI until April
1994, said Hasselwander. That request came only after then-Georgia
Gov. Zell Miller asked GBI officials to contact their Alabama
counterparts and ask if they or the Cherokee authorities needed
assistance. Miller had been contacted by Spivey, a Lithia Springs
resident who believed Barton killed his wife and daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Spivey was terribly frustrated because there was no
cooperation between law enforcement there and here,'' said Dennis
Chandler, a former state representative from Douglasville who went
to bat for the Spiveys. ``They made it clear it wasn't Georgia's
jurisdiction.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wynn said that GBI investigators did canvass Barton's home
in Lithia Springs and his car. There were chemical reactions to
blood in the sinks, in the carport and light traces in the car. GBI
spokesman John Bankhead said the agent who conducted those tests
told him Friday that he turned those findings over to Cherokee
County authorities at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Wilson, a Cherokee sheriff's office investigator, said
there was no physical evidence. ``All we have is circumstantial
evidence and that's all we've had from the start. There was nothing
that we could recover (from the crime scene).''
</P>
<P>
   Wynn said Barton was having an affair with Leigh Ann Lang before
his first wife's slaying. Wynn said he talked to acquaintances of
Barton who reported a chilling prediction. ``In June, (Barton) put
his arm around Leigh Ann and said to these witnesees, `We'll be
together by October.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Cherokee district attorney's investigator Danny Smith said he
shared the Georgia authorities' belief that Barton was the killer.
When he talked to Lang at the time, he said,``At the conclusion of
the the interview I told her then, whenever she ceased to fill his
needs, then he'd kill her too.''
</P>
<P>
   Said investigator Smith, ``My personal feelings from the very
beginning of our investigation was that Mark Barton was dangerous
and his potential to kill again was very high. I also felt that his
potential for suicide was very high. As it turned out, both of
those feelings were right.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
