<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anderson talks are going nowhere
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ Jamal Anderson wasn't here again Friday. He
probably won't be here today, and from the sound of his agent, he
might not ever return to the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   With Jim Sims heading to Europe Friday and his client home in
Salt Lake City tending to a concert thrown today by his ``Jam
Entertainment'' company, things don't look rosy.
</P>
<P>
   Sims spoke by phone with Falcons general manager Harold
Richardson at least twice Friday, but had nothing to report.
</P>
<P>
   And as trade speculation continued involving the Washington
Redskins and new rumors popped up involving Miami, Chicago,
Carolina and even Pittsburgh, Sims sounded more disappointed than
he has in weeks.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Falcons coach Dan Reeves said the teams most
recent offer is off the table, and there would be no more
negotiation until Anderson reports to training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Sims said Anderson is not showing up until he is promised a new
deal will be done by the start of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson's not making that promise. It's not clear, in fact,
what he's talking about on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole tone may change from trying to get a deal done to
trying to get a trade done so he can play somewhere in 1999,'' Sims
said. ``I'm not strongly asking for that yet, but I have asked for
permission to participate in any trade discussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, though, it is in the best interest of both parties
for Jamal to remain a Falcon.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said the only team that he had contact with regarding
Anderson was the Redskins. ``(Coach) Norv Turner called me at home
(before camp),'' Reeves said. ``I made it clear Jamal is not
available. I haven't talked to any of those other teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said he hasn't talked to those teams, either.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as Sims departed for a two-week European vacation, he
said Richardson has his phone numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I indicated to them, we're going to be very patient,'' Sims
said. ``This whole deal has very serious career implications for
Jamal. The longer it gets before something is resolved, the more
acrimonious it becomes, and the it doesn't endear the Falcons to
Jamal or Jamal to the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
