<SLUG> BC-FBC-FALCONS31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Picking Falcons was easy for Carter
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ Marty Carter won't be able to look forward to
his mother's meals after home games this year, but the Falcons' new
strong safety is hardly complaining.
</P>
<P>
   An eight-year veteran, he spent the past four seasons playing
for the Chicago Bears, and when Ellen Dunlap would visit, game day
often would be too cold for her. The Windy City, after all, is a
bit cooler in the winter than Carter's native LaGrange.
</P>
<P>
   ``She'd come up (to Chicago) and stay at my apartment and just
cook,'' said Carter, whose half-brother, Dell McGee, is a
cornerback on the Lions' roster. ``It would be 30-below with the
wind chill. When I committed to Atlanta, I called her, and I heard
a `thump.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `What happened?' and she said, `I fell off the sofa.'
She was so happy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons can't help but be happy to have the 6-foot-1,
212-pound Carter, who led the Bears in tackles three of his four
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   He's faster and bigger than former strong safety William White,
who came off the field in passing situations.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, when Carter, 29, was a rookie in 1991 with Tampa Bay,
he chased down former Falcons defensive back/wide receiver Deion
Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a preseason game, and Deion caught a pass,'' Carter
said. ``He thought nobody was near him and he started doing that
strut. I collared him at the 2-(yard line). I love to say I caught
Deion from behind. I've got it on video.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons gave Carter a five-year, $15 million contract with a
$2.6 million signing bonus. In exchange, they get a player who
isn't expected to leave the field in passing situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you replace a guy like William, who did a good job
for us, you're looking for the same kind of leadership and some
sort of (additional) upside,'' secondary coach Ron Meeks said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were getting old, especially at safety with Eugene
(Robinson, who is 36), and William (33). Marty is younger, and he's
a big, physical guy with playmaking ability.''
</P>
<P>
   After last season, when he became an unrestricted free agent,
Carter had just visited New Orleans and was getting ready to visit
Baltimore when his agent, Kennard McGuire, called.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said Atlanta called and had good things to say. He said I
should stop by,'' said the former eighth-round draft choice out of
Middle Tennessee State. ``Coach (Dan) Reeves and (secondary) Coach
Meeks ... made an impression on me.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were a team that ... had the personnel to be a contender
for years to come. Plus, I was so eager to play at home near family
and friends.''
</P>
<P>
   So Carter, who lives in Marietta, never made it to Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, a lot of his family and friends will be able to see him
play. When the Bears played the Falcons last season in the Georgia
Dome, ``I had to get like 74 tickets,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They let me put a complimentary message on the Jumbotron
because I bought so many.''
</P>
<P>
   THE FILE ON MARTY CARTER
</P>
<P>
   _ Position: Strong safety.
</P>
<P>
   _ Height, weight: 6 feet 1, 212 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   _ College: Middle Tennessee State.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hometown: LaGrange.
</P>
<P>
   _ Years in NFL: 8.
</P>
<P>
   _ How acquired: Signed as unrestricted free agent from Chicago
in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
