<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0481 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUICIDE-ATTITUDES-2TA     07-30 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUICIDE-ATTITUDES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVOLVING ANSWERS TO THE WHY OF SUICIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``There is but one truly serious philosophical problem,'' Albert
Camus said, ``and that is suicide. Judging whether life is or is
not worth living amounts to answering the fundamental question of
philosophy.''
</P>
<P>
   Suicide has become more than a philosophical question, however.
This week, Dr. David Satcher, the U.S. surgeon general, declared it
a serious public health threat, with the number of reported
suicides among children doubling over the last 20 years. At the
same time, in Japan, statistics show a record increase in suicide
as that country copes with economic recession.
</P>
<P>
   But some social scientists believe that the apparent increase in
numbers, at least in the United States, is due to increased
reporting with the lessening of social sanctions against suicide.
``We now have an increase because we see depression and suicide as
the result of a chemical imbalance,'' said Howard I. Kushner, a
professor at San Diego State University, the author of ``Self
Destruction in the Promised Land,'' (Rutgers University Press,
1989), a history of suicide in America. ``It's legitimized because
it's biological.''
</P>
<P>
   Social attitudes determine how suicide is reported, Kushner
said, continuing, ``One reason we hear about it in Japan is that it
is sanctioned.'' He was referring to the tradition of hara kiri, or
honorable suicide, when a person is shamed or has failed in his
responsibility to others. Social attitudes can also decide what is
considered suicide, he said: ``Risking your life jumping into a
pond can be seen as suicide or as an act of courage.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether there is an actual increase in suicide or better
reporting of it, attitudes toward suicide are a reflection of moral
belief, medical theory and cultural forces, and they are constantly
evolving.
</P>
<P>
   Suicide remains to some extent a taboo, Kushner said, seen as a
violation of natural law and a mark of shame for the families of
those who take their own lives. ``When people die of suicide, our
reaction is to feel anger, grief, responsibility,'' Kushner said.
``Suicides are seen as judgments on the people left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Such attitudes toward suicide stand in the way of treating
serious depression, said Kay Redfield Jamison, a professor of
psychiatry at Johns Hopkins University School of Medicine and
author of the forthcoming ``Night Falls Fast: Understanding
Suicide.'' ``In the United States, we regard it as a highly
individual act. We tend not to see it as a cause of mortality, as
we do cancer or heart disease. We see it less as an illness than as
a consequence of social and relationship issues.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``History of Suicide,'' the French scholar Georges Minois
traces the way attitudes toward suicide have evolved from the
classical period into the modern world. Suicide seems so deeply
threatening at least partly because it is an assertion of
individual freedom against the power of the state, Minois writes:
``It is an affront to all political and religious systems.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who chooses death and its unknowns displays a total
lack of confidence in the theories, ideologies, beliefs, plans and
promises of all leaders,'' he continues. As a consequence,
``whatever its nature, power seeks to prevent and conceal
suicide.''
</P>
<P>
   There has always been a double standard in social attitudes
toward suicide, Minois says. In ancient Rome, there was the cult of
``the noble suicide,'' embodied in the deaths of Brutus, Cato,
Antony and Cleopatra. But suicide was also outlawed for slaves and
foot soldiers ``because a slave belongs to the owner and he doesn't
own his life,'' Minois, 53, explained in a telephone interview from
his home in Brittany. Slaves in ancient Greece were also prohibited
from killing themselves because they were essential for agriculture
and for the maintenance of the society, Minois said.
</P>
<P>
   The early Christians strengthened social sanctions against
suicide. There was the notion that ``God gave us life,'' Minois
said, and ``man hasn't got any right to take his own life.'' Still,
the Old Testament never specifically prohibits suicide, Minois
noted, only murder. In fact, the Old Testament is littered with the
dead bodies of heroes who took their own life _ Samson, for one,
who brought the palace of the Philistines down on his head as well
as theirs.
</P>
<P>
   It was St. Augustine who once and for all solidified the
Church's prohibition against suicide. The estates of those who
killed themselves were confiscated, and a stake was driven through
their bodies to keep them from rising up and haunting others with
their unquiet spirits. They were buried at crossroads under rocks.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Minois says religion was not the only reason for the
prohibition. The Roman Empire was expanding into a totalitarian
system, and outlying regions were being colonized. The Christian
church's own land holdings had also increased. ``An acute shortage
of manpower dictated the requisitioning of all human lives for the
service of the economy and the defense of the empire,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   Although sanctions against suicide were harsh during the
Medieval period, suicide for ``noble'' purposes was sometimes
glorified, in the case of knights who died in battle rather than
surrender, or in the case of the Christian martyrs.
</P>
<P>
   With the Renaissance came a shift in attitudes. ``It was a time
of great changes in values with the wars of religion,'' Minois
explained, ``the discovery of the New World, changes in economics,
capitalism.'' At the same time, he said, ``the medieval types of
family solidarity were becoming looser and looser, leaving the
individual more and more alone.''
</P>
<P>
   The question of suicide was widely discussed in the public
realm. In 1600, Hamlet asked what is essentially the first modern
question: ``To be or not to be?'' Self-destruction occurs no less
than 52 times in Shakespeare, Minois says.
</P>
<P>
   It is significant, he observes, that the word ``suicide'' does
not appear in English until the 1650s. The creation of a new word
marked the final separation of suicide from homicide, he says.
</P>
<P>
   The Reformation and the Enlightenment brought another shift in
attitudes. Religion itself was being re-examined. For the Deists,
God was not a vengeful figure, and Deism reduced the fear of hell,
making death seem less fearsome. The British historian and
philosopher David Hume even wrote a pamphlet defending the right to
suicide, but at the last moment decided not to publish it. Still,
for the Puritans, suicide was the work of Satan.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1700s, suicide came to be known as ``The English
Malady,'' after a popular 1733 treatise by George Cheyne. England
was thought to have a particularly large number of cases because of
the bad climate and rich food. But Minois argues that the increase
was probably only apparent, due to the expansion of the popular
press and the frequent mention of the topic in it.
</P>
<P>
   The death of the poet Thomas Chatterton in 1770 made suicide
fashionable. And with the success of Goethe's ``Sorrows of Young
Werther,'' in 1774, the story of a young man who kills himself
because of his unrequited love for a married woman, the notion of
Romantic suicide was born. ``The figure of Werther arrived on the
scene just as the question of the legitimacy of voluntary death
reached an emotional high point,'' Minois writes.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, in Europe, suicide was attributed to insanity,
resulting in fewer draconian punishments for those who attempt it
or for the families of those who succeed. The leaders of the French
Revolution condemned suicide, because they saw the individual's
body as the property of the state. Nonetheless, sanctions against
suicide disappeared from the penal code after the Revolution in
1791. In other European countries, however, criminalization of
suicide continued into the mid-1950s.
</P>
<P>
   In 1897, Emile Durkheim tried to find sociological causes for
suicide. People are more inclined to commit suicide when they are
not part of a strong social fabric, Durkheim wrote. At the same
time, Freud put forward a psychoanalytic explanation as aggression
turned inward.
</P>
<P>
   In his book on suicide in America, Howard Kushner describes the
way it was transformed there from a moral problem into a medical
one. This coincided with the rise of medicine as a profession, he
writes, and the substitution of the notion of mental illness for
immoral behavior. Doctors, Kushner argued, in an effort to increase
their power and influence, claimed suicide as a medical problem and
had an investment in saying it was treatable.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Arthur Kleinman, a professor of psychiatry and medical
anthropology at the Harvard Medical School, believes that seeing
depression _ and suicide _ as a medical problem alone strips
suffering of its moral and emotional importance. He cites as an
example the depression suffered by terminally ill people. In the
past, that depression has had a moral and religious purpose, as the
terminally ill look back on their lives, sometimes with regret and
apology to their loved ones for their shortcomings and failures. It
is an end-of-life ``conversation,'' Kleinman said, that has a
healing effect, and brings closure. But today, said Kleinman,
``somehow they are ill with clinical depression.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we should be careful before we label them depressed,''
Kleinman continued. With the medicalization of suffering, Kleinman
said, it is too often simply ``easier to give anti-depressants and
walk away.'' ``Often the most important thing,'' he said, ``is not
the anti-depressants, but that people can participate in the moral
and religious conversations of suffering at the end of life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
