<HEADER>
A0483 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-PENNY-SHORTAGE-ART     07-30 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PENNY-SHORTAGE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GREAT PENNY SHORTAGE OF 1999 HITS NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Ill., Mo., Ohio)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By GLENN COLLINS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The long-maligned penny, kicked about the sidewalks
of New York, disparaged by the ``take a penny'' cups at cash
registers and mocked by the ``no pennies'' signs on bridge and
tunnel tollgates, is enjoying its revenge.
</P>
<P>
   New York is enduring the great penny shortage of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Some city merchants are literally penniless, losing money by
rounding off customers' purchases. A McDonald's in Manhattan is
awarding free Big Macs to customers who bring in $10 worth of
pennies. The Chase Manhattan Bank is offering a 5-cent premium for
every 50-cent roll that customers deliver to the teller's window.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've asked all my employees to break their piggy banks and
bring in their pennies,'' said John Pourakis, manager of a Food
Emporium in Manhattan. ``We're going after pennies any way we
can.''
</P>
<P>
   The shortage, which is being felt in the five boroughs, is a
month old, but has worsened in the last two weeks, said Duane
Fingall, manager of the penny-hungry McDonald's at 51st Street and
Broadway, where those free Big Macs are being offered. ``Every day
at least one person comes in to take the offer,'' he said. ``I even
brought in a jar full of $40 worth of pennies myself.''
</P>
<P>
   The penny shortage ``is actually a penny imbalance,'' contended
Peter Bakstansky of the Federal Reserve Bank of New York. ``There
are plenty of pennies out there, but people are putting them into
bottles. They're just not in circulation.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent study by Coinstar, the nation's largest
manufacturer of self-service coin-counting machines, two-thirds of
Americans do not regularly circulate their pennies, instead letting
coins accumulate on bedroom dressers or piggy banks. Some $7.7
billion worth of change is out of circulation for this reason,
Coinstar contends, with the typical American consumer stashing
about $30 worth of change.
</P>
<P>
   Penny-ante, short-lived penny shortages have recently been
reported in Albany, Philadelphia, Pittsburgh, Chicago, St. Louis
and Cleveland, coin experts say. Now it's New York's turn.
</P>
<P>
   But why now? ``We're not at all sure why,'' said Bakstansky of
the Fed. ``There could be some seasonality to it, leading up to the
vacation period.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Mint will produce 13 billion pennies this year.
According to the Mint, projected coin demand is running 21 percent
above the all-time high of 19 billion coins in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   More than 426 pennies for each man, woman and child in the
nation are currently in circulation, according to the Mint, which
has produced more than 312 billion pennies during the last 30
years, 114 billion of which are now in circulation.
</P>
<P>
   Several factors have contributed to the national pattern of
temporary shortages, experts say. Banks have been encouraging ATMs,
telephone and Internet banking. The booming economy has raised the
number of cash transactions, ``and that's creating a demand for
more change,'' said Dave Herrick, a spokesman for Coinstar, which
is based in Bellevue, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Herrick of Coinstar made some additional points. ``Americans are
increasingly time-starved,'' he said. ``Many don't want to sit at
the dining-room table anymore to count and wrap their coins and put
them in paper tubes, then stand in line at the bank to cash them
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Studies have shown that 75 percent of Americans accumulate all
forms of coins at home, while only 21 percent of the population
puts coins in wrappers and takes them to the bank. It takes 167
pennies to make a pound of coins.
</P>
<P>
   Coinstar has established its machines in 5,900 supermarkets in
38 states. The self-service machines count coins and reimburse
consumers for dumping coins in the hopper, after subtracting an 8.9
percent fee for the service. For the first time last May, Americans
put more coins back in circulation using coin-processing machines
than the U.S. Mint produced, according to Coinstar.
</P>
<P>
   Pourakis, the Food Emporium manager, pointed to his store's
large green-and-purple Coinstar change-counting machine. ``We're
practically tackling customers before they can use the machine, and
asking them if we can buy their pennies,'' he said with a laugh.
``Every penny counts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
