<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BRIEFS-$ADV01-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PEOPLE AND PERSONALITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 1) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., N.C.)   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Behind the Apple Of Many Eyes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Apple Computer's iBook, introduced two weeks ago, has a high
``ooooh'' factor _ the involuntary reaction elicited from some
people when they see a thoughtfully designed product. The person
mainly responsible is Jonathan Ive, 32, a London native who is the
personal-computer industry's leading design rebel.
</P>
<P>
   To Ive, Apple's design director, the term ``generic'' is a
derogatory epithet, and he calls generic design (think beige box)
``the curse of computing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ive came to Apple in 1993, after working on the company's first
Powerbooks as a consultant at Tangerine, a London design firm. At
Apple, Ive gained added stature after Steven Jobs, a design zealot,
became acting chief executive two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's all over it from the beginning,'' Ive said of his boss'
interest in the look and feel of the products.
</P>
<P>
   A notebook cousin to Apple's popular iMac, the shell-shaped
iBook that Ive designed comes in blue and tangerine orange. It has
several other distinctive touches _ a swing-out handle, latch-free
opening and closing and a tiny red light that indicates that the
machine is in ``sleep mode'' by winking slowly, almost like a
heartbeat.
</P>
<P>
   Hard-core nerds may regard such stuff as gimmickry. But Ive begs
to differ: ``As this technology becomes more pervasive _ the
computer more and more a consumer product _ design has got to
matter.''
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Lohr &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Fond and Generous Farewell &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the employees of Thompson-McCully, one of the largest road
construction companies in the Midwest, received notes from Bob
Thompson, the owner, with their paychecks asking them to show up
one Saturday last month, they didn't know what to expect. They
arrived to hear executives say that Thompson wanted to thank them
for their role in building the company, which he had just sold to
Oldcastle Materials for $442 million.
</P>
<P>
   He thanked them by giving each of the 80 or so salaried
employees at least $1 million, and each hourly employee $2,000 for
every year with the company. In all, he gave his 550 employees $128
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask and demand of these people to go out every day and
perform well for me, and I wanted to show them I appreciate their
work,'' he said later in an interview. Sharing the proceeds ``isn't
going to change my life,'' he added ``but it's certainly going to
change theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson founded his company in Belleville, Mich., 40 years ago
with $3,500 of his wife's teaching salary. The new owners say they
plan no layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Among the many longtime employees are Joanne Danlovich, a
$14-an-hour payroll administrator, who received a $40,000 check for
her 20 years. `It was such a surprise,'' she said. She plans to use
some of the money to pay for her granddaughter's braces.
</P>
<P>
   _Andrew Bluth &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a Smooth Trip &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the Mikhail Gorbachev of American Airlines, after the long,
sometimes bare-knuckled rule of Robert L. Crandall as chief
executive, Donald J. Carty is finding that glasnost can lead to
chaos (labor unrest, late flights, service with a snarl).
</P>
<P>
   Even events that seem foolproof have run into annoyances: At a
ceremony in March where Carty announced that Dallas' new arena
would be known as the American Airlines Center, one of the
airline's new Boeing 777s swooped so low over the site, dipping its
wing in salute to those attending, that traffic on a nearby freeway
was snarled and nervous residents called the city's emergency
number.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, however, a news conference to reveal the arena's
design, by the architect David M. Schwarz, went more smoothly (with
no flyovers). Carty was joined by Ross Perot Jr. and Thomas O.
Hicks, the arena partners. American's sponsorship of the arena will
cost about $190 million over 30 years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A State of Incubation &QL;
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina, it seems, breeds not only banks _ including two
of the nation's six largest _ but also bankers. By being named the
next president of the First Union Corp. (No. 6) last week, G.
Kennedy Thompson raised the prospect that two of those six will be
led by natives of Rocky Mount, N.C. (population 56,901). Friends
from there remember Thompson, 48, as a star athlete and
speech-maker.
</P>
<P>
   The other Rocky Mount banking star, William B. Harrison Jr.,
became chief executive of Chase Manhattan, the nation's
third-largest bank, on June 1.
</P>
<P>
   _Todd Cohen &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-99 2101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
