<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: NEW THEME ON JETS OPENING DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In suffocating humidity and sweltering heat, the New York Jets
opened training camp Friday. Lawrence Taylor, the former Giant and
Bill Parcells' embodiment of championships past, was on hand with
support and an assessment: ``This team looks damn good,'' Taylor
said. ``He always says he got nothing, but it looks good.''
</P>
<P>
   The theme of the day for the new Jets' season is the here and
now. The coaching staff sported T-shirts that carried the message:
``Starting Over.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a ring of truth to the message. The Jets are starting
fresh despite enjoying their best season in 30 years in 1998. They
won the AF C East and lost to Denver in the conference championship
game. But Parcells wants to forget those accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in 30 years the Jets begin a season with
tremendous expectations, not simply to make the playoffs but to
reach the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   This is also the first time that Leon Hess will not be on hand
for a new season. The Jets owner died last May, ending 36 years of
ownership. The players will not wear commemorative patches on their
jerseys or helmets. That was not the Hess' style. The Jets' owner
was low key and subtle, steadfastly refusing to call undue
attention to himself.
</P>
<P>
   That made Day One of Jets camp incongruous, perhaps even
troubling for anyone looking for a hint of things to come.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells spent the first part of day responding to questions
about a barroom brawl involving Jumbo Elliott, 34; Jason Fabini, 24
and former Jet Matt O'Dwyer, 26.
</P>
<P>
   The three were arrested on July 9 at a Long Beach, N.Y.,
bar-restaurant where, according to the police, Elliott urinated in
a wash basin in the women's restroom. A woman who said she
confronted Elliott, told the police that the 6 foot 7 inch, 300
pound Elliott punched her in the stomach. According to the police,
Elliott then hit a male patron when he returned from the restroom.
Supposedly 30 officers were needed to subdue the three players.
Three police officers and two others who claim they were injured
are suing them.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells, in his first public comment about the arrest, Friday
sounded supportive without offering support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to him, I always talk to players any number of
times about incidents like this,'' he said. ``I read stories to the
team so that they learn about the pit falls. You can't be
judgmental until all the facts in; you can't be judgmental about
hearsay.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells added that he knew ``some things about this case that
aren't true about this case. Given the circumstances that have
evolved I think he wished he didn't go there.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what effect he thought the incident would have on the
team, Parcells said, ``I have to be concerned about it, but I don't
expect it to be a distraction.''
</P>
<P>
   Who knows what to expect? Who expected this? A grimy, blue-light
type controversy on a team whose ownership status _ after three
decades of stability _ is up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   During the course of a season, events unfold that mobilize a
team, bring a team together. In the past, the Jets never needed a
rallying point _ their history of mediocrity was impetus enough.
Bryan Cox, the outspoken linebacker, said Elliott and Fabini are
the early lightening rods. ``We're all for each other,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are we going to do: Go up to him and say, `Bad, bad boy!'
We've go out and get ready for this up coming season. Guilty or not
guilty, that's not important,'' Cox said. ``It's an `Us against the
world' mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   For decades under the benevolent Hess, the Jets were perceived
as the People's team. Now, perhaps as a result of the episode, the
new Jets' motto is `Us Against The People.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Things could be worst: Dolphins wide receiver Tony Martin faces
a federal trial Aug. 2 on charges of laundering money for a drug
dealer. If found guilty, he could be sentenced to as much as 20
years in prison. In West Virginia, 49ers backup quarterback Jim
Druckenmiller was found not guilty of a charge that he raped a
Virginia Tech student last March.
</P>
<P>
   Now Elliott and Fabini. Leon Hess would not be pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is feeling bad,'' Elliott said. ``If you read the
papers you think I was the Son of Sam or something. The only thing
I'll say is that it was an unfortunate deal,'' Elliot said. I wish
we never went anywhere that night.''
</P>
<P>
   But they did go out and perhaps set the tone: for a season, for
a new era and for a franchise trying start over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
