<HEADLINE>
INVESTNG DIGEST, WITH FUNDS WATCH AND MARKETS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 1) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASD Board Votes For Day-Trading Screens &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Securities Dealers board approved a
rule last week that would require day-trading firms to screen
customers to determine if they are suited to the lightning-fast
trading style.
</P>
<P>
   The firms, which train investors and charge them for on-site use
of their trading systems, would have to decide if day trading makes
sense for a customer, based on his or her financial situation,
previous investing or trading experience and investment objectives,
NASD officials said. The rule must be approved by the Securities
and Exchange Commission. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bloomberg News) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FUNDS WATCH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Investing by a Different Book &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You may know where your mutual fund stands on the fundamentals.
But how does it stand with, say, the fundamentalists?
</P>
<P>
   To find out, log onto Crosswalk.com, a publicly traded Internet
portal company (ticker: AMEN) described by its chief executive,
William M. Parker, as ``a leading host and advocate for the online
Christian community.''
</P>
<P>
   The portal's investing site offers a service called ``the
Investigator'' that will evaluate your fund's holdings according to
``values based'' criteria that have little to do with price-to-book
multiples.
</P>
<P>
   The Investigator, which costs $29.95 a year, rates each security
held by a fund based on the corporate policies of its issuer. Funds
are then graded on a scale according to what percentage of their
holdings pass muster.
</P>
<P>
   Companies can fail the screens for various reasons. The
Investigator says that Johnson &AMP; Johnson makes contributions to
Planned Parenthood, that Marriott International shows adult movies
in hotel rooms, that Time Warner markets ``anti-family''
entertainment and that Bell Atlantic has a unit that offers
benefits to same-sex partners of employees.
</P>
<P>
   So how do funds fare in an environment where market leaders like
Microsoft (described as aggressively promoting ``nonmarriage life
styles'') are deemed unacceptable?
</P>
<P>
   Index funds, it seems, haven't a prayer, because of the wide
range of stocks they hold. The $93 billion Vanguard 500 Index,
failed miserably, with an enormous 41 percent of its holdings not
clearing the values-based screens. But its actively managed rival,
the $100 billion Fidelity Magellan fund, didn't do much better,
with 36 percent of its holdings failing.
</P>
<P>
   But those whose funds fail the test may be able to relax. The
Investigator selects alternative funds with similar one-, three-
and five-year returns, but with lower levels of what it calls
``offensive holdings.''
</P>
<P>
   For Magellan, those funds include Fidelity 50 and Janus
Enterprise. At least one alternative to the Index 500 may leave you
scratching your head: the Smith Breeden U.S. Equity Market Plus.
The fund uses futures to track the index, but holds no stock and is
thus deemed ``pure.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Richard Teitelbaum &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Potentially Costly Lawsuit &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The decision by Louis Navellier, the fund manager, to press a
lawsuit against the independent directors who tried to oust him
from the Navellier Aggressive Small Cap Equity fund in 1997 might
prove expensive _ for either the fund's shareholders or Navellier
himself.
</P>
<P>
   A federal district court jury in San Francisco ruled on July 21
in favor of the directors and against claims by Navellier that they
had wasted the fund's money and breached their fiduciary duty in
their fight to remove him as the fund's investment adviser.
</P>
<P>
   The directors accused Navellier of failing to provide
appropriate information about the fund and replaced him with MFS
Investment Management; Navellier, who contended that the directors
were acting in self-interest, waged a successful proxy fight to win
back management of the fund.
</P>
<P>
   But Navellier then lost the lawsuit against two of the
directors, who are expected to seek reimbursement of legal costs
that could total several million dollars, said the lawyer for one
of them, Paul Finigan. The fight over legal fees, first reported on
Ignites.com, a Web site, could put a dent in the fund's net asset
value.
</P>
<P>
   Total assets were just $37.5 million as of June 30, according to
Morningstar Inc., the Chicago financial publisher.
</P>
<P>
   Navellier's lawyer, Samuel Kornhauser, said that an appeal was
planned and that the directors had no right to indemnification by
the fund. However, of Navellier, he said, ``There isn't any legal
obligation, but I think his position is, if there was any recovery,
he would end up paying for it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Richard A. Oppel Jr. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
