<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARGENTINA-FALKLANDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO RED CARPET IN FALKLANDS FOR ARGENTINES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina _ Before the ink was even dry, President
Carlos Saul Menem called his recent agreement with Britain to allow
Argentine tourists to visit the Falkland Islands for the first time
since the 1982 Falkland war ``the crown jewel'' of his 10 years in
office.
</P>
<P>
   Overjoyed by his self-proclaimed diplomatic victory, Menem said
his daughter, Zulema, would be on the first commercial flight
between Argentina and the Falklands in October. He said he would
soon follow, hinting that he might even make it to the South
Atlantic archipelago before his term ends in December as a
victorious swan song.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, Foreign Minister Guido Di Tella said he
wanted to go. After sending Christmas cards to the islanders in
recent years as part of his ``charm offensive,'' Di Tella said he
had new friends to visit.
</P>
<P>
   But two weeks after the initial hoopla, the agreement has not
turned out to be everything Menem had hoped.
</P>
<P>
   His handpicked vice president, Carlos Ruckauf, has sharply
criticized the pact for obliging visiting Argentines to carry
passports _ an explicit recognition that the archipelago is foreign
soil and not Argentine as stated in the constitution. And the first
Argentine journalists reporting from the islands have written that
many of the 2,400 residents, as a front-page headline in Clarin,
the capital's largest daily newspaper, put it, ``fear a flood of
Argentines.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been several small but nasty demonstrations against
the agreement, including one in which a few hundred islanders
burned an Argentine flag and threw stones at the house of a local
official who supported the negotiations that produced the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the disturbances, the British governor on the islands
gave an interview to Clarin warning high-placed Argentines to stay
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``The atmosphere in the islands is such that it would be asking
for problems and hostility toward the visitors,'' the governor,
Donald Lamont, said. ``I don't want to sound negative, but there
are people with very strong opinions.''
</P>
<P>
   Councilor Mike Summers, who was one of two Falkland
representatives who helped negotiate the agreement, told an
Argentine radio station that Di Tella and Miss Menem ought to
postpone their visits because ``there are still angry feelings in
the Falklands toward the Argentines.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, Argentine officials have let it be known that the
president and Di Tella would probably not be setting foot in the
Falklands anytime soon, even if Miss Menem continues to insist she
is going.
</P>
<P>
   Menem told reporters he may send Tourism Secretary Francisco
Mayorga in place of Di Tella. Mayorga's visit would be a message
that the islanders stand to gain monetarily from better relations
with Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   As some of the most vocal islanders see it, the agreement is a
Trojan Horse that will lead to an eventual Argentine conquest. The
agreement, which does not settle the sovereignty issue, opens
commercial air travel between Argentina and the islands and pledges
Argentine-British cooperation in clearing land mines left behind
from the 1982 war.
</P>
<P>
   A poll published last week in The Penguin News, a weekly paper
distributed in Port Stanley, reported that 56 percent of the
islanders oppose the commercial air link that will bring Argentines
to the Falklands.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina has claimed the islands ever since a British force
overwhelmed a small Argentine constabulary there in the 1830s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
