</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990730.0357 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0508 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOT-LEAD31-COX     07-30 1431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOT-LEAD31-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta searches for answers
 &HT;    By Arthur Brice
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Mark O. Barton's notes of explanation, released Friday
by police, did little to answer the question this city asked itself
through the day as it tallied 13 dead and 13 wounded in Thursday's
shootings: How could one man's torment lead so quickly to so much
pain for so many?
</P>
<P>
   What inner demons would lead a man to bludgeon his wife and two
children in their suburban apartment over a two-day period, drive
to an Atlanta financial district and kill nine people, then take
his own life five hours later cornered by police at a gas station?
</P>
<P>
   According to the note Barton left behind in his apartment, typed
on his personal stationery, he wasn't sure himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was little pain,'' he said about killing his 27-year-old
wife, Leigh Ann, and children, Matthew, 11, and Mychelle, 7. ``All
of them were dead in less than five minutes. I hit them with a
hammer in their sleep and then put them face down in a bathtub to
make sure they did not wake up in pain. To make sure they were
dead. I am so sorry. I wish I didn't. Words cannot tell the agony.
Why did I?''
</P>
<P>
   The note hinted of the self-imposed suffering Barton had been
enduring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been dying since October. I wake up at night so afraid,
so terrified that I couldn't be that afraid while awake. It has
taken its toll. I have come to hate this life and this system of
things. I have come to have no hope.''
</P>
<P>
   For the loved ones of those slain Thursday, the only hope Friday
was that their grief will one day pass. For some of those keeping
watch over 11 shooting victims at four area hospitals, hope was all
they had.
</P>
<P>
   As of Friday night, five victims remained in critical condition.
One person was listed as serious, another as stable, and another in
fair condition. Two victims were satisfactory and one was in good
condition. Two were released from the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators could offer no motive Friday for the bloody
rampage at the two brokerage companies, Momentum Securities and
All-Tech Investment Group.
</P>
<P>
   Neither could Barton's mother, with whom he talked by telephone
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no explanation for tragedy such as this,'' Gladys
Barton said in a statement issued at her home in Sumter, S.C. ``I
have been praying for the victims and their families. Even though I
am deeply hurt by the actions of
</P>
<P>
   my son, Mark, I loved him very much. I wish there was some way
to explain why this tragedy occurred or some way that it could have
been prevented.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Barton's conversation Wednesday with her only child ``kind
of upset'' her and left her worried about her son's mental state,
said close friend Zelma Hutchinson. Mrs. Barton said her son was
suffering from depression.
</P>
<P>
   Although there had been widespread speculation that Barton was
despondent over large stock market losses, officials would not say
that's what caused his murderous rage.
</P>
<P>
   Still, officers at Momentum Securities said Barton lost about
$105,000 during 15 days of trading that began June 9 and ended July
27. All-Tech Investment Group would not release any details of his
trading.
</P>
<P>
   Barton became a customer at Momentum Securities on May 13, when
he submitted a notarized statement in which he claimed a net worth
of $750,000. He said he was earning $85,000 a year as a chemist and
his wife was making $40,000 a year as a store manager.
</P>
<P>
   Both brokerage companies reopened Friday morning, though
employees and others returned to a surreal scene that reminded them
of the horror many had lived just hours earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the buildings, a line of TV satellite trucks were parked
along Piedmont Road in the upscale Buckhead section of Atlanta.
They were kept company by a cordon of police and other security
officers.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, workers were hauling out furniture and other items
damaged in the 40-bullet fusillade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The carpet had been removed from one of the elevators,'' said
Tom Stow, a senior accountant at Hardwick &AMP; Co. at the Two
Securities Centre building. ``I understand why, but it brought it
all home for the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   The carnage even shook paramedics and other officials who tended
to the wounded Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see shootings all the time, they almost seem routine,''
said Reginald McCoy, a paramedic. ``But I've never seen anything
like that ... the volume. It was utter chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   John Rustin with American Medical Response, which sent 10
ambulances to the scene, said he entered the offices at Two
Securities Centre and found bodies scattered throughout.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came in and there were two fatalities to the left, one
critical to the right, one fatality in the hallway, two more
critical and one walking wounded,'' Rustin said.
</P>
<P>
   Some victims were still sitting in their chairs behind their
desks, unable to escape Barton's shooting spree. Others lay on the
floor in an office and a hallway.
</P>
<P>
   ``They looked like they never even had a chance to run,'' Rustin
said. ``It's not a natural reaction to stay in your office when
someone is shooting. They were still in their chairs, slumped over
their desks.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of the wounded asked how their co-workers and friends
were, creating a touchy situation for paramedics who knew many were
dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never want to be false or misleading,'' said William Teet,
a Grady paramedic. ``You have to make a judgment depending on the
situation. An anxious patient can make a trauma situation worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the street in Piedmont Center, Timothy Brazie with AMR
said he stepped into the day trading room to find a man who'd been
shot in the face. He was alive and talking.
</P>
<P>
   Eight of the people slain in Buckhead were men, the other a
woman. The first of them was buried Friday.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 people attended the funeral at Congregation Or
Veshalom for Allen Charles Tenenbaum, a 48-year-old father of three
and owner of a downtown Atlanta grocery store. He was buried
quickly in keeping with Jewish law.
</P>
<P>
   Police continued Friday to try to reconstruct Barton's actions
over the last frantic hours of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the green Ford Aerostar minivan in which Barton killed
himself, police found two handguns _ a .45-caliber and a 9mm, both
used in the shootings. Barton used the .45-caliber weapon to shoot
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Police also found a duffel bag with 200 rounds ammunition, two
more handguns and two pairs of handcuffs.
</P>
<P>
   Barton had purchased the 9mm handgun in November 1993 at a gun
shop in Warner Robins, in Middle Georgia. The .45-caliber gun was
registered to a resident of Richardson, Texas, who has not been
identified.
</P>
<P>
   In light of Thursday's slayings, police also refocused on the
bludgeoning deaths of Barton's first wife and her mother six years
ago in northeastern Alabama. Barton, who had taken out a $600,000
life insurance policy on his wife two months earlier, had been
considered a prime suspect but never was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   In the note police found Thursday, Barton denied any involvement
in the 1993 murders.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be similarities between these deaths and the death
of my first wife, Debra Spivey,'' Barton wrote. ``However, I deny
killing her and her mother. There's no reason for me to lie now.''
</P>
<P>
   Barton settled with the insurance company for $450,000,
according to federal court records. Of that, $150,000 was to be
held by Barton for his children.
</P>
<P>
   After the rest was divided among Barton's lawyers and his
children's temporary guardian, Barton was left with about $194,000.
</P>
<P>
   Many who knew Barton, his children and his second wife described
them as a normal family, involved in Boy Scouts and Brownies. But
the marriage was floundering; Barton and his wife had separated and
filed for divorce.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, it's not known when, Barton made other plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't plan to live very much longer, just long enough to
kill as many of the people that greedily sought my destruction,''
Barton said in his note. ``You should kill me if you can.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the survivors are left to wonder and express their
disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   ``So quick. So fast,'' Atlanta police Chief Beverly Harvard said
Friday. ``So many people all at one time. It becomes even more
devastating because of that. Yesterday this time there were nine
people that were alive and breathing and going about their
business. Today, less than 24 hours later, they're gone _ just like
that. All at the hands of one person, by a deliberate act of one
person.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
