<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- July 30, 1999 -- NY-PENNY-SHORTAGE, 07-30 --
Ray Canales of the Brigandi Coin Co. in Manhattan empties a bag of
pennies from 1957 and earlier. The coins at right are
special-edition steel pennies issued during World War II. (Nicole
Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) MEXICO CITY -- July 30, 1999 -- MEXICO-POLITICS, 07-30
-- Vicenta Hernandez Salgado, 22, who lives in a shantytown, was
invited to the neighborhood PRI office to receive free lottery
tickets, below, before an election in the state of Mexico. She also
picked up subsidized groceries. (Wesley Bocxe/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) MADEIRA, Ohio -- July 30, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 1
-- MEDIAN-INCOME-LIFE-4, 07-30 -- Carrie Jones, 42, supplements her
husband, Tracey's salary with a part-time bookkeeping job, posting
a combined income of $49,700. Their home in Madeira, where Mrs.
Jones is shown playing with their son Neil, 5, is modest for the
suburb. (Mark Lyons/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NORWOOD, Ohio -- July 30, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 1
-- MEDIAN-INCOME-LIFE-3, 07-30 -- Gian Nguyen, 51, and his wife,
Kim, 41, both from Vietnam, eating at home in Norwood. ``We don't
go out to eat,'' says Kim, who with her husband has a combined
income of $49,000. ``We don't travel. We buy clothes on sale.''
(Mark Lyons/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) MT. HEALTHY, Ohio -- July 30, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
AUG. 1 -- MEDIAN-INCOME-LIFE-2, 07-30 -- After getting in over
their heads in credit card spending years ago, Geraldine Frazier
and her husband Carl now have their finances back in order. ``But
if we make a wrong move, the pressure we had from the bills will
come back, and that is painful,'' says Mrs. Frazier, shown in the
kitchen with her granddaughter Tia Berry, 14. (Mark Lyons/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- July 30, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 1 --
THEME-PARTYNIGHTS-2, 07-30 -- At the Punk Rock Karaoke at Arlene's
Grocery on the Lower East Side, people turn out to perform with a
live band, and mingle. As if New York's bars and clubs didn't have
enough singles rubbing elbows and noses, some of them are taking
mating-mixology to the next level: mixer bashes disguised as theme
nights. (Miles Ladin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- July 30, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 1 --
THEME-PARTYNIGHTS-1, 07-30 -- Monday evenings are for bingo at
Luvbuzz on the Upper East Side, one of its quirky themes for
parties designed to get singles out from behind their computer
screens. Patrons are encouraged to fill out ``Luvsurveys.'' Trendy
night spots have been giving singles parties a hipster makeover,
with all the giggly savvy of a generation weaned on too many
episodes of ``The Dating Game'' and MTV's bawdy update, ``Singled
Out.'' (David Corio/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- July 30, 1999 -- BELLY-DANCER, 07-30 --
Christine Berl, composer turned belly dancer, performing at Ibis.
After the commissions and the praise from several reviewers,
including those of The Los Angeles Times, which called her music
``lyrical and melodious,'' and The New York Times, which called it
``affectionately pianistic and yet dignified in its bare outlines
and austere tones,'' Ms. Berl threw it all over to become a belly
dancer in Arab nightclubs in New York, Morocco, Barcelona and
Milan. (Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) UNDATED -- July 30, 1999 -- WARNER-BROS-APPOINT, 07-30
-- Barry M. Meyer, the chief operating officer at Warner Brothers,
is expected to be promoted to the top position at the studio in a
corporate reshuffling following the resignations of Robert A. Daly
and Terry Semel, who ran the film, television and music divisions,
company executives say Friday. And Alan Horn, chairman and chief
executive at Castle Rock Entertainment, a division of the studio,
has emerged as the top candidate to run the movie division. (New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) SANDY SPRINGS, Ga. -- July 30, 1999 -- GA-SHOOT-RDP-4,
07-30 -- Mourners walk to the burial of Charles Allen Tenebaum on
Friday at Arlington Memorial Park. Mark Barton, a chemist turned
day stock-trader, walked Thursday into the office of two brokerage
firms where he traded and fired randomly at traders and employees.
Nine people died including Tenebaum and 13 were wounded. Hours
later, Barton killed himself as police pulled over his van.
(Levette Bagwell/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) WASHINGTON -- July 30, 1999 -- TAX-CONGRESS-2, 07-30 --
Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., talks to reporters as, from second
left, Sens. Paul Coverdale, R-Ga., and Kay Bailey Hutchinson,
R-Texas, look on during a news conference on Capitol Hill. The
Senate passed a $792 billion Republican tax cut today, moving
Congress toward a showdown with President Clinton over how the
nation can best use trillions of dollars in projected Federal
budget surpluses. The Republican Senators urged President Clinton
not to veto the bill. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- July 30, 1999 -- TAX-CONGRESS, 07-30 --
Sen. Frank Lautenburg, D-N.J., talks to reporters as, from second
left, Sens. Max Baucus, D-Mont., Harry Reid, D-Nev., and Byron
Dorgan, D-N.D., look on during a news conference on Capitol Hill.
The Senate passed a $792 billion Republican tax cut today, moving
Congress toward a showdown with President Clinton over how the
nation can best use trillions of dollars in projected Federal
budget surpluses. The Democratic Senators called on President
Clinton to veto the bill. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) KENNESAW, Ga. -- July 30, 1999 -- GA-SHOOT-RDP-3, 07-30
-- Huel Clements, right, of the Cobb Police Department and Acworth
Police Cpl. Curtis Endicott talk to reporters on how they stopped
Mark Barton's van on Thursday just outside Atlanta. Barton, a
chemist turned day stock-trader, walked Thursday into the office of
two brokerage firms where he traded and fired randomly at traders
and employees. Nine died and 13 were wounded. Hours later, he
killed himself as police pulled over his van. (Andy Sharp/Atlanta
Journal-Constituion)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) ATLANTA -- July 30, 1999 -- GA-SHOOT-RDP-2, 07-30 --
Police investigators stand next to Mark Barton's van at a gas
station Thursday evening. Barton, a chemist turned day
stock-trader, walked Thursday into the office of two brokerage
firms where he traded and fired randomly at traders and employees.
Nine died and 13 were wounded. Hours later, he killed himself as
police pulled over his van. (Ben Gray/Atlanta Journal-Constituion)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) UNDATED -- July 30, 1999 -- GA-SHOOT-RDP-1, 07-30 --
Flowers, in memorial for those slain, were left in front of an
office building on Friday where a gunman opened fire killing nine
people. Mark O. Barton, a chemist turned day stock-trader, walked
Thursday into the office of two brokerage firms where he traded and
fired randomly at traders and employees. Nine died and 13 were
wounded. Hours later, he killed himself as police pulled over his
van. (John Spink/Cox News Service Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) PITTSFIELD, Mass. -- July 30, 1999 -- PEPSI-POWER-AISLE,
07-30 -- Here in the Price Chopper supermarket is Pepsico Chairman
Roger Enrico's vision of the future: ``the Power Aisle,'' a large
space stocked with mostly Pepsi soft drinks and Frito-Lay snack
food. Pepsi's hope is that a shopper looking for a two-liter bottle
of Mountain Dew will grab a bag of Cool Ranch Doritos as well. The
goal, of course, is to pump up Pepsi's sales and profits by taking
advantage of some synergies unavailable to its arch-rival, Coke,
and thereby boost its lagging share price. (David Jennings/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) SPRINGFIELD TOWNSHIP, Ohio -- July 30, 1999 -- ADV. FOR
SUN., AUG. 1 -- MEDIAN-INCOME-LIFE-1, 07-30 -- Sean Brandyberry,
25, a data manager, and his wife, Tulena, 24, with Emily, 2, and
Elijah, six months. Though the couple, evangelical Christians,
worry little about material possessions, they have a combined
income of $49,000 and a backyard pool. It came, choked with weeds,
with a rundown home in Springfield Township that the Brandyberrys
bought in an estate sale for $65,000. (Mark Lyons/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- July 30, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 1 --
RICKY'S-DRUGSTORE, 07-30 -- From left, Todd, Al and Ricky Kenig,
whose chain offers a wider, and wilder, selection than traditional
drugstores. ``It's probably not a place that your grandmother would
feel comfortable,'' says Ricky. ``Though we would try hard to make
her feel at home.'' (Billy Smith II/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- July 30, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., AUG. 1 --
NITEOUT-LOEB, 07-30 -- Moby, left, and Damian Loeb on the roof of
Moby's loft. Loeb, a tall, lean and handsome musician, and Moby, a
short, wiry and elflike painter, have been buddies since they met
at a church dance in Greenwich, Conn. Moby was a fledgling deejay,
Loeb a gawky teen-ager too shy to dance. In 1987, they packed up a
U-Haul and headed to New York to find fortune and fame. Now, they
both have. (Aaron Lee Fineman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- July 30, 1999 -- NY-HEATWAVE, 07-30 -- Joshua
Barboza, 4, and his grandmother Edith Perez cool off in a water
spray at the newly renovated playground in lower Manhattan on
Friday. Summer in the city is supposed to be a celebration of
sidewalk cafes and Shakepeare in the Park, of bicycle rides,
barbecues and botanical gardens. Instead, as the hottest July on
record comes to a close, it has become, simply, the season of
sweat.(Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) VALLEY TOWNSHIP, Pa. -- July 30, 1999 -- STONEWALK-COX-2,
07-30 -- Earl Standberry, foreground left, of Pecos, Texas, leads
the charge as he and others struggle to pull a caisson carrying a
one-ton piece of granite honoring ``Unknown Civilians Killed in
War.'' The 33-day journey from Sherborn, Mass. to Arlington
National Cemetery, known as Stonewalk, organized by a group called
The Peace Abbey, has been collecting volunteers as it passes
through dozens of towns and cities. The group is scheduled to end
its 485 mile journey at the cemetery on Aug. 6, the anniversary of
the bombing of Hiroshima. (Rick McKay/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) VALLEY TOWNSHIP, Pa. -- July 30, 1999 -- STONEWALK-COX,
07-30 -- In scorching July heat in rural Pennsylvania, a group of
volunteers makes its way south pulling a caisson carrying a one-ton
piece of granite honoring ``Unknown Civilians Killed in War.'' The
33-day journey from Sherborn, Mass. to Arlington National Cemetery,
known as Stonewalk, organized by a group called The Peace Abbey,
has been collecting volunteers as it passes through dozens of towns
and cities. The group is scheduled to end its 485 mile journey at
the cemetery on Aug. 6, the anniversary of the bombing of
Hiroshima. (Rick McKay/Cox News Service) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- July 30, 1999 -- LUNAR-IMPACT-FLOATER, 07-30
-- An artist's rendering of NASA's Lunar Prospector. Scientists
will crash the craft into the moon's south pole on Saturday in the
hopes of learning more about the moon's polar water reserves.
Aboard the Lunar Prospector is a lipstick-sized vial of renowned
astronomer-geologist Eugene Shoemaker whose ashes will be scattered
when the space craft impacts the moon. After his death in 1997 in a
car crash in Australia, one of Shoemaker's associates at the
University of Arizona conceived of the idea of sending some of his
cremated remains on the Prospector mission. (NASA/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) WASHINGTON -- July 30, 1999 -- TRIPP-INDICT, 07-30 --
Linda Tripp during an interview in February. A Maryland grand jury
Friday indicted Linda Tripp for secretly recording phone calls with
Monica Lewinsky, a key figure in the White House sex-and-lies
scandal, a state attorney said. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BOSTON -- July 30, 1999 -- CENSUS-RACE-ART-BOS, 07-30 --
Norma Rosario, center, her father Alejandro Rosario, left, and
nephew Freddy Rosario inspects a sign that will be in this
weekend's Puerto Rico festival. Rosario, who is of black, Spanish
and Indian heritage, says she will mark ``Latino'' on the 2000
census form. While the decision to allow U.S. residents to choose
more than one race on next year's census survey will give Rosario
and others a chance to select their own identity, the move has also
forced an unprecedented bond among black, Hispanic, and Asian civil
rights groups that fear the change will undermine their political
gains and divide their ranks. (Pam Berry/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) WRENTHAM, Mass. -- July 30, 1999 --
FBN-PATRIOTS-COATES-BOS, 07-30 -- New England Patriots' veteran
tight end Ben Coates during a team practice at the Wrentahm State
School field in June. Coates, probably the NFL's best of his era at
his position, may never see his career fully acknowledged because
he has never been there to speak about it. But his words probably
couldn't add much more to this resume of five Pro Bowl selections,
five straight years of catching 60 or more passes, and the power to
fight off what is usually double coverage to haul in Drew Bledsoe's
passes. (Jim Davis/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
