<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0513 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISS-POLITICS-770(TRI     07-30 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISS-POLITICS-770(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSISSIPPI POLITICIANS TRY TO IGNORE EMBATTLED GOVERNOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By EMILY YELLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA, Miss. _ As tradition dictates in Mississippi
politics, Eddie Briggs, a Republican candidate for governor in next
Tuesday's primary, took the podium for his allotted time this week
at the 110th Neshoba County Fair, a mandatory stop on Mississippi's
campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   In front of a mostly white and mostly conservative crowd of
fairgoers who sat waving cardboard fans in the sweltering heat,
Briggs began by introducing his family. But before mentioning his
own wife, he invoked the name of the current governor's wife. ``You
know,'' Briggs said, ``Mississippi has the best first lady in this
nation in Pat Fordice.'' The crowd cheered.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the remainder of his 10-minute speech, Briggs, the
former lieutenant governor, never uttered the name of Mrs.
Fordice's husband, Gov. Kirk Fordice, a Republican. The other
Republican candidates here, including the front-runner, Mike
Parker, a former Democratic congressman who has since switched to
the Republicans, never mentioned Fordice, either.
</P>
<P>
   That might seem odd, because when he came into office in 1991 as
Mississippi's first Republican governor since Reconstruction,
Fordice was hailed by his party as a forerunner of a new Republican
dominance in the historically Democratic South. But now, as
Fordice's second and final term nears an end, Mississippi
Republicans are working to hold on to the power they gained in the
last decade. And most believe the governor and his well-publicized
marital infidelity and rocky relationship with the state
Legislature and the press are better left relegated to the past.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Leaving behind the darker parts of this state's past is an
exercise familiar to many Mississippians, especially here in
Philadelphia, best-known for the murders of three civil rights
workers from nearby Meridian, Miss., in the summer of 1964.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one of Fordice's first acts as governor was to put this
message on signs at the state's borders: ``Welcome to Mississippi _
only positive Mississippi spoken here.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Even Ronnie Musgrove, the front-running Democrat in the race and
the current lieutenant governor, did not mention Fordice directly
in his speech here.
</P>
<P>
   But among the fairgoers he was a hot topic. Jokes, gossip and
some debate about him flowed almost as freely as the lemonade and
iced tea at this weeklong event, dubbed ``Mississippi's Giant House
Party.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not your standard state fair. During the week of the
fair, which ends on Saturday, hundreds of families live on the
fairgrounds in about 600 wooden cabins, all with running water and
electricity, grouped in neighborhoods. Most of the highly coveted
cabins have been passed down from generation to generation. The
atmosphere is more like a campground full of family reunions, with
a midway, horse racing and political speeches thrown in.
</P>
<P>
   But in an election year, the political speeches always get more
attention here. And on Thursday, when Fordice appeared for his last
speech at the fair as governor, a larger than normal crowd packed
the pavilion to see if any political fireworks would occur.
</P>
<P>
   After Fordice took the stage, he began a dry recounting of his
political achievements. He, too, preferred not to mention anything
about his personal indiscretions. He never referred to the recent
scandal that ensued when he was caught by television reporters at
the Memphis, Tenn., airport in June coming back from a vacation in
Paris with a woman who was not his wife. He then declared publicly
that he was going to divorce Mrs. Fordice and marry the other
woman, who had been his girlfriend in junior high school.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Fordice kept his composure during his speech despite
hecklers in the audience who held up signs that read: ``Paris is
lovely in the spring.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, many who follow politics here do not believe Fordice's
problems will have much impact on the state's Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mississippi was a one-party state for so long,'' said Joseph
Parker, a political science professor at the University of Southern
Mississippi in Hattiesburg, ``that voters still don't hold the
party responsible for the actions of a candidate as much they might
elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Marty Wiseman, director of the Stennis Institute of government
at Mississippi State University in Starkville, said, ``I think the
Republicans will just cut Fordice out of the herd and keep going.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   This week, the Mason-Dixon Polling and Research Inc. poll showed
Musgrove with a comfortable lead among Democrats, favored by 69
percent of those surveyed. His closest rival, Jim Roberts, won 17
percent. On the Republican side, the race was tighter, with Parker
favored by 45 percent of those polled, and Briggs backed by 32
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, published in The Northeast Daily Journal in Tupelo,
had a margin of sampling error of plus or minus five percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   Although everyone expressed skepticism about the polls, Parker,
the political science professor, said there was a good chance that
no one would get a majority of the Republican vote in the primary,
thereby forcing a runoff. He also said it was likely that Musgrove
would win a majority in the Democratic race.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But for Zella Bell Barrew, 87, who sat out on the porch of the
cabin her father built before she was born, the choice was clear.
She announced that she would vote Democratic, as she always has and
probably will support Musgrove.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never did vote for Fordice,'' she said. ``I could tell from
day one that he was no good. But he has a sweet little wife who has
put up with more than any one woman should have to. I could just
punch him, but I can't even stand to look at him.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although Ms. Barrew could not make it to the pavilion this year
to hear the speeches, she might have been interested in Fordice's
closing words to the crowd here.
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``I'm here today to begin, anyway, to close the book on
the public service chapter in my life _''
</P>
<P>
   A few people in the audience began to clap loudly at this point.
There was an awkward pause before the governor added, `` _ and
return from whence I came.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, before walking off the same stage at the Neshoba County
Fair from which John Glenn spoke in his unsuccessful presidential
campaign in 1984, Fordice paraphrased Mission Control's remark to
Glenn as he was launched into space to become the first American to
orbit Earth. In what many believe will be one of Fordice's last
speeches before leaving office, his ended by saying, ``Godspeed,
Mississippi.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
