<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-99 2143EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990730.0369 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0523 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILK-ADS-SFCHRON &LR;      07-30 1735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILK-ADS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MILK INDUSTRY TRIES DIFFERENT MARKETING APPROACHES  &HT;     By CAROL EMERT 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
(begin ital)A wholesome, all-American family sits down to dinner.
But look _ happy, smiling Mom has yellow, rotting teeth! Dad's
smile is riddled with cavernous gaps.
<P>
   A shot of the fridge reveals massive bottles of bright blue
soda, the only foodstuff it contains. Just one family member, a
sweet-faced boy, displays a lustrous smile. But before he takes a
sip of soda, he pulls a set of dentures from his mouth and sets
them on the table.
</P>
<P>
   Got milk?(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   Well, not exactly. What you've got instead is a commercial that
will never see the light of day.
</P>
<P>
   The spot was one of several ad concepts developed earlier this
year by Goodby, Silverstein &AMP; Partners, the award-winning San
Francisco ad agency that has been churning out ``Got Milk?'' ads
for six years.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Wholesome Family'' spot represented a significant
departure from the now-familiar ``Got Milk?'' formula, in which a
man stuffs his mouth full of sweets and then discovers that he is
out of milk. Instead, it conveys a much more serious _ and bold _
message: that soda pop, Americans' favorite beverage, is bad for
peoples' health.
</P>
<P>
   Focus group participants found the script for ``Wholesome
Family'' both entertaining and convincing. Moreover, the nutrition
message seemed particularly potent because research has shown that
most consumers who choose to increase their milk consumption do so
for health reasons.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Nevertheless, the ``Wholesome Family'' script currently
resides in Goodby, Silverstein's circular file, along with rejects
on topics like mackerel smoothies and lactose-intolerant weight
lifters. The story of how ``Wholesome Family'' died illustrates the
hurdles milk marketers face as they attempt to take on the
well-financed soft drink industry.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Effective milk advertising is important because the dairy
industry is in a bind. Per-capita milk consumption in the United
States has been dropping for at least 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   According to research by Strategic Information Group, milk
accounted for just 13.9 percent of nonalcoholic packaged beverages
consumed in the United States in 1996, down from 16.8 percent in
1983.
</P>
<P>
   Soft drinks, meanwhile, jumped from 21.7 percent to 29.6 percent
in 1996, the most recent year for which data were available.
</P>
<P>
   The trend was similar in California until the drop-off
stabilized in 1994, one year after the launch of the ``Got Milk?''
advertising campaign here. Sales data indicate, however, that milk
drinking is beginning to slip again.
</P>
<P>
   Why are people drinking less milk? In a Goodby, Silverstein poll
conducted last November, the No. 1 reason cited was ``a preference
for other beverages.'' (Rising prices, something marketers have no
control over, was second.)
</P>
<P>
   Sodamakers appear to be the biggest beneficiaries, although
bottled water and other beverages are believed to be taking some of
milk's market share.
</P>
<P>
   Script Makes the Rounds
</P>
<P>
   Only a small percentage of ``Got Milk?'' ad ideas ever make it
onto the air. All TV commercials must pass through several hoops
before going into production, but regulated commodities face extra
hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   First, the milk scripts are vetted by the 10 directors of the
California Fluid Milk Processor Advisory Board. (The $25 million in
annual ``Got Milk?'' ad spending comes from a milk levy paid by
California processors. A separate, federally mandated Milk Mustache
campaign is funded by processors across the country.)
</P>
<P>
   In the case of ``Wholesome Family,'' processors ``loved the ad
because it's competitive'' with soda, said Jeff Manning, the
board's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   But the ad encountered fatal stumbling blocks at the next two
stages of the process, the California Department of Food and
Agriculture and the national television networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel the approach implying that soda rots teeth is unfairly
disparaging and not acceptable,'' said one network, ABC, in a
rejection letter to Goodby, Silverstein. ``We also feel the
depiction of people with horribly rotten teeth may prove offensive
to many of our viewers.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, ABC guidelines forbid any depiction of dentures,
the network noted.
</P>
<P>
   CBS' rejection letter read, in part, ``It is unacceptable to
suggest, however humorously, that drinking soda will cause one's
teeth to rot and fall out.''
</P>
<P>
   Data Demanded
</P>
<P>
   The networks also demanded data to support the contention that
soda is bad for teeth _ a request that seems absurd since dentists
have been warning Americans about soda for years.
</P>
<P>
   But Bess Cocke, Goodby, Silverstein's broadcast liaison, said
the networks' response to ``Wholesome Family'' was not unusual.
</P>
<P>
   Every advertising claim, from a whiter, brighter bleach to a
safer automobile, must be backed up with hard evidence. Each
network operates an internal research department to review such
data.
</P>
<P>
   Theoretically, network affiliates can have their licenses pulled
and networks can be sued for running a false advertising claim,
although such cases are extremely rare.
</P>
<P>
   But while the networks' concerns weren't unexpected, their
rejection of ``Wholesome Family'' raised suspicions among the milk
marketers that other factors were at play.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the ad in question insults a product category, soft
drinks, that spends an estimated $1.3 billion a year on
advertising. That's more than 10 times as much as &UR;  &LR; milk.
</P>
<P>
   And the networks accepted another ``Got Milk?'' spot, ``Bones,''
that also contained a health claim _ but which did not insult soda.
In ``Bones,'' the arms of a calcium-deficient man, a nonmilk
drinker, break off when he attempts to lift a heavy wheelbarrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's be clear that Coke and Pepsi spend a ton of money on TV
advertising,'' said Rick Kurnit, a partner with Frankfort, Garbus,
Klein &AMP; Selz in New York. ``Networks have a First Amendment right
to choose whether an ad will run or not, and they don't have to run
something they think will hurt their business.''
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, although soda is widely considered harmful to tooth
enamel, it isn't necessarily true that people who drink soda have
worse teeth than people who drink only milk, Kurnit added.
(Toothpaste is a big advertiser, too, after all.)
</P>
<P>
   Evidence Needed
</P>
<P>
   Spokespeople for CBS and ABC declined to comment. One network
executive, however, said his company needs ``hard evidence'' to
back up health claims, and ``Wholesome Family'' ``sort of went
overboard'' in its denigration of soda. (NBC rejected the ad with
no comment.)
</P>
<P>
   Another obstacle was the disgusting visuals in ``Wholesome
Family.'' The last thing TV executives want is for viewers to
change channels because they were repulsed by an ad. But networks
sometimes allow such subject matter if it looks sufficiently
cartoonish and unrealistic.
</P>
<P>
   Fox Network, in fact, accepted ``Wholesome Family'' on condition
that it be shot ``in an over-the-top, comical fashion,'' said
Cocke. And all of the networks have run a ``Got Milk?'' ad in which
a TV chef who eats a hot pepper (but runs out of milk) incinerates
in front of his studio audience.
</P>
<P>
   Goodby, Silverstein had one more card to play with the networks.
Executives there could have argued that the ad was simply ``a
humorous illustration of a truism'' about milk and should not be
taken as a serious claim, said Kurnit.
</P>
<P>
   That was the strategy used by Wendy's many years ago when
MacDonald's and Burger King challenged its ``Where's the Beef?''
ad. Wendy's rivals claimed the ad was misleading because it
depicted their product as a minuscule patty dwarfed by an enormous
bun.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, ``All Wendy's had to prove is that their patty
was a little bigger'' than its rivals, said Kurnit. That was the
real point of the ad, although the point was made through
exaggeration.
</P>
<P>
   The milk marketers opted not take this tack with the networks,
however, for one reason: The ad had already died at the hands of
the California Department of Food and Agriculture, which oversees
all advertising funded by state commodity programs.
</P>
<P>
   Protection of Law
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, California law forbids commodity board-funded
advertising from disparaging other agricultural products, like
orange juice. But the department interprets the law to include any
agricultural derivative, including sweeteners or other ingredients
that might be found in soda.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're obligated to be fair to all commodities,'' said
department spokesman Oscar Hidalgo.
</P>
<P>
   The agriculture department was also concerned that the health
claims in ``Wholesome Family'' could not be substantiated, and
Manning allowed as much.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably could have found a study showing that if you leave
a tooth in a glass of soda it will rot, but it's also true that
there are billions of people who drink soda who have perfectly fine
teeth,'' Manning said.
</P>
<P>
   Producing the spot would have cost the processor board $400,000
to $500,000. At the same time, ``I would probably give it a 50
percent chance of being pulled in the first month,'' said Manning.
``If I felt better about the substantiation, we would have fought
for it, but I just don't think dental is the way to fight soda.''
</P>
<P>
   Continuing the Fight
</P>
<P>
   Manning still believes an anti-soda message could be effective
if the right script comes along. Part of the problem is finding a
plot that will pass muster with milk ads' many reviewers and still
be a hit with audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Other anti-soda scripts have been rejected before they even got
to the networks because they didn't go over well in focus groups.
One, for example, showed soda being poured over breakfast cereal.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Goodby, Silverstein is preparing three more ads in the
conventional mold, focusing on the partnership between milk and
sweets. A fourth spot, ``Y2Cud,'' which will appear on TV this
fall, takes a different approach, but does not broach the topics of
soda or health.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the milk versus soft drink battle is being waged in a
small way elsewhere. Another marketing group, the California Milk
Advisory Board, has spent more than $1 million sponsoring
extreme-game exhibitions at county fairs.
</P>
<P>
   But there won't be any anti-soda ``Got Milk?'' ads for the
foreseeable future. ``Someday, somehow we will take a shot at soda,
but (``Wholesome Family'') just wasn't the spot,'' said Manning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-99 2144EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
