u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-BOTTLE-LAW-BOS &LR;      07-30 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-BOTTLE-LAW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE BOTTLE LAW SHOWING CRACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The state's 17-year-old bottle deposit law is starting
to show signs of breakdown, and none of the repair options look
particularly attractive for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   A state-funded study indicates that the handling fee of 2.25
cents per container that is paid to redemption centers and
retailers is not enough to cover their costs.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to deal with the redemption center problem,
according to the study, is to allow centers to pay consumers 4
cents for returned bottles and cans rather than the full 5-cent
deposit. The study did not address whether retailers should be
allowed to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts residents may also be losing interest in recycling
bottles and cans. Using preliminary numbers, the study said the
recycling rate for bottles and cans plunged last year from just
under 80 percent in 1997 to 69.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   State officials said they plan to use the study to fashion
improvements to the bottle-deposit law. But retailers and beverage
industry officials long opposed to the law asked whether it makes
sense to invest more money in what they considered a bad system.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best option for us is to get rid of the stupid thing,''
said Christopher Flynn, president of the Massachusetts Food
Association, which represents the state's supermarket industry.
``Does it make sense to throw millions of dollars more at a system
that is addressing only 1.5 percent of the state's waste stream?''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Massachusetts Public Interest Research Group,
which led the fight for the original deposit law and is pushing to
expand its reach to water and juice containers, said the law is the
most successful recycling law in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``As such, it's worth saving and indeed expanding,'' said Paul
Burns, Masspirg's environmental attorney. Burns described the
changes needed to fix problems with the existing law as ``minor
adjustments.''
</P>
<P>
   The new study, ordered by the Legislature and conducted by DSM
Environmental Services of Ascutney, Vt., concluded that redemption
centers were telling the truth in recent years when they complained
that they were being driven out of business by inadequate handling
fees. The number of redemption centers has fallen from 250 in 1995
to 130 today.
</P>
<P>
   The study said the average actual cost of handling a container
at a redemption center is 2.57 cents per container. That's only
0.32 cents above the current compensation rate. Given the huge
volumes involved, the losses can accumulate to more than $1 million
a year for an average-size redemption center.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers have even higher costs, according to the study, but
they can offset them in other areas of their businesses. The study
offered limited retailer data, but two supermarket chains with
fairly sophisticated processing systems reported costs of 3.4 cents
and 6.8 cents per container.
</P>
<P>
   The study said redemption centers, which accept all brands of
containers in any quantity, play a crucial behind-the-scenes role
in bottle and can recycling. They handle an estimated 39 percent of
all returns and cater to people who return large quantities. If
redemption centers continue to fail, the report said, recycling
rates will fall and retailers and beverage distributors will be
faced with higher costs.
</P>
<P>
   The study said the least expensive way to stop the decline of
redemption centers would be to allow them to pay consumers 4 cents
instead of 5 cents for every returned container.
</P>
<P>
   This approach would not add new costs to the system. DSM surveys
also indicated that 87 percent of those returning containers to
redemption centers probably would continue to do so even at the
lower rate, partly out of convenience and because in many cases
they recovered the containers from the trash and didn't pay the
initial 5-cent deposit. Those who want the full deposit could still
return the container to a retailer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paying less than 5 cents potentially starts the Commonwealth
down a slippery slope where the value of deposit containers is
significantly diminished and with it the value of returning
containers,'' the report noted. But the report said that already
may be happening, since the 5-cent deposit has remained unchanged
since 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Burns said giving consumers only 4 cents back would shake
confidence in the bottle-deposit system. Robert Renzi, co-owner of
Bottle Bill's Redemption Center in Framingham, called the proposal
``bad for consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Several redemption centers already are paying out 4 cents. The
state attorney general's office filed suit against them, but a
judge recently denied a request for a preliminary injunction. A
spokeswoman for the attorney general's office said she didn't know
the current status of the case.
</P>
<P>
   Other options considered in the report included raising the
handling fee to as high as 3 cents or allowing redemption centers
to charge a higher handling fee to beverage distributors who don't
pick up their empty containers. Both options, according to the
report, would increase the costs of beverage distributors by $2.2
million to $11.2 million and could force an increase in beverage
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Burns was skeptical that price increases would result. ``It's
possible that they might do that,'' he said of distributors. ``It's
also possible they might see the need to compete in the marketplace
and take the money out of their profits.''
</P>
<P>
   State officials said another option would be to use a portion of
unclaimed deposits to shore up the deposit system. The state
currently gets all unclaimed deposits and uses the money for
environmental programs. Total unclaimed deposits are expected to be
$25 million this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-99 2145EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
