<HEADER>
A0525 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN     07-30 0308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMOLINSKI SIGNS ONE-YEAR CONTRACT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Los Angeles Kings general manager Dave Taylor shortened his list
of free agents by one Friday as newly acquired center Bryan
Smolinski agreed to terms on a one-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   Smolinski, 27, accompanied Zigmund Palffy to the Kings in last
month's eight-player trade with the New York Islanders, and can be
penciled in as the Kings' second-line center behind Jozef Stumpel.
</P>
<P>
   After a mediocre 1998-99 season in which he produced only 40
points, Smolinski, a restricted free agent, agreed to the Kings'
qualifying offer, and receives a contract worth about $1.75
million, the same amount he made last season. Smolinski will be a
restricted free agent again in one year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Acquiring Bryan was very important to us when we made our deal
with the Islanders,'' Taylor said. ``He is a proven NHL scorer who
will add a lot of offense to our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Smolinski has played six seasons in the NHL, for the Islanders,
Pittsburgh Penguins and Boston Bruins, producing 289 points in 444
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am ecstatic,'' Smolinski said. ``My wife and I are thrilled
to be coming to Los Angeles. I have already bought a house there
and I am really excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Five weeks remain until the Sept. 5 start of training camp, and
Taylor has several more restricted free agents to sign, most
notably defenseman Mattias Norstrom, right wing Glen Murray and
goalie Stephane Fiset. These negotiations may be considerably
trickier than the swift resolution with Smolinski.
</P>
<P>
   Also unsigned is defenseman Aki Berg, who played last season in
his native Finland after a contract impasse with the Kings, and is
threatening to do so again this year.
</P>
<P>
   The season begins Oct. 2 in Nashville.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-99 2145EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990730.0372 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0526 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIANWELLS-CHAPTER11     07-30 0463
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIANWELLS-CHAPTER11-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 INDIAN WELLS WATER CO. GOES UNDER  &HT;     By PETER SINTON 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO _ Indian Wells Water Co., the Sonoma, Calif., startup
that had ambitious plans to market bottled water for the benefit of
American Indians, announced Friday that it has pulled the plug and
is filing for protection under Chapter 11 of the Bankruptcy Code.
<P>
   When The Chronicle wrote about the company in March, CEO Jim
Stevens, a veteran of Perrier and Coca-Cola, was enthusiastic about
the company's plans to carve a niche in the $4.3 billion U.S.
bottled water market.
</P>
<P>
   It was going to do this by tapping springs and building bottling
plants on tribal lands, hiring local residents and returning
profits to American Indians.
</P>
<P>
   The Mille Lacs Band of Minnesota's Ojibwe tribe also was excited
about the idea. It invested $10 million for a 10 percent stake in
Indian Wells, and five other tribes, including the Washoe near
Carson City, were developing springs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal,'' said Brian McCarthy, who was company president at
the time of the interview, ``is to help American Indians develop a
new economic template besides casinos.''
</P>
<P>
   After the first story was published, The Chronicle ran a second
article after it learned that McCarthy had led several previous
ventures that failed. These included an earlier version of Indian
Wells, another Bay Area water company called Watermark and a real
estate partnership named Brichard &AMP; Co. After theses disclosures,
Indian Wells said it was ``re-evaluating the role'' of McCarthy.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, Indian Wells hired BKS International Business
Consultancy in San Francisco to assess its prospects. BKS principal
Brian Service said that after conducting a study with New York's
Beverage Marketing Corp., it was determined that ``competitive
pressures in the rapidly consolidating bottled water business made
it impossible for Indian Wells to become a profitable venture and
it should cease operations.''
</P>
<P>
   Service, who has been hired as interim manager of Indian Wells,
said the company plans to meet all its financial obligations to its
trade partners. However, he said he did not know how much of the
$10 million invested by the Milles Lacs, some of it still in
escrow, could be returned to the tribe.
</P>
<P>
   Indian Wells' officers and directors reportedly are resigning
from the company and none of them could be reached for comment
yesterday. Neither could tribal investors.
</P>
<P>
   Service said allegations against McCarthy were not important
factors in Indian Wells' demise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very competitive market,'' said Don Saccani, whose
company distributed Indian Wells in Marin. ``Sales were only fair _
nowhere near the penetration of Calistoga or Crystal Geyser.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
