<HEADLINE>
CASE STRENGTHENS FOR PILOT ERROR IN KENNEDY CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The wreckage of John F. Kennedy Jr.'s airplane has shown no sign
of mechanical or structural failure, making it almost certain that
pilot error caused the crash that killed him, his wife and his
sister-in-law, according to a high-ranking aviation source familiar
with the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   While the NTSB has said it will be months before a precise
determination can be made into the cause of the crash,
investigators are still waiting to determine if the plane's radio,
avionics and selected cockpit instruments were working.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kennedy was not licensed to fly using instruments alone.
And, as a pilot, he should not have flown in weather conditions
that required him to fly by continually scanning the gauges on the
cockpit panel, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter if the instruments weren't working because
legally he could not rely on them alone to fly the airplane,'' said
a high-ranking federal aviation official familiar with the
investigation, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are looking to hang your (investigation) out on the
instruments being bad, you can't because he was not approved to
rely on them,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy had his private pilot's license for more than a year,
had accumulated about 300 hours of flight time, and was studying to
become an instrument-rated pilot.
</P>
<P>
   But under his license, Kennedy was a visual-flight-rules pilot,
meaning he could only fly by what he could see, and was grounded
when visibility was less than three miles and the cloud ceiling
lower than 1,000 feet. Such conditions can cause even experienced
pilots to become disoriented and lose control of the airplane.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the plane's automatic pilot was broken, the source said,
Kennedy should have maintained control of the airplane and kept
track of the environment around him so that if weather
deteriorated, or he flew into an area of poor visibility, he could
head back to clearer air.
</P>
<P>
   The source also said the preliminary investigation into the
cockpit instruments has yet to find one not working.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the vacuum pump, which drives the attitude
indicator, a gauge which enables instrument pilots to keep the
wings level, was functional, the source said. The attitude
indicator, which is designed to mimic the position of an aircraft's
wings in relation to the horizon, is crucial to maintaining control
of the airplane when the horizon is obscured.
</P>
<P>
   In its announcement Friday, the NTSB said Kennedy had received
an Internet weather briefing at about 6:30 the night of the
accident for conditions from New Jersey to Cape Cod. The flight
left Essex County Airport in Caldwell, N.J., at 8:38 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy was headed to Martha's Vineyard to drop off his
sister-in-law, Lauren Bessette. He and his wife were then expected
to fly to Hyannis Port for his cousin Rory Kennedy's wedding.
</P>
<P>
   ``The report was for good VFR (visual flight rules) weather,
visibility 6 to 8 miles,'' the NTSB statement said. There were no
significant weather advisories along the route, and ``all airports
along the route of flight reported visual meteorological
conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   However, pilots who had flown over Long Island Sound that
evening reported after the accident that the in-flight visibility
over the water ``was significantly reduced,'' according to the NTSB
statement, which noted that interviews of those pilots will
continue.
</P>
<P>
   Several radar tapes indicate Kennedy flew along the southern
Connecticut shore and turned right, over the ocean, at Westerly,
R.I., for Martha's Vineyard. That turn began a track of more than
40 miles across open water.
</P>
<P>
   Flying on a heading to Martha's Vineyard, Kennedy's plane
descended from 5,600 feet to 2,300 feet, and then veered off course
to the right, when he was about 18 miles from the airport. The
course was corrected, but the plane turned to the right again and
began to dive toward the Atlantic at a rate in excess of 5,000 feet
per minute.
</P>
<P>
   The maneuver, aviation sources said, is indicative of a pilot
who has lost awareness of his flight situation and is suffering
from spatial disorientation, which makes it difficult _ if not
impossible _ to recover from such a dive.
</P>
<P>
   It took about 30 seconds for Kennedy's plane _ which was at a
relately low altitude _ to go from controlled, even flight to
slamming into the water.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB said Friday that the Navy salvage ship USS Grasp
recovered about 75 percent of the fuselage of Kennedy's plane from
the ocean floor about 7 1/2 miles from Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Included in the recovered wreckage was approximately 80
percent of the left wing, 60 percent of the right wing, the engine
and propeller, and the cockpit instrument panel,'' the NTSB said.
``Examination . . . has revealed no evidence of an in-flight
break-up or fire, and no indication of pre-impact failure to the
airframe.''
</P>
<P>
   The recording device on board the airplane, as first reported by
The Boston Globe, was recovered. But the force of the impact
destroyed it, and investigators could not determine if it had been
operating, a source said.
</P>
</TEXT>
