<HEADLINE>
UMPIRES PLAN UNFAIR LABOR CHARGES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Richard Phillips, the head of the major league umpires union,
spent an intensive day Friday preparing unfair labor practice
charges the union plans to file with the National Labor Relations
Board early next week.
</P>
<P>
   The NLRB will be the second front the union opens in its fight
to restore the jobs of 22 of its members. Earlier this week the
union filed a lawsuit in U.S. District Court in Philadelphia trying
to prevent the loss of those jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips did not return telephone calls seeking comment on the
charges he plans to file with the NLRB, but in discussing the
umpires' plight Thursday night, he accused Major League Baseball of
blatantly bad behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a definite charade in baseball today,'' he said.
``I'm not going to go into it any further. We're working together
with Bruce Simon, who is a very experienced labor counsel from New
York, on this and we have a single purpose in mind. That purpose is
to make certain the things that have happened in baseball find the
sunlight in the light of day.''
</P>
<P>
   Commenting specifically on the National League's acceptance of
the resignations of 13 umpires earlier that day, the lawyer said,
``I think today they have served up probably the most blatant
unfair labor practice that I have ever seen. I have been practicing
for 33 years. I've never seen anything like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Other labor experts, however, have questioned Phillips' strategy
in having the umpires resign en masse. That act, the experts have
said, gave baseball officials the right to accept any of the
resignations they chose, effective Sept. 2, the date stated in the
letters. ''Once you sign it and send it,'' one person with vast
union experience said Friday, ``you now assume to be someone who
will be an ex-employee on the effective date. You're not even
guaranteed being an employee until that time. Even if the employer
doesn't respond by saying I accept your resignation, it is still an
effective resignation and nothing you do can change that without
the permission from the one you resigned from.''
</P>
<P>
   Some labor people said they couldn't understand why Phillips
faxed the resignation letters to the league offices the day after
more than 50 umpires signed them. They said Phillips could easily
have held them, and whatever his strategy was, used the letters for
that purpose.
</P>
<P>
   By submitting them to the league offices, he put them in the
hands of the league presidents, giving them the right and the
opportunity to accept as many and whichever resignations they
wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Two umpires who have opposed Phillips' strategy have said they
gained the impression at the July 14 meeting that the union was
going to hold the letters and not send them to the league offices.
</P>
<P>
   They said they were shocked the next day when they learned that
the letters had been sent. After receiving the letters, the
American League hired 12 minor league umpires and the National
League hired 13. The AL then accepted the resignations of the nine
umpires who did not revoke their resignations.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-two NL umpires withdrew theirs last Tuesday, but because
the league had already hired 13 new umpires, it accepted the
resignations of the like number of staff umpires Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
