<SLUG> BC-MA-HARSHBARBER-CAUSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-AG HARSHBARGER TO HEAD   COMMON CAUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL CROWLEY AND ANNE E. KORNBLUT AND  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Having built a career on political ethics and
government reform, former Massachusetts Attorney General Scott
Harshbarger is about to pursue those goals full-time as president
of Common Cause.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger, who won the 1998 Democratic gubernatorial
nomination but lost the November general election, was elected
president of the Washington, D.C.-based nonprofit organization
Friday and will begin his new job in September.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger has been mandated with reinvigorating the
29-year-old organization, a self-described ``nonpartisan citizens'
lobbying group'' that advocates campaign finance reform, government
ethics, and grassroots political participation.
</P>
<P>
   The organization has a membership of more than 200,000 and an
annual budget of about $10 million, but its influence and relevance
have waned in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been specifically asked to broaden the agenda of Common
Cause,'' Harshbarger said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal here is to try to shape this third force representing
the public interest in a far more powerful way, to overcome the
incredible cynicism'' directed toward government, Harshbarger said.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger has long been a good-government reformer, dating
back to his tenure as general counsel for the Massachusetts Ethics
Commission from 1978 to 1980.
</P>
<P>
   He was elected attorney general in 1990 and served two terms
before narrowly losing his gubernatorial bid to Paul Cellucci in
November.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger replaces Ann McBride, who left Common Cause in May.
Common Cause board chairman Derek Bok praised McBride's tenure
Friday, but he said the organization had become too narrowly
focused on winning campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``Campaign finance reform is going to remain a very important
part of the agenda, but I think it perhaps became too dominant, and
maybe we didn't make it clear enough that campaign finance reform
is a means to an end,'' Bok said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In addition to trying to introduce important reforms, we need
to be working on the broader fundamental task of getting Americans
excited about how their democracy works.''
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear Friday what Harshbarger's new post bodes for his
political future. Though many Democratic activists were frustrated
by his 1998 campaign, Harshbarger had explored the possibility of a
comeback in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Harshbarger said he made no promises to the Common Cause
board about his political intentions.
</P>
<P>
   But he added that ``at this point in time, elected office is the
last thing on my mind.'' And Common Cause board members said
Harshbarger had assuaged their concerns that he might see the job
as a stepping stone to political office.
</P>
<P>
   While some saw Harshbarger's move to Washington as a sign that
he was withdrawing from the Massachusetts political arena, others
said the new position was an opportunity for Harshbarger to
refurbish his image here.
</P>
<P>
   ``This certainly does not foreclose any of his political
options. If anything, it gives him a bigger platform,'' said
longtime Harshbarger aide Ed Cafasso.
</P>
<P>
   ``The signal here is that he's not prepared to be mothballed.''
</P>
<P>
   Some board members wondered whether a partisan former elected
official might endanger Common Cause's reputation for independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only concern among some members was having a politician in
the job,'' said one source familiar with the organization's search
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unusual for Common Cause, particularly to have someone
who ran for office so recently. Common Cause prides itself on being
a nonpartisan organization that works in a bipartisan way,'' the
source said.
</P>
<P>
   But Harshbarger said having a former elected official at the
helm would bring the group credibility with other politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Harsharger said that he will be in Washington ``full-time'' to
run Common Cause, but that he will commute regularly to Boston.
Harshbarger still plans to teach a course at Harvard Law School
this fall, and he will maintain his affiliation with Northeastern
University, where he teaches criminal law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
