<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVIS-ADCAMPAIGN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 LEVI'S TURNS TO TV SEX, HUMOR TO LURE BACK CUSTOMERS  &HT;     By CAROL EMERT 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO _ Can Levi's seduce its way into the shopping bags of
jeans-buyers?
<P>
   Levi Strauss &AMP; Co. of San Francisco is taking a 180-degree turn
in its advertising, with new television spots that rely on humor
and sex instead of earnest authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   The ads, which begin airing August 16, promote new styles in the
company's flagship Red Tab product line and carry a new tag line,
``Opt. For the Original.''
</P>
<P>
   Weakness in Red Tab is responsible for most of the 17 percent
drop in sales the company experienced in 1997 and 1998. And the
hemorrhaging hasn't stopped.
</P>
<P>
   The company was forced to steeply discount much of its Levi's
brand merchandise in the first six months of the current fiscal
year, sending U.S. Levi's sales down 10.8 percent for that period,
according to a source close to the company.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the new ads revolve around seduction scenes. One uses
special effects to show an invisible man being seduced by an
invisible woman, just as his invisible mother decides to drop by
unexpectedly.
</P>
<P>
   The second portrays a sexy artist who likes to seduce men and
use their Levi's jeans in her paintings.
</P>
<P>
   In a third spot, which will air early next year, a beautiful
young woman strips off her jeans and lays them in front of an
oncoming train to create cutoff shorts.
</P>
<P>
   The spots are a far cry from the company's last round of ads,
which carried the tag line ``What's True'' and featured urban youth
(not actors) giving earnest, unscripted monologues about their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Dee, Levi's brand director, declined to provide a budget
for the latest campaign but said it would be significantly higher
than that of What's True.
</P>
<P>
   What's True had several problems, said Dee. Consumers found the
ads too serious, Baby Boomers were offended by spots on topics like
drug abuse, and the campaign did not highlight Levi's merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   The new campaign is meant to showcase new Red Tab products,
particularly slim-fit jeans, and remedy the other problems as well,
Dee said. Both campaigns were created by TBWA/Chiat/Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me that (the new, humorous strategy) is a smart
move,'' said Greg Stern, a principal with the ad agency Butler,
Shine &AMP; Stern in Sausalito, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's purely advertising as entertainment,'' a strategy that
has proven successful for Levi's rival Lee jeans, said Stern, whose
clients include Levi's retailer Miller's Outpost.
</P>
<P>
   But the San Francisco jeansmaker seems to be sending a mixed
message by combining its ``Opt. For the Original'' tag line and the
fun, sexy ads, Stern said. ``There seems to be a disconnect
there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
