<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALKAN-SUMMIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON OFFERS U.S. AID AT MEETING IN BALKANS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO, Bosnia _ President Clinton held out a series of
economic incentives to struggling Balkan democracies Friday and
pledged modest financial assistance to pro-democracy forces inside
Serbia to further destabilize the government of President Slobodan
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting with leaders of Europe and the industrialized nations to
kick off the Balkan Stability Pact, the president pledged to
strengthen U.S. trade and investment in the historically
impoverished countries as they embrace economic and democratic
reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, the streets of Sarajevo were deserted except for
heavily armed security forces, one of the haunting reminders of the
fragile peace imposed in 1995, ending the four-year Bosnian war. A
short distance from the sports arena where the leaders met were a
high school that was near the center of battle and a soccer field
that was converted to a cemetery for the war dead.
</P>
<P>
   While he was first to offer a specific aid package to the former
communist states during Friday's Sarajevo summit, Clinton noted
that the European Union would take the lead in rebuilding the
Balkans. The effort is likened to the rebuilding of western Europe
under the post-World War II Marshall Plan and the aid given Central
European countries when the Iron Curtain fell a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The region's partners in Europe and North America must do our
part to help the nations of (southeastern Europe) to stand on their
feet, to remove obstacles to trade and to encourage investment,''
Clinton said in remarks prepared for delivery during the
three-hour, closed-door gathering.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and several European leaders, who met at the site of the
1984 Winter Olympics, repeatedly stressed their opposition to
Milosevic and willingness to include Serbia in regional security
and economic efforts if he is replaced by a pro-democracy leader.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, they outlined plans to bolster Milosevic's
opponents inside Serbia and urged Balkan leaders to assist.
Milosevic faces charges of war crimes stemming from atrocities
committed against ethnic Albanians who are the majority in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serbia will only have a future when Mr. Milosevic and his
policies are consigned to the past,'' Clinton said. ``Those who
have experience leading a democratic transition can offer
invaluable assistance and advice to those who aspire to lead one in
Serbia.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward that end, Clinton said he would ask Congress to set aside
$10 million this year _ and more in the next two years _ to support
independent media, trade unions and the democratic opposition
inside Serbia. In addition, he promised to establish a $150 million
investment fund for the Balkans and provide a $200 million credit
line through the U.S. Overseas Private Investment Corp. He also
said he would urge Congress to lower trade barriers so Balkan
countries could export goods to the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   Bodo Hombach, a former top aide to German Chancellor Gerhardt
Schroeder, said the region is ``waiting impatiently for the
democratization of Yugoslavia.'' Hombach, the EU's Balkan
coordinator, told summit participants that part of that effort was
a conference of municipal leaders, including pro-Western mayors
from Serbia, being convened later this summer in Hungary.
</P>
<P>
   A formal declaration signed by summit participants expressed
``regret'' that Yugoslavia, the federation of which Serbia is the
dominant element, could not be a part of the gathering.
</P>
<P>
   ``We appeal to the (Serb) people ... to embrace democratic
change and work actively for regional reconciliation,'' the
declaration says.
</P>
<P>
   To aid the democratic movement, the document says, European
leaders and their allies will seek ways to extend benefits of the
Balkan Stability Pact to Montenegro, Serbia's junior partner in the
Yugoslav federation.
</P>
<P>
   Asked later if the United States and its allies were seeking a
Serbian civil war to oust Milosevic, White House national security
adviser Sandy Berger said he would not ``prescribe to the Serbian
people how they handle and change governments.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic ``still has control of the apparatus of oppression,
and that is not easy to overcome,'' Berger said. ``But I have faith
in the Serbian people, that they will find a way to do that. Our
role is to provide assistance.''
</P>
<P>
   Balkan participants in the summit _ Albania, Bosnia, Bulgaria,
Croatia, Slovenia, Macedonia and Romania _ agreed to move toward
market economies and more stable, democratic governments. In
addition, they agreed to cooperate in regional security, to open
their borders to the return of refugees, and to recognize the
rights of national minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our shared objective is the development of peaceful and good
neighborly relations,'' the summit participants declared, agreeing
to downsize their military forces and shift defense funds into
economic development.
</P>
<P>
   When the summit adjourned, Clinton and Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright toured the nearby high school, a multiethnic
facility being rebuilt with U.S. aid. They were accompanied by
17-year-old Adnan Memic, who walks with a limp from shrapnel that
struck his leg seven years ago as he waited for a bus.
</P>
<P>
   Memic directed Clinton, Albright and a small entourage through
the school's wartime history, which included a stint as a military
barracks. In one classroom, its walls pock-marked by bullets, Memic
told the group that ``no living man could walk through this room
where we are now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just across the river were Serb fighters,'' he said, gesturing
across a tree-shaded street to the Miljacka River about 50 yards
away. ``There were so many shells and rifle fire that not even the
military could be here for long.''
</P>
<P>
   During a brief speech to students, faculty and diplomats,
Clinton called the rebuilding of the school a symbol of Bosnia's
future. ``It is not enough to end a war; we must build a peace,''
the president said. ``It is not enough to reject a dark past; we
must build a bright future.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
