<HEADLINE>
IT WAS AS IF AN OCCULT HAND HAD . . .  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- It's something of a ritual around these parts. The
Yankees come to town to kick some Boston butt and the Red Sox are
embroiled in controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night's pummeling at the hands of the Yanks was mildly
reminiscent of the Boston Massacre of 1978, but again the Sox were
making news off the field. In these final days of July, the Sox
have provided the X (-Ray) Files of Tom Gordon, and Nomar
Garciaparra's not-so-subtle blasts at Sox owner/physician Arthur
Pappas.
</P>
<P>
   Where's Stephen King when you really need him? Clearly the Sox
fan-author placed some kind of curse of himself and Boston's ace
closer when he penned, ``The Girl Who Loved Tom Gordon.'' The book
was just taking its place on the bestseller list when both King and
Gordon were lost for the season. Why couldn't King have done us all
a favor and written ``The Girl Who Loved Mark Portugal?'' or ``The
Girl Who Loved John Wasdin''?
</P>
<P>
   Gordon got mad this week when he learned that his MRI results
took 13 days to get from Massachusetts to Dr. James Andrews's
office in Alabama. Gordon challenged Dr. Pappas's lack of urgency,
then critiqued the Doc's diagnosis after Dr. Andrews finally closed
the curtain on Gordon's season.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling Gordon's pain, Boston's wonderboy shortstop joined the
chorus line of current and former Sox players who've questioned
their care under Pappas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our doctors are killing us,'' Garciaparra said Wednesday when
it was learned Gordon was done for the year. ``This is just like
the bone bruise (Lou Merloni's injury turned into a stress fracture
last year).''
</P>
<P>
   Nomar wasn't backing off Friday night. He told the Globe's
Gordon Edes, ``We lost our closer. Why did it have to take this
long? Wait this long, so we don't have him next year, too?''
</P>
<P>
   This much is certain: When it absolutely, positively, has to be
there overnight, make sure not to leave it on the desk of Dr.
Arthur Pappas. Apparently, Gordon's MRI results got caught in the
same ``out'' basket that swallowed Carlton Fisk's contract renewal
all those years ago. Next time, why don't the Sox save some dough,
wait till February, and put the folder on the Sox' Florida-bound
equipment truck? Just schedule a stop at Andrews's office in
Birmingham, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   There can be no excuse for the 13-day delay in getting Gordon's
files to Andrews, but questioning the quality of care _ and the
motives of the conflicted Dr. Pappas _ is another matter.
</P>
<P>
   There's plenty of history here. Pappas is a kind man and there's
plenty of evidence that he's a superior doctor, but his dual-role
is bothersome to many players and the conflict is particularly
dicey when the Doc swings and misses.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra was upset last year when Pappas struggled with the
diagnosis of Merloni. The Doc saw a bone bruise that turned out to
be a stress fracture. Saturday's starter, Brian Rose, hurt his
elbow early in 1998, but the severity of his injury went undetected
until Andrews discovered Rose had a stress fracture and bone spur
that was tugging on the ligament in his elbow. Dr. Pappas last
summer told Reggie Jefferson he had a back sprain, but Jefferson
visited back specialist Robert Watkins, who discovered a stress
fracture.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, former Sox pitcher Butch Henry still claims Pappas
last year told him he could pitch despite having a tear in the
anterior cruciate ligament of his left knee. Seven years ago,
former Sox second baseman Marty Barrett sued the team and Pappas,
claiming his career was cut short because of Pappas's misdiagnosis.
A US District Court jury awarded Barrett $1.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Now there is the Gordon mess and Pappas again is defending
himself.
</P>
<P>
   The Doc-as-owner conflict is old news around here and it's
apparent that Pappas is intent on wearing both hats indefinitely.
What makes this latest episode interesting is Garciaparra's
outspoken stance. When Gordon gave his teammates the sad news
Wednesday in Toronto, Nomar started ripping.
</P>
<P>
   Pappas was wounded by the attack and it's got to be a shocker
for the Duke. Nomar has always been Dan Duquette's guy. He is David
to Duquette's Michaelangelo. Nomar was drafted by Dan, groomed by
Dan, and signed to a multiyear contract by Dan. Duquette calls
Nomar ``a real baseball player,'' which is the ultimate compliment
in the boring language that is Dukespeak.
</P>
<P>
   But now for the second time this year, Garciaparra is taking a
stand. He broke his career-long silence and blasted management when
Merloni was sent down earlier this season and Friday night
continued to critique Pappas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talk to Butch Henry,'' said Garciaparra. ``Ask him. Give him a
call. Tim Naehring? Yeah, there's another name. I'm sure there's a
list.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a list. And Nomar is mad. And the Sox are reeling (who
could have known that Jose Offerman's final 1999 appearance at
Fenway Park would be in the All-Star Game?)
</P>
<P>
   Roger Clemens Saturday at 1:15.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
