<SLUG> BC-FBN-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARROLL NEEDS TO SHOW HE'S HOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ Lawyer Milloy's cream-colored Lexus LX470 was
parked in a Bryant College fire lane Friday. It was the most
appropriate space on campus. There were overheated words spiraling
from Milloy's vehicle. At some point, I imagine the words took on
wings and circled the area until they burned the backside of Pete
Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   As Milloy sat in his luxurious driver's seat, he spoke of
management/coaching absurdities, death and war. His words should
make one thing clear to Carroll: The term ``hot seat'' is more than
a cliche. It is the place where the coach now sits, with seat belt
strapped on. If he doesn't see that _ and confront it _ he'll
certainly be jobless by midseason.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll has to realize that something was terribly wrong with
Friday's opening of Patriots training camp. Usually Day 1 is when
head coaches determine what the tone of the late summer will be.
They speak confidently and defiantly. They encourage some players
and make others fear for their jobs. Carroll tried some of that
early in the afternoon. He said he was excited about a challenging
season and was not concerned about the gloomy predictions of
outside critics. He didn't mention the insiders.
</P>
<P>
   Safety Milloy, angry with the team's decision to release fellow
safety Willie Clay, questioned the coach without mentioning him by
name.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your job is on the line, why are you going to get rid of
somebody who's been out there every play for you?'' Milloy said.
</P>
<P>
   This is probably not what Carroll had in mind when he said
earlier in the day that Milloy was ready to step into a leadership
role. He was talking about on the field. Milloy took it further
than that. He took it straight to the fire (lane).
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that these guys understand that we go to war,''
Milloy said, referring to either the coaching staff, management or
segments of both. He said he would ``die for all my teammates,''
but added that the Pats whose replica jerseys are so popular with
young fans ``are not the true football players on our team . . .
they're letting a lot of the true players go. It's getting
ridiculous around here.''
</P>
<P>
   After saying that the release of Clay was a ``bad move'' that
hurt the team, Milloy was asked again what he thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you think? What do you think? What do you think I
think?''
</P>
<P>
   To answer his question, I think he thinks that there are minimal
consequences, if any, to be paid for his veiled criticism of
teammates and obvious criticism of the man who coaches him. And I
think he's right.
</P>
<P>
   Think of all the Boston pro coaches and how they would react to
one of their players challenging them. It wouldn't happen with the
Bruins and Pat Burns. Rick Pitino once told the Celtics that if
they ever criticized him publicly, they would be very sorry
(Antoine Walker is the only one who tested him). As unhappy as Jose
Offerman is about losing his job, you don't hear the Red Sox second
baseman angrily challenging the decisions of Jimy Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Even when players ferociously go at management with other Boston
teams, the teams respond. Dr. Arthur Pappas quickly responded when
the Sox recently questioned his methods; Harry Sinden traded Adam
Oates when the center said that Bruins management was at fault for
the horrible 1996-97 season; the Celtics have explored trading
Walker.
</P>
<P>
   Milloy's words should not be misunderstood as ``Hey, I miss
Willie; I'll be really sad to see him go.'' There was some
accumulated frustration in those comments.
</P>
<P>
   Watch Carroll and Pats management in the next few weeks. Their
actions will give you a preview of Carroll's future. The team
already cut Clay, knowing that he was not a fan of Carroll's and
frequently dogged the coach. But Bobby Grier and Carroll have to
know Clay is not the only player who fits that profile. And if they
didn't know before Friday, they should have some questions this
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I will tell you that I like Carroll personally. He is a
true sports fan, a man who has played basketball, baseball, and
football at a high level. He is approachable. He is pleasant. But
any head coach in any sport knows that when players and coaches are
battling, the players win. So the coaches combat that by making
sure that they always have more control than the men they coach. If
they are going to be fired, they figure, they will be fired for the
team's on-field performance, not its divisiveness off it.
</P>
<P>
   The question everyone, including Carroll, should be asking now
is this: Whose team is this? The obvious answer is Carroll's, since
he is the coach. But have you ever subletted a house? You're paying
for it and you're living in it, but you know it's not yours. There
are still comments and memories here of the silver-haired former
coach with the fishy nickname. There are still whispers about those
who respect the current coach and those who don't.
</P>
<P>
   So, two weeks before the first preseason game, that is Carroll's
challenge. He has to make this team follow him before he can worry
about the Jets, Dolphins, and Bills. You know what will happpen if
he can't.
</P>
<P>
   When Milloy finally finished talking Friday, he pulled out of
the fire lane and turned up his music. It was clearly hiphop. But
for a moment, I swear I heard Carroll singing James Brown's ``Hot
Pants.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Michael Holley is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
