<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-CUBS-325&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH ONE SWIFT KICK, THE METS AVOID GETTING BURNED 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Growing up in the Dominican Republic, Armando Benitez
never played hockey. But Friday, on just about the hottest day
anyone could remember at Wrigley Field, Benitez made a kick save
worthy of a goalie to preserve the New York Mets' wild 10-9 victory
over the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   With one run already in, the Mets in danger of squandering an
improbable comeback from five runs down, and runners on first and
third with two out, Benitez knocked down Tyler Houston's line drive
with his right foot.
</P>
<P>
   Benitez, who momentarily lost the ball, found it in front of the
mound. He bent over, grasped, came up with air, reached down again,
picked the ball up and rifled it to first base, barely beating
Houston to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   So what if the play was not very pretty? To the Mets (62-42),
who are challenging the Atlanta Braves for first place in the
National League East, it was a thing of beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not the Mets' general manager, Steve Phillips, would
make a move or moves before the trading deadline of midnight
Saturday mattered little in the flush of victory Friday. What
mattered most was that Benitez's play ended 3 hours 29 minutes of
torture on a day when the temperature inched over 120 degrees on
the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Venezuela, it gets hot, but not like this,'' said Edgardo
Alfonzo, who played the entire game at second base for the Mets.
``In the second inning, I felt like I was in the sauna.''
</P>
<P>
   And that was because the Mets had to stand out in the sun for
nearly 30 minutes as the Cubs scored six runs.
</P>
<P>
   Masato Yoshii pitched as if he were auditioning for a bullpen
role. He just may have earned the part.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii allowed seven runs and eight hits on 41 pitches in 1 1/3
innings, the shortest outing by a Mets starter in nearly two years.
He could not hold leads of 1-0 and 2-1. And he gave up a home run
to Sammy Sosa, his 38th.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sosa's shot came in the first inning and sailed into the
bleachers beneath the hand-operated scoreboard. The blast, which
traveled an estimated 465 feet, was a sign of things to come.
</P>
<P>
   In the second inning, Sosa was the last batter Yoshii faced.
This time, Sosa launched a moon shot that backed Rickey Henderson
against the ivy in left field. The ball dropped behind Henderson
and off the ivy, while Sosa, who initially thought he had another
homer, had to hustle his way to third, sliding head-first for a
run-scoring triple.
</P>
<P>
   That gave the Cubs back-to-back triples (Mickey Morandini's had
driven in two runs), not to mention six consecutive hits off
Yoshii. And when Pat Mahomes allowed a run-scoring double to Mark
Grace, the Cubs had seven straight hits to score six times for a
7-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But Mahomes settled down and tossed 4 2/3 strong innings. And
the Mets battled back in the oppressive heat.
</P>
<P>
   As many of the 38,594 fans on hand sought shelter from the sun,
(some were mercifully hosed down behind right field), and while WGN
television experienced technical difficulties because its
television trucks were too hot, the Mets scored in every inning
though the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   They knocked Steve Trachsel from the game in the fourth. Staked
to the five-run lead, Trachsel immediately gave two runs back in
the top of the third when he served up Mike Piazza's 21st homer of
the season with John Olerud on first base.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets scored twice more in the fourth to cut the deficit to
7-6, on a leadoff double by Brian McRae, a run-scoring one-out
double from Mahomes, Curtis Goodwin's throwing error that allowed
Mahomes to move to third and Henderson's run-scoring groundout off
reliever Scott Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets briefly took the lead in the fifth with two more runs,
even though Olerud was thrown out at the plate when third base
coach Cookie Rojas questionably sent him home on Piazza's line
single to left that popped out of the diving Henry Rodriguez's
glove. Piazza took second on the throw home, then scored an out
later on Benny Agbayani's two-out double inside the first base
line. McRae walked, and when Rey Ordonez lined a run-scoring single
to center, it gave the Mets an 8-7 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Hernandez erased the lead with a two-out homer in the fifth
off Mahomes. But Henderson led off the Mets' sixth with a solo
shot, his ninth homer of the season, off Kyle Farnsworth. And when
Olerud homered off Rick Aguilera to lead off the ninth, the Mets
were two runs in front.
</P>
<P>
   This time, they were able to make the lead stand up _ by the
length of Benitez's right foot.
</P>
</TEXT>
