<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-TRADETALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES HAVE A DEAL FOR PETTITTE, IF THEY WANT IT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The New York Yankees have a trade for Andy Pettitte
they can accept or reject, they are on the verge of acquiring
former Yankee Jim Leyritz, and they are engaged in serious talks
with Baltimore for Arthur Rhodes.
</P>
<P>
   With Saturday's trade deadline looming, if the Yankees acquire a
major league pitcher or two, like Rhodes or Tampa Bay's Roberto
Hernandez, they are expected to trade Pettitte.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Cashman, the Yankees' general manager, has been frequently
conversing with the Anaheim Angels about Chuck Finley, although
Anaheim executives are becoming more convinced that Cashman is not
really interested in the left-hander and is more intent on driving
up the price on Finley for the Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians have offered second baseman Enrique Wilson and first
baseman Willie Martinez for Finley, but the Angels, who traded
second baseman Randy Velarde to Oakland on Wednesday to clear a
spot for a second baseman like Wilson, want another minor-leaguer
from the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have talked to perhaps 10 teams about Pettitte, but
if they trade him it appears it will be to Philadelphia. The two
sides have settled on two prospects, and it is a matter of the
Yankees' going ahead with the deal. In all likelihood, the two are
right-handed pitcher Adam Eaton and outfielder Reggie Taylor, both
of whom were high draft picks currently playing in the minor
leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte, 27, has 75 victories in less than five seasons with
the Yankees, but he is being shopped primarily because his
performance this year (7-8, 5.65 ERA) isn't living up to his $5.95
million salary. Pettitte is due for a hefty raise next year because
he is eligible for arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Joe Torre participated in two Yankees conference calls
Friday as club officials debated the possible deals. Torre said he
could understand both sides of the argument on trading Pettitte.
``I can't defend what he's done,'' Torre said, referring to
Pettitte's numbers this year. ``I can only defend on how he's
pitched in the past, and if he can come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Eaton, the Phillies' No. 1 draft pick in 1996, is a hard thrower
whose fastball recently was clocked at 97 mph. Taylor is an
extremely fast center fielder who was selected the top defensive
outfielder in the Florida State League in 1997. The Yankees have
also talked to the Giants about a deal for Pettitte _ possibly for
pitcher Shawn Estes _ as well as with the Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
<P>
   In return for Rhodes, the Orioles have asked the Yankees for
D'Angelo Jimenez, a Triple-A shortstop, as well as hard-throwing
pitcher Luis DeLosSantos; the Yankees may want to replace
DeLosSantos in the deal. Rhodes, 29, is having an off year, with a
6.17 ERA, but scouts who have seen him recently say that if he is
used in a certain way _ Rhodes is good at pitching an inning or two
at a time every other day, rather than every day _ he has the most
dominant stuff of any left-hander.
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz, 35, has been injured and missed most of this season,
but the Yankees would like to get him to help their bench and give
them added depth for the rest of the season and the playoffs; his
career playoff record includes seven home runs in 58 at-bats. The
Padres would receive a minor-league pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, an American League All-Star this season, would
greatly augment the Yankees' bullpen as a setup man for Mariano
Rivera, but there are potential complications. Foremost, Tampa Bay
has asked about several players, including Alfonso Soriano, perhaps
the most coveted prospect in the Yankees' system, and at the very
least the Devil Rays wouldn't make a deal without inclusion of the
star Double-A first baseman Nick Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, too, is earning $6 million this year and will make
that amount for each of the next two years; if the Yankees were to
acquire him, they very likely would then trade him in the
off-season, rather than pay a middle reliever such a high salary.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees continue to talk about Finley _ others say they have
offered Pettitte, a player in whom the Angels apparently have no
interest. The Yankees' desire to obtain Finley may be muted by the
fact that they want him primarily in a defensive maneuver, to keep
him away from the Cleveland Indians, and if the Yankees were to
trade for Finley and then allow him to leave as a free agent, they
would not receive draft picks as compensation, due to a clause in
Finley's existing contract.
</P>
<P>
   Teams can still trade after midnight Saturday, but making deals
will become far more problematic, as players must clear waivers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
