<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS' RED SOX RECORD CAN'T BE IGNORED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- If you're a Red Sox fan, it has become almost a ritual
when the New York Yankees come to town. You boo. And it doesn't
matter if they are in first place or last place. You let 'em have
it.
</P>
<P>
   But even that time-honored Fenway tradition will be tested
Saturday with the return of Roger Clemens in a role that even in
your worst nightmare, you never envisioned: Pitching for the
Yankees at Fenway Park. Hopefully, between the boos, there will be
a few cheers. For 13 seasons, he was the best the Red Sox ever
produced.
</P>
<P>
   In the two years Clemens played in Toronto, he went 21-7 (1997)
and 20-6 ('98) and won two Cy Young Awards, and he was booed at
Fenway. The Blue Jays were happy but Roger wasn't. We all know what
he wanted more than individual hardware . . . a championship ring.
Now, nothing would please him more than to make another down
payment on it. But he knows it won't be easy.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the Yankees are good enough to get him to a World Series. A
year ago they walked away with the American League East with a
114-48 record. Boston made the playoffs as a wild-card entry, but
trailed by 22 games. This year's club came to town with a 61-39
record and a 6 1/2-game lead over the Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say anything before this one,'' said Clemens
to several from Boston who tried to approach him.
</P>
<P>
   Yankee manager Joe Torre didn't mind speaking up. In 19 starts,
Clemens is 9-4 with a 4.67 earned run average. Clemens may not be
having the kind of year the man he replaced _ David Wells _ had
last season (the lefthander went 18-4 with a 3.49 ERA), but then
neither are the Yankees. And nobody expects 114 victories out of
the class of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not concerned about (Clemens's) ERA,'' said Torre Friday.
``I'm concerned how he's going to pitch. . . . He's throwing the
ball very well and he had a hell of a game Sunday at Cleveland. He
threw 135 pitches and left after seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure it's going to be a little strange when he goes out
there as it has been in the past when he's pitched here. He'll have
a tendency to walk to that first-base dugout. But he knows what
he's doing. ''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees know what they are doing. They are minus Wells,
Darryl Strawberry, Tim Raines, and Graeme Lloyd, to name a few from
last year's team. They have put newcomers such as Ricky Ledee and
Shane Spencer into active roles. Reliever Jeff Nelson is the most
notable injury, and the starting rotation has for the most part
stayed healthy. For inspiration, you only need to mention David
Cone. His perfect game against Montreal was a perfect lift. The
Yankees haven't been on a long steak this year. But they are 22
games above .500.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team's all right,'' said Cone. ``We haven't played as well
as we think we're going to. Clemens is just getting going and
pitching well. I like our chances. We're past the point of worrying
about last year or the changes that have been made. We're at the
point now that we just want to get to the playoffs. We won't worry
about how many games we've won or are going to win . . . or what
trades have gone down or will go down.''
</P>
<P>
   Comparisons to the 1998 season still haunt the Yankees. That's
not fair, said Derek Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was something that had never happened before in
baseball history,'' he said. ``We'll probably never see it again as
long as we're alive. We're playing better as of late. We're still
in first place. At times we've shown we can put everything together
and play well. But we haven't put it together for a long stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees can live with the boo-birds, he added. They are not
just a Boston invention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you play for the Yankees, regardless of your record,
teams want to beat you,'' said Jeter. ``More so if you win a
championship. You come to town and people want to beat the best
team in baseball. If you win a World Series, teams are going to gun
for you all that much more.''
</P>
<P>
   There in concern on Broadway about the Yankees. Trade winds are
blowing and one of the headliners, Andy Pettitte (7-8, 5.65), is
nearing the end of his run. Torre doesn't like the deals that are
being discussed. It makes him nervous when the name of reliever
Ramiro Mendoza comes up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still believe we're not in any desperate shape to make a
deal,'' said Torre, ``unless it is a deal that we feel is going to
help us. I think we're fine the way we are. I do think there are
some areas in which we can improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could use a little speed. Our depth? We have Ledee,
Spencer. Chad Curtis to back up. A chance down the road that Darryl
Strawberry is there. We're in first place. That's our goal. We
can't worry about measuring up to last year.''
</P>
<P>
   But if a deal has to be made, it has to be made, he added.
Mendoza is too valuable to move. Pettitte is not.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't let yourself get caught up in how you feel about
somebody,'' said Torre. ``Realistically, you have to say to
yourself what is best for the team. If Andy Pettitte were traded, I
would miss him. His stuff is good. He just needs a vacuum cleaner
inside that head to start over again mentally. If you start over,
you sort of build a foundation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
