<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-EDITOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN INDEPENDENT HONG KONG EDITOR IS GIVEN HIS WALKING PAPERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ It had become a running gag in the newsroom of The
South China Morning Post. Whenever the paper's outspoken British
editor, Jonathan Fenby, told his staff that he was leaving town on
vacation, some smart aleck would pipe up, ``Are you coming back?''
</P>
<P>
   Fenby is off at the end of this week, but this time the joke
might catch in people's throats. After more than four years of
editing Hong Kong's leading English-language newspaper _ a tense
period during which this former British colony reverted to Chinese
rule _ Fenby has been handed his walking papers.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong is not like Fleet Street, where editors are
customarily dismissed in a blunt telephone call from the publisher.
</P>
<P>
   Fenby, 56, said his bosses did not explain why they refused to
renew his contract, aside from vague suggestions that they wanted a
change. He has not even talked to the proprietor, Robert Kuok, a
Malaysian billionaire who bought control of The Post from Rupert
Murdoch in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be changes I'm not privy to,'' said Fenby, a
garrulous man who knows the vagaries of newspapering from stints at
The Independent, The Guardian and The Observer in Britain. ``But
obviously, the owners wanted people they could feel more
comfortable with.''
</P>
<P>
   The murky circumstances of Fenby's exit have prompted a rash of
speculation here that he is a victim of Hong Kong's tightening
political atmosphere. Under his editor's pen, The South China
Morning Post has been sharply critical of the Hong Kong government
_ most recently its decision to ask China to overrule an
immigration ruling by the territory's highest court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I strongly suspect this is motivated by his wanting to be more
independent than the owners are willing to be,'' said Margaret Ng,
a pro-democracy member of the Hong Kong Legislature. ``As a whole,
newspapers have become steadily more pro-government since the
handover.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuok, whose company owns 34 percent of the shares of the Post,
declined to comment on the reason for Fenby's departure, as did
Owen Jonathan, the newspaper's chief executive. But Jonathan said
it was not related to The Post's news coverage, adding, ``Editors
do come, and they do go.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Hong Kong still has more than a dozen daily newspapers,
which engage in roisterous competition, they tend to fall in line
behind the government on the most critical issues, such as
overturning the ruling, which would have given over 1 million
mainland Chinese the right to live here.
</P>
<P>
   The Post was almost alone in opposing that move. In an editorial
published the day after Beijing overturned the ruling, Fenby wrote
that Hong Kong had eroded the rule of law _ the bedrock of its
commercial success _ by politicizing its judiciary and humiliating
its highest court.
</P>
<P>
   The harsh words angered the government, which took the highly
unusual step of dispatching its No. 2 official, Anson Chan, to
speak to Fenby. Although a spokesman said the government would
never try to bully the paper, one senior official said The Post
``ought to recognize its responsibility as the paper people outside
Hong Kong read to learn about things here.''
</P>
<P>
   Fenby said, ``There's been a much stronger reaction to the
newspaper, from officialdom, from business circles, from members of
the establishment, than at any time since the handover.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressure from mainland China is mounting as well. Earlier this
month, a senior Chinese official told a group of Hong Kong
journalists visiting Beijing that ``some people, including some
newspapers, have fueled the row and caused all the controversy.''
It was the first time since the handover that a mainland official
had criticized news coverage in Hong Kong. And to Fenby, it was an
unmistakable sign that Beijing has The Post in its cross hairs.
</P>
<P>
   For all the heat, Fenby said he had not been asked by Kuok or
the newspaper's executives to tone down The Post's coverage of the
immigration issue. At other times in the last four years, however,
Fenby said he had to fend off efforts by Kuok's deputies to
influence coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before the handover, Fenby said he received a directive
to refer to the 1989 military crackdown in Tiananmen Square as an
``incident'' _ the word customarily used by Beijing _ rather than a
``massacre.'' He briefly considered resigning over the issue. But
he then decided to leave it up to his reporters to decide which
word to use.
</P>
<P>
   ``The word `massacre' disappeared from the paper for a couple of
months, and I still perceive that the editors are sensitive about
using it in headlines,'' said Gren Manuel, an investigative
reporter.
</P>
<P>
   About the same time, Kuok brought in a prominent Chinese
journalist, Feng Xiliang, one of the founding editors of China's
official English-language paper, China Daily. Reporters promptly
dubbed him the ``political commissar.'' Again, Fenby contemplated
leaving. But instead he decided to marginalize Feng, who ended up
with little influence and is now rarely seen in the newsroom.
</P>
<P>
   By the middle of last year, though, it was Fenby who was in
danger of being shunted to the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Kuok brought in Robert Keatley, a longtime editor at The Wall
Street Journal, ostensibly to bring ``a touch of The Wall Street
Journal'' by encouraging more analytical reporting, as Keatley puts
it. Fenby wondered whether the paper was laying the groundwork for
his departure.
</P>
<P>
   Those fears proved warranted. In May, Keatley was named to
replace Fenby _ at least for the time being. Keatley, 64, said the
paper was searching for a more long-term replacement. Several
reporters said Kuok would like to put a Chinese journalist in the
top job. Jonathan said race was not a factor, though it would be an
advantage if the new editor spoke Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Keatley denied that Fenby had been pushed out
because of political considerations. And he pledged to maintain The
Post's editorial stance on legal issues and Hong Kong's autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do come out of The Wall Street Journal,'' he said. ``It
stands for human rights and the rule of law.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
