u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DROUGHT-NYT &LR;      07-30 1374
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DROUGHT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROPS, AND JOBS, DRYING UP IN LONG, HOT SUMMER 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Spelling of `Maire' in 14th graf is correct.) 
(yn) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRING VALLEY, N.Y. _ Every morning, Magdaleno Fuentes waits by
the shoulder of Route 59, hoping to find a job mowing lawns,
trimming bushes or planting bushes. Eager to impress, he wears his
best button-down shirt and clutches a plastic bag hiding a
sleeveless gray T-shirt, specked with the toil and soil from
previous jobs. Usually, he waits for a few minutes, a couple of
hours at most, before the right job comes along.
</P>
<P>
   But these days, Fuentes is waiting a lot more. It has been two
weeks, in fact, since he last found work, and it may be another
week or more, he worries, before he and other day laborers in
Rockland County are able to find steady work. The reason, he says,
is simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``No rain, no work,'' said Fuentes, 39, a native of Puebla,
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   For all the complaints and misery swirling around the effects of
the dry weather and subsequent water restrictions on verdant lawns,
the quieter reality is that the restrictions are also having a
ripple effect on anyone who depends on rain to eke out a living.
</P>
<P>
   For farmers, no rain means that the life has been sucked out of
cornfields and fruit trees. For landscapers, no rain means
mandatory water limits that have almost forced them to cease
operating _ and stop hiring day laborers like Fuentes. Unless there
is a change in the weather soon, no rain also means that life
promises to become more dire for more people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a trickle-down effect, because if these people don't make
money, they affect our local economy,'' said Mayor Allan Thompson
of Spring Valley. ``It's hurting everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, many farmers are calling this summer the hottest and
driest in recent memory. In the entire eastern United States,
rainfall in June and July has been the lowest in more than a
decade, according to the National Weather Service. And the impact
is being felt across the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing the effects on everything from fields to orchards
to nurseries,'' said Sharon M. Douglas, a plant pathologist at the
Connecticut Agricultural Station, a state agency in New Haven.
``People are trying to get as much water on their crops as
possible, but some growers have pumped their ponds dry.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Wood, a spokeswoman for the New Jersey Agriculture
Department, said the arid weather was having a devastating impact
on corn, alfalfa and soybean crops and that Gov. Christine Todd
Whitman was preparing to ask the federal government to declare the
state's farmland a disaster area, making farmers eligible for
low-interest loans. In addition the state is expected to impose
voluntary limits on water use next week. Already mandatory
restrictions are in place in all of Rockland County and in many
municipalities in Orange County. On July 13, Rockland County, which
draws all its water from within its geographic boundaries, imposed
Stage 1 water emergency restrictions, curbing the watering of lawns
to every other day. But when officials discovered that people
simply watered nonstop on the designated day, causing usage to
actually inch up, the county imposed a Stage 2 emergency on July
21, forbidding the use of lawn sprinklers.
</P>
<P>
   Violators are first warned and informed of the maximum penalty
of $1,000 a day, said Tom Micelli, the county's acting health
commissioner. And so far, at least, the message has filtered
through: daily water usage has dropped from an average of 42
million gallons to 32 million gallons, said Terri Guess, a
spokeswoman for United Water, which provides water to most of
Rockland County.
</P>
<P>
   But still, there has been hardly any rain in the region, and
little prospect for relief in the coming days, according to the
Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Even when there has been rain, it has usually been of the
cloudburst variety. On Thursday night, for instance, a brief shower
dumped up to three inches in some parts of Orange County. But that
was of little use, because the soil did not have time to soak it
up.
</P>
<P>
   What is more desirable, said Maire Ullrich, vegetable crops
agent for the Cornell Cooperative Extension of Orange and Ulster
Counties, is Seattlelike weather for a week: a good, but not
overwhelming, soaking of a couple of inches a day, for four to
seven straight days.
</P>
<P>
   Like any other meteorological calamity, there's not much to
blame here but fate. But in Rockland County, officials and the
public have found a target for at least some of their anger: New
Jersey. United Water, the utility that serves Rockland and parts of
New Jersey, is entitled to channel more water from a Rockland
reservoir to New Jersey if water levels there fall too low. Even
though that hasn't happened, some people in Rockland, where water
use is restricted, are unhappy that United is pumping any water to
New Jersey, where there are no restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like you're standing on this side of Rockland County, and
the grass looks like weed, and in New Jersey,'' said C. Scott
Vanderhoef, the Rockland County executive, with a hint of outrage
in his voice, ``the grass looks plush.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   It is still too early to quantify the impact the dry weather has
had on local landscaping _ a $250 million-a-year business _ or on
local farmers, officials say. But there have been plenty of
anecdotes about the ruinous and near-ruinous repercussions.
</P>
<P>
   In Orange County, onion farmers have been staring at dusty,
desertlike soil and poor yields. ``The farmers are in trouble,''
said Matthias Schliefer, the assistant commissioner for
environmental health of Orange County. ``Our onion-growing country
is just about a total disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Corn fields have been devastated, too, with some farmers
reporting damage to 50, 60 or even 80 percent of their crops. At
the Fort Hill Farm in the Orange County community of Goshen,
Claudia and Phil Johnson have watched helplessly as about 400 acres
of corn have withered in the oppressive heat. That corn was
supposed to be used as feed for their 300-head dairy farm; now,
instead, the Johnsons, sixth-generation farmers, will have to buy
feed.
</P>
<P>
   In New City, in Rockland County, Jim Cropsey, whose family has
owned Cropsey Farms since 1893, has watched his 40 acres of corn
wilt, turning what should have been a lush, green plain of
10-foot-high stalks into a yellow, even singed-looking field of
half-sized corn. On Thursday, for instance, his workers picked 23
bags of corn; during a normal summer with rain, that figure is up
to 125 bags a day.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The pumpkin fields are so dry and dusty, Cropsey said, that his
workers may have to wear masks when they work the fields. His snap
peas do not snap; they look limp. And some of his peaches have been
utterly useless, puny things that resemble golf balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember as dry a summer as this,'' said Cropsey, a
robust 70-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   So far, Cropsey and other farmers have been forced to lay off,
or at least not hire, day laborers to work their fields. There are
easily hundreds of day laborers in Rockland County, mainly from
Latin America, who look for work, have families to support and
generally live in substandard conditions anyway, said Patricia
Feeley, executive director of Catholic Community Services of
Rockland.
</P>
<P>
   And it will be particularly trying in the next few days, she
said, as the rent comes due on the first of the month and food
becomes scarce. ``We're going to see tremendous suffering,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   At Lucrezia's Nursery in Spring Valley, home to lush weeping
Norway spruces, thundercloud purple leaf plums, and Japanese
weeping cherries, hardly anyone stops by anymore because no one
wants to buy something they will not be able to water, said Rosa
Lucrezia, who with her husband owns the nursery.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning, for instance, one person visited the nursery.
It turned out to be an advertising salesman for a local newspaper.
And usually, Mrs. Lucrezia takes out a monthly ad. But this time,
she said, it would be of no use _ not until it rains again, anyway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
