<SLUG> BC-FETUS-FIGHT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON MAN GAINS GUARDIANSHIP OVER COMATOSE WOMAN, FETUS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RON NISSIMOV 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A Houston hospital, ordered last week to do everything
possible to keep a comatose woman and her 16-week-old fetus alive,
claims it does not have to try to save the fetus if the woman is
declared brain-dead.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Law, 35, of Houston was named Tammy Martin's temporary
guardian Friday after he presented a hospital attorney's letter
saying the court-ordered life support would be ``inapplicable'' if
Martin, 34, is ruled brain-dead.
</P>
<P>
   Harris County Probate Judge Rory Olsen's ruling means Memorial
Hospital Northwest must seek Law's permission before performing any
medical treatment on Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Law, who says he is Martin's common-law husband and father of
the fetus, wants her kept on life support _ even if she is ruled
brain-dead _ to try to save the fetus, whose heart is still
beating.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's parents want her and the fetus to be allowed to die,
and Law believes the hospital is doing everything it can to bring
this end about.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's family says her guardian has been her mother, Joyce
Cox, 60, of Brackettville in South Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital attorneys were not present at Friday's hearing, and
spokeswoman Patty Riddlebarger said she could not comment because
of patient confidentiality rules.
</P>
<P>
   Olsen named Law as temporary guardian until Sept. 28, and
scheduled another hearing for Aug. 13 to determine whether the
guardianship needed to be continued. The temporary order does not
allow Law to authorize termination of life support.
</P>
<P>
   Law and his attorney, Michael Stanley, declined to comment. But
in court papers filed Friday, Law said Martin and the fetus
``should be protected from a physician of the hospital's choice,
which has shown by its conduct its hostility to (Law's) efforts to
preserve and protect the lives of his wife and child.''
</P>
<P>
   The papers also claim Martin is showing ``increased activity
when spoken to in the presence of (Law).''
</P>
<P>
   Martin's brother, Lonnie, 40, of nearby Splendora, said he
learned about the latest legal maneuver from a reporter and that
his parents, J.D. and Joyce Cox, had not heard about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe they gave him temporary guardianship,'' Martin
said. ``We believe the baby should go to heaven with her mama.''
</P>
<P>
   Law was granted a two-week temporary restraining order July 23 _
five days after Martin became comatose from a blow to the head _
telling the hospital to do everything possible to keep her and the
fetus alive.
</P>
<P>
   In that order, state District Judge Scott Link said the hospital
was restrained ``from withholding treatment necessary to keep Tammy
Martin and her unborn child alive and from in any way facilitating
or expediting the death of Tammy Martin and Mr. Law's unborn
child.''
</P>
<P>
   The hospital has apparently interpreted the order to mean it
does not have to keep the fetus alive if Martin is ruled
brain-dead.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter dated Wednesday, hospital attorney Gregory Sapire
said Link's order ``would be inapplicable if Tammy Martin were
found to have lost all spontaneous brain function.''
</P>
<P>
   Link's order would have lasted until Aug. 5, when a hearing is
scheduled on Law's request to be declared Martin's common-law
husband. But the order could presumably have been extended.
</P>
<P>
   Since Tammy Martin did not specify if she should be kept alive
by artificial means if she was ruled terminally ill, state law
allows a ``surrogate decision-maker'' to make that determination.
</P>
<P>
   If Law is declared Martin's common-law husband, he would have
top priority in making such a decision. Currently, Martin's mother
has that authority, family members have said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sapire's letter said Martin has not officially been
ruled brain-dead, Lonnie Martin has said that doctors told him
twice last week that they believe she is. He said a test that could
make an official determination was scheduled for last week but was
put off until at least Aug. 5 for ``legal reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Riddlebarger has said the test has not been done for ``medical
reasons.'' Called an apnea test, it measures the brain's ability to
produce a breathing response when ventilating machines are turned
off.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's family claims Law is not her common-law husband and may
be criminally responsible for her death. There is no point to keep
her on life support if she is ruled brain-dead, the family said,
because she was an alcoholic and used cocaine. The family believes
the fetus will have little chance of being healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's former boy friend, Ben Bruce of Houston, has said he
plans to file court papers claiming to be her common-law husband.
The family has said Bruce may even be the father of the fetus.
</P>
<P>
   Law says Martin hit her head on a car door and fell unconscious
several hours later. Even if she is ruled brain-dead, he says, she
should be kept on life support at least until the fetus is old
enough to be taken out, between 23-28 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Martin was facing two years in prison for violating probation
after pleading guilty to recklessly injuring a minor. She had been
charged with injecting cocaine and amphetamines into Bruce's minor
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Lonnie Martin claims Bruce told him that Tammy Martin became
pregnant to try to avoid prison time, and wanted to get an abortion
after she realized it would have no bearing on her sentence. Law
says the story is a lie and that Tammy Martin would have wanted to
give the fetus a chance to live.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
