<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0557 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-HEATWAVE-ART-NYT &LR;      07-30 1276
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HEATWAVE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESIDENTS SWEAT OUT CITY'S HOTTEST JULY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036. 
(yn) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ How hot is it?
</P>
<P>
   At the Willow Restaurant and Bar, the white cloths on the
outdoor tables do not have to be changed after the lunch rush,
because everybody sits inside. Alex Carrera, a letter carrier,
spent $48 of his own money to put a fan in the lobby of 110
Riverside Drive, where he delivers mail to 96 apartments. Mary
Cantazaro of Bensonhurst offered to take a friend dinner as a ruse
to get into her air-conditioned apartment. Midweek movie matinees
are selling out.
</P>
<P>
   And every afternoon after his walk, Bertram, an English bulldog,
hops into the tub in his owner's Upper East Side apartment and
waits for a cold shower.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't require long walks in this heat,'' Margaret Hogg,
who walks five dogs daily, explained as she fed Bertram water from
a Gatorade bottle on a bench in Central Park. ``They seem like we
do, no energy in this heat. It drains them.''
</P>
<P>
   As the hottest July on record comes to a close here, it almost
seems as though summer fun in New York City has been canceled.
</P>
<P>
   People are walking slower, eating less and drinking more. They
are canceling plans to go to the park, the zoo, even the beach.
They are staying home. And, this being New York, they are
complaining.
</P>
<P>
   Summer in the city is supposed to be a celebration of sidewalk
cafes and Shakespeare in the Park, of bicycle rides, barbecues and
botanical gardens. Instead, it has become the season of sweat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We waited for the summer all year, for six months, and then
look at this,'' Maria Rodriguez said as she poured her 4-year-old
grandson a cup of cold Kool-Aid while waiting at a public pool for
the lifeguards to come back from their lunch break. ``I want it to
get cool already.''
</P>
<P>
   How hot is it?
</P>
<P>
   Not counting Friday or Saturday, the average temperature for the
month has been 81.3 degrees. That includes nighttime. There have
been 17 days over 90 and 11 days over 95. The forecast for Saturday
is a sultry 96. July 1995, which previously held the record for the
hottest month, had an average temperature of 80.9 and only 14 days
above 90 degrees, nine above 95.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, there have been 91 deaths linked to the heat in 17
states since July 19. The Midwest, where brick buildings seemed
like baking ovens yesterday, has been hardest hit, with 29
heat-related deaths during the past 10 days in Missouri, 23 in
Illinois and 10 in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   The heat index, which factors in humidity, was 120 in Chicago
yesterday, according to the National Weather Service. The
temperature alone hit 104 degrees in Louisville, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the mercury has not spiked up past 100 since the
Independence Day weekend, with its disastrous blackout for about
200,000 customers in Washington Heights and the Lower East Side.
But the relentless heat and humidity, day after day after day of
summer swelter, is what has everybody dragging.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not as ambitious,'' admitted Tommy King, a waiter at the
Willow, a bistro at 73rd Street and Lexington Avenue. Trying to
make fewer trips in and out of the kitchen, King waits until
multiple orders are ready before bringing them to the table. ``If I
have a table outside,'' he added, ``they won't get as good
service.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any energy,'' King said. ``Even to read. There's
nothing I really desire to do, and I certainly don't do any cooking
or cleaning. My apartment is so sloppy.''
</P>
<P>
   It could, of course, be worse.
</P>
<P>
   He could be the dry-cleaning delivery guy, tromping through the
streets with closetfulls of clothes in their sticky plastic wraps.
Or Cesar Diaz, who plays violin on the subway platform at 79th and
Broadway and depends on the hot wind the trains make as they come
and go and a burst of cold each time the doors to the
air-conditioned cars open. Or Eddie Ayala, the air-conditioning
repairman who has to ride around the city in an non-air-conditioned
van.
</P>
<P>
   ``They get nasty,'' Ayala said of the customers he sees each
day. ``They blame me for the air-conditioning not working when I
haven't even been there.''
</P>
<P>
   How hot is it?
</P>
<P>
   There were 32 heat-related deaths in New York from July 3 to
July 28, with victims ages 27 to 102 (half were over 65). Dr.
Joshua Stillman, the assistant director of emergency services at
Columbia Presbyterian Hospital, said there have been about 50 extra
patients a day with heat-related problems ranging from food
poisoning to dizziness that resulted in a person breaking a leg.
</P>
<P>
   And Marlin S. Potash, a psychotherapist, said she can sense a
kind of mental heat stroke in the workaholics who make up her Upper
East Side practice. Slowing down is uncomfortable for her revved-up
clients, Potash said, and ``they feel like they're losing out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it's, `Everybody else is in the country and I have to
work,' or `My air-conditioner went out,' or `I was planning to
learn how to play tennis but it's so hot I can't bear to,''' Potash
said, ``There's this sense that the summer is getting away from you
without doing the things you look forward to.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, yesterday, Matthew Kelly took his 4-year-old son, Jake,
to the Children's Museum _ where attendance is nearly 25 percent
higher than it was last July _ instead of to the playground. James
Mott, 54, of Sunnyside, Queens, was headed for the biodiversity
exhibit at the Museum of Natural History (which has had an 8
percent jump in visitors) rather than on the ferry to Fire Island.
Kathy Owl, a registered nurse who is training for the Chicago
marathon in the fall, stopped running after a mile and a half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I live in Houston,'' said Ms. Owl, who is visiting a friend
for the weekend, as she left Central Park about 9 a.m. in a tank
top soaked with sweat. ``So this is about the same.''
</P>
<P>
   But Houston is built for this. People in Houston go from
air-conditioned homes to air-conditioned cars to air-conditioned
offices. They have underground, air-conditioned tunnels connecting
them to malls and food courts. They wear stockings in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   New York is the land of sidewalk sightseeing, and these days,
everybody is crowding the shady side.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest challenge, for many, is figuring out what to do with
children, who cannot be satisfied with simply collapsing on the
couch.
</P>
<P>
   At Public School 282 in Park Slope, teachers read to students in
the office, which is the only room with air-conditioning. At Girl
Scout Camp Waneeshi in Dutchess County, counselors are telling
campers to wrap wet bandanas around their necks. In East Harlem,
Rajalar Price has turned day care at A Learning Center into a quest
for water.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go to the sprinklers every day _ any sprinklers we can
find,'' Price, 36, said as he led 16 charges, ages 4 to 12, up the
steps to the Central Park pool. ``We have a really good time
getting in the water. Wherever we can find it, we get in it.''
</P>
<P>
   How hot is it?
</P>
<P>
   Don't ask Sal Ruggeri.
</P>
<P>
   Ruggeri, who has spent two decades driving horse-drawn carriages
around Central Park, is not just upset at the income he has lost
because the horses have been sidelined for 25 days so far this
summer, more than twice the norm. He is also ornery because of the
endless stream of news reporters stopping for heat stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday there was a guy here who must have taken 50 pictures
of me,'' said Ruggeri, declining to be photographed. ``Today, they
tell me I'm on the Internet, also. It's getting to be annoying,
really.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
