<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SENATE VOTES TO CUT TAXES BY $792 BILLION IN 10 YEARS
</P>
<P>
   The Senate voted to cut taxes by $792 billion over the next 10
years, moving the Republican-controlled Congress toward a showdown
with President Clinton over how the nation can best use trillions
of dollars in projected federal budget surpluses. The vote was
57-43. Four Democrats joined 53 Republicans in support of the bill,
while two Republicans and 41 Democrats voted against it.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would cut personal income taxes by reducing the lowest
tax rate starting in 2001. It would give a tax break to many
married couples, expand the Individual Retirement Account program,
create a deduction for some health insurance costs and reduce the
inheritance tax on large estates.
</P>
<P>
   DOW JONES AVERAGE FALLS 136 POINTS
</P>
<P>
   Stocks declined as more evidence of inflation pressures
convinced investors the Federal Reserve might raise interest rates
soon. The Dow Jones industrial average ended down 136.14 points, or
1.26 percent, to 10,655.15, after sliding 180.78 points Thursday.
For the week, the blue-chip index was down 255.81 points. The
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index fell 1.52 points, to
2,638.49, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's composite index of 500 stocks
declined 12.31 points, to 1,328.72.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury bond prices dropped, rounding out the sixth consecutive
losing month for Treasuries. The decline was spurred by reports on
housing, manufacturing and personal income that added to concern
the Federal Reserve might raise interest rates soon. The yield on
the 30-year Treasury bond rose to 6.10 percent from 6.07 percent on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   PERSONAL INCOME INCREASED IN JUNE
</P>
<P>
   Personal income, which includes wages, interest and government
benefits, rose seven-tenths of a percent, faster than expected, in
June. It marked the first time since January that personal income
outpaced the rise in spending. In a separate report, the government
said that new home sales jumped 3.1 percent as buyers rushed to
beat rising mortgage rates. Sales of new single-family homes rose
to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 929,000 units, better than
forecast.
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA EXCHANGE REAPPOINTS
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia Stock Exchange reappointed Meyer Frucher, its
chairman, for two years, despite some opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA AND BRAZIL END DISPUTE
</P>
<P>
   Argentina has retreated from a threat to impose punitive tariffs
on Brazilian exports, easing a dispute between the two countries
that had threatened the cohesion of the $1.1 trillion MERCOSUR
trade bloc.
</P>
<P>
   A MERGER OF BRITISH NEWSPAPERS
</P>
<P>
   Trinity, Britain's largest regional newspaper company, plans to
buy the Mirror Group for (PS)1.24 billion, or about $2 billion. The
deal would create the largest newspaper publisher in Britain,
combining local newspapers like The Liverpool Echo with The Mirror.
Trinity's chief executive, Philip Graf, will head the new group.
</P>
<P>
   HEAD OF CHINA EVERBRIGHT RESIGNS
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of China Everbright Group, one of that nation's
largest financial conglomerates, resigned and was replaced by a
deputy governor of the People's Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL TRUCKERS HALT STRIKE
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilian government reached a deal to end a strike that had
paralyzed road transport. Federal authorities agreed to suspend an
increase in diesel prices, freeze tolls on some highways and send
Congress a proposal that would penalize truckers less than other
motorists for traffic violations.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO TITLE IS IN MERGER TALKS
</P>
<P>
   Chicago Title is in talks to be acquired by Fidelity National
Financial. Both companies provide title insurance, credit
reporting, property valuation and technology services.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-99 2212EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
