<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Argentina: Failed Bid for NATO
</P>
<P>
   Argentina has formally requested to become the first Latin
American nation to become a member of the NATO military alliance.
But Secretary General Javier Solana rejected the request in a
letter to President Carlos Saul Menem, saying the current expansion
was intended only to integrate former members of the Warsaw Pact in
the Western alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Chile: Risk Seen to Pinochet
</P>
<P>
   Two doctors reported that Gen. Augusto Pinochet, the former
dictator, who is under house arrest in London, is suffering from
stress that is so severe it is worsening his diabetes and slowing
his recovery from back surgery. The examination by the Chilean and
British doctors was commissioned by the Chilean government, which
hopes to stop a extradition request by a Spanish judge to try the
retired general on charges of crimes against humanity.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Ireland: Gun-Running Plot Suspected
</P>
<P>
   The police said a Roman Catholic guerrilla group, possibly the
Irish Republican Army, was involved in an effort to smuggle 32
handguns into Northern Ireland from the United States. Two of three
people detained by the Irish police this week remain in custody,
including an American. Meanwhile, three people have been charged in
Florida with attempting to bring firearms to Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   Ivory Coast: Presidential Contender
</P>
<P>
   Alassane Ouattara, a deputy managing director at the
International Monetary Fund, arrived on Thursday from Washington to
pursue a bid for the presidency in next year's elections. Since he
had announced his plans to resign from the IMF, the return of
Ouattara, a former prime minister here, had long been anticipated
by the government, which is contesting his eligibility to run as a
presidential candidate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia: Massacre Charge
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups said the bodies of 51 villagers in the
province of Aceh had been found in two mass graves, and they blamed
the military for what they said was a massacre of civilians. A
military spokesman denied the accusation and said the only deaths
were 31 rebels killed in a raid one week ago.
</P>
<P>
   Cambodia: Request for U.S. Aid
</P>
<P>
   Prince Norodom Ranariddh, president of the National Assembly,
asked the United States to resume direct aid to the government
because ``the democratic process has positively developed in the
country.'' International aid was slashed two years ago when
Ranariddh was ousted in a coup by his co-prime minister, Hun Sen.
The prince then disputed the results of an election last year in
which he was defeated as a candidate for prime minister by Hun Sen.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia: The Skies Darken
</P>
<P>
   Forest fires are burning again on Sumatra and Kalimantan, and
the smoke is again drifting across Singapore and Malaysia. The
pungent haze dims the sun but has not reached the choking levels
that caused disruptions and deaths in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
