<HEADLINE>
AS GUN SEIZURES DROP, POLICE UNIT'S USE OF UNIFORMS IS
RECONSIDERED 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Gun seizures by the Police Department's embattled
street crime unit have fallen so sharply since the shooting of
Amadou Diallo in February that officials are leaning toward putting
some of the elite force back into plain clothes, police said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The 307-person unit has been a critical tool in New York City's
successful effort to seize guns and curb violent crime. But its gun
seizures have plummeted by 40 percent this year, compared with the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The statistics show that we certainly have not been as
productive as we had been before,'' Police Commissioner Howard
Safir said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner said that the department's decision last March,
seven weeks after the Diallo shooting, to have every officer in
what had been a plainclothes unit begin wearing a uniform is one of
several factors in the falloff. Safir said some officers have said
the uniforms hinder their effectiveness, especially in situations
in which they need to act as decoys or conduct surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he said, he has asked his staff to come up with a
plan under which those officers whose tasks require stealth might
dress in street clothes, while those making arrests would continue
to wear uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   In February, four officers of the street crime unit who were
looking for a rape suspect in the Bronx fatally shot Diallo, an
unarmed West African immigrant, in the vestibule of his apartment
building. The plainclothes officers fired 41 bullets, and later
said they thought Diallo was reaching for a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   The move to uniforms was intended to reduce confusion during
potentially lethal confrontations in which officers in jeans and
sweatshirts carrying guns might not be recognizable by the public.
In the Diallo shooting, the four officers were dressed in street
clothes, although their lawyers have said they identified
themselves before the shooting began.
</P>
<P>
   Safir said that under a plan being discussed, each street crime
team would consist of six people, four of whom would be in uniform
and two in street clothes. After the plainclothes officers had
finished their surveillance, the uniformed officers would move in
to make any arrests.
</P>
<P>
   ``This plan, if I decide to go with it, addresses both the
concerns of the officers, in their ability to operate close in,''
Safir said, ``and the concern of the public of misidentification.''
</P>
<P>
   Arrests by the unit for illegal gun possession are also down by
45 percent this year, police statistics show. In Brooklyn, where
shootings and homicides are beginning to climb from 30-year lows,
police officials have theorized that the decline in gun seizures
may be playing a role in the rising violence.
</P>
<P>
   But one analyst, Thomas Reppetto, president of the Citizens
Crime Commission, said that last year, before the Diallo incident,
there had already been a drop-off in gun arrests citywide, in part
because the unit's success had persuaded many criminals not to
carry them. ``Today it is much harder to find gunmen and thus,
consequently harder to make gun arrests,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-99 2227EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
