r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEN-SURF-LADN     07-30 0490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-SURF-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CURREN RIDES PAST DORIAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE STEVENS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTINGTON BEACH, Calif. _ The announcer introduced Tom Curren
as ``the best surfer in the history of California.''
</P>
<P>
   And in the most exciting heat of the Gotcha Pro, Curren surfed a
wily heat to edge Hawaiian Shane Dorian 16.35 to 16.25 Friday in
the third round of the World Championship Tour event.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't really a heat that came down to a surfing contest,''
Curren said. ``It came down to tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   Curren's tactics worked, even though the 35-year-old trailed the
majority of the heat after Dorian surfed in between the poles of
the Huntington Beach Pier to notch a heat-high 7.75. However,
Curren repeatedly rode waves to catch up until he needed just a 6.0
with one minute left to beat Dorian.
</P>
<P>
   Curren, a crowd favorite, is one of 16 surfers remaining in the
48-surfer tournament. Ten surfers from the mainland have competed
in the Gotcha Pro, but only three remain: Curren, Kelly Slater and
Shea Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   The wild bunch: Three of the four wild-card competitors have
advanced, including Curren and Slater. Another wild card, Brazilian
Neco Padaratz, finished highest among unranked surfers in last
week's surfing U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   Padaratz has become one of the favorites of this Gotcha Pro. Not
only did he knock out surf legend Mark Occhilupo in the second
round, he beat Michael Campbell 23.0 to 22.6 in the third. Padaratz
had the best single-wave score of the day with a 9.0.
</P>
<P>
   Slater update: Slater beat Damien Hardman, a two-time WCT champ,
12.75 to 12.00 after both were left without quality waves.
</P>
<P>
   Slater is not on the WCT this season after winning his sixth
championship last year. But he doesn't appear rusty after his tour
departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like second nature,'' Slater said. ``It's like lying down
six weeks and thinking you can't walk.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he'd like to see in this Gotcha Pro, Slater said,
``Me and Curren in the semis, man.''
</P>
<P>
   That seems to be the overwhelming sentiment at the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Irons dethroned: Andy Irons, who was the champion in both weeks
of competition at Huntington last year, lost his heat to Australian
Nathan Webster 20.65 to 12.75. Webster jumped to an early lead and
controlled the heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't add anything special to beat him as defending
champ,'' Webster said. ``Andy's always going to be tough to beat,
whether he's the defending champ or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Beachley's wave ends: Layne Beachley, 1998 women's WCT champion,
was knocked out in the quarterfinals by fellow Australian Pauline
Menczer, 14.75 to 12.05. Beachley had been hampered by a torn
ligament in her left knee and competed against the advice of
doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Tita Tavares, Rochelle Ballard and Trudy Todd will join Menczer
in the semifinals at 1:10 p.m. today. The women's and men's finals
are Sunday at 12:10 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-99 2241EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990730.0403 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0607 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTER-SECURITY-ART     07-30 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-SECURITY-ART-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT AND COMPAQ ADMIT VULNERABILITY TO SECURITY FLAWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Second graf now attributes report of Hewlett-Packard
vulnerabilities to ``one expert.'')  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF and SARA ROBINSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp. and Compaq Computer Corp. on Friday confirmed
the existence of several significant software security flaws that
could enable intruders to gain access to the computers of millions
of customers and to damage their data via e-mail or through
commands sent from a malicious Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Certain Hewlett-Packard computers are also said by one expert to
be vulnerable, but a spokesman for the company said Friday that the
company would not confirm the security vulnerability.
</P>
<P>
   The vulnerabilities, which affect computers running Microsoft's
