<SLUG> BC-WOODSTOCK-RAPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN WOODSTOCK'S WAKE, SECURITY IS DEBATED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Ill., Mich., Va.) (yn) 
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As police investigators delve into allegations of rape and
catalog property damaged by marauding fans at the Woodstock '99
concert last weekend, a debate is emerging, online and among
experts in the concert business, about the performance of the
festival's security force and whether it was adequate.
</P>
<P>
   On one side are Woodstock promoters and many concertgoers, who
contend that the 200,000 young people in attendance were as
protected as they could have been, given the concert's sprawling
site, a shuttered Air Force base in Rome, N.Y. On the other side
are experts on crowd control, who believe that the reported rapes
and Sunday's five-hour melee, which left trailers burning and
vendor stalls looted, could have been prevented.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question we had enough security,'' said John Scher,
a Woodstock promoter and the president of Metropolitan
Entertainment Group in New York, which manages concerts for Limp
Bizkit and Korn, two bands whose Woodstock performances were marred
by allegations of sexual abuse and rape in the ``mosh pits'' near
the east stage. ``We met all the permit requirements. But was
anybody prepared for this kind of thing? I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   That was precisely the problem, said Paul Wertheimer of Crowd
Management Strategies, a consulting firm in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Woodstock was symbolic of everything that's wrong about
safety at rock concerts,'' he said. Around the notorious mosh pits,
where young men slam against one another as hard-core rap-metal
bands play, Woodstock's yellow-shirted ``peace patrol'' security
forces were nowhere to be seen, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the organizers' responsibility to protect people,'' said
Wertheimer, who did not attend the concert but watched portions of
it on television. ``You cannot blame the victims for an environment
they can't control. You don't have to make it perfect, you just
have to take care to prevent injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodstock organizers should have created a separate area for use
as a mosh pit, which otherwise forms spontaneously directly in
front of a stage, and stationed specially trained security forces
inside the crowd to calm those who veer out of control, he said.
``That could have possibly stopped some of the injuries and also
some of the sexual assaults that went on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the 1,100 security guards should have not allowed
``crowd surfing,'' in which fans get tossed overhead on a sea of
hands.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Donohue, a retired New York City police official who
supervised Woodstock's security force, said it was unrealistic to
think that any number of security guards could have prevented the
four reported rapes, three of which were said to have occurred in
tents on the concert's vast campground.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that could have prevented them is having no one
camp there, or a completely lighted area,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the teeming, body-crunching acts inside mosh pits,
Donohue said: ``No one is forced into the banging around that they
do there. If you don't want to be in the mosh pit, you shouldn't be
near it.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he said, security guards cannot watch everyone all the
time. ``You make some assumptions that people behave in a normal
fashion at a concert,'' Donohue added. ``You take certain chances,
like you do at a Yankee game. You don't have 5,000 cops inside a
Yankee game.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people at the concert, however, described security as lax.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was worthless,'' said Tim Beynart of Athens, Ga., a
Woodstock '99 stage worker, in a telephone interview. With no
security guards around, he and several other crew hands at
Saturday's Limp Bizkit performance were forced to stand guard
around a three-story lighting and sound tower after fans began
tearing it down. ``We were keeping them off the building,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Along with their rape investigations, the police continue to
account for millions of dollars in property damage. Fans burned 12
refrigerated tractor-trailers, looted concession stands and smashed
into vehicles on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the violence directed at property, only seven people
were injured in the melee.
</P>
<P>
   The human toll from the mosh pits, where dancing was reduced to
jumping and kicking like kernels of stove-top popcorn, appeared to
have been far greater.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything I experienced at the concert, people were friendly
except for the mosh pit,'' said Andrew Mitchell, 21, of St. Louis,
Mich., in a phone interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real big guys will form a circle and start kind of beating
on each other. If you get caught in that, you could get a hard
shoulder, a hard elbow; worst case is you get something broken.''
</P>
<P>
   During the Limp Bizkit performance on Saturday, a violent mosh
pit formed a few seconds into the first song, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was almost a stampede back from the stage with people
who were trying to get away from it,'' Mitchell said.
</P>
<P>
   But to others, the mosh pit is a rough but friendly place where
strangers become friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a real strong sense of pit etiquette,'' said Jim
Elliott, 19, of McLean, Va., who joined the mosh pit as Korn, Limp
Bizkit and Rage Against the Machine played. ``If you fall down,
there's always eight or nine hands reaching down to pull you up.
Fights are always broken up after the first punch.''
</P>
<P>
   The rape allegations have sparked a lengthy debate among many
concertgoers who have logged on to the concert's official Web site,
Woodstock.com, to post their insights and opinions on concert
security.
</P>
<P>
   In one posting Tuesday, a man said his daughter had been raped
in a tent on the campground and asked for help in finding the
``clean-cut, college-looking guy'' who did it. Other postings
described how body-surfing women had to fend off swarms of
anonymous, groping hands.
</P>
<P>
   One woman posted a message saying she and a friend had been
trapped in a women's bathroom at the campground after a horde of
men surrounded them and barked requests that they shed their tops.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
