<SLUG> BC-NY-TERROR-SUSPECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE RULES EGYPTIAN LINKED TO TERRORISM SHOULD BE FREED 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal immigration judge ruled Friday that an
Egyptian man kept in solitary confinement for the last three years
on the basis of secret evidence allegedly linking him to a
terrorist organization should be freed from jail.
</P>
<P>
   The man, Nasser K. Ahmed, and his lawyers have never been told
exactly what secret evidence the government had on Ahmed, and
contended that he was innocent. Friday, Judge Donn Livingston
agreed, ruling that Ahmed was not a threat to national security and
should, in fact, be given political asylum in the United States
instead of being deported.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling was the third case in the last year where immigration
judges have questioned the Immigration and Naturalization Service's
procedures in using secret evidence against suspected terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   In a practice assailed by civil liberties and Arab-American
groups, two dozen suspected terrorists, all Arabs, are being
detained around the country by the immigration service on the basis
of secret evidence.
</P>
<P>
   None of the defendants and their lawyers have been allowed to
see the evidence against them. Immigration and intelligence
officials say that the evidence cannot be disclosed because it
endangers the sources of the information and could compromise
national security.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed, 38, a father of three, is unlikely to be freed quickly.
Immigration service lawyers filed an immediate appeal of
Livingston's decision that could take months to resolve. Ahmed is
also awaiting sentencing for his conviction in June of making false
statements on an immigration form.
</P>
<P>
   Government lawyers accused Ahmed of being a follower of Sheik
Omar Abdel Rahman, a blind Egyptian cleric convicted of conspiring
to blow up the World Trade Center and other New York landmarks.
Ahmed served as the sheik's legal assistant during his 1995 trial,
but he vehemently denied being a terrorist.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyers said that the ruling Friday further undermined the
government's use of secret evidence. In such cases, government
lawyers are allowed to present secret evidence and witnesses to
judges in private sessions in the judge's chambers. The defendants
and their lawyers are not allowed to be present and are unable to
rebut any of the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the detained men said they were eager to have a
higher court rule on the constitutionality of the use of secret
evidence. But no appeals of an immigration judge's decision have
been ruled on by a higher federal court to date. Livingston, an
administrative judge for the immigration service, was restricted to
ruling on the facts of Ahmed's case only, not on the
constitutionality of the practice.
</P>
<P>
   In his ruling Friday, Livingston openly questioned the
immigration service's procedures for calling evidence secret. He
said some of the evidence so declared in Ahmed's case could have
been obtained from unclassified sources, thereby giving Ahmed and
his lawyers the right to know and rebut it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
