</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPOTLIGHT FALLS ON COACHES, QUARTERBACKS IN FAME, BLAME GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ We open this training camp for NFL fans by
reviewing the first rule of pro football: The quarterback always
gets more credit and more blame than he deserves.
</P>
<P>
   It's in the rule book. The quarterback must be the hero or the
goat _ except in unusual weather conditions when, at the discretion
of the referee, said duty may transfer to the coach.
</P>
<P>
   The rule was carefully observed in the offseason by the league's
general managers.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a dozen NFL teams won more games than they lost. Of
those winners, 10 begin their summer of sweating and grunting with
the same starting quarterback and the same head coach, in several
cases rewarding those men with contract extensions.
</P>
<P>
   The two exceptions are Super Bowl winner Denver, which lost
quarterback John Elway to retirement, and 11-game winner Green Bay,
which lost coach Mike Holmgren to Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, 13 NFL teams finished with more defeats than
victories. Of these losers, 10 reacted by changing either their
starting quarterbacks or their head coaches, and five took no
chances and changed their starting quarterbacks and their head
coaches.
</P>
<P>
   The teams changing quarterbacks include Washington, whose
problems seemed to reside on defense but which traded for
Minnesota's Brad Johnson shortly before 1998 starter Trent Green
signed with St. Louis; and Cincinnati, another club that might have
concentrated on the other side of scrimmage but chose instead to
release Neil O'Donnell and hope for more points from Jeff Blake and
rookie Akili Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Such mechanical applications of the rule might seem
unreasonable. Why should Green and O'Donnell pay for the outside
linebackers' shortcomings, and for that matter, why should coaches
Ted Marchibroda and Dave Wannstedt be fired because Baltimore owner
Art Modell and Chicago president Mike McCaskey mess up their
franchises?
</P>
<P>
   At least it isn't arbitrary. NFL coaches and quarterbacks can't
claim to misunderstand the terms of their employment. This isn't
about stealing paper clips or sloppy penmanship on the timecard.
</P>
<P>
   Win more than you lose, and you stay. Lose more than you win,
and you're out. The .500 mark cuts like a guillotine.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the league's leading men go to camp this week knowing
that in a front-office supply room, a chopping block is kept oiled
just in case.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo: Can 36-year-old Doug Flutie work magic again? If not,
USC's Rob Johnson is set to take over.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina: Ex-Raider Steve Beuerlein had a solid year but the
Panthers' 4-12 record and the trade for John Elway backup Jeff
Lewis should make him nervous.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit: Does coach Bobby Ross get a pass because of Barry
Sanders' ill-timed retirement? Or does he get blamed for it?
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville: The pressure is on Tom Coughlin _ time to begin
referring to him as ``The Only Coach the Jaguars Have Ever Known''?
_ as he takes over the play-calling for a team many see in the
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City: Elvis Grbac gets no break. Rich Gannon may have
gone to Oakland, but 42-year-old Warren Moon can take Grbac's job.
</P>
<P>
   New England: From 11 wins under Bill Parcells to 10 and 9 under
loose-reined Pete Carroll. See where this heads?
</P>
<P>
   New York Giants: Coach Jim Fassell begins the second-to-last
year of his contract, meaning that come January he'll get either an
extension or a summons to the owner's office.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia: No. 1 quarterback Doug Pederson, 31, has been
released eight times and never started a game in his NFL career.
Will he make it through the season before first-round draft pick
Donovan McNabb takes over?
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh: Slash's slide to 26th among NFL passers coincided
with the slip to seven wins. It's a pivotal year for Kordell
Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle: Former Barcelona Dragon Jon Kitna replaces the departed
Warren Moon. If the Seahawks slip below their 8-8 records of three
of the past four seasons, it won't be Holmgren taking the fall.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis: Dick Vermeil, who gave us the word ``burnout'' when
he left Philadelphia in 1983, seems intent on inflicting the
condition on Rams players. Trent Green, on the scale of Rams
quarterbacks, rates closer to Karl Sweetan than Roman Gabriel.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay: Trent Dilfer couldn't get it done in the red zone.
Now he's in the danger zone.
</P>
<P>
   Washington: After four starting quarterbacks in four seasons,
Brad Johnson brings stability to the position. And pressure to
coach Norv Turner, who has broken .500 once in five years.
</P>
<P>
   Well, that's it, a win-or-get-out ultimatum for about half the
league's quarterbacks and coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Unfair? Not really. In a few cases losing will actually be their
fault.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-99 2308EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990730.0407 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
