r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     07-30 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KARROS IS WORTH KEEPING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's edition of The Sporting Muse, where there is always a
deadline, trade or otherwise:
</P>
<P>
   If the Dodgers are really looking to improve themselves by
trade, they should consider this power-hitting first baseman whose
name has been mentioned several times as the trade deadline nears.
</P>
<P>
   He averages 25 home runs and 95 RBIs every full season, and he's
also hit for average the last two seasons. He's solid defensively,
is a stand-up guy in the clubhouse, refuses to be a Pollyanna, and
has never told anything but the unvarnished truth when asked about
his team.
</P>
<P>
   By now, you may have guessed I'm talking about Eric Karros, who
is a Dodger and should stay a Dodger for as long as he likes.
Because while there may be a hundred different ways to analyze
what's wrong with the Dodgers, Eric Karros is never part of the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the word around the ballpark is that neither General Manager
Kevin Malone nor manager Davey Johnson are fans of Karros, and that
the Dodgers have entertained offers for him and would move him by
today's deadline if they could get the right package of players in
return.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about those reports, Johnson said there have been
rumors about Karros for a long time, that Karros ``was a grinder,''
and that it was disappointing that the team hadn't put things
together.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly gushing praise. At least Tommy Lasorda raved about
guys before telling them to move on.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and Malone are good baseball men, and you normally would
assume they know what's best. But based on their work in assembling
and operating the Dodgers of '99, there's no reason to trust them.
And I can trust Karros.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Karros shows up every day and plays hard. He plays hurt. He
gives you a consistent 25-95 every season with absolutely no fuss
or bother. He has never hid in a bullpen, half-stepped on the
basepaths, or bailed on community work.
</P>
<P>
   And when it comes time for the Dodgers to look at themselves in
the mirror, Karros is often the only reflection you can see.
</P>
<P>
   Tell him his numbers say he's done his job and he'll say that
doesn't matter. He resists any attempts at positive spin, even
during short term success, in a disappointing season. Ask him about
Mike Piazza and he'll tell you the Dodgers shouldn't have made the
trade. And that chemistry wasn't the issue three years ago any more
than it is today.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people said break it up, and maybe those people were
wrong,'' said Karros. ``A lot of people said it was the chemistry,
and it wasn't. Each season we've had different kinds of endings,
and you can't look at any one thing and say `oh, this is the
problem.'
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is that winning solves everything, and it's what we
haven't done.''
</P>
<P>
   All I know is that trading Karros won't solve a thing.
</P>
<P>
   Boston and Toronto were interested in Karros, but both teams
made smaller deals this week to fill their needs, Boston getting
Butch Huskey and the Blue Jays David Segui.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta has also expressed interest since injuries has left them
with a bit of a power void. But they fully expect Andres Galarraga
to return next season. Karros is signed through 2000 and is in the
$5 million-a-year zone. ...
</P>
<P>
   Two thoughts come to mind while watching the Carlos Perez
fiasco. His outrage at being send to the minor leagues is exactly
what one would expect of the overpaid modern player who believes
his salary makes him invulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   And he would likely be picked up by another major league team as
soon as the Dodgers released him, mostly because he's left-handed
and teams are willing to overlook anything for a left-handed
pitcher. ...
</P>
<P>
   Malone spent most of the week on the phone, but he may not have
been looking to make a trade as much as dump salaries. What he
found out is that no one wants the Dodgers he and others overpaid
to get or keep.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone was most interested the Dodgers young pitchers -- Chan
Ho Park, Darren Driefort, Ismael Valdes -- or Karros. No one wanted
Eric Young, Jose Vizcaino, Devon White, Todd Hollandsworth or
Carlos Perez.
</P>
<P>
   Sources say that Malone was willing to discuss Gary Sheffield
and Raul Mondesi, too, but their salaries ended most conversations
quickly. ...
</P>
<P>
   Some Angels fans are probably bummed that the team was so
willing to trade Omar Olivares and Randy Velarde for three
prospects. But both are free agents next season, and they're not
the kind of players you build a team around.
</P>
<P>
   That said, any package for Chuck Finley better have more in it
than prospects. Finley is the kind of player who can make a
difference in a pennant race, which is why the Indians and Yankees
want him. They should pay accordingly. ...
</P>
<P>
   The same sources that said the Dodgers were willing to talk
about Sheffield and Mondesi say the Angels have mentioned Darin
Erstad, Garret Anderson, Jim Edmonds and Troy Glaus in trade talk
with other teams. ...
</P>
<P>
   How nice of Jack McDowell, who has spent most of his Angels
career on the disabled list, to say that he hopes his two recent
starts will get him traded to a contender. ...
</P>
<P>
   The trade deadline consumes baseball talk, but the reality is
few of them make a short-term difference and some teams come to
regret their impatience.
</P>
<P>
   Texas won a division after making deals last year, but I'm sure
they wish they could have Fernando Tatis back from the Cardinals.
...
</P>
<P>
   Here's an ugly thought. Tony Gwynn has just two home games left
before the start of an 11-game road trip, so he's likely to smack
hit No. 3,000 on the road.
</P>
<P>
   His first stop is a four-game series in St. Louis, a great
baseball city. But the next stop? Montreal for four games, meaning
Gwynn may very well get No. 3,000 before a crowd of 2,500.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
