r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-COMPETE-KAN &LR;      07-30 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-COMPETE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE VARIETY OF CHALLENGES, VIDEO STORES ARE ALIVE AND WELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- Ever since Blockbuster Video stores started
rolling over America in the 1980s, independent operators have
scrambled to come up with new ways to stay competitive. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Because Blockbuster doesn't carry adult titles, for example,
some independents do as a way to survive. Indeed, X-rated titles
and a variety of other niche products have become lifelines for
many independent video stores. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Blockbuster's goal is to own 50 percent of the video rental
business in America, and it's making gains. In the first six months
of this year the video behemoth gained five points of the market
for a total of 31 percent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last year, national chains, primarily Blockbuster and Hollywood
Video, added about 1,000 stores. Meanwhile, 2,500 independents
died. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't many of us left,'' said Brian Mossman of the Fine
Arts Theatre and Video in Mission, Kan., in suburban Kansas City. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like most independent operators, Mossman has a niche. He is
unique in this area in that his video ``store'' is in the lobby of
his theater, which shows independent, art and foreign films. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Much of his video stock consists of the same types of titles. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't spend much on advertising because my video customers
are my movie customers,'' Mossman said. ``They come a few minutes
early, browse the videos and then see a movie.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Valentine Video in Westport, a stone's throw from a
Blockbuster, adult videos comprise more than half of the store's
rentals. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Valentine competes in other ways, too, says film buyer and
co-manager George Robertson. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We carry, obviously, mainstream titles but also alternative
titles, cult movies, foreign films, and recently we started a
director's section, which has been real popular,'' Robertson said.
The director's section groups movies by directors, such as Woody
Allen or Robert Altman. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And unlike in a Blockbuster store, Robertson added, he knows
most of his customers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The same goes for Hollywood at Home, said Steve Wolverton,
manager of the Overland Park, Kan., independent video store in
suburban Kansas City. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood at Home has carried a limited selection of adult
titles for the 20 years it's been in business, but it also has
other niches. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For instance, it stocks 3,000 magazine titles, carries some
books and has an assortment of cigars and cigarettes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, about 50 percent of our business is videos, while books
and magazines probably account for 30 to 40 and the rest is cigars,
cigarettes and candy,'' Wolverton said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And then there are stores like Lissa's Videos in Kansas City,
Kan., which deals exclusively in Spanish-speaking videos. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Blockbuster declined to comment on its strategies because it's
in the midst of a so-called ``quiet period'' before a stock
offering planned for later this summer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Sumner Redstone, chairman of media and entertainment giant
Viacom, which owns Blockbuster, exulted in a conference call with
analysts earlier this month over Blockbuster's successes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``BrandingWeek recently ranked Blockbuster as the 13th-most
recognized brand in America,'' Redstone told analysts. ``And by the
way, Blockbuster's next biggest competitor, Hollywood Video, also
made the list -- at number 1,932.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Partly fueling those gains were a series of revenue-sharing
deals with studios, which allow Blockbuster to buy a video for
about $7 a copy while independents still have to pay from $60 to
$85. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That gives Blockbuster the ability to stock dozens of new
titles, while the independents can afford only two or three. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the horizon for all video stores is video-on-demand, whereby
moviewatchers will be able to download a movie off the Internet or
through their television cable system onto a disc and watch it at
their convenience. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Will that technology kill the video rental industry?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good question, but who knows where we'll be 10, 15
years from now,'' said Mark Holmes, an associate analyst with A.G.
Edwards. ``For the high-tech user, maybe they'll quit going to
rental stores, but I don't think everyone will.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, VCRs continue to sell well. In the first six months of
this year, 13.8 million VCRs were sold, compared with 10.7 million
in the same period last year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason is that prices have dropped and people are
either replacing older VCRs or adding more. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Noting the still-strong sales of VCRs, Redstone quipped to
analysts, ``and these people aren't buying them to wash their
clothes.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The more immediate issue for the video industry: DVDs. For the
first six months of this year, 1.3 million DVD players were sold,
compared with 283,000 in the first half of 1998. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, many video stores are starting to stock DVD titles,
including 500 of the 6,500 Blockbuster stores. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet, even though 2 million households now own DVD players, video
rentals grew 9 percent last year, with Americans spending a record
$8.1 billion renting movies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Will DVDs someday replace videocassettes?'' said Holmes of
A.G. Edwards. ``Maybe. But it will take a long time. It took years
after the release of compact discs to replace albums and cassette
tapes are still out there.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Wolverton of Hollywood At Home said he doesn't fret
about video-on-demand. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been talking about it for the last 10 years and it's
still not here,'' he said. ``It will surely make a difference, but
until then, I'm not going to worry about it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-30-99 2335EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
