<SLUG> BC-TEN-MERCEDES-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNHERALDED SEKULOV MAKING NAME FOR HIMSELF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There were fans in the Mercedes-Benz Cup
grandstand who wondered about James Sekulov. ``What kind of name is
Sekulov? Where's he from?''
</P>
<P>
   The name is Russian, but Sekulov is from Perth, Australia, and a
veteran of the same tennis academy that produced Todd Woodbridge
and Mark Woodforde.
</P>
<P>
   And today he plays in his first ATP Tour semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   Sekulov, ranked 236th in the world, had never even won a match
in any of his previous seven ATP events until this week, but now he
faces second-seeded Pete Sampras in today's semifinals after
beating Michael Chang 2-6, 6-2, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, this is a 22-year-old who originally planned to take
this week off and ``hang out with friends somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead he entered the qualifier last week and won his way into
the main draw, He earned his first ATP victory in Monday's first
round over Martin Damm. On Wednesday, he upset fifth-seeded Thomas
Enqvist, a two-time L.A. finalist. Then he beat Chang, ranked 70th,
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who would've thought I'd beat Enqvist? Who would've thought
I'd beat Chang?'' Sekulov said. ``Of course, I did. You guys
didn't. I thought I had a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Since turning pro in 1995 Sekulov has spent most of his time in
Futures and Challenger events, without the benefit of a full-time
coach because ``It's expensive to go out and get one full-time and
there's not a lot of money in Challengers.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he gets Sampras.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 22, 23 this year,'' Sekulov said. ``I haven't done much,
but you've got to take a chance when you get it. I'm in the semis.
Everyone in the semis is playing well.''
</P>
<P>
   Down on his luck: Chang continues to struggle. Injuries to his
knee and wrist last year left him out of the top 20 for the first
time since 1988. His confidence continues to be low, which was
evident when Sekulov went up 5-2 in the third set. Chang appeared
downcast throughout the changeover and into the start of the final
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to lose matches like this,'' he said. ``This year
I've lost more than I've won, which is a strange feeling for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Chang, who won this event three years ago, refuses to
retire.
</P>
<P>
   Aussies on rise: Joining Sekulov in the semifinals is countryman
Andrew Ilie, who beat France's Anthony Dupuis 6-7 (6-8), 6-4, 6-4
in the day's first quarterfinal.
</P>
<P>
   Sekulov said he got a charge out of Australia beating the U.S.
in the second round of the Davis Cup two weeks ago. And Australian
Pat Rafter ascended to the top of the world rankings this week.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't rank: Ilie thinks he'll catch grief from the other
players, but he's not a fan of the new ranking system.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Jan. 1, there will be two rankings: the current one,
which will be used for entry and seeding, and a new one. All
players begin the year 2000 with a zero ranking and earn points
based on how they fare in the Grand Slams, the Mercedes Super 9
series (that includes next week's Canadian Open) and any five other
tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a lot of rankings confuses the players,'' Ilie said.
``The simpler the better, that's my opinion. It's a little bit
silly. `I'm ranked 40th, 15th and 25th.' You do an average and
we'll be ranked nothing. If it works, don't change it.''
</P>
<P>
   Most players either don't care or aren't sure how the rankings
will work.
</P>
<P>
   As for Ilie's ranking, he might worry less if he continues this
successful run. Today is his second semifinal this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
