<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-30 23:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0746 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REEVESCOLUMN-TEX     07-30 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVESCOLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW THAT I KNOW: HAIL TO GEORGE W.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
Once upon a time _ and this starts like a fairy tale because it
seems so long ago and far away _ I didn't particularly care for
George W. Bush. That has suddenly made me a popular guy in some
parts.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Never mind that those feelings had no real basis, or that they
were developed before I got to know the man, or that I've since
done a 180-degree turn on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody _ ``anybody'' _ who ever said anything critical about
Bush is currently in demand.
</P>
<P>
   True story: Phone rings at the house a few weeks ago. I'm home
on an off-night cooking steaks on the grill. Female voice on the
other end says, ``Oh, you're not here.''
</P>
<P>
   Where, I asked, is here?
</P>
<P>
   ``Here at The Ballpark,'' she said. ``We thought you'd be
here.''
</P>
<P>
   The voice on the other end of the phone belonged to a TV
producer for a national cable sports network. She and her crew were
doing a special on former Rangers' owner George W. Bush, now Texas
governor and presidential hopeful, and they were ``looking for
balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Balance? OK, I'll bite. What kind of balance?
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody we talk to raves about George W. Bush,'' she said.
``We saw your quotes in ``Texas Monthly'', and, well, we thought,
here's at least somebody who hasn't always liked him.''
</P>
<P>
   Hold it right there. It's true: I did have kind of a
circumstantial grudge against George when he bought the Rangers
back in 1989. I just figured he was coasting on his father's name
and that that's why then-commissioner Peter Ueberroth had approved
his group, once it paired up with Richard Rainwater and Rusty Rose.
George wasn't putting all that much of his own money in, and I
believed, at the time, that there were other groups that might have
merited as much or more consideration.
</P>
<P>
   I was probably also at least vaguely affected by my faint
political leanings: Yes, I'm one of those hated left-wing media
liberals who believes in helping the poor and the elderly, women's
rights, animal rights and protecting the environment. So sue me.
</P>
<P>
   On the issue of Bush and Rangers' ownership, however, let's just
say I was dead wrong on all counts. One of those big 0-fers, if you
will.
</P>
<P>
   The TV producer remained adamant despite my disclaimers. Would I
mind coming to The Ballpark that night (the game had already
started). Yes, I said, I would mind. Could they send a crew to my
house then? OK, but it's a 45-minute drive to Johnson County, and
that's if you know where you're going. Plus, it's about to get
dark.
</P>
<P>
   Directions? Sure.
</P>
<P>
   They never showed, which is just as well. I doubt I'd have been
able to provide the kind of balance they seemed to need.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll bet, on average, I talk to somebody in the media three
times a week, calling about George,'' former Rangers' president Tom
Schieffer said a few days later when I told him about the phone
call. ``Now we're kind of into the questions going beyond the
ballpark and baseball. It's things like, `What kind of executive is
he? What kind of person is he? How does he function?'''
</P>
<P>
   I'd often wondered how Bush and Schieffer, who served three
terms in the Texas House of Representatives as a Democrat, were
able to come to a compromise on their respective political beliefs
and work so well together.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't, `How do you feel about this issue or that issue.'
Our names had both been on the ballot before, and we'd both been
beaten,'' Schieffer explained. ``There was an instant rapport. We
found the same things to be funny about the lessons you learn when
you're in politics.''
</P>
<P>
   They became close friends, co-workers and confidants, enough so
that Schieffer, surprisingly, will not be at The Ballpark this
weekend for the Nolan Ryan festivities. He and wife, Suzanne, left
Cooperstown, N.Y., on Tuesday to join Bush at his family's vacation
home in Kennebunkport, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Could there be a role for Schieffer in the Bush campaign at some
point? I wouldn't bet against it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we agree on all issues? No, we don't,'' Schieffer said.
``But I'll vote for George for president because he is going to do
something because he thinks it's the right thing to do, not because
it's politically expedient. I'll take those kind of politicians in
either party at any time.''
</P>
<P>
   Schieffer likes to tell a story from this season's Opening Day,
when Bush showed up for the team's luncheon for the Richard Greene
Scholarship program. There was a student there from each of
Arlington's five high schools. Bush, the first one to arrive, spent
time talking individually with each of the scholarship recipients.
</P>
<P>
   As the room filled with corporate executives, Bush got his
plate, located the five kids sitting by themselves in the corner of
the room, and ate his lunch while chatting with them. The students,
naturally, were thrilled.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll remember that for the rest of their lives,'' Schieffer
said. ``I thought it was so George Bush, when he could have been
sitting beside the president of this big company or that one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like politicians, but there are not many politicians I know
who would have passed the opportunity to schmooze with some big
corporate guy, someone who might mean money in the future. We need
more people in office with that attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   I can't say for sure what kind of president George W. Bush will
make. A pretty decent one, I suspect, because what I learned, once
I gave him a chance, is that he's a good man.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not a political analyst, by any means, so, I don't know if
that's enough to be president. There are other issues that will
certainly come into play.
</P>
<P>
   But it would certainly be a refreshing change. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
