<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-SPELLMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWEST COWBOY GRATEFUL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ In his first interview after his first
Cowboys practice, defensive end Alonzo Spellman was asked, ``What
do you bring to the Cowboys?'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As it turned out, it was the next-to-last question, No. 10 out
of 11, before a club official politely pulled the plug so that
Spellman could take a shower and grab some lunch. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``What do I bring?'' Spellman asked yesterday with a weary laugh
that suggested part humor/part exasperation. ``I can stop the run
well. I can get to the quarterback well. I'll be getting into shape
during camp. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll see it. ... You'll see.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   [ A man of Spellman's past, it's]It's easy to understand why he
would choose not to talk about anything but the present and the
future. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not even looking at the past,'' said the 27-year-old
former Chicago Bears first-round draft choice.[ , who] He has been
diagnosed with bipolar disorder, which apparently contributed to
several behavioral problems shortly before and after his June 1998
release from the Bears. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When asked to[ look back and] analyze what has happened to him _
such as barricading himself in his publicist's house during an
eight-hour standoff with police in March 1998, such as having to be
subdued by police with pepper spray when breaking up a fight
between two female companions _ Spellman replied, ``If you're
looking back, there's no way you can walk forward.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the Cowboys taking a risk on him, Spellman kept
his composure and said: ``Hey, I'm not worried about that stuff. My
only judges are the guys on the team and the guys upstairs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cowboys are the best place for me right now because they
have so many leaders on the team. They're an established
organization as far as winning goes. They know how to get to the
\RSuper Bowl\S. It's not a place where I would have to come in and
be in a limelight role. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a perfect opportunity in a perfect place.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spellman's Shangri-la is a practice field on the Midwestern
State University campus[ in a town of 136,600 people]. Here, in a
span of less than 18 hours beginning Thursday afternoon, Spellman
went from being an unemployed football player to playing defensive
end for the Cowboys behind only a rookie fourth-round draft choice
named Peppi Zellner. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kavika Pittman, the Cowboys' incumbent starter at that same
defensive end position, broke at least two small bones in his hand
during a freak accident at practice yesterday. Pittman tried to
break his fall in a dummy drill and ended up breaking his hand. He
is expected to be out three to four weeks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spellman's window of opportunity just cracked opened a little
wider. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As for Spellman playing behind Zellner, who has been impressive
in this camp but is a rookie, Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said,
``We'll just have to evaluate that as time goes on.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As for what Spellman showed in his first two workouts, Cowboys
defensive-line coach Jim Bates was encouraged and impressed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not in the best of shape now, not in football shape, but
he gave us some good solid work for a first day'' since he played
in 1997, Bates said. ``He's strong. He's got long arms. He can play
with leverage. He did everything we asked of him today.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys know that if Spellman can keep himself on track,
physically and emotionally, they have a steal. Spellman signed a
one-year deal for the NFL veteran minimum of $400,000, no signing
bonus, with a hard-to-earn incentive package worth another
$400,000. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``My desire to play has been there since I came into the
league'' in 1992 as the 22nd draft pick overall, Spellman said. ``I
just ran into a whole lot of problems, and they're behind me now.''
</P>
<P>
   Aware that both Spellman's mother and fiance were in attendance
for Spellman's first day as a Cowboy, Calvin Hill, who heads the
Cowboys' behavior program for players, pointed out that Spellman's
``support system'' is one strong indication that he has a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trust me,'' Hill said, ``I've been here for a couple of years,
and I've seen some cases _ mostly draft choices _ where you say to
yourself, `Wow! This scares you.' But in \RSpellman's\S case, the
red flags that typically come up ... did not come up.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a nice, young man who has had some problems in the past.
We think we have some things in place that can help him. I just ask
people not to rush to any judgments. Let him be a player again.
Give him a chance.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
