<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-BOSOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES THRASH BOSTON, 13-3 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The '99 New York Yankees have lapses like the '98
Yankees almost never experienced. When these Yankees play
second-division teams like the Chicago White Sox or the Florida
Marlins, the monotony wears on them; their intensity wanes.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Red Sox will never benefit from this, however. With
the Yankees' big-game adrenaline pumping, they began Friday night's
game with back-to-back home runs from Chuck Knoblauch and Derek
Jeter and went on to thrash Boston, 13-3, as club executives
discussed a handful of trades.
</P>
<P>
   With just a day remaining before Saturday's midnight trade
deadline, the Yankees agreed in principle to a trade for Jim
Leyritz of San Diego; they were mulling the idea of sending Andy
Pettitte to Philadelphia for three prospects; they were bartering
for Baltimore's Arthur Rhodes, and they remained in serious pursuit
of Roberto Hernandez of Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Clemens, a longtime member of the Red Sox, will make his
first Fenway Park start as a Yankee on Saturday, when he faces
Boston's Brian Rose.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox (55-47) are barely hanging on in the American League
East race, 7 1/2 games behind the Yankees and staggered from the
scary shoulder soreness experienced by the ace Pedro Martinez and
season-ending elbow injury to the closer Tom Gordon. If Boston
harbored thoughts of ambushing the Yankees this weekend and
creeping back into the race, the Yankees quickly squashed them.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch had not been expected to play Friday night after he
had been sidelined in Chicago by a virus. But the medication he
took before getting on the plane Thursday helped him greatly, and
before the game, he said he felt much better. It showed, as he
finished with five hits.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch slammed the second pitch of the game from Mark
Portugal into the net above the fence in left-center field, and
right away, the Red Sox fans began murmuring. Their angst grew when
Jeter followed with his 19th home run, into the Boston bullpen
beyond the short wall in right-center field. It was the first time
since April 27, 1955, that the first two Yankees batters had
homered; Hank Bauer and Andy Carey began a game against the Chicago
White Sox with successive homers. Jeter's home run matched his
career-high total set last year.
</P>
<P>
   Hideki Irabu (8-3) took a 2-0 lead to the mound in the bottom of
the first, with great reason to believe he was going to win his
seventh consecutive decision. But he appeared to be having trouble
with the mound: Irabu kicked at the dirt in front of the pitching
rubber constantly, working at the hole left by Portugal in the top
of the first.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's John Valentin hit a home run with one out, and with two
outs, Troy O'Leary doubled to score Nomar Garciaparra, tying the
game, 2-2. But then the Yankees blistered Portugal in the second
inning, in a rally prolonged by Boston errors.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra booted Shane Spencer's ground ball before Scott
Brosius singled and the Yankees were on a roll: Knoblauch hit a
ball off the third-base bag, a single that allowed Spencer to
score, Jeter singled home another run and Portugal was relieved.
</P>
<P>
   But Jin Ho Cho, following Portugal, couldn't slow the Yankees.
When Paul O'Neill flied to deep right, Knoblauch tagged up and
scored _ and when Trot Nixon's relay escaped Donnie Sadler's grasp,
Knoblauch waved frantically for Jeter to follow him across home
plate. The Yankees were ahead, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu was still kicking at the dirt when he came out for the
second inning, and he walked the first two Boston batters. Then
Irabu (12 strikeouts) found his stuff. He struck out Nixon and
retired the next two batters.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees added three runs in the third inning, Jorge Posada
hitting a run-scoring double, the first of his three-extra base
hits, and soon Cho was gone. By the seventh inning, manager Joe
Torre had begun taking out some of his starters.
</P>
</TEXT>
