<SLUG> BC-CONTINENTAL-ASSAULT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRLINE SUED BY PASSENGER IN ASSAULT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.) (yn) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A passenger accused of hurling a Continental Airlines gate agent
head-first to the floor at Newark International Airport last week
has sued the airline, saying that it was he who had been attacked.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed Friday in Superior Court in Essex County,
provides a sharply different version of the confrontation between
the passenger, John C. Davis Jr., and the gate agent, Angelo
Sottile, than the one offered by the authorities at the airport.
</P>
<P>
   The Port Authority police said that Sottile, 50, of Kearny,
N.J., was working at Gate 115 of Terminal C at 9:10 p.m. on July
22, preparing to board passengers on a flight to Orlando, Fla.,
when Davis' toddler darted from the waiting area into a passage
leading into the aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, Vickie Davis, and a gate agent pursued the girl into
the passageway, the police said, but Davis, who also tried to chase
the child, was stopped because he did not have a boarding pass.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, the police report continued, then became enraged and
bear-hugged Sottile, turned him upside down and dropped him
head-first onto the floor. Sottile suffered several fractures of
the spine and neck, as well as head injuries. Davis, 29, of
Fredericksburg, Va., was arrested and charged with aggravated
assault. He was released on $50,000 bail.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony J. Pope, Davis' lawyer, said that it was Sottile who had
been the aggressor. Sottile, the lawyer said, did not let Mrs.
Davis follow her child and shoved her to keep her away from the
passageway.
</P>
<P>
   ``John sees this,'' Pope added, ``and says something to Mr.
Sottile to the effect of, `Hey, don't touch my wife.' Then the
ticket agent grabs him around the neck.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis grabbed Sottile back and they both crashed to the ground,
Pope said. He said that he had photographs showing red finger marks
around Davis' neck.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit does not mention Sottile by name; rather, it charges
Continental with creating ``an atmosphere of heightened and
unnecessary tension'' by failing to train its employees properly.
It also accuses unidentified Continental employees of assault and
battery.
</P>
<P>
   Sottile, who was released from the hospital Friday after neck
surgery, will suffer a permanent 50 percent to 60 percent loss of
neck motion, Continental officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Treacy, a spokeswoman for Continental, called Davis'
lawsuit ``a complete perversion of the facts'' and said many
witnesses saw Davis attack Sottile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Continental will expend whatever resources necessary to assure
that Davis is brought to justice and pays for his violence,'' she
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
