BURN BEGINS CRUCIAL SWING THROUGH WEST VS. RAPIDS (For use by
NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BLANE BACHELOR 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
Burn defender Brandon Pollard admits to not always knowing where
his team stands in the ranks of Major League Soccer.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But even Pollard doesn't need reminding of the importance of
tonight's ESPN-televised 7 p.m. game against Western
Conference-leading Colorado (13-5) at the Cotton Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the guys on our team, the people in the office, everybody
knows the importance and our willingness to come out strong this
weekend,'' Pollard said.
</P>
<P>
   A victory would accomplish several objectives for the 10-10
Burn, which is entering the final 12 games of its regular season.
Perhaps at the top of the list is sparking a late-season revival
against Western Conference rivals. The Burn is 4-8 against teams
from the West, and five of its next six games are intra-conference
matches. Getting a winning streak started could spark crucial
momentum to finish high in the standings and provide the Burn with
some extra confidence in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sets a little precedent, and you definitely think about
sending a message,'' Pollard said. ``You can imagine going into the
playoffs losing all of your games to \Rthe Rapids\S, or one or two
to them. Taking one or both of these next games is mentally and
psychologically important. It's important that we get that edge.''
</P>
<P>
   The Burn is looking for a turnaround from its past game, a 4-1
drubbing from Columbus that was Dallas' worst loss this year. Even
more disappointing for the Burn was the fact that it came after a
10-day break, which it entered with some confidence after two
convincing victories.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the Burn's chances of making the postseason look good.
Dallas and Chicago are tied for second with 28 points, with Los
Angeles one point behind in third and San Jose and Kansas City
trailing far behind.
</P>
<P>
   But making the playoffs isn't what the Burn has in mind. It has
sights set on first _ and knocking off Colorado in the next-to-last
game of the series would be a good start for a strong finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've put ourselves in the position where every game now is
critical because we want to be the first-place team,'' Burn coach
Dave Dir said. ``Every game against LA, Colorado and Chicago is
big-time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Burn has bitter memories of the 1997 playoffs, when Colorado
swept Dallas en route to the MLS Cup. The Rapids also had their
first victory in seven games at the Cotton Bowl this season, a 2-1
shootout. Colorado then defeated the Burn in regulation, 2-1, the
last time the teams met, in June.
</P>
<P>
   All of those factors have helped stir up motivation against the
Rapids.
</P>
<P>
   ``They beat us in the playoffs, and we felt that we were clearly
the better team,'' Dir said. ``And they beat us in two pretty close
games. The intensity has upgraded since then. But I don't think
they have the same intensity and rivalry toward us that we do
toward them. It will take us knocking them off their perch for that
to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rapids could be ripe for a fall. Colorado might be missing
five starters: injuries and absences, including] Midfielders Anders
Limpar (strained quadriceps) and Ross Paule (knee) are injured, and
Paul Bravo, Marcelo Balboa and Matt McKeon will probably be with
the U.S. national team in the Confederations Cup.
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect Colorado to hand over its top-place perch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got the most points and the best record, and with games
in hand on a lot of teams, teams shoot for you,'' Rapids coach
Glenn ``Mooch'' Myernick said. ``But there's an awful lot of soccer
to be played. We've got to avoid any major slumps, ensure we make
the playoffs, make sure we stay at the top and get home-field
advantage, which we've never had in the playoffs.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
