r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-BUTTERBEAN-TEX     07-30 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BUTTERBEAN-TEX </SLUG>
 
ONCE JUST A BRAWLER, NOW ERIC `BUTTERBEAN' ESCH COULD BE THE NEXT
BIG THING (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSE SANCHEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
His Rocky-colored shorts, Mr. Freeze-hairline, jumbo waistline _
and mouth to match _ have made him as much of a fixture on fight
cards as women's bouts and ``Let's get ready to rumble.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the attraction-starved world of boxing set out to invent a
new leading man, the character might look much like International
Boxing Association title holder Eric Esch. You might know Esch
better as ``Butterbean,'' the behemoth seen regularly on
pay-per-view cards, ESPN, USA and Showtime dominating four-round
undercard bouts and challenging Mike Tyson after each victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next to Oscar De La Hoya and Floyd Mayweather, he's probably
the most popular boxer we have,'' said Lee Samuels of Top Rank
Inc., one of the top fight promoters.
</P>
<P>
   During the past five years, however, Esch has evolved from an
undercard sideshow into a mainstay among big-money professional
boxing cards. He still packs some circus attraction that has
resulted in ``Butterbean'' lookalike contests and six appearances
on ``The Tonight Show with Jay Leno Show.''
</P>
<P>
   But Esch has held the International Boxing Association super
heavyweight title since January 1997 and takes a 48-1-1
professional record with 35 knockouts into a scheduled fight on a
card featuring World Boxing Council super bantamweight champion
Erik Morales tonight in Tiajuana, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants to fight Butterbean,'' said Art Dore, Esch's
manager. ``He could fight, get crowds every day if he had to. He's
just the kind of guy who has an appeal in the ring, and people like
him as a nice guy out of it. He never forgot where he came from,
making $12,000 \Ra year\S building mobile homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Esch, who turns 30 on Tuesday, came from Americus, Ga., but
spent his formative years in Jasper, Ala. As a young adult, he
labored eight years as a mobile home manufacturer before being
coaxed into his first Tough Man contest in 1988. Tough Man is more
or less a competitive version of street fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys all dared me to get in and paid my entry fee,'' said
Esch, ``I fought the local champion and won it. It was
unbelievable, the rush.''
</P>
<P>
   Weighing 411 pounds, 11 pounds over the Tough Man weight limit,
Esch endured a two-week diet of butter beans to lose 20 pounds for
his first fight. That's where the nickname comes from.
</P>
<P>
   After winning his first Tough Man title, Esch went on to win 18
National Tough Man Tournaments, and 21 World Tough Man Tournaments
during the next six years. With each title, Esch's reputation as a
Tough Man champion grew, but consequently discouraged potential
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would always sign up on the last day, but once people heard
I was in it, they all dropped out,'' he said. ``Nobody else would
fight me anymore; it hurt competition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when I decided to go after \RMike\S Tyson.''
</P>
<P>
   But Esch's transition into the professional boxing ring was
anything but typical. He made his professional debut Oct. 15, 1994
with a four-round decision against Tim Daniels and then went on to
put together a string of 15 consecutive victories over the next 14
months. He suffered a technical knockout loss to Mitchell Rose in
New York in December 1995 in his 16th fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was tired,'' Esch said of his only professional loss. ``I
was fighting almost every other week, and it was too much.''
</P>
<P>
   After losing to Rose, Esch won 19 consecutive bouts before
fighting to a draw against Michael Eaton in September 1997. He won
his fight on a card at Texas Motor Speedway in June, and his most
recent victory was a knockout of Peter McNeely.
</P>
<P>
   As for next step in his boxing career, Esch anticipates a
showdown with Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first started I couldn't hold my own with Tyson,'' Esch
said. ``Now, I feel like I can beat him. He's not the same. He
don't box anymore. He's too stupid. He'll try to brawl, and I'll
knock him out.''
</P>
<P>
   Esch's trainer, Murray Sutherland, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tyson of old, now that would be a different story,'' said
Murray, who has trained Esch since 1993. ``Now he \RTyson\S is
brawler. It's very feasible because Tyson is no more than a
four-round fighter, at best, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray's confidence comes from hours of reprogramming Esch into
more than just a slugger.
</P>
<P>
   ``You must remember, he had no formal boxing training, just
brawling,'' Murray said. ``I come along, and say we are going to do
it different, but it took time to develop. Now he's got confidence
in his skill.''
</P>
<P>
   But before Esch takes on Tyson, he must faces challengers eager
to capture his IBA crown. Esch still averages two fights per month
but now commands more than $50,000 per appearance. He recently
built a gym and a home in Jasper where he lives with his wife,
Libby, and their three children. He claims to be an entertainer and
said he has quieted critics by improving his boxing skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more of a boxer, but I'll always be brawler,'' he said. ``
I give the crowd what they want. They can't say nothing no more.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
